<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN'S BLUNDER COSTLY TO ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO -- If only Mo Vaughn were as good on his feet as he is
with his hands, the Angels might be onto something.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, Vaughn is not the fleetest of foot, and his lack of
footwork cost the Angels a run at a time runs were at a premium.
Because the Toronto Blue Jays scored five runs in the eighth
inning, Vaughn's baserunning blunder became a moot point in the
Angels' 7-1 loss before 13,622 at SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   But it certainly changed the complexion of the game when it was
there for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   In the top of the sixth with the game tied at 1, Vaughn appeared
to score from second on a single to center by Garret Anderson. The
Blue Jays appealed at third, claiming Vaughn missed the base as he
came home to score. Third-base umpire Rick Reed gave the out call
and the run -- and a 2-1 lead -- was erased.
</P>
<P>
   After Anderson hit the ball to center, Vaughn looked over his
shoulder to make sure the ball would drop. That seemed to throw off
his timing, and Vaughn, who had three hits in the game, clearly
missed the base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked back ... it was just stupid, really,'' Vaughn said.
``I've been in the league 10 years. I've been around too long for
something like that to happen. We go up a run and you never know
what could happen. I have no excuses about it. It's a bad play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should have been a clear-cut play. I should have stuck my
foot in the middle of the bag. ... It's a game of momentum, a game
of swings. I'm disgusted.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed also made a key call in the fifth inning. The Angels led,
1-0, when the Blue Jays had the bases loaded with two out. Angels
starter Ramon Ortiz went into a stretch, but hesitated during the
motion and Reed called a balk. Brad Fullmer was allowed to score
from third to tie the game at 1.
</P>
<P>
   For Ortiz, the balk was his second in two starts this season. He
had two balks in nine games last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (catcher) Bengie (Molina) gave the sign I started to make
a little move,'' Ortiz said. ``I didn't wait for Bengie to finish
giving the sign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He started up and stopped,'' manager Mike Scioscia said. ``It
wasn't part of his normal motion. Once you're in contact with the
rubber, the only thing you can do is come into your normal set and
pitch. Hey, we're dealing with a young pitcher. The bottom line is
he pitched great.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz gave up two runs and five hits in 5 2/3 innings, but
despite what Scioscia said, he didn't feel he threw the ball great.
</P>
<P>
   ``My control was not there today compared to last time,'' Ortiz
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think he was on his game even though he was good,
numbers-wise,'' Molina said. ``I didn't see him pitch the way he
usually pitches. His control wasn't there. Every pitch was
belt-high or down the middle. Usually he pitches on the corners.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays broke the game open in the eighth inning against
Angels relievers Mark Petkovsek and Lou Pote. Raul Mondesi led off
the inning with a home run off Petkovsek, and three batters later,
the Blue Jays had the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Pote replaced Petkovsek and gave up a grand slam to Fullmer, and
that was that.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what looks like a lopsided score, Scioscia said the game
was one that could have been won if not for the two plays and the
Angel offense's continued problems in key situations.
</P>
<P>
   They failed to score in both the first and second innings
despite putting a runner on third with less than two outs, and went
2 for 11 with runners in scoring position in the game. In their
past two games, the Angels are 4 for 24 (.167) when hitting with
runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in position to panic,'' Scioscia said. ``You're
going to have games where you don't execute like you should. A lot
of what we had is fixable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
