<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD SITS OUT WITH INJURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO -- Darin Erstad's spectacular diving catch in Sunday's
game against the White Sox came at a price. Erstad hurt his right
shoulder making the play and missed his first game of the season
Monday vs. Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tweaked it a little bit, it's nothing major,'' said Erstad,
who began Monday leading the league in hitting (.472) and leading
the majors in hits (25). ``It's something that will take a couple
days. I don't see it as causing any problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad said he didn't feel any pain when he made the catch of
Paul Konerko's liner to the left-center field gap in the seventh
inning Sunday. But late Sunday night it got sore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about getting these guys off the turf one day or
another, so this was a good day to give him a break,'' manager Mike
Scioscia said. ``I'd be surprised if he wasn't feeling much better
(today).''
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Gary DiSarcina (bruised left thumb) began taking
groundballs Sunday and hitting soft-toss Monday.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina, who is eligible to come off the disabled list when
the Angels return home April 24, hurt the thumb April 8 knocking
down a ball hit hard by Boston's Nomar Garciaparra. DiSarcina has
played in only five games, but has three errors and is hitting
.412.
</P>
<P>
   ``The swelling's down and the mobility's coming back,''
DiSarcina said. ``There's still slight pain, but it's pretty
managable. I think hitting's going to be tougher than fielding
groundballs because you have to squeeze the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Derrick Turnbow made his major league debut in the
eighth inning Monday night after the Angels had fallen behind, 7-1.
He gave up a single to Marty Cordova before retiring the next three
hitters. Turnbow, 21, pitched in single-A in the Phillies'
organization last year and was acquired by the Angels in the Rule V
Draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty nervous, but when I started throwing I got a
little more relaxed,'' Turnbow said.
</P>
<P>
   It took two weeks for Turnbow to actually get into a game, but
he said he was patient along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I would (get into a game) eventually,'' he said. ``I
just wanted to be ready when I got in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was cool as a cucumber,'' Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   Infielder Keith Johnson, called up last week to replace
DiSarcina on the roster, also made his major league debut in the
game, replacing Mo Vaughn as a pinch-runner in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the numbers might be considered mind-boggling, but
through the first two weeks of the season, the Angels' starting
staff has been one of the best in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Monday's game, the staff's ERA of 3.01 was the best
in the majors; opposing hitters were batting .233 against them,
best in the American League and second best in the majors (Mets at
.226); the Angels had three starters among the A.L.'s top 10 in ERA
-- Scott Schoeneweis (2.35), Kent Bottenfield (2.41) and Jason
Dickson (2.77).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't put much stock in that,'' Scioscia said. ``We look for
guys to execute pitches. If they execute pitches the results will
be there. The thing about our starters has been consistency. You
hope they stay consistent all season, but there are going to be
bumps in the road. To say where they stack up against the league,
is it enough for us to win? That's what's important.''
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS AT TORONTO
</P>
<P>
   Time: 4:05 at SkyDome
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: No TV; KMPC-1540, KIK-FM 94.3, XPRS-1090
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: Jason Dickson (1-0, 2.77 ERA) will start for Anaheim
against Toronto's Frank Castillo. The two pitchers faced each other
last Wednesday in Anaheim, but neither was involved in the
decision, a game eventually won by Toronto, 6-2. Castillo gave up
two runs in 6 2/3 innings; Dickson gave up two runs in 6 1/3
innings. With 10 home runs, the Angels have hit the fewest in the
American League.
</P>
<P>
   -- Joe Haakenson
</P>
</TEXT>
