<SLUG> BC-U.S.-TAIWAN-ARMS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., WITH EYES ON BEIJING, DECIDES WHICH WEAPONS TO SELL TAIWAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout) 
By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a decision intended to avoid further roiling the
tensions between China and Taiwan, the Clinton administration
agreed on Monday to sell Taiwan upgraded versions of three missiles
and a long-range radar system, but not four technology-laden
destroyers.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was made on Monday at a White House meeting among
the national security adviser, Sandy Berger; Defense Secretary
William S. Cohen, and Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, and
it was relayed to Taiwan on Monday evening, Pentagon and White
House officials said.
</P>
<P>
   As details of the decision spread, senior Republicans on Capitol
Hill voiced some anger that the administration had not delivered a
more robust weapons package.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, the Republican of North Carolina who is
chairman of the Foreign Relations Committee, pledged to seek
passage of a bill known as the Taiwan Security Enhancement Act that
would greatly strengthen military ties between Washington and
Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   How to gauge what to sell to Taiwan has become one of the most
sensitive questions for Washington's relationship with Beijing,
which has in recent months been recovering after almost a year in
the deep freeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are conscious this is a sensitive time, but our primary
guide is what is needed for Taiwan's security,'' said
Undersecretary of Defense Walter B. Slocombe.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the sale of weapons to Taiwan _ governed by the
1979 Taiwan Relations Act, which calls for the United States to
provide ``sufficient'' means for Taiwan to defend itself _ has been
a fairly routine affair.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, particularly after China released a policy paper
in advance of the Taiwan presidential election that toughened its
stance toward the island, the shopping list from Taiwan was among
the most sensitive. China, which regards Taiwan as a renegade
province and has long refused to rule out military action to block
Taiwan's formal independence, warned in the paper that putting off
serious talks on reunification could be grounds for war.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing had repeatedly told Washington in recent months that
selling four Arleigh Burke-class destroyers, equipped with the
Aegis battle-management system, would be ``unacceptable.'' China
views such a sale as tantamount to endowing Taiwan with a system to
defend against ``theater missiles,'' a move it has consistently
opposed.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official called the weapons package a
judicious response to Beijing's military threat to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is the increasing investment Beijing has put in
its offensive capability against Taiwan,'' the official said. ``And
to the extent that Beijing has fired missiles around Taiwan and is
adding 50 missiles a year to its arsenal, that increases what we
have to do to provide adequate countermeasures.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Republicans in Congress led by Sen. Trent Lott of
Mississippi, in whose district the destroyers are built, have
threatened to move more swiftly on the security enhancement bill if
the administration does not proceed with the destroyers. The White
House has said it will veto the bill, which the House has passed.
</P>
<P>
   Also at stake is legislation that would give China permanent
normal trading relations with the United States, a pivotal element
if American businesses are to benefit from China's requested
membership in the World Trade Organization. The White House is in a
tight battle with Congress over passage of the trade legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The package falls in three categories _ missiles that Taiwan has
requested but that Washington declined to sell, a long-range radar
system that was promised last year and whose precise character is
to be determined and a study of Taiwan's naval needs. Pentagon
officials said on Monday night that the study would not rule out a
reconsideration of the Aegis destroyers, which are mounted with
missiles and radars that can track up to 100 targets
simultaneously. The ships ost $1 billion each.
</P>
<P>
   The missiles to be sold to Taiwan include advanced medium-range
air-to-air missiles, which are to be stored in the United States.
If China acquired a similar missile like the Russian-made AAX-12,
the medium-range missiles would be moved to Taiwan, a Pentagon
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Another missile to be sold is an upgraded version of the
Maverick air-to-ground missile, guided by an infrared sensor. The
third is the Javelin antitank weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Probably most objectionable to Beijing is the long-range radar,
Pave Paws. A senior Pentagon official said ``exact details'' were
to be worked out on what would be the best model to give early
warning for long-range missile launchings, as well as incoming
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The long-range radar would be ``geared to the threat which we
expect to be up a few years out'' in China, the Pentagon official
said.
</P>
<P>
   The most sophisticated version of Pave Paws can track missiles
3,000 miles away. But it is far from clear that this is the model
contemplated for Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   China has deployed in its eastern areas 200 ballistic missiles
against Taiwan and is adding 50 a year, according to Adm. Dennis
Blair, commander in chief of U.S. forces in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech last month, Blair characterized those missiles as
``terror weapons _ too inaccurate to hit military targets with any
confidence'' but able to post a military threat to Taiwan as their
numbers increase and their accuracy improves.
</P>
<P>
   In deciding on the weapons package, the Pentagon, whose
officials had been suggesting that they proceed ahead with the
Aegis ships, finally acknowledged that such a move would be too
provocative, a senior administration official said. ``The Pentagon
looked around and found they had underestimated what the Chinese
reaction would be,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Chinese Embassy here said his government was
``particularly concerned that Washington was selling advanced
weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any American arms sales at this time,'' said the spokesman,
Zhang Juanjuan, ``might be viewed by the pro-independence people in
Taiwan as open support.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
