<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES PREVAIL OVER RANGERS, 5-4 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ If John Wetteland blows a save, that's
significant. When Mariano Rivera fails to hold a lead, that's
incredible. But when Wetteland and Rivera, arguably the two best
closers in the American League, both blunder in the same game, it's
bound to be a night made for the truly bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wetteland or Rivera entered Monday night's game, the
Rangers' Darren Oliver held the Yankees hitless for six and a third
innings and David Cone pitched seven effective innings for the
Yankees. After Wetteland and Rivera contributed to four lead
changes, Tino Martinez singled home the go-ahead run in the
Yankees' 11th, two innings after he had tied the game with a hit
off Wetteland, and the Yankees finally prevailed, 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who escaped a bases-loaded, no-outs jam in the
11th, have won six straight over all and have a 25-11 record
against the Rangers since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver didn't allow a hit until Paul O'Neill's single in the
seventh, just before Bernie Williams ripped a two-run homer that
tied the score at 2-all. The Rangers' Rafael Palmeiro blistered a
home run to right-center for Texas off Mike Stanton with two out in
the bottom of the eighth, and Oliver, who didn't allow a hit until
the seventh inning, remained in the Texas dugout, wearing a
blue-and-red Rangers' jacket, clapping.
</P>
<P>
   But there had to be some doubt in Oliver's mind, and in
Wetteland's.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Wetteland had tried and failed to protect a 1-0 lead
against Cleveland in the bottom of the ninth, allowing back-to-back
homers to Manny Ramirez and Jim Thome _ his first blown save in 19
chances.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had two hits in the first eight innings, and yet
they began picking at Wetteland immediately. Chuck Knoblauch
smacked a single, and one out later, O'Neill laced a hit, as well,
Knoblauch stopping at second.
</P>
<P>
   When Williams whiffed, there were two outs. But after Wetteland
could not overpower Martinez with high fastballs _ Martinez kept
fouling them back _ he tried a curve and Martinez lined it over the
head of the first baseman, scoring Knoblauch with the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera shut out the Rangers in the ninth, and Jorge Posada led
off the top of the 10th against Tim Crabtree with a long, high home
run to straightaway center field. Posada ambled around the bases as
Crabtree stared, stunned. Rivera went out to pitch the bottom of
the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Royce Clayton singled, however, moved to second on a sacrifice
bunt, and after Rivera jumped ahead in the count no balls and two
strikes against Ivan Rodriguez, Rivera tried to get Rodriguez to
chase after high fastballs. The count went to 3-2, Rivera relented
and threw a pitch over the plate, and Rodriguez singled through the
middle, tying the game again, at 4-4.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter singled to start the 11th inning, and after Mike
Venafro relieved Crabtree, O'Neill walked and Williams lined to
center. Jeter tagged up and moved to third, scoring from there when
Martinez ripped a single to right.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the game, with Oliver pitching, the Yankees hitters
kept glaring in disbelief at the home-plate umpire, Jeff Kellogg,
as if Kellogg was responsible for what Oliver was doing to them.
Derek Jeter muttered over his shoulder at the umpire as he walked
back to the dugout. Chuck Knoblauch turned to Kellogg and sneered,
as if to say, You've got to be kidding me.
</P>
<P>
   What the Yankees probably could not grasp was reality. Oliver, a
journeyman left-hander who barely got through five innings at
Yankee Stadium last week, was dominating them. A 29-year-old
pitcher who averaged about eight victories per year in his seven
seasons was shutting them out. Oliver had an earned run average of
7.45 in his first two starts, and incredibly, the Yankees had no
hits after six innings.
</P>
<P>
   In the context of this one night, there was nothing flukish.
Oliver has extraordinary control with his fastball, pitching to
corners, and when the Yankees hitters tried to anticipate this
pitch, Oliver would cock his wrist and snap a curveball, and the
swings would be awkward, off-balance.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Kelly and Clay Bellinger rolled ground balls to
shortstop for the first and second outs of the sixth inning, and
with the count two balls and two strikes on Knoblauch, Oliver
dropped over a curve in the strike zone that Knoblauch merely
observed. Oliver had 18 of the 27 outs required for a no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter led off the seventh, swung at Oliver's first pitch and
like so many Yankees before him, grounded weakly, to second base.
Eight outs to go. But when Oliver tried jamming O'Neill with a
fastball, O`Neill muscled a looper over the head of the shortstop
Clayton, a cheap hit gladly embraced by the Yankees. Fans stood and
cheered for Oliver, the eighth pitcher in the Rangers' 29-year
history to take a no-hitter past the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   When pitchers lose no-hitters, some member of the infield will
often stroll to the mound to settle his teammate, to make sure he
is not overwhelmed by disappointment. There was no such meeting
before Williams stepped in to hit. Nobody checked on Oliver before
Williams smashed a two-run homer off the screen attached to the
left-field foul pole.
</P>
<P>
   The score was 2-2, it was the seventh inning and it did not
matter how many hits Oliver had allowed to that point.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
