<HEADLINE>
MARKET ROLLER COASTER CAN BE MANAGED WITH SOME STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Practically everyone
in the stock market got beat up last week. Monday's rally made it
easier to answer the bell again.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But there ought to be a lesson in the bruises. Is there a way to
tell whether you're overexposed to the volatile stock market? More
importantly, what should you do if you are?
</P>
<P>
   Financial planners said they don't have easy answers to the
first question. And although they offered a few tips and
benchmarks, they agreed that each individual has his or her own
threshold for financial pain.
</P>
<P>
   Investments shouldn't cost you sleep or push you into checking
mutual fund prices every day, the planners said.
</P>
<P>
   But some people likely found last week's pummeling too severe.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not rare, and someone shouldn't be embarrassed by
recognizing that,'' said Sheryl Garrett, president of Garrett
Financial Planning Inc. in Overland Park, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   The worst damage came from the record 25 percent, one-week
plunge in the Nasdaq stock market. Friday's descent left the Nasdaq
where it had stood last November. Even the blue-chip Dow Jones
industrial average fell 7.3 percent last week, most of it coming in
Friday's 617-point dive.
</P>
<P>
   Investors got some of that back Monday as they hunted for
bargains, especially among big-name technology stocks. Both indexes
climbed more than 200 points, with the Dow Jones gaining 2.7
percent and the Nasdaq 6.6 percent. It was the Nasdaq's
second-largest one-day percent jump ever.
</P>
<P>
   Still, both indexes remain below where they started the year.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the broad decline in stocks means just about all
investors have less exposure than they did even a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the opposite is true, too. The big run-up in technology
stocks this winter means investors who haven't looked lately
probably have far more invested in tech than they originally
intended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody ought to have a good handle on how much technology
they own,'' said Wayne A. Starr, a principal at BKD Investment
Advisors LLC in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund investors are particularly vulnerable to owning more
technology stocks than they expect. Many so-called growth funds
favor technology stocks, but their fund names don't suggest it.
</P>
<P>
   More than one planner suggested using the mutual fund reports
from Morningstar Inc., which are available at most public
libraries. You also can visit www.morningstar.com to check your
funds' exposure to technology.
</P>
<P>
   But how much is too much?
</P>
<P>
   About one third of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index is made up of
technology stocks. Some planners said that's a reasonable benchmark
for individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett said most growth funds are likely to provide enough
exposure without seeking out technology specifically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think the majority of people need to buy a
mutual fund with technology in its name,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how much technology you own, last week's market
was a good test of most investors' risk tolerance. And planners
were in agreement on what to do if you failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't stomach the volatility and you can't stomach the
risk...then you should back off,'' said Bill Hoeschele of Wm. F.
Hoeschele &AMP; Associates in Lenexa &QL;  Kan.
</P>
<P>
   That means sell at least some of your stocks or stock funds,
even at these sharply lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   Just because you made it through last week's damage doesn't mean
the ride is over. Investors who got a wake-up call from the stock
market this time might be struck even harder in the next round.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is the sudden realization, then reality may be better
faced now than later on,'' said Bud Kasper, president of Financial
Security Investment Advisors Inc. in Lee's Summit.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who stick with their long-term plans simply will have
to put up with more volatility.
</P>
<P>
   Even before last week's plunge in the Nasdaq, Prudential
Securities market commentator Greg A. Smith wrote that ``...an
important lesson may be that high volatility is now a way of life.
We will all have to become more accustomed to it, I believe, if we
are to continue to be investors in the U.S. market.''
</P>
<P>
   Some stocks certainly are less volatile than technology stocks.
Investors can look for stocks that pay dividends, earning part of
their rewards through income rather than rising stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Several kinds of mutual funds try to take a less risky approach.
These include balanced funds and asset allocation funds that invest
in a mix of stocks and bonds or cash investments, and value funds
that look for out-of-favor stocks that should suffer less in market
downturns.
</P>
<P>
   Planners routinely recommend stocks for clients' retirement,
college and other long-term financing goals, because the equity
market historically has offered the best potential for gains.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, even fleeing the stock market won't insulate you from
volatility. Starr points out that bonds bled investors' pockets
last year after stuffing them with quick gains late in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do you hide from it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is one spot. Bank certificates of deposit are federally
insured up to $100,000. And, with some five-year CDs paying 7
percent, Hoeschele said it's not a bad deal. Especially for folks
who don't have the patience to ride out the short-term peaks and
valleys on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people who shouldn't even be in the stock
market,'' Hoeschele said.
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
