<HEADLINE>
IT'S UNANIMOUS; BASEBALL OWNERS APPROVE DAVID GLASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE ROCK  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   HOUSTON _ The final vote lasted, in the
words of baseball commissioner Bud Selig, ``about 40 seconds.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   And just like that, after years of instability that plagued the
Royals in both the standings and the stands, the ownership drought
of Kansas City's baseball team effectively ended on Monday. The
full group of baseball's owners, voting unanimously, approved David
Glass as the next owner of the Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   That marked the last significant step in Glass' pursuit of
ownership, a maneuver that, as expected, proved to be little more
than a formality.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals and Glass hope to close the legal transaction, at the
agreed-upon price of $96 million, before the end of the month. Once
that happens, Kansas City will have a permanent owner in place for
the first time since Ewing M. Kauffman died in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about it,'' Glass said after the meeting, only a
slight smile forming on his face. ``I may not look excited, but I
am.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great day. I've waited for this day for a long time.
I'm really excited about the way it's turned out.''
</P>
<P>
   And baseball's owners wasted no time in formally approving
Glass. Meeting at the posh Four Seasons Hotel in downtown Houston,
they originally planned to gather for two days. The first order of
business was to discuss Glass' proposal. Drayton McLane, the owner
of the Houston Astros and one of Glass' good friends, made the
formal recommendation that the owners approve Glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves the game, and he understands the game,'' McLane said
after the meeting. ``He'll make an outstanding owner.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no objections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go into the meeting,'' Glass said, ``and it's over five
minutes later.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners hustled through the rest of the agenda, adjourning
shortly after 7:30 p.m. Monday. Glass and team president Mike
Herman headed from there to Houston's new baseball stadium, Enron
Field, to celebrate the latest development.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting seven years for this,'' Herman said. ``This
is great.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't exactly shocking, not for a man who has worked
with the league owners since 1993 and was a known quantity within
baseball's political circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody respects David Glass a great deal because of his
business acumen, because of his intelligence,'' said Jerry
Colangelo, chairman of the Arizona Diamondbacks. ``He is
well-respected in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very positive move, both for baseball and for Kansas
City.''
</P>
<P>
   The transaction won't be finalized until near the end of the
month, Herman said. The two sides have to navigate a maze of legal
paperwork, and the Royals board has to meet again and approve the
final sale.
</P>
<P>
   Once that happens, Glass expects few immediate changes in the
day-to-day operation of the club.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he will see to it only that son Dan takes on a more
active role with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Glass worked in the front office for about five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'd like to do,'' David Glass said, ``is get him in there
and let him learn the areas that he hasn't been in yet before he
has to pick up a lot of responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Glass' exact role with the club, and his title, hasn't been
determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited,'' said Dan Glass, who was at the meeting in
Houston. ``And I'm excited for him. This is his baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just do whatever he asks me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's development marked the conclusion of a journey that has
dragged on for years. There have been countless hurdles along the
way, things like an unwieldy 26-month review by the IRS to approve
Kauffman's intricate succession plan. There was the auction that
Glass abandoned in 1997, the one in which he was convinced that
Royals fans didn't support him. There was the lengthy Miles
Prentice flirtation, the one that saw Prentice win the endorsement
of the Royals board of directors but ultimately get rejected by
this same group of owners.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the team went to the very person that Kauffman
originally hoped it would.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled,'' said Julia Irene Kauffman, Ewing Kauffman's
daughter and a member of the Royals board of directors. ``David
Glass is the right owner for Kansas City fans and for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   There haven't been many baseball owners in this town, a city
that was spoiled by Kauffman's generous pockets. Others have tried,
people like Prentice and Avron Fogelman, but only Glass had the
financial and political clout to pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very, very happy day for me personally, for Major
League Baseball, for baseball in Kansas City,'' Selig said. ``Ewing
Kauffman took me under his wing back in 1969. I felt a special
responsibility, all through this process, to make sure it came out
as close to the Ewing Kauffman mold as we could ever do. I really
feel a sense of fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, somewhere...Ewing Kauffman is happy. I know he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a permanency, a long-time stability that's very, very
important. I'm very proud of the club. I'm happy for the fans in
Kansas City, who deserve stability and deserve the kind of owner
they got. And, in my judgment, they got the best.''
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
