<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON DIPLOMATIC ABOUT POTENTIAL CONFLICT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Among the Kings fans watching on television
Saturday was Lakers coach Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Kings, Lakers and Clippers have pretty much lived
harmoniously in the new arena, this is playoff time and scheduled
dates are precious for the teams involved.
</P>
<P>
   Does Jackson hope the Kings force a Game 6 with the Red Wings
scheduled for Sunday at Staples Center?
</P>
<P>
   That's Easter Sunday, the day NBC and the Lakers hope to play
Game 1 of their first-round series against the loser of tonight's
game between Seattle and Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA playoffs begin Saturday, but the Lakers would love to
get an extra day's rest. Jackson wasn't biting when asked if he
hopes the Kings series is over by Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm rooting for the Kings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Andy Murray was pleased to hear his Staples neighbor
was keeping tabs on his team. Murray, who sometimes watches up to
eight NHL games a night off the satellite at home in Hermosa Beach,
also follows the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watch their games, too,'' he said Monday. ``Of course, I've
probably seen more of their games than he's seen of ours.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings opened their first-round series with the Red Wings on
Thursday in Detroit instead of Wednesday so they would not play
Sunday at home, a conflict with the Lakers game against Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   After that game, the Red Wings' Chris Chelios and the Lakers'
Ron Harper, old friends from their days in Chicago, visited in the
Lakers dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing for granted: Taking a 3-0 lead in a best-of-seven series
speaks for itself. But the Red Wings knew from experience that
going up 2-0 can mean nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, they were the two-time defending Stanley Cup
champions when they took a 2-0 lead over Colorado in the first
round. The Avalanche won the next four games and sent the Wings
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody pretty much had Colorado gone last year,''
Detroit winger Kirk Maltby said. ``I think maybe we got a little
caught up in reading the papers. They came back and kicked our
butts.''
</P>
<P>
   The beautiful people: Kings playoff games always have brought
out the stars and Monday night was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Actresses Michelle Pfeiffer and Drew Barrymore headed the A
list. Also on hand: actors Cuba Gooding Jr. (season-ticket holder),
Kristy Swanson (original Buffy), Tiffany-Amber Thiesson, singer
Mark McGrath from the band Sugar Ray and tennis star Lindsay
Davenport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
