<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT MUST BE SPRING: SONICS AT IT AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Among the biggest concerns in the local sports media
when George Karl took all his neuroses to Milwaukee was we would no
longer be able to use for the Sonics those wonderfully hackneyed
adjectives that TV Guide uses to describe sit-coms.
</P>
<P>
   You know: Wacky. Zany. Screwball.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out the concern was unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   Even without Karl, the Sonics' springtime is again rich in
shaving-cream pies and seltzer bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Sacramento Tuesday night for their biggest game of
the year, and on the eve of a return to the playoffs, the Sonics
for the past three games swapped out 60 percent of their
season-long starting lineup to insert two rookies and a second-year
player not yet 21 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the club's star power forward, a U.S. Olympian in
whom the Sonics invested $87 million last summer, admitted over the
weekend to being out of shape, depressed and on a crying jag. But
at least, he said, he doesn't have an alcohol problem.
</P>
<P>
   These developments came on the heels of a fight between the
franchise superstar and a teammate that involved the hurling of
locker-room objects and resulted in a one-game injury absence for a
third teammate.
</P>
<P>
   If you're keeping score at home, this grades out as a full Jerry
Springer.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when it was considered a big deal in the final week of
the regular season to hear that Karl was quitting on his starting
center?
</P>
<P>
   That was back when the Sonics were winning 55-plus games and
people cared. Now, of course, with one of the great attendance
falloffs in the NBA, the annual April intrigue apparently has been
replaced by ennui.
</P>
<P>
   The average fan is not inspired by the subtle distinctions of
the stakes tonight: Getting run over in the playoffs by an
18-wheeler or by a freight train.
</P>
<P>
   This boredom may also be a result of the fact that the current
vaudeville is nothing particularly new. As was mentioned, panicky
lineup changes prior to the playoffs are hardly original to coach
Paul Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are locker-room blowups. Who can forget that splendid moment
a few years ago when Ricky Pierce threatened to fetch his gun at
halftime of a playoff game to settle a dispute with Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does one need a photographic memory to recall previous
Sonics power forwards troubled by unplanned paternity and reports
of drinking problems.
</P>
<P>
   Even the purely basketball troubles being experienced by Vin
Baker are hardly a matter of astonishment. In fact, here's a little
test for you professors of Sonics history:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Identify the date and speaker for the following quote: ``I'm
just playing like crap. I'm not doing anything to help my team.
It's a travesty not to play well.''
</P>
<P>
   A: Ah, you knew where this was going, didn't you?
</P>
<P>
   Baker uttered that self-assessment in May 1998, the first _ and
last _ time he was in the playoffs in his seven-year career. The
Sonics were in mid-swoon to the Los Angeles Lakers, who blasted the
Sonics from the postseason, 4-1, despite the fact that the Sonics
won 61 regular-season games. The four losses to L.A. were by an
average of 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, then the Sonics' only real inside player, was a primary
culprit, slinking through the series' first four games before a
28-point, 12-rebound effort in a mostly pointless Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   It was plain that he was intimidated by Shaquille O'Neal. That
is hardly unique to Baker. Some of the smaller continents have been
scared by Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   It also fails to explain what happened to Baker in the first
round against Minnesota, a mostly broken team that was down to
starting 6-foot-4 guard Terry Porter at center the final contest,
but still managed to extend the Sonics to the full five games
before losing the series.
</P>
<P>
   Baker averaged 14.8 points against the Timberwolves, five below
his team-leading average. After a mostly stellar first season in
Seattle following the trade of Shawn Kemp, Baker's series against
Minnesota was the first glimpse of his soft side that is now
painfully familiar.
</P>
<P>
   So the fact that Baker is now offering up a self-diagnosed case
of depression as a source of his travail rings a little hollow.
</P>
<P>
   Tests following the season may establish that he is indeed
clinically depressed. If true, it is a disorder that must be taken
seriously by him and the team. He deserves whatever support, time
and therapy is needed to return to good mental health.
</P>
<P>
   But if it is discovered instead that Baker is simply too nice
and/or too lazy to play pro basketball well, then he and the Sonics
have made a massive misjudgment. There is no treatment or pill for
a lack of fortitude.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it is almost impossible for outsiders to know what
troubles Baker. Even he may not know. But the mystery has been
going on for longer than the past couple of months, and the Sonics
have games Tuesday and Wednesday to figure it out, plus a couple of
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Take the freight train or the 18-wheeler, and give the points.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 0055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0089 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBO-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-18 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
RAWLINGS, the official juice supplier for major-league sluggers,
contends nothing has changed in 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   The longtime manufacturer of baseballs says the dimensions and
ingredients are the same today as they always have been: stitched
rawhide around a wound core, with the balls never weighing less
than five ounces nor having less than nine inches of circumference.
</P>
<P>
   Sure. And players still wear wool uniforms, pitchers still own
the inside of the plate, the strike zone hasn't changed, and all
those little vitamin cocktails players drink before and after
workouts are the same as the ones Babe Ruth used to guzzle.
</P>
<P>
   While there's no reason to believe Major League Baseball has
issued some sort of mandate directing Rawlings to make baseball
cores out of titanium while lacing the covers with plutonium, the
balls have changed.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients? Yes, the ingredients for baseballs are the same as
always. So are the ingredients for homemade bread.
</P>
<P>
   But does the stuff that comes out of the breadmaker on your
kitchen countertop taste as good as the rolls Mom used to make from
scratch? Of course not. Technology changes everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because the specifications are the same, that doesn't
mean they're the same kind of ball,'' Astros president Tal Smith
said. ``Without being a physicist, it would just seem to me that if
they are wound tighter, the ball goes further. I do think there
could be some validity that the balls, just through the
manufacturing process, could be wound tighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the first two weeks of the 2000 season, pitchers
throughout the game have complained about slick covers on baseballs
and the tightness of their feel.
</P>
<P>
   Fans, meanwhile, have rejoiced. Attendance numbers are solid,
and no matter what purists might say, it's home runs that make
channel-clickers tune in the evening news.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who has been involved in the game for more than 40 years,
won't argue the feel of the ball either way, but he admits that,
more than ever, the slide seems to be leaving sliders and the curve
likewise with curveballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``(In the past), you could almost pinch the skin on some of the
baseballs,'' Smith said. ``You could feel looseness on the cover.
You could almost move the skin of the ball with your hand.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk of smaller strike zones, diminished pitching
depth, better athletes taking better care of themselves and _
perhaps most significant _ more hitting-friendly ballparks, batters
still need to put the bat on the ball. But whenever that has
happened this season, the ball has been flying out of stadiums,
whether it's been Colorado's Coors Field, Enron Field or the
traditionally tough SkyDome in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Home run numbers have been going through the roof, almost
literally. On April 7, there were more homers hit (57) than on any
other day in baseball history. Dodgers shortstop Kevin Elster, who
only once in 12 previous seasons had more than 10 home runs in a
year, hit three in one game. Last Thursday, the St. Louis Cardinals
departed Houston and Enron Field, where they enjoyed a homerfest,
and promptly hit three home runs in the first inning of their game
at Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the Rockies took a 14-13 game against St. Louis that
featured 32 hits, Seattle's Alex Rodriguez parked three homers in a
19-7 win at Toronto, and Boston's Carl Everett slammed a
game-winning home run into a ninth-inning wind estimated at 20 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than just the ballparks,'' Smith said. ``Ballparks
have something to do with it, but obviously that doesn't impact
what happens in Philly and Toronto.''
</P>
<P>
   After the first homestand in its history, Enron Field was viewed
as some sort of hitter's paradise, and compared to the Astrodome it
is. But home run and batting numbers at Enron are only in the
middle of the pack in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   This question about the ball always seems to come up whenever
home runs start flying out of yards at such dizzying rates. Is the
ball juiced?
</P>
<P>
   Of course it is _ this year more than ever. Baseball is in line
to shatter home run records in 2000, and no matter how many other
factors are involved, it's what has been happening when the wood
hits the horsehide that is the best evidence of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just the number of home runs but the distances
they've been traveling,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Purists might not like it, and MLB and Rawlings might be
reluctant to admit it because baseball clings to its tradition and
history. ``That's baseball,'' they say.
</P>
<P>
   But no doubt about it, the balls are juiced. That's technology.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 0105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0090 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBO-OWNERS-REALIGN-HN     04-18 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-OWNERS-REALIGN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
Selig
<TEXT>
<P>
   Major League Baseball owners met at the Four Seasons Hotel on
Monday to discuss a realignment plan for next year, just two years
after the last realignment. The next reorganization of divisions,
expected to be approved in June, probably will be a short-term move
once again.
</P>
<P>
   After the meetings concluded, commissioner Bud Selig said, ``I
do think there will be some realignment next year. We'll go to an
unbalanced schedule, and we'll rotate divisions for interleague
play, absolutely. Everything I wanted to do, we will do.''
</P>
<P>
   His plan calls for the Texas Rangers to move from the American
League West to the AL Central. Arizona would switch from the
National League West to the AL West, and Tampa Bay would go from
the AL East to a new NL division to be called the Southeast. It
would include Atlanta, Florida and Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh would leave the NL Central for the NL East, where it
would be grouped with state rival Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   That would give the National League four divisions of four teams
each _ and no wild card.
</P>
<P>
   Selig said the main ``problem'' with this plan is the creation
of a six-team AL Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll work on that and vote on it at our league meetings in
June, at a site and date yet to be determined,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Royals president Mike Hermann, whose club is in the
AL Central, said, ``When our young team becomes a contender, I want
to be on a level playing field. I don't want to be in a six-team
division when the other teams are in four-team divisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Use your common sense. But that doesn't always work for
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Hermann also opposes abolishing the wild card in the National
League.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make sense to have it in one league and not in the
other,'' he said. ``Is that fair? I think the fans want regional
competition and a wild card.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig is committed to grouping teams regionally, and he appears
to place more importance on that concept than on maintaining
traditional league affiliations.
</P>
<P>
   Some owners, including the newest one, David Glass, whose
purchase of the Royals was unanimously approved Monday, favor the
sort of extensive realignment that would render the National and
American leagues virtually indistinguishable or perhaps even
nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Selig hedged on how much realignment he eventually wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leagues do have this wonderful history and tradition,'' he
said. ``Do I believe this is the last phase of realignment? I do
not. I believe there will be more.''
</P>
<P>
   By dismissing the league presidents, Leonard Coleman of the NL
and Gene Budig of the AL, Selig showed last year he was not bound
by tradition.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1998 realignment, he became the first owner to switch
leagues when he moved his Milwaukee Brewers from the American to
the National.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see them throw away all the leagues and just
organize it by regions,'' Hermann said. ``Now that you don't have
league offices, I don't think league identity is important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our traditional leagues are just an historical thing. With
realignment and expansion, that's all changing. By keeping us in
these artificial leagues, you make us play games that don't draw
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig hopes to create better draws by setting up more
interleague play between rivals. He said the Astros and Rangers
``are clubs that should play each other _ as soon as next season.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr., a member of baseball's
realignment committee, was happy to hear that. ``We want to get the
Texas Rangers to the American League Central, so we can play them
regularly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McLane doesn't see a one-league concept developing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll always have the National and American leagues,'' he
said. ``I don't see any change in that. I think you'll have the
leagues and the importance of the leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hermann doubts fans are as concerned with tradition as they
once were.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's as much sensitivity to it as there was
in the 1950s and '60s,'' he said. ``I think the players moving the
way they have in the last several years, where you don't have the
long-term rivalries, with players you identify with, you get
confused over which teams you're playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Glass, whom Selig called ``the father of radical realignment,''
would like to see the major leagues divided into East and West,
rather than National and American.
</P>
<P>
   Hermann said that in time, fans as well as players would
appreciate the advantages of teams playing in their own time zones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually you get used to whatever division you're in,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, for fans to get used to their divisions, Major League
Baseball will have to keep from changing them every three or four
years. But Selig made it clear that realignment will continue to be
an ongoing, one-step-at-a-time process.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
