<P>
   SCI-DIVING-MAMMALS (Undated) _ New research is unraveling the
old mystery of how air-breathing animals manage to dive so far
beneath the waves and stay down so long. Seals, dolphins, whales
and other marine mammals can plunge up to a mile or more into the
abyss and stay there as long as two hours on a single breath, a
feat that has baffled scientists for centuries. But the secret of
their deep diving may not lie, as had been thought, in their
physiological adaptions. Instead, the new findings suggest, it has
everything to do with the way they dive, gliding as much as
possible and freezing their movements to conserve energy and
oxygen. By William J. Broad.
</P>
