<SLUG> BC-REFUNDS-IRS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRS SITTING ON MILLIONS IN UNCLAIMED REFUNDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALEXA HAUSSLER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ So day trading's left you short, tax day drained
your savings and Regis Philbin won't give you the time of day.
Don't sweat it, just phone a friend: Uncle Sam.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, the Internal Revenue Service has millions of
dollars in unclaimed and undeliverable tax refunds for Americans,
including a $178,000 check waiting for one unnamed Los Angeles
County resident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We discovered that the IRS had all these checks that they just
had sitting there, credited to the taxpayer but undelivered,'' Rep.
Brad Sherman, D-Woodland Hills, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As last-minute filers were scrambling to mail their 1999 income
tax returns before the midnight deadline, Sherman announced that
his congressional Web site now displays the names of more than
4,500 taxpayers in Los Angeles and Ventura counties who have
unclaimed refunds from the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   The list shows names and communities but does not include dollar
amounts, to maintain individuals' privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The average unclaimed check is for more than $800, Sherman said.
The largest unclaimed refund check in the San Fernando Valley is
for $81,621.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in the Valley, there's 81 grand waiting for somebody,''
Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials say the unclaimed refunds, some of them
dating back to 1980, were undeliverable for various reasons. Some
taxpayers moved without giving the Post Office a change-of-address
notice. Others changed their names, such as in marriage, without
notifying the Social Security Administration that a new name goes
with the old Social Security number.
</P>
<P>
   ``People move with no forwarding address,'' said IRS spokeswoman
Maria Maqueda.
</P>
<P>
   She said the tax agency tries each year to get the word out that
thousands haven't received refunds, and some haven't even filed for
them.
</P>
<P>
   But Sherman said he thinks the tax agency could try harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to come as a surprise that the IRS doesn't work
as hard to find people when they owe you money than when you owe
them money,'' Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News located one taxpayer listed on the Web site by
looking up his number in the telephone book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea! What a surprise,'' Kurt H. Bradley of Sherman
Oaks said when a reporter told him he was on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Internet list does not include dollar amounts, Bradley
was going to use an IRS toll-free number to find out how much he
will receive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get on the horn immediately,'' Bradley said. But
when he did, an IRS hotline operator said his name does not appear
on the agency's list, even though his name is on the Web site list.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, some 100,000 people failed to claim more than $72
million in IRS refund checks in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles and Ventura counties, 4,548 residents have failed
to claim $3.8 million in undeliverable checks since 1980. The
average unclaimed refund check is for $837.
</P>
<P>
   About 870 current or former Valley residents have failed to
claim tax refunds.
</P>
<P>
   A taxpayers' advocate in Los Angeles County said the government
needs to try harder to find the taxpayers it owes money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's $72 million, they ought to get some of the
bureaucrats to try to start searching them out,'' said Ernest
Dynda, president of the United Organization of Taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman said interns in his office this summer will search for
taxpayers who are owed refunds.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, those who suspect they are on the list can
check via www.dailynews.com or Sherman's Web site at
www.house.gov/sherman, or call the IRS hotline at (800) 829-1040.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, 48, a Paramount Pictures teamster, said he has moved
three times in three years and was shocked to learn he had money
coming to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually when somebody owes you money, unless you ask for it,
unless you confront them, they just let it go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He doubts his is the $81,000 check, and doesn't know how much
his newfound fortune may be. But he knows what he'll do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to put it in the bank,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to listing the names of residents who are owed
money, Sherman said he will push the IRS to post a searchable
national list on its Web site and work harder to locate people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
