<SLUG> BC-PROTEST-LAPD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAPD OFFICERS WATCH D.C. PROTESTS TO PLAN FOR CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV, LISA VAN PROYEN AND BILL HILLBURG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As protesters tied up Washington, D.C., on Monday,
Los Angeles police were there watching and learning _ to avert
similar disruptions at the Democratic National Convention in
August.
</P>
<P>
   About six officers from several Los Angeles police divisions
observed Washington metro police tactics and security plans. The
Democratic National Convention takes place in Los Angeles between
Aug. 14 and Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not anticipate any problems here, but we will absolutely
be prepared for anything that may occur,'' said Los Angeles police
Cmdr. Dave Kalish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already started training for officers on all the issues
that will be involved, from crowd control to protecting people's
First Amendment rights,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A protest area will be set up near Staples Center in downtown
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators converging on Washington represented at least
100 groups with various agendas, all allied to protest the
International Monetary Fund and World Bank's loans to Third World
countries. A spokeswoman for an organizing group said she knows of
no plans to demonstrate in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are only concerned with issues involving the IMF and the
World Bank,'' said Becka Economopoulos, spokeswoman for
Mobilization for Global Justice. ``But there are more than 100
groups represented here with a number of concerns. I believe that a
lot of these players will be in Los Angeles when the Democrats meet
and will be in Philadelphia for the Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police said they are taking no chances after
watching World Trade Organization demonstrators overrun Seattle,
causing severe damage and disrupting downtown for days.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, Seattle was caught off guard, and we want to be
sure we learn from that experience,'' Kalish said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not inexpensive, but it's an investment that's well worth
it,'' Kalish said. ``We knew this would be an outstanding
opportunity to watch and learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police are monitoring Internet sites of groups
involved in the Washington protests to try to learn their plans for
the convention, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Some security experts have voiced privately their concern that
convention planners are not taking seriously the security concerns
on a variety of issues, such as access to areas designated as
private within Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Officials, however, said they are following the advice of the
LAPD, FBI and Secret Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very confident with the work being done by the LAPD
and the federal law enforcement agencies,'' said Ben Austin,
spokesman for the LA2000 Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 0154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
