<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PRIX-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIZZY DAY FOR DRISSI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEN VILLA  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ The officials took away Tomy Drissi's title
on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But what they couldn't take away was the feeling of taking home
the checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   One day after finishing first only to learn later the outcome
had changed after the Trans-Am Race of the Toyota of Long Beach
Grand Prix, Drissi was in relatively upbeat spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Drissi, who was last season's Rookie of the Year on the Trans-Am
Circuit, thought he had won Sunday's Trans-Am race for his first
career win.
</P>
<P>
   But two hours later, race officials ruled that lap 35, the
race's final one, should have never been allowed because the
60-minute time limit had expired.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of winning the race, Drissi wound up third, behind
Johnny Miller and Chris Neville.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just technical stuff,'' Drissi said. ``No one can take
that win away from me ever. No one can take the thousands of people
cheering for me when I crossed the finish line first and no one can
take the feeling I had when I drove up to the winner's circle and
hoisted the first-place trophy over my head.
</P>
<P>
   ``The race officials had two options, to go by the rule book or
to let the race end the way it originally did, with me being the
winner. It's not my fault they dropped the green flag when they
shouldn't have, but I'm not a judge or anything like that. I'm just
a race car driver whose job is to finish in first place when the
checkered flag is dropped and I did that.''
</P>
<P>
   All the controversy started on lap 34. The race, which was under
the yellow caution flag at the time, was heading into its final
lap.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was the leader, Neville was in second and Drissi in
third. By all accounts, the race should have ended in the 34th lap
because the 60-minute mark had expired.
</P>
<P>
   But race officials who were unaware of the situation dropped the
green flag, allowing the drivers to continue.
</P>
<P>
   With every driver in a full sprint to the finish line, Neville
ended up hitting Miller, sending both cars into the wall. The
accident cleared the way for Drissi to take home first place.
</P>
<P>
   He was allowed to drive to the winner's circle, take part in the
trophy presentation and was even escorted to the media room to be
interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, rules officials declared Miller the winner
because he was in front under the caution flag when time expired
and notified Drissi that he had been relegated to third place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously the decision benefited me,'' Miller said. ``I do
feel bad for Tomy though, he ran a great race, but the fact is,
they should have stopped it when 60 minutes was over. I knew the
race was over in my car when we were under the yellow caution flag
because the 60-minute timer in my car had expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my crew chief that the race was over but he said they
were going to drop the green flag anyway and for me to get ready. I
thought they were crazy. I was glad the race officials made the
right decision and changed the ruling, but I hated to win like
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
