<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0106 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     04-18 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURRAY MAKES RIGHT CHOICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This is why Andy Murray gets our vote for NHL
Coach of the Year over St. Louis's Joel Quenneville. Because he
kept his head when a lot of people were calling for Stephane
Fiset's.
</P>
<P>
   Murray reinserted Fiset in the net Monday, two days after Fiset
had a shaky outing against Detroit, for the same reason he wouldn't
divorce his wife Ruth if she maxed out a credit card or disown any
of his three children if they brought home failing grades.
</P>
<P>
   Murray does not act impulsively. He has principles and he
adheres to them even when it's neither convenient nor conventional.
In some circles, that's called character. In Southern California,
though, where tans tend to last longer than convictions or
commitments, Murray's decision to stand by his No. 1 goaltender was
considered curious.
</P>
<P>
   The day before the Kings' 2-1 loss - we'll get to that in a
second - we found ourselves in an animated discussion with an L.A.
native who absolutely, positively believed Fiset should have had to
sit for letting in Kris Draper's unscreened shot in the fourth
minute of the second period of the Kings's 8-5 loss Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Fiset had played so well in the Kings's Game1
loss, he earned the No.2 star. Nothing we said could convince Mr.
You've-Got-To-Go-With-Jamie-Storr otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt there will be more second-guessers where he came from.
They're sure to sprout like mushrooms after a rain now that the
Kings stand one loss from being swept out of the playoffs, same as
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   So we'll be outnumbered, just like the Kings were when Detroit
scored each of its first two goals.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Show us somebody who tries to pin this latest loss on Fiset and
we'll show you somebody who watched the game blindfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset didn't give up an even-strength score. The Red Wings got a
power-play goal in the sixth minute of the first period and another
in the 15th minute of the second. Meantime, the best the Kings
could do when skating with an extra man was a solitary shot-on-goal
during a four-minute power play early in the second.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you keeping track at home, they are 0 for 16 with a
man advantage in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset stopped 22 shots - including two rapid-fire shots by
Detroit captain Steve Yzerman on a breakaway late in the third.
With any help from his friends on special teams, that would have
been enough.
</P>
<P>
   It says here Murray's method of dealing with his players was
validated Monday, even if victory eluded the Kings. Unlike his
predecessor Larry Robinson, who benched Fiset in the 1998 playoffs
under circumstances similar to this year's, Murray vowed to stick
with the glove hand that had brought the Kings this far.
</P>
<P>
   For this, Murray doesn't think he ought to be lauded or even
applauded. In his eyes, he wasn't being controversial, merely
consistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``All season I've always gone back to a player and given him
another chance,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday would be no different, even if it was the most monumental
game of Murray's first year with the Kings. ``I just thought it was
what you should do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This is why we heralded Murray's hire last June and are even
higher on him 10 months later. The consistency of his coaching
means his players never have to wonder where they stand.
</P>
<P>
   If a couple of players (a veteran centerman? a left wing?) stand
between the Kings and greater glory in the playoffs, well, that's
something to take up with general manager Dave Taylor, not Murray.
</P>
<P>
   For however much longer the season lasts, you can bet Murray
will continue to pull players aside daily for speeches that are
never canned. You see, to Murray his players are just like
snowflakes each uniquely different. He'd sooner run an unscripted
practice than treat his players like interchangeable parts.
</P>
<P>
   He recognizes that Fiset's personality is different than Storr's
and handles each netminder accordingly. Fiset is more sensitive and
wears his passion like extra padding.
</P>
<P>
   ``That comes from being French-Canadian,'' Murray said,
referring to the goaltender's Montreal roots.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing Fiset as well as he does, Murray made a point of pulling
Fiset early in Game 2, benching him just long enough to tell him
``I have confidence in you.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he had to chase after Fiset first. His memories of
1998 opened like an old scab, the goaltender headed straight down
the hall to the dressing room, assuming his day was done.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes into the second period, it would be. But even as
he supplanted Fiset with Storr, Murray whispered reassuring words
into Fiset's ear. He knew then, even if the dejected goalie didn't,
that he would go back to Fiset on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing in coaching,'' Murray said, ``is you can't ever do
something or say something you can't follow through on.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, that's the thing in playing, too, and Monday the
Kings' special teams simply didn't follow through.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
