<HEADER>
A0108 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN     04-18 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS RUNNING OUT OF CHANCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It looked like the fans wore black for a reason,
but the Kings were just itching to take a peek under the shroud of
the Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   After playing most of Monday like they had nothing to win, the
Kings finally came out in the third period with nothing to lose.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, they still lost 2-1 to the Red Wings and now face
the hockey no-man's-land of trying to come back from an 0-3
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   But they gave themselves and the 18,118 at Staples Center a few
moments to remember in the third period, beginning with a goal by
Luc Robitaille and a jump in their step that brought cheers from
the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille's goal, the 49th of his playoff career, came just
three minutes into the period after the Kings had fallen behind. He
did not have a shot in the game's first 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a disastrous power play that is 0 for 16 in this
best-seven series, the Kings started to apply pressure. Several
minutes later, seldom-used Brad Chartrand had playoff hero written
on his jersey when he took a pass from Ian Laperriere in front of
the Red Wings' net with a chance to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   But goaltender Chris Osgood, who shut out the Kings in Game 1
and held on for dear life to win Game 2, made the stop.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Red Wings are one game from heading to the second
round and one game from their third consecutive series sweep in a
playoff series opener.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings now face the daunting task of coming back from 0-3,
accomplished only twice in NHL history.
</P>
<P>
   The first happened in 1942 when the Toronto Maple Leafs won four
straight to defeat the Red Wings for the Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, the New York Islanders defeated the Pittsburgh Penguins
in the Eastern Conference finals after falling behind 0-3.
</P>
<P>
   Osgood's save destroyed the Kings' momentum and they never
seemed to recover.
</P>
<P>
   After each game in the series they came away saying they had
shown the Red Wings their best.
</P>
<P>
   In a 2-0 loss in Game 1, the Kings held their own against the
Red Wings' superior talent, but couldn't quite make it through the
neutral zone.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 2, they lost 8-5 but refused to back down from Detroit's
fire power.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there is a reason staying close has not been good enough
in this series. Most of the Detroit players are holdovers from
Stanley Cup champions two of the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   But at the end, goaltender Stephane Fiset showed why he has been
the Kings' most consistent player in the series, even though he
allowed nine goals in three games.
</P>
<P>
   With 4:55 remaining, Detroit's top player Steve Yzerman had a
chance to put the game away when he broke in on Fiset. Yzerman
waited until Fiset dropped to the ice before shooting, but Fiset
made a spectacular glove save agains the left goal post.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not enough for the Kings, who managed just 22 shots
on Osgood. They went 0 for 6 on the power play, including a
four-minute man advantage four minutes into the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit jumped on top just 5:21 into the game because of another
Kings problem: too many penalties. The Red Wings enjoyed a
five-on-three advantage after Rob Blake was whistles off for high
sticking.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit, which led the league with a 20.3 percent conversion
rate on the power play, toyed with the Kings in their zone. Sergei
Fedorovwon the faceoff after the Blake penalty, took a spot near
the Kings net and beat Fiset after a pass from Niklas Lidstrom.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings second goal, the eventual game winner by Tomas
Holmstrom also came on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   With 14:40 gone in the second and Jozef Stumpel off for cross
checking, Holmstrom redirected a Lidstrom shot past Fiset.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
