<SLUG> BC-PINNACLE-MERGER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINNACLE MERGER CREATES MAJOR PLAYER IN CASINO INDUSTRY
</HEADLINE>
bc-LADN-PINNACLE.F (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON TAKENOUCHI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE, Calif. _ Pinnacle Entertainment Inc., the
Glendale-based casino owner and operator, said Monday that it has
agreed to be purchased by a subsidiary of Harveys Casino Resorts
for up to $1.3 billion in cash and assumed debt.
</P>
<P>
   Under the planned merger, Lake Tahoe, Nev.-based Harveys' newly
formed subsidiary, PH Casino Resorts, would pay $24 per share for
all of Pinnacle's stock.
</P>
<P>
   PH would pay an additional $1 per share if Pinnacle sells its 97
acres of surplus land in Inglewood for at least $40.75 million
after taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Harveys would also assume about $625 million in Pinnacle debt
under the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The deal _ signed early Monday _ marks the end of an era for
Pinnacle. In recent years the former owner of Hollywood Park
racetrack in Los Angeles has transformed itself from a horse racing
firm to a major player in the gambling industry, with eight casinos
in Nevada, Mississippi, Louisiana and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger consummates the transformation,'' said Bruce
Hinckley, Pinnacle's senior vice president and chief financial
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Hinckley said the deal would create the fifth-largest casino
company in the country and one of the biggest players in markets
outside of Las Vegas and Atlantic City, the traditional capitals of
U.S. gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The board of directors for Pinnacle and Harveys have already
approved the deal. Pinnacle senior management would retain a $50
million investment in the merged company, and Hinckley said
Pinnacle's management would likely continue operating the new
firm's casinos.
</P>
<P>
   But the merger still faces several hurdles, including the
approval of Pinnacle stockholders and gaming regulators in several
states.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Rafferty, senior vice president of marketing for Harveys,
said he expects the regulatory process to go smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of these are outstanding, well-run casino companies,'' he
said. ``We're assuming licensing will be positive.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal is also contingent on the timely completion of
Pinnacle's Belterra Resort and Casino in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The resort is key to the success of the merger, according to
analyst Mike Crawford of B. Riley &AMP; Co. in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most attractive thing about Pinnacle, besides cash coming
in from asset sales, is the crown jewel resort they're building in
Indiana,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford estimated that the new project could create cash flow
of $40 million in its first year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 0159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
