<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0110 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KINGS-SIDE-LADN     04-18 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER OUTAGE FOR KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's called a power play, but for the Kings, it's
more like powerless play.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen times in this Western Conference first-round series with
Detroit, the Kings have had a man advantage, including seven times
for 11 minutes, 29 seconds in Monday's third game. Each time, they
failed to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's anemic right now,'' defenseman Garry Galley said.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the Kings locker room disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   Not after taking just one shot during a four-minute power play
in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Not after spending more time chasing down the puck than setting
up shots.
</P>
<P>
   Not after taking no more than two shots on any chance over the
final two periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the time, we were going crossways instead of
north-to-south,'' Galley said. ``We struggled to get the puck in
good position. We know our assignments. We just have to execute.''
</P>
<P>
   Executing on the power play has been a problem for much of the
season. Sure, the Kings started the season scoring at least one
power-play goal in eight of their first 10 games, helping
themselves eventually reach not only the Pacific Division lead but
also the Western Conference's best record.
</P>
<P>
   But that was back in October and November. In March, the Kings
scored on just five of 59 attempts and finished the regular season
60 for 355 (16.9 percent). Amazingly, that ranked them 10th in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   That won't get it done in the playoffs. They can only wish they
can reach 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our power play didn't make the other team pay,'' Kings coach
Andy Murray said. ``They took as many bad penalties as we did, but
we couldn't take advantage. The best way to take advantage when a
team is playing physical is to score goals on the power play.''
</P>
<P>
   And they didn't, in part because the Red Wings took Rob Blake
out of the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit decided Blake was the key to the Kings attack, so it
shadowed, checked and poked him wherever he went. Blake got off
just three shots the entire game, none of which were quality
power-play shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made it tough for them getting the puck into their zone,''
Detroit goalie Chris Osgood said. ``We got on Blake and forced him
to make bad dumps.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just the Red Wings, however. The Kings' first
opportunity ended after just 57 seconds when Luc Robitaille was
called for charging in the attacking zone.
</P>
<P>
   But the worst came early in the second period, when Detroit's
Darren McCarty was called for tripping, complained and was hit with
an unsportsmanlike conduct penalty, giving the Kings a man
advantage for four minutes while down 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   When that ended with one shot, by Ziggy Palffy on a breakaway
right into Osgood, the crowd booed, and it booed often because
numerous times the Kings would pass behind to no one, and the puck
would slide into the neutral zone.
</P>
<P>
   With 4:55 to play, Chris Chelios went off for holding with the
Red Wings holding a 2-1 lead. Two minutes later, the score remained
the same, and the Kings had taken just one shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some good chances on the power play,'' center Ian
Laperriere said. ``We have to keep working and try to put some
traffic in front of the net.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 0217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 02:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0113 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-L     04-18 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS RUNNING OUT OF CHANCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The fans were dressed in black, but it was the
Detroit Red Wings who wore the shroud.
</P>
<P>
   They sent the Kings to the no-man's land of playoff hockey
Monday night with a 2-1 victory at Staples Center, giving Detroit a
staggering 3-0 lead in this best-of-seven first-round series.
</P>
<P>
   Only two teams have come back from such a hole, now a black hole
that 18,118 fans couldn't help fill.
</P>
<P>
   And though there are plenty of numbers that help explain the
Kings' predicament, like 0 for 16 on the power play and 0 for their
last 11 playoff games, it's the words from coach Andy Murray after
Game 1 that still haunted his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played well enough to stay close but not well enough to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   They still gave up too many penalties to the league's best power
play. Both Red Wings goals _ by Sergei Fedorov just 5:21 into the
game and Tomas Holmstrom 14:40 into the second came with the man
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But now the Kings have not won a playoff game since Game 1 of
the 1993 Stanley Cup Finals. And they aren't sure why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that is the biggest question of this series,'' said
defenseman Mattias Norstrom. ``Why have we done well but come up
short? One thing I do know, we will be back Wednesday (Game 4) and
our heads will be held high.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem Monday was except for a few sparkling moments early
in the third period _ when Luc Robitaille scored and seldom-used
Brad Chartrand had a chance to tie _ the Kings rarely matched up
with the Wings.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille's goal, the 49th of his playoff career, came 2:35
into the third period. But for the first 40 minutes, he did not
have a shot on Detroit goaltender Chris Osgood, who shut out the
Kings in Game 1 and held on for dear life to win Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, when Chartrand had playoff hero written on
his jersey after taking a pass from Ian Laperriere, Osgood was
there again. It destroyed the Kings' momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every minute of this series the Kings have been playing
real well,'' Osgood said. ``We've been battling for everything
we've earned.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings now face the daunting task of coming back from 0-3,
accomplished only twice in NHL history.
</P>
<P>
   That first happened in 1942 when the Toronto Maple Leafs won
four straight to defeat the Red Wings in the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, the New York Islanders defeated the Pittsburgh Penguins
in the Eastern Conference finals after falling behind 0-3.
</P>
<P>
   In a 2-0 loss in Game 1, the Kings held their own against the
Red Wings' superior talent but couldn't quite make it through the
neutral zone.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 2, the Kings lost 8-5 but refused to back down from
Detroit's fire power.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there is a reason staying close has not been good enough
in this series. Most of the Detroit players are holdovers from
teams that won the Stanley Cup two of the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   But at the end, goaltender Stephane Fiset showed why he has been
the Kings' most consistent player in the series, even though he
allowed nine goals in three games.
</P>
<P>
   With 4:55 remaining, the Detroit's top player, Steve Yzerman,
had a chance to put the game away when he broke in on Fiset.
Yzerman waited until Fiset dropped to the ice before shooting, but
Fiset made a spectacular glove save against the left goal post.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset was pulled by Murray after allowing five goals in Game 2.
Murray blamed his defense and vowed to stick with Fiset.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, the Kings got his best Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really important for me tonight to prove to Andy that
he did the right thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
