A0223 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l WEBS&AMP;MAGS &LR;      04-18 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 WEBS&AMP;MAGS  
 Please call (602) 444-8298 for cost information) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Editors: MOVING IN THE ``E'' AND ``L'' CATEGORIES. Here are
Bill Muller's capsule reviews of a Website and some current
magazines)
</P>
<P>
   WEBSITE
</P>
<P>
   Kosherfinder (www.kosherfinder.com)
</P>
<P>
   With Passover beginning Wednesday, there's no better time to
check in with Kosherfinder, a site that celebrates all things
Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   The opening page includes links to a special Passover report,
and also features sections on health and nutrition, wine, kosher
dishes, books, colleges and dispatches from Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the ``on campus'' features notes that this summer,
20 Dartmouth students will be participating in ``Israel 2000,'' a
program that allows Jewish college students who have never been to
Israel to visit the Jewish Holy Land for free.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the news section led off with a British court ruling
against historian David Irving, who challenged the scope of the
Holocaust. Irving had sued an American scholar for libel, claiming
she had labeled him a ``Holocaust denier.'' In ruling against
Irving, a British judge labeled him ``anti-Semitic and racist.''
</P>
<P>
   The Passover section is especially interesting, even for the
uninitiated. It explains the origin of the Jewish holiday, the
significance of the Seder plate and how to prepare for Passover,
among other things.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe section (known alternately as ``Kosher Classics'' and
``Bubbie's Kitchen''), offers Passover specialties, such as
cauliflower kugel with mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   You have to register to access the main areas of this site, but
the registration is quick and painless. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE REVIEWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MONEY
</P>
<P>
   In the problems-we-wish-we-had department, there's a big piece
on ``sudden-wealth syndrome'' {ndash} essentially people who strike
it rich investing in Internet stocks or somesuch and immediately
plunge into depression. Apparently, psychiatrists solve the problem
by charging outrageous fees and siphoning off some of that
new-found wealth. Favorite line in the piece, ``Once you're done
sneering{hellip}'' Oh, I don't think we'll ever be done. There is
also a fairly useful story on tech investing, which tries to steer
you toward the stock that isn't about to crash into a bridge
abutment and burst into a ball of flame. Bottom line: You might
have better luck picking winners at Phoenix Greyhound Park. There
is also an interesting short written by someone who made a cell
phone their only phone, and soon learned what ``searching for
service'' really means.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORKER
</P>
<P>
   It's only like a page long, but Chris Harris' takeoff on the
Census (an ersatz letter written by Census director Kenneth
Prewitt) is one long belly laugh. A few samples: ``We have been
accused of undercounting certain segments of the population. This
is simply not true, and we think all three of our nation's Native
Americans will back us up on this.'' Or, ``Moreover, although there
are no problems with the Census, we are constantly making
improvements to correct those problems.'' There is an interesting
piece on the Russian mob in America, noting FBI warnings that the
so-called ``Mafiya'' could soon become the No.1 criminal
organization in the U.S. Finally, an explanation for the popularity
of Yakov Smirnoff. A well-done piece on obsessive-compulsive
disorder questions whether it's such a great idea to drown the
``doubting disease'' in an ocean of Prozac.
</P>
<P>
   TRUE WEST
</P>
<P>
   This fun little mag , published in Cave Creek, devotes itself to
debunking some of the myths of the Old West perpetuated by
Hollywood. For example, John Wayne didn't really die in
(beginitalic)The Cowboys(enditalic). So you can stop being so mad
at Bruce Dern. Seriously, this month's issue notes that not all
cowboys carried Colt Peacemakers. Some, including notorious outlaws
Frank and Jesse James, were more partial to Remington revolvers.
Also, Wild Bill Hickok and Calamity Jane were not lovers, despite
what the supermarket tabloids said. There is also an interesting
piece on Western ``stock actors,'' who traveled from town to town
performing in different plays, making the grandiose sum of $8 per
week. The most famous stock performer may be John Wilkes Booth,
Lincoln's assassin.
</P>
<P>
   VANITY FAIR
</P>
<P>
   There is the usual Hollywood feature, this time on flaky cover
girl Kim Basinger, the Janie one-note actress who is always being
compared to someone who was a lot better. In this case, it's
Marilyn Monroe. Puh-lease. We get to hear about her angst over
being famous, beautiful and married to hunk movie star Alec
Baldwin. It's a heavy load to bear. Searching for more fluff? The
magazine doesn't disappoint, posing Sarah Ferguson in a blazer and
fishnet stockings for a Q&AMP;A. On the serious side, there is a book
excerpt on the real-life maritime disaster that inspired Melville
to write (beginitalic)Moby-Dick(enditalic): the 1820 sinking of the
Nantucket whaler, (beginitalic)Essex, (enditalic)by a rogue sperm
whale. Historian Nathaniel Philbrick draws on newly discovered
documents to weave the tale of the crew, who were driven to near
madness after being set adrift in the Pacific.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
