<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0225 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l NEW&AMP;NOTABLE &LR;      04-18 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 NEW&AMP;NOTABLE  
 NEW &AMP; NOTABLE (a) 
 &HT;    Please call (602) 444-8298 for cost information) 
 &HT;    (Editor's note: Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule book
reviews. 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By Anne Stephenson(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (EDITORS: MOVING IN THE ``E'' and ``L'' CATEGORIES)
</P>
<P>
   LAS MAMIS
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Esmeralda Santiago &QL;
</P>
<P>
   and Joie Davidow(Knopf, $20)
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Goldman ((beginitalic)The Ordinary Seaman(enditalic))
points out that Gabriel Garcia Marquez once was asked to write the
introduction to a book about Che Guevara, and he said, roughly,
``Sure, but I'll need 1,000 pages and 10 years to do it.'' That,
Goldman says, is the way he felt when he sat down to write about
his mother. But he managed (in only 12 pages), and so did the other
contributors to this anthology of poignant essays written by Latin
authors about their mothers. Dagoberto Gilb ((beginitalic)The Last
(enditalic)(beginitalic)Known Residence of Mickey Acuna(enditalic))
writes about his love as a young child for the beautiful woman who
gave birth to him, and the sadness of his estrangement from her as
he grew older. Editor Santiago (beginitalic)(When I Was Puerto
Rican)(enditalic) recalls the difficult life of her mother, a
determined, tenacious, sometimes violent woman who was, her
daughter says, ``an example of what we should avoid and what we
should aspire to.'' Other contributors include Junot Diaz and
Gioconda Belli.
</P>
<P>
   IN THE FALL
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Lent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Atlantic Monthly Press, $25)
</P>
<P>
   This is a terrific first novel that will appeal to readers who
loved Charles Frazier's 1997 book, (beginitalic)Cold Mountain.
(enditalic)You might even think they're the same story for a while,
because Lent's hero, like Frazier's, is a soldier making his way
home at the end of the Civil War. But Lent's Norman Pelham reaches
his family's farm in Vermont quickly and without trauma, and he
brings a woman with him. Her name is Leah, and she is a runaway
slave who helped Norman when she found him wounded in Virginia.
Lent's novel tells three stories: that of Norman and Leah, their
marriage and family and the making of their successful farm; that
of their troubled son, Jamie, a bootlegger during the years of
Prohibition; and that of Jamie's sweet-tempered boy, Foster, who
travels into the South to uncover the secret that eventually
destroyed his grandmother's life with Norman and their children.
There's violence, romance and poetic prose here, from a writer who
shows remarkable talent. Enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   BURT LANCASTER  &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kate Buford
</P>
<P>
   (Knopf, $27.50)
</P>
<P>
   During filming, studio censors suggested, laughably, that
``either Karen or Warden put on a beach robe or some other type of
clothing before they go into the embrace.'' Karen was Deborah Kerr,
Warden was Burt Lancaster, and the beach robe was notably absent
from their surf-jostled kiss in (beginitalic)From Here to
Eternity(enditalic). Lancaster, Buford says, ``blends into our
collective memory like a famous uncle who was once a great
athlete.'' Throughout his life, he was a study in contradiction.
Known for his rages, promiscuity and mood swings, he also was
capable of great kindness and loyalty. In his youth, he was one of
Hollywood's most macho stars, yet the town simmered with rumors of
his bisexuality. And his movies were both provocative
((beginitalic)Atlantic City(enditalic)) and vapid
((beginitalic)Airport(enditalic)). Most of all, he was known for
his physical presence - his strength, his beauty, his sexuality.
That's what readers bring to the table, and what makes this
biography so fascinating: our memories of how splendid he was.
</P>
<P>
   WANDERLUST
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Solnit
</P>
<P>
   (Viking, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Your mind will wander as you read this, and who's to say that's
not what it's supposed to do? Solnit offers a history of walking,
in which meandering, both mental and physical, is part of the
exercise. As Jean-Jacques Rousseau said, ``I can only meditate when
I am walking. When I stop, I cease to think; my mind only works
with my legs.'' Or, as Solnit writes, ``Walking is a state in which
the mind, the body and the world are aligned, as though they were
three characters finally in conversation together, three notes
suddenly making a chord.'' She discusses how walking touches many
fields - anatomy, gardening, anthropology, architecture, geography,
history, literature, philosophy, sexuality, religious studies.
This, of course, gives her license to talk about everything and
everyone, from the street sense of Charles Dickens to the poetry of
Gary Snyder to the role of walking in courtship, protest and
emancipation. Best of all, this is a book that encourages you to
put it down, and go for a walk of your own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0029 </DOCNO>
