A0234 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECHNO-NOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      04-18 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTER NET CALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phoning over the Internet still conjures up images of stringing
tin cans to your computer to make free, fuzzy calls to Pakistan.
But the technology is rapidly going mainstream, with a lot of help
from local companies.
</P>
<P>
   Burlington-based iBasis has just announced it signed a deal to
carry voice and fax traffic through carefully directed Net packets
with Operadora Protel, a top Mexican national carrier. More than 4
billion minutes of calls were made between the United States and
Mexico last year.
</P>
<P>
   iBasis is in a dogfight with California-based ITXC for bragging
rights to being the biggest phone-to-phone Net carrier. Already,
though, iBasis is handling about one of every 10 calls between the
United States and China. And the worldwide market for Internet
telephony is expected to hit $19 billion by 2004, according to
market analysts IDC.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge market there that's not going to go away for a
long time,'' says Ofer Gneezy, the iBasis cofounder and president.
``This space is so huge that we don't feel like anybody is crowding
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's announcement late last month that it was teaming with
partners to take a $1.4 billion stake in Net2Phone was also read as
a big stamp of approval for the technology. Net2Phone of
Hackensack, N.J., and New York-based Deltathree.com are leaders in
the computer-to-phone Net calling market, where you buy a headset
to make calls from your computer, often for free.
</P>
<P>
   Supporting the growth of Net telephony are a passel of local
system and equipment vendors, including Natural MicroSystems Corp.
of Framingham, Mass., which just reported a profitable first
quarter with revenues 67 percent ahead of last year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Built-in DSL modem
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Mansfield, Mass. unit of Motorola has unveiled software
technology that can eliminate the need for a separate modem to get
high-speed digital subscriber line Internet access for your
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Called SoftDSL, the product is expected to start appearing in
computers next winter, said Pat Casey, general manager of
Motorola's software products division. Instead of having to buy a
$199 DSL modem, you might spend half as much to get a built-in DSL
modem in your computer. Motorola also announced a faster, smaller
version of its built-in dial-up computer modem that is now barely
the size of a postage stamp.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Conversent deal
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Conversent Communications of Marlborough, Mass., a start-up
telecom business that focuses on markets the big guys often ignore,
is signing a $3.6 million, 20-year deal with NorthEast Optic
Network in Westborough, Mass. for fiber capacity to cope with rapid
growth and expand its operations around New England.
</P>
<P>
   Two-year-old Conversent has found a promising niche in smaller
cities such as Worcester, Providence, Quincy, and Lowell. Nearly
all of its customers have less than 24 phone lines. Its CEO, Robert
Fanch, sold his last business to Microsoft cofounder Paul Allen
last November. And with several former Brooks Fiber executives at
the helm, the company is looking to expand nationally into second-
and third-tier markets this year.
</P>
<P>
   In the same vein, Choice One Communications of Rochester, N.Y.,
has also been quietly making big inroads into Central and Western
Massachusetts, installing equipment to provide digital subscriber
line access for small businesses _ along with voice lines _ from 42
central offices from Bellingham to Deerfield.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Huh?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Are you in a fog about what all these new telecom products
actually do? Don't feel bad. Unisphere Solutions in Chelmsford
recently had Impulse Research of Los Angeles poll 200 CEOs and
chief information officers at Fortune 500 companies.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty percent said they can't understand what new technologies
they are being pitched are supposed to do, and almost as many said
technology vendors don't understand their needs. But fewer than 1
in 8 said they are confident their company has the communications
technology it needs for the near future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0235 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-NEWENGL-ECONOMY-BOS &LR;      04-18 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWENGL-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER THE FALL: SHAKY GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Buoyancy returned to Wall Street Monday, but a bear
market in technology stocks had already gone to work on the
Boston-area economy.
</P>
<P>
   With companies absorbing last week's market losses and halting
planned stock sales, economists and analysts said a
long-anticipated shakeout may finally be underway in the Internet
and software industries _ and may ripple into the larger economy.
</P>
<P>
   The local economy, with its huge stake in technology, expanded
in recent years with each 1000-point breakthrough by the Nasdaq
Composite index. So it follows that, as technology stocks fall back
to earth _ and analysts say they may fall further, despite Monday's
217.87-point rebound in the Nasdaq to 3539.16 _ the metropolitan
area inside Interstate 495 is more vulnerable than the nation
overall.
</P>
<P>
   That's the conventional wisdom. Some economists, however, say a
Nasdaq correction may actually restore balance to a tech-driven
economy that is increasingly out of whack. The Internet boom has
fueled huge appreciation in Boston-area real estate prices and
intensified a labor-market shortage that had already crimped job
creation in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear stories from non-(tech) employers who are happy this is
happening, because they figure they'll be able to fill some jobs
they haven't been able to,'' said Alan Clayton-Matthews, an
economics professor at the University of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   That logic may also apply to the US economy, which is beginning
to experience rising wages and prices.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market decline ``could be a very positive thing'' if
it causes ``enough cooling of the economy to prevent a boom-bust
scenario,'' said Rachael Chioino, an economist for Standard &AMP;
Poor's/DRI, a Lexington consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan has credited the
``wealth effect'' from rising stock prices with powering the
economic boom of the late 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow is now 10 percent below its January high. If a market
downturn dampens consumer spending, it may open a relief valve for
a US economy that is boiling over, some analysts say. Last week,
the Labor Department reported that the consumer price index surged
in March by 0.7 percent, with the inflation driven only in part by
higher oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened over the past week is exactly what Greenspan
might've been looking for in terms of squeezing some of the excess
euphoria out of the market,'' Chioino said.
</P>
<P>
   The economy grew at a 7 percent annual rate in the fourth
quarter. Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. forecasts that may be followed with 6
percent annual growth in the first quarter of this year _ a
revision from a prior 5 percent forecast _ due to unusually high
consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   Calling this performance ``really remarkable,'' John Youngdahl,
Goldman's senior money market economist, said, ``It remains to be
seen whether we've taken (the economy) off the boiler.''
</P>
<P>
   In the high-tech sector, a cooling off is inevitable, and it
will cause pain in hotbeds such as Boston, San Francisco, and
northern Virginia, economists say.
</P>
<P>
   They say Boston is in no danger of a crash like that experienced
in the late 1980s _ when minicomputer manufacturers, defense, and
housing went into a tailspin _ because the underlying economy is
sound.
</P>
<P>
   But funding for start-up software and Internet companies has
started to dry up, depriving them of money they would use to expand
and hire more workers. And employees at both large and small tech
companies have seen the value of their stock options plunge _
sometimes by half or more.
</P>
<P>
   The shakeout may cut into demand, too _ especially for high-end
housing, luxury automobiles, and mutual funds increasingly laden
with computer-company stocks, economists said. One of the largest
mutual funds, Fidelity Investments' Magellan fund, increased its
tech holdings during the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows what the fallout is going to be. We've never been
through exactly this before, but we will be impacted,'' said Fred
Breimyer, chief economist for State Street Corp. ``The high-flying,
sky's-the-limit view of the economy and markets is getting a sober
reassessment.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's rebound followed a historically bad week in which the
index lost a quarter of its value. But the uncertainty remained,
measured by wilder and wilder swings in tech stocks during the past
year. And it has shaken confidence, in the near future, in the tech
industry.
</P>
<P>
   That could cause a sharp reversal in the tech industry's recent
hiring binge.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, tech employment has expanded to about 10
percent of all jobs, driving the jobless rate down to 3.1 percent _
a full point below the US rate. Job growth in the nonmanufacturing
areas of high tech, such as software, surged 10 percent annually
during the mid-1990s and is still growing a robust 7 percent a
year.
</P>
<P>
   The downside of that tech explosion, which coincided with a boom
in the Boston mutual fund industry, is the strain on the state's
labor market.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, businesses such as banks and health maintenance
organizations have a tough time competing for starry-eyed young
talent drawn to promises of stock options and early retirement in
the technology field.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's great demand for those skills,'' Matthews said. The
tech stock correction poses the question for the local economy of
``how smoothly the transition will be from decreases in employment
at dot-com companies to filling unfilled positions in more
traditional firms.''
</P>
<P>
   Pay tends to be higher than average for high-tech employees,
whose compensation also may include stock. If the industry stops
hiring, sales of luxury goods may decline or grow more slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If annual increases in the high double-digit range in the
stock market turn into a flattish market, that will cause the
consumer to be a little more circumspect and cautious,'' said
FleetBoston Financial's chief economist, Wayne Ayers.
</P>
<P>
   Well-paid tech and biotech employees have pushed up housing
prices. If fewer cash in options to buy homes, said Jon Southard,
senior economist for Torto Wheaton Research in Boston, the housing
market may calm down.
</P>
<P>
   The same holds true for commercial real estate around Boston,
where vacancy rates have plunged to 5.9 percent. That's down from
17 percent in 1991, with much of the surge in demand coming from a
dot-com and Internet boom that has stretched the market to its
limits and driven up rents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good time'' for a Nasdaq correction ``because things
are so tight,'' Southard said. ``It could result in a sort of
settling down, rather than a crash.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0236 &Cx1f; tdt-z
