<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-PANIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ DISASTER SHAKES WORLD OF STOCK OPTIONS, IPOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, the employees of Boston's Zefer Corp. were
summoned to a meeting. It was to have been their IPO party.
</P>
<P>
   Caterers served wine and hors d'oeuvres for 200 in the Internet
consulting firm's downtown office. The top executives were back
after three weeks of wooing investors in 20 cities. Four hundred
colleagues in offices from San Francisco to London joined the
gathering by conference call.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no happy announcement. Instead, company officials
reported that the IPO was off.
</P>
<P>
   The news might have been shocking on any other day. But Nasdaq
stocks bled one quarter of their value last week, in the worst week
ever for the market that witnessed the dot-com boom and is now
seeing its bust.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were ready to go,'' said Zefer chief executive William
Seibel Jr. ``We saw an opportunity to go out there.
</P>
<P>
   We'll just wait for it to be back.''
</P>
<P>
   When the bruised technology sector will regain favor with
investors is the question bedeviling entrepreneurs, high-tech
workers, and investors from Boston to Silicon Valley. The market
for Internet-related stocks has tumbled 34 percent in a month, and
last week's massive losses sent shudders through the dot-com world.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies canceled stock offerings, while others worried
they'd run out of cash, unable to go back to the market to sell
more stock. Dot-com employers fretted about the waning appeal of
their stocks and options _ big selling points in recruiting and
retaining employees in the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   Every stock but one in the Globe's High-Tech 50 roster dove by
double digits last week. And it wasn't just the beleaguered
e-commerce companies. Sycamore Networks Inc., a telecommunications
company, lost 56 percent of its worth, as did Web-speed provider
Akamai Technologies Inc.
</P>
<P>
   On the West Coast, the young and disappointed drowned their
sorrows in microbrews at the Oasis Beer Garden in Menlo Park,
Calif. The Nasdaq free fall was the theme for last week's
not-so-happy hour, noted in e-mail invitations to dozens of dot-com
executives: ``Whining over market losses will engender sympathy.
There will be counseling for the afflicted.''
</P>
<P>
   Dark humor was the order of the evening, said Charles Wilson,
organizer of the weekly happy hour and vice president of marketing
for Pivia Inc., a Cupertino, Calif., Internet software company. So
was lamenting the fallen value of investment portfolios that hold
only Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like when you're taking an elevator, going down, and
there's this feeling of weightlessness right before the door
opens,'' said Wilson who, like so many at start-up companies, holds
options in his company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Gaw, research manager at International Data Corp. and a
regular at the happy hour, said: ``We talked about how there
haven't been any suicides because all of the buildings in Silicon
Valley are really short.''
</P>
<P>
   While ordinary investors bemoaned their paper losses in a
head-spinning week, insiders at high-tech companies tried to put a
brave face on the stock downturn. They noted that tech stock prices
may have gone too far, and that the market is merely back to where
it was a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been saying we didn't deserve this money and,
frankly, they were right,'' Gaw said. ``Technology used to be about
making cool stuff. Then a couple of years ago, it was about making
lots of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week's market tumble dashed many get-rich-quick dreams. And
there was little pity for the billionaire entrepreneurs ensnared in
the plunge. Chief executive David Wetherell's CMGI Inc. holdings
were slashed to $1.85 billion from nearly $4 billion in January.
Amazon.com chief Jeffrey Bezos's fortune has shrunk 59 percent
since December, to $5.51 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But the stock crash seems not to have dampened the spirits of
MBAs getting ready to join the technology wave. Some, though, say
they are mulling job prospects more carefully than a few months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Regnault, a 29-year-old student at MIT's Sloan School of
Management, said he plans to join Siebel Systems, a Silicon Valley
software company, after graduating next month. He shrugs off the
fact Siebel's shares have plummeted to $87 from $167 since March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not joining this firm to make a million bucks in my first
six months,'' Regnault said.
</P>
<P>
   That's not what lots of people already working for high-tech
companies say. Many of them joined pre-IPO start-ups, in hopes of
reaping big gains on stock and options when their employers went
public.
</P>
<P>
   At LavaStorm Inc., a closely held Internet services firm in
Waltham, chief executive Miller Newton said too many tech-sector
employees assumed options alone would make them rich. ``A lot of
employees who get stock options just don't understand them, and it
does cause a morale problem'' when riches don't materialize, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   John Courtney, LavaStorm's vice president for marketing, has
worked for three other technology companies since 1997 and jumped
ship when none became big hits. He expects Nasdaq's recent declines
will prompt plenty of similar moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this hyper-environment, it's hard to pick up a newspaper
and read about an Amazon or an eBay's success and not feel like
you're missing the boat,'' Courtney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially if you have a a friend at another company that's
really doing well, you can really feel like you're missing the
boat, and you have to dog-paddle over and get on another boat,''
Courtney said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wolfenberger, an investment banker with Credit Suisse First
Boston, who advised Zefer, said he got four calls on Thursday night
alone from CEOs who are worried about losing employees. Many
private employers say the recent stock selloff presents them with
an opportunity in this tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   BizLand.com chief executive Steve Sydness said he's been able to
hire 55 people in recent months. ``We're seeing a lot of people
with underwater options trying to get into better positions,''
Sydness said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, chief executives were suddenly talking about
long-term goals and profits _ an anomaly in the realm of upstarts
and serial entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com, which had planned to go public soon, put off its
IPO, fired 29 of its 200 employees in Framingham, Mass. and said
its days of free deliveries were over. Big furniture deliveries
will now come with a $95 delivery charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is looking for e-commerce companies to become much
more focused on the bottom line,'' company spokesman Don Goncalves
said. ``We've gone function by function throughout the business,
with an eye to fast-forwarding our path to profitablity.''
</P>
<P>
   Lower stock values could mean trouble for cash-strapped
start-ups. Young companies often run quickly through the cash they
raised in their IPOs, and a weak market means they may not be able
to go back for more. Forrester Research last week predicted that
half the e-commerce retailers that have sprung up will fail by the
end of 2001 next year.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon B. Hoffstein, chief executive of Be Free Inc., was
thanking his lucky stars that his company's secondary offering had
gone off well in February _ even as Be Free shares watched half
their value evaporate in a week.
</P>
<P>
   Coming barely three months after the Internet marketing services
company's initial public offering, the sale raised $100 million,
boosting Be Free's cash reserves to about $175 million. That's
enough to help weather additional market storms, Hoffstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel lucky. We have the money to compete,'' Hoffstein said.
``I believe we'll still be around'' when the correction is over.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffstein's personal stake in Be Free has declined substantially
in the stock drop _ to $33.7 million from $208 million at the peak
_ but the stakes are different for multimillionaires than for more
earthly investors.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran of four computer-based companies in two decades, he
calls himself conservative with his own finances. At 47, he has no
mortgage on his house. He invests mainly in corporate bonds and
large blue-chip stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in personal debt,'' Hoffstein said. ``I am
much more conservative with my own money than I am in business. I
only play with money that been given to me to play with.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors are increasingly expecting companies to be more
careful with the money entrusted to them. Gautam Prakash, a partner
with Bessemer Venture Partners, said the stock slump reflected a
loss of confidence in start-ups that were overfunded by imprudent
venture capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very rude awakening,'' he said. ``It's not healthy
to my pocketbook or yours, but it will ring out the excesses of the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology and innovation aren't going away, Prakash said. But
there's a much sharper focus on results now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CEO has to deal with questions that focus on the long
term,'' he said. ``It's not about a quick flip.''
</P>
<P>
   Private companies that do a good job will be able to get
continued funding from their venture capitalists to hold them over
until the market is better for public offerings, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfenberger, the investment banker, called Seibel and his
employees brave for delaying the coveted prize of the IPO.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes courage,'' he said, but it's best for the investors
and employees. ``It's harder to explain why you'd be willing to
give the company away at these levels.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, if a company goes public and its stock flops, it may
never come back.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Morse, director of an entrepreneurship center at MIT's Sloan
School of Management, has encouraged his students to see the recent
declines in technology stocks as a positive development.
</P>
<P>
   ``I welcome the shakeout, which separates the sheep from the
goats,'' Morse said. ``Now a line of bull and a Powerpoint
presentation won't be enough to get you funded anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good thing for the world and my students,'' Morse
said, ``because it means they'll go back to basics and create
sustainable businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alex Pham, Stephanie Stoughton, Jerry Ackerman, and Ross Kerber
of the Globe staff contribted to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
