<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-SEARCHES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORN OUT OF NET FRUSTRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ Like millions of Web surfers, Eric Ziering has
endured the hellish experience of spending days searching the
Internet for information he knew for certain was out there
somewhere _ but darned if he was ever going to find it.
</P>
<P>
   Many people just throw up their hands in frustration at the
message, ``Your search returned 29,212 pages matching your terms.''
Ziering decided to do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   He started a company.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, he launched Fact City, now a 27-person start-up.
The company has rolled out what is apparently the Web's first
service (www.factcity.com) that can respond to a typed-in question
with an answer and an attributed source, usually in as little as a
tenth of a second.
</P>
<P>
   Fact City is not a search engine, but a company that sells its
service to search engines and portals.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, ESPN.com and Fox's sports Web page unveiled Fact
City-powered services that can take a baseball query and give an
attributed answer. Type in the question: ``How many game-winning
RBIs did Mo Vaughn hit in 1996?'' You'll get the answer: ``Thirteen
in 161 games for the Red Sox, according to STATS Inc.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports is only the beginning. In time, Fact City hopes to
provide Web-based access to Census population numbers, restaurant
listings, corporate financial statements, election results,
geography facts, crime statistics, movie trivia _ basically any
kind of information you could imagine looking up in a book full of
tables.
</P>
<P>
   The world is seeing a mad rush to develop search engines that
will find the needle in the Internet haystack, which now totals
something like 1.5 billion pages of information.
</P>
<P>
   Besides such meta-search engines as Googol and Northern Light
that try to organize results from multiple searches, one of the
better-known attempts to respond to questions is Ask Jeeves. But it
mainly works by steering you toward the half-dozen Web sites that
seem most likely to answer your question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask Jeeves pretends they're like Fact City, but they're not,''
says Robin Schreier Hohman, an analyst with The Hurwitz Group in
Framingham who specializes in Web search engines. ``Fact City is
the first one I have seen that answers a specific problem that has
not been addressed yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Among services that try to get you to human beings through the
Net, AskMe.com in Seattle offers access to 30,000 experts who
answer questions. But it can take a while to wait for an answer to
come back. And trusting the source can be an issue.
</P>
<P>
   A host of companies are developing systems allowing you to find
the, say, 29 online retailers that sell men's argyle sweaters or
the dozen ISPs serving your town. And don't forget the helpful live
people at the Boston Public Library reference desk who can answer
millions of questions over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   With Fact City, ``you've got answers, not hyperlinks,'' said
Ziering, 42, a database-design veteran formerly with computer audio
start-up Cakewalk Software. ``We're allowing you to get to actual
databases, many of which are not on the Web anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that making money has suddenly become a less quaint idea for
dot-com start-ups, Fact City has a profit-minded business model. It
involves sharing banner-ad dollars during the presumably much
longer time people would spend using a Fact City-enhanced search
site, or perhaps getting bounties when people pursue answers to
source pages.
</P>
<P>
   Ziering launched the company soon after he tried to get some
information from the Web on personal computer ownership in New
England communities. That was in November 1998, when he was
thinking of launching a consumer Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   Today he says he can't even remember what the idea was. But in
his frustration with being unable to use the Web to find data he
knew had to be out there somewhere, Ziering saw a huge business
opportunity in creating a company that would get useful answers
from the Net.
</P>
<P>
   The technology that drives Fact City is subject to several
pending patents. Executives acknowledge it is best suited for
mining specific facts from rows and columns in a table, not
answering a subjective question like ``Where can I get a listing of
Cape Cod golf resorts?'' or a request for articles from magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of them as an empty database waiting to be populated by
whatever information is out there,'' said Schreier Hohman. ``What
it can't do is crawl the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Fact City technology uses fairly rudimentary
language analysis to interpret your question as a request to find
the piece of information that lies at the intersection of several
lines of data, like names, years, places, and numbers.
</P>
<P>
   You don't even have to add a question mark or use exactly the
right term: Punch in ``Pete Rose career whiffs'' and you'll get how
many strikeouts Charlie Hustle racked up.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Fact City, whose management team includes veterans
of Lycos, Motorola, and Torrent Systems, hopes to launch services
linking its search technology to entertainment sites, including
information about movies, television shows, and music.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has its eye on incorporating speech recognition
technology so that you could call a site on a wireless phone, ask a
question, and have the answer shot back as a message to the phone
screen. Another option could be studding online sports reports with
hyperlinks to every statistic you would ever want to know about an
athlete mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to respond to probably 80 percent of what
comes through a search engine,'' Ziering said. ``But when we don't
have any information, we have to be able to say `no' very fast. The
only question is: How much data do we load into our warehouse?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peter J. Howe is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached
by e-mail at howe(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
