<HEADLINE>
TWO DISTINCT WAYS TO LOOK AT THE KENTUCKY DERBY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are two ways to look at Kentucky Derby 2000. Either
Fusaichi Pegasus is a cinch, and all the other horses are running
for second money, or the race is wide open. If an observer doesn't
believe that Fusaichi Pegasus is the next Secretariat, there are at
least 10 other 3-year-olds who have a chance to wear the blanket of
roses on the first Saturday in May. They are: Anees, Aptitude,
Captain Steve, China Visit, High Yield, Impeachment, Mighty, More
Than Ready, The Deputy, and War Chant.
</P>
<P>
   There is ample evidence that Fusaichi Pegasus, a son of the
late, great Mr. Prospector, is a monster. He was a $4 million
yearling, which attests to his looks and confirmation; and, after
losing his first start by a neck, he has won four straight races
impressively. He defeated The Deputy, who went on to win the Santa
Anita Derby, in the San Felipe March 19, then made a lot of
converts with a strong tally over Red Bullet in the Wood Memorial
at Aqueduct Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The connections of Red Bullet, who was defeated for the first
time in four starts, certainly believe Fusaichi Pegasus is the real
deal. They withdrew the promising son of Unbridled from Derby
consideration Monday. ``We looked at everything, and decided to do
what is best for the horse, and not to just follow our hearts,''
said Joe Orseno, who trains Red Bullet for Frank Stronach and his
son, Andy. ``I think it says a lot about the Stronachs. How many
people would pass on a chance to run in the Kentucky Derby in order
to preserve the welfare and longevity of a horse?''
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet will be pointed straight to the Preakness, at Pimlico
May 20. ``This will give us five weeks to get Red Bullet ready,''
said Orseno. ``He'll be a fresh horse going against horses that
will have had a tough race in the Kentucky Derby. Our goal is the
3-year-old championship, and I really believe that when we look
back, we'll all feel we made the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet ran well in the Wood, but Fusaichi Pegasus ran right
past him at the eighth-pole, drawing away to score by more than 4
lengths. ``He was very fluid all the way around,'' said Kent
Desormeaux, who rides Fusaichi Pegasus. ``On the turn, he just
reached forward, and went after the targets. At that point I was
really confident. He did everything I asked in fine fashion. He's
certainly got a world of talent. The only question now is: Can he
get the mile and one-quarter? I think so. But it's a question we'll
have to answer on the first Saturday in May.''
</P>
<P>
   Which horse can handle 10 furlongs is always the key question at
the Derby, but Fusaichi Pegasus has other issues. He is headstrong,
and he balked, standing still at times, going to the gate and
coming back to the winners circle. A high-strung horse often leaves
his race in the paddock when he looks around and sees 150,000 noisy
spectators crowding every corner of Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a bit of a mind of his own, and he loves to look and
stare at things,'' said Neil Drysdale, who trains Fusaichi Pegasus
for Japanese entrepreneur Fusao Sekiguchi. ``We sent him to the
track with a different pony. He should have gone with his own pony,
and, next race, we'll send him with the pony he's accustomed to. He
doesn't get excited, he just gets to looking around. It's like he's
saying: `I'll come when I'm ready.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The drumbeat has just started for Fusaichi Pegasus, who was
flown to Louisville Monday. He was 4-5 in the Wood Memorial, and,
by the time the hype ends, he'll be odds-on in the Derby, too. The
choice is simple. You can try to beat him, or you can join him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pool closed
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The third and final Kentucky Derby Future Wager pool closed
Monday with Fusaichi Pegasus favored at 3-1. The odds on the Wood
winner are the lowest in the two years that the pool, which is
sponsored by Churchill Downs, has been conducted. The Deputy was
next at 6-1, followed by High Yield at 11-1. The field, which is
composed of any nominee not listed in the top 23 selected by a
panel of handicappars, stood at 12-1.
</P>
<P>
   One of the challenges of a future bet is that you lose if your
horse does not make the race, regardless of the reason. Those who
bet on Red Bullet, who closed at 18-1, lost Monday when his camp
declared it was holding him out.
</P>
<P>
   Combined wagering on the three pools was $1,158,919, up from
$676,233 last year. This year's third pool set the individual
record, with $387,206 wagered.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Four on the floor?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Todd Pletcher could have as many as four chances to pull
an upset in the Run for the Roses. Even D. Wayne Lukas would be
envious. Pletcher trains More Than Ready, Impeachment, Trippi, and
Graeme Hall, all apparantly headed to the Derby. Impeachment and
Trippi, who is an undefeated (4 for 4) front-runner, are owned by
Dogwood Stable, and would race as an entry. The other two are
privately owned. More Than Ready was second in the Blue Grass at
Keeneland; Impeachment was third in the Arkansas Derby at Oaklawn;
Trippi won the Flamingo at Gulfstream, and Graeme Hall won the
Arkansas Derby. ``It really hasn't sunk in yet,'' said Pletcher.
``It's hard to get one horse to the Derby. To have four in the same
year is really unbelievable to me. It's just been one of those
years where everything has come together at just the right time,
and things have gone well. I guess we'll have a pretty busy Derby
week, won't we?'' . . . Louisiana Derby winner Mighty, and Florida
Derby winner Hal's Hope, were major disappointments in the Blue
Grass. Mighty, who hit the side of the gate coming out, was
seventh, and Hal's Hope was eighth and last. ``He's fine, perfect,
couldn't be better,'' said Frank Brothers, who trains Mighty. ``I'm
not one to make excuses for my horses, but it could have been the
racetrack. He didn't seem comfortable running over it.'' ``I don't
know what happened in the race,'' said Harold Rose, the 88-year-old
trainer of Hal's Hope. ``He came out of it without a scratch. Maybe
the Florida Derby took more out of him than I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Material from publicity departments at various racetracks and trade
publications was used to prepare this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
