<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The news that knocked the market for a loop on Friday was a
government report that showed the underlying inflation in the
consumer price index rising in March at its fastest rate in five
years.
</P>
<P>
   What are the chances that the report was a fluke?
</P>
<P>
   Alas, not very good. With concern for the health of the
underlying US economy about to replace the pleasant euphoria of the
last six months, each new bit of data now will be scrutized with
the same kind of gimlet eye that last week cost the stock markets
$2 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Since virtually every recession since World War II has been
precipitated by a Federal Reserve Board determined to prevent a
still bigger crash by sharply raising short-term interest rates, a
suspenseful watch will be instituted.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Fed engineer yet another ``soft-landing?'' Or must the
longest expansion in history come to a painful end? The answer,
economists agree, depends on an intricate web of relationships that
simply are not very well understood, between stock market
valuations and consumer psychology.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer prices jumped 0.7 percent last month _ not, by itself,
a particularily persuasive indicator of a trend. The next major
readout of economic activity will be the manufacturing productivity
report for the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer England, who tracks government statistics for his Equity
Review, says that he expects it to be barely half of the robust
10.3 percent reported for the fourth quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Since only soaring productivity in the last few years has
enabled employers to pay higher wages without raising prices,
slowing productivity growth would be interpreted as a harbinger of
more inflation, since compensation costs already are rising at
increasing rates.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with rising inflation and falling productivity, the Fed
could have to tighten more dramatically, perhaps by as much as half
a point when they meet next May 16. The Fed already has increased
rates five times by a quarter point since last June in an attempt
to slow the bouyant spending that has been caused in part by
soaring stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   To understand changing attitudes towards the stock market,
you`ve got to understand that for most of the last year, the stock
market has enjoyed a holiday from ordinary economics.
</P>
<P>
   It was last September that the technology-rich Nasdaq composite
came unhitched from the Dow Jones Industrial Average, beginning a
dizzying upward march that had it doubling by mid-March, while the
Dow traded in a relatively narrow range.
</P>
<P>
   Many stories have been told to explain those values, but all had
one thing in common. They depended on continued low inflation to
protect the value of the future earnings streams for which
investors were paying record prices.
</P>
<P>
   When Alan Greenspan testified in Congress on Thursday, he said,
``If you look at the underlying cost structure of American
business, I see no evidence of an acceleration in unit costs.'' It
was in that context that Friday morning's announcement of the CPI
constituted such bad news.
</P>
<P>
   But didn't the strong performance Monday of both the Dow and the
Nasdaq signal that the long bull market still has a way to run? Not
necessarily. Despite the indexes, the broad market was Monday
decisively negative, with declining stocks outnumbering advancers
on both exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, bear markets are notoriously deceptive, holding out the
prospect of further advance for days and weeks at a time, before
settling to lower levels. First quarter earning reports may take
center stage for a time, before yielding the spotlight to
underlying economic data.
</P>
<P>
   The basic fact of the stock market remains that price-earnings
ratios are at historic highs _ nearly thirty times earnings in the
broad market, compared to a historic average closer to eighteen
times earnings. Periods of such rosy outlooks are not uncommon in
the history of the market; they can last for extended periods of
time. But they cannot withstand a determined Fed tightening.
</P>
<P>
   What price would bring valuations back in line with potential
earnings growth, adjusted for low inflation? Franco Modigliani of
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology estimates that a Dow of
around 9000 would do it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
