u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     04-18 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRICK NOW IS PICKING OUT TECH BARGAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One thing we can say with certainty about all those clobbered
technology stocks: Some are bargains, but others will languish or
fare even worse in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Telling them apart is the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Some extreme cases are obvious, either hopeless or
indiscriminately punished. But the bulk of the technology stock
market lies battered somewhere in-between.
</P>
<P>
   Ask professional investors how to separate the winners from
losers, and you will get a lot of different answers. But we heard a
smaller handful of issues popping up in one call after another.
Here are three of them.
</P>
<P>
   --Potential versus performance _ The answer isn't quite as
clean-cut as you might think.
</P>
<P>
   Actual financial performance clearly counts for more than
anything else now. That means earnings where you can get them, but
at least a pattern of accelerating revenues that would lead
reasonable investors to believe profits are around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   The tech stock rebound Monday may have been real or temporary.
But it was certainly driven by rising stock prices for very
profitable companies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, professional investors said they weren't giving up on all
companies without immediate prospects of any earnings. The catch,
they said, is the need for some tangible measure of robust business
growth, such as product orders, that can become the basis of a real
valuation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between aggressive investing and speculating is
whether you can get your arms around it fundamentally,'' said Fred
Kobrick.
</P>
<P>
   --Small versus large _ Hands down, larger technology stocks are
the better short-term bet, but that could change depending on how
long you're willing to wait.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual funds and other institutional investors sold some big
tech stocks last week because they were the most liquid and easiest
to unload.
</P>
<P>
   But those investors prefer big names and tend to gravitate back
toward them. No one is counting on institutions to take many
small-stock tech gambles right away, and no one is sure how
individual investors will react.
</P>
<P>
   ``Institutions have to go back to the most liquid names,'' said
David Smith, a money manager with Loomis Sayles in Boston. ``But
that's not to say over the next 12 to 18 months investors can't
make as good or better returns'' in smaller tech stocks. ``The
growth rates are much more dynamic at the smaller companies.''
</P>
<P>
   --Technology themes vs. individual performance _ Investment
themes drove huge sums of money into certain types of technology
stocks over the last year, often with little regard to the quality
of the individual businesses.
</P>
<P>
   High-speed telecommunciations, various corners of the Internet,
and biotechnology were all embraced as the places for investors to
be at one time or another. The good and the mediocre were bid up in
unison and usually dumped like hot potatoes the same way months
later.
</P>
<P>
   Investors won't be so indiscriminant about individual companies
this time, but themes will continue to play a big role in what
stocks are purchased.
</P>
<P>
   There is a tech stock theme at work right now, harder to see in
the confusion of the moment but still protecting some companies
from a deeper slide than they might have faced.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that make semiconductors or equipment used in the
manufacture of semiconductors are the clear favorites today. Most
did not fall as steeply as other tech stocks and, if Monday's
performance is any gauge, are first in line to bounce back up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their business is booming,'' said Alan Lowenstein, co-manager
of the John Hancock Global Technology fund. ``You probably have a
good 18 months of very good earnings growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Two local semiconductor equipment makers moved higher Monday.
Teradyne Inc. of Boston gained $11.8125 to $87.25; PRI Automation
Inc. of Billerica advanced $7 to $63.125.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tech stock bear market seems to be having an impact in the
venture capital world already.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Lax, the general partner in Softbank Capital Partners,
said he pulled three term sheets for proposed venture funding of
business-to-business oriented Internet companies in the last four
days.
</P>
<P>
   Lax's fund focuses on late-stage venture funding. He said he
pulled the plug because initial public offerings that had been
anticipated for those companies by late this year no longer seemed
likely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
