<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0419-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This old house
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Chicken Little was right. The sky is falling
_ all over the kitchen floor. Welcome to another episode of ``My
Old House.''
</P>
<P>
   The day dawned clear, and the sun rose in the east _ a good omen
for spring cleaning I hear. My helper Elaine and I were hard at it
_ she washing woodwork and vacuuming radiators downstairs while I
put the final touches on the upstairs bathroom _ the only one in
the house with a tub. Keep that in mind _ it's a clue. It couldn't
have been more than three seconds after I put down the last clean
rug, when I heard Elaine call. ``Elizabeth, you'd better come here.
There's a crack in the kitchen ceiling and water's dripping through
the plaster into the cat's food dish.''
</P>
<P>
   Believe me when I tell you there are any number of things the
owner of an 84-year-old house would rather hear than the sound of
water dripping _ anywhere _ but particularly through the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   My stomach churned _ I guess because my heart had just dropped
into it _ as we stood transfixed, watching each drop wiggle its way
through the fissure and fall to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly my entire wicked life began to flash before me. I
recoiled from the memory of the time I'd taken a nickel in change
out of the Sunday school collection plate and then gotten it stuck
in my windpipe. Mother liked to say I'd have choked to death if
there hadn't been a firehouse right across the street.
</P>
<P>
   Contrition for every breach of good manners and other rotten
acts, draped itself over me like a shroud. I even whispered an
apology to Phyllis Hofstedter for the time I flushed her Monopoly
tokens down the toilet because she'd never let me use the flat
iron.
</P>
<P>
   This must be the kind of stuff folks think about when they're
singing hymns on the deck of a sinking ship. Underneath the bravado
is abject penitence. And a little deal making _ ``I promise never
to... whatever...if this leak will stop.''
</P>
<P>
   For a brief moment I even had a nightmarish vision of standing
atop the stove as the waters rose, waving goodbye to the neighbors
and asking them to feed my cat.
</P>
<P>
   The moment of self-pity passed quickly. I grabbed the phone to
call Roger the plumber, my new best friend. Water dripped on my
head as I dialed.
</P>
<P>
   The plumbing shop lady told me Roger was on a job in a nearby
town but she'd see what she could do. I think I babbled something
about the Erie Canal. Five minutes later she called back to tell me
help was on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine finished up and left for the day. I sat on the kitchen
floor staring at the ceiling and trying to visualize the maze of
pipes lurking beyond the plaster. It wasn't pretty. By the time
Roger came in I was feverishly rambling on about moving to central
Florida and building a stilt house with no indoor plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``First things first,'' Roger said as he uprooted the toilet.
``This would be the most logical spot for a leak.'' A new seal and
a couple of flushes
</P>
<P>
   later, it looked like maybe he was right. No more drip. Then we
tried the tub. Guess what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Too much bathing,'' he teased. ``Running all that dirty water
down the pipes just wore 'em out.'' I muttered an apology and
suggested maybe he should moonlight as a stand-up comedian at Hoy's
bar.
</P>
<P>
   That was a week ago. Now I have half-a-new kitchen ceiling and
all new plastic drains. Roger said he'd never seen a house with
copper ones before.
</P>
<P>
   Said he'd been expecting rusty galvanized stuff.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, Roger's next door banging on the neighbor's pipes
and Tom the carpenter, painter, and plaster man, is rolling a final
coat of ivory on my new ceiling. Life is good again.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, Roger.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, Tom.
</P>
<P>
   And thank you Sharon, for letting me use your shower all week.
(I hope the guys digging up your septic tank aren't blaming me for
that too.)
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
