<HEADER>
A0262 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECHNOCAR19-COX     04-18 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOCAR19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Techno the music of car sales
 &HT;    By Chris Hutchins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The periodic table of elements flashes
on the screen. And then comes the sound _ a whooshing noise
somewhere between a jet engine and a tornado siren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scientists announced today the discovery of a new element,'' a
woman's voice announces. ``They're calling it Turbonium.''
</P>
<P>
   And so begins one of the latest Volkswagen ads. With an
electronic snarl, little computer-animated Beetles zip around in
atomic formation. The music picks up _ an infectious, grainy
amalgam of beats and bleeps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The addition of Turbonium to the periodic table of elements
... practical applications are still unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   The tune gets frenetic. Strange sounds _ are they pan flutes? _
swirl by. The bass keeps thumping. We're going at more than 140
beats per minute now.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, you've seen the guts of a ``Turbonium'' atom, and
you've seen the new turbo-charged Volkswagen Beetle from just about
every angle. But it's the music you remember. That's what got your
attention _ got your feet tapping and your head moving.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the point, say the folks at Volkswagen of America and
Arnold Communications, the Boston-based firm that created the
commercial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to create an image where people will remember us for
our music,'' says Liz Vanzura, director of marketing at Volkswagen
of America. ``When you go after the youth market, they're very
in-tune with music. They love what we do with it. It's our way to
carve a niche.''
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen isn't the only one banking on cool songs these days.
In the hyper-competitive automotive market, companies are using
music as an integral element for their commercials. Viewers have
heard everything from Van Halen (Nissan) to Ozzy Ozborne
(Mitsubishi) in car ads.
</P>
<P>
   But the music genre that's being tapped more and more is techno.
It's a kind of dance music, mixed and filtered through computer
software. That's what the Turbonium theme is. And so is the band
Orb's tune that's used in the Beetle's ``Reverse Engineered By
UFOs'' ad.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Nissan commercial features mechanical grinds created by
a musician named Rob D, which is perfectly synchronized to
on-screen robots building a Maxima.
</P>
<P>
   ``The role of music in car commercials is one of the last tools
in the marketer's arsenal,'' explains Rob Schwartz, creative
director of Nissan's ads at the firm TBWA/Chait/Day. ``It can get
under people's radar. People have grown up on commercials _ they've
seen everything. But the one thing that is disarming, the place
where you can connect, is the music. That's why it's been playing
such a prominent role.''
</P>
<P>
   And techno's prominence has been growing in advertising. Last
year, a song by the Norwegian band Biosphere was used in a Levi's
ad. In January, Pirelli tires used a Chemical Brothers tune to
accompany the adventures of a woman as she dashed through ice
plains, across lakes and over lava pits. Channel surf tonight, and
you'll probably see a Sears commercial hocking some hi-tech goods,
as an electronic beat keeps up. The new McDonald's Monopoly ads
feature electronic music, too.
</P>
<P>
   Why use this music? Ad firms are looking for tunes that fit the
mood of a commercial, says Vanzura. If you're making a gentle
commercial, you'll go for gentle music. But if you're doing a
commercial that evokes a ``technical'' emotion, an electronic,
high-paced feeling, you go techno, she says.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're attracting the youth market _ people college-age
to around 35 _ you want to go with what they know.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go by what we think goes best with the spot,'' Vanzura
says. ``We used techno for the Turbonium spot. ... We were
introducing a new engine technology; it was very
performance-oriented. So we wanted something fast.''
</P>
<P>
   They went to Ben Neill, a New York-based musician who began
experimenting in electronic music more than 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I immediately heard the sound, what it would be like to
actually be inside the atom,'' Neill says. ``That fast-spinning,
that rrrrshh. That was the motivation for that one. It came
together pretty quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   If you like techno, you love the ad. And you'll also probably
like what Neill's cooking up for VW later this year: Music for four
ads plugging VW's pre-owned cars.
</P>
<P>
   And if you don't like it? Plug your ears, because the techno
trend is going to continue, Vanzura says. ``Music is a big part of
us. It's gotten to the point where artists are calling us up, and
saying, `Please consider us for your next ad.'''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. Techophobes can always count on the U.S. Postal
Service. It's still using Steve Miller's ``Fly Like an Eagle'' in
its commercials.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT IS TECHNO?
</P>
<P>
   It's a music genre known for its fast beat, digitally processed
sounds and danceability. Popular at clubs and rave parties, techno
has its roots in Detroit, where underground DJs developed it during
the early 1990s. The most popular techno bands include Prodigy,
Chemical Brothers and Moby.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
