<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0263 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TESTDRIVE-AUDI19-COX     04-18 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE-AUDI19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A grand debut for Audi A8L
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Start enumerating the big luxury cars, and the
response is certain to include German-built sedans, but probably
none produced by Audi. But Audi justifiably hopes to change that,
among well-informed buffs at least, with the addition of the A8L.
</P>
<P>
   Although classified by the EPA as a midsize car, the A8L is a
formidable-appearing machine with a competent feel based on its
aluminum space-frame construction and ``quattro'' all-wheel-drive
system. Rear-wheel spin and front-wheel torque steer are difficult
to produce or detect despite the A8L's 310-horsepower V-8 engine.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being a top-of-the-category performer, the A8L
also ranks among the leaders in price with a base of $67,900. The
test car, with a full complement of options, totaled $72,525.
</P>
<P>
   Like the exterior, the interior is understated, with nice
touches including window screens, good drink holders and a concert
hall stereo with CD player. The A8L has the requisite
leather-and-wood touches, excellent seating and precise
fit-and-finish, but it's not a grabber. A first-time driver or
passenger may nod in satisfaction at the cabin, but isn't likely to
call it the epitome of luxury.
</P>
<P>
   The A8L drives in much the same manner, doing what's expected
with composure and _ appreciate it again _ the stability that comes
with a refined four-wheel-drive system. The steering's on the numb
side, and the A8L needs grippier, quieter tires than those on
showroom cars, but otherwise rides like a muted dream.
</P>
<P>
   Left alone, the five-speed automatic transmission is smooth up
and down through the gears, although it takes a firm foot to induce
downshifts for passing or merging with traffic. The Tiptronic
feature, allowing what's called ``manumatic'' shifting by flicking
the console-mounted shifter forward or back, may be a plus to some
drivers, a needless gimmick to others. The novelty soon wears off.
</P>
<P>
   What will endure is an appreciation of the seamless ride,
performance and ease of driving built into the A8L. Big ol' cars,
domestic or import, like the A8L prove that automakers can build
all-around satisfying vehicles with good safety features, but they
come with premium prices.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 2000 Audi A8L all-wheel-drive sedan
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $72,525 (base: $67,900, plus $525 delivery)
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 4.2-liter V-8 (310 horsepower), five-speed automatic
transmission with semimanual Tiptronic mode
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual front air bags, front and rear side air
bags, head-protective curtain side air bags, height-adjustable
front shoulder belts, power anti-lock disc brakes
</P>
<P>
   Options on test vehicle: pearl white paint, $1,200; 18-inch
wheels and performance tires, $1,500; xenon headlamps, $500; ski
sack, $200; acoustic parking, $700
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 17 mpg premium unleaded city, 24 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
