<HEADER>
A0267 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHARP-DRIVING19-COX     04-18 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    E-mail function on Cadillac might be a mixed blessing
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Are you a true member of the e-generation? Then odds
are you are one of the people that General Motors, specifically its
Cadillac division, is hoping to appeal to with the introduction of
the 2001 Web-enabled vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with the 2001 model year, all GM vehicles equipped with
OnStar will be able _ via a service called Virtual Advisor _ to
receive audibly a variety of information, including e-mail. All
2001 Cadillacs will come with OnStar as standard equipment. It will
be optional on selected other models.
</P>
<P>
   You set up a personal account to specify what information you
want. To access it, you simply push the vehicle's OnStar button.
</P>
<P>
   The list of options will include news headlines, sports scores,
stock quotes and e-mail. No more will you be stuck in those
seemingly endless traffic jams with nothing to do.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more. Through technology provided by collaboration
of Bose Audio Systems and Delphi Automotive Systems, the 2001
Cadillac Seville and DeVille models will become the first vehicles
to offer an installed PC.
</P>
<P>
   These two Cadillac models will combine the functionality of the
OnStar system with an in-car PC and a digital voice recorder.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the scenario. You are on your way to work. Barely out
the back door, you find yourself stuck in traffic. You call OnStar
and request your e-mail summary. Up pops ``Call your boss,'' so you
ask the attendant to read the entire e-mail. The boss gives a phone
number where he can be reached. You record that number on your
digital recorder. Then you activate your audio-controlled cell
phone, telling it to dial the number you have stored on the digital
recorder.
</P>
<P>
   Your boss announces that he wants you to attend a meeting in an
hour _ in the opposite direction of where you are heading. You
record that information on the digital recorder. You pull to the
side of the road and activate the car's on-board navigational
system and program in the street address. With turn-by-turn
instructions, your Cadillac gets you out of the traffic jam and
leads you to your meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty cool, huh? Or is it?
</P>
<P>
   I have mixed emotions about the concept of being multifunctional
while driving a car. Call me old-fashioned, but I think a vehicle
in motion requires all the driver's attention. That's not just
hands and eyes, but the brain as well.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, I can appreciate that in today's fast-paced
society, there are those who will welcome this opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac's general marketing manager Mike O'Malley claims
motorists spend about 500 million hours a week in their vehicles.
So Web-enhanced vehicles could result in increased productivity _
not to mention a longer workday.
</P>
<P>
   But General Motors is to be applauded for making this system as
distraction-free as possible. Gratefully, the e-mail screen is
blanked out whenever the car is in motion, allowing the driver to
receive this information audibly.
</P>
<P>
   Hand-held cell phones are enough of a distraction. Can you
imagine the road rage that could be generated by someone stopped in
the middle of rush hour reading e-mail?
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp, a training consultant to auto manufacturers, writes
for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
