<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
  
 
 Yo, Martha Stewart: The demitasse has been thrown   
 By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many of us, I suspect, are still a little wobbly and woozy from
last week's shocking announcement: Martha Stewart may bug out of
the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   In a piece for The New York Times, the titaness of taste and
tidiness revealed that she's fed up with life in fashionable
Westport, Conn. It seems she recently tried to give several new
neighbors fresh eggs and garden produce, only to be snubbed _
``once with a slammed door!'' So she's moving.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about you, but I smell weakness in good old Mart,
and I couldn't be happier.
</P>
<P>
   At long last, here's my chance to ``redecorate.'' While she's
busy packing up her belongings in boxes stylishly redone in pastels
and flowery prints, I intend to stage a hostile takeover of her
newspaper column.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, I'm a guy, and a rather slobby one at that. But I'm
confident I can bring a breath of fresh, albeit garlicky, air to
the home decorating racket. (I'd know exactly what to do if someone
slammed the door on me and my housewarming gift. I mean, c'mon,
(ITAL)I'm carrying eggs.(END ITAL) Duh.)
</P>
<P>
   So here, without further ado, is my first installment of Daryl
Lease Living. I call it, ``Drinking problems: The only one I got is
finding a halfway clean cup ...''
</P>
<P>
   When my wife and I got engaged nine years ago, I manfully tried
to convince her we should ``register'' at our bank and list our
checking account number as our ``pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   She wouldn't go for it, so instead of cash, we ended up with a
lot of expensive pieces of china and silver that _ from Day 1 _ I
have not been allowed to handle unsupervised. I can't even go near
the plates, lest I do something foolish like, say, eat a sandwich
off them.
</P>
<P>
   I accept this as a fact of married life. It's OK. Truth be told,
we hubbies can't quite make out what most of these things are for
anyway. A sorbet spoon? (ITAL)Please.(END ITAL) If you're going to
serve us fancy ice cream, have the decency to give us utensils of
appropriate size so that we can eat the stuff before it melts.
</P>
<P>
   I can live with the fact that most of our kitchen is devoted to
items we use only on very, very special occasions _ occasions that,
not coincidentally, are guy-free.
</P>
<P>
   I really had to object, though, when my lovely bride tried to
push this china-and-silver frippery too far and ruthlessly demanded
that I not bring into our marriage a very, very special _ nay,
sacred _ form of kitchenware from my bachelor days.
</P>
<P>
   I'm speaking, of course, of plastic stadium cups. Lots of guys
have them. All women hate them.
</P>
<P>
   Like snowflakes and fingerprints, no two plastic cups are alike.
They may emerge from factories the same, all sparkly and
dishwasher-safe, but they quickly assume their own distinct
personalities _ faded, scuffed and usually a little warped.
</P>
<P>
   Some plastic cups are simple works of art, brightly colored but
unadorned. Others are decorative, often recalling a special event.
A college keg party. A ballgame. A night at a classy restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   These unassuming plastic cups are, of course, as much a part of
a guy's life as a well-worn, comfortable T-shirt, or a well-worn,
comfortable pair of jeans, or a well-worn, comfortable pair of
shoes. What's more, they're darned useful.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fairer gender's reputation for common sense and
practicality, it's been my observation that they often fail to see
the beauty in utilitarian objects. They favor form over function,
image over substance, polish over spit.
</P>
<P>
   They prefer pretty but unusable china over perfectly good,
discount-store plates. They toss out our fine, serviceable plastic
cups in favor of fragile stemware that holds no more liquid than a
demitasse. (At least I think that frou-frou, thimble-sized cup is a
demitasse. I can't get close enough to identify it with accuracy.)
</P>
<P>
   Through a bit of diplomacy on my part, my wife and I have
reached a compromise. I am allowed to stash a specific number of
plastic cups _ four _ in a remote kitchen cabinet. I can bring them
out only for use by guys. (I refused her demands to do so only with
the shades drawn.)
</P>
<P>
   So far, the system has worked well, but I would caution all men
to remember the old nuclear arsenal adage: Trust but verify. Count
the cups before they go in the dishwasher, and count them as they
emerge. It's the only way to keep the peace.
</P>
<P>
   (ITAL)Next week's Living:(END ITAL) ``The toilet seat: What's
the deal? Why can't they put it up when they're done?''
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
