   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-ISUZU-TROOPER (San Antonio) _ I heartily recommend that you
test-drive a new Isuzu Trooper if you're in the market for an SUV.
And if price is a concern, you might be pleased to know that for
2000, Isuzu has introduced the first-ever two-wheel-drive version
of the Trooper, which lowers the price a bit for people who don't
need four-wheel drive. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-MAPS (San Antonio) _ Want to get something for the man who
never asks for directions? Check out the latest in hi-tech maps:
computerized automotive navigation systems, with their own
interactive video screens within eyesight and reach of the driver.
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SUV-HYBRIDS (San Antonio) _ For many rugged types, this
just might be the best of two worlds: the marriage of a pickup and
a sport-utility vehicle. Automakers call it a hybrid, designed to
bring consumers the two types of vehicles that are the hottest
among U.S. consumers. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EBONICS (San Francisco) _ In ``Spoken Soul,'' father and son
John and Russell Rickford render a 267-page analysis of the
language of black folks, now commonly known as Ebonics. John
Rickford, a Stanford University linguist, and Russell Rickford, a
former Philadelphia Inquirer reporter, argue that spoken soul (a
term writer Claude Brown coined in the '60s) is a language African
Americans should celebrate and proudly claim as their own, in
addition to mastering standard English. By VENISE WAGNER.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SF-GROWTH (San Francisco) _ A new plan to give the cramped
dot-com industry more space to grow in San Francisco has ignited a
long-simmering battle over the city's development, pitting the
entrepreneurs of high-tech against the advocates of slow growth. By
RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The latest fad in this
complicated world is simplicity and how to achieve it. Apparently,
the first thing you have to do is complicate your life with more
magazines and Web sites. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Are you ticked off at the
federal government for anything? Hate paying all those taxes, for
instance? Think NASA is a big waste of time and money? Maybe you
just liked the way Old Glory looked with 48 stars and want to
rescind Alaska's and Hawaii's statehood. Have we got the solution
for you. Call the 800 number now scrolling across your screen and
find out where the nearest Elian's Miami Relatives School of Civil
Disobedience is located in your area. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   PAUL-REVERE (Danville, Calif.) _ April 18 is the anniversary of
a historical moment remembered primarily because of its rendering
as ``true story'' art. The moment is a night in 1775 before the
American Revolution. The artist is poet Henry Wadsworth Longfellow.
The art is Longfellow's famous poem, ``Paul Revere's Ride,''
written 85 years after the event. The discrepancies between
Revere's real ride and his ride in the poem are many; they force us
to question how seriously (if at all) we should trust artists to
tell the truth. By CYNTHIA BASS.
</P>
</TEXT>
