A0315 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     04-18 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE REVEALING CENSUS QUESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have just received preliminary results of 2000 census and I
must admit that I find some of the statistics rather startling.
</P>
<P>
   According to the new census, only 11,486 people now live in
Florida, compared to 13 million in 1990. This huge population drop
comes as a pleasant surprise because I was under the impression
that Florida was growing more crowded by the second to the point
that the combined weight of its inhabitants was causing it to sink
into the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Since the census is conducted by the U.S. government, I know it
must be infallible, but I still have trouble believing 11,988,514
people moved out of Florida in the past 10 years without anyone
noticing. Perhaps this is just another example of how the Monica
Lewinsky scandal riveted our attention to the point that we were
unaware of any other news.
</P>
<P>
   Another interesting statistic that I have combed from the new
census is that 75 percent of U.S. families list their annual income
as ``none of your $%&AMP;(AT)(NU) business.'' This is a substantial
increase, or possibly decrease, from the 1998 median family income
of $44,568. It will take a better economist than I to determine if
``none of your $%&AMP;(AT)(NU) business'' reveals a robust economy or
one where citizens will soon be reduced to filling the tanks of
their SUVs with eyedroppers.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of U.S. citizens has also undergone a dramatic
transformation, according to the preliminary figures I have been
provided. In 1998, the median age of Americans was 35 years; in the
year 2000, the median age is ``sit on it.'' What exactly this will
mean to Florida, which has a large (256) population of people 65
and older, is unclear. Federal funding for programs for the aged
will probably depend on whether a Washington bureaucrat interprets
``sit on it'' to mean that our senior citizens are more in need of
federal handouts or less.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, 16 percent of Florida residents were foreign-born. This
year, the number of Florida residents who are foreign-born is
``so's your mother.'' I am not conversant in foreign languages so I
cannot say if ``so's your mother'' is of Spanish, French or German
derivation, but I think it's clear that our state is enjoying, or
suffering through, a period of unprecedented, or perhaps utterly
predictable, cultural diversity the likes of which this great
nation has never, or has often before, seen.
</P>
<P>
   There was some concern early on that citizens would refuse to
fill out their census forms, or would provide inaccurate
information, out of fear that the information would be leaked to or
pirated by unscrupulous parties other than the federal government.
Happily, this did not happen. According to the Census Bureau, 85
percent of Florida's 11,486 residents returned their forms and not
only completed every line but also often included extra,
unrequested information, such as suggestions as to where the Census
Bureau could get off and how cold a day in hell it would be before
they would reveal their child-care arrangements or how many days
they had been unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to know that the American people still trust their
government to the point that they will gladly and voluntarily share
with it intimate details of their personal lives that they would
not feel comfortable talking about with other family members or
best friends.
</P>
<P>
   If the government says it needs this information, than it must
be so, because the government has never lied to us in the past, or
at least admitted to it.
</P>
<P>
   And besides, if it weren't for the census, how would we know
that the number of American adults who have been divorced jumped,
or plummeted, from 10 percent in 1997 to ``bite me'' in 2000?
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
