   BROADWAY-CONDUCTOR (New York) _ Conductors on Broadway are often
overlooked as so much wallpaper, just some guy waving a stick under
the stage. But in addition to conducting the orchestra _ which
does, in fact, take considerable technical skill _ musical
directors play a major role in shaping a show as the liaison
between the composer and the theater company. After more than 30
years as musical director of almost every Sondheim work as well as
productions by other composers ranging from flops like ``High
Society'' to hits like ``Crazy for You,'' Paul Gemignani has become
something of a legend. By Robin Pogrebin.
