<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0319 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-SUV-HYBRIDS-HNS &LR;      04-18 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SUV-HYBRIDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AUTOMOTIVE `HYBRIDS' COULD BE THE NEXT BIG THING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ For many rugged types, this just might be the best
of two worlds: the marriage of a pickup and a sport-utility
vehicle. Automakers call it a hybrid, designed to bring consumers
the two types of vehicles that are the hottest among U.S.
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. and General Motors Corp. earlier announced plans
for their own versions of the hybrid pickup-SUV. But Ford's 2001
Explorer Sport Trac is the first to market _ it went on sale in
late January.
</P>
<P>
   Early next year, Chevrolet will introduce the 2002 Avalanche, a
cross between the full-size Tahoe SUV and Silverado pickup, and the
S-10 Baja, a mixture of the compact S-10 pickup and Blazer
sport-utility, GM spokesman Roger Gray said from the company's
Dallas office.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche has been described as a Swiss Army knife with a
V-8 engine. It comes with a 5-foot-3-inch bed that can be extended
to 8 feet by removing the ``midgate,'' which separates the back
seat from the cargo area, Gray said. It's based on the platform of
the full-size GM pickups.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's Lincoln division plans to introduce the Blackwood, a
blend of the full-size Lincoln Navigator luxury sport-utility and a
pickup. A variant of the Blackwood was shown at the 1999 North
American International Auto Show in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   That was when Ford also showed the first Sport Trac, which now
has begun flowing from the factory in Louisville, Ky., to U.S. Ford
dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   The Sport Trac _ a four-door Explorer midsize sport-utility from
the nose to the back of the rear seat, and a pickup from there to
the rear bumper _ carries a price that falls between the two-door
Explorer Sport and the four-door Explorer SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   Even for those who don't particularly need the truck
capabilities of the Sport Trac, with its 4-by-4-foot pickup bed,
the Sport Trac comes off as a bargain-priced Explorer, with an
exposed cargo area.
</P>
<P>
   For about $25,000, a consumer can purchase a fully equipped
Sport Trac, with a passenger compartment identical to that of a
regular Explorer and the same V-6 engine. To get an Explorer this
well equipped would cost several thousand dollars more, easily more
than $30,000. Sport Trac prices range from about $23,000 to
$27,000, and most dealers are selling them at sticker, without
extra markup.
</P>
<P>
   Such bargain prices _ when compared with the average midsize
sport-utility _ make the Sport Trac an attractive option for SUV
buyers on a budget, Ford dealers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you buy the hard cargo-area cover, you can turn the bed
into what essentially is a large trunk, and whatever you are
hauling is protected,'' Ford spokeswoman Marcey Evans said from
company headquarters in Dearborn, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this combination of truck and SUV will appeal to a large
number of consumers remains to be seen, but the early signs are
promising. Ford already has orders for more than 40,000 for the
2001 model year, but it had planned to build only 50,000 for the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Because demand is already outstripping supply, dealers are
taking orders and putting customers on waiting lists, and Ford has
delayed its national TV advertising for the Sport Trac until at
least mid-May, Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like to do a lot of advertising if we don't have
enough dealer stock,'' Evans said. ``Dealers get upset, customers
get upset. We try in all of our new-vehicle launches to make sure
the advertising hits with a volume of the product being out there
for people to buy. We don't feel there is enough product out there
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Sport Trac buyers say they like the luxury of a nice
sport-utility like the Explorer, but they also need the utility of
a pickup bed to haul dirty cargo around.
</P>
<P>
   The Sport Trac has a wheelbase that is 14.25 inches longer than
the four-door Explorer's. Its pickup box is made of composite
plastic, which is 20 percent lighter than steel and also resists
dents better than steel.
</P>
<P>
   Ford says the Sport Trac appeals to younger buyers more than the
four-door Explorer. Buyers mostly will be in the mid-30s with an
active lifestyle, the company said. They are expected to use the
truck bed to haul such sports items as personal watercraft,
mountain bikes, motorcycles, snowmobiles and all-terrain vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   Combining two vehicle concepts into one isn't a new idea. Ford
did it with the Ranchero and Chevy with the El Camino in the '70s _
vehicles that were cars up front and pickups at the rear. Today,
though, the sport-utility/pickup combination seems more relevant.
</P>
<P>
   But Chevrolet got rave reviews at the 2000 North American
International Auto Show in Detroit in January with the SSR concept
vehicle, a futuristic car-truck combo strongly reminiscent of the
El Camino. There is no word yet as to whether this vehicle will
ever see production. But judging from the positive reaction from
nearly 5,000 automotive journalists in the audience when the car
was unveiled, it could be a success.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the sport-utility/truck combos will continue to
hit the market as the automakers try to make the most of the
current consumer craze for SUVs and pickups.
</P>
<P>
   If demand for the Sport Trac continues to exceed supply, Ford
has the capability to shift production at the Louisville plant to
build more Sport Tracs and fewer Explorers, Evans said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
