<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0342 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-ISUZU-TROOPER-HN     04-18 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-ISUZU-TROOPER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ISUZU TROOPER POISED FOR A COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _Once upon a time, before sport-utility vehicles
became the rage and appeared in almost everyone's driveway, a
Japanese company called Isuzu introduced a four-door SUV that took
the market by storm.
</P>
<P>
   For five years, the Isuzu Trooper was the No. 1-selling import
sport-utility in North America _ until 1990, when Ford introduced
the Explorer, Jeep rolled out the Grand Cherokee and both Nissan
and Toyota began producing their four-door sport-utilities.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier Trooper model was quite affordable, with a price on
par with midsize sedans of the day.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1992, Isuzu took the Trooper upscale, completely
redesigning it to compete against the new, more-expensive crop of
four-door SUVs that were selling in the high $20,000s to
mid-$30,000s.
</P>
<P>
   To replace the Trooper in the affordable segment, Isuzu
introduced the smaller Rodeo, with prices ranging from the upper
teens to the mid-$20,000s.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Isuzu, the redesigned Trooper, with its higher
price tag, never caught on as well with consumers as the earlier
model did. That's unfortunate for consumers, too, because the
current-generation Trooper is among the best SUVs on the market.
</P>
<P>
   So why have consumers been slow to embrace it?
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the higher price tag and the availability of a whole
new batch of SUVs with more-familiar automakers' names on them were
to blame. But Isuzu hasn't done much to advertise and otherwise
promote the Trooper, either, so some of the blame also has to go to
the company.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 and 1997, Trooper sales suffered because of a bad rap
the vehicle got from a flawed but dramatic rollover test conducted
by Consumers Union, which was played up in Consumer Reports and ran
on almost every TV news program.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, in a federal lawsuit brought against Consumers Union
by Isuzu, a jury ruled that eight of the 17 statements in the
Consumer Reports article questioned by Isuzu Motors were false.
</P>
<P>
   The jury also found that the magazine showed a ``reckless
disregard'' for the truth when it published this statement:
``Careful driving, however, is ultimately not the answer to the
problem. Isuzu ... should never have allowed these vehicles on the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury did not, however, assess any monetary damages against
Consumers Union.
</P>
<P>
   Trooper sales have recovered from the drop that Isuzu
experienced after the Consumer Reports article, but they still
aren't where they should be, considering that this is, in my
opinion, the best SUV buy on the market in the mid- to full-size
class.
</P>
<P>
   Even Consumer Reports has changed its tune about the Trooper,
and has since given it favorable ratings, especially in reliability
and dependability. The Trooper consistently rates way above average
for reliability, while some other better-selling SUVs rank way
below average.
</P>
<P>
   I heartily recommend that you test-drive a new Trooper if you're
in the market for an SUV. And if price is a concern, you might be
pleased to know that for 2000, Isuzu has introduced the first-ever
two-wheel-drive version of the Trooper, which lowers the price a
bit for people who don't need four-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'd still prefer four-wheel drive, and I can tell
you from experience driving Troopers on some of North America's
most rugged trails that this is one of the most capable off-road
vehicles ever built.
</P>
<P>
   But for those of you who aren't planning off-road expeditions,
and who just want a solid, comfortable, dependable and well-built
sport-utility vehicle for home and family use, the two-wheel-drive
Trooper is an excellent choice.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   There are three trim levels of the two-wheel-drive Trooper: the
base ``S'' model, the midlevel ``LS'' and the top-of-the-line
Limited.
</P>
<P>
   For this review, I tested the LS with a base price $28,650 plus
$495 transportation. There is so much standard equipment on the LS
that it's not really necessary to add anything to it to have a
truly premium SUV comparable to, say, a $38,000-plus Land Rover
Discovery, Mitsubishi Montero or Mercedes-Benz M-class.
</P>
<P>
   All Troopers come with a 215-horsepower, 3.5-liter,
double-overhead-cam, 24-valve, aluminum V-6 engine that offers more
power than many of the Trooper's competitors. It is connected to a
heavy-duty, smooth-shifting four-speed automatic transmission. A
manual transmission is offered only on the four-wheel-drive S
model.
</P>
<P>
   Standard equipment includes automatic, air-conditioning, dual
power outside mirrors (with a power fold-in feature that tucks them
out of the way for tight spots), power windows and door locks with
remote keyless entry, 16-inch aluminum wheels, eight-way power
driver's seat and four-way power passenger's seat and an in-dash
compact-disc player.
</P>
<P>
   It also includes four-wheel antilock brakes, cornering lamps,
cruise control, heated front seats, variable-assist power steering,
limited-slip differential, stainless-steel exhaust, 5,000-pound
towing capacity, tilt steering wheel, beige velour upholstery, and
full-size outside-mounted spare tire in a painted hard cover.
</P>
<P>
   The exterior paint job on the Trooper is a nine-step process
that is comparable to what you would find on a luxury car.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the Trooper comfortably seats five adults, and there
still is room for 46 cubic feet of cargo (also among the most in
class). The split-folding rear seat allows for expansion of the
cargo area while maintaining some rear seating.
</P>
<P>
   I've always liked the Trooper's rear cargo-door arrangement.
There are two doors, in a 70-30 split. The larger door opens first,
creating an opening sufficient for most loading and unloading of
cargo. But the smaller door opens, too, allowing for loading of
bulky items.
</P>
<P>
   Our test vehicle came with just three options: a power moon roof
($1,100), a trailer hitch ($253) and a cargo mat ($92). Total
sticker was $30,950, including transportation, a bargain in the
premium SUV segment.
</P>
<P>
   The warranty is among the best in the industry, too. Besides the
three-year/50,000-mile basic coverage, the Trooper comes with a
10-year/120,000-mile limited powertrain warranty and a
six-year/100,000-mile anti-corrosion warranty.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings are about typical for a sport-utility
of this size: 15 miles per gallon in the city and 19 mpg on the
highway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
