<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-TELESCOPES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGES SCOPE OUT POWER AND PRESTIGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Around the time Harvard astronomy professor Robert Kirshner was
boasting that the Magellan, the 21-foot telescope that Harvard and
MIT are jointly building in Chile, will be the most powerful
university telescope in the Southern Hemisphere, a disturbing
report began floating around: The California Institute of
Technology is thinking of building one 25 times more powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Caltech has reason to be concerned: It holds the record for the
world's largest optical telescope, and Harvard and MIT are trying
to build a better one in their Chilean venture.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, schools in Texas and Switzerland have made similar
plans to build bigger telescopes, setting off a veritable arms race
in the academic world.
</P>
<P>
   In the field of astronomy, it can be hard to impress. This is
the field, of course, that proved galaxies lie beyond the Milky
Way. These days, at major universities at least, it's not the
ability to stalk the cosmos that brings admiration and envy from
colleagues, it's the size and power of your telescope.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one really wants to be left behind, especially not
Harvard,'' said Kirshner. ``Part of it is the adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years, these giant versions of the basic
reflecting telescope made famous by Isaac Newton have popped up in
places far from the classroom _ on mountain peaks in The Andes, on
the top of volcanoes in Hawaii, and in the Arizona deserts.
Engineers in schools all over the world are fighting to be the king
of the mountains, introducing blueprints of telescopes so big they
have been dubbed ``GODS'' _ for Giant Optical Devices.
</P>
<P>
   And just to ensure that everyone knows how large these
instruments are, the scientists have given them nicknames like
``Very Large Telescope'' (belonging to German institutions) and
``Extra Large Telescope'' (the name of a planned telescope at a
Swedish university).
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the appeal of the behemoths is that the magnanamous
mirrors will gather more light and allow astronomers to see fainter
objects. But, some say, the reality is that none of the astronomy
schools want to be caught with the smallest toy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't say there isn't an element of bragging rights,''
acknowledged Stephen Maran, spokesman for the American Astronomical
Society.
</P>
<P>
   In the most competitive schools, said Maran, the telescopes are
needed to lure and keep the best scientists. They are also a good
way for colleges to look, at least to alumni with deep pockets, as
though they are staying on the cutting edge of technology, Maran
added.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1948, when Caltech began to run the 200-inch Hale
telescope _ for decades the world's greatest _ at Palomar, Calif.,
it seemed that most colleges were too busy studying astronomy
rather than optical exploration. By the early 1990s, when colleges
realized they were being left behind, Caltech and the University of
California were completing ``The Keck,'' which remains the largest
telescope in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Keck became a tool for Caltech to steal young stars from the
best science departments. Five years after Caltech lured Charles
Steidel, a promising scientist from MIT, many folks on the banks of
the Charles River are still fuming.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really hurt us,'' said Paul Schechter, a professor of
physics at MIT. ``We learned that to keep the best faculty we
better have the best resources necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard University believed it could lure Steidel back to
Cambridge by its mere reputation. But it didn't work. The last time
Harvard's telescope, a 16-incher, was the greatest in the world was
in 1840.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been working hard for a very long time to get with the
program and to catch up,'' said Kirshner, who, along with
Schechtner, was a graduate student at Caltech in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard and MIT had access to large national telescopes, but
that lost its allure since Caltech and the University of California
had exclusive rights to their own big telescope.
</P>
<P>
   Both universities needed a plan and soon: In the mid-1990s,
Kirshner and Schechter began to brainstorm with two graduate school
buddies.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Harvard and MIT had joined the University of Arizona,
University of Michigan, and the Carnegie Institution in Washington,
D.C., in building the two 6 1/2-meter telescopes called Magellan.
Others schools were collaborating: The University of Texas joined
Penn State and two German institutions to build The Hobby-Ebberly
Telescopes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, scientists are racing again to be the first to build the
next super telescope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to worry about what other people are doing,'' said
Steidel, who said Caltech is exploring the possibility of building
a 30-meter telescope. ``But I believe competition leads to more
inventive science.''
</P>
<P>
   While Lund University in Sweden announced the possibility of
building a 50-meter telescope, The European Southern Observatory
had a bigger plan. It wants to build the mother of all telescopes _
a 100-meter instrument simply called ``The Overwhelmingly Large
Telescope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
