<SLUG> BC-SCI-COCKPIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPGRADING THE SHUTTLE WITH 21ST CENTURY TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOUGLAS BAILEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When astronauts Jim Halsell and Scott Horowitz crawl into the
cockpit of the Shuttle Atlantis next Monday for their scheduled
nine-day space mission, they'll be confronted with the first major
technological face-lift of the spacecraft's flight instruments
since they were first designed in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The changes won't be hard to miss. The original Shuttle's three
monochrome cathode ray tubes, along with more than 30 mechanical
gauges and dials, have been replaced with nine flat-panel color
computer screens, giving the Shuttle a real 21st-century look _
more like the slick new Boeing 777's cockpit than the dull
government-issue display of the original models.
</P>
<P>
   For NASA and the astronauts, this conversion is the homeowner's
equivalent of finally tossing out the little black-and-white TV
with rabbit ears and investing in a widescreen Dolby surround sound
home theater system.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more to it than aesthetics and modernization. NASA
says the new ``glass cockpit'' _ officially called MEDS, for
multifunction electronic display system _ weighs less, uses less
electrical power and significantly reduces pilot workload during
launch and landing, the Shuttle's most dangerous moments. The $209
million MEDS system is the first of a major overhaul that will
radically upgrade the Shuttle by 2005 and, NASA says, greatly
improve the safety and reliability of the craft as it prepares to
make frequent visits to the International Space Station.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is '90s technology,'' said Elric McHenry, manager of the
Space Shuttle's program development. ``We're moving toward where
the airline industry is going.''
</P>
<P>
   The objectives behind the upgrade are twofold, McHenry said. The
old Shuttle equipment was facing obsolescense and becoming
increasingly more difficult to maintain. The second objective was
to give pilots access to more information _ in color-coded and
graphical form _ so they can make split decisions when faced with
emergencies. And time is critical. Within eight minutes after
liftoff, the Shuttle is traveling at 18,000 miles per hour and, if
a problem crops up, the pilots have to decide quickly if it's worth
risking a planned abort. This could call for the craft to separate
from its rocket boosters and fly backward and inverted through its
own exhaust plume in order to attempt an unpowered glide back to a
landing at the Kennedy Space Center. It's never been attempted, and
no one wants to be the first to try it.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttle astronaut Steven Lindsey, who is in charge of the
cockpit upgrade, noted that the Shuttle's crew spends nearly all
its training practicing for emergency aborts during the hazardous
liftoff phase. In the old cockpit, a pilot might have to scroll
through three or more screens of data to diagnose the problem
before deciding on a course of action.
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR; Today &LR;  we have to time-share information on the three
screens,'' Lindsey said. ``During a normal ascent, we put
trajectory information on those screens, but, if there's a problem,
we have to drop that information on one screen and start looking
for the problem. The new monitors will give us all the information
at a glance without having to drop a display.''
</P>
<P>
   And, where the pilots would have to interpret data from
mechanical gauges in the old cockpit, the MEDS display will color
code all the data, showing normally running systems in green and
potential problems in red, greatly reducing the time a pilot has to
evaluate the information.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey said the technological improvements are similar to those
already embraced by the nuclear power and commercial airline
industries, which reduce the stress of information overload for
their operators and pilots.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a failure, you don't want that one failure to take
your attention away from your primary job,'' Lindsey said.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the Shuttle will be upgraded with a ``smart
cockpit'' that will not only diagnose problems but recommend
courses of action, another step that will significantly cut pilot
workload.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can cut your workload and enhance situational
awareness, your safety margins go way up,'' Lindsey said.
</P>
<P>
   Other, less-obvious upgrades to the Shuttle include improving
the optical sensors in the main engines to detect problems
milliseconds before they occur, new hydraulic power systems that
don't depend on toxic hydrazine fuel for operation, and
improvements in the solid rockets and external fuel tanks to make
them stronger and more reliable.
</P>
<P>
   All of the changes, NASA estimates, will greatly reduce the
chances of an abort during liftoff that might result in a loss of
the crew.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing the new systems won't do, Lindsey insisted, is fly
the shuttle. They still need pilots for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time we can't physically fly the Shuttle is during
the first 80 seconds of the mission,'' he said. ``And after that,
we're really monitoring systems during ascent. But that's the way
it's designed and there's not a lot of difference between
monitoring and flying, because you've got to be ready to take it
over and fly at any point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
