<HEADLINE>
VENICE'S JEWISH GHETTO IS THE WORLD'S OLDEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENICE, Italy _ At first glance it could be any ``campo,'' the
kind of small square usually found beside a church in a Venetian
residential neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   A group of men sit at a cafe table, arguing amiably. A boombox
beside an open window sends the words of a haunting song echoing
across the square. Two small boys kick a soccer ball to and fro,
occasionally bouncing it inadvertently off a nearby wall. But we're
in Campo del Ghetto, heart of the four-centuries-old Jewish quarter
that gave its name to any section of a city in which Jews, or other
minorities, have been compelled to live because of legal or social
discrimination. (``Ghetto'' means ``foundry'' in Venetian dialect,
and there was once a cannon foundry here.)
</P>
<P>
   The houses of worship around this campo are synagogues. The men
in the cafe are wearing yarmulkes, and the point being argued
probably a Talmudic one. The lyrics of the song are in Hebrew. And
the wall the boys' ball ricochets off bears a plaque listing the
names of the more than 200 ghetto residents who died in Nazi
concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   Despite persecution, deportation, emigration, and assimilation,
a visible Jewish presence remains in this, the oldest so-called
ghetto in the world. There are five synagogues or ``scoles'' that
are among the oldest in Europe, a kosher restaurant, and a bakery
that makes unleavened bread. Also, you'll find a Jewish museum with
a collection of books, tapestries, silverware, and various
religious artifacts. The museum also operates a bookstore and
offers guided tours of the ghetto, including visits to several
synagogues.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jews are now a distinct minority in the neighborhood
they inhabited exclusively for centuries. The ghetto was created in
1516, when hundreds of Jews fleeing a war on the mainland sought
haven in Venice, which was protected by its lagoon and navy and was
one the few cities in Western Europe at the time that allowed large
numbers of Jews to reside permanently.
</P>
<P>
   But conditions of residence were harsh. Jews were not allowed to
own property outside the ghetto and could not practice most
professions and many trades. And they were obliged to wear
identifying yellow badges or distinctive caps wherever they went.
</P>
<P>
   Jews were also forbidden to leave the ghetto after dark. (An
exception was made for Jewish doctors, who could visit patients
anywhere in the city at night.) The gates of the ghetto were closed
and locked at sundown and guarded by Christian watchmen, whose
salaries had to be paid by the Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Athough the original ghetto was expanded in the mid-17th
century, the quarter remained incredibly overcrowded. By 1797, when
Napoleon occupied Venice and abolished the ghetto, an estimated
5,000 people were living in just over two square blocks.
</P>
<P>
   To fit so many people into such a small area, tenement houses in
the ghetto were higher than most in Venice and had very low
ceilings (typically below 6 feet) to allow as many stories as
possible, usually six or seven. Claustrophobia was yet another
burden that went with living in the ghetto.
</P>
<P>
   Although they shared a common religious tradition and were
subject to the same legal disabilities, the ghetto dwellers were
surprisingly diverse. There were Italian Jews, of course, but also
separate groups from Germany, the south of France, the Levant
(Lebanon and Syria), and Spain. Each nationality had its own
synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish museum's guided ghetto tour begins with a visit to
the Italian synagogue, located in one of the tall tenements facing
the campo. According to the guide _ a young woman who gives her
tour in English for an international group that includes Americans,
French, Germans, and Israelis _ the Italians were the poorest of
the ghetto communities.
</P>
<P>
   By tradition there could be nothing between the roof of a
synagogue and the sky; but the impoverished Italians couldn't
afford a freestanding building. So their synagogue occupied the
entire top floor of a tenement, and was reached by six flights of
steep and narrow stairs. Visitors frequently arrive out of breath,
but so probably did many worshipers.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1575, the Italan synagogue is no longer used for
worship but is preserved as a museum. Architecture was one of the
professions Jews were forbidden to practice, and the Italian
synagogue, like others in the ghetto, was designed by a Christian
architect who specialized in churches.
</P>
<P>
   So, as in Italian churches of the period, there is a great deal
of painted stucco and much gilded wood. The sanctuary also includes
a high and ornate pulpit of the sort Catholic priests mounted to
give their sermons at Mass on Sundays. Distinctively Jewish
features include a screened balcony for the women, who, according
to custom, worshiped separately from men.
</P>
<P>
   There are also secret panels and hidden storage areas next to
the ark where the Torah and other synagogue valuables could be
quickly concealed. The Doge of Venice once courageously defied a
command from the pope to burn Jews as heretics; but he did comply
with an order to burn Jewish religious books.
</P>
<P>
   The German congregation was the most prosperous in the ghetto,
and its Scola Tedesca, built in 1529 and also on the campo, was one
of the most elaborate. The second oldest in Europe after Prague,
the German synagogue is being completely restored and is currently
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Two synagogues are still active, the Levantine (built in 1538)
and the Spanish (late 16th century). The Spanish synagogue is noted
for its gilded Baroque-style wooden columns and also its unusual
frescoes representing Bible stories, such as Moses parting the Red
Sea. To avoid violating the commandment about making graven images,
the artist depicted only the parting sea and Moses' staff _ leaving
out the prophet and the Children of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The influence of church architecture is very noticeable in the
Levantine synagogue, which has a sanctuary area that resembles a
Christian chapel. This was definitely a male-dominated
congregation. Women sat on benches in a cramped loft, but men had a
spacious ground-floor area with seats and what look like
old-fashioned hinge-topped school desks where they could store
prayer books.
</P>
<P>
   The ghetto today is served by only one rabbi, and Sabbath
services alternate between the Spanish and Levantine synagogues.
According to the museum guide, both are also still used for
weddings and other special occasions.
</P>
<P>
   There are around 600 Jews in the city, she said, but only about
30 _ a half-dozen families _ actually live within the confines of
the old ghetto. Most of Venice's Jews are Orthodox and of Sephardic
origin, descendants of Jews expelled from Spain and Portugal in the
15th century.
</P>
<P>
   Although few Jews actually live in it now, the ghetto remains
the focal point of Venice's scattered Jewish community. The
Lubavitcher movement has a study center on the campo, and there are
several small gift shops in the area selling Jewish religious
goods.
</P>
<P>
   On the edge of the old ghetto, beside the Cannaregio Canal, is
Gam Gam, the neighborhood's only kosher restaurant. Here, diners
are served by waiters wearing yarmulkes, and the menu includes
local specialties such as ``eggplant ghetto style.'' (You can also
get potato latkes and falafel.)
</P>
<P>
   Although off the main tourist trails, the ghetto is a worthwhile
place to explore, and in recent years has begun to attract artists
and antiques dealers. But wandering its narrow streets you can come
across poignant reminders of the painful past. The marks left by
the hinges of the ghetto gates, for instance, can still be seen _
200 years after Napoleon's soldiers ripped them down in the name of
reason and the French Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Most moving and painful of all, however, is the memorial on the
north side of the campo. Here a series of seven powerfully executed
bas reliefs depicts the arrest, deportation, and death in
concentration camps of the Jews of the ghetto.
</P>
<P>
   At the outbreak of World War II, some 1,500 Jews still lived in
the former ghetto. Most went into hiding and survived, often with
the help of Italian friends. But near the end of the war the
Germans rounded up the remaining ghetto residents, many elderly and
a number bedridden or in nursing homes. Of the 289 Jews deported
from the ghetto, only two returned.
</P>
<P>
   On the memorial wall is a poem _ inscribed in Hebrew, Italian,
and English _ that reads:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Your sad holocaust is engraved in history
</P>
<P>
   And nothing shall purge your deaths from our memories
</P>
<P>
   For our memories are your only grave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
