<HEADER>
A0356 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-ZAROULIS-BOS &LR;      04-18 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-ZAROULIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTORIAN BOSTON ADDS CHARACTER IN MYSTERY SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Twenty-plus years ago, author Nancy Zaroulis had an
idea for a mystery series set in Victorian Boston, an era, she
says, when ``everything was so hidden, so repressed'' and ``there
was so much going on beneath the surface.'' She recalls telling
herself back then that ``writing a mystery looked to be too hard,''
so she put the idea aside and started writing what would be the
first of several novels.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' she says, ``the idea stayed with me. It haunted me and
finally, I had to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, writing under the pen name Cynthia Peale, Zaroulis has
written ``The Death of Colonel Mann; A Beacon Hill Mystery,'' the
first in an expected series to be published by Doubleday.
</P>
<P>
   What Zaroulis finds particularly fine, in a mystery-setting
sense, about the Victorian period in Boston is an atmosphere that
one of her characters describes as ``well _ proper. And often
stuffy. And cold and unforgiving.''
</P>
<P>
   That atmosphere produces the plot for ``The Death of Colonel
Mann.'' The colonel, based on a real figure, a New Yorker, not a
Bostonian, is the publisher of Town Topics, a scandal sheet. He is
happy to offer blackmail as an alternative for proper Bostonians
caught in improper relationships. For that, he is murdered.
</P>
<P>
   The sleuths are Addington Ames and his sister Caroline, who are
living in what would be called ``straitened circumstances'' in the
family house on Louisburg Square.
</P>
<P>
   Was Mann's killer a member of their own circle whose
indiscretions he had threatened to expose? Their search takes them
to the bastions of Brahmin society: the St. Botolph Club, a
debutante cotillion, Christmas Revels, and a meeting of one of the
most proper of its institutions, a sewing circle. For atmospherics,
says Zaroulis, ``there are foggy streets and gaslights.''
</P>
<P>
   For an outside observer of Boston's Brahmin culture, Zaroulis
has created Dr. John Alexander MacKenzie, a friend of the Ames
siblings who is recovering from bullet wounds received while
serving with the Army against the Sioux.
</P>
<P>
   MacKenzie ``watched his footing carefully, aided by his cane,''
Zaroulis writes. ``He wore a stout overcoat, a bowler, and a worn
muffler that he'd had for years. He'd been a little embarrassed
about that muffler at first, until he'd seen that the Ameses,
Boston Brahmins though they were, sported articles of clothing that
were even older and shabbier than it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaroulis launches her career as a mystery writer confident that
people enjoy series. ``They get attached to the characters,'' she
says, ``and want to follow them along.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers will have that opportunity next spring with ``Murder at
Bertram's Bower,'' in which the Ameses solve a murder at a shelter
for ``fallen women'' _ prostitutes _ modeled on a real place that
was located on Washington Street in the South End. After that
there's a third, now being written, and even a fourth. ``I know
what that'll be about,'' Zaroulis says, ``but I haven't researched
it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting to this point comes only after a long detour through
three novels and ``Who Spoke Up?'' an account of antiwar protests
written with her husband, former UMass/Boston professor Gerald
Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Her first novel, published in 1973, was ``The Poe Papers,''
based on an episode in the life of Edgar Allan Poe. Then came
``Call the Darkness Light,'' a saga of women in the Lawrence and
Lowell textile mills (acquired for Doubleday by the late Jacqueline
Kennedy Onassis) and finally ``Massachusetts,'' a James
Micheneresque historical novel.
</P>
<P>
   Zaroulis, who allows only that she is in her 50s, grew up in
Chelmsford and went to Suffolk University. As a student and later
an editorial assistant for several Boston publishing houses, she
lived on Beacon Hill, ``when you could still rent a place for $25 a
month,'' she recalls. No wonder, then, that she chose the
neighborhood as the setting for ``The Death of Colonel Mann.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Boston pretty well,'' Zaroulis says. ``But sometimes,
it's better to have the Boston of your imagination, because
Victorian Boston is the Boston of people's dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, Boston has changed enough so that a Doubleday editor
questioned Zaroulis's placement of MIT in the Back Bay. `` `Isn't
it in Cambridge?' she asked me. `Not until 1915,' I told her.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Victorian Boston ``is a perfect period in which to
set a mystery,'' Zaroulis says. ``If you like Anne Perry,'' and her
mysteries set in Victorian London, she adds by way of
self-promotion, ``you'll love Cynthia Peale.''
</P>
<P>
   The name change was necessitated by the publishing-world canon.
``Neither the industry nor readers,'' Zaroulis says, ``like authors
to change the type of work they have been used to seeing from
them.''
</P>
<P>
   She took the ``Cynthia'' in memory of an old friend who had
recently died, and the ``Peale'' partly for the painter Charles
Wilson Peale, but also, she admits ``to give me a spot on the
bookstore shelves between Robert Parker and Anne Perry.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaroulis insists she is ``not trying to hide'' her real
identity, and she is pleased when people bring copies of ``Call the
Darkness Light'' _ in one case, a first edition from 20 years ago _
to her ``Cynthia Peale'' readings and signings.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, however, directs readers who might be interested in
other books by the author of ``Colonel Mann'' to Norman Vincent
Peale, the inspirational writer who died in 1979. ``I was thinking
of complaining, but then I decided, no, people just might be
intrigued and buy my book,'' Zaroulis says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of branding,'' she adds. ``I've got `Cynthia
Peale' on my mailbox in Chestnut Hill. I had a discussion with our
mailman about it. I told him we were having someone new coming to
live there and he said, that's fine, just put her name on the
mailbox.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
