<HEADLINE>
O: EARNESTNESS FROM WINFREY IN NEW PACKAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cool blue debut cover of O, The Oprah Magazine, whispers
seductively about the good life, with the magazine's founder _
Oprah Winfrey _ perched comfortably in a pretty wicker chair.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a mere 20 pages later, Winfrey's magazine preaches
passionately about the right life, offering a ``Tap Your Personal
Courage'' calendar filled with exhortations to ``ask yourself, what
was I created to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Set to hit the newsstands Wednesday, O reads a lot like Eleanor
Roosevelt meets Martha Stewart. Perhaps that's the natural
outgrowth of a venture between Hearst Magazines _ publisher of such
tried and true women's lifestyle publications as Cosmo and Good
Housekeeping _ and Winfrey, with her emphasis on the spiritual
roots of self-help.
</P>
<P>
   Where else would you find an ad for ``Oprah's Personal Growth
Summits,'' next to a piece on PMS remedies. Or a series of
inspirational quotes from Ralph Waldo Emerson and Maya Angelou
vying for space with ``Five Fabulous Things to Do With Fresh
Strawberries''? Or a piece from sharp-elbowed political partisan
Peggy Noonan gushing that the ``sheer joy'' of hard work is ``a
bubbling happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   If as Winfrey writes, O is a magazine that asks women to ``peel
back the layers and excavate the real you,'' it delivers that
painful-sounding message with a velvet glove. There are pages and
pages of traditional fashion and beauty features, as well as food
and design coverage. There is mild celebrity worship as Tina Turner
admits her weakness for scary movies, and Camille Cosby sits down
for an interview with Winfrey. (Winfrey's first question -_ are
``you are aware of your womanness?'' _ suggests she's a much better
TV than print interviewer, but the session later picks up steam.)
</P>
<P>
   At its core, however, O is a resolutely upbeat and
non-ideological vehicle for preaching self-improvement and cultural
harmony. The stories focus on people like Bea Salazar, a poor woman
who managed to create a makeshift network of children's service
centers. Mixed-race author Danzy Senna writes about coming to terms
with her white grandmother, who was brilliant, combative, and
racist. And in O's one truly memorable piece of journalism, writer
Elizabeth Kim recounts her struggle to surmount her wrenching
experiences and forlorn destiny as an illegitimate child in
post-war Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Given the 166 pages of ads in the initial 318-page issue, O
displays courage with a piece extolling the mental-health benefits
of shedding excess worldly goods. More typical is an article called
``Make Your Dreams Come True'' which lays out pragmatic steps _
``Excavate your true desire,'' ``Hatch a plan,'' ``Keep yourself
motivated'' _ for changing your life.
</P>
<P>
   Heart Magazines president Cathleen Black has pointedly noted
that O ``is not a television program, it's a magazine.'' But it's a
magazine placing its chips on Winfrey's phenomenal TV celebrity.
Not only does she grace the cover, she writes two columns and
interviews Cosby. The magazine's ``bookshelf'' is an extension of
Oprah's Book Club, and a major health and fitness piece includes
advice from her personal trainer.
</P>
<P>
   In O's closing column, called ``What I Know for Sure,'' Winfrey
lays out her basic philosopy that ``the happiness you feel is in
direct proportion to the love you give.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beatles _ with their lyric ``And in the end, the love you
take is equal to the love you make'' _ may have said it better. But
nobody markets it better than Winfrey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
