<HEADLINE>
TESTING FOR HIGH BLOOD PRESSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What is the best test or procedure that a doctor can use to
determine that a person's high blood pressure is caused by an
improper signal from the area of the brain that is supposed to
control it? What other causes of hypertension are there?
</P>
<P>
   M.W.K., Peabody, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Blood pressure is the force that keeps blood flowing around
your body. If it's too low, your body parts won't get enough oxygen
and you could die. If it's too high, you can wear out arteries and
they could burst, and again, you could die.
</P>
<P>
   High blood pressure, or ``hypertension,'' can be caused by many
things. These include narrowing of blood vessels due to drugs or
stress, or blockages in them due to a lifetime of eating junk food.
Excess blood viscosity can also contribute, as can poor elasticity
of blood vessels, or excessive blood volume, which can be
associated with eating too much salty food.
</P>
<P>
   The brain stem and hypothalamus both have some control over
blood pressure but, as you can see, they're not the only ones in
the game, and there's no immediate way to know if they're the ones
causing trouble or if it's mostly something else.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy to single out which bit of the body is causing
high blood pressure in any single case. Unless the patient is about
to explode, doctors usually recommend cutting down on salt to try
to stop the body filling up with water to dilute it, to start
exercising, to reduce stress, and to cut down on foods that
encourage gunk to clog their circulatory systems. If this isn't
enough, the brain control system may become suspect, though other
organs may be involved and a combination of tests and attempts at
controlling the high blood pressure with drugs will begin. In the
event of a brain-related problem, doctors may well elect not to dig
around in there in case they mess up, and rather than having your
high blood pressure ``cured,'' you may wind up managing it as a
chronic illness.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Dr. Knowledge answers your questions about health and science each
week. E-mail the doctor at drknowledge(at)globe.com; or send fax
to: 617-929-9263, or a letter to Dr. Knowledge, in care of The
Boston Globe, Health/Science Section, P.O. Box 2378, Boston, MA
02107. Please include your initials and hometown. Selected
questions of general interest will be answered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
