<HEADER>
A0364 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-SHUTTLE-KRANZ-BOS     04-18 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SHUTTLE-KRANZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-FLIGHT CHIEF RECALLS `LET'S DO IT' DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOUGLAS BAILEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thirty years ago this week, Gene Kranz was celebrating the US
space agency's most successful failure, an event he himself dubbed
``NASA's finest hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Kranz, the former fighter pilot who served as flight director
for most of the Mercury, Gemini and Apollo missions in the 1960s
and early 1970s, was at the helm in Houston's Mission Control when
engineers had to improvise a risky and untested rescue plan after
an explosion crippled the Apollo 13 spacecraft when it was halfway
to the Moon.
</P>
<P>
   Although the mission was indeed a failure _ it was intended to
be NASA's third Moon landing _ the three astronauts returned safely
and the mission provided perhaps the most easily absorbed drama of
any spaceflight before or since. Hollywood certainly recognized
this when it chose Apollo 13, not Apollo 11, as the first mission
to be memorialized in film. And, it could be argued that the flight
contributed more phrases to the popular lexicon than others.
``Houston, we have a problem,'' is heard more than ``That's one
small step . . .'' And, although he didn't actually utter it,
Kranz's ``failure is not an option'' command to his troops during
the Apollo 13 crisis in the movie has become the battle cry for
managers everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the title of Kranz's just-published book, which
recounts his incredible career in the space program during that
heady decade when the Moon was just a four-day rocket ride away. In
it, Kranz writes that the improvisation within Mission Control's
boiler room that saved Apollo 13 was only the most glaring example
of a space agency that was making it up as it went along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we thought we reached a plateau, they moved the
objective farther out,'' said Kranz in an interview Monday. ``And
we saluted and said, `We'll do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For Kranz, who still speaks in the clipped, no-guff phrasing
made famous by actor Ed Harris's portrayal of him in the movie,
``Apollo 13,'' the space flights were a series of dramatic near
misses, not the perfectly executed missions most appeared to be.
But, by the time of Apollo, Kranz and his team of young flight
engineers (most in their mid-20s) had become masters of innovation,
management and planning who believed entirely in their abilities to
do the audacious.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were given the opportunity to show what America can do,''
he said. ``It was almost like President Kennedy grabbed an idea
from the 21st century and said, `Let's do it now.' It might have
been more logical to do the space station then and eventually go to
the Moon in this century. But we really got ahead of ourselves
because we were in a Cold War.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Kranz said, the nation needs leaders willing to make a
stand on space exploration, and the public needs to get excited
about it. But he doesn't know what it will take to jump-start a new
space era.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might take a crisis,'' he said. ``One would be a
recognition that we're not developing technology as quickly as
other countries are. Or maybe we'll realize that space technology
can solve some of our environmental problems like global warming.''
</P>
<P>
   But you'll never justify space travel on pure economics, Kranz
said, unless you can consider what a renewed space effort would
contribute to technological progress, the formation of new
companies, and educational initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're short-timers. We want to measure results in six- to
12-month increments,'' he said. ``But if you really want to measure
it, you have to ask yourself where you want this country to be in
10 or 20 years, and could reviving the space program get us there.
I think it could.''
</P>
<P>
   Now retired, and still a booster of NASA itself, he has harsh
words for the present NASA brass, and blames the recent string of
highly publicized satellite failures on their reliance on faddish
management techniques and an unwillingness to foster debate with
their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those weren't NASA failures, they were management failures,
pure and simple,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not opposed to an occasional PR stunt, like letting
Senator John Glenn take a ride on the Shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand the risk he took in his first Mercury
flight,'' he said. ``Those Atlas boosters were exploding all the
time and he was willing to climb on top of one not knowing if it
was the third good or the fourth bad one. He deserved it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0365 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-BLACK-VETERANS-ART-BO     04-18 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-VETERANS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 BELATED SALUTE URGED FOR BLACK WWII VETERANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMAL E. WATSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he was 19, Paul Parks enlisted in the Army and became part
of the bloody European campaign to defeat the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   But after helping rid the world of a heinous totalitarian
regime, Parks and his black comrades came home from battle to
segregated bathrooms and water fountains, and seats at the back of
public buses.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people still don't know that blacks played a major
role in World War II, and I think that's unfortunate,'' said Parks,
now 77, a longtime civil rights activist and former Massachusetts
education secretary. ``The conditions that we faced in the military
and the conditions that we returned to after the war was over were
outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks and other black war veterans across the country are
pushing for a national Day of Honor next month to remember those
who fought for their country in a segregated military rife with
racism.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy is backing their effort to have
President Clinton and Congress set aside May 25 as a special day of
commemoration for all minority soldiers who fought in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because history books and the media have not told the story of
the contribution of minorities to World War II, most Americans are
not aware that in spite of racism at home and on the battlefield,
men and women of color stood shoulder to shoulder with other
Americans,'' said William H. Smith of Marlborough, Mass., one of
those behind the national effort.
</P>
<P>
   The time to remedy that, Smith and others say, is long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   The experiences of black soldiers in Word War II have gone
largely unrecorded, many say. Few documentaries, for example, have
highlighted their heroism on the beaches of Normandy during D-Day.
School textbooks, for the most part, have ignored their valor under
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Even Hollywood has not given them their due, some black war
veterans say. Many were disappointed that Steven Spielberg's 1998
blockbuster ``Saving Private Ryan'' did not include any black
faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``These black veterans have incredible stories,'' Smith said.
``World War II is the preeminent event of this century and blacks
and other minorities are perceived as having not served. We know
that's not true _ in fact, they served under conditions that have
since been condemned.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who runs a multimedia service, knew little about minority
war veterans until the Army hired him to produce a documentary,
``African-Americans in World War II: A Legacy of Patriotism and
Honor.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 film has been shown on military bases nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   As he interviewed dozens of black veterans and combed through
archives, Smith came to understand that minorities played a key
role in the war.
</P>
<P>
   Black soldiers like Parks were ordered to activate and
deactivate land mines throughout southern England and France. The
Rev. Arthur Joseph Jr., now an ordained minister in Houston,
transported German soldiers to Allied prison camps after they
surrendered. And Colonel John B. Roach, an original Tuskegee airman
who flew B-25 bombers and now lives in Woburn, Mass., shot down
several German planes.
</P>
<P>
   In all, about 1.2 million African-Americans served alongside
300,000 Hispanic-Americans and 50,000 Asian-Americans in World War
II, according to the National Association of Black Veterans Inc.,
based in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were there,'' Smith said, noting that the percentage of
black soldiers during the war paralleled the black population in
America.
</P>
<P>
   As Smith toured the country promoting the Army documentary, some
black veterans asked him to make another one that examined the
harsh experiences of racism black soldiers faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one of the screenings, a few of the men came up to me
afterwards and said `Thank you, Brother Smith, for showing a
picture of us,'' Smith said. ``But you know you didn't really talk
about the terrible conditions that we lived in.'''
</P>
<P>
   So, using his own money, Smith made and last year released ``The
Invisible Soldiers: Unheard Voices,'' a documentary that chronicles
through interviews and archival footage the conditions black
soldiers encountered in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a (captured) German soldier who once asked me why I was
fighting in this war,'' said Joseph, 82, who volunteered to go
overseas in summer 1941. ``I told him that I always wanted to be a
soldier and that I had joined the Army because my government asked
me to.''
</P>
<P>
   During the war, Joseph kept a diary of the mistreatment he and
other black soldiers endured at the hands of their white superiors.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daddy was a soldier in World War I, and I really believed
in my heart that things would change for blacks back at home if we
won the war over in Europe,'' he said. ``Of course, that didn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Stories like Joseph's inspired Smith to push for the day of
recognition. The effort has been gaining momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to support a congressional resolution
introduced last week by Kennedy and US Representative Sheila
Jackson Lee of Texas calling for the establishment of the special
day.
</P>
<P>
   And five US mayors have agreed to mark the holiday in their
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often during World War II and in the years since then,
these brave men and women who fought to protect our freedom were
subjected to unfair discrimination and have never received the
recognition they deserve,'' Kennedy said in a statement. ``On land,
sea and air, far from their homes, they fought brilliantly to
defeat facism and protect our freedom. And large numbers of them
did so in spite of the racism and injustice they had suffered in
our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he hopes the Day of Honor will force Americans to
reflect on an important and ugly chapter in history. ``The goal of
this day is to formally say thank you as a nation to a generation
whose service paved the way for freedoms African-Americans and
other minorities enjoy today,'' he said. ``It is also a measure of
social and moral reparations _ paying respect to those who served
under the yoke of suffering and discrimination.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
