<HEADER>
A0368 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-DOG-DISEASE-BOS &LR;      04-18 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DOG-DISEASE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCREASE IN DOG DISEASE HAS VETS WONDERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quincy, an active and hardy 7-year-old mutt, worried her owners,
Thomas and Rosemary Rennicks, when, in the course of three days,
she went from a being a normal, healthy dog to one who could hardly
use her hind legs. She couldn't get off the bed. And she refused
even a dog biscuit.
</P>
<P>
   Bundling her off to veterinarian Mary Labato at the Tufts
University School of Veterinary Medicine last month, the Rennicks,
who live in Worcester, learned that Quincy was sick with
leptospirosis, something they'd never heard of.
</P>
<P>
   Leptospirosis is a sometimes deadly disease caused by
spiral-shaped bacteria of the genus Leptospira and is spread by
contact with the urine of an infected animal. This could occur if
an animal with leptospirosis urinates in standing water, and
another comes along and drinks from the source. It can be treated
with antibiotics such as doxycycline or penicillin if caught early.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, the disease can be transmitted from dogs to
humans, but it is a rare occurrence and, according to Dr. Bela
Matyas of the Massachusetts Department of Public Health, there have
been no recorded cases of the disease in humans in Massachusetts
for at least a decade. Some experts believe the frosty New England
winters kill off much of the bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   But, for some unknown reason, there appears to be an increase in
cases in dogs in the state. Veterinarians don't know if this is
because more cases are simply being detected or if the disease is
on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 and 1996, the vets at Tufts' Foster Hospital for Small
Animals saw no cases of dogs with leptospirosis. But in 1997, there
were 13 cases; that rose to 16 in 1998, and 17 last year. Dr. Linda
Ross of the Tufts University School of Veterinary Medicine
explained that you cannot pick upleptospirosis just from patting or
playing with your dog, or even having the dog lick your face. You
have to come into contact with an infected dog's urine, and this is
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Any mammal can contract the disease (cats get it more rarely
than dogs). In addition to being picked up through tainted water or
food, it can be transmitted through mucous membranes or a cut in
the skin.
</P>
<P>
   While relatively uncommon in the United States, leptospirosis
thrives in some tropical countries, where it does kill humans. It
is generally carried in the rodent population, and is transmitted
to people who drink, bathe or wash clothing in infected waterways.
</P>
<P>
   This knowledge should make you hesitate before dipping a toe in
a pond in Madagascar, but you should not waste a moment worrying
that you'll get the disease from your dog. You are far more likely
to get it from a rodent in Nicaragua than a dog in Natick.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the largest outbreaks of leptospirosis occur in
places where there is a breakdown in sanitation and water sources
are fouled. In the aftermath of Hurricane Mitch in 1998, for
example, at least 68 people were diagnosed with leptospirosis in
Honduras, and the disease caused at least four deaths. Those who
have been infected in the United States are generally people who
work on farms, or are veterinarians or sewer workers.
</P>
<P>
   It can take two days to four weeks, but usually one to two
weeks, between exposure to the bacteria and the development of
disease. Symptoms in people include high fever, headache, chills,
muscle aches, vomiting and perhaps jaundice. And for dogs, symptoms
may include fever (normal body temperature for a dog is 100.5 to
102.5 F), loss of appetite, lameness, and lethargy.
</P>
<P>
   Once suspected, the bacteria can be detected through blood and
urine tests. With some people and dogs, there are no symptoms at
all and the infection resolves on its own. Others develop
respiratory distress, kidney damage, meningitis, or liver failure.
This serious phase of the illness is known as Weil's disease.
</P>
<P>
   With early detection, dogs are given fluid therapy and a minimum
of four weeks of antibiotics. Even in cases of renal failure,
therapy can reverse the situation. But Tufts' Ross said the results
simply are not predictable: Some animals get better, others die,
and still others survive, but with residual kidney problems.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Quincy is recovering nicely. After five days in the
hospital receiving intravenous fluids and weeks of antibiotics, she
is her old self again.
</P>
<P>
   So, how do you prevent your dog from contracting leptospirosis?
That turns out to be a rather cloudy issue. Simple measures include
keeping the areas around your home rodent free, since rodents can
carry the bacteria. You could also try to prevent your dog from
splashing around in and drinking standing water (easier said than
done), such as puddles in the woods that might be contaminated with
wild animal urine. And you can help keep wildlife away from your
house by making sure your trash cans are covered, and not leave pet
food outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   There are vaccines for leptospirosis, but their efficacy is
debatable. Even though the Rennickses hadn't realized it, Quincy
had, in fact, been vaccinated against leptospirosis, but not
against the strain the dog contracted. Vaccines do not exist for
all strains. Worldwide, there may be as many as 200 strains, each
adapted to a particular environment. It's best to discuss the issue
of vaccination with your own vet, who will have a good idea about
whether other dogs in your area have been infected.
</P>
<P>
   Five strains have been found in New England. Ross of Tufts
explained that leptospira interrogans canicola and leptospira
interrogans icterohemorrhagiae were traditionally considered to be
the agents causing leptospirosis in dogs. Now vets are finding
three new strains _ pomona, grippotyphosa and bratislava.
</P>
<P>
   This makes Dr. Robert Cook, chief veterinarian with the Wildlife
Conservation Society, wonder whether leptospirosis should come
under the umbrella of suspicion for emerging diseases, although it
is still considered rare. The society played a critical role in
identifying the outbreak of the West Nile encephalitis virus in New
York last summer, which killed seven people.
</P>
<P>
   The Rennickses are hopeful that Quincy will make a full
recovery. Until the vet is certain Quincy's urine is clear of the
bacteria, her owners will have to do something they feel a little
silly doing, but it will help prevent the spread of the disease:
They must stalk the dog and spray bleach onto every urine puddle
she produces in order to kill the bacteria. They will be able to
stop when Quincy gets a clean bill of health from the vet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
or more information on leptospirosis, call the Massachusetts
Department of Public Health's Division of Epidemiology at
617-983-6800. Or check out the department's Web site at
www.state.ma.us.
</P>
</TEXT>
