<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSIAL BISHOP PUBLISHES NEW BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW PAULSON AND DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bishop John Shelby Spong is at it again.
</P>
<P>
   His newest book, ``Here I Stand,'' published earlier this year
will likely do nothing to change Spong's standing, among critics
and admirers, as one of the most controversial American Christian
prelates of recent times.
</P>
<P>
   Spong, who retired in February after 24 years as Episcopal
bishop of Newark and is now teaching and lecturing at Harvard
University, has been branded a heretic by detractors for his views
questioning Christian tenets like Jesus's virgin birth and the
resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters hail Spong as a hero for his championing of
women's and, particularly, gay causes, including the ordination of
gays and lesbians as Episcopal priests, as well as his rhetorical
challenges to the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   In his latest book, an autobiography subtitled, ``My Struggle
for a Christianity of Integrity, Love &AMP; Equality,'' Spong, 68,
minces no words in targeting his long-time foes. He refers to
fundamentalist Protestantism, the theological fuel for the
religious right, as ``ill-informed, prejudiced, close-minded and
doctrinaire.''
</P>
<P>
   And as he surveys the religious landscape, Spong bemoans what he
considers a demoralizing topography.
</P>
<P>
   ``A strident fundamentalist Protestantism, an antiquated Roman
Catholicism, and an irrelevant Orthodox tradition,'' Spong writes,
are ``the major expressions of Christianity at the dawn of the
twenty-first century. There is no leaven in that ecclesiastical
lump and no candle left to shine in that ecclesiastical darkness. I
see no hope for a Christian future in any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   His condemnation won't surprise conservative believers,
including fellow Episcopal bishops, who say Spong has abandoned
Christian values and embraced a popular culture _ reflected in the
mass media _ with questionable sexual mores and a hostile attitude
toward religion.
</P>
<P>
   After Spong's 1998 book, provocatively entitled, ``Why
Christianity Must Change or Die,'' was released, his opponents
published a response, a collection of essays called ``Can a Bishop
Be Wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   In it, Episcopal Bishop James M. Stanton of the diocese of
Dallas, states: ``The fundamentalist has no better friend than John
Shelby Spong. No one demonstrates better the futility of liberal
religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Spong, in a recent interview at the Harvard residence where he
is living, said he never deliberately set out to become an
iconoclast nor is he, as some critics assert, simply interested in
attracting publicity.
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, Spong's tumultuous career has been one long
response to the environment he encountered in his native North
Carolina, which was dominated by fundamentalist Christians who
believed the Bible was the inerrant word of God.
</P>
<P>
   It also was a world, Spong noted, characterized by racism,
sexism, anti-Semitism and homophobia. And the Bible, he said, was
often used to buttress this intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people just don't buy that and the culture has moved
way beyond that,'' said Spong who also wrote a popular book
entitled ``Rescuing the Bible from Fundamentalism. ``The religious
right believes they represent God and if you disagree with them you
disagree with God. Americans don't want to persecute anyone's
religious views, but they also aren't interested in having
religious views imposed on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the responses his writings and public lectures have
generated, Spong believes many Americans share his vision of
Christianity. They yearn, he believes, for a faith that is
tolerant, less dogmatic and not so focused on Biblical stories
Spong says are difficult for the 21st century mind to accept.
</P>
<P>
   In his most recent book, Spong summarizes his life's work as
having been an attempt to ``free people from the clutches of
religious systems that create a false security, provide a phony
peace and pretend to solve profound questions of life with
simplistic answers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOLIDAYS OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For both Christians and Jews, this week is one of the most
important of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Christians are celebrating Holy Week, which began with Palm
Sunday, which marks Jesus's entry into Jerusalem, continuing with
Holy Thursday (also called Maundy Thursday) to mark the last supper
and Good Friday the crucifixion, and concluding with Easter, which
marks Jesus's resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   Among the rituals at many churches: the distribution of palm
fronds, a reminder of the branches crowds used to welcome Jesus to
Jerusalem. Catholics, and some Lutherans and Episcopalians, will
venerate the cross on Friday; some churches hold foot-washing
ceremonies on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox Christians, because of a different calendar, will
celebrate Holy Week starting April 23.
</P>
<P>
   For Jews, Wednesday night marks the start of Passover, an 8-day
holiday marking the Jewish exodus from Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   On the first, and in some families, on the second night of
Passover, Jews hold a seder, a banquet with a liturgical text,
called a haggadah, which tells the story of the enslavement of Jews
in Egypt, the confrontation between Moses and Pharaoh, and the
escape of the Jews across a divinely-parted Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
   The seder is laden with ritual symbols, but the central practice
is the consumption of matzah, an unleavened bread. Observant Jews
do not eat bread or other fermented grain products throughout
Passover, honoring ancestors who left Egypt in such haste that they
did not have time for dough to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Question of the Week
</P>
<P>
   What is the connection between Jesus's last supper and Passover?
</P>
<P>
   Most scholars now believe that Jesus's last supper -- the last
meal Jesus ate before being crucified -- was a Passover seder.
</P>
<P>
   The gospel of John disputes this conclusion, but Mark, Luke and
Matthew all say that the last supper was a seder, and scholars have
sided with them, according to the Rev. John H. Elliott, a
University of San Francisco theologian.
</P>
<P>
   The Passover meal is the symbolic basis for the central element
of Christian ritual, the eucharist, or holy communion, which is
called in some denominations the Lord's supper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an expression of the continuity of Christianity and
Judaism and the unity of the two,'' Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   Passover and Holy Thursday, which is the Christian commemoration
of the last supper, are both dated according to a lunar calendar,
but do not coincide because of complicated dating adjustments made
by Christian authorities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
