<HEADLINE>
THE SKY ISN'T FALLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Over the last 10 astonishing economic years, the
sky was first said to be falling when the Mexican peso went south
at the end of 1994, not coincidentally at the same time confidence
in Mexican self-government was headed in the same direction.
</P>
<P>
   Barely two years after that crisis, Chicken Little started
shrieking again when a devaluation of Thailand's currency set off a
financial scramble that upset applecarts not just throughout Asia
but in less advanced, emerging economies throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   And then, for good measure, the summer of 1998 brought an
additional jolt when Russia's financial system, rotten in its core,
melted down in panic.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, of course, the ability of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries, after several years of relative
weakness, in order to make a production limit stick and produce a
sharp spike in prices set off a fresh round of commentary that
global recession (lead by the United States) was again in prospect.
</P>
<P>
   And now those who equate the US stock markets with the US
economy are leading a fresh chorus as preposterous equity values
concentrated in still-emerging sectors of our prosperous economy
seek a more sensibly valued floor.
</P>
<P>
   In the context of all this serial angst, the relentlessly sober
views of the International Monetary Fund deserve more attention
than they have received in the days leading up to its annual
conference here with the World Bank. It's more fun to focus on
street theater here and irrational anti-exuberance on Wall Street,
but the World economic outlook for this spring from a bunch of very
smart people with solid track records for prediction and policies
that make prediction self-fulfilling has a place, too.
</P>
<P>
   Just for the record, the IMF's estimate of the world's output of
goods and services last year has now been raised a full percentage
point from Asian financial crisis-induced pessimism of late-1998 to
a basically robust 3.3 percent. The main reasons: a shift toward
more stimulative monetary policy in the major industrial economies,
especially Europe; and the success in the short term of
stabilization and reform efforts in the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   For this year, the targets have also been raised. For the world,
the IMF puts growth after inflation at about 4.25 percent, an
especially hopeful sign because the estimate assumes healthy
progress throughout the world. According to Michael Mussa,
directors of the IMF's research department, ``All areas of the
world economy are contributing to the strengthening and growth
prospects going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the proper context for thinking about the United States,
still the source of one-fourth of the world economy's output. The
IMF now recognizes the reality of the last two quarters' rapid
growth rates and has sharply increased its estimate for this
country from only 2.5 percent last October to more than 4 percent
now, with inflation still expected to be in the 2.5 percent range.
</P>
<P>
   Using the broadest brush, the US economy in recent years has
been the major source of growth juice by far for the rest of the
world, best reflected in our huge imbalance in trade and thus
financial accounts, which are unsustainable over time and need to
come down, hopefully gradually. Now, however, the rest of the world
is growing more rapidly and the American economy will benefit in
the long run if it starts growing less rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits will be similar if the US sticks to its healthy
posture in terms of fiscal discipline, is vigilant in avoiding
inflation, relentless in reducing private and public debt burdens,
and responsible in saving more.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the main risk to the IMF's outlook in the fund's own
view is that growth in the US will be much more vigorous than
expected, not less. To the extent that happens _ with some signs of
gradually accelerating inflation already visible beyond just oil _
the monetary tightening that would be necessary by Alan Greenspan's
Federal Reserve would be much more severe and harmful to the
prospects for continued growth.
</P>
<P>
   This is really boring but really basic. The Chicken Littles have
been wrong, not by accident, but because mature people worked their
tails off to get the fundamentals as right as possible. And in
deference to a great song from a great movie, the fundamental
things really do apply as time goes by.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
