<HEADLINE>
WORLD'S FAIR WILL BE LARGEST EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the year to visit Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot remember a year in which so many fascinating
phenomena have come together to add enrichment and depth to visits
to our country,'' said Udo Grebe, general manager of the German
National Tourist Office in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   EXPO2000 will not only be Germany's first world's fair, but also
the largest such fair to date. The fair will run June 1 through
Oct. 31 in Hannover with more than 190 nations participating. While
not official, the United States is expected to have a pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout 2000, visitors to Germany will have hundreds of
opportunities to celebrate the extraordinary life and work of
Johann Sebastian Bach, who died 250 years ago. Events began in
Eisenach where Bach was christened in 1685. Leipzig, where Bach
spent many years, will have a major cultural event, Bach 2000, July
21-30, and the year will end with a final crescendo with a New
Year's Eve concert in Leipzig's 13th-century St. Thomas Church.
</P>
<P>
   This is also the 600th birthday of Johannes Gutenberg, the
father of printing. Mainz, where he was born, will have many events
to mark his invention of movable type, a technology that changed
the world forever.
</P>
<P>
   Once every 10 years the villagers of Oberammergau perform a
Passion play recalling the last days of Jesus. The May 22-Oct. 8
performances continue a promise made in the 1600s.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on travel to Germany, write the German
National Tourist Office, 122 East 42nd St., New York, NY 10168;
telephone 212-661-7200 or visit www.germany-tourism.de. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Taxing thoughts &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With this year's tax deadline, maybe an escape to the Charles
Hotel in Cambridge, Mass. is in order. It offers a Blessed Relief
Recovery Overnight that includes a welcome Blessed Relief Martini,
limo to the post office (Tums will be on board), an overnight stay,
a body wrap at Le Pli Day Spa in the hotel (to rehydrate that
dried-out post-IRS feeling), one hour session with a tax attorney
or investment counselor, complimentary copy of ``The Complete Guide
to Offshore Money Havens: How to Make Millions and Legally Avoid
Taxes,'' Sunday brunch, free piggy bank, and admission to the
Regatta Bar Jazz Festival. The package, if still available, is
$399.99 a person, double occupancy. For information, call
800-882-1818.
</P>
<P>
   While taxes are unavoidable, Budget Rent a Car is letting
members of its customer loyalty program, Perfect Drive, benefit
from them. Members receive points on each rental to be used toward
motorhome rentals, resort and cruise vacations, airline miles, and
more. Budget's tax break will let members receive points for the
entire rental transaction, taxes included. Perfect Drive
participants who book and rent their vehicles on Budget's Web site,
www.budget.com, will receive double points on all rentals until
June 30, 2001. For more information, or to enroll in Perfect Drive,
go to the Web site. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Patriots' trail &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For those interested in learning more about the events of this
Patriot's Day weekend, the Literary Trail of Boston is featuring
Saturday guided tours in April that emphasize the link between
native authors' most memorable writings and the events of 1775. The
tour begins at the Omni Parker House where Henry Wadsworth
Longfellow read excerpts from his famous poem ``The Midnight Ride
of Paul Revere.'' The tour includes Longfellow's house, which also
was George Washington's headquarters during the Revolution, and
other landmarks. The tour begins at 9 a.m., stops in Harvard Square
at 12:15 p.m. for those wishing to tour Cambridge, and returns to
the Parker House by 12:30 p.m. Tours are $35 for adults, $29 for
students and seniors. Reservations are required but tickets may be
available on the day of the tour. For tickets or information, call
617-574-5850 or visit www.lit-trail.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fiesta time &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 109th Fiesta San Antonio will be held Saturday through April
30. The nine-day celebration commemorates San Antonio's rich
history and diverse cultures. More than 150 events are planned
including three parades, one that travels down the city's famed
River Walk on April 24 and another, the Battle of Flowers Parade on
April 28. The Fiesta Flambeau Parade, the largest illuminated night
parade in the nation, will be held April 29. For more information
on the fiesta, call 877-723-4378 or on the Web, visit
www.fiesta-sa.org. For information on San Antonio, call
800-447-3372 or visit www.SanAntonioCVB.com.
</P>
