<HEADLINE>
HOW'S YOUR GEOGRAPHY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How's your geography? Not so good if you think the Tropic of
Cancer is a sunscreen lotion or that the Gaza Strip is a daring
Mideast dance. We don't know who originally wrote these, but
Kitty's Daily Mews (www.katscratch.com) lists more instances where
you need to brush up on your geography if you think that:
</P>
<P>
   --The $10,000 Pyramid is in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   --The Cumberland Gap gives out a pair of clogs with every set of
jeans sold.
</P>
<P>
   --The Equator is a cartoon action figure.
</P>
<P>
   --The Continental Shelf is a specialty section of the
supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   --The Bermuda Triangle is a percussion instrument in a reggae
band.
</P>
<P>
   --The Dust Bowl is Granny's old favorite dish.
</P>
<P>
   --A fault is what you find in other people.
</P>
<P>
   --A fiord is a Norwegian car.
</P>
<P>
   --You can do a research paper to find out who killed the Dead
Sea.
</P>
<P>
   (We thank faithful contributor and Web whiz Mike Schuster of
Foxborough, Mass. for locating this nonsense.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: It's the volcanic belt surrounding the Pacific
Ocean. It's also a song by Johnny Cash. What is its name? (Answer
at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
How's that again? A Cape Cod traveler reports that he and his wife
were reading the information provided about their hotel in Puerto
Plata in the Dominican Republic. One warning said there can be ``no
toples at the pool.'' Because there were no lifeguards, they
assumed this meant ``no topples''; that is, no diving. ``How
naive!'' the traveler writes. ``It meant no topless bathing for
women.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Wildlife and comfy quarters: Combine New England's natural delights
with lodging in charming country inns, and you've got Bird/Inn
Tours. A six-day excursion, beginning Sunday, May 14, will focus on
the beauty of spring in New England, with its diverse wildlife.
Escorts will include Audubon Society guides and biologists from the
New Hampshire Department of Fish &AMP; Game. The tour, designed for
beginning and intermediate nature enthusiasts and birders, will
visit the Plum Island area in Massachusetts and remote wildlife
sanctuaries in New Hampshire's White Mountains and Great North
Woods regions. Prices, which include most meals, begin at $1,825
per person, double occupancy. For more information, call
603-464-4783 or 888-258-0841, fax 603-464-5401, e-mail
birdinn(at)karno.com or visit www.lkarno.com/birdinn. Warblers and
moose are standing by. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mailbag: To Barbara Donchess of Canton: What you heard in Ireland
is basically correct: There is no one word in Gaelic for ``yes.''
When asked a question, a person speaking Gaelic may answer like
this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you going?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am.''
</P>
<P>
   (We thank Orla Carey of the Irish Tourist Board and Lorraine
Moloney of Aer Lingus for the information.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Advice to go: Few things are more irritating than a stain on
your clothes when you're on the road and your wardrobe is limited.
Here, from Travel Holiday, are some readily available helpers:
juice from a lemon for a spaghetti-sauce stain; lemon juice with
salt for ink on light-colored fabrics; hairspray for lipstick;
shaving cream for coffee, ketchup, or blood; and talcum powder or
NutraSweet, sprinkled on stains from salad dressing or other oils,
then brushed or rinsed off. The magazine advises working from the
opposite side of the fabric and using cold water only on non-greasy
stains. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Oh, woe: Sixty-three percent of travelers reported that they or a
companion have gotten sick while on vacation, according to a
national survey. The most common illnesses were sunburn (62
percent), motion or seasickness (34 percent), and allergies (34
percent). Other illnesses included ``Montezuma's Revenge'' (23
percent), and food poisoning (12 percent). The survey, commissioned
by Transderm Scop Transdermal Therapeutic System, a prescription
motion-sickness patch, also found that the vacationers surveyed
spend more than $1,200 per trip. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? The Ring of Fire.
</P>
