<HEADLINE>
AN INNOVATIVE SHIP FOR THE MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you ask two of the people closely associated with the new
Celebrity Cruises Millennium what is great about the ship, chances
are they'll talk about what you can't see.
</P>
<P>
   While the ship is breaking ground in innovations for passengers,
Demetrios Kaparis, senior vice president, new building for
Celebrity, and Richard Fain, chairman of Royal Caribbean
International, can't say enough about the ship's engines.
</P>
<P>
   The engines are gas turbine, and so you won't forget, the words
Gas Turbine will be emblazoned on both sides of the ship, which
enters service on May 31 in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers are not allowed in the engine room, nor will they be
able to see the azoids that propel the ship. But they may sense the
engines in the smoother, quieter ride promised. The engines built
by General Electric in Cincinnati will soon be making their way
into all new Celebrity and Royal Caribbean International ships.
</P>
<P>
   What passengers will see will be a ship that promises luxury,
comfort, fine dining, entertainment, shopping, and safety in a
style that, according to the line, will set the pace for the 21st
century of cruising. The Millennium will have glass-enclosed
elevators that ride on the outside of the ship and will afford an
ocean view on each journey between decks. It will have an
alternative dining room where guests can see into the kitchen (one
section of the dining room will have paneling taken from the
first-class dining room of the Olympic, sister ship to the
Titanic); there will be a lavish spa for taking water therapy to
new heights; and it will have more shops on board than any other
ship. The Millennium will have the largest percentage of ocean-view
staterooms of any cruise ship with 74 percent having verandas. Two
of the largest penthouse suites on the seas will be featured, each
with an outdoor whirlpool, along with 48 other large suites, all
with butler service. The main dining room will be on two levels
with huge expansive windows. Other features include a cinema, a
music library with 1,500 selections, an Internet cafe, a glamorous
casino, a sports deck, children's area, and an extensive
contemporary art collection throughout the ship.
</P>
<P>
   The 91,000-ton vessel will carry 1,950 guests with a crew of
999.
</P>
<P>
   The Millennium is in its final stages of construction in France.
Celebrity Cruises has assembled an international cast of designers
to create interiors that are expected to be the talk of the cruise
world. The design team of Wilson Butler Lodge of Boston is creating
the grand foyer, music library, extreme sports bar, and other
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Fain and Kaparis can't say enough about the power
plant. While the new engines will cost more to operate than diesel
engines, they point out the engines' small size allows more room
for passenger comfort, added cabins, and a cleaner atmosphere,
which meets the new stricter Alaskan environmental laws. Even
passengers near the engine room will not hear the engines, Fain
said. ``The combination of the gas turbine, steam turbine
integrated electric system with podded drive propulsion units will
create a revolution in marine propulsion technology while
introducing a new unique era in future Millennium cruise-ships
design,'' said Kaparis.
</P>
<P>
   Like all Celebrity ships, the food service is expected to be
superb, but the Millennium will be just a cut above the line's
other ships with the introduction of a specialty dining room, the
Olympic. Like all Celebrity ships, the food service is overseen by
Michel Roux, a renowned French chef whose Waterside Inn near London
consistently wins three stars by Guide Michelin. The Olympic will
provide a new dining experience. The alternative dining room
seating 134 guests will have 10 chefs, with each cooking for about
13 guests, providing what Roux said will be ``the highest level of
service and gastronomy available onboard any large cruise vessel
today.'' Tableside cooking will also be offered.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity targets guests between 35-54 with a household income
of $75,000. The passenger list, Celebrity said, includes about 93
percent couples, 5 percent families with children, and 2 percent
singles. It added that 83 percent of its passengers are from the
United States and 14 percent international.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity is Royal Caribbean's premium cruise line, but like all
cruise ships, by booking early, travelers can enjoy the luxury
without paying a premium price. A seven-night Caribbean cruise this
fall begins at $1,795 but the early booking price is $1,199.
</P>
<P>
   This more than promises to be the ship of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The ship is the first of a series of Millennium-class ships by
the line. The second will be the Infinity also under construction
at Chantiers de l'Atlantique in St. Nazaire, France. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston cruises &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston's cruise season begins this week. The Norwegian Majesty
returns for another season of 27 weekly embarkations to Bermuda. In
addition to the Majesty, three cruise lines have added embarkations
from the Black Falcon Cruise Terminal in South Boston. Two of the
lines are new to Boston. The first, Premier Cruise Lines, launches
36 cruises aboard the SeaBreeze alternating between two-night
cruises to nowhere and five-night cruises to Halifax, Nova Scotia,
and Saint John, New Brunswick. Another Premier vessel, The Big Red
Boat II, will make 20 port-of-call visits during its New
England/Canada itineraries out of New York. Carnival Cruises has
three cruises scheduled out of Boston _ one three-day cruise to
Saint John and two four-day cruises to Halifax and Saint John.
Cunard Line's Queen Elizabeth 2 will offer four theme transatlantic
cruises from Boston to Southampton, England, in May, June, and
September.
</P>
<P>
   A record-setting 116 ship calls are scheduled at the Black
Falcon Cruise Terminal this year. Some 200,000 passengers are
expected with an economic impact on the region estimated at $50
million.
</P>
<P>
   Also this season, Silverseas' Cruise Line's Silver Wind, a
296-passenger luxury class ship, arrives in Boston after a 10-day
Atlantic crossing from Dublin on Sept. 22 for a Sept. 23
embarkation to New England/Canadian ports. The line's brand new
ship, Silver Shadow, visits on Oct. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean's Splendour of the Seas makes four embarkations
to New England and Canadian ports. Princess Cruises' Crown Princess
visits six times. Holland America's Maasdam visits four times,
including a 10-day New England/Canada sailing from Boston. Other
cruise lines visiting Boston include Dolphin, Clipper, Regal, and
Seabourn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Converts wanted &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   St. Thomas in the US Virgin Islands is looking to convert cruise
passengers into future resort guests. The West Indian Company
Limited and the St. Thomas-St. John Hotel and Tourism Association
are setting up Welcome Centers along the St. Thomas dock. At these,
cruise passengers will be greeted and encouraged to complete a
short questionnaire card with their name and address. As an
incentive to supply the information, each adult who fills out a
card is entered into that month's free vacation sweepstakes, a
six-day vacation on St. Thomas. The information supplied on the
cards will be used for mailings with promotional materials and
special vacation offers on the islands. The information kiosks will
also have information on the islands' resorts and attractions.
Similar incentives are planned for St. Croix. Cruise ships bring
1.6 million visitors to the island every year, said Rafael Jackson,
acting commissioner of tourism for the islands, ``One would be
foolish not to approach these people and ask them to come back.''
For more information on the islands or the program, call the
visitors' bureau at 800-372-USVI. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cruise plus &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travelers age 50 or older looking to experience the greatest two
minutes in sports have the opportunity to take advantage of Saga
Holidays Two for One sale. Book a four-night cruise down the Ohio
River to the 126th running of the Kentucky Derby aboard the
legendary Delta Queen and receive a free seven-night holiday to
either Scottsdale, Ariz., or Bangkok, Thailand. Prices begin at
$2,999 a person, including air fare. For details call 800-952-9590.
</P>
</TEXT>
