<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKINNY STRIP OF EARTH SEEKS COMPATIBLE NAME  
 WHERE DOES YOUR GARDEN GROW? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer in the city will be better than ever now that so many
homeowners are planting flowers not only in front of their houses,
but in that little strip of dirt between the sidewalk and the curb,
too. On one street in my neighborhood, tall orange daylilies line
almost a whole block, fluttering and dancing in the breeze in fine
Wordsworthian style. There's only one problem with this burgeoning
floral trend: What do we call that curbside planting strip?
</P>
<P>
   In much of my native Midwest, it's a tree lawn. But tree lawn
sounds a bit grand for the scrubby 14-inch ribbon of earth on a
semi-urban street, and besides, none of my Boston-bred colleagues
know the term. My queries have brought, so far, some quizzical
looks, shakes of the head, and one ``It isn't berm, is it?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it could be, but not in Boston: Berm for the sidewalk
strip is a Great Lakes usage, according the Dictionary of American
Regional English. Other parts of the country call it devil strip or
planting strip or terrace. But surely Boston and the Northeast _ a
civilized territory that knows the value of sidewalks _ should have
a label for this streetside strip.
</P>
<P>
   If it does, please let me know, you native speakers out there in
your sprouting gardens; if it doesn't, let's find one. Fill in the
blank: ``This year I want to plant something different in my
-----.'' A place that's still fighting to call its soda pop tonic
and its milkshakes frappes should be able to come up with a
colorful name for a floral fringe along the curb.
</P>
<P>
   Not that local lingo is in danger of dying out. Despite the
leveling influence of television and radio, regional accents and
idioms are flourishing, according to recent linguistic studies. And
as someone who hails from a lexical border area _ to the north were
seesaws and faucets, to the south teeter-totters and spigots _ I
find regional variations more fascinating than frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is so tolerant. Boston has a goodly share of
citizens who wait and stand on line, but as long as 40 years ago,
some usage commentators were complaining about it, warning that on
line could displace the more usual in line.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on line, they seem to agree, began as a New York City
idiom. And from the '60s to the '80s, language watchers believed
the use was spreading, or at least becoming more recognizable: It
finds its way into print in Houston, for example, in the '80s.
Magazine editors and television writers, they theorized, were
helping to spread the virus.
</P>
<P>
   But is standing on line really spreading? And if so, will the
Internet's appropriation of on line (and on-line and online) stop
it dead, any minute now?
</P>
<P>
   The evidence from the Globe's 22 years of electronic records was
surprising: Even in Boston, probably second only to New York in the
conversational use of standing (or waiting) on line, the on line
idiom is rare in print. The peak year for on line in the New York
sense was 1978, when six different stories used it _ and one of
them was a jeremiad by a native Bostonian incensed by the invasion
of on line, which he took for a ``pseudo-British affectation.''
Standing in line, by contrast, is so common the computer refuses to
count it: ``Your search is too general,'' it tells me.
</P>
<P>
   And now, even The New York Times has repudiated standing on
line. The latest edition of the newspaper's stylebook, published
last year, says, ``In most of the English-speaking world, people
stand in line. Use that wording.''
</P>
<P>
   This ruling means that over time, as editors' ears adapt to the
new order, the Times will print standing on line only in
quotations. This doesn't mean it will disappear from the language;
we need lots of expressions we would rarely put into type, like a
whole nother thing and put the groceries in the way back. But it
may turn out to be simpler if we all get in line, and reserve
waiting on line for those interminable seconds we spend staring at
our struggling computer screens.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jan Freeman's e-mail address is freeman(at)globe.com; write to
her at The Boston Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378. Please
include a hometown and phone number.
</P>
</TEXT>
