<HEADER>
A0384 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-PILATE-BOS &LR;      04-18 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PILATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO WAS PONTIUS PILATE? A THOROUGH LOOK AT JESUS' JUDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
Pontius Pilate
<TEXT>
<P>
   by Ann Wroe
</P>
<P>
   Random House, 412 pp. $26.95
</P>
<P>
   BookReview
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He was a central actor in one of history's greatest moments, and
yet we have available to us mere shreds of his life. But that
hasn't stopped writers across the ages from trying to flesh out the
remains of Pontius Pilate.
</P>
<P>
   The mythology that has grown around Pilate is enormous. To some,
he was the ultimate villain _ the man who condemned Jesus, a man
who is central to this Holy Week for Western Christians.
</P>
<P>
   To others, who have sought to cast blame on the Jews of the
time, he was an honorable figure who capitulated to the demand that
Jesus be put to death.
</P>
<P>
   To others, he was a politician willing to sacrifice an
apparently innocent man to keep the peace in a restive outpost of
the Roman Empire.
</P>
<P>
   Now Ann Wroe, the American editor of the Economist, weighs in
with her own thoughts,in a compelling, eloquent and vivid work that
offers a complex portrait of Pilate as neither all good nor all
evil. Hers is an ambivalent Pilate, who when faced with the
decision nearly chose to risk it all, but in the end threw up his
arms, sent Jesus to the cross and then wrote a memo to Rome
defending his actions.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever one chooses to ascribe to Pilate, our fascination with
the fifth governor of Judea has endured over time because, in
``Pontius Pilate,'' Wroe says, ``he stands at the center of the
Christian story and of God's plan of redemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without his climactic judgment of Jesus, the world would not
have been saved. Without Christ's death _ pronounced by Pilate _
there would have been no Resurrection, no founding Christian
miracle,'' she writes. ``To have a faceless bureaucrat at the heart
of all this drama was unacceptable: Something had to be made of
this man.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course there is precious little with which to make something
of Pilate: a few paragraphs from a handful of early Roman histories
and, of course, the well-known accounts in the New Testament. Each
of these, however, is colored by the author's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Even Pilate's actual name is unknown, as is his place of birth.
He might have come from a region south of Rome, or he might have
been born in Seville, Spain, or in a town on the Rhine. A clear
picture of Pilate is frustratingly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   But in a superb blend of scholarship and creativity, Wroe weaves
together the many legends that have grown around Pilate into a rich
tapestry that brings this elusive, yet pivotal, figure to life in
the reader's imagination. Pilate was an ``obstinate, proud,
patriotic, cunning, flippant and heavy-handed'' man, Wroe writes,
and an ``immature and hotheaded'' governor ``who seems less on the
edge of destroying the Jews than of destroying himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Pilate found himself ruling over a volatile corner of the Roman
Empire, the Jewish land whose inhabitants believed they were God's
chosen people, and so were superior to the Romans. Wroe starkly
illustrates how the combination of Pilate's personality and the
Jews' resistance inevitably led to conflict.
</P>
<P>
   And it was these confrontations, Wroe intriguingly intimates,
that set the stage for Pilate's encounter with Jesus. This fierce
and cocky representative of the most powerful empire on earth could
not have his way with the Jews: Their ultimate loyalty was to God,
not Caesar. Instead, Pilate sought an uneasy coexistence with his
subjects, making sure to maintain stability over Judea not because
he harbored any great fondness for the Jews but he feared, more
than anything else, incurring Rome's wrath.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus proved a menace to Pilate's tenure because he challenged
the system; his religious convictions were secondary. Jesus, Wroe
writes, ``threatened the established order in two ways: He
proclaimed indifference to it, seeming to recognize laws of his
own, and he was connected by his followers with `kingship' of a
peculiar and ungraspable sort.''
</P>
<P>
   In a splendidly written section, Wroe depicts a vacillating
Pilate interrogating Jesus, agonizing over his judgment, and
leaning toward mercy. But in the end, when the chief priests who
had condemned Jesus to die won to their side the crowd gathered
outside Pilate's home in Jerusalem, Pilate chose a momentous and
notorious path.
</P>
<P>
   Pilate, Wroe notes, was trapped by his own misdeeds. ``For even
if he wanted to be merciful in this case, he dared not be if it
would lead to a blistering report to Rome of everything else he had
done,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the efforts by some chroniclers to lay the blame for
Jesus's death primarily at the feet of the chief rabbis, Wroe makes
a compelling case that Pilate ultimately bears responsibility. Wroe
does a masterful job of forcing us to think about Pilate in new
ways _ as a man wracked by pain, doubt and guilt who sealed his
fate for millennia to come, and of his own accord.
</P>
<P>
   At a singular moment in history, Pilate had the potential ``for
darkness or light . . . He could take untraveled roads, open hidden
doors, escape the bounds of earth and flesh, exceed himself. Or he
could stay as he was: shrug, scratch his ear, write another
memorandum. He stayed as he was. As most of us do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
