 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, April 19:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-SHARIF (New Delhi) _ Prosecutors in the case of the
deposed prime minister, Nawaz Sharif, filed an appeal in the
country's high court on Tuesday seeking the death penalty instead
of his current sentence of life in prison for hijacking and
terrorism. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   (This story will move by 3 p.m. EST)
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-PHOTOGRAPHERS (Hanoi, Vietnam) _ Twenty-five years after
the Vietnam War ended, a new visual record is emerging from
thousands of photos, little known outside Vietnam, taken from the
communist perspective. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is part of an occasional series marking the 25th
anniversary of the end of the war.)
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-FARMERS (Harare, Zimbabwe) _ In a relatively mild
speech to the nation marking his 20 years in power, President
Robert Mugabe promised Tuesday to redistribute Zimbabwe's best
farmland but did not order war veterans to end their occupation of
white-owned farms. By Henri E. Cauvin.
</P>
<P>
   With locator map.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-POLITICS (Washington) _ Morgan Tsvangirai, the leader
of Zimbabwe's biggest opposition party, visits Washington to seek
help in ensuring free parliamentary elections next month. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-ASYLUM (London) _ William Hague, the Tory leader, has
proposed placing all asylum seekers in detention camps and
deporting them after six weeks if their applications are
unsuccessful. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.N.-RIGHTS (Geneva) _ China used a procedural move to
prevent the U.N. Commission on Human Rights from accepting a U.S.
resolution condemning its human rights policy. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TURKEY (Istanbul) _ President Jiang Zemin of China arrived
in Turkey for a long-awaited state visit Tuesday, but hopes that
the two countries can build a new power axis were overshadowed by a
dispute over ethnic Turks living in China. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   (This story will move by 2 p.m. EST)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-EDUC (Otumba, Mexico) _ A pledge to teach English to all
schoolchildren and to put a computer in every school has backfired
on the presidential candidate of the governing party, Francisco
Labastida. It has left him vulnerable not only to nationalist
attacks about teaching English but also open to questions about
where all the money that is supposed to be spent on education goes.
By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BRIEFS (Undated) _ World news in brief.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA-BOMBING (Oklahoma City) _ The bombing of the federal
building here five years ago Wednesday helped create an identity
for a state that had little outside its own borders. From the ruins
and shattered lives emerged a picture of the Heartland, of
neighbors pulling together to help each other. Some people, like a
local businessman and National Guardsman who now runs an institute
on terrorism here, have a new focus. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-COMPUTERS (Chicago) _ Speaking at a computer trade show,
President Clinton gives more details on his plans to bridge what he
calls the digital divide. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Dateline to come) _ Developments on the continuing
custody battle over Elian Gonzalez. The mayor of Miami has
scheduled a press conference for 12:15 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-ACTIVIST (Miami) _ As other Cuban-American leaders
have dealt with the press and the politicians, Ramon Saul Sanchez
has been a leader of the protesters in front of Lazaro Gonzalez's
house. Once a hard-line opponent of Castro, he has adopted a more
peaceful approach and has pressed for civil disobedience. By
Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CAROLINA-FLAG (Atlanta) _ The symbol of the Confederacy that has
caused so much trouble on one flagpole in South Carolina is on
thousands of poles in Georgia and Mississippi because it is
incorporated in the state flag. Energized by action in South
Carolina to move the Confederate Flag from atop the Capitol dome,
black lawmakers in Georgia and Mississippi are renewing efforts
this year to erase the emblem from their states' flags. By David
Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   DIALLO-LAWSUIT (New York) _ The family of Amadou Diallo, who was
killed by the police last year, files a civil suit against New York
City. By Amy Waldman.
</P>
<P>
   NY-WATER (Undated) _ The New York state attorney general
released a report Tuesday charging New York City environmental
officials with being ``grossly behind schedule'' in their efforts
to modernize 102 old sewage plants that discharge into some of the
city's upstate reservoirs. The plants, mostly in small rural
communities near the city's reservoirs in the Catskills, have long
been seen by water experts as a troublesome source of pollution and
disease-causing parasites. By Andrew Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-DEATH-PENALTY (Washington) _ In two separate cases the
Supreme Court overturned two Virginia death sentences Tuesday in a
significant interpretation of the new federal law governing the
right of state prisoners to appeal in federal court. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CAMPAIGN (Troy, Mich.) _ Gov. George W. Bush visits Battle
Creek to promote a $1.7 billion low-income housing program, then
takes his message to Detroit for a conversation on low-income
housing with housing providers and residents, and ends the day in
Troy at a fundraiser. The day is all part of a constant focus by
his campaign to inject compassion into the conservative message. By
Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks are robust at 1 p.m., with the Nasdaq
composite index up 200 points, the Dow Jones industrial average up
145 points and the S&AMP;P 500 up 27 points. Overseas markets all
higher as well. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-EMPLOYEE-OPTIONS (Undated) _ In the last three years,
Internet companies, with their promise of stock options, have had a
huge advantage in attracting and keeping employees. The sharp
swings in technology stocks have caused these companies to
reassess. Some are looking at stock grants and repricing, all the
while mindful of new accounting rules that will force them to take
a hit. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-STOCKS-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Examining the outlook for
technology in the wake of the recent selloff in technology stocks.
So far, results for the technology leaders have been stellar. By
Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   MERRILL-HSBC (New York) _ HSBC and Merrill Lynch form a joint
venture that will offer online banking and brokerage services to
customers outside the United States. Each company will provide up
$1 billion in start-up capital. The services _ stock trading,
checks, debit cards, cash management and financial planning _ will
be aimed at customers with $100,000 to $500,000 in net assets. By
Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-ANTIQUARIANS (Undated) _ Ordinarily the antiquarian trade
is the dusty, genteel corner of the book market that attracts
fiercely independent booksellers who savor the musty fragrance of
brown-spotted rag paper and the Eureka moment of spotting a rare
first edition dumped in a garage sale heap. But now the dust motes
are flying in the rare and used book market with the flashy
emergence of Alibris, a virtual used bookseller with Wall Street
ambitions and Silicon Valley money. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   COKE-EARNINGS ((Undated) _ Coca-Cola reports weak first quarter
results, but at the high end of expectations as bottlers cut orders
for concentrate. Coke's chief bottler, Coca-Cola Enterprises,
reports a first-quarter loss in line with analysts' expectations.
By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-EARNINGS (Undated) _ America Online expected to post
earnings after the stock market closes. Nine cents a share is the
consensus forecast. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-NUCLEAR (London) _ On British Nuclear Fuels, the
government-owned company that operates the sprawling Sellafield
nuclear complex. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   NOMURA-BRITAIN (London) _ Nomura Securities has agreed to buy
Hyder, the Welsh water company, for $636 million, adding a utility
to its pubs and hotels in Britain. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   WORKPLACE-BOSS (Undated) _ Workplace profile of Homayoon Hariri,
the chairman of System Group Tehran.
</P>
<P>
   WORKPLACE-BLIND-CONSULTANT (Undated) _ Blind people can't easily
tell if a job candidate is white or black, thin or obese, plain or
pretty. So if they should happen to assess an applicant's
professional qualifications, they might well focus on a more
mundane matter: Is she actually suited for the job? That is, in
essence, the question that Herbert Greenberg, 70 years old and
blind since he was 10, has been helping managers answer for the
past 39 years. By Geoffrey Brewer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Commentary by Paul Krugman.
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Commentary by Maureen Dowd.
</P>
