<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0394 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-MAPS-HNS &LR;      04-18 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-MAPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HI-TECH GADGETS HELP DRIVERS FIND THEIR WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Men generally don't ask for directions. It's one
of those rules of masculinity.
</P>
<P>
   But most men will play with the newest gadgets on the market,
even though one of those gadgets just might also direct him to a
destination that he's not sure how to reach.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the new, high-tech, computerized automotive
navigation systems come in. These systems, most with their own
interactive video screens within eyesight and reach of the driver,
have been available for the past two or three years in several
different car makes.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the Global Positioning System satellite network, these
onboard navigation systems instantly determine the vehicle's
location and plot that position on a detailed map in the system's
database.
</P>
<P>
   Using that database, the driver can select a destination, and
this amazing gizmo will lead him or her to it, using either the
most direct or fastest route. Some can even be programmed to use
freeways as much as possible, or as little.
</P>
<P>
   Most also display a moving map that shows the vehicle's present
position, along with the number of miles and the length of time to
the destination, based on the car's average speed.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the driver from having to divert attention from the road
to the video screen, most of these systems also call out directions
as the trip progresses. Sure, the operator must first ask the
navigation system to direct him to a specific destination, but
that's not the same as pulling into a gas station and asking
someone how to get somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Programming the destination into an in-dash navigation system is
usually the first step. To prevent distracting the driver from the
most important task _ operating the vehicle safely _ many of the
systems only allow programming when the vehicle is stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the systems are rather easy to program. We've tried out
several of them, including one installed on a 2001 Volvo V70 wagon.
Most of the systems are installed in the front, center of the
dashboard, next to the instrument panel and just above the audio
and heating/air-conditioning controls.
</P>
<P>
   But the Volvo's navigation screen pops up out of the top of the
center of the dash and is accessed through controls mounted on the
right side of the steering wheel, so the driver can control it
without taking his hand off the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Navigation options on most of the systems include local
landmarks and tourist spots, airports, restaurants, hotels and
government buildings. But every one also allows the operator to
program in a specific street address, then directs the driver to
that location step by step.
</P>
<P>
   One notable exception to this navigation-system setup is the
General Motors OnStar system. It doesn't come with a video screen.
Instead, one push of the OnStar button on the vehicle's dashboard
connects the driver with an OnStar operator via hands-free cellular
phone. Instantaneous transmission of GPS data from the car tells
the OnStar operator exactly where the vehicle is.
</P>
<P>
   The driver can ask the OnStar operator for directions to a
specific destination, and the operator works out a route and reads
it off to the driver. The drawback here is that you still have to
ask a live person for directions, you must write those directions
down (if you're not sure you can remember them) and you have to
call the OnStar operator again if you get lost.
</P>
<P>
   There are advantages to a system such as OnStar. It's more than
just a navigation system. It's set up so the OnStar operator can
unlock the vehicle's doors, turn on the headlights or even honk the
horn by remote control.
</P>
<P>
   For safety's sake, the OnStar system automatically notifies the
operator if one of the vehicle's air bags has deployed or if the
vehicle has been in a collision. The operator will then try to call
the vehicle and, if there is no response, will automatically send
fire, police and rescue personnel to the vehicle's exact location.
There is even a button on the dash to call for help automatically
in any kind of emergency.
</P>
<P>
   The system is highly personalized. During a weeklong test-drive
of a Chevrolet Tahoe equipped with the OnStar system, I was
impressed that the operator already knew my name when I called the
first time to try out the navigation options.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I like the systems with a video screen, where you don't
have to call someone to get directions. I gave the Volvo system a
good tryout on a drive of about 270 miles. All was not perfect, but
the system got me there. Almost, that is.
</P>
<P>
   I punched in the address, and, instead of taking me right to the
house I had programmed into the system, or even the street, it took
me to a street right around the corner from where I was going. And
when it got to that wrong street, about four houses away from my
real destination, it announced to me that I had arrived. Not bad,
but not exactly what I was hoping for.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem with the navigation systems I have tested is
that they don't have a lot of common sense when it comes to
route-mapping. They will get you there, but not always by the most
direct route.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the navigation systems can be a great tool for drivers,
especially those among us who are geographically challenged.
</P>
<P>
   These systems aren't cheap, however. They run about $2,000 to
$2,500 each, and there is an additional charge for periodic updates
of the database to account for new roads and routes.
</P>
<P>
   With the OnStar system, there is an initial installation charge
of about $2,500, plus a monthly fee of about $25 to pay for the
convenience of having an operator on the other end of the line 24
hours a day, seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   So if you have a real need for computerized, automated,
high-tech navigation and can afford it, one of these systems might
be a good idea. But a simple roadmap, which costs about $3 these
days, is a whole lot cheaper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
