<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0405 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-CELL-PHONES-$ADV23-CO     04-18 1609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELL-PHONES-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LAWMAKERS BEGIN TO WEIGH DANGERS OF DRIVERS WITH CELL PHONES
 &HT;    1000&AMP;add. With CELL-LAWS and CELL-DATA. For release Sunday,
April 23.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Ohio _ Take heed in this working-class burg on the
southern outskirts of Cleveland. Motorcycle cop Rick Hovan has a
sharp eye out for motorists who dare to gab on their mobile phones
while cruising through town.
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn (pop. 11,000) welcomes visitors at its city limits with
a stern reminder on roadside signs: ``Park 2 Talk. It's the Law.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first municipality in the nation to ban the use of
hand-held cellular telephones while driving, a law created last
year after a city employee changing a tire was nearly run down by a
driver with a phone to his ear.
</P>
<P>
   Driving and talking is a social epidemic nearly everyone seems
to complain about, yet nearly everyone with a cell phone does.
</P>
<P>
   Every two seconds in America, a new customer signs up for mobile
telephone service, and the total number of subscribers is already
more than 91 million. As many as 85 percent of drivers with phones
use them at least occasionally while on the road, according to a
recent survey.
</P>
<P>
   Some law enforcement officials and safety policy experts fear
that the risks will only grow as car manufacturers and the wireless
telecommunications industry team up on designs for a generation of
``smart'' cars offering built-in telephones, computer mapping
displays, Internet access and voice-activated e-mail. Ford and GM
are set to offer digital services in selected luxury models next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should drivers keep both hands on the wheel? Any reasonable
person would say, 'Of course,''' said Fran Bents, a researcher who
co-authored a 1997 study of wireless devices and driving by the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite proposals introduced in at least 34 states since
1995, including Georgia and Texas, no state legislature has managed
to pass meaningful restrictions on cell phone use by motorists.
Only a handful of small cities have enacted such laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike other transportation safety issues like drunk driving
and seat belt use, you don't have a strong, well-organized national
group behind this issue, but you've got the telecommunications
industry lobbying hard against it,'' said Matt Sundeen, a policy
specialist at the National Conference of State Legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn, a town of trim, suburban bungalows and several robust
factories _ home of American Greetings, the greeting card maker _
passed its law in March 1999 and began enforcing it last September.
</P>
<P>
   The law bans hand-held phones, but allows hands-free devices.
About 300 tickets have been issued. With a fine of just $3 per
citation, less than a parking ticket, the law is intended to raise
public awareness, not fill the city's coffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are tired of seeing drivers weave in and out of
traffic, paying more attention to their conversation on the phone
than what's in front of them on the road. It's a nuisance,'' said
Police Chief Jack Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   In Pennsylvania, Patricia Pena knows first-hand the danger. Her
2-year-old daughter, Morgan Lee, died last November from injuries
suffered in an accident in Hilltown Township, near Philadelphia,
when a driver on a cell phone ran a stop sign and broadsided Pena's
car.
</P>
<P>
   In suburban Gwinnett County near Atlanta, Lisa Duffner, 35, had
a similar experience as she and her family took a walk on their
quiet street. A teen-age driver on a cell phone ran up onto the
lawn, killing her 2-year-old son Ryan and the family dog in March
1999. Duffner was in a coma for three days, only to awake to the
news from her husband that Ryan was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Pena and Duffner are leading a grassroots crusade to warn of the
dangers of cell phones and driving. Pena has made appearances on
national television, including the ``Oprah'' show, and before state
lawmakers in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Duffner appeared before a Georgia legislative committee earlier
this year to support a bill. She is distributing bumper stickers
that read: ``Hang up and drive _ cell phone abuse kills,'' and
plans to create a Web site and lead a drive to convince the Georgia
legislature to act in next year's session.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people think we're trying to take away their freedoms.
Well, my son had rights, too. He had the right to live,'' said
Duffner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd go anywhere. I'd do anything to talk about this issue. I
feel I owe it to my daughter,'' Pena said in a telephone interview.
``My goal is to make this socially unacceptable, to make drivers
embarrassed to have a phone at their ear and to make people on the
other end threaten to hang up if they know the person they talking
to is behind the wheel.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Pena's accident, three Pennsylvania towns have created
laws restricting cell phone use, and some 300 municipalities around
the country are considering similar ordinances.
</P>
<P>
   Tom and Ray Magliozzi, hosts of the popular ``Car Talk'' show on
National Public Radio, also have taken up the cause. They
distribute bumper stickers declaring: ``Drive Now, Talk Later.''
</P>
<P>
   Few state and local governments keep statistics on cell phone
use as a contributing factor in traffic accidents. With a lack of
hard evidence, state legislators have been reluctant to impose
restrictions that could provoke the fury of constituents who enjoy
the convenience of cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   The mobile telephone industry and automobile manufacturers
oppose laws restricting the use of phones and other electronic
gadgets, contending that drivers simply need to be educated in
order to prevent accidents. When radios began appearing in the
first production automobiles in the early 20th century, critics of
proposed cell phone restrictions point out, some officials wanted
to ban them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single state has laws that address careless driving,
inattentive driving, reckless driving. Police know it when they see
it, whether the driver is using a radio or putting on makeup or
using a wireless telephone,'' said Lisa Ihde, who runs the public
education program for the Cellular Telecommunications Industry
Association.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The industry association has created a safety-awareness campaign
on its Web site and with a toll-free number (1-888-901-SAFE). The
industry also points to statistics that suggest that cell phones in
cars save lives. The ability of motorists to make 911 calls to
report accidents has reduced paramedic response times.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a controversial 1997 Canadian study published in the New
England Journal of Medicine concluded that the risk of an accident
increases fourfold if a driver is using a cell phone, about the
same risk as driving while drunk when measuring factors such as
reaction time and susceptibility to being easily distracted.
</P>
<P>
   The study's authors have since pointed out, though, the drinking
and driving is far more dangerous for a long list of other reasons,
such as the lingering effects of alcohol in the bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   A National Highway Transportation Safety Administration report
of 1998 crash data showed that driver distraction was a factor in
about 1 of every four fatal accidents. Cellular phones were a
factor in at least 57 deaths, compared with only seven in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But experts consider the data to be weak because of the lack of
nationwide reporting. For the most part, an eyewitness or police
officer must see a driver on the phone to record it as part of the
accident report. Drivers involved in accidents can easily slip the
phone into a pocket or glove compartment.
</P>
<P>
   From the vantage point atop his Harley Davidson, patrolman Hovan
sees the dangers nearly every day as drivers with phones drift
across lanes and roll through stop signs.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent rainy spring day in Brooklyn, Hovan pulled over a
luxury sedan to write a ticket to a man on his cell phone. The
driver protested, saying he was a vascular surgeon who needed to
use his phone to deal with medical cases and operating-room
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   With the ticket, Hovan issued his bottom-line warning: Is
talking on the phone worth risking taking a life? Why not pull over
to finish your call?
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want to hear it. He's got a hectic lifestyle,
emergencies, kids with him in the car,'' Hovan said. ``Everybody
thinks they have no time and they've got to be on the phone while
they drive.''
</P>
<P>
   To hammer home his message, Hovan now carries a picture of
Morgan Lee Pena, sent to him by her mother, and explains the story
of the dead Pennsylvania girl to the drivers he stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell people, 'The city doesn't want your three dollars.
Damn, I'll give you three dollars to pay the fine. Just please be
aware of the danger,''' said Hovan. ``Some tell me they think it's
stupid, and you know what I say to people like that? 'I wonder if
you'd say the same thing if it had been your daughter.' ``
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   National Highway Traffic Safety Administration:
www.nhtsa/gov/people/injury/research/wireless/index.html
</P>
<P>
   National Conference of State Legislatures:
www.ncsl.org/programs/ESNR/phonauto.html
</P>
<P>
   New England Journal of Medicine:
www.nejm.org/content/1997/0336/0007/0453.asp
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Pena's campaign for cellular phone legislation:
www.geocities.com/morganleepena/
</P>
<P>
   Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association safety
campaign: www.wow-com.com/consumer/driving/safety/cfm
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
