<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0416 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-EBONICS-HNS &LR;      04-18 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBONICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EBONICS REVISITED, NEW BOOK CHALLENGES THE OLD CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VENISE WAGNER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In ``Spoken Soul,'' father and son John and
Russell Rickford render a 267-page analysis of the language of
black folks, now commonly known as Ebonics.
</P>
<P>
   John Rickford, a Stanford University linguist, and Russell
Rickford, a former Philadelphia Inquirer reporter, argue that
spoken soul (a term writer Claude Brown coined in the 1960s) is a
language African Americans should celebrate and proudly claim as
their own, in addition to mastering standard English.
</P>
<P>
   They bolster their argument with a comprehensive examination of
the origins and grammar patterns of black English or as linguists
call it, African American Vernacular English. They delve into the
debate about whether it's a language or dialect and whether it has
connections to West African languages. And they examine the
country's social construct that likely has contributed to the
continued existence of black English.
</P>
<P>
   The Rickfords, who are African American, courageously jump into
the Ebonics controversy that rocked Oakland, Calif., in 1996 when
the school board approved a resolution _ albeit garbled _ that
recognized black English as the home language of African American
students. The resolution called for a curriculum that acknowledged
Ebonics and used it as a starting point to teach standard English
to African American students - most of whom were performing way
below average.
</P>
<P>
   While correcting some of the inaccuracies reported throughout
the ordeal, the Rickfords also critique media coverage of the
issue, blasting print and broadcast journalists and columnists for
their myopia and lack of depth on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   The authors review the history of black English in black
literature, making the point that some of the outrage toward
Oakland's plan came from people who have used Ebonics in their art,
Maya Angelou was one.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the Rickfords present the material in an awkward
order, forcing them to refer to preceding or succeeding pages
mid-sentence. And they spent too little time discussing the effect
of class on the debate of Ebonics' legitimacy that raged, and in
some circles still rages, within the black community. Although,
they do examine briefly some of the social factors that led to the
blind reproach of Oakland's plan in the larger public.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, middle- and upper-class African Americans felt a sense
of embarrassment that white people would believe they, being
educated and professional African Americans, condone the use of
Ebonics, a symbol of poor education and laziness.
</P>
<P>
   The authors adeptly blow this theory out of the water
demonstrating that Ebonics is not corrupted English, but a complex
system of language patterns.
</P>
<P>
   There's a right way to speak Ebonics and a wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   They run down the accepted uses of Ebonics by preachers,
singers, pop artists, rappers, comedians and writers.
</P>
<P>
   Where would Malcolm X and Martin Luther King Jr. be without the
intonations and cadences of spoken soul, they wonder. Ebonics is
the stamp of authenticity of the black experience in the works of
playwright August Wilson, novelists Toni Morrison and Langston
Hughes and poet Paul Lawrence Dunbar.
</P>
<P>
   It's an impressive list of rich works that demonstrates the
hypocrisy of denouncing black English as backwards. Yet as the
Oakland controversy demonstrated, Ebonics in art is much easier to
swallow than the notion that Ebonics is legit enough to use in the
schools.
</P>
<P>
   As advocates for Ebonics, it would have been easy for the
Rickfords to claim West African languages as the sole origin of the
language system. But they take the high road, offering theories
from both sides of the debate among scholars: the Anglicists who
say the grammar, pronunciation and vocabulary of black English
comes from British dialects that blacks might have heard from
English settlers in the 17th and 18th centuries; and the
Africanists who say Ebonics pronunciation and grammar largely rises
from African language systems imposed on an English construct.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Anglicists maintain that the pronunciation of
``th'' as ``t,'' ``d,'' ``f,'' and ``v'' (dem for them or bave for
bathe) comes from British settlers, many of whom were peasants,
speaking nonstandard English. Africanists, however, argue that
because West African languages did not include the ``th'' sound,
Africans in America substituted consonants similar to ``th'' in
their own language, the Rickfords write.
</P>
<P>
   The authors conclude both cultures more than likely influenced
this pronunciation.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Rickfords reveal that Africans in America and
their descendants probably used both British dialects and African
languages, and creole to develop a complex system of grammar,
pronunciation and vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, ``Spoken Soul'' offers insight into the evolution of
Ebonics (Black English, as a living, breathing language, continues
to evolve.) and the debate surrounding it. If the Rickfords aimed
to make readers pause and think about their own reactions to the
language and those who speak it, then they succeeded.
</P>
</TEXT>
