<HEADER>
A0420 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-SNIFFER-$ADV23-COX     04-18 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNIFFER-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE ELECTRONIC NOSE IS GROWING FAST
 &HT;    620&AMP;add. For release Sunday, April 23.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON You may say to-MAH-to and I may say to-MAY-to, but
with one quick sniff, the electronic nose can say, ``vine ripened''
or ``picked green.''
</P>
<P>
   Pass the orange juice, and the machine will tell you if it is
fresh-squeezed or made from frozen concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   Sensors on electronic chips can now detect and measure low
levels of the same airborne compounds that activate the natural
sense of smell, without getting tired or distracted or bored or
subjective or revolted, all problems of human and even dog noses.
</P>
<P>
   The very young science of using electronics and computer
programs to detect and recognize signature ``odors'' is maturing
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, electronic noses, which didn't exist until a few
years ago, are about to start showing up all over _ in industry,
food processing, medicine, national security, even in your home.
</P>
<P>
   One ``E-nose'' developer sees his equipment performing such
disparate tasks as:
</P>
<P>
   _ Diagnosing diseases by sniffing a patient's breath.
</P>
<P>
   _ Informing coffee buyers whether the beans in a bag are true
Kona coffee or a Colombian substitute.
</P>
<P>
   _ Making it possible for a microwave oven to know when food is
really done, not just how long it has been in there.
</P>
<P>
   _ Checking dairy cows to make sure they are in heat and ready to
be artificially inseminated. The monitoring task is now performed
by eternally frustrated bulls that, while skillful at assessing a
cow's frame of mind, do not possess the kind of genes available
through artificial breeding.
</P>
<P>
   At a U.S. Department of Agriculture research laboratory at
Athens, Ga., microbiologist Judy Arnold rinses a piece of chicken
and places the tip of a small syringe-like tool over the rinse
water.
</P>
<P>
   In seconds, an electronic nose tells her whether the meat has
been kept refrigerated or has been allowed to warm and then
re-cooled. It also can tell her if disease-causing pathogens such
as salmonella or e.coli are present.
</P>
<P>
   Her work is not aimed at improving the performance of e-noses.
Instead, she is concerned with finding ways to reduce the presence
of pathogens on processed poultry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't always know the specific compounds that are present
in the odor,'' she said. ``There may be a few, like five or 10, or
there may be 100 or more.''
</P>
<P>
   But the e-nose knows.
</P>
<P>
   At another Agriculture Department lab in Winter Haven, Florida,
a different kind of sniffer not only can tell whether a tomato was
picked ripe or green, but also whether the inside is bruised, even
when damage is not outwardly apparent.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to rapidly assessing the aroma of new varieties of
fruit, the Florida lab uses e-noses to study the way the flavor of
orange juice changes with time.
</P>
<P>
   In one test, the devices correctly distinguished fresh juice
from concentrate mix in 36 of 42 samples, an accuracy of better
than 90 percent, said food chemist Philip E. Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   The artificial noses use a variety of technologies, but in all
of them, the principle is the same. It is based on recent
improvements in the understanding of how natural noses work.
</P>
<P>
   Nerve receptors in the human nose detect volatile airborne
compounds and relay the results to the brain, which analyzes the
manner in which individual receptors are stimulated to identify the
odor.
</P>
<P>
   E-noses consist of arrays of sensors. Contact with a particular
compound may or may not cause an easily measurable change in the
way a given sensor conducts electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Imitating the human nose, e-nose computers analyze the degree to
which various sensors are affected by airborne compounds, and uses
statistical software to recognize specific patterns.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``E-nose'' technology originated in Europe in the late 1980s,
said Steven Sunshine, president of Cyrano Sciences, a California
company that takes its name from the fictional Cyrano de Bergerac,
a gallant and brilliant man who was embarrassed by his abnormally
large nose in the 19th century French play by Edmond Rostand.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier sensors were developed around the ability to detect and
respond to a single chemical, Sunshine said. An example is the
sensor in a carbon monoxide detector.
</P>
<P>
   ``As people came to understand the biology of the natural nose,
with a series of sensors and the brain identifying a pattern unique
to a particular smell, they began to say, 'Maybe we can replicate
this process,' `` Sunshine said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of approaches emerged.
</P>
<P>
   In some sensors, such as the one being used in Athens to check
on the freshness of poultry, the presence of airborne compounds
changes the ability of electricity to flow through metal-oxide
circuits, each tuned to a different group of compounds.
</P>
<P>
   At the Agriculture Department's laboratory in Winter Haven,
individual plastic nodes have been doped with an
electricity-conducting material such as graphite or carbon black.
Electrons move through the nodes at predictable rates. But when the
plastics absorb molecules of a vapor, they swell like sponges and
the spacing between the conductive particles is changed. That
changes the electrical conductivity.
</P>
<P>
   Each node reacts differently to different compounds. The
computer analyzes the differences.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects the electronic sensors to match the range of a
natural nose. A human nose may have a million different receptors,
and the chip in an e-nose may have only a dozen or so. Dogs,
sometimes referred to as ``noses on legs,'' have a hundred million
receptors.
</P>
<P>
   But for specific odors, an array of sensors can be designed that
is more sensitive than human noses. Besides that, e-noses don't
catch colds and don't tire, and nothing smells ``bad'' to them.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency is
working to develop an ``electronic dog's nose'' to detect buried
land mines, and the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
installs odor-sensing equipment in spacecraft to detect such
problems as electrical fires before astronauts would be aware of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine said Cyrano is now accepting orders for its first
commercial product, an $8,000 hand-held device slightly larger than
a cell phone. In place of the stubby antenna on a cell phone, the
Cyranose 320 portable sniffer has a short ``snout'' that draws in
the vapors surrounding a target.
</P>
<P>
   The chip at the center of the Cyranose 320 contains an array of
32 doped plastic dots, each lying along a printed microelectric
circuit. When a dot absorbs a target vapor, it swells, contacts
nearby printed wires and completes the circuit.
</P>
<P>
   The plastic in each dot reacts to a different group of vapors,
and the overall pattern identifies the odor.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine envisions a time when sales contracts will contain
specifications for specific smells, ensuring that a product such as
coffee or rice is authentic and fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be surprised what people try to do when the price is
right,'' he said, ``and this technology, with its ability to
digitize smells and detect off-odors, will help control that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
