<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0448 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-LONDON-LIVINGSTONE-PR     04-18 3799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-LIVINGSTONE-PROFILE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED KEN RISING 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following excellent ``separate-buy'' article
about Ken Livingstone, who is likely to be London's next mayor, is
from The New York Times Magazine. It can be purchased _ the rate is
not prohibitive _ by contacting one of the following New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
 &HT;    --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. 
 By ANDY BECKETT  
 c.2000 ANDY BECKETT  
<TEXT>
 &UR; FROM: The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Just to the east of the center of London, across the mud-brown
Thames from Parliament, there is a great gray ghost of an office
building. It is almost a century old, and its heavy columns and
doorways and row upon row of unlighted windows extend along the
riverbank for hundreds of yards. From a distance, it might be an
abandoned palace or an emptied party headquarters in Eastern
Europe; up close, there is dust on glass doors and piles of debris
in hallways. Here and there, rooms are occupied: by a shop selling
soccer memorabilia, a Marriott hotel, a busy riverside McDonald's.
But the refurbishments feel thin, temporary. And along two sides of
the building, more carefully drawn than the corporate logos, is a
message from the past in carved gold capital letters. ``County
Hall,'' it reads. ``The Home of London Government From 1922 to
1986.''
</P>
<P>
   County Hall is currently owned by a Japanese leisure and
property company, Shirayama Shokusan. Originally, though, it was
designed to imitate, and rival, the home of Britain's national
government across the water. Then, as now, London was by far the
biggest, most potent and most confident British city. How it was
administered, and by whom, greatly mattered, and every glimpse of
County Hall was to act as a reminder.
</P>
<P>
   During the early 1980s, when the head of the Greater London
Council was a young and irreverent Labor Party radical named Ken
Livingstone, the steeply pitched roof was used, day and night, as a
vast billboard for propaganda against Margaret Thatcher's
Conservative government. One of his more potent devices simply
stated the number of unemployed people in London. From Parliament,
the figures were quite legible.
</P>
<P>
   The British way of politics, however, has limited tolerance for
such independent gestures. In 1986, Thatcher abolished the GLC by
an act of Parliament. County Hall was sold, and Livingstone was
relegated to talk shows and doing voice-overs for commercials. In
1987, he published his autobiography, ``If Voting Changed Anything,
They'd Abolish It.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone is 54 now, a creased-looking man of medium height,
with a tendency to slouch and wear beige suits. His eyes are narrow
and watchful. His forehead is furrowed by a life of calculations.
When he speaks, his mouth barely seems to move. But what emerges,
nasal and deadpan in the same droning tone as a thousand London
taxi drivers, is still a sort of political gold.
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone is a left-winger with jokes, a deal maker's
instincts and a seemingly impregnable sense of self-deprecation. In
modern British politics, so dominated by Tony Blair and his sternly
moderate government, such qualities are rare indeed. ``Ken
Livingstone is a unique phenomenon,'' says Prof. Tony Travers of
the London School of Economics. ``A populist far-left-winger with a
constituency that stretches from the young and anarchic to business
leaders.'' And next month, if all goes as expected _ and against
the conventional wisdom of two decades _ Livingstone will again be
running the capital.
</P>
<P>
   On May 4, London is to elect a mayor. From the first poll of the
campaign, ``Ken,'' as he is almost always called, has been the
favorite. No matter that since the GLC, as a Labor member of
Parliament he has been a drifting loner. No matter that his party,
unceasingly, has tried to stop him from becoming a mayoral
candidate: by threats and persuasion, by vicious public criticism,
by electoral machinations and, finally, by expelling him from the
party altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone is now an independent candidate. He has a bare
skeleton of an electoral machine. His staff is young and sparse.
His campaign headquarters is a single small house with dirty
windows. Until quite recently, it had three phone lines. Yet he has
loomed over almost every day of the contest: smiling mischievously
on his populist trips by bus and subway, delivering his sly
one-liners to the cameras, being featured as graffiti (``Go On
Ken!'') on the walls of pub toilets, being constantly discussed by
the other candidates, being offered back his old office at County
Hall by Shirayama Shokusan, being urged on by pop stars (Fatboy
Slim, Blur and the Chemical Brothers have given very public
support) and artists (Damien Hirst and Tracey Emin, among many
others, have auctioned works on his behalf).
</P>
<P>
   One evening last month, Livingstone appeared with the other
candidates at a debate in north London. South Hampstead, at first
sight, is not the sort of place for political excitement. Its
mansions stand somber and tall on a slope above central London,
fanned by vast old trees. Along its long straight avenues there is
the quiet that money brings. Almost every car is a Mercedes or a
BMW. Yet that evening, in the scrubbed and gleaming gymnasium of a
private girls' school, several hundred local residents in their
shooting jackets and furs had come to sit on plastic chairs and
cheer for socialism.
</P>
<P>
   Their moment arrived soon after 8 o'clock. Two of the minor
candidates had made their pitches, to moderate applause.
Livingstone, seated center-stage, had clapped politely, looked at
the ceiling, yawned. When his turn came, he got to his feet a
little sluggishly. The bright ceiling lights caught the bags under
his eyes, his scuffed brown shoes. His voice was even more nasal
than normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job of the politician isn't to tell you what you want to
hear,'' he began, ``but to tell you what needs to be done.'' And
for the next five minutes, to great cloudbursts of applause, he
described and justified his plans to raise taxes, very
specifically, on the sort of people in attendance that night.
Londoners who drove from suburbs like South Hampstead into the
center, Livingstone said, would pay a daily 5 pound ``congestion
charge.'' The money would be spent on buses, which were
predominantly used by the poor.
</P>
<P>
   He explained this almost distractedly, without a hint of
salesmanship, in flat, colloquial sentences that struggled at times
to be heard above the murmurs of agreement in the hall. All the
time, he barely moved, except for a few weary circling gestures
with his arms. His jacket hung long and shapeless. It did not quite
match his chinos. He ended with a heresy, made to sound like the
most obvious common sense: ``The great shining lie of British
politics is that you can have good public services without putting
up taxes.'' The crack of palm on palm was thunderous.
</P>
<P>
   London has never had an elected mayor. Until the mid-19th
century, when the sheer sprawl and mess and hazards to health
across its great shallow basin made a single body to oversee
amenities unavoidable, the city did not have a unified government
at all. And since 1986, the capital has again lived in a political
and administrative vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   A patchwork of boroughs and development corporations and
independent enclaves left over from the Middle Ages has looked
after its own interests, loosely overseen by a minor department of
the national government. As a result, some parts of London seem as
neatly governed as Switzerland; others seem to teeter toward chaos.
And all the while, the clotting traffic and choking roadworks and
housing shortages and all the other problems requiring citywide
attention have been left to worsen.
</P>
<P>
   London has always been distrusted by national politicians.
During the civil war of the 1640s, Charles I fled with his court to
Oxford. During the 18th century, the riotous ``London mob''
intimidated Parliament repeatedly. In 1892, an anonymous
conservative pamphlet predicted that the London County Council, the
GLC's predecessor, would raise a private army, abolish the national
government and soon be running the whole country.
</P>
<P>
   The contest for mayor has proved no more controllable. Yet it
seemed a sensible and timely idea when it was proposed, almost
exactly four years ago, by Frank Dobson, a veteran Labor spokesman
who would eventually become the Labor candidate. Labor was
extremely popular, the national government in waiting. One of its
best-received plans was to spread power, at long last, more evenly
across the country: Wales and Scotland were to get parliaments; the
capital would get an elected legislature, the Greater London
Authority, or GLA, and to make this cautious package more enticing,
a mayor. ``There is a sense in which getting a mayor is the
crowning moment for a revived city,'' Travers says.
</P>
<P>
   Or that, at least, has been the theory. In practice, instead of
the quiet, exemplary race Blair wanted _ as good international
publicity for his project of ``modernizing'' Britain and as a model
for choosing mayors in other British cities _ London has put on a
noisy, drawn-out and almost completely unpredictable piece of
political theater.
</P>
<P>
   There have been unwanted candidates. There have been scandalous
withdrawals. There have been disputes over electoral procedures,
public feuds, the flouting of party manifestoes. And infecting it
all has been the giddy sense of an election being fought by untried
and barely understood new rules. For the first time in a big
British election, there have been primaries. In the general
election, voting will be by a volatile, European-style system, with
voters having first and second preferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election is a learning process,'' says John Bartle, a
lecturer in British politics at the University of Essex. ``There's
a slight panic.'' Livingstone agrees: ``In a sort of haphazard way,
we are slowly turning ourselves into a modern decentralized
European state.'' To an unprecedented and vivid extent,
personalities have been free to dominate.
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone, famous for keeping newts in his back garden, is
only one of several bizarre candidates who have appeared in the
last year. Glenda Jackson, the former actress, sought the Labor
Party nomination, but came in third in the contest. The
Conservative candidate, Steve Norris, is a former car salesman
notorious for having had five mistresses. He supports gay rights
against his party's wishes. The Labor nominee, Frank Dobson,
refused party advice to shave off his beard, and in March he
referred to Blair's strategists as incompetent ``prats.'' His
campaign before and since, despite being organized by supposedly
the most potent party machine in European politics, has stuttered
and grumbled to a poll rating of barely 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Before settling on Norris, the Conservatives first nominated
Jeffrey Archer, the millionaire writer of melodramatic novels.
Then, when an ancient deceit of his involving a prostitute came to
light, he was dropped. Norris, whom Archer had beat to the
nomination, tried once more. But a group of influential
Conservative women, appalled at Norris' insouciance about his
personal life _ his tabloid nickname, which he makes little effort
to play down, is Shagger _ had his candidacy halted. A curious
lineup of alternatives emerged, including a baroness remembered for
once leaning on a light switch during a speech by Thatcher and a
local councilor whose uncle was a wrestling dwarf. Norris was
reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   Another strange hopeful has been Malcolm McLaren, the former
manager of the Sex Pistols. He ran briefly as an independent, hair
still as flaming as his rhetoric, advocating ``a more earthy
political era.'' Then, last month in South Hampstead, right after
Livingstone had finished speaking, McLaren stood up in a green
tweed suit of some flamboyance and announced he was giving up. ``I
don't really want any politician for a mayor,'' he said, ``But if I
have to have one, please let it be Ken Livingstone.''
</P>
<P>
   The more Labor has sought to block and batter Livingstone, the
more popular he has emerged. In January, Gordon Brown, the
chancellor of the exchequer, and Blair himself addressed a meeting
of the London Labor Party about the dangers of choosing the
``extremist'' Livingstone as candidate for mayor. The boos could be
heard on the radio. In February, Dobson was nominated as the Labor
candidate after winning barely a third of his local party members'
votes _ Livingstone won the rest _ thanks to an electoral system
that was widely described as ``North Korean.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone has remained smirkingly calm throughout. Even on a
freezing street corner, with winter blowing in again down Tottenham
Court Road and the central London traffic roaring past and his
cheeks pink with talking and the cold. Behind him looms his first
campaign poster, just unveiled. ``You Can't Save the Underground by
Taking the Party Line,'' it reads, highlighting his two favorite
themes: his independence and his scheme to repair the tube by
issuing bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very confident that the government's existing plan can be
overturned,'' he says. His mouth crinkles a little, defiantly.
``Any system that is bad for Londoners will be open to judicial
review in the courts.'' Why does he concentrate so much on
transport? ``Most of the mayor's powers are on transport.'' Does he
expect those powers to expand? His eyes flick up. ``I think it's
inevitable, with the mandate the mayor will have, that they will do
more than people expect now.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping his hands deep in his coat pockets and without raising
his voice at all, he begins to list policies. ``I'm also demanding
that we get back the police we've lost. ... The mayor's got to get
back from the national government the money that we pump into it.
London contributes 19 billion pounds more than it receives. ... And
the mayor's going to have to advocate tolerance. One of the reasons
that we've got openly gay government ministers now is that the GLC
stood up for tolerance 16 years ago.'' Isn't all this a bit
ambitious? ``If I can't make a difference, I shouldn't get
re-elected.''
</P>
<P>
   But can he? For a few weeks earlier this winter, in the lobby of
the Museum of London, there was a small exhibition that suggested
otherwise. It was called ``Message to the Mayor,'' and it included
scale models and magnified diagrams from previous vain efforts to
rationalize the capital. There was the Abercrombie Plan of 1943,
which proposed dividing the city into zones for different
activities, linked up by huge new roads. Its maps were almost
beautiful, all arching black lines and amoebalike colored circles,
but as realistic as children's drawings. Elsewhere, there were the
fragmentary remains of other grand designs: the Greater London
Development Plan (1969), six failed schemes for Piccadilly Circus
(1958-71) and a proposal called ``Towards an Urban Renaissance''
(1999).
</P>
<P>
   Outside, around the circular site of the museum, the early
afternoon traffic was already coiling and tightening. Opposite, an
enormous builders' scaffolding was swamping a sidewalk. Beyond it,
the long smooth precincts of the Barbican Center, London's last big
piece of civic self-improvement, were, as usual, almost deserted.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will have to learn what a mayor can and can't do,''
Bartle says. And it is unlikely that measurable improvements to the
capital will be quick to arrive. The newest subway line, for
example, took more than a decade to complete. Yet expectations,
stirred by the campaign, and the probable intensity of interest in
the first mayor's activities may ignore such practicalities. ``Each
time a bus is late, the mayor will lose votes,'' says Travers.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor is to stand for re-election every four years.
Livingstone, though, knows these pressures better than the other
candidates. In the five years that he headed the GLC, his
popularity swung wildly. At the start, he was widely considered a
chilly extremist. He lived in an ascetic, one-room apartment,
talked a bit like a Marxist and was accused of supporting
Republican terrorists in Northern Ireland. But once ``the commissar
of County Hall'' began to appear on television _ and the
invitations were not slow in coming _ his rumpled, droll persona
eroded such stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   Red Ken, as he became slightly more affectionately known, liked
his newts and gossiping in smart restaurants. He was part
cartoonish city boss, part English eccentric. And some of his
policies _ in particular Fares Fair, which cut the price of tickets
on public transport by a third _ were expertly publicized,
effective and eventually popular. For the first time, before or
since, many thousands of Londoners stopped crawling to work by car.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Thatcher, as Blair has done since, identified a threat.
Livingstone, with the capital as a base, with the country's largest
electorate and a London-obsessed press, could destabilize British
politics. He was sufficiently ambitious: he wooed the middle
classes, he realized the importance of presentational ``style'' and
effective political advertising, he appealed to environmentalists
and, to his political credit ever since, the minority voters who
now make up almost a third of London's electorate. All of these
notions, in Britain in the early '80s, were substantially ahead of
their time. Blair himself, who was just starting out in Labor
politics, was groping toward similar conclusions from a less
left-wing starting point.
</P>
<P>
   And nowadays, with the government enduring its first period of
fierce criticism and self-doubt _ for being too controlling and not
left-wing enough, in the capital and beyond _ Livingstone is,
perhaps, even more beguiling than before. Conservatives, who used
to find Livingstone infuriating, may now vote for him simply for
defying Blair. Liberals, who used to think Livingstone slippery and
vain, now admire his capacity for reinvention and survival. And
Londoners generally, dismayed at the state of public amenities, may
well be in the mood for left-wing municipal gestures.
</P>
<P>
   Early in February, in a very different suburb from South
Hampstead, I heard Livingstone speak in another gymnasium. It was
in Orpington, a long finger of public housing groping for the
countryside beyond southeast London. The room was smaller and
dirtier and full of Labor Party members, almost all pensioners.
Livingstone gave a performance of pure nostalgia. He called the
audience ``comrades.''
</P>
<P>
   He talked about putting conductors back on London buses and
guards back on the subway trains. He would persuade ``city gents in
their pin stripes'' to use public transport, just like ``when I
first started going to work in 1962.'' He lingered on his ``safe''
London childhood, about going to the zoo without an adult _
``that's what we have to get back.'' For an hour and a half, as the
wet evening misted the windows, a fantasy London of old-fashioned
neighborliness and order formed from his Cockney vowels.
</P>
<P>
   The public is much fonder of Livingstone than are many who have
worked with him. Few former members of the GLC or London Labor MPs
or heads of the city's boroughs have publicly supported his mayoral
bid. ``The problem with Ken,'' says Clive Soley, the chairman of
the Parliamentary Labor Party and one of Livingstone's more
thoughtful critics, ``is that he's an individualist.'' For example,
Soley adds, Livingstone's strong views on Northern Ireland would
have made him a useful member of the parliamentary select committee
on the subject. ``But he was never there. He was not there during
the peace process. He is not a team player.'' In his autobiography,
Livingstone praises the novel ``The Godfather'' as providing an
``honest account of how politicians operate.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the parliamentary standards committee announced that
Livingstone had violated regulations by failing to report $251,221
of outside income. The charge was a common and relatively minor one
_ MPs are notoriously lax about listing outside enterprises. But
the sources of Livingstone's income looked slightly suspect for a
declared socialist: $58,458 for after-dinner speeches to
businessmen and $52,272 for reviewing restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, his precise politics have blurred somewhat with the
years. At times, he promises a mayoralty like his GLC days,
confronting corporations he dislikes, sacking ``the racist and
corrupt minority'' in London's police and making the capital kinder
to its poor and disadvantaged. In other speeches, he offers to form
alliances with Conservatives and to run London like a pure
pragmatist. Most likely, if Livingstone wins _ and his poll lead
currently is, as it has been for months, a scarcely believable 40
percentage points _ he will govern more radically than Blair would
like but less radically than his most excited supporters are
currently imagining.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Party, for all its public assaults on him, is already
privately preparing for life with Livingstone. Party members who
support his independent candidacy will not be purged, as
regulations say they should be. He, in turn, has avoided directly
criticizing Blair. The mayor, whoever it is, will have to work with
the 25-member Greater London Authority, which is likely to have a
large Labor element. And in the gymnasium in South Hampstead, near
the end of the evening, there was a tiny hint that a Livingstone
mayoralty might, at least occasionally, be friendly to the national
government.
</P>
<P>
   Someone had asked him a question about the euro. As mayor of a
major financial capital, would he favor Britain's joining Europe's
single currency? Livingstone laid out his view, which is cautiously
pro-euro _ little different from that of the government. Of course,
he added, it wasn't certain that Britain would join the single
currency under Labor. ``I don't think it's guaranteed,'' he said,
``that we will even win the next national election.''
</P>
<P>
   A few in the audience noticed the slip. ``He said 'we' meaning
the Labor Party,'' someone half-whispered near the front. Perhaps
Livingstone heard. He sat down, after he finished speaking, behind
a paper sign that read, ``Livingstone: INDEPENDENT,'' with his
mouth fixed, unusually, in a slight frown. For a moment, being
mayor looked like less of an adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andy Beckett is a features writer for The Guardian, a London
daily newspaper.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) &QL;
</P>
