<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A CONTROVERSIAL PLAN ON BAY-AREA DOT-COM GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RACHEL GORDON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A new plan to give the cramped dot-com industry
more space to grow in San Francisco has ignited a long-simmering
battle over the city's development, pitting the entrepreneurs of
high-tech against the advocates of slow growth.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Leslie Katz on Monday introduced the first in a
series of proposed regulations for e-firms, the fastest-growing
segment of the city's red-hot economy.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, the multimedia companies have created an
estimated 55,000 jobs, many in the South of Market and Mission
districts, bringing new opportunities and new worries to those
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, high-tech firms would get their own zoning
designation _ ``research, development and technology business
service use'' _ separating them from the more traditional office
space, research and development and light-industry categories they
have fallen under.
</P>
<P>
   By carving out a special niche for the high-tech enterprises,
Katz hopes to accomplish two goals:
</P>
<P>
   _ Make them pump more money into the city's affordable-housing
fund than under their current designations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Exempt them from the city's long-standing cap on new
development. That idea, the most explosive component of the
package, is being drafted and Katz said she plans to present it
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition M, which local voters approved in 1986, limits new
office development to 875,000 square feet annually. In some years,
when the economy slacked, not all the allotment was used, and the
leftover square footage could be rolled over into subsequent years.
</P>
<P>
   The pot grew to 2.3 million square feet for use this year, but
it is quickly being depleted in a building boom not seen in the
city for decades. Planning Director Gerald Green said the cap might
be reached by June.
</P>
<P>
   Katz said that worried businesses, particularly those involved
with dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're nervous because we have tremendous opportunity to stay
on the cutting edge _ the biggest obstacle now is lack of space,''
said Katz.
</P>
<P>
   But Board of Supervisors President Tom Ammiano is opposed to
giving special development considerations to the new industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main concern about Supervisor Katz's proposal is that
increasing affordable housing fees for multimedia is not an
appropriate quid pro quo for circumventing the will of the
voters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano has joined forces with a coalition of community groups
that have come out strongly against the Katz plan.
</P>
<P>
   Community activists already have threatened to go to the ballot
to stop the Prop. M exemption should the board approve the
legislation. Mayor Willie Brown, meanwhile, backs Katz's efforts
regarding new construction.
</P>
<P>
   Katz said critics didn't have all the facts about what her
legislative package was striving to do. She said she wanted the
Planning Commission to create special zones where the dot-com
industry would be locked out. In addition, she wants a ban on the
destruction of housing to make way for a high-tech firm.
</P>
<P>
   Other proposals call for setting height limits on the new
projects and getting developers to pay relocation fees for existing
displaced businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's proposal also would force research, development and
technology companies to either provide on-site childcare or pay
into a special child care fund at the rate of $1 per square foot of
development.
</P>
</TEXT>
