<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0466 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-JOURNAL-0419-     04-18 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-JOURNAL-0419-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOREIGN JOURNAL: PEACE THROUGH ANTIQUES _ JIHAD HAS A DEAL FOR
YOU
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, West Bank When I ask how he got his name, antiques
dealer Jihad Mubarak sits back on his Syrian, mother-of-pearl
chairs and flashes one of his wide smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born May 1, 1948,'' he began.
</P>
<P>
   That was just days before the Arab nations attacked Israel in an
attempt to crush its bid for statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak's uncle was a doctor in the Jordanian army and delivered
the boy. ``He has to be named 'Jihad,''' the uncle insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, ``Jihad'' is a Muslim name. It can mean a holy struggle
_ such as in Iran where a ``Construction Jihad,'' exhorts people to
donate time to public works.
</P>
<P>
   In Jihad's case, it was probably imbued with the other meaning,
``holy war'' against Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly three years in the Middle East, I'm used to seeing
people trapped in the past, living out bitter destinies set down
for them by their ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Jihad Mubarak is not one of them. Despite his name,
his attentions have focused on motorcycles, old furniture and old
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Now, instead of fighting a jihad against Israelis, he sells
antiques to them _ along with Arabs, Europeans and Americans.
</P>
<P>
   This is far from the only case of cross-cultural commerce here.
Even while Israelis and Palestinians engage in angry rhetoric _
especially from the Palestinian side _ Israelis more and more are
frequenting Arab shops and markets. And, tens of thousands of
Palestinians go to work every day in the employment of Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak's shop, a converted old block house, is one of the more
peaceful places I've found. I've bought a few pieces myself, but go
more often to browse and sip tea.
</P>
<P>
   Downstairs is the workshop, where workers refurbish the pieces
Mubarak buys from Palestinians in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs are two small showrooms and a patio where customers can
look over furniture before a backdrop of olive groves and
stone-terraced hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   You can browse through the old English desk with the hidden
drawers or the Byzantine-style church icons. He has a few old photo
portraits from the American Civil War, a five-foot-tall throne-like
English armchair, and a Syrian gaming table for chess, backgammon
and cards.
</P>
<P>
   He's got heavy old iron scales, antique clocks and small, wood
cages for homing pigeons.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak has a typical background. Like many Christians in the
Bethlehem area, most of his family left the tumultuous Middle East
for Latin America. He sold most of his inventory and headed to
Chile himself when the Palestinian Intifada uprising of the late
1980s scared off Israeli customers.
</P>
<P>
   He returned in late 1993, after the signing of the Oslo peace
plan. A few years later, he moved his store to its current
location. It is a lone building along one of the West Bank's
so-called ``bypass roads,'' constructed to give Israelis access to
West Bank settlements without traveling through Palestinian towns.
</P>
<P>
   The route takes just 15 minutes from Jerusalem and passes
through one Israeli army checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   The customers are back in full. Mubarak even supplied antiques
for the sets of ``The Body,'' an Antonio Banderas movie filmed
here. It will be released later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent day, I sat with Mubarak's son, 19-year-old Amir, who
told me about his experiences in South America. An Israeli browser
overheard us and engaged us in Spanish, saying he learned the
language in his native Greece.
</P>
<P>
   When prodded on politics, the elder Mubarak says the Israeli
occupation of the West Bank is ``clearly unjust.''
</P>
<P>
   But, amid the antiques, the Israelis, and the Spanish music on
the tape deck, he adds, ``I don't understand politics.''
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow can be reached by e-mail at:
larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
