<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0472 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-MISSILEDEFENSE-POPULA     04-18 1406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILEDEFENSE-POPULARMECHANICS-ADV24-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV24 
 THREAT FROM ``ROGUE NATIONS'' SPURS MISSILE DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   For release Monday, April 24, or thereafter.  
 &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is from the May issue of
``Popular Mechanics.'' For purchase information, contact one of
these New York Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 By JIM WILSON  
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   In a few weeks, a modified Minuteman missile will blast off from
Vandenberg Air Force Base in California and arc gently over the
blue Pacific. As the intercontinental ballistic missile approaches
the Marshall Islands, 4,300 miles west of Los Angeles, a sheet of
white flames will erupt from beneath a second missile on nearby
Kwajalein Atoll.
</P>
<P>
   In the minutes that follow, a high-speed drama will unfold 140
miles in the sky. Using radar and infrared eyes, the second,
interceptor, missile will delicately adjust its trajectory until it
is aimed into the flight path of the ICBM.
</P>
<P>
   If a collision takes place _ and most defense experts believe it
will _ the United States will have at long last perfected a
practical means of protecting American cities from a limited
missile attack.
</P>
<P>
   This summer President Clinton will decide whether to approve
construction of 20 to 100 interceptors. Based in either Alaska or
North Dakota, they would protect all 50 states against a limited
ICBM attack.
</P>
<P>
   The quest for a missile shield began in 1945. Fearing this
technology would set off a new type of arms race, Washington and
Moscow later signed the 1972 Antiballistic Missile treaty, which
allowed limited antimissile deployment. The Soviets ringed Moscow,
the United States activated one Safeguard ABM installation in
Nekoma, N.D., in 1976. After only four months it was shut down as
too costly to operate.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years later, in March 1983, President Ronald Reagan
reintroduced the idea with his Strategic Defense Initiative. Dubbed
``Star Wars'' by its detractors, the plan called for using
high-tech wizardry, including long-range radars and orbiting
supercomputers, to aim antimissile missiles, lasers and particle
beam weapons at the thousands of incoming warheads that might be
used in a Soviet attack.
</P>
<P>
   Before defense contractors could solve the myriad problems
involved in distinguishing real warheads from dummy warheads and
putting kill vehicles and laser beams on targets, the Soviet Union
went belly up. An operational system was never built.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Cold War competition between the superpowers began to
recede, and the need for an ICBM shield seemed to diminish, a new
threat emerged from a long-simmering conflict in a technologically
backward corner of the world. The Gulf War erupted and the Iraqis
hurled about 90 Scud missiles against Israel, Saudi Arabia and
coalition forces.
</P>
<P>
   One of those Scuds loaded with conventional explosives struck a
barracks near Bahrain, killing 28 U.S. soldiers. Overnight,
Americans learned that they now faced two distinctly different
missile threats, the familiar threat against our homeland, and a
new threat against fighting and peacekeeping forces in foreign
theaters of war.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Gulf War, intelligence experts say, both types of
missile threats have intensified. Some weapons analysts believe
that Iranian and Iraqi rockets now can reach Paris and London.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 Tokyo was drawn into the crosshairs following the
successful launch of a North Korean Taepo Dong 1 missile.
Intelligence reports presented to Congress predict that a
longer-range Taepo Dong 2 could deposit North Korean weapons of
mass destruction on Honolulu or Anchorage, Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation today faces a changing world and an increasingly
diverse and proliferating air and missile threat,'' said Gen. John
M. Urias. As program executive officer for the U.S. Army Air and
Missile Defense Command, he is the Pentagon's point man for
developing the hardware that would make a missile defense shield
work. ``Two elements are needed to counter this threat _ theater
missile defense and national missile defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Theater missile defense, which shoots down short-range missiles
and cruise missiles, will protect armed forces in combat zones.
National missile defense will protect American soil against weapons
of mass destruction carried by fast-moving ICBMs.
</P>
<P>
   While the theater and national defense systems draw heavily on
research and development that led to the original Safeguard shield
around missile silos, they differ in one critical respect:
precision.
</P>
<P>
   When Safeguard was conceived, microprocessors did little more
than simple math. The technology to steer one speeding missile in
the path of another simply didn't exist. To compensate for that
lack of precision, the Spartan and Sprint missiles used in the
Safeguard system were tipped with low-yield nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Improvements in computer technology now permit a simpler
physics, the brute force of two objects colliding at 16,000 mph.
``We hit a bullet with a bullet,'' says Gen. John Costello,
commander of the U.S. Army Space and Missile Defense Command. It is
called ``hit to kill'' technology and it is the heart of both the
theater and national defense shields.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy for protecting battlefields is to engage incoming
missiles at each stage of their flight path. If it is completely
deployed, the theater missile defense system will work something
like this: During the enemy missile's boost phase, just after it
has left its launch pad and when it is heavily laden with fuel and
moving relatively slowly, it will be fired upon by one of the Air
Force's airborne lasers. If the target eludes the laser, the Navy
Theater Wide system will begin firing Standard missiles from an
Aegis cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   If it is still airborne, the Army's Theater High Altitude Area
Defense system steps in. It takes its first shot when the missile
is at about 60 miles _ if needed, it can fire again at lower
altitudes. Missiles surviving the gauntlet will then come
head-to-head with the Army's Patriot Advanced Capability-3, Medium
Extended Air Defense System or the Navy Area Defense system. ``The
cumulative kill probability of these systems would provide a nearly
leakproof defense,'' says Urias.
</P>
<P>
   While theater missile defense must be flexible enough to fight
wherever duty calls, the national missile defense system will have
one unchanging mission: to protect all 50 states from a limited
ICBM attack. Here, the operational strategy is to engage incoming
missiles at long ranges and at high altitudes.
</P>
<P>
   The muscle for the knockout punch will be delivered by
ground-based interceptor missiles stored in underground silos and
on 24-hour alert. The missile will consist of a multistage solid
fuel rocket and a kill vehicle with on-board guidance to direct it
to its deadly rendezvous.
</P>
<P>
   Interceptors will have several sets of eyes. A solid-state,
phased array X-band radar will perform long-range detection,
tracking and target classification. The missile's on-board radar
will use the same transmit/receive modules as THAAD missiles.
Infrared eyes will help to distinguish real warheads from dummy
warheads by reading their heat signatures.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the new $12.5 billion national missile defense
system is linked to two future events. One is technical, the other
diplomatic. The obvious technical hurdle is the next interception
test, which will most likely take place in May. Despite two earlier
failures, engineers close to the program expect it to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   A more curious problem has emerged on the diplomatic front.
Russia has warned State Department officials that deploying a
national missile defense would break the 1972 ABM treaty, which
limits the number and type of defensive missiles either country may
install.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed solution to this dilemma shows just how much the
world has changed. To encourage Moscow to drop its objections, two
key U.S. senators have suggested that the Pentagon share its
missile defense secrets with our former adversaries, so they, too,
can be protected against attacks by rogue nations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jim Wilson is science editor for ``Popular Mechanics''
magazine.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1459EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
