<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0499 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-18 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SIMPLICITY: HOW HARD CAN THAT BE? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The latest fad in this complicated world is
simplicity and how to achieve it. Apparently, the first thing you
have to do is complicate your life with more magazines and Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Time Inc. has a new magazine called Real Simple, which offers
all kinds of helpful household hints to reduce complication in the
lives of people who are apparently so simple-minded they don't know
how to clean the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Oprah Winfrey has a brand-new magazine, called O, The Oprah
Magazine, aimed at women who need simpler and more fulfilling
lives. Oprah also has her O2Simplify.com Web site, which offers
overstressed women helpful hints about everything from packing an
easy and nutritious school lunch (try bagels or sliced cheese, bet
you never thought of those) to step-by-step advice on how to start
your own business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lock onto a vision'' is the first step. Say, how about a
magazine selling simplicity?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there's another new magazine called Simplicity. It's
aimed at professional women looking for meaning and balance in
their lives. According to a recent Examiner interview with the
editors, the magazine teaches such useful skills as how to go to
work with ``bed hair,'' and reassures the young professional that
she won't have to give up cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of simplicity is that? Don't make roaming calls?
</P>
<P>
   The new simplicity magazines are a logical and slightly more
complicated outgrowth of the ``voluntary simplicity movement.'' One
of that movement's gurus, Duane Elgin, says it consists of frugal
consumption, ecological awareness and personal growth.
</P>
<P>
   A Web site for the movement features a passage from Henry David
Thoreau. Thoreau moved to the woods and built a cabin, but you can
take a workshop and tape course called ``Transforming your
Relationship with Money and Achieving Financial Independence.''
</P>
<P>
   To take the course, simply transform $60 of your money into the
promoters' account.
</P>
<P>
   Voluntary simplicity is fine, but as recent temblors in the
stock market remind us, young professional Americans may have to
learn about involuntary simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   Surviving the '00s may take more than cutting down on cell phone
calls, buying the small Land Rover and only ordering off the
appetizer menus of your favorite fusion restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The simplicity magazines seem to be both too simple and too
complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Real Simple's feature on how to clean a bathroom, for example,
says to clean from the top of the bathroom down, as if people are
so simple that they purposely wash the floors first and walk around
in water while they clean the mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many young professional males follow an even simpler
rule in cleaning bathrooms: Wash the parts that smell, ignore the
rest.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Simple Solutions'' section of the Real Simple Web site has
such brilliant advice as, ``Every time you bring something new into
your house, like a new set of sheets, donate the oldest set to a
charity.''
</P>
<P>
   Have any of these people at Real Simple ever taken the time to
donate something to a charity? It takes time. It isn't simple. You
have to take that old set of sheets to the Salvation Army in some
godforsaken part of town and fill out a form stating how much you
think they're worth, which will later take a lot of explaining to
the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   For real simplicity, tear the sheets into rags and wash the more
pungent parts of the bathroom with them. Then throw the rags away,
and let the environment take care of itself.
</P>
<P>
   The sad fact of American life is that no one is throwing
anything away, and if you take a walk though upscale shopping
districts you notice that people are acquiring a lot of things they
don't need at all, like frames for pet photographs, olive pitters
and everything at Restoration Hardware.
</P>
<P>
   If you want simplicity, live on the streets, a lifestyle that
may be in the cards for many of you paid in stock options. Even
then you'll find yourself needing a bigger shopping cart.
</P>
<P>
   Another fact of American life is that young people aren't
learning to cook. America has become New York, with all the young,
overworked people going to the latest restaurants and eating out of
cardboard boxes.
</P>
<P>
   We have a generation of people calling themselves ``foodies''
who don't know how to make a grilled cheese sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   Real Simple has a feature on one-dish meals that can be prepared
in 30 minutes. Sorry, these recipes far overestimate the culinary
ability of young Netizens in search of the simpler life, while at
the same time having disgusting pseudo-gourmet names like
``Pineapple shrimp with scallions and rice.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, the dot-commies can find the canned pineapple, but do they
know how to shell and de-vein shrimp? Is there fresh basil,
cilantro and scallion in the refrigerator with the leftover pizza?
And frankly, I'd rather eat the leftover pizza.
</P>
<P>
   The one Real Simple one-dish meal that sounded appetizing was
``Lentil Stew with Sausage and Potatoes.'' Somehow, though, I doubt
the young, overworked programmers will rinse and pick through dried
lentils instead of going out to the Universal Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if the recession ever comes, and simplicity becomes
involuntary, the young folks can line up at soup kitchens for bowls
of lentil stew _ hold the arugula and feta cheese.
</P>
<P>
   That's simplicity, and it sounds easier than it is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0518 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-INTERNET-POLITICS19-C     04-18 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-POLITICS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL PLATFORMS BECOMING INTERACTIVE AFFAIRS
 &HT;    360&AMP;add. Moving in the (w) Washington and (p) political
categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Internet is breathing new life into political
party platforms, those long, dry-as-dust documents that in the past
often went unread _ even by the presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Al Gore, the prospective Democratic nominee,
launched a plan that lets anybody draft a plank online for the
upcoming party platform. By Tuesday, more than 2,000 people had
done so and received ``personalized'' thank-you letters from Gore
and Joe Andrew, the Democratic national chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of it as the world's best civics lesson, one that allows
us you to craft your own manifesto,'' said Joshua King, a spokesman
for Speakout.com, the Web site that cut a deal with the Democrats
to host the novel platform-drafting service.
</P>
<P>
   Speakout.com, a for-profit site which includes both well-known
Democrats and Republicans on its advisory board, also supplies
sophisticated software that lets users easily cut, paste and edit
parts of the 1996 Democratic platform to create their own 2000
version.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, the Republican national chairman, has bought into
a more modest set of interactive tools from the same site,
including chat rooms, surveys and e-mail messages to candidates and
other political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great initiative,'' said Larry Purpuro, deputy chief of
staff for the Republican National Committee and the party's top
guru for online activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the Web must be a two-way form of communication, and
we hope to have a fully interactive issues forum for voters up on
our site in the near future,'' Purpuro added. It will include a
comparable ability for outsiders to draft GOP platform language, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there's no guarantee that the presidential
candidates or their top political minions will pay attention to the
online submissions before the final handiwork is made public in
August at their national conventions.
</P>
<P>
   But King, a former aide to President Clinton, held out some
hope. ``If they're smart about it,'' he said, ``they'll find some
golden nuggets here and they'll cite them.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Indiana Republicans on Tuesday became the first
statewide group to stage ``high-tech platform hearings'' on its Web
site. Purpuro said other Republican state parties, beginning with
California, will soon follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to adapt to new technology. In this day and age, it's
quite difficult to get folks to come to a meeting to give their
views,'' said Lisa Kobe, a state party spokesperson in
Indianapolis. ``And, frankly, it's unnecessary,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking input on ``what are the most critical issues to be
included in the 2000 GOP platform'' Mike McDaniel, the Indiana
Republican state chairman, has created an e-mail address _
platform2000(at)aol.com _ to solicit testimony.
</P>
<P>
   National political parties have been writing platforms since
1840, when the Democrats adopted a compact 1,000-word document. In
1996, their platform ran to some 18,000 words, but others have been
as long as 40,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 platforms are widely expected to be the first ever to
cite the Internet. The Democrats, in particular, have made an issue
of the need to close the ``digital divide,'' one of Gore's favorite
themes and the topic of a speech that Clinton gave in Chicago on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: Speakout.com.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1523EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0111 </DOCNO>
