<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0529 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-18 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IT TAKES A PARISH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Long after all the reasonable folks in the
parish knew that Connie Ebora's dog was never coming back, Connie
kept praying.
</P>
<P>
   Every weekday morning with Mother Teresa's Missionaries of
Charity in the convent behind St. Paul's Church, Connie was on her
knees. During weekend Masses in the church, or in the school gym
next door when St. Paul's closed for earthquake retrofitting,
Connie wouldn't let up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I asked the Mother of God, `Please give me my dog
back,''' she said. ``I told the Sacred Heart (of Jesus), `My heart
is broken. Please help me find my dog.' I know it sounds crazy, but
I prayed every night at home to Eileen, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Eileen'' is not a Catholic saint, but Eileen Keane, a lifelong
St. Paul's parishioner who died in February 1999 at the age of 82.
</P>
<P>
   It was she who, eight years ago, adopted a wiry little
strawberry-blond mutt from the pound and named him ``Barney.'' It
was she who, in the last, debilitating months of her life,
entrusted Barney to Connie Ebora for walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was a little puppy, Eileen would stick Barney in her
coat and take him into church for Mass,'' Connie said. ``He loves
going to church. That's why I took him with me every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was from his customary spot in the foyer of St.
Paul's that Barney disappeared Dec. 4. Connie had tied him to the
wrought iron gates that lead to the choir loft and gone to Mass.
</P>
<P>
   How he got loose and lost no one knows.
</P>
<P>
   Some kids who were playing outside the church may have taken him
or chased him away, but they never copped to the deed. Then there
were reports of ``a lady in an SUV'' who drove by, claimed Barney
was her dog and scooped him up.
</P>
<P>
   All that really mattered was, Connie Ebora's dog was gone, she
was devastated, and the entire parish was totally bummed out.
</P>
<P>
   Which was kind of ironic.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty years old and decades-retired from her job at the Social
Security Administration, Connie had been a familiar face around St.
Paul's since moving to the parish in 1983. Despite some sacristan
duties a few years back, though, the diminutive Hawaii native
tended to keep to herself. Few parishioners knew much about her.
</P>
<P>
   But everybody knew that she and her little dog with the white
triangle on his forehead were inseparable. So, when word got out
that Barney had been snatched (Lord knows he wouldn't have left on
his own accord), everyone felt the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, flyers with Barney's picture were posted all over
the area. People haunted the city and SPCA animal shelters. On
their daily walks or jogs, they kept an eye out and asked
shopkeepers and passersby if they'd seen a little guy with a
``white star'' on his face.
</P>
<P>
   As the days turned into weeks and months, several folks,
including St. Paul's pastor Father Mario Farana, tried to buy
Connie a new dog. Just the sight of her walking the streets, head
down, crying and wearing her grief like a 500-pound shroud, was
unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   But Connie said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, `I don't need another dog. I have a dog. I have
Barney, and he needs me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine's Day came and went, as did Ash Wednesday, St.
Patrick's Day and the first day of spring. The weather turned soft;
the buds on the trees bloomed.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone but Connie figured Barney had gone home to God.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on April 2, Marie Doherty, a St. Paul's parishioner for 40
years, made one of her periodic visits to the city's animal control
shelter. She'd come, as usual, to drop off old towels, blankets and
bundled newspapers for the shelter staff to use in its pet rescue
work.
</P>
<P>
   As she had since Barney's disappearance, Marie added a tour of
the just-rescued and now-adoptable pets section. There, in a cage
bearing the nameplate ``Sandy,'' she saw a little terrier-like dog
with white on his forehead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was Barney. I recognized him from church,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Marie's message didn't get to Connie until the next day. But as
soon as the shelter opened, Ruth Tortorelli, St. Paul's rectory
secretary, drove her down.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Barney saw me, he was climbing all over the door, saying,
`Get me out! Get me out!' He was so happy to see me,'' said Connie.
</P>
<P>
   According to Charlie Miller, the shelter representative, it's
``very unusual'' for a dog to be on the loose for four months and
end up reunited with its owner. And though Barney had lost weight,
he showed no signs of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barney only got to the shelter March 26,'' said Tortorelli,
the church secretary. ``I asked him where he spent the rest of the
time, but he's not talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the people of St. Paul's feel as though the parish
got an early Easter gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Total strangers stop me and say, `Oh, I'm so happy you got
Barney back!' I had no idea so many people supported me. It's just
amazing,'' said Connie.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as longtime parishioner Elsa Vida put it so succinctly:
``It's a miracle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
