<HEADLINE>
WESTERN TO BE SHOT IN TEXAS HAS WEST POINT BACKGROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brackettville, Texas, once confused with the fictional Nike
commercial town of ``Bracketville,'' appears to be the new West
Point of the West.
</P>
<P>
   Black Knight Films has begun shooting a western at Alamo
Village, a movie set and entertainment park just outside the South
Texas town, and the film has an unusual connection to the U.S.
Military Academy at West Point, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   But not in the story, titled ``Jericho.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an 1870 piece in the tradition of `Shane,''' said Gil
Dorland, Black Knight chairman. ``It's about a guy who loses his
memory and doesn't know who he is. The story is his odyssey to find
his memory. He begins to learn that he was a gunslinger, but he
doesn't know if he was a good guy or bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorland promises the film will have an unusual twist at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Dorland, a writer and director, is also a former Vietnam combat
commander and a West Point graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Black Knight president, Merlin Miller, is a movie producer and
director. He's directing ``Jericho,'' and is also a West Point
graduate.
</P>
<P>
   John Draper, a member of Black Knight's board of directors, is
an investment banker who graduated from West Point. Renny Rozzoni,
another board member involved in the film's marketing, graduated
from the academy as well.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem nearly impossible for the company to keep this
kind of U.S. Army connection going into the casting of the film,
but it did. Soap opera star Mark Valley, who plays Jack Deveraux on
``Days of Our Lives,'' is cast in the title role as ``Jericho.''
</P>
<P>
   Valley was previously on ``Another World.'' He has appeared in
several feature films including ``The Innocent'' with Anthony
Hopkins. And he is also a West Point graduate.
</P>
<P>
   It makes you feel kind of sorry for the film's co-star, rodeo
clown Leon Coffee. Coffee is a horse trainer, a bulldogger, and
calf roper, and he served in the Army for three years. But he was
an enlisted man who never went to West Point.
</P>
<P>
   North Texas artist and film star Buck Taylor is also starring in
``Jericho.'' He didn't go to West Point either.
</P>
<P>
   Dorland said the West Point connection was somewhat
serendipitous when it came to Valley's casting. He wasn't selected
because of his academy connection, Dorland said.
</P>
<P>
   The film company first sought a New Mexico location for
``Jericho,'' but settled on Bracketville because it was
logistically more economical.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New Mexico, we would have had to go to several places to do
the film,'' Dorland said. ``Alamo Village can be four or five
different towns.''
</P>
<P>
   Filming is also taking place along the Rio Grande at Rancho Rio
Grande, a ranch owned by Galveston businessman Bill Moody. Both
Rancho Rio Grande and Alamo Village were used in the filming of
``Lonesome Dove.'' Alamo Village was first built as the site of
John Wayne's saga, ``The Alamo.''
</P>
<P>
   During the recent NCAA Basketball Championships, Nike
commercials featured a fictional town where life revolved around
basketball. It was called Bracketville. Nike later filmed some of
their ads in the South Texas town.
</P>
<P>
   There is no release date yet for ``Jericho,'' but Dorland calls
the script ``one of those wonderful scripts Hollywood has forgotten
about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jericho'' is considered a low-budget movie at a cost of less
than $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
