<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-ASYLUM-540&AMP;NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORIES RENEW DEBATE ON ASYLUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ For months, Britain's Conservatives have accused the
Labor government of turning Britain into a ``soft touch'' for
``bogus asylum seekers,'' saying that most refugees come here to
exploit British generosity, not to escape persecution at home.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Tories turned up the heat. In a major policy
speech meant to seize the upper hand in an increasingly bitter
debate, the Conservative Party leader, William Hague, said new
asylum seekers should be immediately placed in secure detention
centers and then deported within about six weeks if their claims
are rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next Conservative government will detain all new
applicants for asylum, whether port applicants or in-country
applicants, in reception centers until their cases have been
determined,'' Hague told the Social Market Foundation, a
right-leaning think tank. ``This policy will have a significant
deterrent effect on those thinking of traveling here without a
well-founded case.''
</P>
<P>
   The government immediately denounced Hague's proposal as
``cynical,'' saying, in the words of Jack Straw, the home
secretary: ``William Hague's speech is further confirmation that
the Conservatives are more interested in exploiting the asylum
issue than they are in dealing with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither Straw nor the other government officials who spoke
out against Hague Tuesday accused him of going too far. Instead,
they took pains to present themselves as the party with the tougher
asylum policy, intent on quickly weeding out refugees who have no
business being here.
</P>
<P>
   To drive home his point, Straw noted that the Tories had opposed
a number of elements of the recently enacted immigration bill,
including one that forces truck drivers to pay a penalty of about
$3,300 for each illegal refugee they bring into the country. They
had also tried to block Labor's plan to replace the system of cash
benefits for asylum seekers with a much more stringent one of
vouchers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his own response, David Blunkett, the education secretary,
said that the government would ``not tolerate people believing
Britain is a soft touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, more than 71,000 people applied for asylum in
Britain, a record number that reflected the rise in upheavals in
Eastern Europe, Africa, Asia and South America. With some 375,000
people applying for asylum around Europe in 1998, the most recent
year for which official figures are available, the problem is
hardly limited to Britain. But the government has been increasingly
vulnerable to the charge that its asylum policy _ and not the
increase in the total number of refugees from around the world _ is
what is attracting so many asylum seekers to Britain.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Straw defended his government's harsh new
immigration law, saying that it had already built a detention
center in Oakington, Cambridge, with room for 400 asylum seekers,
and begun dispersing other new arrivals around the country. He also
pointed out that 10,000 asylum applications had been processed last
month, making a slight dent in a backlog of 103,000 outstanding
cases. He added that ``removals of asylum seekers are at record
levels.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Straw said some 3,000 ethnic Albanians who fled
Kosovo last summer would be required to leave Britain in the next
few months, when their 12-month permits expired. ``Enforcement
action will be taken in due course against those who are unwilling
to go back voluntarily,'' he said. ``But we will encourage them to
go back voluntarily.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last several weeks, a number of people, including the
British representative to the office of the U.N. high commissioner
for refugees, have accused politicians from both parties of in
essence scrambling for the moral low ground in the asylum debate by
stirring up racist sentiments in a country that has never been
thrilled by the presence of too many foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   The bishop of Croydon, the Rt. Rev. Wilfred Wood, compared the
language in the current debate to the inflammatory words used by
the politician Enoch Powell in his 1968 ``rivers of blood'' speech,
which fueled Britons' worry about black immigration. Bill Morris,
the leader of the Transport and General Workers' Union and one of
Labor's most prominent supporters, accused the government of
fostering a ``climate of fear and loathing'' on race and asylum
issues.
</P>
<P>
   And in the House of Lords, Baroness Scotland of Asthal, a junior
foreign minister and a former member of the Commission for Racial
Equality, said Tuesday that, ``I am becoming increasingly concerned
by the tone of some of the rhetoric which has been voiced in
relation to refugees, where it seems to be almost synonymous an
idea that if one is a refugee, one is somehow unsuitable or
unsound.''
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial, the Daily Mail, which has led the way in
anti-refugee rhetoric, praised Hague's proposal as being ``at one
with ordinary people's serious concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The system is on the verge of a breakdown and it is imperative
that this growing scandal should be debated,'' the paper said.
``This country, with its proud and generous reputation for
welcoming those in genuine need of asylum, simply cannot allow
itself to continue as a soft touch for those who would ruthlessly
exploit our generosity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
