<HEADLINE>
TEAS, FROM GREEN TO `BLACK DRAGON' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 By SHELLY BELZER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tea soothes, as everyone knows, but it also may be
good for you. Green tea, especially, contains potent antioxidants
called polyphenols. Researchers believe polyphenols prevent cell
damage and may treat or protect against rheumatoid arthritis, skin
tumors, heart disease and oral and digestive-tract cancers.
</P>
<P>
   (So far, laboratory rodents have shown the best results.) Second
to green tea for antioxidant content is oolong tea, and last is the
fully oxidized black tea, which is the favorite of American tea
drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   Black tea has enough flavor to stand up to lemon or milk. Green
tea and even oolong, described by its fans as smoky, fruity,
mellow, bold and sometimes flowery, are acquired tastes. A new Web
site, www.teasofgreen.com, is dedicated to helping beginners
acquire it. The site, the electronic child of Larry and Sachiko
Ormsby in Berkeley, Calif., sells high-grade green and oolong teas
(all loose, no bags), which the Ormsbys import from China, Taiwan
and Japan. They also provide online tea lore.
</P>
<P>
   Among their green teas is lung ching (also longjin), the most
famous of all, from the West Lake area in Hangzhou, China ($18 for
3 ounces). The taste of green tea is always described as delicate,
and its preparation requires quick dousing of the leaves. Devotees
say that cups made from subsequent steeping of the same leaves are
mellower and taste even better.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan is famous for oolong (the name means black dragon), and
the Ormsbys sell the tea that transformed Taiwan, bai hao ($18 for
2.5 ounces), with its honey and ripe fruit flavors. It is the most
oxidized, or air-cured, of oolongs. This tea was called Oriental
Beauty in the 19th century, when its popularity in the United
States caused a boom on the island.
</P>
<P>
   The oolong rush led to the felling of a camphor forest, the
burning of clearings and the planting of tea up to 4,000 feet in
the hills above the Taipei basin. In 1896, 20 million pounds of
Oriental Beauty brought $3.5 million in America alone. It was then
the costliest tea in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The site also sells oolong tea sets from China, including an
eight-ounce teapot, two cups, a nine-ounce glass pitcher, a bamboo
scoop for leaves and a tea strainer ($58, or $93 with optional
thermos), and green tea sets from Japan ($65, or $98 with
thermos). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sugar-Free, and Bittersweet &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sue Slater, who lives in St. Louis, has degrees in business
administration and social work. She also has Type 2 diabetes,
characterized by elevated levels of blood sugar, which she controls
through her diet. But Slater still has a sweet tooth. It has led
her to search out sugar-free desserts in bakeries and restaurants
around the country. The results appear on www.sugarfreesites.com.
</P>
<P>
   The listings, from 20 states, give names, addresses and phone
numbers. For New York, Slater gives about 50 places, including
Zabar's for rugelach; Pozzo Pastry Shop, 690 Ninth Avenue (48th
Street), for poundcake; and Candy Man, 402 13th Avenue in Brooklyn,
for chocolates and candy.
</P>
<P>
   In the interests of research, she has gone into the field to
taste for herself and has received desserts by mail.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping up a Web site is demanding work, maybe a little harder
for Slater than for others because she is also blind. She finds
bakeries and restaurants through the Yellow Pages online, activated
for voice by software, and spends about four hours a day
telephoning them about sugar-free goods. She gets help with the
site from her daughter, Chelsy, 14, and her husband, Larry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
