<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG STRIDES FOR SICILIAN REDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Historians tracing the story of winemaking in Italy
say that Sicilian vineyards flourished around 2,500 years ago. Wine
lovers might say it's been all downhill from there.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is ever that simple, of course, particularly on the
island of Sicily. With its hilly geography and warm climate, it is
one of the most productive wine regions in the world. But aside
from Marsala, the well-known fortified wine, Sicilian wine has
largely been used for most of the 20th century as a blending agent
for cheap, potent wines or for distilling into spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Things began to improve around 25 years ago, when winemakers,
sensing the vast potential in Sicily, began modernizing their
agricultural methods, equipment and techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the progress is especially apparent in Sicilian red
wines, which seek a careful balance between remaining true to the
island's winemaking history and appealing to international tastes.
These wines have none of the baked, raisiny qualities that are so
often typical of old-fashioned hot-weather red wines, yet they are
by no means Bordeaux or Tuscan knockoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Though some of the wines I tasted incorporated small amounts of
cabernet sauvignon and merlot into their blends, most capitalize on
the flavors of traditional grape varieties, like nero d'avola,
frappato, nerello and others little known outside of Sicily. They
are accessible and enjoyable, and don't require extra aging.
</P>
<P>
   I was impressed by how carefully these wines were made, but I
couldn't help thinking that they ought to be, because they are not
cheap. In tasting a dozen Sicilian reds, I found a general
correlation between price and quality. The $10 to $15 wines tended
to be simple and direct, fine for everyday drinking, while the more
expensive bottles offered hearty complexity, and occasionally even
elegance. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VALLE DELL'ACATE, CERASUOLO DI VITTORIA, 1996 $21 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cherry and chocolate aromas. Sweet fruit and smoky tar flavors. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CONTE TASCA D'ALMERITA, REGALEALI, ROSSO DEL CONTE, 1997 $37 &QL; 
Dark purple; aromas of mint and cedar. A rich, thick texture. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CEUSO, CUSTERA, 1997 $30 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dark purple; flavors of tobacco, berry and chocolate. Very
smooth. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DONNAFUGATA, TANCREDI, CONTESSA ENTELLINA, 1997 $29 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Plum and violet aromas. Fruit flavors have a minty edge. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
