<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0566 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     04-18 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHERHOOD MANUAL TAKES THE FAST LANE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My 13-year-old man child and I were alone in the car listening
to the radio as I drove. A love song was playing, and my son was
singing along quite earnestly. My boy's eyes were closed and his
new, deep voice blended nicely with the voice of the singer.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, I was admiring my son's new skill because, before
his voice changed, he couldn't carry a tune if you put super glue
on it. Then, he sang something like, ``You and me baby, all night,
all right,'' and I was so shocked that I drifted into the other
lane of traffic.
</P>
<P>
   I veered back into my lane and waved at the driver who was
yelling at me, although I didn't use my middle finger to wave like
she did. Anyway, I quickly changed the radio station to WRR, which
plays classical music.
</P>
<P>
   My son's eyes flew open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom! Why did you do that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do anything. They changed the song,'' I said, joking.
</P>
<P>
   He groaned and rolled his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``So son, do you have a girlfriend yet?'' I asked. It's the
first question from my lesson plan on women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, please. Dad already told me about girls. Can we talk
about something else?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No. This is a required conversation. I can not let you move
away from home until we have this talk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, I'm not going anywhere. I'm a kid. And who says we have
to talk about this stuff?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the Motherhood Manual, son. I have to cover a million
lessons in life before you leave home. And yes, you are going
somewhere. College, military, barber school _ I don't know where
exactly, but you must leave at some point. Dad and I need your room
back. We think it would make a fine sauna.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Son, when you were about 4 years old I told you not to touch
the stove because it was hot. As soon as I turned my back, you
touched it anyway and burned your little finger. As I wiped the
tears from your eyes, you said, `Hot, mama.''' I kissed your finger
and spanked the bad stove. That was a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, when you were 7 or 8, your great-uncle took you to the
store and bought you $10 worth of candy. I told you not to eat it
all at once so, of course, you went outside and ate every piece.
You were sick for two days. I stayed home from work to take care of
you. That was a lesson, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, there's no such thing as a Motherhood Manual. Those
things just happened.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there is a huge manual son, and the lessons get harder
and harder. Sometimes, I don't even understand them. But I'm trying
to teach you everything that I can, to the best of my ability.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is this so important to you?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because if you fail, I fail.''
</P>
<P>
   With a puzzled expression, he wondered, ``Where exactly is this
Motherhood Manual? Can you show it to me?''
</P>
<P>
   I shook my head.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm sorry but I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it's in my heart,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, who put it there?''
</P>
<P>
   How could I explain this to a child?
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' I said, ``you put it there on the day you were
born. When I saw you, it was love at first sight and I vowed to be
the best mom that I could possibly be for you. That means teaching
you a lot a lessons, no matter how hard they are for you or for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   He was quiet for a while. Then he spoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what did you want to tell me about girls?''
</P>
<P>
   I took a deep breath and started class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey, girls are wonderful. However...''
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a dentist, wife and mother in
Arlington, Texas. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
