<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0568 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-DIGITAL-CHART-$ADV23-     04-18 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-CHART-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH-DIGITAL-SIGNATURES. Moving in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories for release Sunday, April 23.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   Any typed notation on an electronic document. But merely typing
a name, such as ``signed/John Doe,'' is not a secure way of
identifying a signer. A ``digital signature'' is a specific type of
electronic signature that is virtually impossible to forge.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   A way of creating and verifying a unique signature using
cryptography, a branch of applied mathematics dealing with the
conversion of messages into unintelligible forms and back again.
Digital signatures make use of an algorithm using two distinct but
mathematically related ``keys'' needed to open the text and verify
the signer's identity.
</P>
<P>
   Such a signature must provide two elements:
</P>
<P>
   _ It should identify the person who signed the document and be
virtually impossible to forge.
</P>
<P>
   _ It should identify what is being signed, making it virtually
impossible to alter or falsify the signed material.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL CERTIFICATE
</P>
<P>
   The equivalent of an ID card, a digital certificate is issued by
a ``trusted third party,'' called a certification authority, after
it verifies that a particular company holds a certain mathematical
``key.''
</P>
<P>
   The digital certificate typically is sent along with a digitally
signed message to verify that the sender is truly the entity
identifying itself in the transmission. The recipient uses the
widely publicized ``public key'' of the certification authority to
open the message and be assured of who sent it.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL NOTARIZATION
</P>
<P>
   Using cryptography, it combines the digital ``fingerprint'' of
an original electronic document or online transaction with a
trusted time stamp and the digital signature of a trusted third
party, creating a digital record that can be archived as proof of
the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL RECORD
</P>
<P>
   Allows a record produced by digital notarization service to be
securely stored with an audit trail.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL RECEIPT
</P>
<P>
   A specially formatted digital record that combines payment and
authentication information with other transaction details. It tells
you who were the buyers, sellers, and financial institutions
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Source: VeriSign
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
