<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1613EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0570 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-DIGITAL-SIGNATURES-$A     04-18 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SIGNATURES-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS NEARS PASSAGE OF WAY TO DIGITALLY 'SIGN' DOCUMENTS
 &HT;    940&AMP;add. With DIGITAL-CHART. Moving in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories for release Sunday, April 23.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the flourish of a quill spelling out ``John
Hancock'' or with a simple pencil scratching out an ``X,''
Americans have long used their signatures to seal a deal.
</P>
<P>
   But in the age of the Internet, business owners say electronic
commerce will never reach its full potential unless two parties can
complete a contract by using a computer to ``sign'' and send
legally binding documents.
</P>
<P>
   To speed the development of e-commerce, Congress is in the final
stages of writing legislation to give consumers and businesses the
ability to close contracts with ``digital signatures.'' The House
and Senate have passed versions of a digital signature bill, and
now a conference committee is trying to smooth out differences
between them.
</P>
<P>
   Observers predict compromises may be reached soon enough to
allow a final draft to be passed by Congress and signed into law by
President Clinton before this summer's recess for political party
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   A digital signature works by turning identifying information
into a secret code that only the participating parties can
unscramble. It provides two elements needed to make a contract.
First, it identifies the person who signed the document. Second, it
identifies the document itself, making it virtually impossible to
alter or falsify the signed material.
</P>
<P>
   The nation needs ``a uniform legal framework that will enable
businesses to depend on contracts signed over the Internet,'' said
Rhett Dawson, president of the Information Technology Industry
Council, a trade group supporting digital signature legislation.
</P>
<P>
   House Commerce Committee Chairman Tom Bliley, R-Va., predicts
the legislation will bring about an ``explosion in the growth of
e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   But while seemingly everyone agrees digital signatures will
hasten the business world's transition to the Internet Age,
consumer advocates are still battling to make sure protections for
the ``little guy'' are embedded in the bill's final version.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no problem with those who want to proceed with
electronic contracts,'' said Margot Saunders, managing attorney for
the Washington office of the National Consumer Law Center. ``But 68
percent of households are not on line.''
</P>
<P>
   Without legal safeguards, those unsavvy consumers could find
themselves signing electronic documents that they do not fully
comprehend, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Attorneys General also has sent a
letter to Congress stating its concerns about the House bill's
potential erosion of consumer protection laws.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders gave examples of what her group fears could happen
without strong consumer safeguards:
</P>
<P>
   _ An elderly woman could be visited by a salesman who talks her
into an overpriced home improvement. He could pull out a laptop
computer and get her to sign the deal, agreeing to receive all bill
notices and disclosures on line. But if she has no computer, she
won't be able to read the contract's fine print.
</P>
<P>
   _ A shopper goes to a car dealership and is told that if he
wants a particular car, he can have it for $25,000, but only if he
signs all documents and accepts all follow-up information on line.
If he wants everything on paper, the car will cost another $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders says consumers must continue to have the option of
getting a contract in writing and signing it with a pen without
financial penalty. They should get follow-up information and bills
mailed to the home, rather than e-mailed to an online address.
Allowing companies to send legally binding notices via e-mail is an
invitation to trouble, she claims, because electronic communication
is far less reliable than traditional mail.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a consumer might agree to receive notices regarding
his health insurance online. But then he runs into financial
trouble and drops his Internet service. When the insurance company
e-mails a notice of the change in terms of coverage, he never sees
it. His child gets sick, and it's not until he gets to the doctor's
office that he discovers his insurance no longer will cover the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a hundred reasons why you might not get an e-mail
sent to you,'' Saunders said. ``We want consumers to have some
assurance that important information will be delivered.''
</P>
<P>
   That means mailing notices out through the U.S. Postal Service,
which, unlike Internet service providers, will forward missives to
new addresses. ``Despite glitches, there is a 99.9 percent chance
that the mail will be reliable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has passed a bill that recognizes a digital signature
as the paperless equivalent of a written signature on a contract.
But the House has passed a more elaborate version of the
legislation, permitting not only the use of digital signatures, but
also the recognition of electronic records, such as monthly bills.
</P>
<P>
   It is the House version that has stirred up concerns among the
National Consumer Law Center, Consumer Federation of America,
Consumers Union and similar groups who fear it will pre-empt states
from enforcing traditional legal protections for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration supports federal legislation to
recognize digital signatures, but is joining with consumer groups
in calling for more protections in the final bill prepared by the
House-Senate conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech industry appears willing to compromise to get the
legislation moving in May. ``We are very hopeful that the minor
differences that exist can be ironed out in short order,'' said
Matthew Tanielian, a lobbyist for the Information Technology
Industry Council.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   A number of private companies, such as VeriSign Inc. of Mountain
View, Calif., and Entrust Technologies Inc. of Plano, Texas, have
developed ways to allow two parties to sign a document without fear
of forgery.
</P>
<P>
   Such companies can create and verify a unique signature by using
cryptography, a branch of applied mathematics dealing with the
conversion of messages into unintelligible forms and back again.
Digital signatures make use of an algorithm using two distinct but
mathematically related ``keys'' needed to open the text and verify
the signer's identity.
</P>
<P>
   VeriSign vice president Michael Baum said using digital
signatures and related products, such as digital time stamps, helps
``hammer down the who, what, where and when of a transaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Employing computer-based methods to document a transaction is
just a new way of doing what people have traditionally done to make
contracts binding, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are writing to a friend about your trip to France, a
33-cent stamp will do just fine,'' he said. But if you are entering
into a contract, ``you probably would make a copy of it, have it
notarized at the bank and send it with a courier,'' he said.
Likewise, a digital signature ``provides probative evidence of a
transaction.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.nclcdc.org., www.itic.org.,
www.techlawjournal.com
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1613EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
