<HEADER>
A0574 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-U.S.-RIGHTS-625     04-18 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-RIGHTS-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA EVADES U.N CENSURE ON HUMAN RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ China once again evaded international censure of its
human rights record when it won a preemptive procedural maneuver on
Tuesday to block debate by the United Nations' main rights forum.
</P>
<P>
   Splitting 22-18, with 12 countries abstaining, the member
countries of the U.N. Human Rights Commission rejected an attempt
to bring China to account for what the Clinton administration says
is a deteriorating human rights climate for political dissenters,
practitioners of the Falun Gong spiritual movement, unregistered
churches, Internet users, ethnic minorities and disfavored
academics and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate vote, Cuba was criticized for its rights
practices, particularly repression of political opposition and
detention of dissidents. The tally was 21 countries voting for the
resolution, 18 against and 14 abstaining. Although European
countries backed the resolution fielded by the Czech Republic and
Poland and co-sponsored by the United States, they noted that the
measure ignored the negative effects the American economic embargo
has had on Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The case of Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old Cuban shipwreck
survivor, did not appear to sway votes despite Havana's charge it
showed the hypocrisy of U.S. accusations against it. Two more
countries voted for the anti-Cuba resolution this year than in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   The votes were among those taken by the 53-country commission,
which meets in Geneva for six weeks annually, to review the prior
year's performance by some of the world's worst human rights
offenders. This year, the body also criticized Yugoslavia for its
repression of media and political foes, Myanmar for using forced
labor, and Iraq for executions and torture, among others. The
question of Russian atrocities in Chechnya has been delayed until
next week to see if a compromise can be reached.
</P>
<P>
   While commission censure incurs no penalties, most nations seek
to avoid such unfavorable international scrutiny. China is chief
among them, and has used a procedural maneuver to avoid
full-fledged examination of its human rights practices. This has
worked all but one year since resolutions began to be lodged at the
commission following the 1989 killings of protestors at Tiananmen
Square.
</P>
<P>
   If a no-action motion passes, there is no further discussion of
a country's record. In 1995, the effort against China passed the
first hurdle, but commission members then voted against rebuking
the country.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. arguments that China's rights situation had worsened in the
past year found little support among African and Asian countries,
some of which have questionable histories of treating their own
citizens. Countries, including Pakistan, Russia, Cuba, India and
Sudan, lined up behind Chinese envoy Qiao Zonghuai who declared the
U.S. effort was ``nothing but an anti-China political farce
directed and played all by the United States alone,'' and labeled
``a blatant lie'' the American contention that China's rights
situation had seriously worsened.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the vote, both sides lobbied extensively to sway a
half-dozen uncommitted countries. Chinese officials traveled to
various capitals, and kept up a barrage against the ``evil cult''
of Falun Gong. Hundreds of human rights dissidents and supporters
poured into Geneva, with colorfully garbed Tibetans demonstrating
against Beijing's policies.
</P>
<P>
   Some rights campaigners said they thought the European Union's
tepid backing had sunk the U.S. effort. The 15-country EU had been
unable to agree on a common position and individual countries were
worried over the possibility of commercial retaliation by the
Chinese, according to several people following the commission. In
an unusual development, Romania's delegation left the room during
the China vote.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The resolution's prospects this year also were seriously
weakened because many countries saw it as a sop to U.S. domestic
interests opposing China's entry in the World Trade Organization.
China's ally, Pakistan addressed the issue directly, declaring it
opposed the United States bringing ``domestic political horse
trading into'' the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Hongju Koh, U.S. assistant secretary of state, said
Washington expected China would ``play by the world's trading
rules'' if it enters the WTO, just as it should ``play by the
world's human rights rules.''
</P>
<P>
   He was particularly critical of the no-action motion as China's
attempt ``to exempt itself from its obligations to uphold
international norms and standards.'' Following the vote, he said
that ``China's invincibility has been pierced. The notion that they
can regularly put up a no-action motion has been called into
question,'' because the winning margin has been narrowed to four
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to China's assertions, Washington's resolution is not
confrontation, Koh insisted. ``When a government consistently
confronts its own people and denies them basic human rights, it is
our duty, as commission members, to speak up for the rights of
these people to believe, worship, speak, work and assemble without
government repression.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By sponsoring a resolution on China,'' he argued, ``we have
helped draw the attention fo the world and the Chinese authorities
themselves to China's poor human rights record, and the plight of
the Chinese people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One rights official noted that the U.S. effort ``was awkward but
necessary to deal with the human rights of one-fifth of the world's
population.''
</P>
</TEXT>
