<HEADLINE>
OVER-THE-COUNTER GENERICS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies GENERIC DRUGS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most popular over-the-counter drugs are available today as house
brands at major drug chains, such as Eckerd, Walgreen and Drug
Emporium, and mass merchandisers such as Wal-Mart and Target.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration evaluates nonprescription
``copy cat'' drugs in the same way it does prescription generics,
that is, they must be ``bioequivalent'' to the name brand.
</P>
<P>
   The generic drug's labeling must contain information that is
essentially the same as that of the approved name-brand drug, and
the manufacturer must show that its generic drug is stable under
extremes of heat and humidity before it can be sold.
</P>
<P>
   Selecting a house brand or other generic equivalent can save
money over brand names and work just as well.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a bottle of 100 name-brand Tylenol recently was
selling for $8.99 at Eckerd Drug while Eckerd's own brand of
acetaminophen runs $6.99 for 100, Drug Emporium's regular price for
its own brand is $1.99 for 100, while Tylenol runs $7.67. At
Target, Tylenol was selling at $6.49 for 100, while the comparable
Target brand was $4.89.
</P>
<P>
   Similar savings are available on store brands of other popular
pain relievers, antihistamines, decongestants, antacids, vitamins,
cough suppressants and stomach-acid reducers.
</P>
<P>
   Check the labels to compare indications for use, warnings and
both active and inactive ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
