<SLUG> BC-GENERICDRUGS-CHART-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN GENERIC SUBSTITUTION MAY NOT BE THE RIGHT THING TO DO
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies GENERIC DRUGS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Food and Drug Administration stands by any and all of
the generic equivalents it approves and says there are no
documented examples of a generic product manufactured to meet its
approved specifications that could not be used interchangeably with
the corresponding brand-name drug.
</P>
<P>
   However, many doctors, including those responsible for The Merck
Manual, the most widely used medical reference in the world, say
generic substitutes should not be used in some cases, especially
when there is a ``very narrow therapeutic index.'' With these
drugs, there is very little difference between a therapeutic dose
and a dangerous overdose or underdose.
</P>
<P>
   For some drugs, especially those taken for congestive heart
failure, asthma, epilepsy or psychosis and some high blood pressure
and diabetes drugs, patients should consult their physicians before
substituting a generic for a brand-name version.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't that these generics are bad. They can be perfectly
fine, and most of the time, they are,'' says Dr. Robert Berkow,
editor of the Merck Manual. ``But, for a drug like theophyline and
some of the hormone formulations and heart drugs, we recommend
against switching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hormone preparations all work, but if you are taking one and
you like the way it is working for you, whether it's generic or
brand name, I wouldn't want you to switch. A very tiny difference
could be a problem. The drug itself may be equivalent, but pressed
into a tablet, it may not be so equivalent. It's not always a
question of one being better than the other, but of changing from
one to another.''
</P>
<P>
   For long-lasting potassium supplements, Berkow says doctors
recommend against generics sold in tablet form, but capsules may be
freely substituted. It seems that some generic potassium tablets
are so compressed they do not dissolve quickly enough to be
absorbed fully.
</P>
<P>
   In another example, Berkow says that when he prescribes warfarin
(to prevent blood clotting) he has a good idea of how the brand he
prescribes is going to work, so he wouldn't want patients to take a
generic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want anybody switching it to another preparation
because the range of safety is too narrow. It may lose its effects
and you end up with a blood clot or it may be too effective, and
you end up with uncontrolled bleeding,'' Berkow says.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer prescriptions are written ``DAW,'' (dispense as written)
today, but when they are, there is usually good reason, says Dr.
Marvin Shepherd of the University of Texas College of Pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   Digoxin, a heart medicine, is almost always prescribed under the
brand name, Lanoxin, for example, because so many people have used
it under that brand name for so long, and doctors know it is very
dependable and predictable.
</P>
<P>
   In a reversal of their usual policy, some HMOs refuse to cover
the cost of generic digoxin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a heart medicine that works for you, you don't
want to change it,'' says Shepherd. ``It is an inexpensive drug
that costs about $8 a month for the brand-name. Why would anyone
want to change to the generic?''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Drug Category --- Examples --- Comments
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Drugs for which the toxic dose is only slightly higher than the
therapeutic dose.
</P>
<P>
   Warfarin (to prevent blood clotting), digoxin (for heart
failure); also, phenytoin, carbamazepine, valproic acid and other
anti-seizure drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The margin of safety is relatively small (narrow therapeutic
index); too little may not work at all, too much may cause side
effects.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Drugs on the market before the 1938 amendments to the Food, Drug
and Cosmetic Act.
</P>
<P>
   Digoxin and other digitalis derivatives (for heart failure);
also, thyroid hormone and derivatives such as levothyroxine and
liotrix (for hypothyroidism and Graves' disease).
</P>
<P>
   These drugs are exempt from generic requirements and are seldom
still prescribed as generics. Doctors say switching among different
versions is unwise because no standards of comparison have been
established.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Corticosteroid creams, lotions and ointments.
</P>
<P>
   Alclometasone, amcinonide, betamethasone, clocortolone,
desonide, desoximetasone, dexamethasone, diflorasone, fluocinolone,
fluocinonide, flurandrenolide, fluticasone, halcinonide,
halobetasol, hydrocortisone, mometasone, triamcinolone (to relieve
swelling and itching).
</P>
<P>
   These drugs are standardized by skin response, which is varied
and unpredictable. A product that is effective shouldn't be
switched.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Corticosteroid tablets.
</P>
<P>
   Dexamethasone, some brands of prednisone
</P>
<P>
   Many generic versions are not equivalent to trade-name drugs and
shouldn't be freely substituted for them.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   High blood pressure drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Reserpine, reserpine plus hydrochlorothiazide, reserpine plus
hydroflumethiazide, hydralazine.
</P>
<P>
   Generic versions are not equivalent to trade-name drugs.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Aerosol drugs, especially those for asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Metaproterenol and terbutaline (widely used bronchodilators),
also some aerosol corticosteroid preparations.
</P>
<P>
   Any one of the versions may be effective, but standards for
comparing them are still under development.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Oral asthma drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Theophyline, dyphiline, some brands of aminophyline.
</P>
<P>
   Products are generally not equivalent. Someone doing well with a
particular brand should avoid switching unless absolutely
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Antidepressant drugs.
</P>
<P>
   A few brands of amitriptyline, one amitriptyline-perphenazine
combination.
</P>
<P>
   Not all brands are substitutable. A pharmacist can advise
whether a particular generic drug is considered equivalent by the
FDA.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Glyburide (for adult onset diabetes)
</P>
<P>
   One brand of glyburide (Glynase) may not be interchanged with
the others.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Antipsychotic drugs
</P>
<P>
   Chlorpromazine tablets
</P>
<P>
   Generic versions are not equivalent to the trade-name version.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Gout drugs
</P>
<P>
   Probenecid, colchicine
</P>
<P>
   Generic versions are not equivalent to the trade-name version.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Hormones
</P>
<P>
   Esterified estrogen (for estrogen replacement therapy in
postmenopausal women); some brands of medroxyprogesterone; most
generic versions of methyltestosterone.
</P>
<P>
   Since hormones are generally taken in extremely small doses,
differences could produce major swings in patient response.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Potassium
</P>
<P>
   Most long-acting potassium replacement products in ``tablet/
form.
</P>
<P>
   The long-acting potassium replacement ``capsules/ are considered
equivalent and may be freely substituted.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Other drugs
</P>
<P>
   Disulfiram
</P>
<P>
   Fluoxymesterone
</P>
<P>
   Mazindol
</P>
<P>
   Nicotine patches
</P>
<P>
   Phenytoin prompt
</P>
<P>
   Promethazine tablets and suppositories
</P>
<P>
   Rauwolfia serpentina
</P>
<P>
   Trichlormethiazide.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTS: Generic versions of these drug products are not
equivalent. Although any brand can be effective, brands should not
be interchanged. _ The Merck Manual of Medical Information _ Home
Edition
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
