<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-RALLY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GROUP RALLIES TO PUBLICIZE RACE BIAS SUIT AGAINST COCA-COLA
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY Jr.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Chanting slogans of outrage, nearly 50 current and
former Coca-Cola employees held a rally Tuesday on Capitol Hill to
publicize a discrimination lawsuit against the company and pressure
Coke officials to settle the suit quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The event was part of a five-day, four-city ``Ride for Corporate
Justice'' tour that is also aimed at raising public awareness of
racial discrimination at the Coca-Cola Co. and calling for an end
to employment discrimination in corporate America, said the
organizers, the Atlanta-based Committee for Corporate Justice.
</P>
<P>
   The federal lawsuit, filed by eight current and former
employees, alleges that Coca-Cola has discriminated against blacks
in pay and promotions. The plaintiffs are seeking class-action
status so they can represent about 2,000 current and former black
Coke employees in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The company has denied the allegations and has fought efforts to
make the suit a class-action case. Phone calls to Coke headquarters
were not returned Tuesday, but company spokesman Ben Deutsch said
Saturday, ``We continue to work towards a quick and equitable
resolution of the lawsuit.'' Black employees at Coke earn an
average $27,000 less than their white counterparts in the same
positions, Larry Jones told fellow protesters wearing red hats with
buttons reading ``Justice Riders.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before Jones spoke, the group thundered, ``What do we want?
Justice! From who? Coca-Cola!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are tired of the deception, and I would like to challenge
(Coke CEO Douglas Daft) to prove to us that those problems don't
exist,'' Jones said, waving a 20-ounce bottle of Coca-Cola in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   Jones referred to Coca-Cola layoffs a few months ago as ``ethnic
cleansing,'' saying it was likely that a majority of those losing
their jobs were black.
</P>
<P>
   Former Coke employee Angela Graham told the rally that despite
her excellent performance record, she was passed over for promotion
several times while less-qualified whites were promoted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad thing about all this is that you come in the company
with a lot of hope,'' said Graham, who left the company in January
after three years' employment. But ``before I let Coca-Cola or any
company in corporate America oppress my people, I will die and go
to my grave first.''
</P>
<P>
   Several times in his speech, Jones alluded to a boycott of Coke
products, but said the group would use every option available to
avoid one. But he said that if nothing is resolved at Coke's annual
shareholder's meeting in Wilmington, Del., on Wednesday, he could
call for a boycott.
</P>
<P>
   The rally in a House hearing room was the group's only event in
the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The rolling protest started started in Decatur, Ga., on Saturday
and made stops for rallies in Greensboro, N.C., and Richmond, Va.,
before coming to Washington. The ride will end at the shareholders
meeting, which protesters plan to attend along with the Rev. Jesse
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailt(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
