<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T CRY: IT'S JUST AN ONION  
 A NUT IN NAME ONLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)Last week's Food Chain column discussed ways to chop
onions without tears. It suggested that to reduce the eye
irritation caused when allicin, a volatile substance, is released
from the onion, cooks should wear protective eyewear, do their
chopping under running water or chill the onion first. Readers had
a few other suggestions.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is another method for reducing crying while cutting
onions. You hinted at in in your answer. The goal is to prevent
cutting the cell structure and having the juices or vapor from the
onion get into your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Use a very sharp knife and slice the onion by sawing, so that
you don't crush the cells and cause the liquid in the onion to
spray. Don't chop as if chopping a log. A sharp knife will make it
unnecessary to push hard. It works. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Two readers had the same idea:(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I've found munching on a piece of bread or cracker does wonders.
But I have no idea why! &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cut off about an eighth of a slice of bread and place it on the
roof of your mouth. It does the trick, although if you are chopping
a lot of onions, you may have to change the bread. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)The food scientist and author Harold McGee hypothesized
why the bread trick might work.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're holding something in your mouth, you won't be
inhaling that way, so you might take in slightly less of the onion
fumes,'' he said. But he noted that most of the irritation comes
from your eyes making direct contact with the fumes, not from
inhaling them. McGee recommends either chilling the onions or
blocking the fumes with glasses.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is an easy, successful method I have used for many years.
I do my chopping on the back part of the stove-top with the exhaust
fan running. No fumes, no tears. The only requirement is an exhaust
fan! &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Several members of my family suffer from nut allergies.
Recently, we were preparing a recipe that called for water chestnut
flour. Is the water chestnut actually a member of the nut family?
</P>
<P>
   A. Despite their name, water chestnuts are not related to nuts.
Technically, they are corms, or fleshy underground stems, of the
water chestnut plant (Trapa natans), which grows along the muddy
edges of ponds and lakes, or in flooded fields. When raw, water
chestnuts have a juicy-crisp texture that is somewhat like
jicama's.
</P>
<P>
   Cooked, the flesh softens around the outside but still retains
that characteristic crunch within. Water chestnuts can also be
dried and ground into a starchy flour, which is much like arrowroot
starch. In fact, arrowroot starch, available in most health food
stores, makes a good substitute for water chestnut flour, which can
be difficult to find.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
