buttons reading ``Justice Riders.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before Jones spoke, the group thundered, ``What do we want?
Justice! From who? Coca-Cola!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are tired of the deception, and I would like to challenge
(Coke CEO Douglas Daft) to prove to us that those problems don't
exist,'' Jones said, waving a 20-ounce bottle of Coca-Cola in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   Jones referred to Coca-Cola layoffs a few months ago as ``ethnic
cleansing,'' saying it was likely that a majority of those losing
their jobs were black.
</P>
<P>
   Former Coke employee Angela Graham told the rally that despite
her excellent performance record, she was passed over for promotion
several times while less-qualified whites were promoted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad thing about all this is that you come in the company
with a lot of hope,'' said Graham, who left the company in January
after three years' employment. But ``before I let Coca-Cola or any
company in corporate America oppress my people, I will die and go
to my grave first.''
</P>
<P>
   Several times in his speech, Jones alluded to a boycott of Coke
products, but said the group would use every option available to
avoid one. But he said that if nothing is resolved at Coke's annual
shareholder's meeting in Wilmington, Del., on Wednesday, he could
call for a boycott.
</P>
<P>
   The rally in a House hearing room was the group's only event in
the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The rolling protest started started in Decatur, Ga., on Saturday
and made stops for rallies in Greensboro, N.C., and Richmond, Va.,
before coming to Washington. The ride will end at the shareholders
meeting, which protesters plan to attend along with the Rev. Jesse
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailt(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
