<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0589 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TALK-ART-NYT &LR;      04-18 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AMERICA IT'S MUZAK, IN FRANCE A SYMPHONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someone once asked Harry Waugh, the English wine merchant,
writer and director of Chateau Latour, if he had ever mistaken a
Burgundy for a Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not since lunch,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   I console myself with Harry's words when I confuse a California
merlot with a California cabernet in a blind tasting. I'm not
alone. Even skilled winemakers mix them up.
</P>
<P>
   Merlot, the red grape of the moment, was once seen as mostly a
blending grape. In the last decade, it became a popular solo act,
an alternative to cabernet sauvignon. Cabernet is described as
lean, austere, angular and astringent, with lots of tannin. Merlot
is softer, fleshier, rounder and easier to drink.
</P>
<P>
   Winemakers add merlot to cabernet ``to soften it up a bit.''
They add cabernet to merlot ``to give it structure, or backbone.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder that red wine fans often ask themselves: ``Is
this a rounded, softer cabernet or a drier, tannic merlot?'' In the
final analysis, California cabernet sauvignon and California merlot
have so much in common that it is not easy to tell them apart, even
unblended.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for all of merlot's inroads in the United States, it is a
pallid bit player here, compared with the flamboyant star that
merlot is in France, from Petrus on down.
</P>
<P>
   Merlot as a varietal has been on the market since the late
1960s. In the '70s, when Napa Valley wineries like Duckhorn began
making it an alternative to cabernet sauvignon, it took off. It
appealed to wine buyers intent on staying ahead of the crowd, part
of which was moving into red wine and asking for cabernet. The wine
industry is ever on the lookout for a new favorite. In the late
1980s, merlot filled the bill perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   Merlot grows all over the world. Italy, Eastern Europe, Chile,
Australia and New Zealand all make some wine with it, usually
without much distinction. It is in France, and specifically in
Bordeaux, however, that the grape comes truly into its own.
</P>
<P>
   More than twice as much merlot as cabernet sauvignon is planted
in Bordeaux. Just as in California, it is widely used to make
cabernet more accessible. It is an important component in almost
every great Bordeaux wine, including the five First Growths:
Haut-Brion, Latour, Lafite-Rothschild, Mouton-Rothschild and
Margaux.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Bordeaux region of St.-Emilion and Pomerol, merlot is
something more. The best wines of Pomerol are almost all merlot.
Chateau Petrus, often considered the finest of Bordeaux, is
normally 92 percent to 95 percent merlot. The fabled Chateau Le Pin
is usually 95 percent merlot, Clinet is 80 percent, La Conseillante
70 percent and Vieux Chateau Certan about 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A bottle of decade-old Petrus can cost $375 to $1,550 in New
York, depending on the vintage. Bottles from chateaus like La
Conseillante, Vieux Chateau Certan and Le Pin all sell for more
than $100. This is because of location and has little to do with
the merlot grape. Merlots or wines that are predominantly merlot
from vineyards in Fronsac and Lalande-de-Pomerol sell for as little
as $20. Location, location, location.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation of the fame of Petrus goes back to the 1950s,
when an importer holding much of the Petrus in the United States
made a big sale of it to Henri Soule, owner of Le Pavillon, then
the reigning French restaurant in New York. Soule convinced diners
that Petrus was the Bordeaux to drink, and the wine has been
popular ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The wines of Pomerol differ widely in style, but all have
elegance combined with concentrated fruit and a soft, almost
velvety texture, which is why Pomerol is sometimes called the
Burgundy of Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   To say that the wines of neighboring St.-Emilion are closer in
style to Medoc oversimplifies, because there are separate styles
within St.-Emilion. Generally, however, St.-Emilions are more
structured and less opulent than Pomerols.
</P>
<P>
   The wine of Chateau Troplong-Mondot, a Grand Cru Classe, is
usually about 80 percent merlot; Magdelaine is 90 percent;
Grand-Mayne, 70 percent; La Gaffeliere, 65 percent; and l'Angelus
and Ausone, both about 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   No one who has ever drunk more than a few bottles of Bordeaux
will ever confuse these wines with the cabernet-dominant wines of
Medoc. Why? Because of terroir, that elusive word, which seems to
combine the importance of the soil and weather.
</P>
<P>
   Merlot is first mentioned in the records of Pomerol and
St.-Emilion in the 18th century, so the growers there have had at
least 200 years to seek out the best combinations of land and
vines. The soils of Pomerol are different from those of
St.-Emilion, and those of Petrus are different from the rest of
Pomerol.
</P>
<P>
   The Petrus vineyards form a small island of clay in the center
of a small sea of gravel, the predominant soil of the surrounding
vineyards. Much of St.-Emilion is on limestone, but in parts there
are clay, sand and gravel.
</P>
<P>
   For years, California winemakers played down the importance of
terroir, maintaining that the weather _ the heat, rainfall and
sunlight _ mattered most for grape growing. That attitude has
changed, notably since the phylloxera epidemic of the 1980s and
early '90s provided an opportunity to replant thousands of acres of
prime California vineyard land.
</P>
<P>
   There are California merlots that are not just softer cabernets.
Matanzas Creek, Duckhorn, Newton, Ravenswood and Shafer come to
mind. Washington State also has good choices. Its red wines, both
cabernet and merlot, can be leaner, more elegant, more Bordeauxlike
than California's. Washington merlots worth sampling include Andrew
Hill, Canoe Ridge, Columbia Crest, Seven Hills and L'Ecole No. 41.
</P>
<P>
   Among Bordeaux, lesser appellations in and around Pomerol and
St.-Emilion are merlot-based and affordable. Lalande-de-Pomerol,
which adjoins Pomerol, produces creditable Pomerol-style wines.
</P>
<P>
   Wines from chateaus like Belles-Graves, Les Templiers, Chambran
and Bertineau, which is owned by the enologist Michel Rolland, are
worth hunting down. Chateau Puygueraud, in the Cotes de Francs, is
owned by the Thienponts, who own Le Pin and Vieux Chateau Certan.
It often shows up in serious wine shops.
</P>
<P>
   While Petrus is inaccessible to the average buyer, the winery is
owned by the Moueix family, which owns many properties in the
region. I am partial to wines from the family's smaller places in
Fronsac and Canon-Fronsac, like La Croix, Canon Moueix (usually
more than 90 percent merlot) and La Croix-Canon.
</P>
<P>
   None of the French properties mention grape contents on their
labels. One day, perhaps, Americans will move beyond varietal
labeling.
</P>
<P>
   But if a wine comes from a good place and is made by someone I
respect, I don't care what grapes are in it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
