<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0590 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-FRESH-HAM-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      04-18 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRESH-HAM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HAM WITH AN ELEMENT OF SURPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN WILLOUGHBY and CHRIS SCHLESINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like actors, foods can become typecast, so closely identified
with a particular approach that we never think of them any other
way. Often, though, an unrecognized but exciting player lurks
behind the familiar guise.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly enough, in the pork department this role is occupied
by ham. Everybody recognizes it. It is the hind leg of a hog that
has been cured and often smoked as well, acquiring in the process a
delicate pink hue and a rich flavor strongly underpinned with salt
and smoke.
</P>
<P>
   That's a ham, all right. But so is that same hind leg of pork
uncured and unsmoked. To distinguish it from the cured version, it
has come to be called ``fresh ham,'' and it is a truly wonderful
pork roast. Anyone looking for a new centerpiece for the holiday
table ought to give it a chance.
</P>
<P>
   We first encountered fresh hams when we started attending
barbecue competitions in the South a number of years ago. Along
with pork shoulders, these uncured hams were very popular options
for the long, slow process of smoke roasting that is barbecue. But,
as we found out when we decided to explore further, a fresh ham is
also exceptional when roasted in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet, tender, juicy and full of pork flavor, it is also quite a
bit less expensive per pound than the more traditional loin roast.
This makes it ideal for big, celebratory dinners. It also has the
added advantage of unfamiliarity, a quality that makes it memorable
to guests.
</P>
<P>
   And you need to have guests, because this is a large roast.
Weighing in the neighborhood of 20 pounds, a whole fresh ham is too
big for all but the largest celebrations, not to mention most home
ovens. A half pork leg is often more appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   You can get either the rump or shank section of the leg, each of
which has its advantages. The rump, or butt half, which is rounded,
has a higher proportion of meat to bone. But we slightly prefer the
somewhat larger shank half, which is tapered, because it is easier
to carve and somewhat leaner.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever end of the leg you buy, make sure it is bone-in and
skin-on. The bone adds considerable flavor, and the crisp skin is
our favorite part of the meal.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the first time we cooked a skin-on fresh ham, we
discovered what is probably the original inspiration for the
somewhat mysterious crisscross pattern that adorns pineapple-topped
cured hams on all those buffet lines and Easter dinner tables.
Making cuts in this way opens up the inside of the ham to whatever
flavored rub or paste you might want to apply, but without forcing
you to take off the tasty skin.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve this useful pattern, take a sharp knife and slash the
skin all over in a crosshatch pattern, cutting just down to the
flesh, but not into it. If you are going to the right depth, the
skin will spread apart a bit as you cut.
</P>
<P>
   Like other large pork roasts, a fresh ham will benefit from
brining. This treatment, lasting only 12 to 24 hours, is a distant
relative of the long brining and curing process that those pink
hams undergo. It is certainly not an essential step, but it's a
good idea if you have the time (and the room in your refrigerator).
</P>
<P>
   During brining, the salt and to a somewhat lesser extent the
sugar penetrate the meat. This causes the meat's proteins to unwind
a bit. As they do, they interlock with one another to form a matrix
that traps moisture inside the meat. As a result, it is juicier and
more tender when it is cooked. With today's leaner pork, that's a
very good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Although fresh hams are beginning to show up more often in
supermarkets, you may well need to make a trip to the butcher shop
to get one. As usual with roasts of this size, it pays to call
several days ahead to make sure you can get it. If the butcher says
he doesn't carry fresh ham, ask him if he has fresh pork leg roast,
an alternative name for this cut that is gaining some ground these
days.
</P>
<P>
   On the off chance that even your butcher can't get you a fresh
ham, you can substitute a Boston butt in this recipe. Since that
shoulder cut typically runs about five pounds, cut the amount of
the spice paste in half, and reduce the time it roasts at the lower
temperature by about one hour.
</P>
<P>
   But we strongly recommend that you search out a fresh ham. Not
only will you be rewarded with a succulent, very flavorful and
relatively inexpensive roast, but you will also have the
satisfaction of releasing the full potential of a role-bound
culinary star.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. RECIPE FOLLOWS IN 2nd TAKE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   MAPLE-GLAZED FRESH HAM WITH RAISIN AND HARD CIDER SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2{ to 3 hours; if brining, add 12 to 24 hours  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup kosher salt (if brining)
</P>
<P>
   } cup sugar (if brining)
</P>
<P>
   1 8- to 10-pound butt or shank portion fresh ham (half a leg),
skin on
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups raisins
</P>
<P>
   { cup dark rum
</P>
<P>
   1 cup packed dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup fresh sage leaves
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons finely grated lemon zest (from about 2 lemons)
</P>
<P>
   8 cloves garlic, peeled
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   1 cup maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   1 liter hard apple cider (or substitute regular apple cider).
</P>
<P>
   1. If brining the ham, combine salt and white sugar with 2
quarts water in a pot large enough to fit the ham comfortably. Stir
well to dissolve. Add ham, cover, and place in refrigerator for 12
to 24 hours. Remove, rinse well, and dry with paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a small bowl, combine raisins and rum and allow to sit
while ham cooks, at least 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   3. Preheat oven to 500 degrees. Place brown sugar, sage,
mustard, lemon zest, garlic, salt and peppercorns in a blender or a
food processor fitted with a steel blade, and process until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   4. Using a sharp knife, score entire surface of ham in a
crosshatch pattern, cutting down just through skin to the flesh
underneath. (If you are cutting to the right depth, the skin will
spread apart a bit as you cut.) Rub outside of ham all over with
spice mixture, pressing it gently into crosshatch spaces between
the skin. Put roast on a rack in a large roasting pan and place in
oven.
</P>
<P>
   5. After 20 minutes, reduce oven setting to 300 degrees. After 1
hour, begin painting ham every 15 minutes or so with maple syrup.
Continue roasting until the very center of ham reaches an internal
temperature of 145 degrees, 2 to 2{ hours total cooking time.
(Begin checking at 1{ hours to be sure.) To check for doneness,
insert a meat thermometer into the absolute center of the roast,
let it sit for 5 seconds, then take the reading.
</P>
<P>
   6. While ham is cooking, place cider in a medium saucepan and
bring to a boil over high heat. Reduce heat to medium high, and
simmer vigorously until liquid is reduced by about half, about 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   7. When ham is done, remove it from roasting pan, cover it
loosely with foil, and allow it to rest for 20 to 30 minutes. Tip
roasting pan to the side so you can spoon off all the fat from pan
juices, then place pan on stove over medium-high heat. Add reduced
cider, and bring to a simmer, scraping bottom of pan to free the
browned bits. Skim any film off surface and season liquid as needed
with salt and pepper. Add rum-soaked raisins, along with any
remaining rum, and stir to combine. Pour into a gravy boat.
</P>
<P>
   8. Carve ham into thick slices, drizzle with raisin-cider sauce
and serve, passing remaining sauce separately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 10 to 12 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
