<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0593 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-FRENCH-COOKBOOK-ART-N     04-18 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-COOKBOOK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY THE BOOK: THE FOUR-STAR KITCHEN WORKOUT PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't say he didn't warn you. On Page 2 of ``The French Laundry
Cookbook,'' Thomas Keller, the author, chef and owner of the Napa
Valley, Calif., restaurant of that name, makes his approach quite
clear: ``Cooking is not about convenience, and it's not about
shortcuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy for him to say.
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed the first red flag, Michael Ruhlman, his
co-author, writes on Page 9, ``Most of the recipes are
time-consuming.'' He adds: ``This is not fast food, nor is it
four-star cooking simplified for the home kitchen. It is four-star
cooking, period.''
</P>
<P>
   Having read all that, I would still spend the $50 the book
(published by Artisan) costs, if I enjoyed complex cooking and
didn't have a day job; wanted to impress my friends by leaving the
book on the coffee table; craved its odd bits of information, which
can turn an ordinary dish into an extraordinary one without a lot
of effort; or was as taken by beautiful pictures of food as others
are by beautiful paintings.
</P>
<P>
   What else can account for the three prizes the book received in
this year's International Association of Cooking Professions
contest? It won prizes for a first cookbook, for design and for the
best cookbook of the year. It has also been nominated for two
awards by the James Beard Foundation, which are given in May.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Keller, I have neither the time nor the inclination to
devote an entire weekend to cooking a meal. Having eaten at the
French Laundry, I appreciate his complex cooking and know that I
want to eat it only on very special occasions.
</P>
<P>
   And only when it has been cooked by him.
</P>
<P>
   But after the book's prize-winning streak, I took a closer look.
Obviously, practicality is not a strong point. But as a testament
to the work of one of the best chefs in America and as a piece of
art, it deserves its honors.
</P>
<P>
   So I took the advice of Susie Heller, who tested the recipes.
``If the degree of difficulty of a dish exceeds your desire to make
it, please remember that it's all right to do only part of a
recipe,'' she writes in the book.
</P>
<P>
   So I made only the Parmesan crisps from a heavenly recipe for
over-the-top ``macaroni and cheese,'' which dauntingly calls for
five component dishes to prepare before the final assembly: a
lobster broth, a butter mixture, a coral oil, lobsters and the
crisps. The crisps were delicious, but they might not take as long
to bake as the recipe suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Five dishes are intimidating enough for the average cook, but
hardly as harrowing as the eight dishes that are required to make
Keller's hearts of palm with puree of marrow beans and field
greens.
</P>
<P>
   I also made a risotto with white truffles. Besides lots of fat
(like five tablespoons of butter and three-quarters of a cup of
heavy cream), it calls for three tablespoons of white truffle oil.
The oil, instead of delicately perfuming the dish, overwhelmed it.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the book for what it is, a chef's four-star recipes
without apology, I still have a couple of quibbles.
</P>
<P>
   I don't see any reason to manipulate a sublime piece of cheese
like a fine Brie into something it is not by whipping it, forming
it into quenelles and serving it with a balsamic glaze. Yes, it
tastes wonderful, and so do the other cheeses, but instead of being
the centerpiece of the cheese course, the cheeses become only one
component in a multi-ingredient dish.
</P>
<P>
   And I wish Keller had not titled the chapter that includes
ingredients like tripe and pig's head ``The Importance of Offal.''
It's a bit much.
</P>
<P>
   I will not be doing much cooking from this book, but I have
committed to memory some of Keller's most enlightening tidbits:
</P>
<P>
   Choose oysters with the thickest shells. They have the most
juice.
</P>
<P>
   Buy black truffles when they are in season. Poach them in
mushroom stock and freeze them for later use.
</P>
<P>
   Do not store white truffles in rice: it dries them out. Keep
them in an airtight container wrapped in a moist towel.
</P>
<P>
   If you serve smoked salmon warm, heat it in milk to leach out
the salt while keeping the smoky cured flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Keller produces brilliant food by focusing on certain flavors
and making them more intense. His search for perfection is beyond
most of us, amateur or professional, but for hobbyist cooks, for
those who want to impress their friends and for those who just love
to read cookbooks, this may be $50 well spent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1657EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
