<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASTA TREATED LIKE A COUSIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I recently cooked with a friend who had a novel idea
that immediately seemed sensible and appealing: Why not cook pasta
like risotto? Adding broth a bit at a time and stirring frequently
certainly seemed as if it should create a creamy pasta dish in less
time (no waiting for the water to boil).
</P>
<P>
   My one concern was that the starch given off by the pasta, which
is usually poured off with the cooking water, would make the dish
too starchy. But we both realized that it is exactly that
starchiness that gives risotto its texture.
</P>
<P>
   Our first attempt was encouraging if underflavored. We used
gemelli, although we guessed that any cut pasta like penne or
fusilli would work. (Long pasta is far too unwieldy.) It took only
a few more tries to perfect the technique.
</P>
<P>
   Because pasta is so bland _ even more so than rice _ I decided
to brown it first in butter (or oil). As with risotto, high-quality
stock really made a difference. If you're using canned stock,
consider heating it with an onion, a carrot and a garlic clove
before beginning to add it to the pasta.
</P>
<P>
   A good handful of freshly grated Parmesan added at the end
turned out to be essential for creaminess and flavor.
</P>
<P>
   One more step was needed, however: the addition of a vegetable.
Carrots added color and sweetness, but for this version I settled
on asparagus, which is not only in season but also provides
distinctive flavor. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PASTA, RISOTTO STYLE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Total time: 30 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 pound asparagus
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 pound gemelli
</P>
<P>
   6 to 8 cups good stock, heated
</P>
<P>
   Salt and fresh black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Freshly grated Parmesan. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Break woody ends off asparagus, and peel stalks if desired.
Break or cut off tips, and cut stems into {-inch sections.
</P>
<P>
   2. Put half the butter in a deep 10- or 12-inch skillet or broad
saucepan, and turn heat to medium-high; when butter melts, add
onion and cook, stirring occasionally, until softened and beginning
to brown, 3 to 5 minutes. Add pasta and cook, stirring
occasionally, until it begins to brown, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add a ladleful of stock. As stock is absorbed and pasta
swells, add more stock and continue to stir occasionally, until
pasta is beginning to become tender, about 5 minutes. Add asparagus
stems, and continue to add stock as needed until pasta is just
about done, 5 minutes or so.
</P>
<P>
   4. Add asparagus tips and a little more stock, stirring until
tips are crisp-tender, the pasta is cooked to your liking and the
mixture is moist but not soupy. (Add a little more stock if
necessary.) Season with salt and pepper to taste. Stir in remaining
butter and Parmesan to taste, and serve. Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1701EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0599 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      04-18 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN DELOUVRIER: FRESH AND SALTED COD FLOATING UNDER A CLOUD 
</HEADLINE>
   This is the last of eight columns by Christian Delouvrier, the
executive chef at Lespinasse in Manhattan. They have been written
with Melissa Clark. Next week: Wylie Dufresne, the chef and owner
of 71 Clinton Fresh Foods.  
 (editors: recipe at end of article)  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cod and mashed potatoes are perfectly balanced
partners, each so subtly flavored that one never overshadows the
other. When the cod is fresh, the mild-mannered ingredients enhance
each other. But when the marriage is made with salt cod, in
brandade, the potatoes mellow the briny aggressiveness of the fish.
</P>
<P>
   Both those classic combinations are supremely satisfying, but I
came up with a three-way partnership that takes all the flavors
even further. I spread the creamy brandade on a crouton, which is
how it is typically served in the South of France, and perch the
fresh roasted cod on top. The garlicky brandade acts almost like a
sauce, flavoring the cod with every bite. But then I cover the
whole layering with an airy blanket of foam made from mashed
potatoes and skim milk. Its sweet lightness is a great contrast to
the dense brandade.
</P>
<P>
   My cod with mashed potatoes involves several steps, but none of
them are the slightest bit difficult. The fresh cod is simply
brushed with olive oil and roasted for 10 minutes. The croutons can
be baked and the brandade pureed a few days in advance. And the
foam can be whipped up while the fish is roasting.
</P>
<P>
   The first step in cooking with salt cod is to soak it overnight,
so that it softens and plumps and gives up much of its salt.
Simmering it in whole milk sweetens the flesh of the cod and leaves
it even more tender and flaky.
</P>
<P>
   In the Mediterranean, cooks traditionally make brandade by
pounding salt cod in a mortar with cooked potato, garlic and a
drizzle of olive oil until it homogenizes into a smooth paste. For
the sake of convenience, I use a food processor, being careful not
to overprocess the mixture. The potatoes can go from perfect to
gluey in one pulse.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, potatoes for brandade are boiled, but I bake them,
because they mash up fluffier when they don't absorb liquid.
</P>
<P>
   The only slightly tricky part of this dish is the foam, getting
the balance of potatoes to milk just right so that the flavors come
through and the mixture foams. I use skim milk because the extra
fat in whole milk makes it too heavy to foam, especially once the
potatoes and olive oil are mixed in. The finished dish looks white
on white, and the flavors have the same purity.
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED COD WITH BRANDADE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2 hours, plus overnight soaking  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces skinless, center-cut salt cod
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter, cut into cubes
</P>
<P>
   2 cups whole milk
</P>
<P>
   4 slices homemade-style white bread, cut into 2{-inch rounds
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons plus 2 teaspoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 medium Idaho potatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 skinless cod fillets (4 ounces each).
</P>
<P>
   2 cups skim milk
</P>
<P>
   1. Rinse salt cod under running water and place in a bowl. Cover
with water and refrigerate overnight. Place half the butter cubes
in freezer.
</P>
<P>
   2. Drain salt cod. Place in a saucepan with whole milk and
simmer over low heat for 1 hour. Drain cod and let cool.
</P>
<P>
   3. Meanwhile, preheat oven to 400 degrees. Brush bread rounds on
both sides with 2 tablespoons olive oil. Place on a baking sheet.
Prick potatoes all over with a fork and place next to bread. Bake
bread until toasted, about 7 minutes, turning after 4 minutes.
Transfer to a wire rack to cool. Continue to bake potatoes until
very soft, 40 to 50 minutes. Cool, then peel and lightly crush with
a fork.
</P>
<P>
   4. To make brandade, put drained salt cod, 2 tablespoons olive
oil and garlic in a food processor, and puree. Add 1/3 cup of
crushed potato, and pulse until mixture is just smooth, taking care
not to overprocess. Put half the remaining potatoes in a small
saucepan with the unfrozen 2 tablespoons butter. Heat, stirring
gently, until butter is melted and potatoes are hot. Mix in
brandade, taste, and add more salt if necessary. Cover and keep
warm.
</P>
<P>
   5. Brush fresh cod all over with 2 tablespoons olive oil, place
on a baking sheet, and sprinkle with salt. Roast cod until it turns
opaque, about 7 to 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   6. Meanwhile, bring skim milk and remaining 2 teaspoons olive
oil to a simmer in a small saucepan. Add the remaining potatoes and
remove from heat. Using an immersion blender, whip the mixture,
adding frozen butter cubes gradually. Continue to whip until
mixture is very foamy, about 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   7. To serve, dab a small amount of brandade on each of 4 serving
plates. Top each dab with a toasted bread round, then spoon
remaining brandade over. Place cod fillets on top, and cover with
foam. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
