<HEADER>
A0600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-DEER-DEPORT-ART-NY     04-18 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-DEER-DEPORT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY TOWN PLANS TO SEND UNWELCOME DEER TO NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT6 and NYT7 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILLBURN, N.J. _ Like many of their neighbors across the
suburbs, the people of Millburn have had it with Bambi.
</P>
<P>
   They are sick of deer eating their garbage, tomato plants and
azaleas. They associate deer more with Lyme disease and highway
collisions than with the wonders of nature. Last year, town workers
picked up 100 battered carcasses from local roads, double the
number of a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've become a major safety hazard,'' said Judith Kramer, a
lawyer who lives in the town's Short Hills section. ``I've seen a
school of them cross my street. What about the children? What about
my dog, Breezy? What if he tries to go after them and gets hurt?''
</P>
<P>
   But unlike other places where hunters or hired sharpshooters
cull the herds, Millburn is taking a costly, though far less
volatile approach to the problem. If all goes according to plan,
dozens of deer will be traveling by trailer on the New Jersey
Turnpike later this month, heading to a temporary home on an
upstate New York farm.
</P>
<P>
   What happens to them after that is unclear. The man
orchestrating their removal, Mark MacNamara, a deer handling
specialist, said some may end up in zoos and some as breeders for
venison farms. Others could go to the slaughterhouse.
</P>
<P>
   New York state law prevents any from being released into the
wild.
</P>
<P>
   Millburn officials admit that exporting deer out of state may
sound extravagant, but the alternative is far less palatable. ``We
don't want to have troubles,'' said Timothy Gordon, the town
administrator, referring to the strife that has engulfed other
places that proposed lethal means for controlling deer.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the region's wealthiest communities, Millburn can
afford to spend $20,000 to battle overpopulation without inciting
civil war. Bob Lund, who directs the state's Community Based Deer
Management Program, said there were 40 or so New Jersey towns
tearing each other apart over hunting. ``Deer overpopulation has
become a social problem, not a biological one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, as the herds grow, the weak and old starve and
the less nimble meet their deaths on the grilles of sport utility
vehicles. Last year, he said, about 20,000 deer were killed by cars
in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Millburn is the first municipality to try moving out its
unwanted deer, and Lund confessed a twinge of doubt over whether it
would succeed, mostly because of basic arithmetic. Whitetail deer,
one of the few species to produce twins and triplets, can replenish
their numbers by 40 percent a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in interviews with nearly two dozen Millburn residents,
most agreed that while far cheaper, hunting was out of the
question. ``I'd rather just deal with the problem than have them
shot,'' said Jennifer Benenson, 40, who recounted the day she had
to stop jogging and halt traffic so a herd of deer could cross busy
Wyoming Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   There were, however, a few dissenters. Lena Einhorn, 41, a
native of Sweden, called the trapping plan absurd, especially since
some of the deer would invariably end up on the menus of
restaurants. ``I guess it's the American way,'' she said. ``Maybe
I'm not so softhearted, but where I come from, deer meat is a
delicacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Plavin, 39, a personal trainer, said she thought the deer
should just be left alone. ``We're the ones destroying their
habitat,'' she said. ``I happen to think they're beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   MacNamara is racing the biological time clock of the does, which
begin to give birth in May. To get a sense of how many have to be
removed, town officials hired a Colorado-based company to survey
the deer population with an infrared camera mounted on a
helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Lewis, the general manager of Hot/Shot Infrared Inspections,
said the counting was not finished, but a census last year by Essex
County recorded 349 deer in the South Mountain Reservation, 2,000
acres of parkland that borders much of Millburn.
</P>
<P>
   Using figures established by state wildlife officials, Millburn
might have to remove two-thirds of the deer to reach a healthy-size
herd. To maintain that number, the process will have to be repeated
every year.
</P>
<P>
   The town has set up portable pens in parks, where deer will be
lured by apples and molasses. Once caught, they will be shipped
off.
</P>
<P>
   And while Millburn is the first municipality in the state to
adopt the deer export program, Essex County, which includes
Millburn, had decided to try the same approach.
</P>
<P>
   The county is planning a deer control campaign that includes
hiring MacNamara and his padded trailer. About $248,000 of the
$260,000 expenditure will pay for construction of a 23-acre deer
paddock in South Mountain Reservation, where deer will be corralled
into smaller enclosures and eventually shipped out of town.
</P>
<P>
   The fenced-in area, it turns out, replaces one that the county
dismantled two decades ago after animal rights advocates fought to
have its occupants set free. Officials say that many of today's
unwanted deer are descended from those freed from the paddock in
1980.
</P>
<P>
   Having just returned from the job of removing a rotting carcass
from someone's yard, Millburn's animal control officer, Danny
Pariso, could barely contain his glee over the prospect of fewer
deer in town.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to collecting the deer killed by cars, Pariso has to
deal with three or four angry calls a day from town residents who
demand that he remove live deer from their backyards. ``I'm tired
of the dead deer,'' he said, ``and I'm tired of the nasty phone
calls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1706EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
