<HEADER>
A0603 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-STOOGES-TV-NYT &LR;      04-18 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOOGES-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE THREE STOOGES AS ALUMNI OF THE SCHOOL OF HARD KNOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Who doesn't know those numskulls Moe, Larry and
Curly? The Three Stooges _ whose pies in the face, punches in the
gut, headlocks, insults and pratfalls have been embedded in popular
culture since the 1930s _ are back.
</P>
<P>
   But this time the Stooges are poignant, even sad. ``The ideas
that comedians have broken hearts, that's in some ways the story''
of the comedy team, said James Frawley, the director of ``The Three
Stooges,'' a two-hour drama to be broadcast Monday night by ABC.
</P>
<P>
   What stamps the movie, which includes re-creations of original
Stooges comedy routines, is the occasional bleakness of its
portrait of the rise of some working-class boys who took their
cheerful violence onto the vaudeville stage in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Their fame and success in Hollywood was extraordinary. They made
nearly 200 shorts for Columbia Pictures in the 1930s, '40s and
early '50s but were so exploited by Harry Cohn, the titan who ran
the studio, as well as their longtime agent, Harry Romm, that they
earned relatively little money for themselves and were left
unemployed in 1958. At one point after that, Moe Howard, the
group's leader, was working as a messenger at the studio, even
though Columbia had earned a fortune off the Three Stooges. (In
their years at the studio they never made more than $20,000 each a
year.)
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, they weren't high art icons,'' said Evan Handler, the
actor who plays Larry Fine in the film. ``But you go up to anyone
anywhere and tell them you're playing one of the Three Stooges, and
they begin to laugh. They had that kind of impact. It's actually a
bittersweet story.''
</P>
<P>
   If the story of the Stooges is hardly as tragic as that of
Marilyn Monroe or Judy Garland, who have been depicted in recent
books as victims of Hollywood as well as their own personal demons,
the new drama is a bleak account of a group of men whose zany
public personae were strikingly different from their troubled
private lives. The account has a somewhat happy ending: in the
early 1960s television rediscovered the Stooges' old movies and a
new group of fans emerged.
</P>
<P>
   With the film, the Stooges seem to have come full circle. Not
only is Stooges merchandising earning steady income for the comics'
heirs, but the act has influenced comedians as varied as Jim
Carrey, Adam Sandler, Steve Martin and Chevy Chase, directors like
Robert Zemeckis and Quentin Tarantino and actors like Mel Gibson,
an ardent fan who has credited some of the humor in his ``Lethal
Weapon'' films to the Stooges. ( Gibson's company, Icon
Productions, produced the Stooges film along with, among others,
Craig Zadan and Neil Meron).
</P>
<P>
   The Stooges film is based on Michael Fleming's book, ``From
Amalgamated Morons to American Icons: The Three Stooges''
(Doubleday, 1999). It was adapted by Janet Roach and Kirk Ellis and
stars Paul Ben-Victor as Moe and Handler as Larry, the two
constants in the Stooge lineup; Michael Chiklis plays Moe's brother
Curly and Jon Kassir is Shemp, their other brother, who preceded
Curly in the act and replaced him after Curly's death. In later
years two other comedians, Joe Besser and then Joe DeRita, became
Stooges. But Moe, Curly and Larry are most fans' favorites.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts the Stooges were troubled men. Curly had an
alcohol problem and fell in love with the wrong women; a series of
strokes cut short his career. Larry was addicted to gambling and
was broke most of his life. Moe, the group leader and the most
stable, was despondent that Columbia had brushed him aside.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Lyne, executive vice president of movies and mini-series
at ABC, said the project began when the producers visited her about
a year ago and said that they had a three-word pitch: the Three
Stooges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so startling,'' Lyne said. ``Frankly, I didn't love the
Three Stooges like other people. I was never a fan as a kid. All I
knew about them were they were guys bopping each other on the head
and flopping their arms. But the story was so moving and
surprising. They were guys who fell in love with the idea of show
biz in the early days of vaudeville and went to Hollywood and never
got their due. And only late in life did they realize the impact
they had. I thought this story was great drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleming, an author and a columnist for Variety, as well as Joan
Howard Maurer, Moe's daughter, said that the financial insecurity
of the Stooges, who grew up in poverty, had been exploited by Cohn,
who ran Columbia, as well as by Romm, the group's talent agent.
Romm had what Fleming called ``a cozy relationship'' with Cohn. The
two men were close friends.
</P>
<P>
   The Stooges ``were always looking for their next jobs,'' Fleming
said. ``When they began making two-reelers, they were grateful. Moe
was the businessman. But he was so nervous about making waves that
he never tested the waters.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurer, who lives in Los Angeles, said: ``My Dad was fearful. He
didn't want to rock the boat. He didn't have the confidence to sit
down with Harry Cohn and say, `We need more money.''' The Stooges
had been signed by Columbia in 1934. By 1958 the studio, giving up
on comedy two-reelers and seeing no future with the trio, declined
to renew their contact.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Benjamin, Curly's stepson and general counsel of C3
Entertainment, which handles Stooges merchandising, said there were
now about 100 Stooges licensees for apparel, toys and candy, which
provides a steady income for their heirs. He declined to say how
much money was involved, but he said that the yearly income from
merchandising ranked with that of such figures as James Dean and
Elvis Presley.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're as good as any classic property in the world, if not
better,'' he said. ``Their property is worth more now than it was
in their lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the way the Stooges were treated, Benjamin said: ``You have
to keep in mind the context of the times. They didn't have
sophisticated lawyers or agents.'' He added: ``They never forgot
the memory of the Depression. It was that generation _ their
attitude was, `I'm lucky to be working.' The sad part was that they
never knew how popular they really were.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtually the entire cast of characters in the saga of the Three
Stooges is dead. Moe Howard, whose original name was Moe Horwitz,
died of lung cancer in 1975 at the age of 78. Larry Fine, born
Larry Feinberg, also died in 1975, after a stroke. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   Curly Howard, originally Jerome Horwitz, died at 48 in 1952
after a series of strokes.
</P>
<P>
   The act appeared in feature films in the 1960s including ``It's
a Mad Mad Mad Mad World,'' in which the had a cameo as firemen. But
they are known almost entirely from their two-reel shorts, which
have been replayed on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Harry Cohn died, my father went to the studio one day
and the guard wouldn't even let him in,'' said Maurer, recalling
Moe's humiliation. ``That was a low point. He didn't want to see
his acting career end. And then the first segment of their old
comedy was released on television. And my father realized the fans
were still there, a new generation. That was the most important
thing to him. The fans were still there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1716EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0604 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-LINGERING-DINERS-NYT     04-18 1475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINGERING-DINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BON APPETIT. AND NOW GET OUT!
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(Dining)  
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now that ``No Smoking'' and ``No Cell Phones'' icons
have become standard signage at New York restaurants, it may be
time for one more admonishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Lingering.''
</P>
<P>
   Daryl Loecher and five of her friends had descended from the
Upper East Side to the East Village for dinner on a recent Saturday
night at one of her favorite restaurants, Il Bagatto, a tiny
bargain on Second Street, between Avenues A and B. The group
arrived five minutes early for an 8:45 P.M. reservation, well aware
of Il Bagatto's policy that diners who arrive more than 10 minutes
late risk losing their table. At 9:05, they were seated. A little
before 11, they were asked to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hostess told us they needed our table,'' Loecher said. ``I
was shocked when she said we'd been given our allotted two hours
for dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   The busboy tried to clear the water and wine glasses, not all of
which were empty, she said. ``Then another hostess walked over and
said, `OK, guys, I gotta ask you to leave. You had your two hours,
now get out.' '' The restaurant serves until 12:45 on Friday and
Saturday. ``I can understand two hours for two people, but six?''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Loecher is not alone. The ups and downs of the stock market
aside, there is still plenty of hungry money out there: demanding
diners and restaurants eager to turn as many tables as possible in
a night. The occasional bum's rush from a white-tablecloth
establishment is not a new phenomenon. But an informal survey
suggests that skirmishes on the contentious border between service
and civility are on the rise. The go-go '00s are no decade for
lingering, especially over dinner. Fortunes are made and lost in
the time it takes to sip a second cappuccino.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Goldman, a director at Newmark &AMP; Co. Real Estate, was
handed his hat in February at Zocalo, an upscale Mexican restaurant
on 82nd Street between Lexington and Third Avenues. The reservation
was at 7, for four. Two of them showed up on time and were seated.
The others, including Goldman, came at 7:35, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within a minute, the appetizer plates were removed and the
entrees were thrown in front of me,'' Goldman recalled. ``A minute
after dishes were removed for the entrees, we were immediately
asked if we wanted dessert. We said we were going to pass on
dessert, but would like a cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The waiter walked away and when he came back said, `I was
instructed to give this to you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It was the bill. Goldman protested, demanding to speak to the
manager. The owner came over and told him she had a 9 p.m. party
waiting for the table. Voices were raised.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant has its own version of those events, needless to
say, but more on that in a minute. Nancy Ross was hastened to an
even speedier exit at Angelo &AMP; Maxie's, the steakhouse on Park
Avenue South. Ross, who works in the garment center, clocked her
8:30 Saturday night dinner at a record 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been quick before, but this was ridiculous,'' she said.
``I don't think we were in the chair yet and the menus were
there.'' Within milliseconds the waiter was back over, she
recalled. ``It was nerve-racking. I predicted the time between
coffee and the check would be 50 seconds. It came in at 40.''
</P>
<P>
   In the annals of untimely ejections, though, it is is hard to
beat the tale of Dr. Richard Stock, an oncologist at Mount Sinai.
It happened two years ago, at the old Daniel, but still makes him
angry thinking about it. Stock and 12 colleagues had a 7:30
reservation and were on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like wines and we were ordering $500 to $600 bottles,'' he
recalled. ``We all had the tasting menu.'' This was probably about
a $6,000 dinner, maybe more, Stock figured, throughout which the
waiter kept informing the group that another party had booked the
table after them. ``I remember them really pressuring us to
leave,'' he said. ``We said we want to order after-dinner drinks _
spending more _ and they just said you can't stay, you've got to
leave.'' It was 9:30.
</P>
<P>
   ``So all of us crammed into the little bar area drinking
Armagnac,'' he said. ``I was so teed off to be treated that way,
especially when we were paying that kind of money.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It is one thing when a restaurant tells you when you make the
reservation that it will need the table by such-and-such a time, as
reservationists often do at Nobu and other coveted restaurants
around town. That is fair warning. What riles people is being
ambushed with the news midmeal. That and any whiff of attitude, as
in ``Don't let the door hit you on the way out.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine dining in New York has always been a more businesslike
transaction than in, say, France. One of the reasons cheese courses
are still a rarity in this city of sophisticated and exacting
palates is that they take too long. As Cello's chef, Laurent
Tourondel, explained, ``It's 30 more minutes at the table.'' He
does it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Smart restaurateurs also avoid accepting 7:30 reservations.
Zarela Martinez, the chef-owner of Zarela, on Second Avenue between
50th and 51st Streets, said, ``The 7:30 table is the one thing that
ruins you. They will stay there till 10 at least. You can't afford
to lose a table like that.''
</P>
<P>
   When the esteemed French chef Alain Ducasse opens his first
American outpost in the Essex House early this summer, he will
adhere to the three-star Michelin requirement of a single seating.
Arrive when you want and own the table for the night. (Paying
dearly for the privilege, one suspects.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is a luxury and a restaurant is a place of luxury,'' said
Ducasse, on the phone from Paris, emphasizing the importance of
``hospitalite'' and `convivialite'' as if they were constitutional
rights inseparable from a three- or four-hour meal. ``We should not
impose time limits,'' he said. Otherwise the restaurant will not be
a place where New Yorkers can find sanctuary from their mortal
enemy: ``le stress.''
</P>
<P>
   New York restaurateurs without Ducasse's deep pockets say that
they can't afford lingerers and that most diners understand this.
Julio Pena, co-owner of Il Bagatto, said he thinks that two hours
is ``plenty of time'' for a party of six to finish dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize that the restaurant has been around five
years and the prices don't change,'' he said. ``The way we make our
money is by turning tables over.'' He says if patrons run over that
time and he needs the table back, he offers to buy them a drink in
the downstairs lounge. But, he said, ``sometimes when you start the
conversation, they just assume you're kicking them out. They get
angry. `How dare you? I spent money here!' I had an argument one
night with people who had finished their dinner and were completely
drunk. I said I'll buy you a drink if you give us the table. They
wanted to start a fight. That's the insanity of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearily, Pena said, ``This business is getting rougher and
rougher.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Shapiro, the owner of Zocalo, said she remembers the
confrontation with Goldman. She said that the restaurant made an
exception in seating an incomplete party and that he was ``aware
the table was rebooked at 9.'' The reason she, and many
restaurateurs, don't seat incomplete parties is that the latecomers
think their allotted two hours for dinner starts when they get
there, and the table is ``lost'' for the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was getting ugly,'' Shapiro said of the dispute with
Goldman. ``The guy was just really really really making it
difficult for everybody involved. I asked him never to come back to
the restaurant again.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Goldman said, ``I've waited at Balthazar, I've
waited at Fressen.'' He's even been asked to get up before, he
said. ``But I've never been asked like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Angelo &AMP; Maxie's did not return calls to explain its
table-turning policy. But Georgette Farkas, a spokeswoman for
Daniel, in both its incarnations, said she was shocked that anyone
would have been asked to leave her restaurant. ``We always allow
three hours for every table,'' she said. ``It sounds like somebody
working in the dining room made a big mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hourglass Tavern, the old Restaurant Row standby in the
Theater District, solved the problem when it opened two decades
ago. There's an hourglass at each table. When the last grain of
sand runs out, so does your eating time. But even with those strict
house rules, the Hourglass is more flexible than some of its
competitors. As Christopher Sideris, the owner, said, ``Yeah, sure,
sometimes we let people go an hour and a half.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1717EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
