<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-FETTISDAGSBULLAR-BUN-     04-18 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FETTISDAGSBULLAR-BUN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S ROUND AND SWEDISH AND NOT A MEATBALL?
</HEADLINE>
 By RICHARD W. LANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The sweet almond- and cream-filled buns called
fettisdagsbullar are uniquely Scandinavian treats that were
traditionally served every Tuesday from Shrove Tuesday in February
until Easter.
</P>
<P>
   Their closest Anglo-Saxon equivalent is the much more modest hot
cross bun, which the English, with their usual reserve, manage to
put off eating until Good Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The distinctive essence of fettisdagsbullar, literally Fat
Tuesday buns, derives from cardamom, almond paste, sugar and
whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   With a bow to our waistlines, my family and I no longer consume
a large dinner and then feast on these delicious buns for dessert.
We simply make a meal of them.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner was never so indulgent.
</P>
<P>
   To make fettisdagsbullar, you cut an upside-down pyramid out of
the top of the baked bun, remove this lid and fill the cavity with
a generous helping of almond paste, followed by a large dollop of
whipped cream. The lid is then perched on top of the whipped cream,
and the whole affair is dusted with powdered sugar.
</P>
<P>
   The buns are great served simply that way, but if you want to
eat them in the truly Swedish manner, place each bun in a deep soup
bowl, pour scalded milk all around it and eat the fettisdagsbullar
with a spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you nibble around the edges to keep the bun from
becoming too soggy or cut right to the almond paste so you get some
with every bite is a matter of personal style. In our family, we're
about equally divided.
</P>
<P>
   SCANDINAVIAN SWEET BUNS (FETTISDAGSBULLAR)
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes plus 2{ hours' resting and rising
</P>
<P>
   1 packet dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   { cup sugar, pinch more for yeast
</P>
<P>
   \ pound (1 stick) butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup light cream, plus more for filling
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons freshly ground cardamom
</P>
<P>
   4 cups sifted unbleached flour
</P>
<P>
   7 ounces almond paste
</P>
<P>
   Whipped cream
</P>
<P>
   Confectioners' sugar.
</P>
<P>
   1. Pour hot water into a large bowl to heat it, then empty it.
Place yeast, \ cup warm water and pinch of sugar in warmed bowl.
</P>
<P>
   2. Melt butter in a small saucepan. Add cream and mix well. Cool
liquid to lukewarm, then add it to yeast mixture and beat in one
egg.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a small bowl, stir salt and cardamom into { cup sugar, and
add to yeast mixture. Gradually add flour, stirring until dough is
firm enough to handle. Knead dough for about 3 minutes, cover with
plastic wrap and let rest 30 minutes in a warm spot.
</P>
<P>
   4. Turn dough onto a lightly floured surface, and knead until
smooth and shiny. Divide into a dozen pieces, and roll each one
into a round bun. Place buns on baking sheet, cover with plastic
wrap, and let rise until doubled, about 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   5. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Beat remaining egg, and brush
buns with it; bake until brown, 10 to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   6. Shred almond paste and mix with a little light cream until it
has the consistency of cream cheese. Cut a triangular shape out of
the top of each bun, then fill bun with almond paste and a dollop
of whipped cream. Place cut-out bun on top, and dust with
confectioners' sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 12 buns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
