<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 23)  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Amistad Prepared For Maiden Voyage &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Amistad, a full-size reproduction of the 129-foot slave
ship, was launched recently in Mystic, Conn., and will make a
series of calls along the East Coast on its maiden voyage in July.
Conceived as an educational device, the Amistad will call New Haven
its home port. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1839, 53 Africans seized control of the Amistad, and tried to
force the Spaniards who had purchased them in Havana to sail them
to their homeland. Instead, they were captured and imprisoned in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   After several trials, they were freed by the Supreme Court in
1841, with the help of former President John Quincy Adams. The 35
survivors returned to Africa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new Amistad was built at Mystic Seaport using many of the
tools and methods of the 19th century. On June 1, it will begin sea
trials before embarking on its maiden voyage to New York. The
138-ton schooner is to join the OpSail 2000 parade of tall ships in
New York Harbor on July 4.
</P>
<P>
   From New York, the Amistad will join other tall ships in New
London on July 11, then head to New Haven on July 15. Events in New
Haven will include a $50-a-ticket reception at the Maritime Center
at Long Wharf on July 14, as well as an interfaith service on the
town green, free concerts and arts and crafts events on July 15. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wherever the Amistad is berthed, docents will be on hand to
answer questions, as will a dockside exhibit describing life for
the captives aboard. The public will be welcome to board the vessel
_ free the first year.
</P>
<P>
   The Amistad is owned and operated by Amistad America, a
nonprofit educational foundation.
</P>
<P>
   For the Amistad's schedule, call (860) 536-6003 and for details
about the New Haven events, (203) 499-2680; other information is at
www.amistadamerica.org and www.mysticseaport.org. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Megan Fulweiler &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, Classic Opera In an Ancient Theater &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From May 25 to June 21, Israel's first International Opera
Festival will take place in the Roman Theater in Caesarea on the
Mediterranean Sea, as part of the annual Israel Festival, which is
primarily held in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The opera festival opens with the first of seven performances of
Puccini's ``Turandot,'' directed by Hugo de Ana of Argentina.
``Elektra'' by Richard Strauss receives its first staging in Israel
on June 14 under the direction of Rina Yerushalmi of Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   Two more performances of ``Elektra'' are scheduled on June 17
and 18. On June 21, the soprano Jessye Norman concludes the
festival with a program titled ``Verdi to Duke Ellington,''
conducted by Asher Fisch.
</P>
<P>
   The Israel Symphony Orchestra will play for all performances,
and the New Israeli Opera Chorus will take part in both opera
productions. Scheduled as soloists are Audrey Stottler as Turandot
and Nicola Martinucci and Vitali Taraschenko alternating as Calaf
in ``Turandot.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jane Johnson and Marilyn Zchau will alternate as Elektra,
with Reinhild Runkel as Klytamnestra, Claudio Otelli as Orest and
Tina Kiberg as Chrysothemis. Tickets are $37 to $80 (at 4.05
shekels to the dollar) from the box office, (972-3) 692-7777.
</P>
<P>
   A new acoustical system for the 2,000-year-old amphitheater is
scheduled to be finished for the festival. Excavations of the
ancient city of Caesarea are continuing near the theater, which is
about a 40-minute drive north of Tel Aviv and about an hour and a
half from Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Israel Information Center, (888) 774-7723, or
www.israel-opera.co.il. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Four Seasons Opening Its First Hotel in Egypt &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Four Seasons Hotels and Resorts is opening its first property in
the Middle East this month, with the date set tentatively for
Wednesday, on the west bank of the Nile in Cairo. The hotel is part
of the First Residence, a complex of luxury apartments and villas,
a shopping mall and a casino just south of al-Gamaa Bridge in Giza,
adjacent to the zoo and botanical gardens.
</P>
<P>
   The Four Seasons says the hotel's 230 rooms measure 474 to 614
square feet; there are also 43 suites, four of which have two
bedrooms. All rooms have large marble bathrooms with deep soaking
tubs and separate showers, and many have views of the Pyramids in
Giza, about 10 miles southwest of the hotel. The business center
will offer translation and secretarial services.
</P>
<P>
   Dining choices include Seasons, an all-day restaurant with a
display kitchen serving Mediterranean cuisine, with African and
Italian touches; the clublike Library Bar, which has a cigar bar; a
tea lounge; a coffee bar, and a poolside grill. There will be
24-hour room service. Adjacent to the outdoor pool is a spa with a
beauty salon, exercise room, massages and skin-care treatments.
</P>
<P>
   The Four Seasons Hotel Cairo at the First Residence is at 36
Nile Street, Giza, Cairo, Egypt 12311; (20-2) 573-1212, fax (20-2)
568-1616. Double rooms normally cost $250 to $330 and suites $490
to $3,400 a night, but till July 31, there is an introductory rate
of $145 a room and a 25 percent discount on suites. Reservations:
(800) 332-3442. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Denver Airport Easing Hunt for Computer Jack &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all airports have pay telephones with credit card readers
or jacks for a laptop computer, but travelers can have trouble
finding an open one. Denver International Airport decided recently
to ease that problem by putting those features on every phone. In a
few weeks, technicians will begin pulling out all of the airport's
800 pay phones and replacing them with 1,000 that will have a card
reader and a data port.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Cannon, an airport spokesman, said that about 10 percent
of the current phones have credit card readers or data ports.
Demand from customers with laptops is especially high, he said,
adding, ``Everybody has an e-mail address.'' The phase-in will take
about a year, he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Adults' Get Younger At Disneyland
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Peter Pan wanted to remain a kid: growing up can be
expensive sooner than one thinks. At Disneyland earlier this month,
10-year-olds became adults _ at least at the ticket window.
</P>
<P>
   The theme park in Anaheim, Calif., now applies its $41 adult
price to visitors 10 and older, down from age 12. Children 3 to 9
still get in for $31.
</P>
<P>
   The reasoning behind the decision is that kids seem to grow up
fast nowadays _ physically, anyway. ``We believe our attractions
are enjoyed by people 10 years and above, based on height
requirements,'' Ray Gomez, a park spokesman, said. ``So the change
was appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The parks at Walt Disney World in Lake Buena Vista, Fla., had
already switched to this pricing scale. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
