<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0610 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DANCE-TECH-REVIEW-NYT     04-18 0313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-TECH-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALLET TECH: THE BEAT GOES ON FOR A HARBINGER OF SPRING
</HEADLINE>
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Ballet Tech Co. presented two works for small
casts to repetitive recorded scores on Friday night at the Joyce
Theater. Both pieces, choreographed by Eliot Feld, appeared to
reflect a belief that as long as a musical beat goes on, dancers
should keep dancing. And Feld was inventive enough to make
relentless movement look interesting. Indeed, he created two types
of relentlessness.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Tuthill was perpetually lyrical in ``Kore,'' a solo to
a chiming score by Steve Reich. In Greek, Kore is another name for
Persephone, the mythological maiden doomed to spend part of the
year in the underworld. But when she returns to earth, she brings
spring.
</P>
<P>
   As an eternal harbinger of spring, Tuthill kept circling the
stage, swaying and curving. She sometimes whirled, but never
fiercely; she sometimes sped forward, but never with anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   She also found time to recline on the floor in statuesque
positions. And when she rose, she was light and bouncy. Tuthill
remained unruffled throughout the demanding solo.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas ``Kore'' showed a preservation of serenity, ``Yo
Shakespeare,'' a male duet, required its dancers to look always
energetic. Nickemil Concepcion and Jason Jordan performed it with
unflagging vitality to a score by Michael Gordon filled with sharp,
driving sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Feld had his men race and leap, often in unison, and grapple as
if wrestling. Although the duet resembled an athletic event, it did
not appear to depict cutthroat competition. Rather, both men seemed
caught up by musical and choreographic rhythms. What this dance had
to do with Shakespeare was unclear. But its choreography crackled.
</P>
<P>
   The program also included repeat performances of ``Consort'' and
``Paper Tiger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
