<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, April 19, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly 2 inches of rain fell in Los Angeles late Monday and on
Tuesday as a powerful Pacific storm swept ashore. Wednesday, this
low pressure area will take aim at the eastern Rockies and Plains,
bringing the risk of severe thunderstorms, heavy rain and snow.
</P>
<P>
   An area of showers will affect parts of the Middle West on
Wednesday morning as humid air from the Gulf of Mexico ascends over
a nearby warm front. Strong thunderstorms will then erupt Wednesday
afternoon near the Missouri River Valley. Winds shifting direction
with increasing altitude will cause a few of the storms to rotate.
These rotating storms, called ``supercells,'' are capable of
spawning tornados.
</P>
<P>
   A cold rain will drench parts of the northern Plains. As the air
further cools on climbing the sloping terrain, heavy snow will fall
in the Black Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Damp weather will linger near the New England coast, while drier
conditions return to the interior Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: CALIFORNIA RAIN
</P>
<P>
   More rain fell in parts of Northern California on Monday than
typically falls during all of April. Sacramento more than doubled
its previous daily rainfall record when 1.48 inches fell. Some
areas near the Sierra had more than 5 inches of rain Sunday and
Monday. Heavy rain will become an increasingly scarce commodity in
California as the jet stream winds that energize storms weaken and
retreat northward. Indeed, the average rainfall in Sacramento for
the months of May through September is less than an inch. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
