<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0619 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-FCC-DEAF-NYT &LR;      04-18 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FCC-DEAF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMERGENCY ANNOUNCEMENTS ON TV MUST BE CLOSED CAPTIONED, FCC SAYS
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Communication Commission has adopted a
rule requiring television broadcasters to accompany any
announcements about emergencies with text messages displayed on the
screen, the better to alert deaf viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The rule is part of a broad plan to make telecommunications and
technology more accessible to Americans with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new rule will be a lifesaver for millions of people in
this country,'' said William E. Kennard, the commission's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 54 million Americans with disabilities, about 27 million
suffer from hearing impairments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is long overdue,'' Kennard said. ``This should have been
done years ago. It is that important to public safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The new rule, which was unanimously approved by the commission,
requires broadcasters to deliver information ``intended to further
the protection of life, health, safety and property'' to viewers
with hearing impairments. Information in such reports would include
details regarding the areas affected by emergencies, evacuation
orders and routes and approved shelters, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard said that the rule would apply to a range of emergencies
including tornadoes, hurricanes, floods, snowstorms and
earthquakes. It would also involve warnings and watches, he said,
for impending changes in weather and community disasters like toxic
spills, widespread power failures and industrial explosions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the FCC ordered broadcasters, cable operators and
satellite distributors to provide closed-captioning technology on
new television programs, with all new programming to feature the
service by 2006. Also under the rule, 75 percent of programs from
before 1998 must offer closed captioning by 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Closed-captioning technology provides information on the screen
in text form, like subtitles, that allow deaf people and those with
hearing loss to watch TV. Unlike subtitles, closed captioning is
encoded data transmitted in the television signal, and provides
details about sound effects and background noise.
</P>
<P>
   A viewer seeking closed captioning must have a decoder. All
televisions made since the early 1990s are capable of carrying
closed captions.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the National Association of Broadcasters did not
return phone calls this week seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1741EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
