<SLUG> BC-CMGI-TVISIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CMGI BUYING $20 MILLION STAKE IN TVISIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CMGI Inc. is pumping $20 million in cash into TVisions Inc., a
company that builds large-scale commercial Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI's venture capital unit, CMGI (at)Ventures, will obtain a
stake of undisclosed size in TVisions. Ralph Folz, chief executive
of TVisions, said the Cambridge, Mass. company will use the extra
cash to open more offices outside the Boston area, beginning with
New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The company will also seek to hire more workers and boost its
marketing and advertising expenditures, in an effort to build up
nationwide name recognition. Folz also said that the deal will
enable TVisions to sell its services to some of the approximately
50 Internet companies in which CMGI (at)Ventures holds a stake.
</P>
<P>
   TVisions now employs 150 people. The company has designed Web
sites for a number of large local customers, including Fidelity
Investments, Staples Inc., and Analog Devices Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys have demonstrated the ability to double annually
from a revenue perspective and to be very profitable along the
way,'' said David Nerrow, general partner with CMGI (at)Ventures,
who will become a member of the TVisions board.
</P>
<P>
   Nerrow declined to give precise figures on TVisions' revenue and
profits, but added: ``We look at this investment as one that's not
nearly as speculative as some other investments CMGI (at)Ventures
might make.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of CMGI, of Andover, Mass., closed up 87.5 cents at
$65.875 Tuesday, on the Nasdaq stock exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0171 </DOCNO>
