<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let lushness of leaves supply garden color that outlasts flowers
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, April 20.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If your nails are black and blue _ black from hard work, blue
from bloom-inducing fertilizers _ it may be time to turn elsewhere
for garden color.
</P>
<P>
   Most plants need a certain amount of sunlight to flower, and if
your yard's mostly shade, you know that's an uphill battle. But
even if you're blessed with sun, many spring- and summer-blooming
perennials perform for only two or three weeks. (Annuals bloom for
months, if you don't mind replacing them every season.)
</P>
<P>
   To compensate, why not emphasize plants that offer colorful
leaves throughout the season?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so important to consider the foliage of plants because,
if you're lucky, your plants will bloom for a few weeks _ not a
whole growing season. You need to think about the leaves,'' said
Mildred Pinnell, horticulturist at the Atlanta Botanical Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Garden centers are brimming with options right now, but as you
shop, remember: Foliage with vibrant color or even just interesting
texture can take the form of trees, shrubs, perennials or annuals _
some that bloom, some that don't.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is combining those plants so that the foliage is
complementary. If color wheels and paint charts leave you dizzy,
think of choosing plants as you would a wardrobe: A purple scarf
looks great against a chartreuse dress, a red jacket can really set
off a yellow shirt.
</P>
<P>
   For summer, one of the quickest means for giving your garden
bold leaf color is tropicals, such as purplish-black elephant's
ears and red-, yellow- and purple-striped cannas.
</P>
<P>
   Among annuals, coleus has become a hot seller in recent years
since growers came out of their greenhouses with varieties that
thrive in sun. And speaking of the tried-and-true, when it comes to
bulbs, you can't beat caladiums, with their variegated red, pink,
white and green foliage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mixing some of these wonderful foliage plants _ with or
without great perennials _ gives you interest all season long,''
said Brad Balsis, manager of Habersham Gardens, an Atlanta
retailer.
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of show, what more do you blooming need?
</P>
<P>
   Resources
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Habersham Gardens, 404-873-2484.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hastings Nature &AMP; Garden Center, 404-869-7447.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Planters Nursery,
</P>
<P>
   404-261-6002.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Park Seed Co., 1-800-845-3369, www.parkseed.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wayside Gardens, 1-800-845-1124, www.waysidegardens.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pike Family Nurseries.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lowe's Home Improvement Warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
