<HEADER>
A0640 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PRESIDENT-SCULPTURE-A     04-18 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDENT-SCULPTURE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING FOR A HOME FOR ALL THE PRESIDENTS' ... BUSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 By KATE MURPHY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Rushing about a cavernous warehouse here, David
Adickes, a sculptor, scrambles up and down ladders putting the
finishing touches on Ulysses S. Grant's necktie and Franklin D.
Roosevelt's ears. He doesn't seem the least worried that six of his
18-foot presidential busts _ he has done one for each president _
sit forlornly atop flatbed trailers on the outskirts of
Williamsburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The polished concrete busts have been barred from a proposed
educational theme park there because Adickes and investors in the
project lack the appropriate permits from the local zoning
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bump, not a barricade,'' said the plaster-speckled
sculptor, who has run into opposition before. A 76-foot statue of
Sam Houston that Adickes created for the city of Huntsville on the
bicentenary of the statesman's birth in 1993 drew a storm of
protest, too, but is now firmly in place.
</P>
<P>
   Now as then, the issue is size. ``Big heads scattered throughout
the woods is not exactly going to have a modest impact on the
landscape,'' said Edwin J. Pease, an architect and adjunct
professor of art at the College of William and Mary at
Williamsburg.
</P>
<P>
   But big is the point, Adickes argues. ``You've got to have that
`wow factor' or no one is going to come see it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the huge, walking-stick-wielding Sam Houston has become
a popular attraction in Huntsville, which had previously been
associated mainly with executions at a nearby state prison.
Adickes, 73, has created oversize sculptures for other sites in
Texas, among them a cello, a banana, a trumpet and a telephone
stationed in front of various office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The heads of the presidents arrived in Williamsburg on March 17,
the same day that York County officials secured an injunction
prohibiting Everett H. Newman III, Adickes' partner in the
so-called Presidents Park project, from unloading them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appear to have had a miscommunication,'' said Newman,
president of FCR Group, a commercial real estate development
company in Williamsburg that is also responsible for the nearby
Water Country U.S.A. amusement park.
</P>
<P>
   Newman said he understood from informal discussions with county
representatives that he could accept delivery of some of the heads
from Texas to show zoning officials as well as potential investors
what they looked like. Informed otherwise, Newman is applying for
permits and searching for an interim place to store the six busts:
Woodrow Wilson, John F. Kennedy, Ronald Reagan, Herbert Hoover,
Martin Van Buren and Thomas Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going through the appropriate channels and hope to have
the park open by October,'' said Newman, who estimates that the
park, on an 11-acre site at the intersection of Interstate 64 and
Route 99, will cost $15.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The response to a mail-in ``Heads or tails?'' survey distributed
by The Virginia Gazette, whose readership primarily consists of
Williamsburg's old guard, was overwhelmingly against the Presidents
Park. But the sculptor is undeterred. ``People were in an uproar
about the Eiffel Tower and Statue of Liberty at first, but they
came around,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Adickes said the idea for Presidents Park came to him four years
ago while he was visiting Mount Rushmore. ``It was so grand and
impressive, but because it was so far away, it lacked a sense of
intimacy,'' he said. Better, he thought, to have busts of all the
presidents, not just four, in a lush landscape that visitors could
walk right through while consulting plaques inscribed with
biographical information.
</P>
<P>
   Adickes said he had spent $500,000 constructing the 41 busts,
which took him four years to create. He expects to recoup his
investment from the $8 fee that he and Newman plan to charge for
admission to the park.
</P>
<P>
   Creating the busts has been a painstaking process. ``People
would say, `Surely you can use the same ears,' but no, they're all
different,'' he said. ``And the neckties vary as well. LBJ wore a
thin tie, Ford wore a big fat one and Bush and Reagan wore ties
that were somewhere in between.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't even ask about cravats and bow ties.
</P>
<P>
   If he took any artistic liberties, Adickes said, he might have
been a little kinder than nature. ``I didn't put all the wrinkles
around Ronald Reagan's neck,'' he said, ``and Bill Clinton's nose
is probably smaller than it really is.'' But over all, he said, his
presidents are physically and historically accurate.
</P>
<P>
   To create the presidents' heads, Adickes first sculptured
life-size clay busts based on photos, paintings, etchings and
images on American currency. ``Gerry Ford was the hardest to
make,'' Adickes said, because he has ``no features that you can
really latch on to.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimating each bust's horizontal gradations in circumference,
Adickes cut Styrofoam into corresponding rings, 10 times human
size, then layered them to get a rough outline of each president.
``It's the same idea as cutting a bell pepper into rings and then
stacking them back together to get the full form,'' Adickes
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Spreading clay and plaster over the Styrofoam, he perfected each
face and covered it with a combination of sheetrock, mud joint
compound and cement. Then he applied a layer of rubber, followed by
plaster. When the plaster set he had his mold, which he filled with
concrete to create the final bust.
</P>
<P>
   If Newman files the necessary papers on time, the fate of
Presidents Park will probably be decided in May. ``We are going to
give it a fair shake,'' said Walter C. Zaremba, chairman of the
York County Board of Supervisors, which has jurisdiction over the
site.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the crowds visiting the heads still perched on
their trailers 10 minutes from Colonial Williamsburg, the park
might be a tourist draw. ``You'll never meet a city or county that
is not interested in furthering its economic development,'' Zaremba
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Adickes is contemplating his next project. ``I'm
thinking of a Cadillac ballet with the cars in tutus bobbing up and
down on hydraulic lifts,'' he said. Location to be announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
