<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0641 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PASSOVER19-COX     04-18 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASSOVER19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An Atlanta delegation is in the former Soviet Union to help Jews
hold a Seder and celebrate their fledgling religious freedom
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Say Passover to Alan Kaplan and his response is more immediate
this year than it's ever been.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about connectedness and family,'' said the
35-year-old Atlantan. ``And that family is worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   That point was driven home to him in a ``chilling'' way last
year when he traveled to Minsk, Belarus, in the former Soviet
Union, to teach Jews there how to celebrate the eight-day spring
holiday of Passover that begins at sundown today.
</P>
<P>
   He and three other members of an Atlanta delegation sponsored by
the Jewish Federation of Greater Atlanta were surprised to find
that most people they met in Belarus had forgotten the meaning of
Passover and knew almost nothing about how to celebrate the
traditional holiday feast called a Seder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at this 78 year-old man, and he's telling me his
last memory of Passover was from his grandfather, when he was 5 or
6,'' Kaplan said. ``A lot of the senior citizens said that.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Atlanta delegation is in Minsk this year to help Jews
conduct a Seder and learn about their faith.
</P>
<P>
   These Atlantans are participating in what has become a
significant effort in recent years to help Russian Jews recover the
practice of their faith. In addition to Atlantans, groups from
Baltimore and Chicago are carrying out a similar mission in other
former Soviet republics this week.
</P>
<P>
   Their zeal to reach out is in response to decades of oppression
that has decimated the practice of Judaism in Russia. Because of
the Holocaust and Soviet discrimination, Jews in much of Eastern
Europe know little, if anything, about Judaism, its traditions and
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional roles of teacher and student relative to
holidays and specifically Passover have become reversed,'' Kaplan
said. ``The adults are learning from the younger generation about
Passover and religion.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's federation team is in Minsk today and the rest of
the week to conduct Seders. A Seder is a ritual meal in which the
story of the Hebrews' Exodus from Egypt 3,000 years ago is told.
</P>
<P>
   ``By us being able to send people over, it's like a modern-day
exodus,'' said the federation's Michael Grossman, 37. ``This is one
way of freeing them from the oppression they've lived under for so
long without any sort of Judaism. And we are helping them rekindle
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta agency picked Minsk because it is trying to develop
a sister city program, Grossman said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Holocaust, 5.8 million Jews lived in the former
Soviet Union, but now no more than 1.5 million do. Since 1972, more
than 1.9 million have immigrated to Israel, and hundreds of
thousands to the United States. Jews began trying to leave Russia
to escape persecution before the turn of the 20th century, when
pogroms were common and young Jewish men were often conscripted
into the Russian army for 25 years or more.
</P>
<P>
   Just last year, 57,720 former Soviets immigrated to Israel and
6,641 to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Blumenthal, an Atlanta attorney who's in Minsk now, plans
to conduct several Seders with help from Jewish college students
fromMinsk and Kiev.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've prepared a Haggada (the story of the Exodus
traditionally read at Passover), one in Russian and one English, so
we can all be on the same page, literally and figuratively,'' she
said. ``We shipped matzo. There'll be various Judaic gifts, a Seder
plate and a kiddish cup. All these will be surprises to the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Each Seder has 15 steps, including a commandment to sip several
cups of a special kosher wine, and to recline on pillows _
something the Hebrews under Pharaoh's thumb were banned from doing.
During the entire holiday, Jews are supposed to eat only unleavened
foods. According to the Torah, the Jewish name for the first five
books of what Christians call the Old Testament, Israelites fled
Egypt in such a hurry they had no time to bake bread. They took
dough and baked it in the desert sun into hard, flat crackers
called matzo.
</P>
<P>
   But Jews in Minsk don't know about matzo, or much else about the
holiday's traditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think many will have ever been to a Seder,''
Blumenthal said. ``We hope they will hold Seders in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Ullner, another Atlanta attorney on this trip, said she
expected a side benefit, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a trip like this can give us all a little bit of
perspective and help us realize how lucky we are,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Gastel was part of last year's Atlanta delegation, and her
thoughts echoed Kaplan's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Jews trying to reacquaint Jews with where they came
from,'' she said. ``I'm sad they don't know as much as what my
parents were able to provide me. Jews need to be over there helping
Jews be Jews. Other religions are over there trying to educate
people, too. It's a mitzvah (a good deed).''
</P>
<P>
   Continuing education is critical, Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized how hungry people were there to identify with their
religion, whether it be Jewish or otherwise, after being prohibited
from religious practice for so long,'' Kaplan said. ``These
missions are worthwhile. But what I got out of it personally was a
greater appreciation and dedication for my own religion.''
</P>
<P>
   What seemed to affect those in Minsk most was the idea that they
were part of a worldwide group in which religious rituals are
similar everywhere and Seders were being performed at the same time
of day around the globe, Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're saying the same Haggada they're looking at, and the
words are identical, except there were two languages,'' he said.
``They were struck that the same rituals were being done all over
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that there's an analogy between the Exodus and
Passover in the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made it clear that Passover represents the release from
bondage, which represents freedom, being free from slavery,'' he
said. ``For them, it's almost a metaphor _ they have been released
from religious slavery. We made that connection, that just like the
Jews who were released from bondage in Egypt, so too were they
released from religious bondage to be able to find their promised
land, or freedom of religion.''
</P>
<P>
   It's traditional during Seders for Jewish kids to ask several
questions of adults, including, ``What makes this night different
from any other night?''
</P>
<P>
   When that question was asked during Seders he conducted, Kaplan
was moved, realizing that in Minsk and much of the former USSR,
thousands of people have never heard it, let alone know the answer.
</P>
<P>
   That, he said, made him realize even more how important his
religion is to him. And starting tonight, he feels sure the holiday
will take on added meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was affected in a very profound way, Jewishly,'' he said.
``What I got in Minsk was a greater appreciation and dedication for
my own religion, which I've always been free to practice, but took
for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something I'll take for granted again.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
