<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0642 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-18 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PROTEST WITHOUT PASSION
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Imitations are never as powerful as the original,
whether we are talking art works or street protests.
</P>
<P>
   This week's odd, disorganized demonstration in the nation's
capital by a motley collection of grubby radicals was aimed at
scaring key global financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The simplistic theory was that big is bad, forget the details.
</P>
<P>
   But the days when student radicals could set our moral agenda
with extremist rhetoric are long gone. The rest of us _ perhaps
including these young people's parents, the original hippies _ have
grown up.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters couldn't even explain coherently why they were
demonstrating. Although they accomplished none of their central
goals, they vow to demonstrate again at the Democratic National
Convention in Los Angeles in August. Why pick on the Democrats and
not the Republicans, you might wonder. If their real quarrel is
with international corporate greed, you would think the
conservative party with its big-business ties would be the more
appropriate target.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not about making sense. This is about making noise.
The protesters have every right to do that, and we have every right
to conclude they are stupid and self-indulgent.
</P>
<P>
   They tied up traffic in the nation's capital, forced employees
to lose a workday and businesses to lose money. Wow, that's power.
</P>
<P>
   Childish theater of the absurd, however, has limited practical
appeal. We have seen it before. We are jaded.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators did not manage to shut down the World Bank and
International Monetary Fund meetings, the principal target of all
the fuss. They did not generate a swell of sympathy across the
nation for youthful rebellion. Repeatedly taunting the capital's
police as ``oppressors'' did not provoke visible oppression. If the
protesters wanted confrontation, they should have tackled New York
City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's out-of-control cops.
</P>
<P>
   The marchers did not rekindle the passions of the late 1960s,
when young people had a real cause worth fighting for _ ending the
Vietnam War in which their peers were dying. If the current
protesters had a message, it was lost in a fog of muddled and
meaningless complaints about international financial policies that
few of them understood.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that the demonstrators are behind the curve. The
World Bank and the IMF have already been under pressure for years
from more responsible sources to reform their worst elitist
practices. Scholars, foreign policy experts and politicians have
complained about secrecy, lack of environmental concern and
inexplicable loans to corrupt, ungovernable countries. Both
institutions have been trying to improve, although it is difficult
to distinguish between public relations and sincere efforts to
change.
</P>
<P>
   While the bureaucrats pay lip service to the idea of waiving the
debt of poor nations, for instance, not much progress has been
made.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody has to pick up that tab. And rich countries
understandably don't want to bail out Uganda or Sierra Leone or a
host of others without a guarantee that somehow the killing and
tribal warfare in those places can be permanently stopped. As
usual, reality trumps idealism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make a difference and have fun,'' an organizer advised a
gathering of demonstrators. But having ``fun'' by trashing the
rights of other, law-abiding citizens is a distortion of our
constitutional right to protest. It wasn't fun, of course, for the
police and inconvenienced local citizens.
</P>
<P>
   A well-timed, chilly rain also reduced the fun for kids used to
their creature comforts, many of whom went home earlier than
organizers planned. So much for the depth of their convictions.
</P>
<P>
   And thanks to careful police preparation, there was none of the
violence or property vandalism that characterized protests during
the World Trade Organization gathering in Seattle last fall.
However many thugs were among the crowd here, they never had the
opportunity to run wild.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters are claiming victory because they called
attention to their concern about worldwide poverty. But just what
was it the world was watching?
</P>
<P>
   Many of these protesters weren't serious. They weren't even
passionate. They were just there, milling around, looking for
trouble _ bored teenagers trying to mimic the folks of the old
days. Why should we listen to them, even if we could figure out
what they were trying to say?
</P>
<P>
   If this view makes me an old fogey, so be it. Old fogies get to
have opinions and vote too.
</P>
<P>
   At least I am smart enough to blame the leaders of poor
countries for their own problems, not the international
institutions that are striving to help them. And what did dumping a
manure pile in the street, as one group did, have to do with
protesting poverty anyway?
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
