<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SHRIMPERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXAS SHRIMPERS ALARMED BY FISHERY WARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Texas commercial shrimpers say they are confused
and alarmed by recent warnings from state officials that the
fishery may collapse unless the harvest is reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just baffled. We haven't supported closing areas in the
past, and we certainly don't support it now,'' Wilma Anderson of
the Texas Shrimp Association, which represents gulf shrimpers, said
from her Port Aransas office Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Moore of San Leon, who represents bay shrimpers, agreed:
``It happens every about five years, and here we are again: The sky
is falling, and the industry is about to collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrimping is always a politically sensitive issue in Texas, and
the latest flap came after Hal Osburn, director of the coastal
fisheries division of the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department,
announced the results of an 18-month study.
</P>
<P>
   The agency found a 30 percent decline in adult spawning shrimp
in the Gulf of Mexico since the 1970s, indicating fewer shrimp are
available to replenish the population.
</P>
<P>
   Osburn warned that the shrimp industry faces ruin if current
trends continue, and he said the agency will consider imposing gear
restrictions, as well as bag and size limits to reduce catches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dealing with 30- to 40-year trends, and we're basically
saying they have to be reversed or we'll get to a very bad point,''
said Osburn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also have around the world a number of examples of shrimp
fisheries that have collapsed: Australia, the Persian Gulf, South
China and Mexico,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A frank exchange of views is expected April 26 when the agency's
Shrimp Advisory Committee meets in Austin, the state capital, to
discuss the proposed rule changes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the invited speakers are representatives of environmental
and recreational groups, which favor reducing shrimping, as well as
commercial shrimpers who say their livelihood is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   The committee will later make a non-binding recommendation to
the Texas Parks &AMP; Wildlife Commission, which makes the rules for
commercial shrimpers.
</P>
<P>
   The shrimp industry has a $500 million impact in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Shrimpers, who have seen their numbers shrink steadily over the
years, say further cutbacks will force more of them out of
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1984, we had over 5,000 boats in this fishery. Now we have
1,200,'' said Moore.
</P>
<P>
   He said shrimp populations rise and fall from year to year,
depending on weather and rainfall, and that there is no statistical
basis for Osburn's claim about a looming crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Moore cited a report in January by a National Marine Fisheries
biologist on populations of commercial species of shrimp harvested
in the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The report by James Nance, chief of fisheries management for the
NMF at Galveston, found that ``none of the four managed species are
currently considered to be overfished or approaching an overfished
condition, nor is overfishing occurring.''
</P>
<P>
   While noting that the catch in Texas has been down slightly
since 1995, Nance concluded that ``environmental conditions were
the dominant factors that influenced the catch in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Contacted Tuesday, Nance said he could not comment on the recent
state study or its conclusions.
</P>
</TEXT>
