<HEADER>
A0659 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-825&AMP;ADD     04-18 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PROPOSES $1.7 BILLION PLAN TO ENCOURAGE LOW-INCOME HOUSING 
</HEADLINE>
  By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, Mich. _ Adding to a series of recent proposals that he
says are designed to give low-income people a firmer purchase on
the American dream, Gov. George W. Bush unveiled a new plan Tuesday
for the federal government to encourage private developers to build
and rehabilitate houses in run-down, struggling neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The incentive would be money: $1.7 billion, over five years, in
tax credits for developers who take on the construction or
reconstruction of houses in neighborhoods where families make no
more than 80 percent of the median family income for that area.
</P>
<P>
   Bush estimated that the new program would facilitate work on as
many as 20,000 houses a year. More important, he said, it would
introduce to an increasing number of Americans the experience of
home ownership, which he described as a fundamental aspiration that
should be more easily attainable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the American dream is owning your own home,'' Bush
said as he stood in front of a newly built house in Battle Creek,
in western Michigan, with its owner, a 67-year-old black woman
named Oberrion Gibson. ``Part of the American dream is saying: This
place is mine.''
</P>
<P>
   In recognition of that, Bush said, he continually asks _ and
tries to answer _ ``How do I help people own? Not just those who
are entrepreneurs or those at the top of the economic ladder. But
how do we help every willing heart, everybody in America, own a
piece of this great land? And I've got some ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   The details of the one he introduced Tuesday, along with the
language and symbols with which he promoted it, adhered to the
pattern that emerged the moment the Texas governor sewed up the
Republican presidential nomination last month.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, in a clear bid for moderate swing voters, Bush has
been tackling issues traditionally dominated by Democrats, pitching
modest programs targeted at low-income Americans, framing these
initiatives as the actions of a new kind of Republican and
stressing the compassion that he links to his conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has also been spending, or at least promoting it, to a
degree that has many political analysts questioning how he can
afford his proposals while also pushing through a suggested tax cut
of $483 billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Gore said Tuesday that the numbers were simply not
adding up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He keeps making promises he can't pay for, because of his
enormous tax give-away for the rich,'' said Doug Hattaway, a
spokesman for the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But former Indianapolis Mayor Stephen Goldsmith, Bush's chief
domestic policy adviser, said that the governor's arithmetic was
sound, in part because of projections for federal surpluses, and in
part because of upcoming proposals Bush will make for ways the
government can save money.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the reforms that we have in mind,'' Goldsmith said, ``all
of this will fit into the budget box.''
</P>
<P>
   The housing plan that Bush outlined also brought into sharper
focus his views on the role of the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Bush does not, for the most part, want the federal government to
provide or administer services directly; he wants to use the tax
code and other financial incentives to make it easier for
low-income Americans to use the private sector to meet their needs.
Last week, for example, Bush proposed tax credits to help
low-income Americans purchase private health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   He also advocated several forms of assistance to help low-income
Americans buy their own houses. He said Tuesday that while those
housing initiatives addressed demand, Tuesday's initiative rounded
out the picture by addressing supply. Taken together, the
initiatives totaled $3.7 billion over five years. The newest
proposal would allow developers to apply for as much as 50 percent
of the cost of their work on certain houses in tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   The houses in question would have to be for people making no
more than 80 percent of the median family income in their area _
nationally, the median is about $51,000 _ and living in
neighborhoods where most residents fall into the same income
bracket.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the plan, which Bush's aides said could contribute
to the building or rehabilitation of 100,000 houses over five
years, would be limited. There are about 1.3 million new houses
built in America each year.
</P>
<P>
   But Goldsmith said that the new housing initiative, like the
others, is a supplement to an array of existing federal housing
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not aiming today to solve the nation's housing
problems,'' he said. ``What we've proposed over the last week is a
bucket of new tools.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign said that the vice president has proposed an
additional $5.7 million of federal assistance, over 10 years, to
help states build 180,000 new apartments or houses, including
rentals, for low-income people. Gore also supports an additional
$690 million over 10 years to help 120,000 low-income families with
housing vouchers to subsidize their rent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bush's initiatives are specifically aimed at home ownership,
which he described as a catalyst for safer streets and better
schools.
</P>
<P>
   As the governor spoke, he stood on the front porch of Gibson's
three-bedroom house, built with the aid of a private program that
gave her a low-interest mortgage. Five of her relatives and
acquaintances, all of them black, flanked the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been dribbling out his latest policies, a strategy
designed to give him something new to say every few days. And he
has been choosing the settings of his remarks with care.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan, with 18 electoral votes, is one of the most important
links in a chain of largely midwestern states that may be the
decisive region in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Bush lost the state's Republican primary to Sen. John McCain of
Arizona, an outcome that both Bush and Michigan Gov. John Engler,
who accompanied Bush from Battle Creek to subsequent campaign stops
in the Detroit suburbs of Dearborn and Troy, joked about Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back to the firewall!'' Engler trumpeted as he walked down the
aisle of the Bush campaign plane, referring facetiously to the
assurances he had given Bush that Michigan would halt McCain's
momentum coming out of the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
