u k BC-EDITORIAL-MIRANDA-BOS     04-18 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MIRANDA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRANDA ON TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You have the right to remain silent and to an attorney _ at
least for now.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, Miranda rights go on trial. The Supreme Court
will hear arguments about whether to overturn Miranda v. Arizona,
the 1966 ruling that confessions can't be used against criminal
defendants unless they are informed of their rights.
</P>
<P>
   Despite loud critics, Miranda rights deserve fierce protection
from the court. Miranda grows out of the Constitution's Fifth
Amendment protection against self-incrimination. And it ensures
that even in the most heinous cases _ namesake Ernesto Miranda was
found guilty of kidnapping and rape _ the law proceeds in a just
and consistent fashion.
</P>
<P>
   To some, Miranda seems like a sop to criminals. Police can't
start an interrogation until they essentially hand over a
get-out-of-jail-free card: the right to remain silent. Dismantle
such absurd protections, the thinking goes, and the police _ as
well as the public _ will have a better fighting chance against
crime.
</P>
<P>
   This sounds like common sense. In the Miranda ruling, however,
the Supreme Court wisely stood against giving government that much
power:
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . our accusatory system of criminal justice demands that
the government seeking to punish an individual produce the evidence
against him by its own independent labors, rather than by the
cruel, simple expedient of compelling it from his own mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   In the bright light of this principle, it's easy to see how
deformed investigations can be, ranging from the Salem witch trials
to modern-day coerced confessions.
</P>
<P>
   The threat to Miranda is a 1968 federal law that says
confessions are admissible as evidence as long as they are
voluntary. Confessors need not be informed of their rights. In
addition to setting off alarm bells about constitutional violations
of the Fifth Amendment, this law has never been enforced by the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   By setting a higher standard, Miranda rights inevitably apply to
society's worst felons, and a few may go free. But every time a
false confession is coerced, an individual's rights are violated _
and the real criminal goes unpunished. Miranda deserves to stay a
part of crime-fighting in America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1847EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0664 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-GEPHARDT-BO     04-18 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-GEPHARDT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENGAGING CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The politics of House minority leader Richard Gephardt's
decision to oppose permanent normal trade relations with China may
be complex or opaque, but the policy question at issue is as
unambiguous as these matters can be. It is in America's interest
for Congress to approve the measure.
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton's trade representative, Charlene
Barshefsky, recently told members of the Globe editorial board, the
vote that Gephardt and his fellow members of Congress will cast
toward the end of May will not grant Beijing entry to the World
Trade Organization or access to American markets. The only question
to be decided by that vote is whether America will be able to
benefit from China's accession to the WTO and from laborious
negotiations that opened Chinese markets to American goods and
services.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules of the WTO, each member must grant every other
member unconditional, permanent normal trading rights.
</P>
<P>
   If Gephardt has his way and the House votes down permanent
normal trading rights for China, America would find itself in the
ludicrous position of having opened Chinese markets to the rest of
the world while becoming the only country with no legal right to
those markets.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt and others say they are wary of Beijing's repressive
behavior, and there is a lot not to like about the house that Mao
built. But China has come a long way since Mao, and a vote against
permanent normal trade relations with China would do nothing to
free advocates of democracy from Chinese prisons, liberate
exploited workers, or alleviate the oppression of Tibetans.
</P>
<P>
   The path to better Chinese behavior lies in engaging China in
the rules of free trade, the WTO, open markets, and the
communications revolution. There are 12 million Internet users in
China today; five years from now that number is expected to grow to
120 million users. Communism has already demonstrated that it is
not fit to survive alongside unfettered communication. Gephardt
should realize that a vote to open China's markets is a vote to
loosen political oppression.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1848EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
