u k BC-EDITORIAL-IRS-BOS &LR;      04-18 0373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-IRS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EVEN HAND AT IRS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service, by auditing proportionally more
returns from low-income filers than from the wealthy, is
threatening its own future. Fairness and the appearance of fairness
are essential to the successful operation of a tax system that is
heavily dependent on voluntary compliance.
</P>
<P>
   The question has been put back on the table by an IRS report
issued last week saying that it had audited 1.36 percent of returns
filed by people making less than $25,000 annually compared with
1.15 percent of those over $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is relatively minor, and the IRS attributed it to
more complete employer reporting of income details by higher-income
taxpayers, coupled with a reduction in allowable deductions from
taxable income.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has contributed to the problem by refusing to provide
adequate funding for IRS personnel to keep up with population
increases and consequent rises in the number of returns filed. That
has spread IRS enforcement personnel ever more thinly, but such
reductions make it even more imperative that, within reason, they
focus on cases where they are apt to generate more revenue. It is
particularly galling to have congressional critics of the tax
system sabotage it by providing inadequate funding for efficient
operation.
</P>
<P>
   There is a fine line between enforcement for its own sake and
enforcement designed to advertise the fact that the IRS is alert to
dodges used by taxpayers to avoid paying their fair share. It is
legitimate on both grounds to examine closely at least a sampling
of returns from all income levels. But it undercuts the sense of
fairness and of even-handedness to focus even slightly more
attention on lower-income taxpayers when many people feel that
higher-income taxpayers get better advice and know more ways to
shelter income from taxation.
</P>
<P>
   The American tax system is one of the best in the world, in
large part because most taxpayers comply voluntarily with its
provisions. Maintaining that record depends on confidence in its
general fairness _ and that deserves very high priority at the IRS
and in Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1850EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0666 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-MUGABE-BOS &LR;      04-18 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MUGABE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESTROYING ZIMBABWE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The African nation of Zimbabwe celebrated its 20th year of
independence Tuesday. After a cruel war against white-ruled
Rhodesia, which had unilaterally and illegally declared
independence from Britain in order to maintain itself in power, an
African guerrilla army prevailed. Rhodesia, which was named for the
arch-imperialist Cecil Rhodes, passed into history, and Zimbabwe,
named for an ancient African civilization, was born in promise and
the spirit of racial reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Today most of Zimbabwe's prosperity and promise have been
squandered. Landless Africans are being incited to racial violence,
white farmers are being murdered in their homes, and African
opposition officials are being killed as well.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation is running at 70 percent, unemployment is approaching
50 percent, and Zimbabwean soldiers are making mischief in
neighboring Congo.
</P>
<P>
   The blame for all this rests squarely on the shoulders of Robert
Mugabe, who, having led his country to victory and freedom, now
clings desperately to power, defying the rule of law, stalling on
elections, and generally contributing to his country's ruin.
</P>
<P>
   In February Mugabe held a referendum designed to keep him in
power and allow him to confiscate white-owned farms without
compensation. The referendum was defeated, but Mugabe rammed it
through his rubber-stamp legislature anyway.
</P>
<P>
   He encouraged squatters to break the law and occupy white farms,
which are vital to the economy, even though Zimbabwe's courts
branded the occupations illegal and ordered the occupiers out.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, hours after a second white farmer had been gunned down
_ his home burned to the ground by squatters _ Mugabe used the
independence day ceremony to tell white farmers: ``Our present
state of mind is that you are our enemies . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   It is a sad twist of history to witness Mugabe, who prevailed
over an illegal and racist authority 20 years ago, fast becoming an
illegal and racist authority himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
