u k BC-EDITORIAL-ELIAN19-COX     04-18 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ELIAN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Doctor's orders: Reunite father, son
 &HT;    (EDs: This is an editorial from Wednesday's Atlanta
Constitution.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _There's nothing equivocal about Dr. Irwin Redlener's
warning that ``Elian Gonzalez is now in a state of imminent danger
to his physical and emotional well-being in a home that I consider
to be psychologically abusive.'' Redlener's opinion, in his
capacity as consultant to Attorney General Janet Reno, ought to
spur the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta to rule
promptly to lift an emergency order preventing Elian's removal from
the home of his Miami relatives so he can be reunited with his
father and they can go back to their Cuban homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Redlener hasn't met face to face with the 6-year-old
shipwreck survivor. However, the New York pediatrician and mental
health specialists recruited by him have interviewed Elian's
great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzales, and the boy's father, Juan Miguel
Gonzales. They also have studied a videotape released to the media
last week by the Miami relatives in which Elian states he doesn't
wish to return to Cuba _ a response Redlener likened to that of a
hostage.
</P>
<P>
   The impression conveyed by Elian's father was ``very open, very
caring.'' As for Elian's great uncle, ``he does love the boy, but
he ... has too many other concerns with the (Cuban exile)
community,'' according to Dr. Lourdes Rigual-Lynch, a New York
psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   Especially damaging to Elian, in Redlener's estimation, are the
unsubstantiated threats to the boy's well-being suggested by his
Miami relatives. The uncle charges the father was abusive to Elian
and his late mother, a claim that's hard to credit since her
mother, Elian's grandmother, wants the boy returned to his father.
And then there's Lazaro's daughter, who has stated Elian will be
tortured if he is returned to Cuba, a ridiculous assertion
considering the heroic status the boy enjoys there.
</P>
<P>
   Reuniting Elian with his father would be consistent with
immigration law and procedure. It observes a centuries-old
precedent that a biological parent has the right to choose where
his child will live unless that parent is disqualified for reasons
of neglect or abuse, an exception that doesn't apply in this case.
The mental health imperative is all the more reason for the 11th
Court of Appeals to expedite Elian's return to his father's arms.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
