A0674 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV23-NYT     04-18 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., April 23)  
 By RAY CORMIER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pop Concerts in Tuscany
</P>
<P>
   Q. We will be in Italy in July and would like to get a schedule
for the popular concert series in Lucca. Can we purchase tickets in
advance?
</P>
<P>
   A. Lucca, about 10 miles north of Pisa in Tuscany, is best known
for the 500-year-old walls encircling it and for being the
birthplace of Puccini. But for the third consecutive summer, it
will be the host to some rock and pop musicians. The first two
years featured such performers as Bob Dylan, Joe Cocker, Elton John
and the Backstreet Boys, with 54,000 people attending the 10
concerts last year.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Summer Festival Lucca 2000 is expected to offer
10 more concerts, from July 7 to 27, in the city's major piazzas.
Not all the concerts have been set, but here is the schedule so
far:
</P>
<P>
   July 11, Alanis Morissette, Piazza Napoleone; July 17, The
Cranberries, Piazza Napoleone; July 18, Buena Vista Social Club,
Piazza Anfiteatro; July 19, Joe Cocker, Piazza Anfiteatro; July 20,
Joan Baez, Piazza Anfiteatro; July 22, Natalie Cole, Piazza
Anfiteatro; and July 26, Bryan Ferry, Piazza Anfiteatro.
</P>
<P>
   The producers, D'Alessandro e Galli, say the concerts start at
9:30 p.m. and go till midnight. Ticket prices have not been set at
this writing, but last year ranged from about $26 to $48, and the
organizers say tickets should again start around $25.
</P>
<P>
   More information and tickets are available by calling (39-0584)
30335, and after May tickets will also be sold at several locations
in the city.
</P>
<P>
   A Czech Spa Town
</P>
<P>
   Q. My parents used to vacation in Carlsbad, now Karlovy Vary,
the Czech Republic, and I would like to retrace their footsteps.
Can you tell me about traveling there and accommodations?
</P>
<P>
   A. Karlovy Vary, about 75 miles west of Prague near the German
border, has been a noted spa for centuries. A hundred years ago,
Karlsbad (its German name) was part of any grand tour of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Under communism, it became a vacation destination not for the
rich but for the workers of the Soviet Union, and much of the
grandeur was hidden. In the last decade, the town has been trying
to regain its former image as a more upscale center of culture and
relaxation. Kamila Jancikova, manager of trade relations for the
Czech Tourist Authority in New York, said, ``There are theater,
cinema and concerts all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   While Karlovy Vary's fortunes remain tied to the dozen warm
springs used ``to take the cure,'' the town is also known for its
annual international film festival, the 35th edition of which is
scheduled July 5 to 15 this year. It also is the host of the 17th
annual international jazz festival, featuring the Scott Hamilton
Quartet, May 21 to 27. There is a golf course, and lots of hiking
in the hills of the Slavkov Forest.
</P>
<P>
   The best place to start planning a trip to Karlovy Vary is the
Czech Tourist Authority, 1109 Madison Ave., New York, N.Y. 10028;
(212) 288-0830, fax (212) 288-0971; the Web site is
www.czechcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   CSA Czech Airlines, (800) 223-2365, flies from Newark to Prague
daily in summer, but only three times a week in winter; daily
flights start June 17. Round-trip fares from Newark to Prague, for
a stay of 7 to 30 days, are $958 to $1,015 from May 28 to June 17,
then rise to $998 to $1,058.
</P>
<P>
   There are no connecting flights to Karlovy Vary from Prague, but
buses make the 2-hour 20-minute trip five times a day, leaving the
Florenc terminal at 9:30 a.m. and 12:30, 3:30, 7:30 and 9:30 p.m.
There are at least four return trips daily. Tickets cost $16 each
way in Prague or around $41 round trip when bought with a Czech
Airlines ticket in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dozens of hotels in Karlovy Vary, the grande dame is
the Grandhotel Pupp, an elegant 299-year-old institution. Its best
rooms were renovated a few years ago and the others are to be
remodeled next year. The rates for its 225 rooms and suites range
from $80 to $240 a person a night, but are higher during festivals
and at holidays. Information and reservations: Grandhotel Pupp
Karlovy Vary, Mirove Namesti 2, 360 91 Karlovy Vary, Czech
Republic; (420-17) 310-9111, fax (420-17) 322-6638, and at
www.pupp.cz.
</P>
<P>
   Another elegant choice is the Hotel Richmond, Slovenska 3, 360
01 Karlovy Vary; (420-17) 322-6326, fax (420-17) 322-2169;
www.richmond.cz. Its 76 rooms have TV and minibars. The rate,
including breakfast, is $38 to $72 a person.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel Dvorak, Nova Louka 11, 360 21 Karlovy Vary, (420-17)
322-4145, fax (420-17) 322-2814, Web site www.hotel-dvorak.cz,
offers 79 air-conditioned rooms, with TV, minibars and hair dryers.
Doubles run about $50 to $75 a person.
</P>
<P>
   Packages at these hotels, like most in the city, include spa
treatments. For information and reservations see
www.travelguide.cz.
</P>
<P>
   Cathedrals and Choirs
</P>
<P>
   Q. We are interested in visiting some of Britain's cathedrals
and hearing their choirs sing at services. Do you know of companies
that offer tours including such opportunities?
</P>
<P>
   A. There seem to be surprisingly few companies with such tours
for individuals, though many arrange group tours for choirs.
Perhaps your best bet is Lord Addison Travel, Post Office Box 307,
Peterborough, N.H. 03458; (800) 326-0170, fax (603) 924-9211;
www.lordaddison.com.
</P>
<P>
   Dana Huntley, the company's president, says that it runs about
60 themed tours a year to Britain and that many visit cathedrals,
where choral evensong can be heard on most nights. An example is
the Kent and 1066 Country Tour, Oct. 5 to 14, which will visit St.
Paul's Cathedral in London and cathedrals in Rochester and
Canterbury. The Wells and the Cotswolds Tour, Oct. 19 to 28, visits
cathedrals in Salisbury and Wells, and churches in Cirencester and
Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   These tours, with air fare from Boston, New York or
Philadelphia, cost $2,770 and $2,780, double occupancy. The
land-only cost is $2,290, and includes full English breakfast and
dinner daily, all admission fees, minibus transportation and
lodging in hotels with local flavor, Huntley said. He added that
his company would customize tours.
</P>
<P>
   If you wish to tour on your own, the brochure Singing in
Cathedrals, published by the Friends of Cathedral Music, lists
music schedules and other information about cathedrals all over
Britain and Ireland. It is available from the British Tourist
Authority, 551 Fifth Ave., New York N.Y. 10176; (800) 462-2748, fax
(212) 986-1188; www.visitbritain.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
