u p BC-POL-TICKER19-COX     04-18 1715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Affordable housing proposal
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush, appealing anew Tuesday to voters who have tended
to support Democrats, proposed a $1.7 billion program to increase
housing for low-income people. It would give a tax credit up to 50
percent to developers to refurbish existing houses. Bush was
campaigning in Michigan, where he lost the Republican primary to
John McCain in February. He made his proposal outside the house of
Oberrion Gibson in Battle Creek, who had lived there for 34 years
before tearing down her old home and rebuilding with low-interest
financing provided by a neighborhood development group.
</P>
<P>
   RACE TIGHTENS IN MICHIGAN
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is in a tight race with Al Gore in Michigan,
according to a survey of likely voters released by Epic/MRA Inc., a
polling company in Lansing. The poll showed Bush with a 43 percent
to 42 percent edge. In December the same poll had Bush up 52
percent to 38 percent, said Edward Sarpolus, vice president of
Epic/MRA. The poll's margin of error is 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS ALSO DIFFICULT FOR ANOTHER REASON
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan holds rallies Tuesday night in Irving, Texas, and
today in Houston as the Buchanan Brigade opens a three-week battle
to get the Reform Party candidate on the November ballot in Texas.
Calling it the ``toughest state in the nation'' for an independent
or third-party candidate, Buchanan is mustering volunteers, hired
guns and campaign staff to gather 56,000 petition signatures by May
8. Texas is difficult because of the large number of signatures
required and little time to circulate petitions. Only the
signatures of registered voters who did not vote in a party primary
or sign any other ballot-access petition are valid.
</P>
<P>
   SECOND CHANCE ON FLAG ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   John McCain will fly this morning to Columbia, S.C., where he
will attempt to mend his one campaign regret by condemning the
Confederate flag flying atop the state Capitol. In what he is
calling a ``speech on conservative reform,'' McCain will speak at
noon at a South Carolina restaurant, alongside Rep. Lindsey Graham,
R-S.C., one of his chief backers in the state. The online magazine
Salon reports that McCain will support a compromise bill passed
last week by the state Senate that would move the flag from atop
the Capitol dome to a Confederate soldiers' memorial on state
grounds. During the primary campaign, McCain took the same position
as George W. Bush, saying only that the decision was best left up
to the people.
</P>
<P>
   GORE TESTED IN JERSEY MARSH
</P>
<P>
   With Earth Day fast approaching, Cox News Service's Scott
Shepard reports that Al Gore is facing a situation that could test
his environmental credentials. The Mills Corp. of Virginia, whose
executives and associates have given $43,000 to Gore's presidential
campaign, want to develop a shopping center on 90 acres of wetlands
in New Jersey's Meadowlands. But the mall project is opposed by
Robert F. Kennedy Jr., a prominent environmentalist who has
endorsed Gore as ``the strongest environmentalist running for the
White House since Teddy Roosevelt.'' The Meadowlands Mills project
has thus become a possible litmus test for Gore's environmental
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   WHISTLEBLOWER SUIT NAMES BUSH
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has been named a defendant in a lawsuit by the
fired head of the Texas Funeral Service Commission. She accuses him
of conspiring to impede a 1998 investigation of a company that had
given him campaign contributions. Eliza May says she lost her job
over an investigation of Houston-based Service Corporation
International. She filed her wrongful termination lawsuit last year
and has amended it to include Bush. The company, one of the world's
largest funeral home and cemetery operators, is headed by Bush
family friend Robert Waltrip, who contributed $45,000 to Bush's
gubernatorial campaigns, according to the lawsuit. Waltrip also has
been a trustee for the George H.W. Bush Presidential Library in
College Station and donated more than $100,000 through his company
toward construction.
</P>
<P>
   WITH WIFE LIDDY OUT, TOO, WHO'S LEFT?
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush won the public endorsement of 1996 GOP
presidential nominee Bob Dole, who made the announcement during an
MSNBC talk show. ``I endorse George Bush,'' Dole said, adding, ``I
think he is coming back to the (political) middle, which I think is
very important.'' Dole, whose wife Elizabeth dropped out of the
presidential race early on, had kept quiet during the primaries.
Since then, though, he's been playing liaison between Bush and John
McCain, a close Dole friend.
</P>
<P>
   THE GAP'S BACK _ AND WE DON'T MEAN KHAKIS
</P>
<P>
   The gender gap, in hibernation earlier in the presidential
campaign, is back and reportedly as big as ever. An ABC News
analysis found that the gap is not directly caused by differing
opinions between the sexes on specific issues or by demographic
differences. Instead, according to ABC: greater support among women
for a larger, more activist government; and a broad sense that the
Democratic Party is better attuned in general to the concerns of
women. The 2000 gender gap was minimal last fall, but has grown
considerably since then. In an ABC News-Washington Post poll last
week, Al Gore led among women by 10 points, while George W. Bush
led among men by the same amount _ a 20-point gap. Four years ago,
the gender gap was put at 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH REPORTS $1.3 MILLION INCOME
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush earned an estimated $1.3 million last year and
paid $514,000 in taxes, according to his campaign. He and wife
Laura donated $210,000 to churches and charities, including the
$130,000 in royalties from Bush's autobiography, ``A Charge to
Keep.'' Royalties from the book were earmarked for scouting and
other groups working with youth. Bush's income includes his
$115,345 salary as governor, and investment income from blind
trusts. Last week, Al and Tipper Gore disclosed paying $59,178 in
1999 income taxes on adjusted gross income of $240,792.
</P>
<P>
   VENTURA PRESSES, BUT MCCAIN SLIPS AWAY
</P>
<P>
   Meeting for the first time, Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura pressed
John McCain to resume his presidential campaign, but as an
independent. But McCain went into the meeting saying that no one _
not even Ventura _ could entice him to make such a move. ``I will
not leave the Republican Party,'' he said during a news conference
at the Mall of America before meeting Ventura. ``The Republican
Party is my home. Ventura, who's said he's unlikely to endorse Al
Gore or George W. Bush, repeated his sentiment that McCain could
win as an independent.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK MINISTERS FOR CORZINE
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen leading inner city black clerics in New Jersey
endorsed former Goldman Sachs CEO Jon Corzine for governor, calling
him the ``genuine hope'' for African-Americans. ``Jon Corzine has
given us every reason to believe that he is genuine,'' said the
Rev. Reginald Jackson in the Bergen Record. Jackson cited Corzine's
``promises to support affirmative action, oppose the death penalty,
lower public school class size, and bring about universal health
care and universal gun registration.'' Corzine is facing former
Gov. Jim Florio in the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   DREAMWORKS TRIO PLANNING A BREAK
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood heavyweights Steven Spielberg, David Geffen and
Jeffrey Katzenberg, whose largess has swollen Democratic campaign
treasuries for years, will take a break from fund-raising after the
November presidential election. The the DreamWorks SKG studio
founders have been among the Democrats' most reliable funding
sources, regularly tapping their own bank accounts, as well as
twisting the arms of wealthy Hollywood colleagues. But DreamWorks
spokesman Andy Spahn says the trio plans to take a break after
working fervently this fall for Al Gore's election. During the
Clinton years, Spahn said, Dreamworks has probably raised more
money than anyone in the nation for Democratic candidates. A
Beverly Hills benefit held just last Saturday night brought in $2.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   `DOT-COM' VS. `DOT-ORG'
</P>
<P>
   At least a half-dozen for-profit political Internet sites are
now online, offering much the same blend of in-depth political
information as well as hot links to political and governmental
institutions. Cox News Service's Andrew J. Glass reported that
non-profit political Internet sites are warning that competing
commercial sites are threatening their existence, and that those
sites can expose citizens to special interests seeking to influence
voters and shape legislation. But defenders of the ``dot-com''
sites told a meeting of the Democracy Online Project that they were
merely increasing access to neutral political information, and
fears of the ``dot-orgs'' were unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   SEPARATION OF JUDGES AND CANDIDATE SPOUSES
</P>
<P>
   One for the political etiquette books: If you're a judge, and
your spouse is running for office, you should stay pretty well out
of the campaign _ even if you work in different states. Such was
the advisory from the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court for
Roanne Sragow, a Massachusetts District Court judge whose husband,
Richard Licht, is a Democrat running for the U.S. Senate in Rhode
Island. The opinion means that Sragow will not attend most campaign
events, and Licht told The New York Times that his wife would not
even attend his official campaign kick-off.
</P>
<P>
   BUT YOU DON'T GET TO ENDORSE AS A TICKET YET
</P>
<P>
   The head of John McCain's campaign in Michigan endorsed George
W. Bush _ and called for McCain to become Bush's running mate.
``George Bush is going to be the nominee, and it's time all
Republicans close ranks behind him,'' said state Sen. John Schwarz.
``I worked very hard for John McCain ... (the best thing) which
could happen now is Governor Bush would choose John McCain as his
running mate. And I wish Senator McCain would accept.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from Cox staff and wire reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
