<SLUG> BC-ROCKCITY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    See Rock City the dot-com way
 &HT;    By Howard Pousner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The See Rock City roadside barn, an American
advertising icon dating to the 1930s, is getting a new message fit
for a new millennium: www.seerockcity.com.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the first of what will be dozens of barn roofs was
painted with the attraction's Web address at the base of Lookout
Mountain in Wildwood, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tragedy of the Web world is people create great sites but
don't do a very good job of promoting them,'' says Rock City
marketing director Jim Gilliland.
</P>
<P>
   Rock City has always known something about selling. At its
roof-painting peak, more than 900 barns in 19 states sported the
``See Rock City'' slogan. Today, only about 80 barns remain, and
Gilliland expects at least half of them to be updated with the
digital message in the next 18 months, along with some new ones.
</P>
<P>
   The Web address is being painted in the standard white letters
on a black background _ and split onto three lines, with
SeeRockCity, in a bow to tradition, alone on the middle one.
</P>
<P>
   But some things don't change. Gilliland reports that while the
first www.seerockcity.com roof was being done, several neighboring
farmers approached Rock City officials and asked if their barns
could be painted, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
