<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0681 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0419-COX     04-18 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0419-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHILD EXPERTS BATTLE AMIDST THE WAR OVER ELIAN
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ With a crucial court ruling still pending, the war of
words over 6-year-old Cuban rafter Elian Gonzalez boiled over
Tuesday as child experts on both sides of the bitter custody battle
exchanged heated accusations over the boy's treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the child has been extremely manipulated,'' said Dr.
Irwin Redlener, a pediatrician appointed by Attorney General Janet
Reno to advise the government on how best to transfer Elian to his
father. ``In fact, it's almost like a hostage situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Redlener made the comments to reporters Tuesday, a day after he
sent a letter to Reno calling for the government to remove Elian
from the home of his Miami relatives immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elian Gonzalez is now in a state of imminent danger to his
physical and emotional well-being in a home that I consider to be
psychologically abusive,'' Redlener wrote in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Redlener said his fears were based on the tense atmosphere
surrounding the home, where protesters have massed for weeks in a
round-the-clock vigil, and a controversial home video released by
the Miami relatives in which Elian told his father he doesn't want
to go back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, the boy's Miami supporters blasted Redlener in a
news conference held outside the Little Havana home.
</P>
<P>
   Such comments ``should not be made by people thousands or
hundreds of miles away, who have not even had telephone contact
with any of the parties involved,'' said Dr. Jose Carro(cq), head
of a local association of Cuban exile pediatricians.
</P>
<P>
   Carro noted that during a visit to Miami last week to meet with
the family, Redlener and two other child experts appointed by Reno
never met individually with Elian, and spent only about an hour
with his great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   The volley of accusations came as all sides in the
four-month-old drama awaited a key ruling from the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the court granted the Miami family's request for a
temporary ban on removing Elian from the United States. The family
then asked the court to extend the ban until it hears an appeal of
a lawsuit stemming from the case, which is scheduled for a May 11
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyers asked the court to instead order
Elian reunited with his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who has been
living in the Washington, D.C. area at the home of a top Cuban
diplomat since April 6. Gonzalez has promised to remain in the U.S.
pending the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But Reno insists the boy will be reunited with his father no
matter how the court rules, and legal experts say she has the legal
authority to order the boy turned over.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez has said he will not block federal officers from
taking the boy, but that they will have to come to his home to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   That sets the stage for a tense showdown between federal
officers and the throngs of Cuban exile protesters. Last week
thousands jammed the neighborhood of modest homes when Reno's
initial deadline for handing over the boy approached, but the
situation lapsed into calm after the Atlanta court issued its
temporary order.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's exiles also blasted the media Tuesday, saying they have
been unfairly portrayed in reports as extremists bent on violent
protest. They also charged that officials from the Cuban Interests
Section in Washington scuffled with protesters last week, injuring
several people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our city, our people...and particularly Cuban-Americans have
been slandered and libeled,'' said Miami Mayor Joe Carollo, who
traveled to Washington Tuesday to protest the incident. ``These
diplomatic thugs make the Sopranos seem like the Vienna Boy's
Choir,'' he said, referring to the popular television program about
the American Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban-American representatives in Congress sent letters to the
State Department to complain about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Fernandez, a spokesman for the Cuban Interests Section,
said Cuban diplomats would file their own protest with the State
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are hostile elements that are disrupting the normal
functions of the Cuban Interests Section,'' Fernandez said, while
declining to comment on the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, the Miami Herald reported that state and local
agencies _ police, fire and emergency rescue teams _ have spent
about $1 million on the standoff, mostly on overtime. The total
includes their actions in January when the initial federal order to
return Elian to his father prompted disturbances that led to more
than 100 arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the cost has been borne by the City of Miami, which
teetered on the brink of bankruptcy in 1996 due to poor fiscal
management and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Carollo blamed the expenditures on federal actions in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not our doing,'' he said. ``This is the doing of
federal policies. All we're doing is what local law enforcement has
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   (Cox News Service Writers Sue Schultz contributed to this
report).
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams can be reached by e-mail at:
mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
