<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-KILLING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND WHITE FARMER SLAIN IN ZIMBABWE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ There were no military parades, no soccer games
or other public commemorations.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Zimbabwe marked the 20th anniversary of its
independence Tuesday with the death of a second white farmer and
the reported abduction of a third.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades after the Union Jack slid down the mast for the last
time and Robert Mugabe swore to be faithful to the laws of his new
country, Zimbabwe lies in a state of economic and political turmoil
created, observers say, by its beleaguered president. Mugabe
announced last week that his government would forgo national
celebrations and devote funds saved on traditional dances and
fireworks to flood victims in the southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Little in the country felt festive Tuesday, and Mugabe was
clearly preoccupied more with present concerns than historical
milestones. In a pretaped televised address to the nation, the
president called white farmers ``enemies of Zimbabwe'' for blocking
urgent land reform measures and refused to call off violent attacks
against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we reject is the persistence of vestigial attitudes from
the Rhodesian yesteryears _ attitudes of master race, master color,
master owner, and master employer,'' he said, referring to whites
by their former colonial identity. Land reform ``is the last
colonial question heavily qualifying our sovereignty. We are
determined to resolve it once and for all.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe's political crisis started two months ago after voters
rejected Mugabe's attempt to introduce a new constitution. Put to a
national referendum, the draft would have increased presidential
powers and allowed the government to seize white-owned farms
without compensation. The day after its defeat, Mugabe's
supporters, led by veterans of the liberation war and funded by the
government, began invading commercial farms.
</P>
<P>
   The president has repeatedly defended the increasingly violent
attacks, blaming white Zimbabweans and the British government for
obstructing land reform and leading the campaign to kill his draft
constitution. The war against Rhodesia was fought over land, but 20
years later, most of the best agricultural tracts are still owned
by a handful of white farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Government critics say the invasions are merely a political ploy
to shift attention from the crumbling economy ahead of
parliamentary elections that pose the first real challenge to
Mugabe's rule since 1980. While the president pursues a costly war
in the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Zimbabweans face long
lines at gas stations, rising food prices, and soaring
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   The Movement for Democratic Change, a new opposition party,
enjoys broad-based support among 68 percent of voters, according to
a recent Gallup survey.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe, who returned from Cuba on Sunday, has met over the past
two days with war veterans and commercial farmers. ``We can
understand the frustrations of the war veterans, just as we
appreciate the pressures faced by the commercial farmers,'' he said
Tuesday. ``We should be able to find a way forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the statements, Mugabe has so far refused to call off
the farm invasions.
</P>
<P>
   But the two sides have divergent demands, observers say, and it
is unlikely that Mugabe can close the divide without giving away
his trump card. The farmers want an immediate end to the invasions
and an inclusive approach to land reform. The veterans want land
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no backing down,'' said Gomba Komba, a war veteran
helping to orchestrate the invasions around Harare, the capital.
``We will not go into the elections without a full resolution on
the land question.''
</P>
<P>
   As day broke Tuesday, an angry mob attacked Martin Olds's farm
in Nyamandhlovu, near the southern city of Bulawayo. Olds called a
neighbor shortly after being badly beaten and shot. By the time an
ambulance broke through the crowd and reached his house, the cattle
rancher was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Olds was the second farmer to be killed since the invasions
started in February. On Saturday, David Stevens was hauled off his
land, beaten repeatedly, and fatally shot north of Harare.
Political violence has also claimed the lives of at least two
senior members of the opposition and injured dozens more.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night another farmer, Kevin Tinker, was abducted by a
group of men and held for a few hours before being released,
Reuters quoted a colleague of his as saying. ``He was intensely
interrogated for a couple of hours by the vets and then released
unharmed,'' the colleague said.
</P>
</TEXT>
