<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0686 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DOW-MAIN19-COX     04-18 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-MAIN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It was not sweet, but the market's fall may have been short
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The lure of corporate profits and bargain-basement
share prices apparently is bringing the worst stock market sell-off
in more than a decade to an early conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's over is still a matter of debate among analysts.
But given the bizarre nature of this market on the downside,
analysts see no reason to think the upside won't be just as
strange.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Nasdaq composite set its second straight one-day
point gain record on Tuesday, breaking Monday's mark.
</P>
<P>
   The din from last week's volatile sell-off had drowned out the
noise of an upbeat outlook for first-quarter profits, which
strategists had expected would rally the market. Those expectations
have proven out this week instead.
</P>
<P>
   First Call/Thomson Financial, which tracks earnings forecasts,
said in its latest report that per share profits of Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 companies should grow ``at least'' 22 percent year over
year, making it the third straight quarter of growth near or better
than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, scheduled to report earnings today, helped lead
stocks upward Tuesday. Intel and America Online, which reported
after the exchanges closed, also rose.
</P>
<P>
   Share price winners among blue chips included General Electric,
Johnson &AMP; Johnson and J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson-Humphrey senior strategist Robert S. Robbins, declaring
the recent sell-off ``an attractive buying opportunity for
investors,'' gave the market a more bullish rating on Tuesday. He
also recommended that investors trim their cash holdings by 5
percent and replace it with stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a great time for people who have above average
cash reserves _ some people do out there _ to put that to work and
reduce cash to the 5 percent or 10 percent level,'' said Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   Similar advice from Wall Street analysts and public officials
during the weekend was credited for helping to rally the market
after Friday's record sell-off _ and ease widespread fears of
another 1987-style Black Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The crash on Oct. 19, 1987, was the worst in stock market
history. The Dow fell almost 23 percent in a Monday session that
followed a three-day decline of almost 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But that's where the parallels ended, as investors this time
returned especially to quality stocks in both technology and ``old
economy'' sectors of the market.
</P>
<P>
   The buying propelled major stock averages to their second
straight advance: the recently savaged Nasdaq composite by 7.2
percent, the blue chip Dow Jones industrial average by 1.8 percent,
the broader S&AMP;P 500 by 2.9 percent and the small-stock Russell 2000
by 5.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's two-day gain of 14.8 percent more than wiped out
Friday's 9.7 percent loss that climaxed the worst week in the
Nasdaq market's history.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some analysts are still cautious near-term.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch analyst Phil Rettew told CNBC that a sustainable
rally will probably take ``a minimum of four weeks'' to develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many more times than not, what you get is a bounce and then
another pullback,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
