<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0689 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ECONOMY-HOUSING-BOS &LR;      04-18 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-HOUSING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HOUSING TAKES SHARP DIP IN MARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The government said Tuesday that new housing
construction fell in March by its sharpest rate in six years, a
signal to some analysts that US economic growth is slowing from its
torrid pace.
</P>
<P>
   Housing starts declined 11.2 percent from February to a
seasonally adjusted 1.6 million, the Commerce Department said. It
was the steepest one-month drop since January 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Housing construction is a bellwether of future economic
activity, economists say, as new homebuyers are likely to purchase
big-ticket items like furniture and appliances.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were divided on whether the report truly showed that
economic growth is moderating. But they agreed that housing
construction, and the broader economy, remain so robust that the
Federal Reserve is certain to raise interest rates in May. It would
be the Fed's fifth rate hike since June.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Ayers, chief economist at FleetBoston Financial Corp.,
said a housing construction slowdown in fact is taking place. He
said the cause was previous Fed interest rate hikes, which had
goosed up mortgage rates by about a percentage point in the past
year. A 30-year fixed mortgage now goes for about 8.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, Cynthia Latta, an economist with Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI,
noted that the construction figure had fallen almost entirely
because of a slowdown in new multifamily housing, such as apartment
buildings. Those projects are planned far in advance and require
multiple government approvals, so they are not a good indicator of
recent economic conditions, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The better indicator, she said, is construction starts of
single-family homes, which rose 0.2 percent in March. That figure
suggests that economic growth is not slowing. ``Rising mortgage
rates have not rationed very many people out of the market,'' Latta
said.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, analysts were drawn to Tuesday's housing report
because of what it says about how prosperous people feel.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan has long been worried
about the ``wealth effect,'' or the extra consumer spending that
comes when people feel wealthy. When stock prices rise faster than
household income, he told Congress in February, people are prompted
to spend money at dangerous rates.
</P>
<P>
   The danger comes because consumers have ``additional purchasing
power for which no additional goods have been produced,'' Greenspan
said. In other words, demand for goods and services outstrips
supply, which leads to inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The housing market is a good mirror for the strength of the
wealth effect. ``Mainly because of higher stock prices, people are
not only buying washing machines and furniture, but it spills into
housing activity,'' said David Jones, chief economist with Aubrey
G. Lanston, a New York investment firm. ``Stock prices have caused
people to put on a new kitchen, build new rooms, buy second
homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones read the housing report to mean that housing activity is
slowing, though construction is still brisk. ``What that says is
that if you're making monetary policy, there's still a way to go,''
he said. ``The Fed still has to hike rates some more'' so that
economic growth slows to a sustainable rate, rather than crashing
all at once.
</P>
<P>
   Ayers said that the housing sector itself is a cause of the
wealth effect, as the net worth of many families is tied more to
the price of their home than to stocks. When housing activity is
high and home prices rise, homeowners feel wealthy and take out
equity loans or second mortgages to spend that wealth, Ayers said.
</P>
<P>
   In Ayer's view, new housing construction is slowing, which he
sees as a healthy sign for the economy. ``Most people think that
wealth creation is good, and in general it is,'' he said. ``But
when you get rapid wealth creation that fuels spending faster than
short term production gains, that's a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Further evidence of a housing slowdown came Monday, when the
National Association of Home Builders reported that its market
index rose to 62 in April from 61 in March, which had been a
two-year low.
</P>
<P>
   The index is derived from a survey of home builders, who are
asked to rate the pace of home sales and of the traffic of
perspective buyers seeking homes. Jones called it a ``very
important'' index.
</P>
<P>
   Ayers, Latta and Jones all said that Fed policymakers were sure
to raise short-term interest rates by one-quarter of a point at
their May meeting. Ayers and Latta predicted that another
quarter-point hike would come in June, after which the Fed would
hold off on further increases.
</P>
<P>
   Two quarter-point hikes would take the federal funds rate to 6.5
percent -- the highest it has been since early 1991. That was a far
different time than today. Then, the Fed was in the process of
lowering rates to help nudge the economy out of a recession, which
had been compounded by the savings and loan crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
