<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, April 23,
2000. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHERE-THE-HEART-IS-FILM (Undated) _ People don't get much more
alone in the world than Novalee Nation in the early scenes of
``Where the Heart Is.'' She's 17, very pregnant and even barefoot _
since her shoes fell through a huge hole in the car floor somewhere
between Tennessee and Oklahoma. On the drive from her trailer-park
home to a new life in California, she makes the mistake of asking
her boyfriend to stop at a Wal-Mart so she can go to the bathroom.
When she returns to the parking lot, he and the car are gone.
Novalee (Natalie Portman, looking radiant but very un-Queen
Amidala-like) does the only thing she can think of, since she
doesn't know a soul in Sequoyah, Okla. She goes back into the
store, and when it closes for the night (while she's in the ladies'
room) she just stays. Thanks to the camping, patio furniture and
exercise equipment departments and shelves full of magazines and
working alarm clocks, she's quite comfortable for six weeks. After
she goes into labor there she's a local celebrity, and little by
little she builds a life in Sequoyah, with the usual ups and downs,
weddings and funerals, kidnappings and tornados. Directed by Matt
Williams, ``Where the Heart Is,'' opens on Friday. By Anita Gates. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POPULAR-CULTURE-FILMS (Undated) _ What do we really talk about
with our friends when we're not discussing the vicissitudes of our
personal lives? Why, popular culture, of course! Much of the
conversational glue that binds us together comes from the stuff
that wafts off television, movie and computer screens, from our
stereo speakers and headsets. But go to almost any Hollywood movie,
and you'll find a strange absence on screen of palaver about
recordings, movies, television shows and popular fiction. That's
one reason that when a film comes along that acknowledges the
passions millions of us harbor about favorite works of popular art,
it can strike a deep chord of recognition. Two of the best American
movies released this year _ ``American Psycho'' and ``High
Fidelity'' _ show a bone-deep understanding of how much of our
emotional energy is invested in the consumption of popular culture.
By Stephen Holden. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LISA-KRUEGER-FILMS (Los Angeles) _ The writer and director Lisa
Krueger, 39, has made only two movies, but the longing for
structure is a central theme in both. Indeed, some of the most
touching moments in her 1996 indie debut ``Manny and Lo'' involve
watching how the lives of two underage orphan runaways (Scarlett
Johannsen and Aleska Palladino) are enriched when they kidnap a
discipline-driven woman (Mary Kay Place) and the three become a
makeshift family. As for Joline (Heather Graham), the nightclub
manager heroine of Ms. Krueger's latest film, ``Committed''
(opening Friday), she finds comfort in structure, too. But her
quest _ to save an unraveling marriage by hunting down her wayward
photojournalist husband, Carl (Luke Wilson) _ comes at the expense
of her happiness and, eventually, her own sanity. By Margy
Rochlin. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BIG-KAHUNA-FILM (Undated) _ Last winter, the cast and crew of
``The Big Kahuna'' filmed a feature in the time some people spend
on a beach vacation. Made in Manhattan in just 16 days, stars Kevin
Spacey and Danny DeVito. Adapted by Roger Rueff from his play
``Hospitality Suite,'' the 90-minute film, directed by John
Swanbeck, opens on Friday. It throws three businessmen into one
claustrophobic hotel room and, with a large dose of humor, forces
them to hash out issues of religion, principle and morality. By Ted
Loos. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOUND-FOR-GLORY-VIDEO (Undated) _ Hal Ashby's 1976 film
biography of the militant singer-composer Woody Guthrie, ``Bound
for Glory,'' misses critics' four-star ranking by a fraction, which
isn't bad for a film with some weaknesses to go along with its
considerable strengths. Ashby, who died at age 59 in 1988 and whose
credits include ``Harold and Maude'' (1971), ``Shampoo'' (1975) and
``Being There'' (1979), had a feeling for quirky characters.
``Bound for Glory'' (MGM, 146 minutes, $24.98, PG) is one of those
old movies that gets a substantial second wind from the clarity of
DVD. By PETER M. NICHOLS. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHOUINARD-DANCE (New York) _ Offstage, the Montreal-based
choreographer Marie Chouinard could pass for Joni Mitchell's
double, with her sleek 5-foot-8-inch frame, her fragile beauty and
her long, blond hair. Onstage, her persona is fiercer. During her
22-year dance career, Chouinard has been called everything from
``the high priestess of choreographic shock'' and ``a sorceress''
to ``the praying mantis in the hothouse of Quebec dance.'' Many of
her solo dances _ including the first, ``Crystallization'' (1978) _
are being presented by Compagnie Marie Chouinard in a rare
appearance in New York at the Joyce Theater for five performances,
beginning on Wednesday. By William Harris. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VALLEY-OF-IAO-THEATER (New York) _ Lee Nagrin left her childhood
home, Seattle, to come to New York City, where in the early 1950s
she became a noted Off Broadway performance artist and director,
collaborated with Meredith Monk and painted. Her younger brother,
Bert Swezea, stayed behind, becoming a popular real estate agent in
Seattle, where he married and had two sons. Their decidedly
different-seeming paths rejoined in 1992, when Nagrin received news
that Buddy, as she called him, was seriously ill in Maui, Hawaii,
where he had formed a new life of the spirit. Nagrin traveled to
Hawaii to be with her brother, who died the following year. Out of
that experience has come ``The Valley of Iao,'' which opens on
Thursday for a three-week engagement at La MaMa. By Jennifer
Dunning. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALMEIDA-THEATER (London) _ If we discount the much-hyped London
debut of Kathleen Turner in a stage version of ``The Graduate,''
the Almeida theater has been gobbling up the London critics'
attention in recent weeks. First there was the premiere of Harold
Pinter's ``Celebration'' at the company's grungy headquarters in
Islington. Then it presented Nicholas Wright's new ``Cressida'' in
the West End, with a magnificently dilapidated Sir Michael Gambon
as a trainer of the boy actors who took female roles in
early-17th-century England. And now it has reopened the doors of
the East End film studios once used by Alfred Hitchcock and staged
``Richard II'' with Ralph Fiennes as the king, a production
expected at the Brooklyn Academy of Music in the fall. By Benedict
Nightingale. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SINEAD-CUSACK-THETER (London) _ It would be an easy assumption
to make, but a wrong one, to think of Sinead Cusack as famous by
association. In her native Ireland, the surname evokes associations
to that country's eminent acting clan. Not only was her father,
Cyril, one of the last century's best-known Irish performers, but
having been born into celebrity, Cusack proceeded to marry a man
who became one: Jeremy Irons, the film star. Cusack, however, has
garnered an impressive share of acting renown of her own. Last week
she opened Off Broadway at the Irish Repertory Theater in Sebastian
Barry's ``Our Lady of Sligo,'' reprising a role that won her a
Critics' Circle Award and an Evening Standard prize for best
actress in London in 1998 at the Royal National Theater. By Matt
Wolf. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   YARD-GAL-THEATER (London) _ As is often the case by this point
in the Broadway season, London playwrights are having their say.
This year, three of England's senior dramatists are represented in
plays both new and in revival: Michael Frayn (``Copenhagen''),
Peter Shaffer (``Amadeus'') and Tom Stoppard (``The Real Thing'').
On Wednesday they will be joined Off Broadway by one of Britain's
younger generation when Rebecca Prichard, 28, makes her American
theater debut with her play ``Yard Gal.'' In previews at the MCC
Theater in Chelsea, ``Yard Gal'' is a study over time of two
feisty, quick-witted girl gang members. By Matt Wolf. &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VARESE-MESSIAEN-MUSIC (Undated) _ On Friday evening Christoph
von Dohnanyi and the Cleveland Orchestra will present Edgard
Varese's ``Ameriques,'' and on Saturday evening Seiji Ozawa and the
Boston Symphony will offer Oliver Messiaen's ``Turangalila
Symphony,'' with the excellent Pierre-Laurent Aimard in the
important part for solo piano. Varese began ``Ameriques'' shortly
after he had settled in New York, in 1915, and Messiaen wrote
``Turangalila'' for Ozawa's orchestra (which was then, in the late
'40s, Serge Koussevitzky's, though the first performance was
conducted by Leonard Bernstein). By Paul Griffiths. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RAUTAVAARA-MUSIC (Helsinki, Finland) _ Matthew
Gurewitschinterviews the Finnish composer, Einojuhani Rautavaara,
70, about his Symphony No. 8, subtitled ``The Journey.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEXY-SPRING-SONGS (Undated) _ Soundtracks to spring lust are
nothing new, of course. The booty historian could trace the genre
back to medieval maypole dances or, in modernist times,
Stravinsky's ``Rite of Spring.'' The latter not only depicts the
primitive fertility rituals at the root of today's spring singles
but also uses music more dependent on rhythm than melody, with the
fast-driving string ostinatos and emphatic percussive downbeats
that are at the core of Sisqo's ``Thong Song.'' The song, a
celebration of glimpses of scanty female underwear by Sisqo of the
rhythm-and-blues group Dru Hill, was bubbling well under the Top
40. But by last week, with spring love in the air and spring break
on the beach, it was up at No. 5 and still climbing. By Neil
Strauss. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ACADEMIE-JULIAN-ART (New York) _ One of this season's more
rewarding sleepers is ``Overcoming All Obstacles: The Women of the
Academie Julian'' at the Dahesh Museum, in Manhattan. Visitors,
though not always numerous, tend to be keenly attentive. The
subject matter makes very good points at every turn but does not
set out either to bully or reproach us. It is in every history of
French painting that in 1868 Rodolphe Julian, a former wrestler,
founded an independent art school in Paris that remains active to
this day. It was the only place in the city at which a woman could
study art intensively in a well-lighted room from a living model
and count on being taught by artists of substantial quality. By
John Russell. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
