<HEADLINE>
BOND PRICES BUOYED BY STOCKS AND TREASURY'S DEBT REPURCHASE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bond prices were mostly higher Tuesday, lifted on one
hand by the Treasury's announced intention to buy back debt this
week yet restrained on the other by the allure of rising stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year bond rose 11/32, to 104 26/32. Its
yield, which moves in the opposite direction from the price, fell
to 5.91 percent from 5.93 percent Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department said Tuesday that would buy back up to
$2 billion in national debt Thursday, , the latest in a series of
debt repurchases.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the Treasury wants to buy back 14 outstanding
issues of 30-year securities that will mature between February 2020
and August 2025, with coupon rates ranging from 6.25 percent to
8.75 percent. The spreads in the yield over the current long bond
are 34 to 284 basis points.
</P>
<P>
   The government expects to save money through its buyback
operations because it will save more in interest payments than its
costs to buy the bonds back. In January, the Treasury said it would
like to repurchase up to $30 billion of debt this year. This week
will be the third buyback operation since last month. On March 9,
the Treasury bought back $1 billion in debt, followed one week
later by another $1 billion repurchase. After initially falling
because of a report showing fewer housing starts in March, said
Donald Fine, chief market analyst for Chase Asset Management,
Treasury yields later rose in a ``flight-from-quality.'' The market
responded to both the rise in stock prices and the Treasury's
announcement of the $2 billion buyback, which disappointed
investors who had expected a larger volume of repurchases, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Treasury market has been dominated by supply
considerations lately, Fine said, Federal Reserve policy on
interest rates and overall rates respond to fundamental economic
forces, ``and in this regard housing activity is a key leading
indicator of future economic performance.'' Although the sharp drop
in March housing starts was greater than expected, Fine believes it
was also, in all likelihood, an overstatement of any softness in
housing.
</P>
<P>
   The financial markets anticipate another increase in short-term
rates at the May 16 Federal Open Market Committee meeting, and
recent comments by members of the FOMC, including Alan Greenspan,
the Fed chairman, have done nothing to dispel this view, Fine said.
``Indeed, surging economic growth led by strong consumer spending
and a pickup in the rate of inflation virtually guarantee an
additional 25 basis point pre-emptive move to a less accommodative
monetary policy stance, and while a more aggressive action of 50
basis points cannot be ruled out, it seems less probable in light
of the ongoing gyrations in the stock market.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
