<SLUG> BC-COURT-MIRANDA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRANDA RULING UNDER SCRUTINY BY HIGH COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Television viewers from ``Dragnet'' to ``NYPD
Blue'' know it as well as lawyers: ``You have the right to remain
silent. Anything you say can and will be used against you in a
court of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the opening lines to the so-called Miranda rights,
named for the 1966 Supreme Court ruling requiring police officers
to read suspects their rights.
</P>
<P>
   But the ruling, which has become embedded in popular culture as
deeply as it is rooted in criminal procedure, faces a serious
challenge this week. Wednesday, the Supreme Court will hear
arguments about whether Miranda should be drastically scaled back,
or even eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   And while the high court's opinions are meant to be devoid of
politics, the case comes at a time when there have been serious
questions raised about police misconduct and whether defendants'
rights have been adequately protected.
</P>
<P>
   To conservatives seeking to rid the nation of what they see as
bad law, the Miranda rules are a straitjacket on police, a
too-rigid requirement that puts even confessed criminals back on
the streets _ if their confessions were obtained before their legal
rights were made clear.
</P>
<P>
   To civil rights activists, Miranda is a critical protection for
defendants whose rights have been slowly eroded by the high court
over the past few decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the midst of a criminal procedure
counter-revolution,'' where the rights against self-incrimination
and against unlawful searches and seizures have been chipped away
by the Supreme Court and some lower courts, said Donald E. Wilkes,
Jr., a criminal law professor at the University of Georgia School
of Law.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this has a ripple effect. All of this encourages more
and more bold and aggressive behavior and improper conduct by
police.''
</P>
<P>
   Miranda's critics argue that it's the honorable police officers
whose work is frustrated by a strict reading of the rule. ``The
suggestion that we're going to retreat to rubber hoses and
intimidation (of suspects) is unfair,'' said Todd Gaziano, a senior
fellow at the conservative Heritage Foundation who has been helping
to prepare the challenge to Miranda. ``No one wants to allow
coerced confessions.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue before the court is not the Miranda ruling itself, but
a law enacted by Congress in 1968 in an effort to dilute the impact
of Miranda. The law says that courts should consider whether a
suspect's confession was voluntary, and that the question of
whether a suspect was read his Miranda rights should be just one
factor in deciding whether a confession was voluntary and
admissible as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The court's Miranda decision treats the question as clear cut,
with its holding that no confession, however freely given, can be
used in evidence if a suspect was not read his rights.
</P>
<P>
   The 1968 law is still on the books. But so is Miranda, and the
warnings still are required. Prosecutors across the country have
seldom relied upon the 1968 law to support the use of a confession
that violated the Miranda decision and the Clinton Justice
Department has actively defied it.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative scholars, led by Utah attorney Paul Cassell and
former Reagan administration Attorney General Edwin Meese, have
conducted a decades-long campaign to overturn Miranda. They finally
succeeded in bringing the matter before the Supreme Court with
Dickerson vs. US, a case the court will hear Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The case questions whether Charles Thomas Dickerson's confession
to FBI agents that he robbed a bank in Alexandria, Va., was
admissible. Dickerson insists he confessed before he was read his
rights.
</P>
<P>
   While law enforcement groups have added their names in support
of Cassell's argument, those watching the case on both sides of the
issue note that there was never much of a push by the police
rank-and-file to get rid of Miranda.
</P>
<P>
   ``A handful of people decided they didn't like the law,''
complained Nan Aron, president of the liberal Alliance for Justice,
a Washington advocacy group. ``This is just the culmination of a
very strategic, well-organized campaign to overturn one of the
anchors of American law.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department so despises the 1968 law it has refused
its traditional role of defending federal statutes when they face
high court challenge. In an unusual move, the Supreme Court
appointed Cassell to argue on behalf of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In law review articles, Cassell makes it plain that he regards
Miranda as legal anathema, even though he concedes there are
probably very few instances where a criminal is set free because
police forgot to give a Miranda warning. But, he argues in the
Stanford Law Review, the rate at which police solve or clear crimes
fell ``immediately and dramatically'' after the 1966 Miranda
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights activists and some legal scholars see another
trend, a steady dilution of civil liberties at a time when there
are many allegations of misconduct and mistakes by both police and
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, the police department is under fire for a
spate of shootings of unarmed men. In Los Angeles, public
confidence in the police force has been threatened by a massive
police scandal. And in Illinois, executions have been halted amid
revelations that innocent people were condemned to death.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, legal scholars say, defendants have fewer rights, as
the Supreme Court has steadily expanded police powers.
</P>
<P>
   The high court is not expected to throw out Miranda completely,
although it may water down the rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miranda has been a symbol of both our rights and law
enforcement's respect for our rights,'' said Geoffrey Moulton, Jr.,
a professor at Delaware's Widener University School of Law and a
former clerk for Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may have a bigger cultural or societal impact than a
practical impact.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
