<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOZAM-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``AMATODOS'': JOY AND SERIOUSNESS FOR MOZAMBIQUE
</HEADLINE>
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The performance that the National Song and Dance
Company of Mozambique gave on Sunday night at Town Hall was both
high-minded and high-spirited. The event was a benefit to provide
food, shelter and medicine for the flood-devastated nation of
Mozambique, and proceeds went to the Africa Fund, which will turn
them over to the Mozambique Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   All of the dancing was technically precise, and much of it was
joyous in mood.
</P>
<P>
   But grim seriousness was present as well as merriment, for the
entire first half of the evening was devoted to a dance-drama
concerning AIDS, which has taken a horrendous toll in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Choreographed by Perola Jaime, Maria Helena and the company's
artistic director, Augusto Cuvilas, ``Amatodos'' concerned a
sexually promiscuous businessman (played by Justino Zimba) who
contracts and spreads AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The forceful work included erotic entanglements with a multitude
of sexual partners, mysterious sickenings and an episode in which
Liria Rafael, as a witch doctor, unwittingly helped spread
infection by giving all her patients ritual cuts from the same
razor.
</P>
<P>
   But Abacar Mulima and Noe Manjate, two dancers encased in white
sheaths, symbolized condoms and, eventually, most of the dancers
had condoms on their headdresses as they fought off demonlike
figures representing AIDS. The deliberately blunt choreography
preached a powerful message.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Mozambique the Sun Has Risen Up'' filled the second half of
the program. This suite, based on folk styles, was choreographed by
David Abilio, the troupe's general director, and presented the
dancers, singers and percussionists in a festive mood. In dance
after dance, women glided and swayed, while men moved with the
skill and pride of warriors. There were parades, flirtations and
friendly athletic competitions. And the Mozambique flag was proudly
displayed during the finale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
