u f BC-DOW-EXEC19-COX     04-18 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-EXEC19-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Executive search companies to maintain tech-firm interests
</P>
<P>
   By Tammy Joyner
</P>
<P>
   c. 200 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Executive search firms aren't putting too much stock
in the stock market's wild ride as they remain undeterred in their
quest for ownership in many of the new high-tech startup companies.
</P>
<P>
   Several big-name headhunter firms such as Heidrick &AMP; Struggles
International and Christian &AMP; Timbers have joined real estate firms
and the legal and accounting professions in demanding shares in
Internet-based companies as part of their fees for finding much
needed top talent.
</P>
<P>
   As the market soared on technology stocks, that trend _ until
recently _ has paid off handsomely for firms like Chicago-based
Heidrick &AMP; Struggles
</P>
<P>
   This year, Heidrick &AMP; Struggles, the world's largest executive
search firm, realized more than $20 million when one startup went
public. Heidrick &AMP; Struggles took a warrant _ the right to buy
shares at a specified price _ in Neoforma, an online Web site for
new and used medical equipment as part of its fee for finding the
company's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the market for high-tech stocks has been sagging,
H&AMP;S isn't changing its strategy with regard to warrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take our full cash fee in addition to warrants, and
ownership in our clients has value not just when capital markets
are hot,'' said Pat Pittard, Heidrick's Atlanta-based president and
chief executive officer. The company's fee amounts to a third of a
candidate's first-year compensation package.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland-based Christian &AMP; Timbers is a taking a similar
stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not backing off of it at all,'' said Russell Gray,
managing director in Atlanta for Christian &AMP; Timbers.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market drop, in fact, ``may have done a little more to
entice (executives) to join a firm,'' Gray said. ``If a company's
stock is extremely high, (executives) have to increase the value
even further before options take value. If a stock is low, they can
work hard and realize a more significant gain.''
</P>
<P>
   But one equity expert warned that the market's current
volatility serves as a ``wake-up call'' for companies involved in
the practice of taking warrants or options for their services.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those things people have to be wary of,'' said
Brent Longnecker, an executive compensation expert in Houston who
works for Resources Connection, a Santa Ana, Calif.-based
professional services firm.
</P>
<P>
   While service firms may not be skittish about the market, more
companies will scrutinize more closely the businesses from which
they choose to take warrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a company is banking on the options to pay off and they're
not watching their cash flow, their ability to expand and do
research and development and a lot of other things they would have
been able to do would be impeded,'' Longnecker noted.
</P>
<P>
   Companies ``are rethinking the policies on where they take
options from to make sure that the companies they're doing this
with are sound financially.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the case for Dallas businessman George Michael. His
public relations firm, Michael &AMP; Partners, has taken shares in
several high-tech firms in exchange for his services. Now he views
the practice as a venture capitalist would.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we do something like that, we become venture capitalists
whether we know it or not,'' he said. ``I still believe it's the
right thing to do. But like anything else you're going to have to
look at it closely. People will be a little more cautious. They'll
be looking at the underlying business model.'' For that reason, he
said it may be tougher for some high-tech startups to go public in
the future as potential investors become more critical of the
companies in which they invest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warrants and stock options may not be valued as highly in the
future,'' Michael noted. ``It seemed like you couldn't get hurt
with them (in the past). ... Cash compensation may be a little more
important now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 1913EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
