<HEADER>
A0708 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-EARNINGS-CCE19-COX     04-18 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARNINGS-CCE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola Enterprises cuts loss, matching analysts' expectations
 &HT;    By Christopher Seward
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Enterprises cut its net loss nearly in half
in the first quarter, but price increases continued to stall the
bottler's ability to increase case sales significantly.
</P>
<P>
   The Coke system's largest bottler reported a loss of $35
million, or 8 cents a share, compared with a loss of $62 million,
or 15 cents a share, in the year-ago period. The results were in
line with expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Cash operating profit, which analysts consider is one of the
best barometers of a bottler's performance, rose 11 percent in the
first quarter. CCE said cash operating profit _ earnings before
interest, taxes, depreciation and other non-operating items _ rose
to $462 million, compared with $417 million in the year-ago period.
Cash operating results also were in line with Wall Street
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   But price increases dampened case sales in North America and
Europe. Coca-Cola Co., which owns 40 percent of CCE, charged
bottlers more for the concentrate they use to produce soft drinks.
CCE passed on those increased costs to retailers and other
customers who sell its products.
</P>
<P>
   Overall volume, or the amount of products CCE was able to move,
dropped 2 percent during the quarter, with volume in North America
down 3 percent and results flat in Europe. CCE derives nearly
three-quarters of its revenue from North America. The remainder
comes from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin Romm, an analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston,
expects CCE's volume to strengthen in the United States and profits
to improve for the remainder of the year. Among other things, he
noted that fallout from last year's recall of Coke products in
parts of Europe is behind the company, that pricing remains strong
and that CCE appears to be getting its costs under control. ``We
think the company will have a very strong year in 2000,'' Romm
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would look for accelerating volume growth in the second
quarter, which will translate into an improved bottom line,'' added
Bill Pecoriello, an analyst with Sanford Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   The company also expects to see an improvement in the months
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   John Alm, president and chief operating officer, noted that
while supermarket volume ``remained soft'' in the first quarter,
results ``will strengthen in the second quarter, enabling us to
achieve our full-year profit objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Summerfield Johnston Jr., chairman and chief executive officer,
has indicated he is comfortable with analysts' estimates that put
full-year cash operating profit growth at 12 percent this year,
compared with 10 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   CCE said net operating revenue rose slightly to $3.29 billion in
the first quarter, compared with $3.27 billion in the year-ago
period. Analysts think the company's revenue growth has slowed
because acquisitions have slowed.
</P>
<P>
   In heavy trading on Wall Street, CCE's stock closed at $21.93,
up 68 cents, or 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
