<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: ELIAN'S SAGA? IT'S A MINISERIES; GARNER AS DR. HOPE; THE
STOCK WATCH; TRACKING DINOSAURS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Byline follow notebook items.)  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ELIAN'S SAGA? IT'S A MINISERIES  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Like every other recent subject that has dominated the all-news
cable channels, the Elian Gonzalez epic has already inspired a
Hollywood producer to sell the notion of a television movie version
to a network.
</P>
<P>
   But Craig Anderson, a producer with no history of
ripped-from-the headlines movie projects, wants it known that he
has no intention of making an exploitation film out of the boy's
story.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Monday, he emphasized that although he had a
deal in place with CBS since January to make what is expected to be
a four-hour miniseries, he had not paid any money to any of the
participants and did not intend to do so. Instead, he said, many of
the principals in the story ``have been pursuing us.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who began as a Broadway producer of plays like ``On
Golden Pond'' and ``Da'' and moved to television with projects like
the Peabody Award-winning version of the August Wilson play ``The
Piano Lesson'' and most recently ``Sally Hemings'' for CBS, said he
intended his film to be a serious examination of both the political
and human issues raised by the conflict over Elian's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make a movie that gets into the legal ramifications,
the political ramifications, the family law ramifications,''
Anderson said. ``I don't want to do a newsreel. That's being played
out every day. I want to do a movie that tells what's really going
on behind the scenes, from the bedroom in Miami to the Oval Office
to Castro's office in Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   How he expects to achieve this is not entirely clear, although
Anderson said he had been in contact with many people involved in
the case. ``We will have access,'' he said, adding that the
potential audience of ``40 or 50 million people means that the
participants will be very sensitive to how they are portrayed.'' He
also said that a script for the film was being worked on and was
``already well down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The writer is Raphael Lima, whom Anderson described as a former
investigative reporter who immigrated from Cuba as a young boy.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said that while he tended to see valid arguments on all
sides of the battle for the boy's future, he became convinced early
in the coverage that much more was going on than was was being seen
on the surface. ``I would see the sound bites, and I could tell
that people were not telling everything,'' he said, adding, ``I
personally think there is a handshake agreement somewhere that's
being played out.''
</P>
<P>
   What he most wants to avoid, Anderson said, is being drawn into
what he called ``the circus surrounding Elian.'' For that reason,
he said, he does not expect the film to be broadcast until well
after the current furor has died down. That may be sometime in the
next television season, but it depends on how events play out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ending of the story is maybe two months after Elian goes
back to Cuba, if he goes back, after he has returned to
normality,'' Anderson said. But even with all his intentions to
emphasize the background machinations over the boy, Anderson
conceded that ``in the middle of all of it is going to be the
angelic face of that boy. We will always come back to his
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   GARNER AS DR. HOPE
</P>
<P>
   David E. Kelley thought he had successfully resurrected his
oldest drama series, ``Chicago Hope,'' last fall when he introduced
a host of new characters to the drama on CBS. The initial results
were promising. ``Chicago Hope,'' which had averaged 9.9 million
viewers last season, grew to more than 13 million.
</P>
<P>
   Then came ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.'' That ABC game show
all but obliterated ``Chicago Hope,'' a circumstance that might
upset Kelley more if ``Millionaire'' were not helping his ABC drama
``The Practice'' to ratings highs on Sunday nights. ``That show's
like a big cow,'' Kelley said, ``it gives me milk on one night and
kicks me in the head on another.''
</P>
<P>
   So in what Kelley admits is a last-ditch effort to save
``Chicago Hope,'' he has brought in yet another new character, a
business operator who gets hospitals in fiscal shape, or shuts them
down. The news is the actor playing him: James Garner, one of the
most enduring television stars of the last half-century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a fan of his,'' Kelley said in a telephone
interview. He said that Garner had responded to the character, a
kind of charming killer of an executive.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, Kelley acknowledged, is to try to bring in Garner's
longtime fans, many of whom turned up for his CBS movie ``One
Special Night'' earlier this season. The film, also starring Julie
Andrews, was the highest-rated one of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the cast changes earlier, we tried to make the show
younger,'' Kelley said. ``Now we're trying to go back.''
</P>
<P>
   The results from last week's first of four Garner episodes were
not especially promising: ``Chicago Hope'' fared only slightly
better than it had in recent weeks. This Thursday's episode could
be crucial because the show hopes to be helped by an original
episode of its lead-in ``Diagnosis Murder'' this week.
</P>
<P>
   Of course it still has to go against Regis Philbin. And what if
the ill patient rallies one more time, will Dr. Garner be back to
continue his triage? ``He says he will,'' Kelly said. ``He says
he's having a good time playing this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   THE STOCK WATCH
</P>
<P>
   The recent turbulence in the business world is to CNBC what the
Persian Gulf war was to CNN: a ratings bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   The business news cable channel has reached record audience
levels thanks to the Dow Jones industrial average's largest point
gain ever, its largest point drop ever and the government's
decision that Microsoft acted as a monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   On eight days within the last four weeks CNBC has reached
audience levels ranking within its top 10 daytime performances. In
all, nine of CNBC's 10 highest-rated days were this year.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, CNBC was watched in an average 564,000 homes between
5 a.m. and 7:30 p.m., according to Nielsen Media Research data.
That represented CNBC's largest daytime viewership ever.
</P>
<P>
   On April 3, the day of the Microsoft decision, CNBC was watched
in an average 486,000 homes between 5 a.m. and 7:30 p.m., according
to Nielsen. That represented CNBC's second largest daytime
viewership ever.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, when the Dow Jones average dropped a record 618
points, CNBC was watched in 466,000 homes in the same time period,
representing its third highest daytime audience in its 10-year
history.
</P>
<P>
   These numbers do not take viewers in offices and public places
into account. If they did, CNBC executives argue, they would be 40
percent to 50 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
   The business channel's surging popularity is also causing some
image problems. Some investors have blamed CNBC for contributing to
last Friday's market drop by interviewing stock analysts with
particularly bearish viewpoints. At other times, CNBC has been
singled out for contributing to investor exuberance. Bill Bolster,
the CNBC president, said that such accusations were unfair. ``We
hold a mirror up to the market,'' he said. ``We present the facts.
People act on that.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
<P>
   TRACKING DINOSAURS
</P>
<P>
   CNBC isn't the only cable channel that smashed records last
week.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night the Discovery Channel's three-hour special,
``Walking With Dinosaurs,'' drew the highest audience in the
channel's history.
</P>
<P>
   The special, in which computer animation was used to recreate
the dinosaur era, was watched by 10.7 million people. Discovery
Channel executives said it was the most-watched cable documentary
ever.
</P>
<P>
   _ JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
