<HEADER>
A0713 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-APPEALS-HNS &LR;      04-18 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-APPEALS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES OFFER `MIXED BAG' IN INMATE RULINGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A divided Supreme Court on Tuesday made it more
difficult for condemned killers and other inmates to challenge the
constitutionality of their state-court convictions before a federal
judge.
</P>
<P>
   But in a separate decision, the justices unanimously eased the
burden on convicts trying to introduce evidence on federal appeal
that improprieties at their state trial led to their conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot of the the court's rulings could deprive convicts of
the ability to present before a federal judge the same
constitutional arguments they had unsuccessfully made before state
courts. But the decisions might also enable inmates to bring
federal appeals when they uncover evidence that their
constitutional right to a fair trial had been violated at the state
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a mixed bag,'' said Larry Yackle, a lawyer with
the American Civil Liberties Union, which defends the
constitutional rights of death-row prisoners. Attorneys will have
to await the fate of future federal appeals to determine whether
the court's rulings are ``prisoner-friendly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's two decisions could affect the appeal strategy
of more than 3,600 inmates on death row nationwide, including 459
in Texas, and the hundreds of thousands of state convicts facing
lesser sentences.
</P>
<P>
   In their pair of rulings, the justices saved two condemned
murderers from the Virginia executioner, at least for now, in
clearing the way for them to challenge the constitutionality of
their state convictions in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   The justices said a U.S. appeals court misread a federal law in
denying Terry Williams and Michael Wayne Williams the chance to
have their appeals heard.
</P>
<P>
   That statute, the 1996 Antiterrorism and Effective Death Penalty
Act, was passed by Congress in an effort to limit the ability of
death-row inmates and other convicts to challenge their state
convictions in federal court. Sponsors of the measure had
criticized the long time it took the condemned to be executed as
they spent years repeatedly appealing their state convictions in
federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Texas joined 34 other states in urging the justices to rule that
the law generally bars federal judges from reversing the
convictions and sentences of state courts.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, in one decision, quoted from the law in ruling 5-4
that federal judges cannot set aside state court convictions unless
the verdicts resulted from gross misinterpretations of prior
Supreme Court decisions governing the conduct of fair trials. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Justice Sandra Day O'Connor wrote the opinion, which was joined
by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Anthony M.
Kennedy, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Justice John Paul Stevens led the other justices in saying that
defendants should have broad opportunity to appeal in federal
court. Joining Stevens were Justices Stephen G. Breyer, Ruth Bader
Ginsburg and David H. Souter.
</P>
<P>
   The court, however, was unanimous in its interpretation of a
provision of the law that bars defendants from introducing issues
on appeal based on evidence that they failed to produce at trial.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the court, Kennedy said the provision does not
prevent defendants from making appeals based on evidence that they
tried diligently to find but failed to discover until after the
state courts had ruled against them.
</P>
<P>
   In its decisions, the high court told the Richmond, Va.-based
4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals to reconsider its denial of the
two condemned men's appeals with an eye toward interpreting the law
more broadly.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Williams, convicted of striking and killing Harris Stone
with a mattock in 1985 and then taking money from his wallet, can
now pursue in federal court his argument that he was denied a fair
trial because his attorney had failed to tell the sentencing judge
that Williams was borderline mentally retarded and had been abused
as a child.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Wayne Williams, sentenced to death for the 1993 slaying
of Morris Keller Jr. and his wife, Mary, can tell a federal court
that his conviction should be thrown out because a juror failed to
disclose that she had been married to the prosecution's lead
witness for 17 years until a 1979 divorce and that they had four
children.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
