<HEADER>
A0716 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-EARNINGS-COKE19-COX     04-18 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARNINGS-COKE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Onetime charges give Coke second loss in row
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the second straight quarter, Coca-Cola reported a
loss of 2 cents a share after taking one-time charges totaling 24
cents a share, or $680 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company said Tuesday that it lost $58 million in the first
quarter after spending $275 million, or 8 cents a share, on its
massive reorganization that will eliminate 5,200 jobs worldwide. It
also spent $405 million, or $16 cents a share, to write down its
excess bottling capacity in India.
</P>
<P>
   The reported loss compared with a gain of $747 million, or 30
cents a share, in the year-earlier period.
</P>
<P>
   Without those nonrecurring items, the company would have earned
22 cents a share on an ongoing basis, beating the consensus
estimate of analysts by a penny a share.
</P>
<P>
   Beverage analysts pay closer attention to the ongoing results
than to the reported loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``For comparability purposes, you have to go apples to apples,''
said Scott Wilkins, an analyst with Deutsche Bank. ``Therefore, we
strip out the nonrecurring items to get a better picture of the
ongoing operation.''
</P>
<P>
   That picture, hesaid, was not a bad one.
</P>
<P>
   ``On balance, Coke reported some positive elements in these
results,'' Wilkins said. ``Operating profits and margins came in
ahead of our expectations, partly driven by better than expected
results in the key market of Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Company Chairman Doug Daft echoed that thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the quarter, we started to see momentum in many of our
key markets,'' Daft said in a statement, citing Mexico, Brazil and
Spain, as well as Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford Bernstein analyst Bill Pecoriello credited Daft for
implementing tighter financial controls in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their operating income was up 12 percent, excluding the
nonrecurring items, instead of the 3 percent we were forecasting,''
Pecoriello said. ``It shows that the new management is keeping a
tight control on costs. This means financial discipline and
spending in line with demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola said its earnings also were reduced by another 10
cents a share because of a planned reduction of excess concentrate
inventory by some bottlers.
</P>
<P>
   But Wilkins and other analysts said they do not consider that a
nonrecurring item. ``It's simply lower concentrate sales for the
quarter,'' Wilkins said. Coke sells concentrate or syrup to
bottlers, which add carbonation before filling cans and bottles,
and then distributing the products.
</P>
<P>
   Coke lost $85 million from its equity interest in those bottlers
in the first quarter, while company revenue stayed virtually the
same at $4.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   On the all-important volume front _ the amount of product moved
_ Coke said case sales increased 3.5 percent, including figures
from its recent acquisition of Cadbury Schweppes brands in 161
nations outside the United States. Excluding that acquisition,
volume increased 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins said the 2 percent growth presented a mixed picture. It
was better than the company's most recent estimate but worse than a
prior forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America saw the biggest increase in volume, 9 percent from
a year ago, including the Cadbury brands. In North America, total
case sales rose 1 percent, while increasing 3 percent in Asia, 1
percent in Europe and Eurasia, and 5 percent in Africa and the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   In last year's fourth quarter, Coke lost 2 cents a share, or $45
million, after taking $813 million in charges to write down
bottling assets in the troubled economies of Russia and the
Baltics.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the company nor analysts could remember the last time
Coke reported two quarterly losses in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
