NYT-04-18-00 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0718 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BROADWAY-CONDUCTOR-AR     04-18 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-CONDUCTOR-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELEVATING THE BROADWAY PIT: LEGENDARY CONDUCTOR SHAPES MUSICALS
WITH HIS BATON
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Part of the reason Brian Stokes Mitchell wanted to
play the male lead in ``Kiss Me, Kate'' was that Paul Gemignani
would be in the pit.
</P>
<P>
   John Beal, among the most respected bass players on Broadway,
left ``Phantom of the Opera'' after more than 11 years with the
orchestra to join Gemignani's team for ``Kiss Me, Kate.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gemignani was one of the first people contacted by the
Broadway producer Roger Berlind once he settled on the idea of a
``Kate'' revival. ``He's kind of the dean of the industry,''
Berlind said.
</P>
<P>
   On Broadway, a conductor is often as overlooked as so much
wallpaper, that nameless fellow waving a stick under the stage. But
in addition to wielding the technical skill involved in conducting
the orchestra, musical directors play a major role in shaping a
show, acting as the liaison between the composer and the cast. As
the musical director of almost every Stephen Sondheim work over the
last 30 years as well as such hits as ``Crazy for You,'' Gemignani
has become something of a legend, the last of a breed of conductors
who elevate musical direction to an art form.
</P>
<P>
   Theater veterans say he is one of the major reasons ``Kiss Me,
Kate'' is so musically satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he infuses himself into an orchestra, and drives them
with him and conveys what he's feeling about the music to an
orchestra is, as far as I'm concerned, as deeply passionate as
Lenny's was,'' said Sondheim, referring to Leonard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Gemignani in the pit during a performance as he moves
through memorable Cole Porter numbers like ``Too Darn Hot,''
``Wunderbar'' and ``Always True to You in My Fashion'' yields only
a hint of his depth and ardor. There is no sheet music in front of
him; he always memorizes the score. Occasionally, at a quiet
musical moment, he closes his eyes. In dance numbers his feet move.
He can make the music sound bittersweet or buoyant with the pinch
of his fingers, the thrust of his fist, the lowering of his palm.
It is a language that the uninitiated can never fully understand or
appreciate. But the musicians who play under Gemignani and the
actors who sing for him seem to have a clear sense of what sets him
apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's in the pit and you're onstage, he is breathing with
you,'' said Marin Mazzie, who stars in ``Kate'' and worked with
Gemignani on Sondheim's ``Passion'' in 1994. ``We feel each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   During her solo, ``So in Love,'' for example, Mazzie said, she
and Gemignani are always communicating _ without ever meeting eyes.
``The passion, the way his body moves, the expressiveness,'' she
said. ``It's in him. It's inspiring.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said that Gemignani allowed him to experiment and to
explore new interpretations. ``If I want to sing the song a
different way, I don't have to tell him,'' Mitchell said. ``If I'm
feeling something different, Paul's going to be there with me
because he's connected to me and he's watching me.''
</P>
<P>
   Some conductors take a break between songs and sit down, leafing
through the newspaper or joking with colleagues. Gemignani remains
on his feet, watching so he can sense where a scene is going and
ensure that the song becomes a natural extension of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know where the actors are so I can put the song
there,'' Gemignani said. ``I memorize everything on purpose because
I think my face should be on the stage. I consider myself the other
actor in the show.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The musicians in the ``Kate'' pit, several of whom have worked
with Gemignani on and off for 20 years, say they are also grateful
for the freedom he gives them to make the music their own. ``He's
not married to the written notes,'' said Beal, the bassist. ``He
trusts the players that he hires.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Gemignani has high standards, his musicians say, he is
not a taskmaster. ``If you make a mistake, he doesn't take you
outside and rip your head off,'' said Dennis Anderson, who plays
first woodwind for ``Kate.'' ``He never attacks you personally or
admonishes you in front of people. He might look at you funny or
raise his eyebrows.''
</P>
<P>
   A burly man with slicked-back hair and a graying beard,
Gemignani, 60, was married on Valentine's Day to Derin Altay, an
actress. It is his second marriage. He has a 20-year-old son from
his first marriage, Alexander, who wants to be an actor.
</P>
<P>
   Gemignani's air of authority in the pit is balanced by a boyish
twinkle in his eye, a playfulness that seems to inspire loyalty and
affection. ``You have never seen someone do so many different
things with a baton,'' said Suzanne Ornstein, Gemignani's
concertmaster. ``A stiletto, syringe, fishing rod, hand grenade _
it's all very clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Gemignani's rapport with his colleagues is one of the reasons
why the Broadway director Harold Prince made him part of his team
three decades ago. ``He's jovial but firm,'' Prince said. ``It's a
very good personality to have around on a show. You want somebody
that artistic and dependable whose personality is made for such an
intimate collaboration.''
</P>
<P>
   The two met when Gemignani was a drummer and assistant conductor
for the road company of ``Cabaret.'' The son of a concert pianist
(his mother) and school principal (his father), Gemignani grew up
in a Alameda, Calif., trying various instruments: violin, trombone,
clarinet, tuba and finally drums. ``I hated piano and still do,''
he said. ``It's like a one-note samba.''
</P>
<P>
   He came to New York on a whim in 1967, parked his motorcycle in
front of the Blue Note jazz club and went in to ask for a drumming
job, which he got. Prince's musical director, Hal Hastings, soon
hired him for ``Cabaret.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hastings died in 1973 at the beginning of the run of
Sondheim's ``A Little Night Music,'' Gemignani took over as
conductor and Prince made him his resident musical director.
Gemignani said that moment clinched his career. ``It was like a
dream come true,'' he said. ``I was in the right place at the right
time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I happened to hit the most creative years for the both of
them,'' he said of Sondheim and Prince. ``I was working with two
guys who were at the top of their game and everybody wanted to be
me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pacific Overtures,'' ``Into the Woods,'' ``Passion'' _
Gemignani did all the Sondheim shows except ``Company'' (He was on
the road at the time with ``Follies''). He said that ``Sweeney
Todd'' was his favorite. ``It's near perfect in the sense that its
dramatic intent is there,'' he said. ``The score _ I don't think
you'll find another one like it.''
</P>
<P>
   When he and Sondheim parted ways with Prince after the failure
of ``Merrily We Roll Along'' in 1981, Gemignani said he practically
mourned. ``I loved that family, and that family's gone,'' he said,
tears filling his eyes. ``It's like when Mom says, `Get out, make a
living, I can't support you anymore.' It's the hardest thing I've
ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I could be outspoken and I could be wrong and I could be
brilliant,'' he continued, reminiscing about those days. ``And
those two guys never made me feel anything but a part of the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Theater lore has it that the critical failure of ``Merrily''
broke up the team. But though they conceded that the experience was
painful, the collaborators agreed that their separation was simply
a matter of circumstance. Prince went on to direct ``Phantom of the
Opera'' and Gemignani stuck with Sondheim to do ``Sunday in the
Park with George.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened because at some point there was a conflict between
what Steve was doing and what I was doing,'' Prince said. ``Since I
work with different composers it makes sense that Paul would go
where his strongest connection is. I certainly wouldn't expect or
want anything different.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it looks as if the team will be reunited on ``Wise Guys,''
Sondheim's latest project. The musical stalled on its way to
Broadway this season after a workshop presentation directed by Sam
Mendes, and Prince has taken over. John Weidman, who wrote the
show's book, said that the team hoped to bring the play to Broadway
in the fall of 2001, probably with a new title.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Kate'' is still running, Gemignani said, he will leave the
pit to work on ``Wise Guys.'' ``I've wished this a long time,'' he
said. ``But I can't say I ever thought it would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   That his glory days are past makes the critical success of
``Kate'' particularly sweet, Gemignani said. ``Something like this
should be the norm, not the exception,'' he said. ``This is what
Broadway should be all the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
