<SLUG> BC-EARNINGS-DELTA19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta declines 11%, but exceeds estimates
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Higher fuel prices and weak midwinter ridership pushed
Delta Air Lines' profit down 11 percent, to $179 million, in the
airline's third fiscal quarter ended March 31.
</P>
<P>
   The profit, which excludes one-time gains, handily beat Wall
Street forecasts. Shares in the Atlanta-based airline gained $1.18
3/4, closing Tuesday at $50.18 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Delta was hurt less by higher fuel costs than most carriers
because of an aggressive hedging program that locked in
below-market prices in advance. Even so, Delta's average cost per
gallon of fuel rose almost 21 percent to 58.54 cents in the
quarter. Along with other airlines, Delta added a $20 round-trip
surcharge during the quarter to offset the increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fuel is a very serious problem and continues to be a problem
for the industry,'' Chairman and Chief Executive Leo Mullin said on
CNBC. Despite subsiding oil prices, he added, jet fuel costs ``will
not approach even remotely the prices of last year'' in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to fuel costs, Delta also suffered a ``Y2K
hangover'' that hurt January ridership, as did ice storms in
Atlanta that month.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Financial Officer Ed West, during an analysts conference
call, said traffic rebounded sharply in March and that advance
bookings are running ahead of year-earlier levels.
</P>
<P>
   The $179 million quarterly profit translated to $1.33 a share.
That compared with a prior-year profit of $201 million, excluding
special items, or $1.31 a share. Earnings per share rose because
the company had fewer shares outstanding than a year ago, the
result of a buyback. Revenue climbed 13 percent to $3.96 billion.
Costs rose 14.5 percent, with fuel prices and pay raises the
biggest contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Including one-time gains and charges, third-quarter profit was
$223 million, vs. $216 million a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Delta logged a $73 million gain on the sale of more shares in
Internet seat-seller priceline.com. Delta got shares in the dot-com
in return for its early involvement with the site and has realized
a total gain of $784 million through periodic sales. It still has
priceline.com shares and warrants worth about $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   West said bookings at all Internet sites, including Delta's own,
now account for nearly 10 percent of the carrier's business and
could reach 35 percent over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   West also said Delta is testing new, lower fares for business
travelers in some markets to keep them from defecting to discount
carriers that serve nearby cities.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
