<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PURCHASEWISE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth service lets firms make e-purchases
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth Corp. on Tuesday added to its portfolio for
small-business customers by announcing a service that aims to
smooth the transition to electronic business.
</P>
<P>
   The software, dubbed PurchaseWise, will let an organization's
procurement staff or subordinate officers order supplies, but it
also makes sure the order gets the appropriate approval before
being zipped via the Net to the supplier.
</P>
<P>
   The authorizing executive doesn't need to be directly in touch
with the one doing the ordering, said John Shivanandan, senior
director of e-business for BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This allows him to do it upfront, ahead of time. It eliminates
the need to track him down.''
</P>
<P>
   The software is developed by California-based Commerce One.
BellSouth sees the service as an extension of its expertise in
networking, Shivanandan said. ``And the Internet is a network.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the small-business segment is defined as companies
with fewer than 100 employees and $50 million in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Although more modest than the multibillion-dollar likes of
Coca-Cola or Delta, the small businesses targeted by BellSouth
together are a substantial economic force. They generate $1.3
trillion in revenue in annually and buy more than $200 billion in
goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   ``BellSouth PurchaseWise demonstrates how BellSouth enables its
customers to take advantage of the benefits of e-commerce,''
Shivanandan said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
