<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-NUCLEAR-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER FIRE, BRITISH NUCLEAR ACTS TO EASE SAFETY CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Reeling from a series of debacles over its safety and
management, British Nuclear Fuels PLC the government-owned giant of
Britain's nuclear industry, announced a management shake-out
Tuesday and pledged ``a comprehensive overhaul'' of safety
procedures in an effort to redeem its battered standing in Europe,
the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But the changes ignored critics' demands for a strategic shift
in the company's businesses after government inspectors criticized
its safety culture, particularly at the sprawling Sellafield plant
in northwestern England, which houses nuclear reprocessing, waste
disposal, fuel production and power production facilities.
</P>
<P>
   This year alone, the company has been forced to postpone plans
for a stock offering and dismissed its chief executive after
workers falsified documents accompanying a fuel shipment to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In another incident, a saboteur severed cables on a robotic arm
in a nuclear waste disposal unit.
</P>
<P>
   Irish and Danish activists have rekindled a campaign to shut
down spent-fuel reprocessing at Sellafield, and in the United
States, where the company has billions of dollars worth of nuclear
clean-up contracts through its Westinghouse division, a top
official said he would send a team of investigators to Sellafield.
</P>
<P>
   With Tuesday's measures, announced in a formal response to
criticism by Britain's Nuclear Installations Inspectorate, the
company said it would replace all six nonexecutive directors and
two executive directors, hire new safety personnel, reshape the
chain of command at Sellafield under a single executive, and
streamline the plant's myriad safety procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is that this is not a one-shot response,'' said
Norman Askew, the newly appointed chief executive, in an interview.
``I know and we all know that this doesn't the resolve the
problem,'' he added, unless the company is ``seen to deliver on
that, and that's absolutely what we have got to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there had been no immediate response from some nations
that had suspended commercial ties with the company after last
year's falsification of documents. Japan wants Britain to take back
nuclear fuel shipped with such documents and Germany suspended new
shipments of spent fuel. Bill Richardson, the U.S. energy
secretary, said he would send inspectors to Sellafield, and Askew
said the U.S. team would arrive there soon.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups supported by the Irish and Danish
governments have been pressing British Nuclear to stop nuclear-fuel
reprocessing because of radioactive emissions into the Irish Sea
and into the atmosphere, which the company says it has drastically
reduced.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave the company to focus on nuclear-waste
management and contracts in the United States and elsewhere for
cleaning up contaminated nuclear sites. But company officials said
such plans were not under consideration right now.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``This is not a moment for a knee-jerk reaction on strategy,
particularly as we are aiming to privatize the company in the long
term,'' said Sir Hugh Collum, the British Nuclear chairman, in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Both he and Askew, the chief executive, said the company's order
book for reprocessing spent fuel from reactors ran until 2010. ``It
would be folly for managers to turn their back on that,'' Askew
said. The changes at British Nuclear drew a cautious response from
Britain's watchdog Health and Safety Executive, which supervises
nuclear inspections. Laurence Williams, the chief nuclear
inspector, said, ``If we see any signs of significant failure to
deliver, we will not hesitate to use our extensive enforcement
powers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
