<P>
   EDS: April 30 marks 25 years since the fall of Saigon. This is
the second of several articles on Vietnam and the war's legacy,
there and in the United States. A special section is available on
The New York Times.Learning.Network:
www.nytimes.com/learning/saigon.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead stories:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.N.-RIGHTS (Geneva) _ China once again evades
international censure of its human rights record when it won a
procedural maneuver to block debate by the United Nations' main
rights forum. Splitting 22-18, with 12 countries abstaining, the
member countries of the U.N. Human Rights Commission rejected an
attempt to bring China to account for what the Clinton
administration says is a deteriorating human rights climate for
political dissenters, practitioners of the Falun Gong spiritual
movement, unregistered churches, Internet users, ethnic minorities
and disfavored academics and journalists. By Elizabeth Olson. (The
story has moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-GOP-BALLOT (Albany, N.Y.) _ Leaders of the legislature agree
to pass Gov. George Pataki's plan for knocking down New York's
notorious barriers to candidates getting on the Republican
presidential primary ballot, and for making that primary a
winner-take-all contest. By Richard Perez-Pena. (Scheduled to move
by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-HEROIN (Karachi, Pakistan) _ Pakistan, which does not
lead the world in much, is most likely number one when it comes to
heroin addicts. Reliable country-by-country numbers have not been
compiled, with social science a low priority in the Third World and
addicts hard to poll anyway. But the United Nations estimates there
are 1.5 million heroin addicts in this nation of 150 million, the
unfortunate result of geography, geopolitics, corruption and
poverty. By Barry Bearak. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.)
2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT15-18.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer: BUSH-CAMPAIGN (Troy, Mich.) _ Adding to a series of
recent proposals that he says are designed to give low-income
people a firmer purchase on the American dream, Gov. George W. Bush
unveils a plan to encourage private developers to build and
rehabilitate houses in run-down neighborhoods. By Frank Bruni. (The
story has moved in ``p'' news file.) 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BLIND-RUNNER (Eugene, Ore.) _ Marla Runyan suffers from a
degenerative condition of the retina called Stargardt's disease,
which has left her with a hole in the center of her vision. She has
20-300 vision in one eye, 20-400 in the other. Despite her
impairment, Runyan has an encouraging chance at the U.S. Olympic
track and field trials in July to become the first legally-blind
athlete to make an American team for the Winter or Summer Games.
Her career is remarkable for many reasons beyond her visual
impairment, and she is restless for the day when someone will write
about her as an athlete, not a legally blind athlete. By Jere
Longman. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``s'' news file.) 1,700
words.
</P>
<P>
   TRACKDATA-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Among the many evangelists
for online investing who have appeared in recent years, few have
been as ubiquitous as Baruch Israel Hertz. His New York company
promises to make investing a cinch even for novices, providing
stock quotes, market information and easy access to electronic
trading. ``You don't have to be a pro to trade like one,'' he says
on the Web site of his stock-trading system, MyTrack. But when
stocks plunged on Friday, many investors who had borrowed heavily
to play the market suddenly faced demands from their lenders that
they put up more money to cover their losses. And one of the
biggest losers was Hertz. Market Place column by Gretchen
Morgenson. 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to MARKET, story inside Business.
</P>
