<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBE SPORTS COLUMNIST TESTIFIES IN LEWIS RETRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH RANALLI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Lawyers for Celtics star Reggie Lewis's widow rested
their medical malpractice case against his former chief
cardiologist for a second time Tuesday after calling a Boston Globe
sports columnist to testify about eerily optimistic statements made
by Dr. Gilbert H. Mudge Jr. on the day Lewis died of a heart
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Columnist Will McDonough confirmed that he spoke with Mudge for
about 10 minutes on July 27, 1993, the day Lewis died. The
telephone conversation took place about an hour and a half before
Lewis collapsed while shooting baskets at Brandeis University and
died, McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reggie is doing fine,'' Mudge had said, according to
McDonough's column in the Globe the next day. ``He is working out
at his own pace. I speak with him about it. He is doing the things
he usually does at this time of year to get ready for basketball
and I think you will see, within the next two weeks, that he will
accelerate his program. I expect him to begin playing basketball
and doing all the things that players do to get ready for the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonough, in his column, said he mentioned to Mudge that other
players were already ``into their running programs, already
scrimmaging or playing pickup games with other players.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That will come,'' Mudge reportedly replied. ``Reggie is
setting his own pace. When he feels comfortable with his program,
he will continue to do more. I am very happy with this progress,
and I know from talking to him, that he is very pleased with the
way he feels.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments from Mudge, a Brigham and Women's Hospital
cardiologist, appear to portray Lewis as a player whose return to
professional basketball was imminent, not one, as defense lawyer
William J. Dailey Jr. has insisted, whom Mudge had ordered to avoid
``strenuous'' exercise because he might suffer from a potentially
fatal heart condition.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Harris-Lewis's lawsuit charges that Mudge negligently
misdiagnosed her husband with a benign fainting condition that
would not end his basketball career. McDonough was not a witness at
the first trial, which ended in a hung jury last year.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge has previously testified, however, that his optimistic
public statements were part of a strategy devised by hospital and
Celtics officials and the Lewises to keep Mudge's second, more
serious diagnosis from the public.
</P>
<P>
   In cross-examination Tuesday, Dailey tried to suggest that Mudge
withheld information from McDonough to avoid a debate in the media
over Lewis's medical condition and that his comments amounted to
nothing more than a ``polite brush-off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did Dr. Mudge indicate to you that he had given Reggie Lewis
permission to do any running?'' Daily asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' McDonough replied.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis's lawyer, Neil Rossman, rested the plaintiff's case
after McDonough's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The defense then called its own medical expert, Beth Israel
Deaconess Medical Center cardiologist Warren J. Manning, as its
first witness.
</P>
<P>
   Manning, in direct contradiction to Harris-Lewis's medical
experts, testified that Mudge actions were ``well within the
accepted standard of care'' because the best evidence from Lewis's
test pointed to neurocardiogenic syncope, a fainting disorder, not
a dangerous heart arrhythmia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything (Mudge) did was perfectly reasonable and
appropriate,'' said Manning, who also testified at the first trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
