<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0734 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-LONG-DISTANCE19-COX     04-18 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONG-DISTANCE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth continues uphill battle to offer long-distance
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When BellSouth started talking seriously about
offering long-distance, it was the largest of seven regional Bells,
Newt Gingrich was Speaker of the House and hardly anyone had heard
of Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Many things have changed, but BellSouth is still talking about
long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   And the way it looks, the company _ which has repeatedly been
forced to backtrack on predictions it would enter the market _ will
not likely have an application for long-distance in Georgia until
June.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's at the earliest,'' said David Burgess, vice chairman of
the Georgia Public Service Commission. ``If they don't meet
specifications, then it gets set back again.''
</P>
<P>
   As one of the seven Bells created in the 1984 breakup of AT&AMP;T,
BellSouth was granted a virtual monopoly in its region but was
banned from offering long-distance. A 1995 Georgia law opened the
door to offer competition in local service against BellSouth.
Passage of the Telecommunications Act a year later was meant to
free all Bells and long-distance companies to compete against each
other.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, that free-for-all was supposed to signal lower
rates and the chance to put all telecommunications services on one
bill.
</P>
<P>
   But that was then, when the Telecom Act was wildly praised by
both Gingrich and President Clinton. And this is now, when the
ranks of telecom have been thinned by a series of giant mergers,
making BellSouth the second-smallest of four Bells. And there is
approval for a Bell to offer long-distance in only one state: Bell
Atlantic in New York.
</P>
<P>
   That approval, however, seems destined to be the only one for
awhile. Controversy almost immediately surfaced over whether Bell
Atlantic's systems were really ready for full-scale competition,
with rivals charging that tens of thousands of orders were lost.
Concern over repeating the problems in New York now hang over a
request from SBC Communications for long-distance approval in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The troubles of Bell Atlantic and SBC are cold comfort to
BellSouth, which had hoped to be the first Bell to offer
long-distance. It has been more than two years since BellSouth
filed its first applications for the right to enter long-distance
in Louisiana and South Carolina. Those petitions were endorsed by
state regulators, then snubbed by the Federal Communications
Commission. Then came Bell Atlantic's problems, which only raised
the bar for BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the FCC approved long-distance entry in New York, it set
the minimum standard for what a Bell company must do to win
entry,'' said WorldCom spokesman Joseph Paluska. ``If it's fourth
down and goal to go for BellSouth, we urge the Georgia (Public
Service) Commission to help all of us get into the end zone by
completing the process thoroughly and quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   To get the Georgia PSC's endorsement, BellSouth must prove that
its systems are ready for competition, that the software and staff
can handle thousands of customers switching back and forth each day
between BellSouth and other providers. BellSouth has spent nearly
$1 billion on those systems, which handle all nine states in its
local service region.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives wearily note that BellSouth has lost about
1.5 million lines to rivals and faces 80 competitors offering local
service in Georgia alone. BellSouth prods regulators: There's
competition in local service, isn't it time to level the playing
field and let us into long-distance?
</P>
<P>
   Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   And while the law doesn't mandate that BellSouth have PSC
approval before asking federal regulators, an end-around is
unlikely. When a Bell shows up asking for long-distance, the FCC's
first question is, What do local regulators think? Unfortunately
for BellSouth, the PSC has been anything but a hometown pushover.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth in 1997 announced that long-distance was around the
corner, since its systems were prepared for local competition. That
claim was consistently challenged before the PSC _ especially by
WorldCom and AT&AMP;T. To be fair, those long-distance carriers do have
an interest in holding back the Bells from entering their primary
market. Still, it is up to regulators to referee and the PSC has
found BellSouth systems wanting.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jacobs, president of BellSouth Georgia, said the process
has pushed BellSouth to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PSC has been the best thing that has happened to us. What
we thought would be a fairly straight-forward process when the Act
was passed has become much more complex and defined.''
</P>
<P>
   And as time passed, so did various BellSouth predictions for
long-distance entry. Then, after thousands of pages in testimony
and many months of sometimes rancorous debate, BellSouth and the
PSC last summer agreed to have company systems monitored and tested
by KPMG and Hewlett-Packard. That is the same team that tested Bell
Atlantic in New York.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth predicted an application in the fall. Then, when the
testing faltered, BellSouth vowed to have a proposal to the FCC by
year's end. Y2K came and went, and BellSouth remained on the
outside of long-distance looking in. Early in 2000, BellSouth
predicted that it would file its request in April.
</P>
<P>
   Now April is half gone.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said he agrees with Burgess that an application will not
come before June. He acknowledged the previous predictions as a
mistake _ but an honest one. The company has often found itself
coping with new and unexpected requirements, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a reality, that in 1996 we thought we'd be in it by
the end of '97. But many of the things that we want the systems to
do today we never contemplated two years ago. And I can't guarantee
you there won't be an another surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's systems must handle rivals who want to buy parts of
its high-speed networks _ for instance, digital subscriber lines _
that were not part of the process in 1997, Jacobs said. ``I don't
considerate this a failure of performance on our behalf or a lack
of effort.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Burgess also praised the process but said the
responsibility for the many delays must be placed at the doorstep
of BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They finally believe that the commission will not let them go
forward until they comply with the (Telecom) Act. When it happens,
it will be good for the state and its consumers, but I want it done
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
