<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-POLICE-SCHOOTINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TWO LAWMAKERS SAY JUSTICE DEPARTMENT IS PROBING N.Y. MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two Democratic congressmen said Tuesday that the
Justice Department is investigating New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's release of damaging information about recent shooting
victims killed by city police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Charles Rangel and Jerrold Nadler, both of New York, met
with Justice Department officials earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   They told reporters that in the meeting they had urged Deputy
Attorney General Eric Holder to include Giuliani's and New York
City Police Commissioner Howard Safir's handling of the cases in
the department's current investigation of police behavior in the
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Holder had indicated he would add the mayor and the
police commissioner to the probe, Rangel replied, ``No question
about it.'' The congressman accused Giuliani of ``defaming the
reputation of the innocent victim (an unarmed security guard named
Patrick Dorismond) in order to give some balance to the (fatal)
shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice spokeswoman Kara Peterman declined to say if the
department is investigating Giuliani and Safir. But she said the
existing inquiry ``involves a careful review of all relevant
information.''
</P>
<P>
   The shootings and the Justice Department probe have already
become a major issue between Democrat Hillary Rodham Clinton and
Giuliani, her presumed Republican opponent, in their tough race for
a U.S. Senate seat from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny Mindel, a spokeswoman for the mayor, said Tuesday that
``it is not surprising that supporters of Hillary Clinton'' were
bringing such charges. She said, ``Maybe the Democratic National
Committee should investigate this, and that way we can take the
politics out of the Justice Department.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week Giuliani, reacting angrily to reporters' questions
about his views on the first lady's new economic plan, said they
were ``knee jerk, knee jerk, knee jerk'' and that they should
``join the Democratic National Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month Clinton criticized Giuliani's leadership, accusing
him of refusing ``to reach out, to work with a community that is in
pain'' over the fatal police shooting last year of an unarmed West
African immigrant, Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the congressmen charged that after his death police
illegally searched Diallo's apartment trying to find evidence that
he was a drug dealer. Diallo was killed by four police officers,
who fired 41 bullets at him in February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter written to Holder on April 6, the congressmen said
police had no reason to suspect Diallo of narcotics trafficking and
that they ``ransacked the apartment'' hoping to find a way to
``defame'' him.
</P>
<P>
   The four policemen charged in his death were acquitted two
months ago by a jury in Albany, N.Y., where the trial had been
moved.
</P>
<P>
   At their news conference Tuesday, Rangel and Nadler discussed
their April 6 letter citing instances of Giuliani's or Safir's
release of information damaging to victims of police shootings.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers noted that in defending undercover police in the
shooting death of Dorismond in Manhattan, Giuliani released his
sealed juvenile criminal record and his adult record of arrests for
gun possession and assault even though he was not convicted of
either charge.
</P>
<P>
   After police officers killed a man named Gidone Busch last
August, the congressmen recalled, Safir quoted seven civilian
witnesses as saying that the officers had shot Busch as he was
assaulting a fallen police sergeant with a hammer.
</P>
<P>
   Nadler and Rangel said in their letter that ``it is now
universally acknowledged'' by witnesses that Busch was holding a
hammer over his head but wasn't attacking any officer when he was
shot.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel said Tuesday that the release of damaging information
about victims was possibly ``encouraging wrongdoing by policemen
who find themselves in a situation where they've made a terrible
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Nadler said the release of the information has been ``in every
case irrelevant and in many cases violating constitutional
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The congressmen insisted they were not making the charges for
political reasons but said they wanted to improve community
relations with the police.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Serafin, another Giuliani spokeswoman, said that ``voters
will see this (the congressmen's attack on the mayor) for what it
is. The NYPD record of reducing crime is only exceeded by its
record of restraint.''
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
