<HEADLINE>
HOUSING STARTS PLUNGE 11 PERCENT, BUT INTEREST RATES ESCAPE BLAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Housing starts plunged 11.2 percent in March, the largest drop
in six years, but the decline was attributed entirely to a slowdown
in construction of apartments and other multifamily housing, while
single-family housing starts were unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that overall March housing
starts fell to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.604 million,
down sharply from the February rate of 1.807 million and well below
most analysts' predictions. Single-family housing starts,
considered a less volatile and more meaningful reflection of
whether interest rates are beginning to crimp construction, stayed
about the same, at an annual rate of 1.309 million.
</P>
<P>
   Though the news may have somewhat aided the rebound in the stock
market, which was hammered Friday in part because of fears of
rising consumer prices, industry officials and analysts said the
report that was issued yesterday offered little evidence that
interest-rate increases were significantly hurting home sales. In
fact, some said the housing market appeared surprisingly strong,
considering that the Federal Reserve had raised interest rates five
times since last summer.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the numbers for single-family homes, housing
starts for apartments and other buildings with at least five units
fell 41 percent to an annual rate of 272,000 units during March,
accounting for almost all the decline in the overall numbers.
Similarly, building permits issued in March fell sharply for
apartment buildings but were unchanged for single-family houses,
the Commerce Department said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carliner, an economist with the National Association of
Home Builders, attributed the decline in apartment starts partly to
an unusually strong February that was helped by warm weather. As
for new single-family houses, he said the interest rate increases
``clearly have not been enough to have a big effect on construction
yet,'' adding that in surveys builders cite labor shortages as a
bigger problem. And although the association's monthly survey of
builders' optimism was 62 in April, down from 77 last June, largely
because of interest rate concerns, Carliner noted that it was still
far above the historical average of about 50.
</P>
<P>
   At Toll Brothers, a builder in Huntingdon Valley, Pa., that
specializes in luxury houses, a backlog has steadily risen even as
the company has raised prices. The number of refundable deposits
placed in March for developments open at least one year rose 5
percent compared with March of last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hoping by raising prices to slow that backlog down a
little, but so far the market has been pretty able to absorb the
price increases,'' said Fred Cooper, vice president for finance at
Toll Brothers. ``We've been chugging along. We keep our fingers
crossed a little bit with the stock market volatility, but we
really haven't seen any market change.''
</P>
<P>
   Centex Homes, a unit of Centex Corp., a Dallas builder, said
that higher interest rates had hurt sales in the first two months
of the year but that March and April had been strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do expect that continued increases in the fed funds rate
will translate to increased mortgage rates, which will slow down
the housing market during the year,'' said Tim Eller, chief
executive of Centex Homes. But ``for us right now, it's a little
surprising the market is as strong as it is. We're expecting it to
slow, but it's wait and see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
