<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ A growing rift among House Democrats
is undermining Clinton administration efforts to secure
congressional approval this year for permanent normal trade
relations with China, a top legislative priority for the White
House. The administration's effort will be dealt a major blow
Wednesday when House Democratic Leader Richard Gephardt is expected
to announce that he will vote against the measure. By GREG
McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-APPEALS (Washington) _ A splintered Supreme Court makes
it more difficult for condemned killers and other inmates to
challenge the constitutionality of their state-court convictions in
federal court. In a separate case, the justices unanimously ease
the burden on convicts who are trying to introduce evidence on
appeal that improprieties at trial led to their conviction. By
STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   GIULIANI-POLICE-SHOOTINGS (Washington) _ The Justice Department
agrees to investigate New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's release of
damaging information about victims of city police shootings. New
York Democratic Reps. Charles Rangel and Jerrold Nadler, who had
urged the department to investigate, accuse the mayor of defaming
the victims and say they hope the federal probe will lead to better
handling of such cases. By AUSTIN ZALKIN. Story will also be filed
in the POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' ) category.
</P>
<P>
   WEATHER-SATELLITE (Washington) _ The nation's network of
orbiting weather eyes is expected to be back at full strength next
month following the launch of a satellite to replace one that began
malfunctioning two years ago. By PHILIP CAUTHON.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MICHIGAN (Battle Creek, Mich.) _ Presidential hopeful
George W. Bush, appealing anew to voters who have tended to support
Democrats, proposes $1.7 billion to increase housing for low-income
people. Bush's plan would give a tax credit to developers to
refurbish existing houses. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-CUSTODY (Miami) _ A public relations battle continues
between supporters of Elian Gonzalez, the Cuban boy who was found
adrift at sea, and the government, which now has a pediatrician's
letter suggesting the boy is being psychologically abused by
relatives. By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SHRIMPERS (San Antonio) _ Texas commercial shrimpers say
they are confused and alarmed by recent warnings from state
officials that the fishery may collapse unless the harvest is
reduced. By JOHN MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-LEAVE (Havana) _ As the Cuban government struggles to bring
6-year-old Elian Gonzalez back, thousands of its citizens seek to
leave the country. Last year, more than 100,000 Cubans signed up
for visas from the United States, but only 20,000 were granted. A
look at the Cubans who are lining up to leave. By DUDLEY ALTHAUS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ It was sad to watch the grubby
protesters who tried unsuccessfully this week to recreate the
turbulent '60s with garbled complaints against the World Bank and
International Monetary Fund. The demonstrators brought the city to
a temporary halt but were no match for the well-behaved cops.
Forget it, kids. You don't have the right stuff and you don't have
a universal cause. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' sports)BKN-BLINEBURY (Phoenix) _ A column on
injured basketball star CharlesBarkley of the Houston Rockets and
his bid to return for one final game before his career ends. By
FRAN BLINEBURY.
</P>
</TEXT>
