u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      04-18 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: PREMIER LOOKING TO QUIT
</P>
<P>
   With Prime Minister Massimo d'Alema appearing intent on
announcing his resignation to Parliament on Wednesday after losing
regional elections on Sunday, his shaken coalition was ponderering
whom to propose to try to form a new center-left majority. If
Parliament does not approve a candidate, President Carlo Azeglio
Ciampi will either appoint a caretaker government or call
elections, now likely to favor the big winner in the regional vote,
former Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi, above, leader of the
center-right.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: BLAIR IN TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair spent five hours with politicians in
Belfast and the evening with his Irish counterpart Bertie Ahern in
Dublin but failed to find a way out of the impasse over disarmament
that has stalled the Ulster peace accord. Describing the talks as
constructive, he said there was determination to find a way forward
but no consensus yet on how to do it.
</P>
<P>
   HUNGARY: FLEEING FLOODS
</P>
<P>
   The Tisza, the country's second biggest river, reached its
highest level ever, and 68 communities were ordered evacuated. More
than 23,000 people worked on building and reinforcing dikes, and
the government's budget for flood prevention was not expected to be
enough. In February the river was badly polluted by a cyanide spill
from a Romanian gold mine.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: SLAVE WORKERS' FUND
</P>
<P>
   The Association of German Insurance Business, which represents
463 companies, will contribute $250,000 to a fund to compensate
former Nazi slave laborers. German industry has pledged to
contribute $2.5 billion to the fund, but despite the participation
of 1,300 companies has so far raised only $1.2 billion. Another
$2.5 billion will come from the government.
</P>
<P>
   CZECH REPUBLIC: GYPSIES SUE
</P>
<P>
   Claiming discrimination and segregation of their children in
schools, 18 Gypsy families filed a complaint against the Czech
Republic with the European Court of Human Rights in Strasbourg. The
Gypsy parents say their children have been wrongfully transferred
to schools for retarded pupils, losing their chance to obtain
further education and pursue an adequate career.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: 13 TO BE FREED
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak's security cabinet, meeting in special
session, said it would abide by the Supreme Court order to release
Lebanese detainees. By Wednesday the government will free 13 of the
15 Lebanese detainees, held as ``bargaining chips'' for missing
Israeli soldiers. Arguing that the remaining two, who are guerrilla
leaders, represent threats to state security, the government will
keep them imprisoned and a hearing on their continued custody was
scheduled for May 8.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE: CHOLERA KILLS 32
</P>
<P>
   Health officials have reported 32 deaths from cholera as a
result of poor sanitary conditions after the huge floods of
February and March. The officials are opening new wards for the
treatment of cholera and diarrhea and are renewing a public
awareness campaign to help people prevent the spread of disease.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   PERU: TOLEDO'S WARNING
</P>
<P>
   Alejandro Toledo, who is challenging President Alberto
Fujimori's re-election, threatened to drop out of the race in a
week if sweeping changes are not made in the government's electoral
apparatus and the television networks are not totally opened for
broadcast of his campaign advertising and events. Toledo came in
second in the April 9 first-round vote, which was largely
discredited by international observers.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: TOP REBEL SEIZED
</P>
<P>
   The police have announced the arrest of a leftist guerrilla
leader who they say directed the kidnapping of 160 middle-class
churchgoers in Cali nearly a year ago. Antonio Parra, an Army of
National Liberation field commander, was captured near Cali. In a
raid that provoked nationwide indignation, the worshippers were
seized while attending Mass last May and held for ransom, with the
last of them being freed only in December.
</P>
</TEXT>
