<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEPHARDT'S VOTE ON CHINA A SETBACK TO CLINTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a setback to White House efforts to win approval
from Congress for permanent normalized trade relations with China,
Democratic leader Dick Gephardt will vote against the measure when
the House takes it up next month.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman planned to announce his opposition to the trade
relations proposal during a speech Wednesday in his hometown of St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The move was unexpected by President Clinton and Republican
leaders who have joined with Clinton in hopes of pushing through
the measure over objections of labor, environmental and human
rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt has long been against any kind of normalized trade
arrangement with China, unless it includes agreements that would
force Beijing to comply with minimal labor, environmental and human
rights standards.
</P>
<P>
   His speech Wednesday is aimed at making that position clear,
although aides said he will also stress that he has no intention of
lobbying other Democrats to vote against the legislation. The
proposal would drop Congress' annual review of China's trade status
and help clear the way for the communist country to enter the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important is that he's going to let Democrats ... vote
on this up or down on the merits,'' said presidential spokesman
Jake Siewert. ``We think, given a chance to explain the merits of
this deal to the Democratic caucus, that we'll secure enough
support to approve the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials are confident as the May debate on the
measure approaches that they already have at least 65 Democratic
votes and more than 160 Republican votes lined up, enough to give
them a majority in the House. The Senate is also expected to muster
at least 60 votes in favor of the measure.
</P>
<P>
   But one White House aide said Tuesday that Clinton is concerned
that the House minority leader's opposition could give cover to
Democrats looking for an excuse to oppose the measure, which could
siphon off some votes that Clinton is counting on.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, in his eagerness to win the support of
organized labor in this year's presidential race, has already
provided some cover for undecided Democrats by telling union
leaders that he would support stronger environmental and labor
safeguards in future trade agreements with China.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has expressed his support for passage of the measure this
year. But his comments to union officials were meant to signal that
if the legislation is put off for another year he will move to
strengthen it with provisions more agreeable to U.S. labor and
environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gephardt's opposition to improved trade ties with China
is nothing new, it is more significant in an election year when
Democrats are trying to regain control of the House with the help
of both labor and business interests.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, with Gephardt leading the way, have been fairly
successful this year in drumming up financial support from both.
But some Democrats, led by Rep. Bob Matsui, D-Calif., believe that
voting against permanent trade status with China could end up
hurting some of the party's candidates in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce and other major U.S. business
groups are already targeting wavering lawmakers in some five dozen
districts, where the races this fall could be tight. Lawmakers in
many of those districts are feeling the squeeze as well from
organized labor, which is pulling out all stops to kill the China
trade measure.
</P>
<P>
   Matsui heads a group called the New Democratic Coalition that
promotes the idea that the best way to provide more and better U.S.
jobs is to do everything possible to open up the Chinese market to
more American exports.
</P>
<P>
   China has promised more market access to U.S. exports in return
for permanent trade status and entry to the World Trade
Organization. But Gephardt will say today that those agreements do
not include the kind of labor, environmental and human rights
assurances needed to protect American jobs, or the personal and
property investments of American business interests there.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Republican leaders were quick to emphasize the
split among Democrats over the issue. They are calling Gephardt and
others who might side with him ``out of step with the mainstream''
view of most Americans who are in favor of opening up more U.S.
markets abroad. They criticized Gephardt for caving in to organized
labor interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rep. Gephardt's opposition to permanent normal trade relations
for China is a victory for the special interests, but it's a
tremendous loss for the thousands of workers and farmers that
depend on trade with China each year,'' said House Ways and Means
Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
