<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0755 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ONLINE-ANTIQUARIANS-2     04-18 1440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-ANTIQUARIANS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUST FLIES AS ANTIQUARIAN BOOKSELLERS REACT TO ONLINE OPERATIONS  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore. Wis., Nev., Calif., Spain, Canada)   By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For decades, the antiquarian trade has remained the dusty,
genteel corner of the book market, attracting fiercely independent
booksellers who savor the musty fragrance of brown-spotted rag
paper and the Eureka moment of spotting a rare first edition dumped
in a garage sale heap.
</P>
<P>
   But now the dust motes are flying in the rare and used book
market with the flashy emergence of Alibris, an online used
bookseller that has Wall Street ambitions, Silicon Valley money,
and a strategy that is roiling one of the last bastions of the book
market where small dealers still hold sway. With financial
resources totaling more than $60 million in venture capital,
Alibris is a mix of Internet start-up and industry upstart, a
two-year-old company with a cheeky national advertising campaign
aimed at building a mighty brand on the spines of old books.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business has never had this public persona,'' said Susan
Siegel, who with her husband annually publishes ``The Used Book
Lover's Guides,'' a series of seven regional handbooks. ``It's just
been these little stores that book-aholics and collectors and
academics know about. The Internet has changed that, and
Alibris.com is dealing with customers in a more sophisticated
marketing way that was never needed before.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the battering that Internet companies suffered on the
stock market last week, some analysts question whether Alibris'
plans to lavish as much as $100 million on advertising will be
money well spent.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester Research, an Internet research firm, recently issued a
report predicting that increasing competitive pressures will drive
many e-commerce companies out of business by next year. They advise
companies to redirect resources from expensive ``branding
campaign'' into hard assets, service and speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen their ads and they're very cute,'' said Carrie
Johnson, a Forrester analyst for on-line retail commerce. ``But so
are all these other pure plays that have burned through $50 million
in advertising, and we're watching these disappear. Unfortunately,
there's not a lot of room for new brands.''
</P>
<P>
   Some defiant dealers are refusing to supply books for its Web
site, which draws titles from booksellers lower in the literary
chain and then inspects and marks them up for sale. Others are
searching for alternatives, testing a cooperative Web site of
dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are booksellers who are happily working with the
high-profile newcomer, arguing that Alibris is trying to do what
the vast majority could never afford _ expand the rarified demand
for rare and used books into a mass market.
</P>
<P>
   The hostilities that Alibris has provoked among some traditional
booksellers mirror the same tensions that other industries are
facing over issues of consolidation and the loss of personal
connections. Alibris has stirred the anxieties of many dealers, in
large part because of its corporate trappings and strategies that
stand out among the others like a new paperback on a shelf of
leather-bound editions.
</P>
<P>
   It is not as if Alibris is simply introducing new technology to
the business. The Internet has already helped increase the number
and reach of independent dealers. According to Siegel's survey, the
business has expanded strongly since 1996, gaining 21 percent more
dealers to reach 7,095 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has enabled many sellers of used book to expand
their customer base to the entire world,'' Siegel said. Sales over
the Web make up from 10 to 50 percent of gross sales for the
dealers she has tracked.
</P>
<P>
   But the vast majority of these dealers are tiny operations. By
contrast, Alibris has a growing staff of 100 at its administrative
offices in Emeryville, a warehouse of books in Sparks, Nev. and
another distribution warehouse planned for England.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as the trade has evolved in the last two years, the
titans from the glossier side of the book business are developing a
yearning for dogeared dustjackets. Amazon.com bought
Bibliofind.com, a database for used book dealers last April.
Barnesandnoble.com struck a supply partnership with Alibris earlier
this year. This month, the nation's largest book distributor,
Ingram Book Group, announced its participation in a $30 million
round of new financing to support Alibris' marketing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Its pricey Madison Avenue advertising campaign has appeared in
The New Yorker, USA Today and Gourmet, promoting battered copies of
books like Lewis Padgett's '50s vintage ``Mutant.'' (April 11,
1977. Freaked you out so bad you had to bury it. Jan. 25, 2000.
Unearth on Alibris for son who shares your sci-fi gene.'')
</P>
<P>
   There's more to come. In the next five years, said Martin
Manley, chief executive of the company, Alibris hopes to spend at
least $100 million to market its titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people have tried to computerize the supply side of the
business,'' said Manley, a former assistant secretary of labor in
the Clinton administration. ``But nobody has taken on the job of
creating demand for this product. Most people believe they can't
find books from their childhood, but using e-commerce techniques we
can bring those materials to the market and we can educate these
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even with the recent market rumblings, taking the company public
is a strategy that Alibris is still considering for the future,
Manley said. ``Changes in the capital market are not going to
change the business strategy,'' he said. ``We've always been
focused on the retailer and distributor because nobody else is.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Alibris bills itself as the leading source of rare and
hard-to-find books, but there are other existing online services
for used books with a larger pool of dealers _ at least for the
moment. Advanced Book Exchange, which is based in Victoria, British
Columbia offers books from more than 6,000 dealers, compared with
about 1,500 that Alibris says have joined its fold.
</P>
<P>
   But Alibris is moving aggressively to expand. Last October, it
announced the purchase of Bibliocity, an electronic source of rare
and antiquarian books. Meanwhile, Alibris has been eyeing ABE, with
its list of almost four million titles and 18 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Alibris had made overtures to its competitor, Manley
chose his words carefully: ``We've never had substantial
discussions with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some independent dealers fear that Alibris is moving to create a
monopoly, a fear that was intensified by some recent sharp
Internet-style elbowing for space. In early March,
Barnesandnoble.com alerted antiquarian dealers that it had struck a
new partnership with Alibris to fill its used book orders. That
means that Alibris will be listed first when customers request
out-of-print books from the BN.com Web site. In the past, those
orders had been filled primarily through ABE, which will now be the
second choice.
</P>
<P>
   This change provoked dissent among many dealers because they
could earn more money offering titles through Advanced Book
Exchange, which charges about a $35 monthly fee to list 3,000 books
and leaves it to dealers to fill the orders directly and to keep
the price of the book. In contrast, Alibris exacts about a 20
percent cut of the dealer's final retail price.It operates by
demanding copies for inspection at its Nevada distribution site,
and then repackages the title under the Alibris brand at a
marked-up price for reshipment to a customer.
</P>
<P>
   What particularly irritates some dealers is that the Alibris
process eliminates direct contact with the customer. From her
cramped 840-square-foot Red Wheelbarrow Bookstore in Milwaukee,
Barbara Lightner refuses to list any of the titles in her book
collection specializing in ``avant garde'' political literature.
Instead, she hopes to maintain contact with a wide range of
customers directly through the Internet, which already accounts for
30 percent of her revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barnesandnoble drove a lot of independents out of business and
some used book dealers said Alibris could never do that to us
because we control the supply chain,'' said Lightner, a former
literature instructor at Purdue University who started her
bookstore about two years ago. ``But some of us are concerned that
they could control the databases that we use to make our Internet
sales, and they would be able to destroy our ability to make as
much money on those sales.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Judith Lowry, a second generation bookseller and co-owner of the
seven-decade-old Argosy Book Store suspects that Internet sales are
having an impact on walk-in traffic for her six-story bookstore in
Manhattan. For the first time in 10 years in-store sales are down
slightly. But she gives credit to Alibris for its advertising
campaign, which she says is having a balancing, positive effect.
``As they advertise more, we get more orders,'' she said. ``When we
first started we'd sell five books a week and now it's 15 books
this morning for Alibris.''
</P>
<P>
   The multiplication of online sales has allowed dealers like
Christine Volk, of Volk &AMP; Iams Booksellers, to work from Amador
County in the foothills of rural northern California. Her Internet
sales make up her entire business, which specializes in first
editions in African-American and children's literature. Working
from her outpost with a view of snow-capped Sierras and wild
turkeys, she maintains contact with customers through email and a
new Web site, Bookfever.com.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn DeWeese-Parkinson, a former trial lawyer, makes about 80
percent of his sales on-line and the rest by appointment and
catalogue sales from his home in Cornelius, Oregon. He also
shepherds a continuing and lively debate among book dealers through
his electronic bulletin board, Bibliophile.
</P>
<P>
   For both Volk and DeWeese-Parkinson customer contact _ in all
forms _ is the difference between being a bookseller or a supplier.
It is the reason they do not list their books with Alibris.
</P>
<P>
   Alibris' chief executive, Manley, said he sympathizes with
dealers who want to maintain close ties with customers. But ``a
brand is a promise of reliability, quality, returnability,'' he
said, ``and you can't build a brand out of 2,000 dealers. You build
a brand out of a name.''
</P>
<P>
   That notion is like a red flag for DeWeese-Parkinson whose
specialty is Mexican bullfighting literature. ``Alibris stands
between me and the customer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that as a small specialty dealer the only way I can
stay in business is to be buying for those customers.''
</P>
<P>
   In many cases those relationships are held together by e-mail
since his customers are scattered around the world from Pamplona,
Spain to Providence R.I. ``Finding those people,'' he said, ``is
much more important than the hot experience of finding a nifty book
in a corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Those relationships are at the heart of what makes selling rare
books so personal. When his 22-year-old daughter, Meggan Parkinson,
died in a car crash in May 1997 his book customers arranged for
masses to be said in Guatemala, the United States, Spain and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Before his daughter's death, DeWeese-Parkinson had planned to
race along with her during the running of the bulls in Pamplona.
Instead one of his regular customers, Joe Distler, ran with the
bulls, wearing a sash with Meggan's name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
