<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0757 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-ACTIVIST-AR     04-18 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-ACTIVIST-ART-2TAKES(1055)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIVIST IN CUBAN BOY CASE EMERGES AS A POWER TO BE RECKONED WITH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT20 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ For 35 years, Ramon Saul Sanchez, the man now behind the
army of Little Havana demonstrators, waged war with a cabal of
likeminded warriors. The men, who belonged to a network of
paramilitary groups, practiced armed combat in the underbrush,
plotted violent overthrows of Fidel Castro and, in some cases,
planted real bombs that did real damage.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the early 1980s, Sanchez, under subpoena, refused to
testify before a grand jury against one of the fiercest anti-Castro
paramilitary groups, Omega 7. He served four and a half years in an
Indiana prison, and walked out a disciple of the Rev. Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sanchez, with his round-the-clock vigils outside the home
of Elian Gonzalez's great-uncle and his campaigns of civil
disobedience, has emerged as a pivotal figure in the standoff over
the 6-year-old Cuban boy. And in so doing, he has elbowed his way
into the Cuban-American political hierarchy that has long been
ruled by a handful of powerful organizations, most notably the
Cuban-American National Foundation, a lobbying group.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly five months of fruitless wrangling with the Justice
Department, Congress and the courts, it is Sanchez's street
tactics, and not the work of the mainstream Cuban-American leaders,
that has forced the federal government to back down repeatedly from
reuniting Elian with his father, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to sweat with the people, cry with the people, hope
with the people, go to jail with the people and also smile,'' said
Sanchez, 46, who lives with his parents and says he owns only a
white Sidekick and a heap of clothes. ``You have to be with them.
You can't get them to respond to you, if you are on the 10th floor
of a building somewhere trying to direct them by remote control.''
</P>
<P>
   But in moving the focus from the office towers to the streets,
Sanchez has done more than just add a fresh dimension to the fight
for Elian's future, as he puts it. He also has broken from the path
Cuban Americans have traditionally chosen in battling Fidel Castro,
a course that began early on with guns and bombs under the cover of
darkness and later shifted to money and influence in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Although it remains the dominant political organization in
Miami's Cuban community, and many still cherish it, the
Cuban-American National Foundation has been struggling to keep its
footing, clout and relevance since the 1997 death of its powerful
leader Jorge Mas Canosa, some exile leaders and academic experts
say.
</P>
<P>
   In the Elian case, the group has done what it does best,
lobbying Congress and the Justice Department to resolve the
situation peacefully and give Elian's relatives in Miami the chance
to make their case in court.
</P>
<P>
   But a telling moment came last week, when its president, Jorge
Mas Santos, Mas Canosa's son, set out to broker a deal in
Washington that would have reunited the two families. After the
deal was done, he announced the arrangement in front of television
cameras.
</P>
<P>
   But the crowd in Little Havana, outraged over the possibility of
having to turn the boy over, prodded Lazaro Gonzalez, Elian's
great-uncle, to reject the deal. Angrily, Gonzalez did just that in
a late-night news conference. Some in the community saw it as a
defiant gesture of independence from the group.
</P>
<P>
   Mas, who is nevertheless routinely cheered in front of the
house, said last week in an interview that the Justice Department
had changed the ground rules after the deal had been struck. At
that point the Foundation backed away from the arrangement, as did
the family in Miami, Mas said.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory B. Craig, the lawyer for Elian's father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, has denied that.
</P>
<P>
   The inability to finalize the deal has been seen by some experts
as the kind of shakiness in the Foundation's leadership that has
left room for an upstart like Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the death of Mas Canosa, Sanchez has been the
Cuban-American leader that has gained the most prominence,'' said
Dario Moreno, an associate professor of political science at
Florida International University, who said Cuban leaders often view
street demonstrations as counter-productive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the other political leaders have much more political
power and much more influence in the boardrooms,'' he added. ``But
it is Ramon Saul Sanchez who has influence in the streets, in being
able to control the protests.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez often evokes the disdain and skepticism of more
traditional exile leaders, and even some academics caution that his
influence is untested over the long term and could fade when the
Elian case is over.
</P>
<P>
   Ninoska Perez, a spokeswoman for the Foundation, sidestepped the
opportunity to be critical of Sanchez, and wondered whether any
political group has persuaded people to turn out in such large
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of the people there don't necessarily belong to
one organization or another,'' she said. ``They are there because
of their dedication to the cause of Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez's organization, Movimiento Democracia, runs on a
shoestring budget of $5 and $10 contributions, and some in the
community point out that he has few political connections or
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   At worst, Sanchez is seen as an interloper who angers people by
tying up traffic and using publicity stunts to promote himself. In
the end, it may be that Sanchez has served only to prolong Elian's
inevitable return, a delay that could further sully the reputation
of the Cuban-American community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody in Ramon Saul Sanchez's position is almost in a
situation where they either have to make something happen or
something has to happen that they didn't create, like Elian,'' said
Jose Garcia-Pedrosa, a lawyer for Lazaro Gonzalez, and a fixture in
the Cuban-American elite. ``That inures to Sanchez's detriment
because you can't always control these events.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many other Cuban-American powerbrokers, Sanchez has
publicly immersed himself in the Elian case, and many people in the
community have responded to his dedication and his rapport with the
demonstrators. He sleeps only a few hours a night in a trailer near
Gonzalez's house, fueling himself with Cuban coffee and adrenaline.
His cell phone rings every 30 seconds, it seems; last month, it
logged 6,200 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He is different from traditional leaders, who are mostly
upper-middle-class professionals, in one other way, as well; he
earns $30,000 as a clerk for a nonprofit housing group. Few in the
community had ever heard of him five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When the crowd gets too riled-up, or a skirmish threatens, he
sprints for the barricades, grabs a megaphone and soothes people,
mostly by dispelling rumors and reminding them that their ugly
behavior will taint the community's already tarnished image. One
night, outside of the house of Sister Jeanne O'Laughlin, where a
group had gathered while Elian was inside, Sanchez headed off a
confrontation by urging people to form a large prayer circle.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, he has gained the trust of the family and now acts as
one of their advisers; at this late date, he is still gently
persuading them to meet with Elian's father to try to ensure a
peaceful outcome.
</P>
<P>
   In January, when the government first stepped-up the pressure on
the Gonzalez family, Sanchez, whose good looks and measured charm
have turned him into a media darling, helped organized the first
major demonstration, a march through downtown Miami and a sit-in in
front of the Port of Miami. A number of people were peacefully
arrested that day. He has also called for traffic tie-ups, which
has drawn the ire of Miami residents.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has helped orchestrate, with the support of
Spanish-language radio, the nightly vigils, all of them peaceful,
along with the idea for the human chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has managed to control the situation really well,'' said
Jose Basulto, the head of Brothers to the Rescue, a prominent
Cuban-American group. ``At any given time, the possibility of
demonstrations has kept Janet Reno from sending the boy back to
Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez said he set out 13 years ago to create an alternative to
the major groups and their way of doing things by promoting
nonviolence and civil disobedience. ``I got called some names as
you can imagine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His group first drew attention with its yearly flotilla, a
contingent of boats that pressed right up to Cuban waters. Once
there, flowers were dropped and prayers were sent Cuba's way. It
was pure symbolic theater. But when the U.S. government seized one
of his boats in 1998, he went on a hunger strike to get it back and
lost 31 pounds in 21 days. People in the community started to take
notice.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last summer, when the Coast Guard used fire hoses on a
group of Cuban refugees who had sailed on to a local beach, Sanchez
mobilized people to block the major bridge leading to Miami Beach,
the tourist mecca. That helped persuade the federal government not
to send the refugees back.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some question whether Sanchez's tactics will really do much to
turn Cuba into a democracy. ``He is as much a part of the problem
as the solution,'' said Max Castro, who researches exile politics
at the University of Miami. ``As much as I disagree with the
Foundation completely, it's a serious organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez said he worries mostly about keeping the peace among
demonstrators now, especially if marshals have to tear Elian away
from his relatives. ``How do we show people that we do care about
the nation and the laws?'' he asked rhetorically. ``How do we focus
the attention of the world back on Cuba?''
</P>
<P>
   The endgame could make or break this fledgling leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he succeeds,'' Basulto said. ``But it will be a test of
his ability to control the crowd if this thing takes place in front
of the eyes of everybody there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
