<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 LOOKING LIKE THE STARS LOOK 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Cheryl Shuman-Theo &LR; , who says she is a ``former international
fashion model'' and nowadays calls herself ``optician to the
stars,'' has announced ``Starry Eyes,'' her new line of glasses
``identical to the stars' original designs in hit films and
television shows.''
</P>
<P>
   The first collection, which may be seen in June on the Web at
 &LR; www.StarryEyes.com &LR; , will include frames similar to those in
``Erin Brockovich,'' ``Wonder Boys'' and ``Mission Impossible II.''
Shuman-Theo's glasses have appeared in ``The Terminator,'' ``When
Harry Met Sally ...,'' ``Jurassic Park'' and ``Evita'' (``Don't Cry
for Me, Myopia'').
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; LITERARY ASIDES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _Tarzan didn't have a beard because ``vine sliding is hell on
your testosterone output,'' says  &UR; Matt Buka &LR; . The  &UR; Edgar Rice &LR; 
 &UR; Burroughs &LR;  books, however, describe him teaching himself to shave
with his father's hunting knife because he didn't want to look like
an ape. ``Almost daily, he whetted his keen knife and scraped and
whittled at his young beard to eradicate this degrading emblem of
apehood,'' says a passage forwarded by  &UR; Kash &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Painter  &UR; Julian Schnabel &LR; 's new movie is ``Before Night Falls,''
based on a memoir of  &UR; Reinaldo Arenas &LR; , a gay Cuban poet who came
to the United States during the 1970 Mariel boat lift, suffered
from AIDS and committed suicide 10 years ago. According to
artnet.com, the poet is played by  &UR; Javier Bardem &LR;  and the cast
includes  &UR; Sean Penn &LR; , as an old Cuban peasant, and  &UR; Johnny Depp &LR; ,
who plays both a drag queen and a Cuban army captain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The hard, dreary life of the people and the conditions under &LR; 
 &UR; which they live are very monotonous to one who knows of the high &LR; 
 &UR; state of civilization here. For my own part, I could have been &LR; 
 &UR; happy there _ but for this. In fact there were times, and I &LR; 
 &UR; still have the impression that it would have been better for me &LR; 
 &UR; had I never been brought to civilization and educated. It leaves &LR; 
 &UR; me between two extremes, where it would seem that I can get &LR; 
 &UR; nowhere.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Minik Wallace &LR; , a young Eskimo brought to the United States
with his father and four others in 1897 by explorer  &UR; Robert &LR; 
 &UR; Peary &LR; . After his father and three of the others died, Minik
traveled back and forth to Greenland, unable to find a place he
could comfortably consider home. He died of the flu, at 28, in
1918. The story of Minik, ``cut off from his people, his language
and his sense of belonging in the world,'' writes  &UR; Kevin Spacey &LR;  in
his introduction to &UR; Kenn Harper &LR; 's ``Give Me My Father's Body''
(Steerforth Press; $24), has eerie parallels to that of
 &UR; Elian Gonzalez &LR;  (about whom, it was announced Monday, April 17, CBS
will make a miniseries or movie).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
