<HEADER>
A0761 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ETHIOPIA-JEWS-NYT     04-18 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHIOPIA-JEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHIOPIANS WITH JEWISH ROOTS YEARN TO GO TO ISRAEL
</HEADLINE>
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia _ The Jewish center was packed on Tuesday,
the day before Passover. Children sang in Hebrew. The ritual bath
was filled. Three rows of workers flattened dough for matzo, baked
in 30 ovens so smoky that the place seemed on fire.
</P>
<P>
   If the people at the Beta Israel Community are not really Jews _
and the Israeli government says it has doubts _ they certainly work
hard at their religious practices.
</P>
<P>
   They are among the 26,000 people still in Ethiopia who claim to
be Jewish and want to leave for Israel. To them and their many
supporters, they are the ones left behind. In Israel, the Ethiopian
population has increased to 70,000 people after waves of
immigration since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something special,'' Andrew Goldman, an American with a
charity that assists the group, said on Tuesday as he helped
prepare the center for Passover, which celebrates the exodus from
Egypt. ``These people have been crossing the Red Sea in my
lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Israeli government has been slow to act on their
requests, saying their ties to Judaism are not as certain as those
of the Ethiopians who clearly maintained their faith and were
allowed to emigrate in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Some government officials say they worry that the motives are
really economic: Ethiopia is one of the poorest nations, made worse
by a severe food shortage in the last several months, and Jews here
are among the worst off.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, pressure has mounted over the issue, as the Israeli
Supreme Court last month ordered the government to develop a plan
to process the Ethiopians' immigration applications. Earlier this
month, Natan Sharansky, the Israeli interior minister, visited to
see the situation firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his trip, he promised that applications would be
handled more quickly. Some people have been waiting 10 years. And
he said he was horrified at the cramped and filthy houses where
people are living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can compare them only to the punishment cells in the Soviet
Union, in which I spent years,'' Sharansky, a former Soviet
dissident, told reporters in Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
   But he was firm that Israel would approve only those with strong
claims under the law that governs who is considered Jewish. ``We
can't open up for everyone who wants to come,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They are known as Falash Mura, and what complicates their claim
to be Jewish is that in many cases, their families converted to
Christianity a few generations ago. Descendants say the families
did so to avoid an emerging persecution from Ethiopia's large
Christian population.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hated,'' said Mitiku Yalew, chairman of the Addis
Ababa Beta Israel Community. ``They told us we had the evil eye.''
</P>
<P>
   His story is like many others. His grandfather, he said, was a
practicing Jew near Gondar in the rugged north who taught Hebrew.
Fifty years ago, as Christians in the area harassed the Jews, his
father converted.
</P>
<P>
   But Yalew said the conversion was only ``pretend,'' a situation
that often was plain to Christians, too. The family did not go to
church. There was little intermarriage. Many Falash Mura still
cannot be buried in Christian cemeteries.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many people gave up Jewish religious practices
because they were afraid of provoking their neighbors. ``We didn't
have any teachers to teach us about the Torah,'' said Yalew, who
began observing Judaism five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Yeshinesh Koye, 19, said her grandfather converted to
Christianity, but the family ended up practicing neither religion
until recently. She has a cross tattooed to her forehead, common
among the Falash Mura as a way of convincing Christians that they
were not Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why she began to observe Judaism, she answered: ``It is my
religion. It is inherited from my ancestors.''
</P>
<P>
   This ambiguity makes it hard to sort out the claims, Israeli
officials say. Sharansky noted that there are few written records.
And officials worry that if they let in these 26,000, many others
will claim to be Jews to better their lives in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that most of them lead terrible lives. With the hope
of emigrating in the early 1990's, many left their villages for the
cities. Their land was taken over, and now they live as urban
refugees of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   Gedamu Kassa, 75, sick and bone-thin, lives in a small room made
with walls made of cow manure with his wife and four other family
members. His son lives in Israel. ``Most of our relatives have gone
to Israel and we want to join them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Falash Mura and their supporters reject the idea that they
are economic refugees alone. Many of them have relatives among the
4,000 Falash Mura who have made it to Israel, and who lead
religious lives there, supporters say. ``If they were just economic
refugees there would be no reason for them to do that,'' said
Joseph Feit, a New York tax lawyer on the board of the North
American Conference on Ethiopian Jewry, the charity that Goldman
works for. In the United States, the three branches of Judaism
support emigration for the Falash Mura, and in Israel too there are
many groups backing them.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has accepted thousands of Russians, not all of them
Jewish by Jewish law, a fact that the Ethiopians have noticed.
``Since we are black there are serious investigations,'' Yalew
said. ``For Russians, they don't do the same thing. That is racism.
That's a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   As they wait, the Falash Mura busy themselves at the center in
Addis Ababa and another in Gondar. Most go there to pray three
times a day. Nearly 5,000 children attend school at the centers,
singing the Israeli national anthem before class. The center
employs 850 people to embroider scenes of Ethiopian Jewish life,
which are made into pillows and sold in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   One of the embroiderers is Desalegn Gibte, 55, who stitches
embroidery for about $20 a month. ``We are doing this just to get
paid,'' he said. ``We barely get enough to pay rent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
