<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0767 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-TRACKDATA-MARKETPLACE     04-18 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRACKDATA-MARKETPLACE-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: BOOSTER OF ONLINE TRADING IS VICTIM OF MARGIN
PITFALLS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.Y., Fla., Conn., N.M., N.J.)  (See also MARKET) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Among the many evangelists for online investing who
have appeared in recent years, few have been as ubiquitous as
Baruch Israel Hertz. His New York company, with its constant
advertisements on CNBC, promises to make investing a cinch even for
novices, providing stock quotes, market information and easy access
to electronic trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be a pro to trade like one,'' he says on the
Web site of his stock-trading system, MyTrack.
</P>
<P>
   But when stocks plunged Friday, many investors who had borrowed
heavily to play the market suddenly faced demands from their
lenders that they put up more money to cover their losses. And one
of the biggest losers was Hertz.
</P>
<P>
   Hertz, 50, owes $45 million to four unidentified brokerage firms
to cover his losses in trading stocks, according to a news release
issued Monday by his company, Track Data Corp. To meet the brokers'
demand for him to put up more money, known as a margin call, he
pledged 25 million shares of his own company's stock out of about
45 million shares he owns. In a remarkable twist, Hertz has become
the most public victim yet of the kind of investing he was
promoting.
</P>
<P>
   Even after this week's rebound in stocks, some investors who
borrowed from their brokers to buy high-priced shares have not been
able to come up with additional cash to cover investments that had
fallen in value. This has alarmed Wall Street professionals and
others who worry that when stock markets that have only gone up
finally turn down, many people will be wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   But even in Friday's carnage, nobody expected that the chief
executive of an online trading company would be the one to generate
one of the biggest margin calls ever.
</P>
<P>
   Hertz declined through a colleague to be interviewed. ``This was
Mr. Hertz's personal account, his personal trading,'' said Rafi
Reguer, director of marketing at Track Data. ``It was done with
firms other than this one, in securities other than Track Data.''
Beyond that, Reguer declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Hertz is one of a new breed on Wall Street, people whose
backgrounds are in engineering and computer software rather than
finance, who believe that every individual investor should be able
to have Wall Street's trading action brought right into their
living rooms through a computer. According to the company, Hertz
earned a bachelor's degree in mathematics from Brooklyn College in
1971 and a master's degree in computer science from New York
University two years later.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Hertz, everyday investors who are MyTrack
customers star in its television ads, appearing on camera to give
testimonials to the system. And much of the company's Web site is
devoted to rave reviews from customers, even featuring pictures of
those who are happy using MyTrack.
</P>
<P>
   The company began offering online trading to customers last
June, charging $12.95 a trade and monthly fees of $20 to $95 for
access to quotes, news and other market data. About 100,000
investors have registered for the service. For a more sophisticated
system called MarkeTrack, customers pay $250 to $600 a month.
</P>
<P>
   News of Hertz's misfortune has cast a spotlight on the network
of companies he runs and is affiliated with. He founded the company
that would become Track Data in 1981, merged it with a data
provider called Global Market Information Inc. in March 1996 and
changed its name to Track Data. The company employs 375 people
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Hertz and his company issued new releases unceasingly. In
November, for example, the company issued 20 different news
releases, announcing developments like its offer of a week of
commission-free trading for its customers in celebration of the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 17, Hertz made waves when Track Data put out a news
release announcing that the company had no news to report that day.
``Commenting on the lack of news today,'' the release said, ``Barry
Hertz, chairman and CEO said, `I want to apologize to our faithful
stockholders who are looking each morning for our latest corporate
developments. Rest assured that we do not take this lack of news
lightly.'''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Following the lead of many companies who split their stocks to
attract new investors, Track Data split its stock 2 for 1 twice
last fall. At its peak in January, Track Data had a market value of
almost $780 million; Hertz's 71.7 percent stake was worth about
$560 million. The company's shares, which traded as high as $12.25
just more than two months ago, closed Tuesday at $2.03125.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who buy and sell stocks on MyTrack have most of their
trades executed by Track Securities Corp., which in turn pays Track
Data for the orders.
</P>
<P>
   Track Securities, which is based in Boca Raton, Fla., has had a
number of run-ins with regulators in recent months. Last Thursday,
the securities regulator in Connecticut found that the firm had
been operating in the state without being registered and had
employed unregistered agents. It fined Track Securities $25,000.
And last August, New Mexico's securities regulator censured the
firm and fined it $10,670 for filing a misleading document and for
conducting activity in the state without a license. Florida
regulators also fined the firm $2,500 in August for not registering
a branch office and failing to establish and maintain adequate
supervisory procedures.
</P>
<P>
   According to Track Data's spokesman, Track Securities is owned
and run by Jack Spiegelman, a director of Track Data. But according
to a filing Track Securities made with securities regulators, Hertz
appears to be a close affiliate of the brokerage firm. In that
filing, Hertz is listed as president and chief executive of Track
Data Securities, owning between half and three-quarters of the
concern. Track Data Securities, according to this filing, is
controlled by Track Securities.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even after meeting his $45 million margin call, Hertz remains a
man of means. He will be left with roughly 20 million shares of
Track Data, worth about $40 million. And as chairman and co-founder
of Innodata Corp., a publicly traded company that allows its
customers to create and disseminate information online, he owns
14.7 percent of the company, worth $4.6 million at Tuesday's
closing price of $6.1875.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his salary of $375,000 at Track Data, Hertz
earned $75,000 last year for his work at Innodata, based in
Hackensack, N.J. The company went public in 1993 in an offering
underwritten by A.S. Goldmen, a small brokerage firm that was
indicted last July by the Manhattan district attorney on charges
that the firm orchestrated a securities fraud that cost investors
$100 million in losses. The firm closed most of its operations in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Even before news of Hertz's margin call hit Wall Street, Track
Data announced that it had retained an investment bank to advise it
on strategic options, including a possible sale of the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is going to make the decision which is really the
best thing for the company,'' said Jay Gelman, senior vice
president of sales at Track Data. ``We will look at all the viable
offers and mergers and try to make the best determination.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
