<SLUG> BC-ARIZONA-FOOD-ART-$ADV23-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX: DIVERSITY BLOOMS IN THE DESERT
</HEADLINE>
  (BRYAN MILLER, a former restaurant critic for The Times, is
co-author with the late Pierre Franey of ``Cooking With the
60-Minute Gourmet'' (Times Books). 
 (For release Sunday, April 23.) 
By BRYAN MILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX, Ariz. _ Ten years ago, fine dining in Phoenix was
largely confined to chain restaurants, most of them in frosty
air-conditioned malls.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a batch of scorching Tex-Mex chili parlors, the food
in this shimmering city in the sand was as flat as a bus ride to
Yuma. Or as one local culinary writer put it, ``Back then, people
here thought free-range chicken was something you didn't have to
pay for.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, the Phoenix restaurant scene has grown
geometrically. Thai, Japanese, regional American, Asian _ all can
be found if you can navigate the exasperating circuitry of roads
that stitch together this metropolis of more than 3 million
inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   A few things to remember before heading out to dine in Phoenix:
Restaurants have conventional street numbers, but they are merely
decorative; every location here is identified by intersections. And
once the proper intersection is found, you have to locate the
correct corner (northwest, southeast, etc.); then find the correct
mall (everything is in a mall).
</P>
<P>
   But don't celebrate yet _ restaurants here are masters of
camouflage. One may be disguised as an annex to a shoe store,
another may skulk behind a faux hacienda courtyard encircled by
leafy palms.
</P>
<P>
   Also keep in mind that Phoenicians roll up their knapsacks
early. Lunch kicks off around 11, and dinner usually runs from 5:30
to 9 p.m. A few places whoop it up until 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Los Dos Molinos
</P>
<P>
   If spicy food makes your blood run hot, then Phoenix can give
you desert fever. Arizonans bluster about different chili peppers
the way Yankees fans track batting averages. And the lodestone for
leather tongues is Los Dos Molinos, which occupies a stucco and
terra-cotta hacienda that used to be the home of the Hollywood
cowboy star Tom Mix.
</P>
<P>
   Early on a Saturday evening, we had to cool our heels for nearly
two hours in a pleasant little outdoor courtyard where jalapeno
junkies were chilling down with aquarium-size margaritas. (The
restaurant does not accept reservations; weekdays are much calmer).
</P>
<P>
   Los Dos Molinos specializes in Santa Fe cooking _ which, as far
as I can tell, is identical to other Mexican-style fare except that
the peppers are a lot hotter. Portions here could feed a posse, so
it is advisable to start off slowly with some of the chunky,
vinegar-tinged guacamole (excellent) and various salsas (``hot''
``really hot'' and ``find a garden hose'').
</P>
<P>
   The menu warns of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry, we do not provide a mild sauce,'' says Victoria
Chavez, the chef and owner. ``I do not know how to make mild.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's vivacious daughter Cheryl chaperons the nightly fiesta
in the small dining room that resembles a Tex-Mex frat house, a
riot of dangling chilies, western art, mounted license plates and
neon beer signs. A strolling guitarist works the room with a
repertory that runs from ``Guantanamera'' to Van Morrison's
``Brown-Eyed Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   There are about eight house specialties, and you can get them as
hot as you like (we didn't push the envelope). Adovada ribs were my
favorite _ big, meaty monsters stoked with plenty of hot chilies,
but not excessively so, and flanked by well-seasoned red beans and
rice. Shrimp Veracruz climbed a notch higher on the spice meter,
six charred shrimp that had been massaged with red chili sauce and
served with the same side dishes.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the heat here so special is that it sneaks up behind
you like a bandito in the night. It first intensifies on the back
of the tongue, then leaves you all warm inside, while inferior hot
food only sears your lips.
</P>
<P>
   Other recommendations are the enchilada dinner (blue or yellow
tortillas and chilies covered with cheese and crowned with fried
eggs), and the smoldering flautas filled with shredded beef.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the weekend Pamplona here, the young, denim-clad
servers here seem to be having as much fun as the customers.
</P>
<P>
   For dessert, most diners get another drink _ the restaurant has
a great beer list _ but if you want something sweet, try the
sopaipillas, lasagna-shaped fried dough that is dusted with
cinnamon and drizzled with honey. Don't even think about asking for
wine.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gregory's Grill
</P>
<P>
   For less bellicose fare there is this smart, welcoming spot
owned by 35-year-old Gregory Casale, the chef, and his wife, Kim.
Tucked into a shopping mall _ where else? _ its plain decor belies
some creative and compelling cooking, at very reasonable prices.
</P>
<P>
   Casale logged time at the River Cafe in New York as well as some
major hotels in Phoenix before venturing out on his own. His menu
traipses around the world, and for the most part it is a diverting
ride.
</P>
<P>
   We started with five-spice quail, the chef's twist on Peking
duck, that was nicely burnished and crisp _ though a tad dry _ and
nested on a cluster of mixed greens and homemade ginger chutney.
</P>
<P>
   A big bowl of meaty mussels vindaloo in a fiery
red-mustard-and-curry broth was bold and complex. One of the better
appetizers was sweetbreads in a brittle carapace of ground
hazelnuts served over a creamy risotto studded with peas.
</P>
<P>
   All of the main courses sampled were good, especially the
succulent braised beef short ribs in a sherry-spiked broth along
with horseradish mashed potatoes. Seared, peppery mahi-mahi was
deftly cooked and came with a flavorful crawfish spoonbread (a
great combination) and tasty succotash.
</P>
<P>
   The spiced sea bass was relatively tame _ a jab rather than a
punch _ and had a lively supporting cast of black rice in a peppery
curry broth, and Chinese long beans tossed with cashews.
</P>
<P>
   Our delightful and knowledgeable waitress recommended a host of
desserts, all of which where satisfying, especially the tower of
won ton crisps layered with lemon ice cream and ringed by a
semisweet pinot noir reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory's Grill does not serve alcohol but you can bring your
own wine. (Although, in this circumstance, I don't think they
should charge an $8 corkage fee, or $4 for a Pilsener glass for
beer).
</P>
<P>
   Hapa
</P>
<P>
   This two-year-old restaurant is one of the most inventive and
exhilarating in Phoenix, and it is destined to enjoy a wider
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   It is owned by James McDevitt, who is of Japanese and Irish
ancestry (thus the name, which is Hawaiian slang for half) and his
wife, Stacey, the pastry chef. The menu is described as fusion, but
don't let that fatigued term scare you off.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there are two Hapas: a handsome sushi bar on one side
and, on the other, an airy Japanese-style dining room with an open
kitchen. I decided to try the sushi bar first (in fact, they do not
serve sushi, but rather sashimi-style dishes).
</P>
<P>
   Nobu Fukuda, the chatty and informative chef, started me off
with a wonderful appetizer of sliced raw halibut in a lustrous
sauce combining citrus juice, soy, sesame seeds and toasted garlic.
</P>
<P>
   It was so good that I got carried away and hurtled through a
half-dozen more dishes, including meaty slices of jumbo clam in a
tart sauce of green tea, sea salt and yuzu juice (citrus juice and
minced hot chilies), and thinly sliced poached duck with a gingered
soy-and-red-wine reduction. Exquisitely fresh sea urchins are so
oceanic they should be eaten in a bathing suit.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, specific wines are recommended for each dish; for
example, a tart, acidic Sancerre with the lemony clam dish. You
won't find many bargains on the limited regular wine list, but the
selections are smartly matched to the food.
</P>
<P>
   McDevitt (I stayed at the convivial sushi bar) took the helm
with some excellent crescent-shaped gingered-pork dumplings with a
curried mustard sauce and crunchy taro chips. Foie gras came
crisply seared and with a caramelized mango sauce, a lovely
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   His version of duck was just as appealing as the other, slices
of breast with a Vietnamese-style caramelized ginger sauce, along
with a cleansing cabbage slaw.
</P>
<P>
   Also recommended are the tender lamb chops flanked by charred
scallions and a lovely cashew couscous (another lamb chop entree
has them in a coriander crust and accompanied by a terrific
sweet-potato-ginger cake). A trio of fruit sorbets was the perfect
punctuation.
</P>
<P>
   Hapa is one of the few fine restaurants in town open on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Elaine's
</P>
<P>
   This is a luxurious, first-rate, staggeringly expensive
restaurant in the marmoreal Phoenician resort
</P>
<P>
   The recently arrived chef, James Boyce, has been around the
haute cuisine track, including a stint at Manhattan's Le Cirque. He
is passionate about ingredients, the type of fellow who can get
misty describing special beets from New Mexico. Boyce's cooking is
bright, inventive and as colorful as a desert sundown, yet doesn't
stray far from his classic French training.
</P>
<P>
   The dark, upholstered dining room _ it is so dark that diners
are supplied with little flashlights to read the menu _ offers a
panoramic view of the glittering city. And talk about service _
aside from offering every pampering side point, servers give all
women little footstools so they do not have to place their purses
on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   We started with remarkably sweet butter-braised lobster over
tart leaves of Swiss chard and crisp water chestnuts _ an ambrosial
combination.
</P>
<P>
   Perfectly made gnocchi are given regal treatment with flecks of
black truffles and toasted hazelnuts. I usually don't like people
fiddling with good oysters, but the chef's Belons under a gossamer
horseradish sauce retained their wonderful salinity.
</P>
<P>
   If you have just cleaned up on a high-stakes golf match, you
might try the incredibly buttery Kobe beef (at around $185,
depending on market prices). Or, for one-fourth of that, there is a
seductive chateaubriand of buffalo crowned with a perfectly cooked
slab of foie gras, served with a perfect bearnaise sauce. (Why do
we not see this astonishing sauce anymore?)
</P>
<P>
   Another sublime combination is braised halibut with chunks of
sweet lobster, cubes of thick bacon and basil.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Elaine's international wine list is well chosen, filled
with Bentleys and Jaguars; prices are fair, although I didn't
appreciate the sommelier's recommending a glass of ``nice white
wine'' that turned out to cost $25.
</P>
<P>
   Desserts, as one would expect, are lavish, like warm chocolate
souffle with mint ice cream, and steamed apple pudding with Cognac
sauce and macerated raisins.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's
</P>
<P>
   For a casual good time and better-than-average fare, there is
Richardson's, a large, adobelike spot with a big bar and lots of
big guys watching sports on an overhead television. Surprisingly,
though, some of the Tex-Mex fare is original and satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   You can start off with a nice array of mildly hot salsas, and a
good, but not great, guacamole. Posole, a smoky combination of pork
and hominy in a hot chili broth, is a lovely, warming dish.
</P>
<P>
   For $17, you can't beat the full-flavored Black Angus steak,
cooked to order, with a weird but appealing peppered whiskey lime
sauce, served over grilled portobello mushroom slices with pecans.
This is not the easiest dish to pair with wine, but there is a nice
little selection, mostly Californian and at very moderate prices.
</P>
<P>
   Another fine main course is grilled pork tenderloin that is
basted with a green-and-red chili jelly, and served with a green
chili potato. Our spunky and accommodating waitress went on and on
about this green chili potato (``You gotta try it''), a house
specialty. It may have been the potato chef's night off, but ours
were bland and greasy.
</P>
<P>
   For dessert, there is flan and flan. It's pretty good. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Bill of fare: beyond chilies
</P>
<P>
   Los Dos Molinos, 8646 S. Central Ave. at Baseline, Phoenix;
(602) 243-9113. Open 11 a.m. to 3 p.m. and 5 to 9 p.m. Tuesday to
Friday; 11 a.m. to 9 p.m. Saturday. Closed Sunday and Monday. All
credit cards. A three-course lunch or dinner for two with two beers
is about $45. Smoking is allowed throughout the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory's Grill, 7049 E. McDowell Road at Scottsdale Road,
Scottsdale; (480) 946-8700. Open 5:30 to 9 p.m. Tuesday to
Thursday, until 10 p.m. Friday and Saturday. All credit cards.
Dinner for two with a glass of wine each runs about $75. No smoking
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Hapa, 6204 N. Scottsdale Road at Lincoln Boulevard, Scottsdale;
(480) 998-8220. Open Monday to Saturday 5:30 to 10 p.m. All credit
cards. No smoking. Dinner for two runs about $100.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Elaine's, The Phoenician, 6000 E. Camelback Road at
Phoenician Boulevard, Scottsdale; (480) 423-2530. Open 6 to 9:45
p.m. Monday to Thursday, until 10:30 p.m. Friday and Saturday. All
credit cards. No smoking in the dining room, cigarettes only in the
bar. Dinner for two with two glasses of wine is about $225. Jackets
required for men, and evening or cocktail dresses for women. Closed
Monday from mid-June to mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's, 1582 E. Bethany Home Road at 16th Street, Phoenix;
(602) 265-5886. 11 a.m. to midnight Monday to Friday, 10 a.m. to
midnight Saturday and Sunday. All credit cards. Dinner for two with
a glass of wine runs $60 to $70. Smoking is allowed throughout the
restaurant.
</P>
