<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ARIZONA-$ADV23-2TAKES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPI VILLAGES ON THE MESAS: WHERE ARTISANS WORK WITH ANCIENT
DESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, April 23) 
By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was not yet noon, but the thermometer in our rented sport
utility vehicle showed it was 102 degrees outside when my friend
Georgia and I arrived at the top of First Mesa, a
forbidding-looking plateau of rock in the northeastern Arizona
desert and a thriving traditional center of Hopi Indian life.
</P>
<P>
   Our guide, Lela, whom we had met at the village visitors center,
carried an umbrella against the fierce summer sun. She led us past
vendors of pottery and carved kachina dolls to Walpi, on a bony
rock claw jutting out over the desert that stretched beneath us for
hundreds of miles.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Hopi, she talked proudly but protectively about the
tribe's traditions. When we asked her to explain the nature of the
religious activities that took place in the underground ceremonial
rooms known as kivas, which dot the village, she smiled pleasantly
but said no. Her tone suggested we should leave it at that.
</P>
<P>
   According to legend, the Hopis' ancestors first entered the
world through a hollow reed at a sacred place near a river junction
in the Grand Canyon. They would emerge to wander the earth, but
eventually unite at a mythic sacred circle at the center of the
universe.
</P>
<P>
   That place, at least in the temporal world, is the Hopi
Reservation in northeastern Arizona. Here atop three majestic
promontories that dominate the surrounding desert are the Hopi
villages of the First, Second and Third Mesas, and a culture
closely bound to a spiritual identity dating back a millennium.
</P>
<P>
   We spent four days in July in the high desert exploring the mesa
villages. Our vacation schedules had forced us to visit the region
during one of the hottest months of the year. Doing so, however,
meant we escaped the crowds of spring and fall. We even found the
heat bearable. Temperatures changed rapidly. Sudden downpours had
us reaching for our windbreakers as the thermometer dropped 20
degrees or more within minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Our trip began and ended in Flagstaff, which is northeastern
Arizona's commercial and cultural hub, within easy reach of the
Grand Canyon, Monument Valley and the red-rock country of Sedona to
the south.
</P>
<P>
   There are many chain motels in the area, but we stayed downtown
at the Monte Vista Hotel, a funky, casual spot that captures the
1930's, when its movie star guests filmed westerns at nearby sites.
And although we had rented a four-wheel-drive vehicle at the
airport, we found we did not need the off-road capability because
we almost never left paved roads. From Flagstaff we drove east on
Interstate 40, the main east-west Interstate through Arizona, then
turned north on State Highway 87, through the Painted Desert, to
reach the villages _ a 170-mile drive.
</P>
<P>
   Later, we headed farther north on Highway 191 to Chinle, a
Navajo settlement nearest the glorious red-rock chasm of Canyon de
Chelly, whose alcoves hold excellently preserved stone ruins of the
Anasazi, the ancient forebears of the Hopi. Along the way we
shopped for pottery, baskets and rugs made by native craftsmen _
stopping at some of the many trading posts or, better, visiting
with the artists in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   We found a lot to see around Flagstaff itself. The Lowell
Observatory, where Pluto was discovered in 1930, is about a mile
west of downtown. It was founded on Mars Hill in the 1890s by the
mathematician Percival Lowell. The landscaped grounds provided a
tour of the region's flora. On some evenings, visitors can also
peer through one of the observatory's telescopes.
</P>
<P>
   About 35 miles east of Flagstaff on I-40 is Meteor Crater, a
4,100-foot-wide, 570-foot-deep hole in an otherwise flat desert
floor. The crater was formed 49,000 years ago when a huge iron and
nickel meteor smashed into the earth.
</P>
<P>
   A three-mile drive north of downtown, on North Fort Valley Road,
is the Museum of Northern Arizona, housed in a lovely building of
native flagstone with a red-tiled roof that sits in a ponderosa
pine forest. As first-time visitors, we found it a perfect starting
point for an overview of the region's natural history and native
cultures.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's best exhibits trace the evolution of the area's
native peoples, their history and crafts, both ancient and
contemporary. The pottery collection, in particular, showed us the
dazzling artistry of the native potters and how they have
incorporated ancient designs and construction techniques into their
work.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s, the museum's founders, Harold S. Colton and his
wife, Mary-Russell Ferrell Colton, helped revive the production of
native crafts on the Hopi mesas. The museum continues to support
such work through its displays, shops and Heritage Program _ art
marketplaces held on weekends from May through September that
feature the work of Hispanic, Hopi, Navajo, Zuni and Pai craftsmen.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's shops sell fine pottery, along with exceptional
hand-woven baskets, rugs and jewelry. Prices for the best work can
be daunting. A five-inch seed pot by the best Hopi potters can sell
for several hundred dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Prices are somewhat lower on the mesas. We found that a
traditional approach to shopping for pottery _ visiting the homes
of the artisans _ offered a revealing glimpse into the lives of the
Hopi and a rewarding introduction to their work. (Appointments are
generally not necessary.)
</P>
<P>
   For a treat, we spent a night at a refurbished railroad hotel,
La Posada, in Winslow, east of Flagstaff on I-40. The hotel was
designed by Mary Colter, the well-known Southwest architect who
incorporated native motifs in buildings along the route of the
Santa Fe Railway like La Posada. The hotel opened in 1930 and some
of Colter's admirers regard it as a masterpiece of railway
architecture. Today's owners have kept faith with her work, even
using dishes with native designs that she created for Santa Fe's
luxury train, the Super Chief.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
