<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0776 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-ARIZONA-$ADV23     04-18 1543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ARIZONA-$ADV23-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Super Chief.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1997, Allan Affeldt, a Southern California entrepreneur with
an interest in architectural preservation and ecology, bought the
hotel and began restoring it. Although its original furnishings
were sold and parts of the hotel were stripped of other original
decor, Affeldt and his crew have recently acquired some of the
original pieces and are reproducing some of the tinwork,
animal-shaped tables and monks' chairs based on old photographs. He
has now reopened 20 of the original 75 rooms as well as several
public areas to guests.
</P>
<P>
   North of Winslow, we drove a blacktop road up to the edge of
First Mesa. From there we could see far below the dry-farmed fields
sprouting corn, a crop at the heart of Hopi culture, ceremony and
religion. Hopi dry farming is an ancient agricultural system in
which the crop is grown without irrigation in fields so dry they
are scarcely distinguishable from the desert.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, the parched lowlands were streaked with the
brown, pink and purple sands of Painted Desert country. To the
southwest the dark shoulders of the San Francisco Mountains near
Flagstaff were visible. Hopi myth holds that those mountains are
the home of the kachinas, the Hopi ancestor deities.
</P>
<P>
   Modern-day kachinas, male dancers representing such deities,
arrive periodically in the villages wearing masks and costumes to
bring rain, or celebrate the harvest. Only some ceremonies are open
to visitors, and photographs are not allowed at all on the mesas.
</P>
<P>
   The dusty villages with their one-story mud and stone buildings
are striking in part because they are not the make-believe work of
theme park developers. They are real, and some date back hundreds
of years. Perched high over the desert, they resonate with the
activity of everyday life in a vibrant matriarchal society
organized into highly evolved clans.
</P>
<P>
   First Mesa, and the village of Polacca at its base, is a center
of Hopi pottery making. It is the home of the late Nampeyo, a
famous matriarch of a family of potters, whose work is still on the
market.
</P>
<P>
   We stopped to see Alice Dashee, a traditional Hopi potter. She
met us at her front door and showed us the few pieces that she had
for sale, beautifully shaped bowls and plates. In a wheelbarrow in
a corner was the clay she had dug from the desert rock. Sitting in
her living room, Dashee described how she shaped and rubbed the
pots smooth, working not with a wheel but from hand-coiled lengths
of clay. Using a chewed end of a native yucca stalk, she recreates
some of the 1,000-year-old Anasazi patterns unearthed in
archaeological digs. The pots are fired in outdoor bonfires using
dried sheep manure as fuel, which produces the high firing
temperatures necessary to give the ceramic work its rich orange
blush.
</P>
<P>
   At Second Mesa, about eight miles west of First Mesa, the Hopi
tribe operates a motel and restaurant at the Hopi Cultural Center.
The rooms are modern and clean. The restaurant offers an American
menu along with traditional _ and bland _ native fare like piki
bread, paper-thin blue-corn tortillas and a thin stew of hominy and
lamb.
</P>
<P>
   At Third Mesa, several miles farther west, is the tiny village
of Old Oraibi, which the Hopi tribe says is the oldest continuously
inhabited town in what is now the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours northeast of the Hopi villages, in the heart of
Navajo country, is Canyon de Chelly (drive 56 miles east on U.S.
Highway 264, then 30 miles north of U.S. Highway 191 to Chinle), a
majestic red-rock split in the earth. Traditional Navajo dwellings,
the circular hogans, still stand among the willows and cottonwoods
of the sandy canyon floor.
</P>
<P>
   The canyon subdivides into three main branches, with side
canyons that reach more than 100 miles through rock cliffs rising
in some places more than 1,100 feet. Overlook drives on the south
and north rim provide views into a surprisingly lush valley of
peach orchards and cornfields far below. We took a six-wheel-truck
tour of the canyon floor led by a Navajo guide, who led us to some
of the finest Anasazi rock art and ruins in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   We stayed at Thunderbird Lodge, a comfortable motel with an
attached cafeteria that is one of the older lodging places within
minutes of the canyon. The lodge helped arrange our guided tour.
The Navajo tribe, which controls access to the canyon, prohibits
almost all unescorted trips to the canyon floor.
</P>
<P>
   About six miles from the National Park Service headquarters is
one of the canyon's best-known ruins, the White House. This well
preserved and accessible multistory complex is named for a white
plaster wall on one section; at one time it contained as many as 80
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the Hopi, the Navajo are relatively recent
arrivals to this part of Arizona, migrating to the canyon and
surrounding region sometime after 1400 with a language, culture and
history far different from the Hopi.
</P>
<P>
   The Navajo occupied lands left by the Anasazi, whose departure
is still incompletely explained. The Navajo barely touched the
empty ruins, according to some experts, because they feared the
abandoned rock houses as places of the dead.
</P>
<P>
   We left the canyon, driving back to Flagstaff through two of the
region's greatest visitor sites, Monument Valley and the Grand
Canyon, with their famous vistas swarming with crowds,
traffic-congested roads and tour buses. The drive had been a long
one, under a sometimes sizzling sun, but the native cultures and
high desert had exerted a magnetic influence over us, and we were
ready to go back _ even in summer.
</P>
<P>
   Getting There
</P>
<P>
   Flagstaff was a starting point for our trip. I flew America West
Airlines first to Phoenix from the Baltimore-Washington
International Airport and then aboard an America West Express
turboprop to Flagstaff. Reservations: (800) 235-9292. At the
airport, we rented a Chevrolet Blazer from Avis for a week for
$53.16 a day, not including fees, taxes and surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   What to Do
</P>
<P>
   Lowell Observatory, at 1400 West Mars Hill Road, is a mile west
of downtown Flagstaff. The Steele Visitor Center, (520) 774-2096,
is open daily. Admission: $4; children ages 5 to 17, $2.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Northern Arizona, 3101 North Fort Valley Road,
(520) 774-5213, is north of Flagstaff on U.S. Highway 180. Open
daily 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission: $5; children ages 7 to 17, $2.
Tours by appointment with four weeks' notice.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to see the Meteor Crater is through the visitor
center on the rim. Take Exit 233 on Interstate 40, about 35 miles
east of Flagstaff. The center is six miles south on Meteor Crater
Road, (520) 289-2362. It is open between 6 a.m. and 6 p.m. May 15
to Sept. 15 and between 8 a.m. and 5 p.m. Sept. 16 to May 14.
Admission: $10; people 60 and older, $9; children 6 to 17, $5.
There are trails to three lookout points, but visitors are not
permitted to hike to the crater floor.
</P>
<P>
   First Mesa is on State Road 264, seven miles east of State Road
87. Walking tours (about 45 minutes) by the First Mesa Consolidated
Villages Tourist Program, (520) 737-2262, are an excellent
introduction to the vibrant, spiritual world of the Hopi Indians'
ancient society. Guided tours can be arranged on the spot. During
the summer, tours operate between 9:30 a.m. and 4 p.m. Admission:
$5; children ages 11 to 18, $4; 5 to 10 and over 65, $3.
</P>
<P>
   Canyon de Chelly National Monument. Most motels are in the
canyon area or nearby Chinle, and most will arrange driving tours.
Local guides and outfitters will arrange hiking and riding tours of
the canyon. Unescorted hiking is not permitted. Thunderbird Lodge
gift shop offers half-day and full-day tours led by Navajo guides
on six-wheel-drive open trucks; information: (520) 674-5841. A
half-day tour is $37; a full day is $59.50.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Monte Vista, 100 N. San Francisco St., (520) 779-6971.
With its unpretentious rooms, the hotel has a relaxed style absent
at the antiseptic chain motels on the main roads out of town. Room
rates are $40 to $120, for a small suite with one queen and two
double beds.
</P>
<P>
   WINSLOW
</P>
<P>
   La Posada, 303 E. Second St. (on historic Route 66), (520)
289-3873. Rooms are $79 to $99, for a suite with a fireplace like
the room used by Howard Hughes, who once owned the Winslow airport
(designed by Charles Lindbergh).
</P>
<P>
   SECOND MESA
</P>
<P>
   There are not a lot of lodging or dining options on the mesas.
</P>
<P>
   The Hopi Cultural Center Motel and Restaurant is five miles west
of State Highway 87 on Highway 264; (520) 734-2401. Rooms are $90
Sunday to Thursday; $95 Friday and Saturday. The modern 33-room
pueblo-style motel has a restaurant that is basic but moderately
priced. Note: no alcohol is sold on the Hopi or Navajo reservations
_ even at restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   CANYON DE CHELLY
</P>
<P>
   Thunderbird Lodge is on South Rim Drive, one-half mile south of
the Canyon de Chelly National Monument Visitor Center, (520)
674-5841. There are old and new sections of the 72-room lodge.
Rooms in the older part, with two double beds, are $98 a night.
Rooms in the newer section, with two queen beds, are $101. A
cafeteria and shop with fine Navajo rugs and silver work are on the
grounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
