<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS ADVANCE STRONGLY, RECOVERING MUCH LOST GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALEX BERENSON and JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With corporate earnings soaring, investors flooded
back into U.S. stocks Tuesday for the second consecutive day,
retracing much of the ground lost last week.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on the heels of Monday's gains, the rise put an end to
immediate fears that small investors are ready to abandon stocks.
Yet many Wall Street professionals remain wary that the market is
still overly expensive. Some warned that the current rally may
prove as ephemeral as the Nasdaq's bounce two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Tuesday's gains were impressive. The technology-rich
Nasdaq composite index rose 254.41 points, to 3,793.57. That 7.2
percent jump, coming on top of Monday's 6.6 percent rise, was the
Nasdaq's second-biggest gain ever _ behind only the 7.3 percent
increase on Oct. 21, 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average gained 184.91 points, or 1.8
percent, to end the day at 10,767.42, following a gain of 2.7
percent Monday.
</P>
<P>
   While both indexes remain well off their highs, the Nasdaq now
stands above its close Thursday and has regained almost half of
last week's scary 25 percent plunge, while the Dow has taken back
more than half its 7 percent loss from last week. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index also performed well, rising 40.17 points, or
2.9 percent, to close at 1,441.61
</P>
<P>
   Adding to investors' cheer, several important companies posted
first-quarter earnings well ahead of analysts' expectations. In the
technology sector, Intel and America Online, which reported
earnings after the market closed, both handily beat estimates by
the pros. Old-economy stocks also showed their strength, with drug
companies Pfizer and Johnson &AMP; Johnson both posting
higher-than-expected profits.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, several money managers and Wall Street strategists
pointed to signs that the rally may not last. While earnings are
growing fast, many technology stocks remain expensive, and the
market's unusually high volatility is worrisome, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to pull back from this,'' said Fred
Kobrick, a veteran money manager who invests almost $2 billion.
``People are doing this because they're afraid of missing the
upside, not because they see undervalued companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the weekend's warnings that individual investors might
be fleeing stocks have proven ludicrously wrong so far. Since
Monday afternoon, investors have bought stocks fiercely, especially
in the technology sector, sending bellwethers like Cisco Systems
and Intel up 15 percent or more. That is nearly a complete reversal
of last week, when investors sent the Nasdaq down 25 percent,
including nearly 10 percent on Friday alone, on fears that
technology stocks were overpriced and higher interest rates would
slow earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Callies, chief U.S. market strategist for Credit
Suisse First Boston, warned against reading too much into this
week's gains. ``This is pretty standard stuff for a market that
went down 35 percent,'' she said. ``The harder they fall, the
faster they bounce.''
</P>
<P>
   The more relevant question, Callies said, is what happens next.
She said that the Nasdaq could hit 4,160, a gain of about 10
percent above its current level, but that any rally would probably
not hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most market bottoms require several attempts,'' she said.
Callies also worries that investors could be underestimating the
risk that inflation is accelerating, which would force the Federal
Reserve to raise interest rates. Higher rates would slow the
economy and lower corporate profits, probably hurting the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``If core inflation proves to be higher than the market has
thought,'' she said, ``then the Fed is going to be in a very, very
delicate position for many months.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard E. Cripps, chief market strategist at Legg Mason in
Baltimore, said the Nasdaq rally was more a product of ``defensive
buying'' than of ``full conviction.'' Professional money managers,
he said, are just saying, ``I can't afford to miss this.''
</P>
<P>
   Cripps added that he would ``be surprised if this is an up leg
that carries us back to the old highs.'' In the weeks ahead, he
said, the Nasdaq could even fall below the low it set Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeffrey M. Warantz, equity strategist at Salomon Smith
Barney, said the details of yesterday's rally offered investors
some reason for optimism. The rally was broadly based, unlike
Monday's gains, which were confined mostly to the largest stocks.
The Russell 2000 index of smaller-company stocks was up a sharp 6
percent Tuesday, compared with a gain of just 1.2 percent on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Warantz said he wished stocks would settle down.
Investors may be pleased with their gains this week, but unless the
market calms, he said, ``we could turn around and have another
400-point down day.''
</P>
<P>
   A look at the biggest winners this week offers proof of just how
quickly investors have turned back to their technology favorites.
Four of the 10 best performers in the Nasdaq 100 index, made up the
largest companies in the Nasdaq composite, were among the 10 worst
performers last week.
</P>
<P>
   The four winners: Applied Micro Circuits, which makes
high-bandwidth products, up $2.625 Tuesday, to $107.25, and 50
percent in the last two days; Echostar, which operates a satellite
television service, up $6.4375 Tuesday, to $57.8125, and up 35
percent this week; Network Solutions, which provides Internet
domain registration services, up $27.625 yesterday, to $148.625,
and 40 percent this week; and Broadvision, a manufacturer of
e-commerce software, up $11.125 yesterday, to $38, and up 28
percent this week. Yet all are still below where they were before
last week's sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dow, the pattern is even more striking. Four of the 10
stocks that had the biggest declines last week were among the
leaders in the rebound on Monday and Tuesday, including General
Electric, Hewlett-Packard, Intel and Microsoft. But all four are
still below where they traded when the decline began. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
