<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-COMPUTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOW-TECH PRESIDENT VISITS A HIGH-TECH SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ During a visit to the country's largest computer trade
show on Tuesday, President Clinton wore an ergonomic pillow around
his neck, fiddled with a pager that sends and receives electronic
mail and examined a Web site that a computer expert told him could
retrieve confidential files from the Oval Office while he was on
the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty neat, huh?'' Clinton said as he examined a pager made
by Motorola that doubled as a minicomputer. He held up the gadget
to the reporters trailing him through the exhibition floor and
remarked: ``Think of how much more damage the press corps could do
if you all had one of these.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will never be mistaken for a computer geek. He does not
send e-mail messages. He still speaks in awe of the idea of
ordering gifts over the Internet. And not too long ago, he raised
his eyes at a product as mundane as a screen saver.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his lack of expertise when it comes to the dot-com
world, Clinton has launched a tour aimed at bringing the digital
revolution to the country's computer have-nots. After stops on
Monday in a poor neighborhood near Silicon Valley and a Navajo
Indian reservation in New Mexico, Clinton took his message to the
thousands of Web designers, product developers, software
specialists and others at the Comdex/Spring 2000 computer trade
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here today to ask you to set another trend _ to devote
more time and technology, more ideas and energy, to closing the
digital divide,'' Clinton said in a speech.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I honestly believe that the new information economy
has the potential, at home and around the world, to lift more
people out of poverty more quickly than at any previous period in
all of human history _ and that tapping that potential is actually
in our enlightened self-interest.''
</P>
<P>
   During his tour of the exhibition hall, which had more than 500
booths, the president received a crash course in the next
generation of computing. He saw a voice-activated system to access
the Internet. He examined the latest wireless technology. He picked
up a cellular telephone specially made to accommodate men's larger
fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've given me hope, with my big awkward hands,'' said
Clinton, who passed along to aides the t-shirts, mugs and other
free items that he amassed.
</P>
<P>
   On the exhibition floor, there were digital fingerprint sensors,
personal computerized calorie counters and computer mouses that
double as telephones. At the exhibit set up by StoragePoint.com,
Clinton learned about a system that allowed travelers to access
information stored in their desktop computers. ``If you're on Air
Force One and you have an Internet connection, you can get your
files,'' said Lauren Brinner, the company's director of product
development.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton listened to her comments with mouth agape, but he shook
his head when Brinner told him that the system would even allow him
to store files that only he could access.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had enough problems,'' Clinton remarked, referring to
the dispute with Congress over thousands of White House e-mail
messages that were improperly stored in the administration's
database.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the items the president reviewed, the one that he seemed
to understand best was the most low-tech.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Kowal, a nurse and massage therapist who founded
motherearthpillows.com, placed a warm wrap around Clinton's
shoulders and extolled the virtues of her invention, which
increases circulation and oxygenation and diminishes tension and
exhaustion in the stressed professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be good for me, with my crazy lifestyle,'' Clinton
said, tucking a purple pillow under his arm after Kowal had given
it to him as a gift.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
