<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0781 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INTERNET-EMPLOYEE-OPT     04-18 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-EMPLOYEE-OPTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES TRY REPRICING STOCK OPTIONS TO KEEP THE BEST AND
BRIGHTEST 
BY DAVID LEONHARDT  
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 11 months since it went public, Barnesandnoble.com has
followed a similar recruiting strategy to virtually every other
Internet start-up. To lure employees from secure jobs at solid
companies, it has handed out thousands of stock options that have
the potential to make an annual salary look like loose change.
</P>
<P>
   But based on the company's current stock price, which is about a
third of what it was in October, virtually all the options are
worth nothing. So at the end of February, the company resorted to a
strategy that was supposed to be extinct, thanks to a tough new
accounting rule: It repriced more than a third of its outstanding
options, cutting their exercise price to $8, from an average of
$16.
</P>
<P>
   The move will force Barnesandnoble to take a charge on its next
earnings statement, because of the accounting rule, and it opens up
the company to criticism from large investors who have long railed
against repricings as an unfair bailout. ``It does make for some
difficulties,'' said Marie Toulantis, the chief financial officer.
In the current labor market, however, the company had no choice but
to make the move, which applied only to midlevel managers and
lower-ranked employees, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, CDnow, another high-profile Internet retailer, also
repriced last month. MyTurn.com, a maker of low-cost computers,
announced a similar step in recent weeks. And Iomega, a
computer-storage company, has asked its shareholders to approve a
repricing plan. At other Internet companies, executives have been
running the numbers in recent weeks to decide if they too could
afford repricings, according to pay consultants and venture
capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   Repricing is only the most extreme example of the steps that
companies have taken in recent weeks as a downturn in technology
stocks has tarnished the gold standard in white-collar pay: stock
options. Many stocks continued to recover on Tuesday from last
week's sell-off, but for most public Internet companies, 2000 has
still been a nasty year on Wall Street. The Morgan Stanley Internet
index is down more than a third since early March.
</P>
<P>
   The result, analysts say, is the first significant challenge to
the notion that options are the most desirable form of pay in the
new economy. In response, companies are scrambling to solve morale
problems that many have never before faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``This market decline has exposed the dark underbelly of going
public,'' said Roger McNamee, a partner at Integral Capital
Partners. ``If you can't keep your team together, it's hard to make
a real company.''
</P>
<P>
   Some technology companies, including Microsoft, have recently
given employees unusually large option grants, in an effort to take
advantage of their low prices. Others are considering strategies,
such as granting restricted stock, that have until now been limited
to old-line companies with sagging share prices. More repricings
are likely as well, pay consultants said.
</P>
<P>
   And at dozens of companies, executives are meeting with
employees, both formally and in hallway conversations, trying to
reassure them that a drop in their company's stock price should not
cause them to leave for other concerns, where they could receive
options at the current, lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these employees joined largely because of the
perceived upside in the stock option value,'' said Jim Breyer, the
managing partner at Accel Partners, a venture capital firm in Palo
Alto, Calif. ``The public companies that have experienced pullbacks
in their stock are going to see significant employee turnover over
the next six months.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Mr. Breyer said, the number of resumes his firm
receives daily has more than quadrupled, to about 100, as employees
of many consumer dot-com companies have lost faith in the prospects
of their companies.
</P>
<P>
   For executives, the downturn presents a new type of management
conundrum. In years past, most employees barely noticed whether
their company's share price was up or down. Today, however, the
boom in stock options and the easy access to information have
combined with the most volatile stock market in history to create
headaches for managers at companies across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Alteon WebSystems, a manufacturer of Internet switches
based in San Jose, Calif. It went public in September at $19 a
share and by early December, the stock had zoomed to more than
$120. Over the next three months, it fell, rose again and then
started dropping precipitously, to close at $58 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   So the company's president, Dominic P. Orr, sent out a memo by
e-mail at the start of this month. ``I am sure all of you have been
perturbed in one way or the other'' by the recent decline, the memo
began. It went on to emphasize Alteon's strengths as an equipment
maker, as opposed to a consumer Web site, that will prosper so long
as Internet traffic continues rising. The memo ended with: ``DAMN
THE TORPEDOES ... FULL SPEED FORWARD!!!''
</P>
<P>
   But the stock kept falling, dropping below $60 during last
week's overall market decline. ``Everyone was kind of panicking
there for a minute,'' said Jolene Thomas, who works in Alteon's
information technology support department and checks the company's
stock price about four times a day. ``Everyone was just like, `Wow!
Did you see our stock? It's going down some more.'''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Alteon's top executives will meet with employees in
the company's cafeteria and explain that quarterly earnings, which
it will announce on Wednesday, are more important than the stock
price, said James Burke, the chief financial officer. If the stock
price stays well below its high for months to come, executives will
then consider other steps, including repricing, Burke said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to sit and wait and see what happens,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   That is the attitude most companies are taking, as executives
try to figure out how long the technology slump will last and what
the best response is. In recent weeks, many have called
compensation experts to discuss alternatives that range from making
large new option grants to the radical step of repricing.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies have already taken action. Microsoft, for
example, has given unusually large options grants in recent weeks,
as The Wall Street Journal reported this week. Because the
company's stock has fallen about one third since December, largely
in reaction to the antitrust case, many of the options that the
company had granted over the last year are now under water.
</P>
<P>
   Others are likely to offer employees the chance to exchange
their stock options for shares of restricted stock, pay consultants
said. If a company had granted options at $20, for example, and the
stock was now trading at $10, it could give employees outright
ownership of a smaller number of $10 shares in return for canceling
their $20 options. Even if the stock continued to fall below $10,
the restricted shares _ which workers can keep so long as they stay
with the company for a certain period of time _ would still have
value.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, such an exchange does not require companies to
take an earnings charge, according to the final version of the new
accounting rule released last month by the Financial Accounting
Standards Board.
</P>
<P>
   And, as Barnesandnoble.com and CDNow have shown, even that
earnings charge is not enough to dissuade all companies from
repricing their options when their stock price is falling and they
are facing a tight labor market. Of course, with many dot-com
companies continuing to post a loss and telling investors to watch
their operating income, the charge may seem less daunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since they don't have earnings, they don't have to worry about
a hit to earnings,'' said Ira T. Kay, the head of the compensation
practice at Watson Wyatt Worldwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
