<SLUG> BC-INTEL-EARNINGS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Intel's 1st quarter profits top forecasts
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Strong personal computer sales bolstered Intel
Corp.'s first-quarter earnings, which narrowly beat analysts'
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest chip maker reported net income of $2.7
billion, or 78 cents a share, on revenue of $8 billion. Revenue was
up 13 percent from the first quarter of 1999, while net income rose
37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   After excluding the cost of business acquisitions and excluding
17 cents a share in tax benefits, the company's operations earnings
of 71 cents a share topped the analysts' estimate of 69 cents a
share, according to First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Demand in the first quarter was stronger than we expected,''
said Intel Chief Executive Craig Barrett. ``We are accelerating our
investments in capacity to meet future demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel's strong results follow record sales and earnings by
competitor Advanced Micro Devices Inc., which posted its first
billion-dollar sales quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, which announced plans in March to build a major chip
design center in downtown Austin, has been under pressure from
personal computer makers to boost its shipments of high-performance
processors. Barrett said Intel's supply of processors will remain
tight in the second quarter, but the company's big investment in
new manufacturing capacity should translate into ample supplies in
the second half of the year when Intel will introduce two major new
processors, the Itanium and the chip code-named Willamette.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings were released after the market closed Intel shares
closed at $129 a share, up $6 in Nasdaq trading
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
