<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL EXPERTS DISAGREE ON POSSIBLE ABUSE TO BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Tuesday, with the political and judicial players
temporarily off-stage, the spotlight in the Elian Gonzalez drama
turned to dueling doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Irwin Redlener, a child-abuse expert and the government's
chief medical adviser on Elian, set off a vituperative debate with
a letter _ made public by federal authorities Monday _ in which he
called the Gonzalez household in Little Havana ``psychologically
abusive.'' He suggested that the government should act immediately
to return the boy to his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``The child needs to be rescued,'' Redlener added Tuesday on
NBC's ``Today'' show. He said he reached his conclusion over the
weekend, while watching the home video in which Elian insists to
his father that he wants to stay in this country.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban Pediatric Society in Exile, a 30-year-old organization
that describes itself as nonpolitical, responded with a
condemnation of Redlener's appraisal. Without mentioning his name,
the group said the doctor could not possibly understand Elian's
condition without having examined the boy himself _ which Redlener
acknowledged he had not done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We denounce and strongly oppose statements made by individuals
who have been expressing medical or psychological judgments without
following the most basic rules of medical ethics and care,'' Dr.
Jose Carro, the society's president-elect, said to reporters
outside the house in which Elian has been living since being
rescued off the coast of Florida last November.
</P>
<P>
   A short while after Carro spoke, US Rep. Lincoln Diaz Ballar
stepped up to the same bank of microphones and aimed even more
scathing language at Redlener, who is president of the Children's
Hospital at Montefiore in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``That psychiatrist is just a hatchet man for the Clinton
administration,'' said Diaz Ballar, a Republican who represents the
Miami area. He then implied that Redlener, who is not a
psychiatrist, had been improperly influenced by his government
employers in order to sway US public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder how much he was paid?'' the congressman asked.
</P>
<P>
   The general mood outside the Gonzalez home seemed decidedly less
combative Tuesday than it had a day earlier, when a potentially
critical decision by the 11th US Circuit Court of Appeals seemed
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, official concern remained high about how Cuban exiles and
their supporters will react if the government tries to take the
6-year-old refugee.
</P>
<P>
   Both political and community leaders in recent days have been
urging protesters in the Little Havana area of Miami to keep cool
heads and show the world that they can resolve this dispute
peacefully. Simultaneously, they have been asserting that, if
trouble does break out, it will be the fault of infiltrators loyal
to Cuban President Fidel Castro rather than of the people who stand
vigil every day to demand that Elian remain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is violence not an option, but whoever even threatens
violence is an agent of Castro,'' Diaz Ballar told the group
assembled here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the fallout, federal officials appear to be preparing
both the Cuban community and Americans in general for a
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last week, they have stripped Elian's great-uncle,
Lazaro Gonzalez, of legal custody over the boy and have dropped
broad hints that they are preparing to somehow gain control over
him. The Justice Department indicated it would take no action,
however, until the 11th Circuit renders its decision on Elian's
status.
</P>
<P>
   His relatives want the court to issue a permanent injunction
against the boy's leaving the country while any judicial action is
pending, while the government has asked for an order that Elian be
returned to his father immediately. A ruling could come at any
time.
</P>
<P>
   As if to show that Elian needs to be moved for mental-health as
well as legal or political reasons, the Immigration and
Naturalization Service late Monday gave reporters in Washington
copies of Redlener's letter, which was addressed to Attorney
General Janet Reno and INS Commissioner Doris Meissner. While
Elian's father and his lawyer have argued that it was not in the
child's best interest psychologically to remain in the Miami
relatives' home, the release of Redlener's assessment represented
the first time the government had publicly suggested that it
agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elian Gonzalez is now in a state of imminent danger to his
physical and emotional well-being in a home that I consider to be
psychologically abusive,'' wrote Redlener, who put together the
team of three mental-health specialists who met last week with
Lazaro Gonzalez and other members of his family. Elian did not
attend that meeting and was not examined by the doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Redlener, in his letter, expressed particular concern about the
home video the boy's relatives made and distributed to the media.
The pediatrician said the tape reminded him of a hostage video, and
explained Tuesday that he did not need to examine Elian personally
to come to that conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's relatives in Miami have been no less adamant in making
their case for keeping the boy in the United States than the
government has for reuniting him with his father, even if that
means he will live in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to forcefully rebutting Redlener, supporters of the
relatives Tuesday presented a 10-year-old Cuban girl to the media
here and said her case was very similar to Elian's. They said the
girl had been the lone survivor of a raft trip to this country
during which her mother had died.
</P>
<P>
   ``So why can she stay and Elian cannot?'' a Cuban woman asked
after bringing the girl to the cluster of microphones in front of
the Gonzalez home. Asked whether the girl's father also had
remained in Cuba, like Elian's father, the woman replied ``no'' and
said he had come to the United States earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans' principal argument for keeping Elian in this country
is that their homeland is ruled by a despot who will deprive the
boy of freedom and will brainwash him if he returns. As tangible
evidence of how bad the Cuban government is, its critics pointed to
an incident in Washington several days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Several men reportedly emerged from the Cuban diplomatic mission
Friday evening and beat up a group of Cuban-American demonstrators
who were supportin Elian. Some of the protesters were treated for
minor injuries in local hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   District of Columbia police said they had begun an investigation
into the alleged attack. And the State Department summoned a top
Cuban diplomat to express ``extreme concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis Fernandez, a spokesman for the mission, would not comment
on the allegations but told the Associated Press that the
protesters had been ``performing provocative actions against the
integrity and dignity of our diplomatic mission, disrupting its
normal functions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
