<HEADER>
A0785 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-TEN-UGA-WOMEN19-COX     04-18 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-UGA-WOMEN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lady Dogs hope to recapture '94 magic
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ The parallels with the 1994 season are uncanny.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since that magical season, when Georgia's
women's tennis team won its first and only national championship,
the No. 3-ranked Lady Bulldogs (19-1, 11-0 SEC) have beaten
longtime nemesis Florida, gone unbeaten in SEC play and won the
conference's regular-season title. Now they set their sights on the
SEC Tournament, which begins Thursday in Oxford, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   As league champion, Georgia has a first-round bye and is assured
of a high seed in the NCAA Tournament. But the Lady Bulldogs insist
they won't mail it in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some goals left,'' coach Jeff Wallace said. ``We
reached one by winning the SEC, but now we focus on winning the SEC
Tournament, getting a good seed in the NCAAs and winning the
national championship. We have a lot of tennis left to play.''
</P>
<P>
   That the Bulldogs have been able to put themselves in this
position this year is a testament to the team's fortitude and
versatility.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Marissa Catlin, ranked No. 1 in the nation as a sophomore
two years ago, entered the season with considerable uncertainty
surrounding an injured knee that required offseason surgery and
kept her sidelined this fall. As a result, Catlin plummeted in the
rankings. She enters the tournament ranked 53rd nationally despite
her 11-0 record at No. 3 singles this year.
</P>
<P>
   But while Catlin's game suffered a temporary setback _ Wallace
said she's playing as well as ever now _ her teammates have been
able to elevate their play.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Aarthi Venkatesan, who bounced between No. 2 and No. 3
singles the past two seasons, has flourished in Catlin's former No.
1 position. She's 12-3 this year and 22-7 in dual-match play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you play 1 or 6 or you're the eighth player, everyone
on this team knows they have a role to play,'' said Venkatesan.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia snapped Florida's streak of 65 SEC regular-season wins
in a row with a 5-2 victory last week. The Lady Dogs' only loss
this season was to No. 1-ranked Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's achievements in 15 years as Georgia's coach have begun
to pile up. Only two other coaches in the nation _ Florida's Andy
Brandi and Stanford's Frank Brennan _ have won at a better rate
than Wallace, whose teams have won 327 of their 407 matches (.803)
during his tenure. He's twice been named national coach of the
year, four times earned SEC coach of the year honors and led
Georgia to four SEC titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, it isn't about me,'' said Wallace, 36, from
Portland, Ore. ``Championships are won by teams that don't mind
taking responsibility for doing what it takes to be in that
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what this team has done.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
