<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-CHINA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS CRITICIZE CLINTON OVER REFUSING ARMS SALES TO TAIWAN
</HEADLINE>
 By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Leading Republican lawmakers accused the Clinton
administration on Tuesday of caving in to pressure from China by
refusing to sell high-tech destroyers and other advanced weapons to
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, said the
administration's decision to bar the sale of Aegis destroyers,
submarines and anti-submarine warfare aircraft to Taiwan was based
on ``threats emanating from Beijing,'' rather than on Taiwan's
legitimate defense needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration should worry more about protecting and
promoting Taiwan's democracy than offending the communist dictators
in Beijing,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   China has vigorously opposed Taiwan's latest shopping list,
especially its request for four Arleigh Burke-class destroyers with
sophisticated radar and antimissile systems costing more than $1.5
billion each.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's supporters in Congress have lobbied hard for the
transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials insisted that the proposed arms
package, which will provide Taiwan with new defensive capabilities
in early warning radar and other areas, was calibrated to address a
mounting threat from China without overly antagonizing Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made it very clear to the PRC that because we, under the
law, help Taiwan respond to defensive needs, the greater the threat
posed by China, the greater Taiwan's defensive needs will be,''
said Kenneth H. Bacon, the Pentagon spokesman, referring to the
People's Republic.
</P>
<P>
   He called ``on both sides to show restraint, particularly on the
Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lott warned that China's leaders might construe the limited
weapons package as a ``green light for further threats against
Taiwan,'' which Beijing views as a renegade province.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a tragic miscalculation were Beijing to
underestimate the resolve of the American people to defend
Taiwan,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   But the majority leader did not signal further legislative
action to help Taiwan. He has not yet scheduled a vote on the
Taiwan Security Enhancement Act, a bill that would upgrade military
ties between the United States and Taiwan, including the
establishment of direct contact between their armed forces and
American training of Taiwanese officers.
</P>
<P>
   The House overwhelmingly approved the bill on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, the chairman of the Foreign Relations
Committee, said the administration left Taiwan's supporters in the
Senate no choice but to press for swift approval of the Taiwan
Security Enhancement Act. Beijing has warned that passage of the
act would bring ``very serious damage'' to U.S.-Chinese relations,
and the White House has threatened to veto it.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear, however, if the bill would pass the Senate,
which is poised to approve legislation next month to grant Beijing
the status of normal trading relations with the United States and
help ease China's entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
