<SLUG> BC-AOL-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA ONLINE REPORTS RECORD REVENUE AND EARNINGS FOR 3RD QUARTER
</HEADLINE>
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   America Online reported record revenue and earnings in its third
fiscal quarter, crediting subscription growth, advertising sales
and online commerce fees in handily beating analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding one-time items, the company earned 11 cents per
diluted share, beating the consensus estimate of 9 cents, according
to First Call/Thomson Financial, and meeting the so-called whisper
number.
</P>
<P>
   America Online reported its results after the close of the
market. Its shares closed at $60.75, up $2, on the New York Stock
Exchange, still down sharply from their 52-week high of $95.8125,
reflecting investors' concerns about the company's pending merger
with TimeWarner Inc., and the general downdraft affecting Internet
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended March 31, America Online reported earnings
of $438 million, or 17 cents per diluted share, up from $411
million, or 16 cents per share, in the comparable period a year
ago. Revenue rose 38 percent to $1.8 billion from $1.3 billion in
the third quarter of fiscal 1999, which did not include revenue
from Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   America Online's results included one-time gains from the sale
of investments totaling $275 million this quarter and $567 million
in last year's third quarter. (The year-ago quarter also included
one-time charges of $103 million.) Excluding these items, operating
income for the quarter rose more than 155 percent from the year-ago
quarter to $383 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``America Online has never been more robust,'' the company's
chairman and chief executive, Steve Case, said in a conference call
with securities analysts. ``We have never moved so quickly to
capitalize on so many opportunities on so many fronts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the TimeWarner deal, Case said, ``we've never been
more bullish on the prospects for our combined companies than we
are today.'' Alluding to the blurring of the roles of personal
computers, televisions, telephones, musical recording and digital
networks, he added: ``For many years people have been saying
convergence is just around the corner. Today we believe we are at
that corner. The first steps of convergence are already driving
consumer expectations and the more they get, the more they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite competitors' aggressive promotion of free and low-cost
Internet services, America Online added 2 million new subscribers
worldwide during the quarter and ended with 25.8 million
subscribers to its family of interactive services, which also
includes CompuServe and Gateway.net. Revenue from advertising,
commerce and other sources more than doubled compared with fiscal
1999's third quarter, reaching $557 million.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Kiggen, an analyst with Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette,
said: ``This was a very high-quality quarter on every key metric
but particularly advertising revenue. They grew that by a wider
margin than every one of their competitors, including Yahoo, and
that's probably the key earnings driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Case said America Online and TimeWarner would announce a cable
Internet-access deal in the near future, well in advance of the
expected closing of the merger this fall. In February, the
companies released a memorandum of understanding detailing how they
would open up TimeWarner's cable television lines to other Internet
service providers once their planned merger is completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really made a commitment to open access, and we want to
live up to that commitment by articulating the terms,'' Case said
in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Lise Buyer, an analyst with CS First Boston, said investors had
grown more comfortable with the proposed merger. ``There's an
automatic reaction on the part of institutions to sell stocks
involved in a merger. I think the institutions will be back in
droves as we near completion,'' she said. ``So often mergers look
great on paper, but just don't work out, but in this case there's
so little overlap and so much you can do when you combine
TimeWarner's content with AOL's distribution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
