<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERMONT-GAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERMONT SENATE APPROVES LAW PROTECTING GAY COUPLES 
</HEADLINE>
  By CAREY GOLDBERG  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTPELIER, Vt. _ By almost 2-to-1, the Vermont Senate gave
preliminary approval Tuesday to a bill creating marriagelike
``civil unions'' for gay couples. The 19-11 vote signaled that the
Legislature was likely to clear the few apparently minor political
hurdles remaining and pass the most sweeping law in the country
protecting same-sex couples.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat-dominated Senate also voted down two proposed
amendments to the state Constitution that would have worked against
gay couples. One would have defined marriage as a union between a
man and a woman. The other would have given the Legislature
exclusive authority to confer marriage benefits, thereby nullifying
the recent Vermont Supreme Court ruling that same-sex couples
should be given the same benefits as heterosexual spouses.
</P>
<P>
   The civil-unions bill creates an institution for gay and lesbian
couples almost entirely parallel to marriage, though without the
name. Couples would obtain licenses from town clerks to form their
unions and could go to family court to dissolve them. The 300 or so
benefits that couples would receive include inheritance rights, tax
breaks and the power to make medical decisions for a partner.
</P>
<P>
   But the Vermont bill cannot assure gay partners of federal
rights and benefits, and civil unions, unlike marriages, are not
expected to be recognized in other states.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to vote on giving the bill final approval
on Wednesday. The bill must then pass in the House of
Representatives, which is likely to take it up on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The House passed an almost identical measure last month, after
weeks of hearings and debate that turned up a deep schism in
Vermont between those who favored gay marriage as a civil rights
issue and those who opposed it mainly for religious reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Howard Dean, a Democrat, has said he will sign a
civil-unions measure.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's Senate session, no one spoke forcefully against the
civil-unions bill, but Sen. John Crowley, a Republican, did ask
some pointed questions about whether the bill might not lead to an
increase in homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard W. Sears, the chairman of the Judiciary Committee,
which handled the bill, responded that after all the testimony
lawmakers had heard about the abuse and discrimination suffered by
gay men and lesbians, he could not imagine that anyone would choose
to be gay, civil unions or no civil unions.
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican, Sen. John H. Bloomer Jr., said he was not
sure what the answers were concerning gay marriage, but, he said:
``I do know I represent constituents, that's why I'm here. I'll be
voting with my constituents, which means I'll be voting no.''
</P>
<P>
   But the majority of those who spoke more often echoed the
sentiments of Sen. Jan Backus, who talked about ``tolerance,
acceptance, forgiveness and love,'' or Sen. Jean Ankeney, another
Democrat who said that although she had not had a chance to vote on
women's suffrage or on measures for civil rights in the 1960s,
``Here I am with an opportunity to vote to extend civil rights in
our state. It is indeed for me a high honor, and one I will always
treasure.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. James P. Leddy, a Democrat, read aloud a letter he had
received from a 78-year-old woman on a Williston farm who had borne
eight children and had been told 26 years ago that one son was gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew and we know that he was just plain born gay,'' she
wrote. ``I can only say, God blessed us with eight children and my
God made no mistake when he blessed us with homosexuals and when he
gave us our gay son.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
