<HEADER>
A0797 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NY-GOP-BALLOT-NYT &LR;      04-18 1494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOP-BALLOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK SENATE APPROVES PLAN TO CHANGE REPUBLICAN PRESIDENTIAL
PRIMARY RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The state Senate approved a plan on Tuesday that
would knock down New York's notorious barriers to putting
candidates on the Republican presidential primary ballot, and would
make the primary a winner-take-all contest. The Senate's action
makes it likely that the bill will become law.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Republican majority leader of the state Senate,
Joseph Bruno, waived some minor qualms he had, creating a united
front among the party's leaders for the bill, which was proposed by
Gov. George Pataki. ``The bottom line is to create clarity, to
bring a fair election and to avoid some of what's been going on,''
said Bruno, who last month called the existing primary system
``absolute nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the parties do not interfere in each other's
primary rules, so that the Democrats who control the Assembly would
simply pass whatever system the Republicans had agreed on. By that
standard, Bruno's consent was the only obstacle to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver's office, deep in budget
negotiations, declined to comment on the bill on Tuesday, but
several Democratic Assembly members said that barring unforeseen
problems, they expected their house to pass the Republican plan
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts in election law contend that the bill could run
afoul of the Voting Rights Act because awarding all the delegates
to the top vote-getter would dilute the power of minority voters.
But Pataki administration officials pointed out that California had
undergone scrutiny for similar concerns and the courts had upheld
its primary process.
</P>
<P>
   If the bill becomes law, New York's system will closely resemble
that of most other states, in which major candidates automatically
appear on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hope that going to a winner-take-all system will
raise New York's profile in the Republican nominating process,
forcing candidates to compete more aggressively here to avoid being
shut out. ``It means more is at stake,'' Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and other top Republicans took a political drubbing
this year over their efforts to keep Sen. John McCain off the
ballot in New York's primary, as they tried to orchestrate an easy
victory for their favored candidate, Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   After McCain won some of the early primaries and polls showed
him running strong in New York, the ballot access rules became a
potentially crucial issue in the campaign, one that McCain used to
great effect as he presented himself as the insurgent feared by
party bosses.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won a court fight to get on the ballot, but the criticism
only mounted, as people complained that the form of the ballot was
confusing. In the end, he lost the March 7 primary, winning 44
percent of the vote to Bush's 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The episode became a major embarrassment for state Republicans.
Several public opinion polls showed the governor's popularity
dropping, and his advisers conceded that the ballot access fight
was to blame. Some prominent Republican lawmakers, running as Bush
delegates, lost when McCain carried their congressional districts,
a blow to their prestige. Others who were elected delegates
complained that they had suffered an unexpected scare when McCain
was allowed to compete, after all, and that the affair had
tarnished their reputations.
</P>
<P>
   After the primary, Pataki's aides at first said there was no
rush to reform the system, because it would be four years before
the next presidential primary. But last month, Bruno said he would
push for change this year, and the governor followed a few days
later with his bill.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules would put well-known candidates on the ballot
automatically, rather than requiring them to go through an arduous
petition process that has been called the toughest in the nation.
It would also eliminate the practice of listing delegates on the
ballot, with the candidates they support named only in tiny type
below the delegates' names - a system that caused many voters to
complain that they did not understand the ballot. Instead, only the
presidential candidates' names would appear.
</P>
<P>
   In both respects, the proposed Republican rules would resemble
those used in Democratic presidential primaries, though both
parties still have onerous petition requirements for state races.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's legislation will ensure that primaries are
decided by the ideas, character and vision offered by the
candidates, the way they should be,'' said Michael McKeon, Pataki's
press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The rules changes were generally praised by good-government
groups, but Democrats in the Senate raised some concerns, and voted
against the bill. The vote was 36 to 23, along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Martin Connor, the Democratic minority leader, said the way
the bill was worded could undermine the Democrats' ability to set
their own primary rules. Republican lawmakers said that was not
their intent, and that they would adhere to tradition and pass
whatever law the Democrats want for their primary.
</P>
<P>
   Connor, an election lawyer by profession, also argued that the
proposed new system would violate the federal Voting Rights Act,
and several people in his field agreed.
</P>
<P>
   The Act provides for special scrutiny of voting rules in regions
where certain conditions are found, including a history of ethnic
discrimination in elections, a provision that was originally aimed
primarily at southern states. A lawsuit in the 1970s established
that one such area encompassed Brooklyn, Manhattan and the Bronx,
in part because New York state had a decades-old law on the books
requiring that voters pass an English literacy test, even though
such laws had long since been found unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The federal law says that voting laws cannot be changed in those
areas in a way that diminishes minority voting rights, and provides
that such changes go to the U. S. Department of Justice for review
on that question.
</P>
<P>
   Going to a winner-take-all system, election experts said,
appears to diminish the voting rights of minority voters. ``It does
seem to raise some serious problems,'' said Margaret Fung,
executive director of the Asian American Legal Defense and
Education Fund.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In some cases, the courts have found that electing officials on
an at-large basis, rather than by districts, illegally diluted the
voting power of minorities, and voting rights lawyers say that a
winner-take-all primary could be viewed as a kind of at-large
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``African-Americans and Latinos will definitely have less voting
power under a winner-take-all system,'' said Gene Russianoff, a
lawyer at the New York Public Interest Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   Under New York's current Republican primary system, three
delegates are elected from each congressional district, no matter
how many Republicans the district has, or how few. In this year's
primary, in heavily minority districts in New York City where
Republicans are scarce, it took fewer than 1,000 votes to become a
delegate, while in some predominantly Republican, overwhelmingly
white districts upstate it took more than 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   That means that the current system, paradoxically, gives black
and Hispanic voters a disproportionately large voice in a
Republican presidential primary. ``Almost any change you would make
would potentially diminish their voice, which is what the law says
you can't do,'' said Eric Lane, a professor at Hofstra University
law school. ``It creates a very interesting problem for the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   McKeon, the governor's spokesman, noted that there were
winner-take-all primaries in other states, like California, where
some areas come under Voting Rights Act scrutiny, and that the
courts had upheld those systems.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic party's national rules prohibit winner-take-all
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, Republican candidates must collect thousands
of signatures on nominating petitions, a prescribed number in each
congressional district, to get on the ballot. That system gave the
advantage to the party favorites who had access to the party's
legions of volunteers to do the collecting, and to the lawyers who
were expert at using arcane rules for challenging other candidates'
petitions in court.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would provide that anyone who is certified by the state
Board of Elections as being a well-known candidate would
automatically get on the ballot, as would anyone who qualifies for
Federal matching funds. Candidates who did not meet either
criterion could still go through the petition process.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of having voters vote for delegates also helped the
party favorite. This year, Bush, who was represented on the ballot
by the state's best-known Republicans, while McCain's delegates
were mostly unknowns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
