<SLUG> BC-FLEET-ANNUAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEE PROTESTERS ATTEMPT TO STORM FLEET ANNUAL MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER AND BRUCE MOHL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As state troopers formed a human wall to keep shouting
protesters out of its annual meeting, FleetBoston Financial Corp.'s
top executives Tuesday defended the bank's controversial fee
increases.
</P>
<P>
   The executives also hinted FleetBoston may make more
acquisitions to bulk up its commercial business lines and announced
plans to spend as much as $2 billion to buy back shares, a move to
support the recovery of its stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in FleetBoston, the region's largest bank, have climbed
43 percent since March 8 on strong results from its investment
units, overseas operations, and commercial banking business. Wall
Street analysts have applauded the relatively high share of income
that Fleet generates from fees.
</P>
<P>
   But the fees have drawn criticism from the Neighborhood
Assistance Corp., or NACA, a local activist group that says Fleet
charges its customers too much and unfairly raised charges on many
customers it acquired as part of its $13 billion merger with
BankBoston Corp. last year.
</P>
<P>
   FleetBoston insists its fees are fair and that the bulk of its
fee income comes from its commercial ventures. Consumer banking
fees are a sensitive matter for FleetBoston, however, because it
faces special scrutiny as New England's largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, as FleetBoston's chief executive, Terrence Murray,
outlined the bank's strategy in an auditorium at the World Trade
Center, about 50 activists from NACA arrived in 17 rented vans.
Barred from driving up directly they walked to the building's
entrance, chanting slogans like ``Get your hand out of our pockets.
We're fed up with fees.''
</P>
<P>
   Some shoving matches broke out as the activists, led by NACA
chief executive Bruce Marks, tried to push their way into the
meeting room past state troopers and Massport security officers
assigned to the public facility.
</P>
<P>
   FleetBoston representatives said the protestors lacked
credentials as shareholders, though they said the company was
willing to allow Marks and three others to enter. Marks disputes
that and says he may file a lawsuit over the matter.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, Marks said he will also file a complaint with the
Justice Department and federal bank regulators seeking a review of
last year's merger. He said the bank's fees were ``outrageous,''
citing the roughly $36 million in cash and stock FleetBoston paid
Murray and its president and chief operating officer, Chad Gifford,
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Facing little regional competition, Fleet isn't interested in
serving less-profitable customers, Marks said. ``Fleet looks at
working people as a necessary evil,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   FleetBoston's Murray called Marks' complaints about fees
``totally a bogus issue.'' He said fees have gone down or stayed
the same for the majority of former BankBoston customers, and the
bank's total fee income from retail customer accounts hasn't
increased as a result of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Murray and other executives suggested the protest was chiefly a
bargaining ploy by NACA, which is also negotiating to renew an
agreement to help FleetBoston arrange loans for low-income
homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   A deal NACA struck with FleetBoston in 1994 is about to expire
and Marks said he is seeking new terms under which FleetBoston
would commit about $500 million over five years.
</P>
<P>
   FleetBoston executives wouldn't discuss their ongoing talks with
Marks on mortgage-lending. Marks wields some influence with the
bank since the NACA-assisted loans help FleetBoston meet the terms
of federal rules that require a certain low-income lending
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Marks tried to run an advertisement condemning FleetBoston's
fees in The Boston Globe on Monday. But a Globe spokesman said the
newspaper decided not to print it after concluding some of its
information was misleading.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's confrontation came as FleetBoston tries to show
investors it can maintain its profits and find new e-commerce
opportunities to compete against a host of online-only banks.
</P>
<P>
   Like its peers, FleetBoston seems to be slowly winning back Wall
Street's confidence, partly as the lust for technology stocks cools
off. From a high of $44.9375 FleetBoston shares sank as low as
$25.25 last month before recovering somewhat; its shares rose
$1.1875 a share to close at $36 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Looking forward, Murray said he wouldn't rule out another major
acquisition of the scale of the BankBoston purchase. But he said he
focus would focus in coming months on acquiring what he called
``strategic fillers,'' such as a leasing business, a fixed-income
investment management company, and more units in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Joint ventures are also a possibility, Murray said, as the bank
looks to generate more cash to fund its expansion. FleetBoston will
generate nearly $3 billion in excess capital in the next few years,
which it will spend on e-commerce and other efforts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, FleetBoston expects about 1 or 2 percent of its 2
million customers will close their accounts after the merger,
Murray said. That small defection rate is partly due to his bank's
dominance of the region, Murray acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks after the meeting, FleetBoston's retail banking
director, Robert Hedges, and its managing director of community
banking, Gail Snowden, said the new fees set by the bank weren't
meant to increase income but to move BankBoston customers into new
accounts with comparable terms.
</P>
<P>
   The executives also said some of the bank's merger arrangements
had been negotiated with other community groups and regulators,
including the Organziation for a New Equality and State Senator
Dianne Wilkerson, and meet guidelines from the Massachusetts
Community Banking Council.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview Tuesday, Wilkerson said she hopes
FleetBoston will agree to reduce some fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing is the inevitable result of a market-driven,
profit-minded, competition-less financial environment,'' she said.
``Wherever the banks are, their fees are going up unless somebody
says no.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
