<HEADER>
A0800 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TECH-STOCK-EARNINGS-N     04-18 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-STOCK-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM, INTEL AND EMC INCREASE QUARTERLY PROFITS, BEATING FORECASTS 
</HEADLINE>
   by STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The engine makers, parts suppliers and plumbers of the Internet
have been responsible for the snap back this week in technology
stocks. Companies like Cisco Systems, Oracle and Sun Microsystems
can be seen as the ballast of the new economy, established concerns
with steadily growing profits as opposed to the bubble of fledgling
dot-com companies with their uncertain hopes of survival.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the technology blue chips _ Intel, EMC and IBM _
Tuesday reported earnings that exceeded Wall Street's expectations.
The laggard of the three was International Business Machines Corp.,
whose earnings rose but whose revenues declined 5 percent in the
first quarter. Big Blue suffered from the lingering effects of the
yearend decline in corporate spending on computers and computer
services by companies focusing on the Year 2000 transition.
</P>
<P>
   That problem is mostly behind it, according to company
executives, who predicted IBM would achieve growth rates of 10
percent or more in the second half of the year. Until then,
however, Wall Street analysts regard IBM a bit uncertainly, as a
company that has not really delivered the proof that its transition
to become a supplier of Internet technology to corporate America
has yet paid off in higher growth.
</P>
<P>
   But both EMC and Intel reported strong advances in revenue as
well as quarterly profits. They join other leading technology
companies _ like Sun Microsystems, which last week reported a surge
in sales and earnings growth _ that are benefiting from the
increased investment in information technology as corporations in
industries from automobiles to banking retool their operations for
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the three companies to announce its results
Tuesday, EMC Corp., is a leading supplier of the equipment
increasingly in demand by companies as they adopt Internet
technology.
</P>
<P>
   EMC, based in Hopkinton, Mass., is the market leader in
producing large data storage systems for corporations. As companies
build Web sites, giving employees, customers and suppliers access
to more and more business information, the demand for large,
high-speed storage systems has mushroomed. EMC, more than any other
company, has benefited from that trend.
</P>
<P>
   EMC said its revenue increased 23 percent in the first quarter
to $1.82 billion. Profits for the quarter jumped roughly 50 percent
to $332 million, or 30 cents a share _ a penny above the consensus
estimate of Wall Street analysts, according to First Call/Thomson
Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ruettgers, the chief executive officer of EMC, pointed
to the rising sales to traditional companies. ``We saw surges in
demand from large companies such as Home Depot, Bertelsmann of
Germany and Korea Telecom,'' he said, ``as they built their
Internet initiatives.''
</P>
<P>
   EMC shares rose sharply after it reported its quarterly figures,
rising $5.625 a share to close at $130.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Corp., the world's largest producer of microprocessors,
also reported strong growth in the first quarter. Revenue increased
13 percent to $8 billion. Its profit, excluding certain expenses
related to acquisitions, rose 52 percent to $3.1 billion, or 88
cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   But those results were lifted $600 million, or 17 cents a share,
by a one-time reduction in taxes because an examination by the IRS
reversed previously accrued tax liabilities. Excluding the one-time
tax bonus, Intel's profit was 71 cents a share, or 2 cents above
Wall Street expectations. Intel's microchips not only power more
than 80 percent of the world's personal computers _ still the
primary devices for accessing the Internet _ but also many of the
larger computers, known as servers, that deliver Web pages, e-mail
and other data from networks to desktop users.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's one real problem seems to be that it cannot keep up with
the torrid pace of orders. ``Demand was stronger in the quarter,
across all product lines, than we had anticipated,'' said Andy
Bryant, Intel's chief financial officer. ``If we had had more parts
we could have shipped them.'' IBM reported that its first-quarter
profit rose 3 percent to $1.52 billion, or 83 cents a share, easily
above Wall Street's estimate of 78 cents a share. But the 5 percent
revenue drop to $19.3 billion in the quarter caused some anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   IBM executives said that certain strategic steps, like pulling
back from the difficult retail market for PC's, had trimmed total
revenue but had also improved profitability. Louis Gerstner, the
IBM chairman, was optimistic about the company's outlook. He said
the investments IBM has made in helping corporate customers make
the transition to Internet technology was beginning to ``pay off in
exciting new growth prospects for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking forward,'' Gerstner added, ``we continue to believe
that 2000 will be a good year for IBM.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, industry analysts were disappointed that IBM's revenue
from software and computer services _ two businesses earmarked by
management as engines of growth _ were flat. The company also
stumbled in its data storage business, where it is trying to regain
ground lost to EMC. ``IBM has to prove that it has the products and
the strategy to gain market share again in the information
technology industry,'' said Steven Milunovich, an analyst at
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   In after-hours trading, IBM shares fell as low as $112 a share,
after closing at $115.125 a share Tuesday on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
