<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-SATELLITE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFTOFF OF NEW WEATHER SATELLITE SET FOR MAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PHILIP CAUTHON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation`s network of orbiting weather eyes will
be back at full strength next month when a new satellite is
launched to replace one that began malfunctioning two years ago,
federal officials announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The GOES-L _ soon to be part of the Geostationary Operational
Environmental Satellite system _ is scheduled for launch May 3,
then maneuvered into orbit 22,240 miles over Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite, a back-up for either of the nation's two primary
orbiting weather observers, was originally scheduled for launch
last year, but it was delayed because of problems with its Atlas II
booster.
</P>
<P>
   GOES images are known best for the moving cloud formations seen
on television weather forecasts. Data collected from the satellites
are a mainstay for U.S. meteorologists.
</P>
<P>
   The GOES system _ run by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration _ uses one satellite over each U.S. coastline to
detect severe weather anywhere in northern half of the Western
Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman for NOAA's National Weather Service, Louis
Uccellini, said the new satellite will ensure that GOES service
will become operational before the next hurricane season begins
June 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the worst hurricane in (recorded) history, forecasters
not only didn't know where it was going but were arguing over
whether there was actually a hurricane or not,'' said Uccellini,
referring to the hurricane that hit Galveston, Texas, in 1900.
``When you see (GOES) images, you know there's a storm out there,
and you know where it's going.''
</P>
<P>
   Since early 1998, the GOES system has been without a
fully-operational back-up satellite, which normally orbits
somewhere between the eastern and western satellites in case one of
those two should malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   The former back-up satellite, GOES-10, was moved into
operational orbit over the West Coast when GOES-9 began
malfunctioning.
</P>
<P>
   GOES-9 has since been in orbit as the spare satellite, although
the images it returns are clouded by static.
</P>
<P>
   The system's third satellite _ GOES-8, which is in orbit over
the East Coast _ has already outlived its five-year life
expectancy.
</P>
<P>
   GOES-L is equipped with the same complement of instruments as
its predecessor, including an atmosphere imager, a moisture
detecting sounder and communications equipment, which can also be
used for search and rescue operations on the Earth's surface.
</P>
<P>
   Later this week, GOES-L will be mounted atop its Atlas II rocket
which will boost it into orbit. After two weeks of positioning and
testing, the satellite will become operational as GOES-11.
</P>
<P>
   The faulty GOES-9 will be shifted to a higher orbit where it
will become space garbage along with countless other outdated
satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Only two former GOES crafts are still in operation. They were
donated to research groups, which use the crafts' communications
systems.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
