<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CAN A FISH BRING PEACE TO METLAND? 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bobby Valentine found himself in trouble over a
creative writing exercise some college student managed to get
posted on the New York Mets' own Web site. The lad claimed he never
realized the trouble he was causing with his imaginative
interpretation of Valentine's comments.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine had apparently given a witty talk to students at the
Wharton School, with a few admirable defenses of freedom of speech,
and a few examples of baseball economics, until the student, known
forever as Brad34, got inventive and made it seem that Valentine
was ripping his team.
</P>
<P>
   After four days, the Mets sorted out this foray into the
wonderful world of the Web, where anybody with a mouse can be Matt
Drudge.
</P>
<P>
   Now, everybody needed a good laugh. Mary Branca Valentine had
planned to fly up from Texas to spend the homestand with her
husband. She arrived bearing a gift _ a facsimile of a fish,
mounted on a plaque, with the words BIG MOUTH BILLY BASS printed
underneath. Valentine could have taken this personally. He could
have shrieked, ``You, too?''
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to get mad at a plastic fish. And then Valentine
was treated to the beauty part of this particular fish. It sings.
</P>
<P>
   Press one button and it gives off a rather gravelly version of
Bobby McFerrin's song, ``Don't Worry (Be Happy).'' Not only that,
but the fish also occasionally rotates his head toward the
audience. Press another button and it gives off a somewhat squawky
version of the Talking Heads song, ``The River,'' with the lyrics,
``Take me to the river . . .'' On this one, the fish alternates
rolling its head and its tail.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife said it was the last one in Texas,'' Valentine
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Just about any other manager in captivity would have shared the
joke with his wife, and nobody else. But Bobby Valentine is nothing
if not generous. He brought the fish into the office to show it to
General Manager Steve Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sharing is very healthy,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   The fish was lying on Valentine's desk, giving its rather fishy
stare at the waves of the news media that flocked in to hear
Phillips and Valentine warble their own particular versions of the
McFerrin theme. They were not worrying. They were happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby and I have agreed we will have no more comments on this
situation,'' Phillips droned. ``We're on the same page on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody noted that neither he nor Valentine has a contract
after this season. ``It's one thing we have that's similar,''
Phillips agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips had rushed out to Pittsburgh when word broke of this
article. His trip wound up as just another exercise in the
dysfunctional, with Phillips receiving some criticism for drawing
attention to some foolscap on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad for the soul to read all this stuff,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither he nor Valentine cared to discuss the excursion into the
murky waters of the Web. They were putting it all past them.
``Steve and I are on a really good team, and I'm happy to work with
him,'' Valentine recited with far less animation than his singing
fish displayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That put it into perspective for me,'' Valentine said of Big
Mouth Billy Bass. ``My wife was trying to bring a little laughter
to the situation. Let's be happy sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   He was happy, at least until he had to go out and face the
arctic wind and numbing drizzle, as the Mets tried to get in their
game against Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   The game would also be a test for Mike Hampton, who was imported
to be the rent-an-ace for the year, but had lost his first three
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it goes in New York. The Mets deal with Internet
foolscap and controversy and lingering hard feelings. The Yankees
won a game Monday night with the help of an unassisted double play
by the catcher on a tipped ball that should have been called foul.
When you're hot, you're hot.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine did not see any ominous overtones to his singing fish,
and he seemed totally mystified when somebody mentioned that a
talking fish had recently played a major role in the season finale
of ``The Sopranos,'' on television a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   In that episode, Tony Soprano, the underworld chief, is having
fevered bad dreams, which he suspects are linked to a bad meal. The
fish warns him that a close friend is deceiving him behind his
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't watch it,'' Valentine said. ``I don't know anything
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He has other things to do, like managing a ball club, and
fighting off scares from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it doesn't kill you it makes you stronger,'' Valentine
said, doing his best to not worry and be happy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0803 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-VALLEY-OF-IAO-THEATER     04-18 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALLEY-OF-IAO-THEATER-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HEALING POWERS OF HAWAII  
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)   By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lee Nagrin left her childhood home, Seattle, to come
to New York City, where in the early 1950s she became a noted Off
Broadway performance artist and director, collaborated with
Meredith Monk and painted. Her younger brother, Bert Swezea, stayed
behind, becoming a popular real estate agent in Seattle, where he
married and had two sons.
</P>
<P>
   Their decidedly different-seeming paths rejoined in 1992, when
Nagrin received news that Buddy, as she called him, was seriously
ill in Maui, Hawaii, where he had formed a new life of the spirit.
Nagrin traveled to Hawaii to be with her brother, who died the
following year. Out of that experience has come ``The Valley of
Iao,'' which opens on Thursday for a three-week engagement at La
MaMa.
</P>
<P>
   In the performance piece, Nagrin explores their two lives,
summoning up her brother's new life on the beaches and streets of
Maui, which he spent with a second wife and with a street preacher
and a musician. Through visual and spoken metaphors, she chronicles
his reconciliation with his previous family and her own acceptance,
with him, of the idea of his death.
</P>
<P>
   These grand themes will be evoked in the magically dark and
cavernous La MaMa Annex Theater in what Nagrin has called a
painting that moves, peopled by 22 performers of all ages, among
them traditional Hawaiian hula dancers. The cast will move
industrial carts and sculptural flags in a processional that
ultimately becomes a small village, lighted from within as little
houses at night, with stars above. The mystical, potent Valley of
Iao in Maui looms over it all, in a work with elements inspired by
the paintings of Fra Angelico and the 20th-century American
outsider artist Henry Darger.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, audience members may walk through the set in their
own experiencing of Bert's life. ``My brother became someone who
sold real estate as a kind of passion for selling the exactly right
house to a family,'' Nagrin said in a recent interview. ``He
believed he was doing something wonderful.'' Eventually, she said,
he became immersed in a search for ``some kind of conduit to the
Lord,'' which he found not in Christianity but in the ancient style
of chanting and hula known as Kahiko.
</P>
<P>
   At age 7, Nagrin had had a similar vision when, walking home
hand-in-hand with her mother from Sunday school, she looked up at
the sky and realized that ``that was the wonder, the mystery I
could discover my whole life.'' A small, round woman with a
deliberate gaze and way of speaking, Nagrin has reminded more than
one reviewer of a benign fairy or witch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my brother really found his heart in Maui,'' she said.
During the last week of his life, she added, ``we were able to
separate, basically, and go on into our own lives. Me into my own,
he into his death. We both knew what we were doing. It was a very
intense time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
