<HEADLINE>
COLONIAL'S ALTERATIONS WON'T LET TROUSERS DROP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Progress has its price. Such is the case
with the 13th hole at Colonial Country Club, where off-season
course tweaks will render it impossible for competitors at the
MasterCard Colonial to duplicate two of the most memorable shots in
tournament history.
</P>
<P>
   Because the lips of greenside bunkers were sharpened, creating
steeper escape angles, no one will be able to putt out of a sand
trap for birdie, as Tom Purtzer did during the final round of his
victory in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll need a 60-degree loft on that putter to get out of that
bunker now,'' said David Hull, chairman of the Colonial greens
committee and who oversaw the $3.5 million course renovation
project.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar fashion, an ornamental rock wall at the shoreline
of a greenfront pond will prevent players from playing shots out of
the hazard. With no reason to wade into the water, players will
have no reason to remove their pants, as Ian Baker-Finch did while
recording his memorable ``Bogey in Boxer Shorts'' during 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Because he had forgotten to pack a rain suit, Baker-Finch
removed his trousers and chipped from the pond wearing blue boxer
shorts. ``It's lucky I had my good ones on,'' he said after his
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we've altered a bit of history,'' Hull said, laughing.
``No more bunker putts and no more dropping drawers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
