<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BURCH-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FULL SALUTES ARE DUE FOR COLONIAL, NELSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Spike Dykes, former Texas Tech football
coach and world-class philosopher, once theorized that the subtle
yet significant difference been involvement and commitment could be
found in a plate of ham and eggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chicken is involved,'' Dykes said. ``But that pig is
committed.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, we offer a four-oink salute to organizers of
the MasterCard Colonial and GTE Byron Nelson Classic for their
off-season efforts to enhance PGA Tour events in Fort Worth-Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Each group, in its own way, has shown tangible proof that it
will not settle for mere involvement with professional golf in the
21st century. Both events are committed to keeping star players
roaming local fairways.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, that sounds like a chamber-of-commerce stance. But it's
also an accurate one, based on what has transpired at both courses
since the final putts dropped at the 1999 tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Colonial officials have completed a $3.5 million course
renovation project and bumped the purse for their May 18-21 event
by $500,000, to $3.3 million. Nelson officials have begun the first
phase of a $3 million course improvement effort and bumped the
purse of their May 11-14 event by $1 million, to $4 million. That's
putting your money where your golf is, to the combined tune of
almost $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Among PGA Tour stops, you'd be hard-pressed to find more hard
evidence of long-term commitment than what has unfolded within a
35-mile radius over the past 12 months. That's why 46 of the top 50
money winners from last season, including Tiger Woods (Nelson) and
David Duval (Colonial), are expected to compete in at least one
local event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being right next to each other, you can't help but compare,''
said Patrick McEvoy, Nelson tournament chairman. ``We've got two
unique tournaments, but, hopefully, we complement each other. We're
trying to spread the message that we're serious about making our
event one of the premier events on the PGA Tour. Colonial, I think,
is sending the same message.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of Colonial's face-lift], which required shutting down
the course for 10 months, every green has been rebuilt to original
specifications. Some bunkers have been added, others removed. The
course has been lengthened by 95 yards with new tee boxes at hole
Nos. 5, 7, 9, 11, 12 and 18. Yet most changes are so subtle that
``85 percent of the members will look out there and think that
nothing's changed,'' said David Hull, chairman of the Colonial
greens committee that oversaw the project.
</P>
<P>
   Some ornamental changes, like stone facades on the bridges, will
be evident to fans during tournament week. But the real star of
this show will be the new greens, which have been covered in A-4
bent grass. More resistant to heat than its predecessor, a Pincross
bent, the new grass provides almost twice as many blades per cubic
inch. That means truer rolls and, best of all, elimination of an
infestation of poa-annua grass that plagued Colonial in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to identify his primary piece of feedback from the
renovation, Hull said: ``Everyone compliments the greens.''
</P>
<P>
   They should. Media members joined club officials in a Monday
tournament. The greens were the purest I've putted in Texas. From
personal experience, the closest comparison would be Augusta
National Golf Club. That's not meant as hometown boosterism. That's
a fact.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a fact that Nelson officials are involved in a $3
million renovation of the TPC-Las Colinas layout at the Four
Seasons Resort. Those changes will be implemented over three years,
although the course already is home to 781 more trees than last
year. In addition, the 10th hole has been radically redesigned,
with a new tee box, five new bunkers and a more sloping green. More
major changes are in store, including a lake for the closing hole
by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice to say, there will be nothing subtle about the Nelson's
approach to course renovations. Just as there was nothing subtle
about an April 4 announcement that the Nelson purse _ for the
second time in six months _ would be bumped by an additional
$500,000, to $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, tournament officials benefited from a PGA Tour commitment
to underwrite 50 percent of any purse increase up to $4 million
during the 2000 season. But it was still a bold step. Why take it?
</P>
<P>
   McEvoy said tournament officials wanted to send a message to
other tournament organizers and to players who once objected that
Nelson purses were out of line with the tournament's charitable
contributions. In 1992, the tournament offered a $1.1 million purse
and donated $3.05 million to charity. This year, the purse is $4
million and the charitable target is $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a perception among some golfers that we hope to
change,'' McEvoy said. ``We viewed this as an opportunity to make
people scratch their heads and show them that we're serious. We'd
like to be a bell cow in setting the standard to attract the top
golfers.''
</P>
<P>
   Just don't expect Colonial officials to raise their purse to $4
million ... yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is not the only answer in this deal,'' said Phil Thomas,
Colonial tournament chairman. ``I can't believe that another purse
increase, at this stage, would affect our field.''
</P>
<P>
   Colonial members, in other words, are comfortable with their
current commitment level. Based on the quality of their off-season
course changes, they have reason to be.  &QL; 
Praise for Haas
</P>
<P>
   Of all the notable rounds played at the 2000 Masters, one of the
most overlooked accomplishments may have been a second-round 73
posted by Hunter Haas, the amateur from Fort Worth who recently
joined the field for the MasterCard Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the perspective of John Grace, a Fort Worth
resident and Senior Tour competitor who has walked a mile in Haas'
golf spikes. Grace, 52, played as an amateur in the 1975 and 1976
Masters. He failed to break 75 in either tournament, missed both
cuts and posted a scoring average of 77 at Augusta National Golf
Club.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Grace was intrigued when Haas, 23, bounced back from
an opening 80 to shoot a 73 before missing the cut at Augusta
National Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't realize how good a score that really is,
especially for an amateur,'' Grace said. ``But I do. It's tough on
amateurs to play at Augusta, for a lot of reasons. The golf course
is so different than anything else you've ever played. It's hard to
adjust to the speed of those greens. That's why very few amateurs
play well there. To rebound like that shows me that Hunter Haas is
a heck of a player.'' \Nsubheds:Nicklaus to New Orleans Jack
Nicklaus has joined the field for the Compaq Classic of New Orleans
(May 4-7), where he will compete in the same event as his son,
Gary, a PGA Tour rookie. For Nicklaus, 60, it marks his first
appearance since 1991 at a tour event outside Florida other than
the major championships, the Memorial Tournament or the AT&AMP;T Pebble
Beach Pro-Am.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus, 60, also designed English Turn Golf &AMP; Country Club,
host site of the New Orleans event.  &QL; 
Kuehne adds events
</P>
<P>
   Hank Kuehne, the 1998 U.S. Amateur champ from SMU, has accepted
sponsor's exemptions to the Shell Houston Open (April 27-30) and
the Kemper Open (June 1-4). Kuehne, a Dallas native competing on
the Buy.com Tour, was added last week to the field for the GTE
Byron Nelson Classic (May 11-14). Kuehne said he hopes the PGA Tour
appearances will help hone his game in time to qualify for the U.S.
Open (June 15-18).  &QL; 
Double birdie
</P>
<P>
   Annika Sorenstam successfully dealt with two birdies on the same
hole at last week's Longs Drug Challenge. While sizing up a 15-foot
birdie putt on the 10th hole in the first round, Sorenstam was
distracted by a wild turkey that decided to roost on the green at
Twelve Bridges Golf Club in Lincoln, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   She joined caddie Terry McNamara is chasing the bird off the
green. Sorenstam returned and drained the birdie putt. She went on
to finish in a tie for sixth, 11 strokes behind winner Juli
Inkster.  &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2110EDT &QL; 
