<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GONZALEZ-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELIG'S WILL DRIVE REALIGNMENT PLANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ At first glance, Bud Selig's remarks at the owners'
meeting Monday look like they were spoken with a touch of
arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some realignment, we'll go to an unbalanced
schedule, we'll rotate divisions for interleague play,''
Commissioner Bud said. ``Everything that I wanted to do, we will
do.''
</P>
<P>
   It's fair to criticize the commish for such things as his role
in the 1994 strike that canceled the World Series and his handling
of the John Rocker affair, but it would be wrong to call him
arrogant.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing brash about the statement. It merely serves as
an acknowledgement of Selig's strength as commissioner, namely his
ability to build a consensus.
</P>
<P>
   When the owners next meet in June, there will be moderate
realignment that will move the Rangers to the American League
Central, the Tampa Bay Devil Rays to the National League East and
the Arizona Diamondbacks to the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   There will be an unbalanced schedule, because that lends itself
to good pennant races and intriguing matchups in September.
</P>
<P>
   And there will be new matchups for interleague play, to revive
interest in games between NL and AL clubs.
</P>
<P>
   It won't happen because Selig will brandish his big ``best
interests of the game'' hammer, but because he will convince one
and all that it is the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   He will work the phones, listen again to the various gripes that
were aired Monday and in the weeks leading up to that meeting, and
persuade everyone that while his realignment plan isn't perfect,
it's the best option.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things you like to do with the clubs is address
their concerns,'' Selig said. ``The things we heard today and in
the last month aren't anything we didn't know about. You still try
to be sensitive and let people know that you care about their
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to address some problems and we will do that.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those problems is the proposed six-team AL Central, which
would include the Rangers, Cleveland Indians, Chicago White Sox,
Detroit Tigers, Kansas City Royals and Minnesota Twins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make any sense,'' Royals president Mike Herman
said. ``I don't think we're not going to win anyhow for a couple of
years, but when this young team of ours is a contender I'd rather
have a level field like everyone else. If everybody has four, why
shouldn't I have four? Why have two more teams you've got to go
through if they get hot? You just have to use your common sense,
but that doesn't always work for baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The other problem is the proposed alignment in the National
League, which would have four divisions of four teams. There is
some debate about what teams go where _ do the Astros go in with
the Braves, Marlins and Devil Rays, or do the Reds, who are in the
same time zone? _ but the biggest controversy is the lack of a
wild-card team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The National League really works out pretty well, there's no
question about that,'' Selig said. ``The only negative I've heard
is that there's no wild card.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``negative'' actually is a source of some amusement. When
the wild card was proposed before the '94 season, there was much
consternation about it messing with the fabric of the game. Now,
it's apparently such a part of that same fabric, some clubs can't
live without it.
</P>
<P>
   Selig won't budge on his plan, though, because the schedule
gurus tell him the best way to go unbalanced is to have an even
number of teams per division, and the best way to do that is the
4-6-4 alignment in the AL and the 4-4-4-4 alignment in the NL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're willing to go back and look at anything, but that
produces in structure the best schedule for the most clubs,'' Selig
said. ``As we address one concern, we have to be very careful not
to disrupt the schedule to the point that every thing we set out to
do we injure.''
</P>
<P>
   If it's the best thing for the most clubs, it will be Bud the
Consensus Maker, not Bud the Brash, that gets it passed.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
