<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-STEWARDS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWARDS USE VARIOUS TOOLS TO MAKE THE CORRECT CALLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ If there's a close call that doesn't go
someone's way at the horse track, no one charges out of a dugout
and kicks dirt all over the finish line. But that doesn't mean
horse racing doesn't have umpires.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike baseball, however, horse racing's umpires _ they're
called the stewards _ aren't on the field of play. The stewards
view the racetrack from a booth seven stories up in the grandstand
at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   That's too far to kick dirt on their shoes. But the history of
horse racing has stories of fans who showed their displeasure over
a steward's decision.
</P>
<P>
   After a horse was disqualified from first place in a race at
Bandera Downs in 1990, people who had bet on the disqualified
winner beat on the glass surrounding the track's video replay
booth. Don Essary, who was general manager at the time, thought
that was tame. He said he could remember when fans set fires in
garbage cans after a disqualification at Sportsman's Park near
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't happened at Lone Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear of that more in Chicago and New York,'' Lone Star
steward John Ferrera said. ``The fans are more vocal.''
</P>
<P>
   There hasn't been anything to complain about at Lone Star. There
have been 38 races through the first week of the thoroughbred
season, but no races were reviewed due to a stewards' inquiry or
jockey objection. The class of racing might have something to do
with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There sometimes isn't much work for a steward when he's
watching the races because of the expertise of most of the riders
in the jockey colony at Lone Star,'' said Mike Burleson, director
of racing for the Texas Racing Commission and the person in charge
of hiring the stewards. ``By the same token, there are a lot of
upscale stables with good horses that come in to race there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrera is joined in the Lone Star booth by two other stewards,
Chuck Nuber and Dennis Sidener. They are employed by the Texas
Racing Commission, and they rotate between Lone Star and the
thoroughbred seasons at Texas' other tracks _ Sam Houston Race Park
in Houston and Retama Park near San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Some tools that the stewards use to monitor the racing are
obvious. For a close call at the finish line, they are assisted by
placing judges who find the horse who hit the wire first by using a
high-tech digital photo-finish camera. And if there are horses who
are bumped off course or have to alter course because of
interference from another horse and rider, the stewards rely on
video cameras that provide head-on, rear-view and side-angle views.
</P>
<P>
   Other sports might still be wrestling with the practicality of
instant replay, but it has been a part of horse racing for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's helped especially when a horse owner or trainer has a
question about a decision we rendered they can come back here to
the racing office building and watch the replay,'' Nuber said.
</P>
<P>
   The stewards' decision stands, unless the owner, trainer or
jockey wishes to appeal to the racing commission. The commission
hires a state-sanctioned hearings examiner to listen to the case
and make a proposal for decision at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   But Nuber estimates that more than half of the stewards' work
comes away from the time they spend watching the races. The
stewards keep an office in the barn area where they make rulings on
eligibility of horses, trainers and jockeys and also impose
penalties and fines for misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of it is legal work. So, like umpires who go to umpire's
school, stewards go to stewards school as a part of mandatory
accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   Burleson said it's a 10-day school that is followed by written
and oral exams. There are two recognized stewards schools _ at
University of Louisville and University of Arizona _ and every
three years a steward must participate in continuing education
program provided by those institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Burleson also said Texas law requires stewards to pass an annual
test and eye exam.
</P>
<P>
   Stewards come from various backgrounds mostly related to the
racetrack. Some, such as Larry Snyder at Louisiana Downs and Bill
Hartack at Fair Grounds, are former jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   At Lone Star, Ferrera previously worked as a director of racing
at Fonner Park in Nebraska. Sidener had a training career that took
him through 10 states. Nuber's family has owned and raced horses
since the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in this room has a different background in racing,''
Nuber said. ``That's a positive. When the three of us get together
to discuss a ruling, we all can draw from different points of view.
I think it helps us render a proper decision.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
