<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MICHIGAN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
BUSH STILL CONSIDERING McCAIN FOR VICE PRESIDENT 
 
By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ Gov. George W. Bush said Tuesday he plans to
talk to former rival John McCain about being his vice presidential
running mate _ a possibility that McCain rejected previously and
again after Bush's latest remarks.
</P>
<P>
   On May 9 in Pittsburgh, Bush will have his first face-to-face
meeting with McCain since the Arizona senator dropped out of the
acrimonious GOP presidential race. On a daily basis, Bush is asked
whom he would consider as a running mate if he secures the GOP
nomination this summer.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance with Michigan Gov. John Engler, Bush was asked
again about the status of his deliberations. He surprised his news
media audience by saying that although McCain has repeatedly and
emphatically rejected a vice-presidential nomination, Bush may
offer McCain the right of first refusal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's said he's not interested, but until I talk to him
and find out how interested or not interested he is, I'll give him
consideration,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty outspoken about his opinion, but I want to look
him in the eye and visit with him,'' Bush said. ``I'm going to take
him for his word'' that he's not interested, Bush added, but he
said he'll know for sure once he meets with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many people on the list, there is no list'' of
potential running mates, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people will be given consideration. Then, of course,
the list will be narrowed over a period of time to get to the final
short list,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seemed to further water down his comments when he said
Engler, who failed to deliver a Michigan primary win for Bush, also
would be considered. He's made similar comments about Govs. Tom
Ridge of Pennsylvania, Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin and Christine
Todd Whitman of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Engler, Bush said, ``John's a friend of mine. I
like him. I trust him. In spite of the fact that we had a rough go
here in Michigan, he's still a friend of mine.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain spokesman Todd Harris reacted to Bush's comments by
saying ``talk like this is always flattering whether it's from
Governor Bush or Jesse Ventura. However, Sen. McCain has made it
more than clear that he is not interested in being vice
president.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
