<HEADLINE>
STOCK CHAOS MAY POINT TO CONSOLIDATION IN ONLINE TRAVEL BOOKING
INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (duplication warning: also sent with `t' code) 
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week's train wreck in technology stocks drew a sharper bead
on predictions, long ignored by many in the hubris-heavy realm of
online travel commerce, that the future belongs to a relative
handful of Internet companies that can establish themselves as
major brands, with easy-to-use technology to provide the best
service within well-defined travel niches.
</P>
<P>
   That's a mighty grand statement. So let's ask Melissa Shore, the
senior analyst for Jupiter Communications, the Internet commerce
research firm, to bottom-line it instead: ``The big get bigger, the
smaller get focused, and the middle dies,'' she said Tuesday,
discussing the short-term prospects for the online travel industry,
which is now the leading single category of respectable Internet
commerce. (I say ``respectable'' only because the Internet's actual
star money-maker happens to be pornography).
</P>
<P>
   Online booking is not yet widespread among corporate business
travelers, most of whom are required to use company travel agencies
to make their arrangements. Only about 40 percent of employees,
mostly in smaller companies, make their own travel arrangements,
according to PhoCusWright, a leading Internet travel researcher.
However, business travelers are now paying more attention to
Internet booking because companies large and small are increasingly
wiring their travel departments to provide internal online booking
engines affiliated with their existing travel agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some companies now are offering employees the choice to book
online or use the traditional agency service,'' Shore said. ``And
some are planning to mandate the use of online booking in a few
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, that category _ managed, in-house online booking _ is
so new that Internet commerce analysts don't even track it in
projections. But Shore predicted that within a few years, in-house
bookings could well grow to ``dwarf'' the other categories of
online travel booking. In short, the experts suggest, if you're a
business traveler, get used to the imminent prospect, or at least
the opportunity, of going online to make your own arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   This is a rapidly growing phenomenon across the board. Americans
booked $6.5 billion in leisure and business travel online in 1999,
almost triple the amount booked in 1998, according to Jupiter. That
represented only 5 percent of all travel bookings, most of which
continue to be made through traditional travel agents and by
telephone directly with airlines and hotels. But by 2005, when the
growth is expected to level off, about 14 percent of all travel
booking will be online, according to Jupiter projections. That,
however, doesn't include the anticipated increases in in-house
online booking, Shore said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the consolidation in the industry is gathering force.
Last week's dot-com debacle ``certainly adds to the frenzy of it
all,'' Shore said. The trend became notable last year, especially
with the $2.2 billion merger of Saber Holdings Inc.'s
Travelocity.com and Preview Travel Inc., two big online travel
companies that together now have 17 million registered users.
</P>
<P>
   According to PhoCusWright, the online site that booked the most
air tickets last year was Travelocity.com. Expedia.com and
Priceline.com ranked third and fourth, respectively. The other
sites among the top nine belonged to individual airlines, with
Southwest Airlines _ whose Web site is admired for its easy-to-use
technology _ ranking second overall. Southwest, incidentally,
announced Tuesday that its Web site accounted for 25 percent of its
passenger revenue in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Among leisure travelers who book online, low fares are the main
consideration. But the PhoCusWright study found that business
travelers are a different breed. Less than half of frequent
business travelers surveyed said that price was their primary
consideration when booking online. Business travelers also
indicated that, once they have booked online, they are far more
enthusiastic than leisure travelers about doing so in the future.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lesson in the second-place ranking in online bookings
by Southwest, which is a favorite of business travelers: easy to
use doesn't necessarily mean simple-minded. The Internet world is
beginning to catch on to the idea that most of us don't have the
time or patience to wander aimlessly through their virtual
wonderlands. We just want to get to Los Angeles next Tuesday, with
some degree of convenience. And we don't want to spend all day
making the arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Partly reflecting this, Expedia.com said Tuesday that it had
added a new feature _ ``Build Your Own Trip'' _ to its Web site
that allows users to immediately see a wide range of fares for
specific itineraries. It's an astonishingly complicated technology
that is meant to make the booking process both more useful and more
simple, said Expedia, which does about 25 percent of its bookings
in business travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be less clicks,'' said Suzi LeVine, Expedia's
marketing director. ``The goal with this new feature is to address
the more time-sensitive folks.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
