<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-HSBC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL LYNCH AND HSBC IN JOINT VENTURE
</HEADLINE>
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To fulfill its dreams of creating a financial services empire on
the Internet, Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. is teaming up with HSBC Holdings
to offer online banking and investment services throughout Europe
and Asia, the two companies announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of merging with a bank or spending billions of dollars
to buy one, Merrill will spend up to $500 million over five years
on its half of a venture that Merrill's chairman, David H.
Komansky, 60, described as the first international combination of
electronic banking and investment services. HSBC, which is based in
London and is one of the biggest banking companies in Europe and
Asia, will own the other half of the venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a stroke, this makes Merrill Lynch and HSBC major players,
maybe the major players, in global e-commerce,'' said Sir John
Bond, 58, group chairman of HSBC.
</P>
<P>
   Komansky and Sir John said that the link was not a prelude to
further ties between the two companies or a full-blown merger, but
they said the arrangement did not preclude either company from
trying to buy the other.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came together so quickly that the companies
have not come up with a name for the operation or chosen a
management team. Until they do, Edward L. Goldberg, 59, an
executive in Merrill's operations services group, will be the
interim chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Merrill rose $9.25, or 10 percent, to $99.50 on
Tuesday, but the announcement probably will not put an end to the
long-running speculation that Merrill will merge with or be
acquired by another big financial company, like the Chase Manhattan
Corp. It does show how Merrill plans to grow outside the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way financial-services firms are going to do
deals,'' said James P. Gorman, 41, a former McKinsey &AMP; Co.
consultant who joined Merrill as its chief marketing officer last
year. He said the companies could create a system to serve several
countries much faster by working together than either company could
on its own. That approach is new on Wall Street, where firms have
traditionally guarded their products and customers closely.
</P>
<P>
   Together, Merrill and HSBC plan to offer online access to their
services to customers they describe as the ``mass affluent'' in
Britain by the end of the year and in Australia, Canada, Hong Kong,
Japan, Germany and other countries over the next four years. They
will focus on people with more than $100,000 to invest who want to
make their own financial decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Customers will be able to buy stocks, bonds, mutual funds and
other investment products created by the two partners and other
companies. The service will also allow users to write checks or use
debit cards or automated teller machines. It will compete with
different online banks and electronic brokerage firms in different
markets but probably will not be the lowest-priced offering in any
of them, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is somewhat of an acknowledgment by Merrill Lynch that
the self-directed market is not only real but is substantial in
size,'' said Henry McVey, an analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, Merrill dismissed do-it-yourself investors as
an unattractive segment of the market. But now, having introduced
an online brokerage service that has received strong reviews,
Merrill hopes to export its new technology along with its
investment research and products, like initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This puts an exclamation point on financial services
convergence,'' McVey said. ``We're at an inflection point where
brokerage companies can no longer just manufacture their own
product and sell it through their proprietary networks. They have
to use alliances to seek alternative distribution channels.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill has learned through experience how costly foreign
acquisitions can be. Over the last few years, it has paid more than
$5 billion to buy Mercury Asset Management, a mutual fund company
based in London, and extended its network of brokerage branches
into Canada and Japan. In Canada, it bought Midland Walwyn, a
healthy brokerage firm, for $855 million. In Japan, it bought
branches of a failed firm, Yamaichi Securities, and spent much more
than planned to revive the operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are heavy costs and the payback period is really long,''
McVey said. ``With this, you get instant access to a whole new
group of customers and it doesn't put a big drag on your income
statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives of Merrill and HSBC emphasized that they hoped the
venture would attract new customers, not cannibalize their existing
bases. There are 10 million households within the target market for
the new service, said Roberta Arena, group general manager of
global e-business for HSBC, and that number is expected to rise to
50 million in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Komansky said the companies expected the venture to break even
within five years, with operations in some countries turning
profits along the way. Thomas Patrick, Merrill's chief financial
officer, said that, with tax credits for its share of the venture's
losses along the way, the investment should not have a significant
effect on Merrill's earnings. On Monday, Merrill reported
first-quarter profit of more than $1 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0815 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CHINA-U.S.-RIGHTS-1ST     04-18 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-RIGHTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. RIGHTS GROUP FOILS U.S. EFFORT TO CONDEMN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS for complete rewrite, changing emphasis; expands; changes
byline) 
(Eds., skedded on some NYT budgets as CHINA-U.N.-RIGHTS) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an embarrassing defeat for the Clinton
administration, the major United Nations human rights body voted in
Geneva on Tuesday not to act on a U.S. resolution criticizing
China's human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   The vote came after the State Department released one of its
most withering annual reports on human rights in China and after
the secretary of state, Madeleine Albright, made a rushed overnight
trip to Geneva from India last month to make an impassioned speech
to the group, the U.N. Commission on Human Rights. It was the first
appearance by a secretary of state before the body, officials have
said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission voted 22-18 to back a Chinese motion for no
action on the U.S.-sponsored resolution; 12 nations abstained. In
effect, Tuesday's vote prevented discussion on the substance of the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department made an extra effort this year to have
China's human rights practices condemned in what has become an
annual test of Washington's desire to criticize Beijing. The
resolution also failed last year, but the United States committed
less lobbying power then.
</P>
<P>
   By announcing its intention in January to sponsor a critical
resolution, much earlier than usual, the administration signaled to
Congress that it was paying as much attention to rights abuses in
China as to Beijing's desired entry into the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House on Tuesday, a spokesman for the National
Security Council, P.J. Crowley, said the administration was
disappointed. He noted that the vote today was closer _ a
difference of four votes, rather than five last year.
</P>
<P>
   In Geneva, where the assistant secretary for human rights,
Harold H. Koh, led the lobbying campaign among delegates, he tried
to put a positive face on the vote. ``The basic message we sent to
the Chinese was that the United States will stand up for the
Chinese people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the senior Chinese official at the vote on Tuesday,
Qiao Zonghuai, denounced the resolution as ``an anti-China
political farce directed by the United States alone.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department's human rights report this year described
China's ``poor human rights record'' as having ``deteriorated
markedly'' throughout 1999 and specifically referred to actions
against Falun Gong, the spiritual movement whose top leaders were
sentenced to long terms in prison in December.
</P>
<P>
   The report also cited Beijing's ``extremely limited tolerance of
public dissent aimed at the government, fear of unrest and the
limited scope or inadequate implementation of laws protecting basic
freedoms.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution itself rebuked China for ``severe measures taken
to restrict the peaceful activities'' of Buddhists, Moslems,
Christians and the Falun Gong.
</P>
<P>
   The Beijing government takes the 53-member U.N. human rights
body seriously and has worked hard in the past several years to
thwart Washington's efforts to criticize its record in such a
public forum.
</P>
<P>
   In assessing Tuesday's defeat for the administration, the
executive director of Human Rights Watch, Ken Roth, applauded the
State Department's efforts but said they were not adequately backed
by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``This never became a White House issue,'' Roth said. In
response, an administration official said the National Security
Adviser, Sandy Berger, had brought the issue up with counterparts
in other countries.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In reviewing the vote, Roth said it was clear that among
countries that abstained there were at least seven that could have
been persuaded, with a White House campaign, to vote in favor of
the United States. Among those he cited were South Korea, Rwanda,
Argentina, Ecuador and Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Four votes needed to be changed from abstentions into votes
against the Chinese motion for a substantive discussion on the U.S.
resolution to move ahead. A tie would have allowed discussions at
the commission to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   In preparing for the vote Tuesday, the State Department was
publicly upbeat. Koh told reporters last month that Washington had
the ``best chance since 1995'' to defeat the Chinese motion to
block discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Koh commended Albright, at the time, saying that she was ``more
committed to the issues of democracy, human rights and labor than
anyone I've known.'' He added, ``She is the leader of our team, and
she is in charge of putting forward and advancing our entire
commission agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   But behind the scenes, the State Department had a fairly
difficult task. Their prime goal was to persuade the European Union
to co-sponsor the resolution with Washington, to put up a more
united front against the Chinese and to encourage smaller countries
to stand up to the concerted efforts of Beijing to block the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   According to an account by a State Department official of
Washington's efforts to build unity within the European Union,
France and Belgium remained holdouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The European Union adopted a sub-optimal approach _ that they
would vote with us on the no-action but wouldn't co-sponsor,'' the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the European Union was against the Chinese motion to
block discussion.
</P>
<P>
   But the official acknowledged that leaders of those European
Union countries in favor of co-sponsoring the resolution, including
Britain, did not go out of their way to lobby other countries for
sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The European Union's commitments on these human rights issues
are concerned with how their relationship plays with Beijing,'' the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   In its efforts to get co-sponsorship, the United States
encountered a recently developed tactic of the Beijing government
in which China offers countries ``dialogue not confrontation.''
Under this rubric, China holds closed door meetings with
governments who say they are concerned about Beijing's rights
record.
</P>
<P>
   Australia and Canada are among those that conduct such a
dialogue with China. Neither co-sponsored the U.S. resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The United States also held a human rights dialogue with the
Chinese in 1999 but the Chinese canceled the dialogue for 2000 _ a
visit by Chinese officials to meet with administration officials _
after the bombing of their Belgrade embassy during the Kosovo war.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the year of the summit between the Chinese leader,
Jiang Zemin and President Clinton, Washington did not submit a
resolution to the human rights commission, saying there were
improvements in the record.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the United States succeeded for the only time in
defeating the Chinese government's procedural vote to block
discussion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
