<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL REVOLUTION IN IRAN
</HEADLINE>
 By HOMAYOON HARIRI Written with VIVIENNE WALT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was working on my computer science graduate project in Tehran
when the Islamic revolution broke out in Iran in 1979. It was so
exciting; it's hard to describe the feeling. I was 28. Everyone
took part in the revolution, hand in hand. There was no difference
between religious people and those who had their own ideas. We just
hoped for a better country.
</P>
<P>
   I grew up in Tehran and got my electrical engineering degree
from Shiraz University. If I hadn't gone into computers, I would
have become a heart surgeon or maybe a university professor. But
during my military training, for about 18 months I was working in
an army computer center, and I really liked it.
</P>
<P>
   Some of my friends left the country. When I was finishing my
bachelor's degree I thought about continuing my studies overseas.
But then, after a while, I forgot all about it. I've had short
business trips to England, France, Germany and even Dubai, in the
United Arab Emirates. But I wouldn't want to live in any of them. I
thought I could help Iran by using my expertise.
</P>
<P>
   When I graduated, I got a job for the government, running the
computer department for the railways. After about 10 years there, I
started my own company. That was nearly 12 years ago. We develop
software and create management-information systems.
</P>
<P>
   We are very interested in exporting our software, like India
does. But we are under economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   We've discussed ideas with about 10 companies in Canada,
England, Dubai and Saudi Arabia. But whenever it gets to the point
of signing a contract, everything freezes.
</P>
<P>
   We signed a contact with a company in Sheffield, England, to buy
software from them. But about eight months ago they told us they'd
been bought by an American company and had to end their
relationship with us. We'd made about a $30,000 investment.
</P>
<P>
   I think the best kind of business connection we could have with
the United States would be to work on outsourcing.
</P>
<P>
   They could order us to develop software for them. We'd do it
even better than India. The rate of pay is very low here. We pay
software engineers about $50 a day. But it won't happen until the
United States lifts the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Our engineers are very young. They've heard a lot of stories
about young Americans getting very rich. Some have emigrated to
Canada, others are looking for jobs. But people love the
environment of this company.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the software we use in the company is Microsoft. When
friends fly to Dubai, they bring back software we need. But they
can't give us any training or support, and we always have problems.
They have no representatives in Iran, so we have to solve all our
problems ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is growing very, very fast in Iran. There's no way
to escape it.
</P>
<P>
   In three years' time most of the television sets will be digital
and automatically connect to satellite television. That's banned
right now. But 10 years ago, VCR's were forbidden; eventually, they
had to change the law.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody can prevent people from getting information. When they
have information from outside, this will have an influence on
people.
</P>
<P>
   I have two children: my son is 24 and is finishing his last year
of university, studying software engineering and working with me as
a Web designer. My daughter's finishing high school. She wants to
study English literature at university. I'm sure they will stay.
They both love this country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
