<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CART-INDY FEUD TAKES ITS TOLL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's news-views-and-phews edition of The Sporting Muse:
</P>
<P>
   News: Long Beach Grand Prix a huge success once again, bids
adieu until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Views: There is a trend about the Grand Prix that bears
watching. Each year, it seems more and more people attend the event
for its ambiance than its exhaust. It has always been a great
party, but there were plenty of gearheads in the crowds when the
Unsers and Andrettis were regulars. The current CART roster is
loaded with talented, promising drivers, but most of them hail from
Brazil or Europe. Add the ever-growing reputation of NASCAR, and
one can see why CART events and its drivers are suffering from a
lack of exposure.
</P>
<P>
   The snit between CART and Indy has hurt everyone involved, to
the point where even the casual customers can note a difference.
Take the example of driver Kenny Brack. The 1999 Indy 500 champ was
in Long Beach, but who knew or cared? His Indy win was hollow
because the best drivers weren't there, and he was just another
driver in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   CART and Indy need to come to terms with their problems soon,
for the sake of themselves and cities like Long Beach that have
supported them so well.
</P>
<P>
   News: Renovations at Dodgers Stadium are unveiled.
</P>
<P>
   Views: I expected the worse, so I was pleasantly shocked that
the changes were subtle and effective. The extension of the field
seats was seamless and made the whole park seem more intimate. The
new suites on the club level turned out to be more aesthetic than
originally planned. Plus, the club was able to retain a handful of
club seats, so not every former season-ticket holder was forced to
move.
</P>
<P>
   One potential drawback: The corporations that can afford season
tickets for the new field seats don't always use their tickets, and
the sight of empty seats down is very Clipper-esque. The team needs
to work out a system that will put a butt in every new seat down
there.
</P>
<P>
   News: Kings play their last game of the season tonight at the
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Views: Their current 0-3 first round playoff status against
Detroit was predictable. It's not the Kings' fault that the Western
Conference is loaded. Detroit simply has more and quicker forwards
than the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the Kings are still trying to overcome the league's
mid-season rule changes of two seasons ago, when it legislated
against the neutral zone trap. Larry Robinson's Kings used the trap
and employed bigger players to make it work. Kings' G.M. Dave
Taylor attacked that problem in the off-season and he'll need to
attack it again this off-season. Kings fans hopefully will remain
patient. Taylor and coach Andy Murray have the team headed in the
right direction.
</P>
<P>
   News: Kings critics say Jamie Storr should be tonight's starting
goaltender. Views: I agree. But not because of anything Stephane
Fiset has or hasn't done. The Kings simply need to shake things up
after three straight losses. Considering their 0-for-series power
play stat, maybe the Kings can use Storr on the point.
</P>
<P>
   News: Baseball postpones talks on realignment until June.
</P>
<P>
   View: Bud Selig's plan to have four divisions in the N.L. and
one six-team and two four-team divisions in the A.L. doesn't have a
lot of support. So what would be wrong with going back to two
divisions per league? It's the easiest way to make things work and
keep the wild cards involved short of trashing both leagues and
starting over from scratch (a horrible idea that I shouldn't have
even mentioned).
</P>
<P>
   One man's suggestion:
</P>
<P>
   A.L. East: Baltimore, Boston, Cleveland, Detroit, New York,
Tampa Bay and Toronto. This keeps the essence of the old A.L. East
intact.
</P>
<P>
   A.L. West: Anaheim, Chicago, Kansas City, Milwaukee, Minnesota,
Oakland and Seattle. All of these teams have been division-mates in
the past. Milwaukee never should have moved to the N.L. in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   N.L. East: Atlanta, Chicago, Florida, Montreal, New York,
Philadelphia, Pittsburgh, St. Louis. Keeps the important St.
Louis-Chicago rivalry intact.
</P>
<P>
   N.L. West: Arizona, Cincinnati, Colorado, Houston, Los Angeles,
San Diego, San Francisco and Texas. Likewise, they've all been
mates before except for Texas. Taking in Texas and shipping the
Brewers out solves the desire of the Rangers and Astros to be in
the same division. This plan also keeps the D-Backs in the N.L.
</P>
<P>
   If Selig insists on staying in the N.L., put him in the N.L.
West and send Colorado to the A.L. West. If ever a park was made
for the DH-ing A.L., it's Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduling? In the two divisions of eight teams in the N.L.,
teams would play 16 games against division-mates (112 games), four
games against each team in the other division (32), and 12
interleague games (158 games total) based on interest and
geography.
</P>
<P>
   In the two divisions of seven teams in the A.L., teams would
play 17 games against division mates (102), six games against each
team in the other division (42), plus 12 interleague games (158
games total). Each division champ and best two wild cards per
league advance to the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   News: USC's R. Jay Soward goes in the first round of the NFL
draft while UCLA's Danny Farmer goes in the fourth. Raiders pick a
placekicker in round one.
</P>
<P>
   Views: The Soward-Farmer debacle underscores how skewed-up the
NFL is. Soward was unreliable as a Trojan, but fast enough to get
first-round money. All Farmer did was catch everything thrown at
him as a Bruin.
</P>
<P>
   The Raider pick of Sebastian Janikowski makes sense. They have
often reached for a player with an off-field dossier (Anthony Smith
1990, Todd Marinovich 1991, Chester McGlockton 1992). Not only do
they embrace that type of player, but it also allows them to
occasionally pay them under the going rate.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, they've been desperate for a kicker since 1996. In the
last three seasons, the Raiders made just 51 of 82 field goals.
They have gone 20-28 in those three seasons, with ten losses by
three points or less. All eight Raider losses last season were by a
touchdown or less.
</P>
<P>
   News: John Rocker returns to the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Views: If he gets a standing ovation from Braves fans in his
first appearance, Atlanta management can go ahead with its Sheet
Night promotion in August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
