<HEADER>
A0820 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ACADEMIE-JULIAN-ART-$     04-18 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACADEMIE-JULIAN-ART-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR WOMEN, A CLEAN, WELL-LIGHTED PLACE TO PAINT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.) 
 By JOHN RUSSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of this season's more rewarding sleepers is
``Overcoming All Obstacles: The Women of the Academie Julian'' at
the Dahesh Museum, in Manhattan. This little museum is an oasis of
quiet and comfort. Visitors, though not always numerous, tend to be
keenly attentive. The subject matter makes very good points at
every turn but does not set out either to bully or reproach us.
</P>
<P>
   It is in every history of French painting that in 1868 Rodolphe
Julian, a former wrestler, founded an independent art school in
Paris that remains active to this day. It was the only place in the
city at which a woman could study art intensively in a well-lighted
room from a living model and count on being taught by artists of
substantial quality.
</P>
<P>
   Though decidedly comical in his own appearance, and a lifelong
favorite of caricaturists, Julian was not at all stupid. He knew
that his school responded to needs and ambitions that could not at
that time be satisfied anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Women were not yet admitted to the official Ecole des
Beaux-Arts. Julian made it possible for them not only to be taught
by established artists but also to work in class from naked models,
male as well as female.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers recruited by Julian included Adolphe-William
Bouguereau, Tony Robert-Fleury and Jean-Paul Laurens. Though their
reputations may by now largely have faded, they were national
figures at the time, undoubtedly fascinating to their students. In
addition, Bouguereau had married one of his students, a young
Englishwoman called Elizabeth Gardner, so why should others not be
as fortunate?
</P>
<P>
   The Academie Julian was distinctly an original idea whose time
had come, and before long students from all over the world were
applying for admission. Julian was eager, but not at all
disinterested. (Fees for women at his academy were twice as high as
fees for men).
</P>
<P>
   Nor did he accept young people who thought that life in a
Parisian art school would be soft. He kept strictly professional
standards, set his fees as high as the market would bear and was no
fool when it came to spreading the word overseas.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the students in his school included a Philadelphian,
Cecilia Beaux; a Pole, Anna Bilinska; a Californian, Anna Klumpke;
two Germans, Louise-Catherine Breslau and Kathe Kollwitz; a
Russian, Marie Bashkirtseff; and others from Belgium, Sweden and
elsewhere. There was also a hardy body of young Englishwomen who
braved the rigor of grim lodgings and early-morning starts.
</P>
<P>
   It is important to realize that this school proselytized not for
``modern art'' but for superior Salon art. It was through the Salon
that reputations were made. Artists who had never been accepted for
the Salon were unlikely to make a living, let alone a name.
</P>
<P>
   After work by former students at the Academie Julian was first
exhibited in New York, by the Shepherd Gallery in 1989, the school
got a burst of renewed life from Catherine Fehrer, whose father,
Oscar Fehrer, had studied there. Not only did he talk about it with
his daughter at great length, but he also put her in touch with
invaluable, never-before-explored source material in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The present exhibition would in fact have been incomplete
without her advice, her research and her discovery of irreplaceable
archival material.
</P>
<P>
   Those who feel like spending $29.95 on the catalog of this show,
which is on view through May 13, will find what is in effect an
extensive supply of archival photographs, illustrated cartoons and
newspaper articles, together with essays that fill out the whole
history of the Academie Julian.
</P>
<P>
   But with or without the catalog, they will be quietly seduced _
``sedated'' might be as apt a word _ by the sheer comfort of almost
everything that is on view. There is nothing rough, nothing
violent, nothing bitter and nothing provocative about ``Overcoming
All Obstacles.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all was peace and harmony among the female students at the
Academie, however. Marie Bashkirtseff came from a moneyed family
and didn't care who knew it. If she got to class late, as she often
did, she would throw a tantrum unless the best place in the studio
had been kept for her. If she sensed that people thought Breslau
was the better painter of the two _ as many did _ Bashkirtseff knew
how to make herself obnoxious.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Dahesh Museum we don't have to bother with that.
Bashkirtseff looks adorably demure in her self-portrait. As for
Breslau's portrait of the English versifier Henry Davison, he is
the very apotheosis of English foppery. Oscar Wilde should have
written an immortal comedy expressly for him.
</P>
<P>
   In thinking over the impact of this exhibition, the word
``nice'' keeps coming to mind. The room is nice, the staff are
nice, the chairs are nice and the silence (with Fifth Avenue just a
yard or two away) is blissful. And there is a place, after all, for
nice art.
</P>
<P>
   But nice art need not be insipid. There is a drawing by
Rose-Marie Guillaume of someone called simply ``Mademoiselle
Breuil'' that is typical of the quality described in the catalog by
Gabriel P. Weisberg as ``a sense of introspection and strong
individuality.'' It should not surprise us that she held her own in
the Salons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
