<HEADER>
A0823 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CHOUINARD-DANCE-$ADV2     04-18 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOUINARD-DANCE-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBSESSED WITH THE BODY'S FORMATIONS AND FUNCTIONS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   William Harris writes about avant-garde dance, theater and art.  
 By WILLIAM HARRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Offstage, the Montreal-based choreographer Marie Chouinard could
pass for Joni Mitchell's double, with her sleek 5-foot-8-inch
frame, her fragile beauty and her long, blond hair.
</P>
<P>
   Onstage, her persona is fiercer. During her 22-year dance
career, Chouinard has been called everything from ``the high
priestess of choreographic shock'' and ``a sorceress'' to ``the
praying mantis in the hothouse of Quebec dance.''
</P>
<P>
   And little wonder. In her piece ``Petite Danse Sans Nom''
(1980), Chouinard walked onstage, drank a glass of water, crossed
the space, urinated in a bucket, then exited. In ``Mimas, Lune de
Saturne'' (1981), she simulated masturbation, with a human skeleton
standing sentry. Or consider her ``L'Apres-Midi d'un Faune''
(1982), Chouinard's homage to Vaslav Nijinsky. In her Debussy-less
version, the dancer breaks off a horn from her head and reattaches
it to the crotch of her costume, where it becomes an erect phallus.
</P>
<P>
   These and eight other solo dances _ including her first,
``Crystallization'' (1978) _ are being presented by Compagnie Marie
Chouinard in a rare appearance in New York at the Joyce Theater for
five performances, beginning on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Les Solos 1978-1998,'' as the two-and-a-half-hour evening is
called, will not be performed by Chouinard, as the dances were
originally, but by three other women, Lucie Mongrain, Carole Prieur
and Elise Vanderborght.
</P>
<P>
   Chouinard is obsessed with the body, the delicate architecture
of its circulatory, muscular and skeletal structures, and its more
practical functions. Using contorted, spastic movements, often
accompanied by the amplified sound of breathing, she creates moody
meditations that celebrate life's mysteries _ and its impermanence.
</P>
<P>
   The work is about time and transformation, presented with a
theatricality that is both showy and unsettling. As Anna Kisselgoff
noted in a 1990 review in The New York Times, ``Marie Chouinard
specializes in imagery that most would like to repress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in awe of the systems of the body,'' said Chouinard,
smoking a panatela during a recent interview in New York. ``My work
explores the intelligence of the body _ its soul _ to touch what is
unknown, to make incarnate something that has never been
incarnated.''
</P>
<P>
   Chouinard began studying ballet as a teen-ager, not because she
had dreams of becoming a dancer but because she wanted to be an
actress and felt uncomfortable in her gangly body. ``I did not
think of dance as an art form when I was training,'' she said.
``Then I saw a performance of Simone Forti,'' the pioneering
postmodern choreographer of the late '60s and early '70s whose
dances were built from pedestrian movement. ``It was a revelation
to me. I was 21. It was like traveling into another dimension, like
taking drugs. I loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, Chouinard created ``Crystallization.'' Twelve
years later she formed her company, having choreographed more than
30 solos for herself in the interim. She supported herself by
teaching ballet classes.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are two Compagnie Marie Chouinards. The larger one,
a 12-person troupe, presented a new work, ``Le Cri du Monde,'' in
Toronto in March. The three women touring ``Les Solos'' have been
on the road nonstop since the fall of 1998. Last year, they gave
more than 50 performances.
</P>
<P>
   Why revive older work? ``I hope they are not old, it's just
work,'' said Chouinard, now the mother of a 2{-year-old son. ``It's
good to see it again, like revisiting a painting in a museum.
Besides, 20 years is not a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
