<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0825 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SINEAD-CUSACK-THEATER     04-18 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINEAD-CUSACK-THEATER-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVURA ROLES OF MOODS AND MEMORIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)   Matt Wolf is the London theater critic for Variety and a regular
writer on the arts from Europe.  
 By MATT WOLF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It would be an easy assumption to make, but a wrong
one, to think of Sinead Cusack as famous by association. In her
native Ireland, her surname evokes immediate associations to that
country's eminent acting clan. Not only was her father, Cyril, one
of the last century's best-known Irish performers, but having been
born into celebrity, Cusack proceeded to marry a man who became
one: Jeremy Irons, the film star.
</P>
<P>
   Cusack, however, has garnered an impressive share of acting
renown of her own. Last week she opened Off Broadway at the Irish
Repertory Theater in Sebastian Barry's ``Our Lady of Sligo,''
reprising a role that, at the Royal National Theater, won her a
Critics' Circle Award and an Evening Standard prize for best
actress in London in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Playing the angry, alcoholic, cancer-ridden Mai O'Hara _ a
portrait of Barry's own grandmother _ Cusack moves in and out of
bed, shifting moods (and years) at will, as she summons the
memories of her weak husband (played by Jarlath Conroy) and bitter
daughter (Melinda Page Hamilton).
</P>
<P>
   Describing the London production, John Peter wrote in The Sunday
Times that Cusack ``gives the most harrowing performance of her
career, the most expertly articulated, the gravest, the most
painfully hilarious, the most venomous and most deeply felt.''
</P>
<P>
   Cusack is succinct: ``It's a mountain, compared with a lot of
the little hillocks that I've climbed before,'' she said, although
she hasn't been exactly neglectful of the classical canon. She last
appeared on a New York stage in 1985 with the Royal Shakespeare
Company, playing in repertory as Roxane in ``Cyrano de Bergerac''
and Beatrice in ``Much Ado About Nothing.'' (Her co-star was Derek
Jacobi, who is making his own return to the New York stage this
season in ``Uncle Vanya'' on Broadway.)
</P>
<P>
   In London and Dublin in 1990, Cusack joined her father and two
of her sisters in an all-in-the-family production of Chekhov's
``Three Sisters.'' Two years later, she surpassed her own
performance as Masha, the middle Prozorov, when she revealed the
scarred soul at the core of Brian Friel's ``Faith Healer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She takes no prisoners,'' said Joe Dowling, the Irishman who
directed that ``Faith Healer'' at the Royal Court Theater, and who
has known Cusack since their student days at University College
Dublin. By that point, she had changed her first name from Jane to
its Gaelic equivalent, Sinead (pronounced shuh-NAY-ed).
</P>
<P>
   Carving out that career in the face of the fame her father had
and her husband has can't have been easy,'' Dowling said from the
Guthrie Theater in Minneapolis, where he is the artistic director.
``She has made her own life so individually from her own gift.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear Cusack, 52, describe it, the advancing years have been
kind to her in a profession that doesn't always know what to do
with actresses in middle age: ``The work I've done in the last
decade has been more challenging than I could have done before. I
went about my career probably the wrong way round, in that I
possibly should have done my theater work in my 20s and, instead,
was taken up with television and film and was very unskilled and
had no craft. In my 30s, I decided to right that wrong and started
working in classical theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Her stage career has co-existed with roles on the large and
small screens. She has her own leading part in ``My Mother Frank,''
an independent Australian movie scheduled for release later this
year, and many filmgoers reserve a particular soft spot for ``Bad
Behavior,'' the sweet-tempered 1993 British movie in which she and
Stephen Rea play gently embattled North Londoners.
</P>
<P>
   She has also played opposite her husband in ``Waterland'' (1992)
and ``Stealing Beauty'' (1996), among other ventures. The two were
young actors sharing a stage door in separate London productions
when they first met 26 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the defining role in ``Our Lady of Sligo'' that can be
said to draw on an actor's lifetime of experience and technique.
The play invites comparison with ``The Steward of Christendom,'' an
earlier work by Barry that, like this one, puts an ailing and
bedridden Barry forebear at centerstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Steward of Christendom'' visited the Brooklyn Academy of
Music to warm reviews several years ago, with the great Donal
McCann in the rending title role. But Max Stafford-Clark, the
English director of both Barry plays, pointed to a crucial
difference between the two that is well beyond the gender of their
central characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways,'' Stafford-Clark said, `` `Our Lady of Sligo' is
a more difficult play in that it is about someone to whom Sebastian
doesn't so easily extend grace and redemption. It trivializes it to
say that `Our Lady' is simply the distaff version of `Steward.'''
</P>
<P>
   Both plays do, however, allow for unmistakable bravura. ``I bob
about all over the place in my morphine-induced hysteria or
euphoria,'' Cusack said of the demands of the part. ``It's the
wonders of morphine, really. You can do anything you like on
morphine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
