<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HOUSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ROLLS OUT PLAN FOR AFFORDABLE HOMES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATTLE CREEK, Mich. _ Standing on the front porch of a modest
new house Tuesday, presidential candidate George W. Bush unveiled a
$1.7 billion plan to help more Americans afford their own homes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his proposal for special tax credits for builders and
lenders would not only help more people achieve ``the American
dream,'' but would improve entire neighborhoods and lead to better
schools.
</P>
<P>
   But the presumptive Republican nominee's compassionate pitch was
quickly criticized by housing advocates for the poor. They said his
plan would be more helpful to people with moderate incomes.
</P>
<P>
   And while Bush said his plan would build or fix up 100,000
houses over five years by giving investors tax credits of up to 50
percent of project costs, his critics called that a small attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to see this as a real low-income initiative,'' said
John Henneberger, co-director of the Texas Low-Income Housing
Information Service. ``It's more of a moderate-income initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines for Bush's plan call for families who earn up to
80 percent of area median income to be eligible. Henneberger and
other low-income housing advocates say the need is greatest among
those earning less than half the median income _ or $28,350 for a
family of four in the Houston area.
</P>
<P>
   Under Bush's plan, a Harris County family of four earning as
much as $45,360 would qualify.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Henneberger said Bush's program would be beneficial and should
be enacted, but ``we're still looking for a major low-income
housing initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   Most current federal and state programs help the poor pay for
rental housing or promote construction of apartment buildings, not
single-family homes.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor outlined his ``Renewing the Dream'' plan at
the new home of Oberrion Gibson, a 68-year-old grandmother who
earns less than $18,000 a year. The house was built with the
assistance of a nonprofit group that helps low-income families like
hers.
</P>
<P>
   With a 4.5 percent mortgage rate secured though a local
nonprofit group, Gibson recently moved into a new three-bedroom
home with her daughter and granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to be here,'' said the longtime resident of the Park
Hill neighborhood. Her previous, smaller home was torn down to make
room for the new dwelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a beautiful home, isn't it?'' Bush remarked.
</P>
<P>
   Although her home provided a suitable backdrop for Bush's
campaign appearance, Gibson wouldn't disclose her political
leanings nor commit to supporting Bush's GOP presidential bid. Even
so, Bush said it's people like Gibson he wants to help, ``not just
those who are entrepreneurs or who are at the top of the economic
ladder.``
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the American dream is to own your own home,'' Bush
said after a quick tour of the humble house and a moment of prayer
with its proud occupants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear this is a nest. It's part of her future as well as
her family's future. It's much easier to have that future when you
own something,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's proposal would extend the use of federal tax credits, now
limited to multi-family rental housing, to include single-family
homes for ownership. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Bush also has called for changes in the federal ``Section 8''
program that helps low-income renters. He said he wants to change
that program to turn renters into home buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Section 8 participant should be allowed to take his or her
stream of rental payments and convert that into a down payment and
mortgage payments,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he proposed giving banks a tax credit for matching a
person's savings if used for a home down payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community is strengthened when there is a sense of
ownership. It makes the schools better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Bush's optimism, a spokesman for Vice President Al Gore
said his Republican foe's promises ring hollow because of
persistent housing woes in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is yet another issue where Bush has done nothing in Texas
but expects us to believe he'll be a leader as president. His
housing authority is under investigation by the FBI, and his
housing rhetoric should get the same kind of scrutiny from
voters,'' said Gore spokesman Douglas Hattaway.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to federal and state investigations into the
Texas Department of Housing and Community Affairs regarding
questionable lending practices. Two officials targeted by the probe
were appointed by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Since he took office in January 1995, Bush said Texas home
ownership has increased from 59 percent to 63 percent, and in
1998-99, the state provided housing to 8,600 low-income people, a
200 percent increase over the previous two-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush's housing proposal was his message of the day, he
also got a political boost when the Michigan state coordinator for
his former rival, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., endorsed him. State
Sen. John Schwarz said Bush can't ignore the McCain message that
made him the biggest vote-getter in the Michigan primary, where
Bush finished second.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
