<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0827 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WORKPLACES-CHURCHES-A     04-18 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACES-CHURCHES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE WHO DO THEIR JOBS RELIGIOUSLY
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
By JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year, Our Lady Help of Christians, a Roman Catholic church
in Newton, Mass., was host to 155 baptisms, 110 funerals and more
weddings _ 96 _ than any other church in the Boston Archdiocese.
Add in the Masses, support-group sessions, prayer meetings and
school plays and scheduling becomes an administrative juggling act.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Mary Ellen Cocks, a pastoral associate who was sitting
at a 7:45 a.m. parish staff meeting recently, had reason for
distress when a colleague violated the sanctity of the schedule
book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not happy when I saw a 9 o'clock funeral written in
after we put in for a 9:30 rehearsal,'' she said sternly, sending
the hint of a glare across the conference-room table. Luckily, the
funeral reservation had been made for a contingency, not an actual
event, so she added, ``I'm just praying that nobody dies.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most of her colleagues at the table, Cocks is not ordained,
but she takes her job seriously. She is one of nine full-time,
nonclergy employees who run the business side of Our Lady's, as
parishioners call it.
</P>
<P>
   Churches are primarily houses of worship, of course, but they
are workplaces, too, and together they make up a pretty big
economic sector. The 352,000 full-time clergy in the United States,
for example, outnumber the nation's 266,000 psychologists and
310,000 bartenders. Add in all the lay people who work full-time or
part-time in churches, synagogues and mosques, from music directors
to secretaries and janitors, and the religious work force probably
surpasses a million.
</P>
<P>
   And to make all the religious events happen, they have to do
what people in any other businesses do: hold meetings, write
memorandums, resolve conflicts, plan budgets, meet deadlines, hire
and fire people and deal with grumpy bosses.
</P>
<P>
   As the early morning conference at Our Lady's shows, the
Catholic Church is responding to a worsening shortage of priests
and nuns by recruiting people from the secular world. More lay
people than seminarians are now seeking degrees in Catholic
ministry, said Scott Appleby, director of the Cushwa Center for the
Study of American Catholicism at the University of Notre Dame.
``It's very difficult to run a modern parish without a specialized
core of pastoral ministers,'' he said. ``Some will be business
managers and keep the books and worry about the physical plant.
Others will be specialists in religious education.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Walter Cuenin had two assistant priests when he came to
Our Lady's as pastor in 1993; now he has none. But his staff now
includes three pastoral associates; a business manager; an office
manager; a parish secretary; a principal to run the high school; a
director of religious education and another of youth ministry; two
custodians and a music director.
</P>
<P>
   In short, he never worries about whether there will be enough
processional candles. ``We're trying to model the way the church is
going to be, one priest with a whole group of lay people,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cuenin recruited Marie LaBollita, a nun, as a pastoral associate
six years ago, and a year later he enticed Cocks, who has 25 years
of experience in religious education, away from another parish.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Malloy, who became director of youth ministry five
years ago, said he knew from his first interview with Cuenin that
he could talk back, even when it came to church doctrine. ``You're
allowed to speak your mind,'' Malloy said. ``I don't see Walter or
Marie as different from the rest of us. That all fades away.''
</P>
<P>
   Like any good chief executive, Cuenin has learned how to
delegate authority. Cocks is in charge of the logistics for
baptisms and of liturgical planning, while LaBollita counsels
converts to Catholicism and ministers to the sick. Thomas Leahy,
the third pastoral associate, oversaw a four-year, $3 million
renovation of the 126-year-old church that was completed last year.
He points to a three-drawer file cabinet in his office that is
devoted solely to paperwork for the project.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining the church staff 16 years ago, Leahy worked as a
buyer for a department store chain until he became fed up with the
corporate bureaucracy. Now 70, he rarely complains about working
from 8 a.m. until 9:30 many nights. ``I've already had four
meetings this morning,'' he said as he took a break shortly after
10:30. ``But this is who I am, and this is my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuenin doesn't mind poring over the blueprints for the
redesigned parking lot or discussing whether there should be a
trumpeter at the 11:30 Mass. But with the little details taken care
of (``I don't have to be over there to make sure the microphones
are working,'' he said with satisfaction), he has focused on
increasing membership at the once-stagnant parish. To attract the
increasingly diverse parishioners, Masses are now said in Italian,
French and Spanish. (He speaks all three.) And in an ambitious
outreach program, the church has held 50 separate meetings with
small groups of parishioners since January.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts paid off. Close to 2,000 people attend one of the
four weekend Masses, a huge increase from four years ago that means
standing room only at some services.
</P>
<P>
   Collections are up sharply, enabling Our Lady's to absorb the
huge cost of hiring all that secular help. Unlike priests and nuns,
who take vows of celibacy and often live on church grounds, lay
workers have to worry about mortgage payments and their children's
college educations. ``It costs money, because you have to pay
people a living wage,'' Cuenin said. ``And I think a lot of
churches are not prepared for that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't just the extra expense that gives some churches pause;
it is also the threat to tradition. It is no secret around Our
Lady's that the pastoral associates would like to take on duties
that are now the domain of the priests, like performing the
sacraments.
</P>
<P>
   Cocks flipped through her Liturgical Desk Calendar at a recent
meeting, looking for a vacancy at the baptismal font. ``I'm totally
filled for April, for May and for the first week of June,'' she
said. ``I was at lunch 45 minutes and when I got back there were
four more requests for baptisms.''
</P>
<P>
   She gave Cuenin a meaningful look. Another task for him. ``I
hate to do it Walter,'' she said with just a touch of sarcasm,
``but until they tell me I can do baptisms. ... ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2126EDT &QL; 
