<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0314 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0829 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-POPULAR-CULTURE-FILMS     04-18 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPULAR-CULTURE-FILMS-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO OUR OTHER OBSESSIONS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What do we really talk about with our friends when we're not
discussing the vicissitudes of our personal lives? Why, popular
culture, of course! Much of the conversational glue that binds us
together comes from the stuff that wafts off television, movie and
computer screens, from our stereo speakers and headsets.
</P>
<P>
   It's an endless torrent of gossip and opinion filtered through
personal taste. The focus of conversation could be the Academy
Awards, a diva fest on VH1, a sports hero's latest feat, Oprah's
newest inspirational gambit, a Jerry Springer freak show or the
guys in 'N Sync.
</P>
<P>
   If we're honest with ourselves, these choices are crucial in
defining who we are. Like it or not, in a world ruled by television
chat and an increasingly interactive relationship with the media,
each of us is a walking market niche of opinions and choices ripe
for manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   But go to almost any Hollywood movie, and you'll find a strange
absence on screen of palaver about recordings, movies, television
shows and popular fiction. That's one reason that when a film comes
along that acknowledges the passions millions of us harbor about
favorite works of popular art, it can strike a deep chord of
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the best American movies released this year _ ``American
Psycho'' and ``High Fidelity'' _ show a bone-deep understanding of
how much of our emotional energy is invested in the consumption of
popular culture. Both movies recognize that to have a well-chosen
period pop soundtrack isn't enough anymore to lend a movie
credibility. A surefire bridge to identification with the
characters is to make them as opinionated about popular culture as
real people.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Psycho,'' a sleek, surreal horror-comedy set in the
late 1980s, wouldn't have the resonance it does without its
serial-killing protagonist's hilarious double-edged speeches about
the '80s hitmakers Phil Collins, Whitney Houston and, especially,
Huey Lewis and the News. Because his fulsome lectures on these
middle-of-the-road phenomena are preludes to murder, their music
and iconic status are profoundly implicated in the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Discoursing on Lewis and his group's recording career, the
movie's homicidal yuppie, Patrick Bateman, offers the sort of slick
assessment you might read in a pop record consumer guide. ``Their
early work was a little too New Wave for my taste,'' he sniffs
while getting ready to whack one of his Wall Street cronies. ``But
when `Sports' came out in 1983, I think they really came into their
own, commercially and artistically. The whole album has a clear,
crisp sound and a new sheen of consummate professionalism that
gives the songs a big boost.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick's lecture culminates in a gruesome ax murder during
which ``Hip to Be Square,'' a song he has just proclaimed the
group's ``undisputed masterpiece,'' becomes a heavily ironic theme.
Christian Bale's supercilious delivery subtly mocks a debased,
grandiose vocabulary of contemporary pop criticism (of movies and
television as well as music) that tosses around words like
``masterpiece'' as though they were penny stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Another implied joke is the ludicrous notion that a
squeaky-clean pop anthem like ``Hip to Be Square'' could incite
murder. The 1980s were the decade, if you recall, when the
Christian Right frothed at the mouth about the supposed
relationship between heavy-metal rock and satanic cults. The
paranoia became so acute that some records were played backward to
determine if they contained the cryptic ``backward masking'' of
Satanic messages.
</P>
<P>
   Pop music fanaticism is also the subject of ``High Fidelity,''
Stephen Frears' wonderful screen translation of Nick Hornby's
best-selling 1995 novel about the problematic love life of Rob
Gordon (John Cusack), a London record store manager.
</P>
<P>
   The relocation of the novel from London to Chicago without a
serious loss of credibility only illustrates the pervasiveness of
the pop fanaticism the movie describes. Anyone who grew up
devouring the pop charts can identify with the way Rob sees
everything in his life, including failed love affairs, as fodder
for top-five lists.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond Rob's mania for rankings, what makes the character so
sympathetic is the way Rob's personal hit parades become the
imaginary soundtrack to his fantasy life, lending his day-to-day
existence a secret rock 'n' roll grandeur. If his pop passions are
more extreme than most people's, it's only by a matter of degree.
</P>
<P>
   For many of us who grew up with rock, our personal musical
tastes weren't casual consumer choices but assertions of identity.
How many of us, like Rob and his record-store cronies, judge other
people based on their tastes in movies, music and celebrities?
</P>
<P>
   But until recently, it's amazing how few movie directors have
acknowledged the degree to which people talk about such things.
Martin Scorsese is one who knows, and Woody Allen (with his 1940s-
and '50s-schooled high cultural tastes) another. But it wasn't
until Quentin Tarantino laid his cards on the table in ``Reservoir
Dogs,'' with its brilliant, crazy riff on Madonna, and ``Pulp
Fiction,'' with its nightclub of celebrity impersonators, that the
walls began to crumble.
</P>
<P>
   So why has Hollywood not really gotten the message? One reason
may be competition between movies and other popular art forms.
Filmmakers cringe reflexively at crediting any other form with
matching film's emotional clout. Another reason may be the short
shelf-life of pop culture.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hollywood still likes to imagine its dream world as larger
than television's ``reality'' and deeper than pop music's
trendiness. But as the forms of entertainment meld into a giant
blob of interactive, interdependent everything, such thinking seems
increasingly delusional.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
