<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0831 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BOOTY-SONGS-$ADV23-NY     04-18 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOTY-SONGS-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LATEST SOUNDTRACK TO SPRING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Please note subslug for SEXY-SPRING-SONGS)  
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you were locked in an underground cave, with no sunlight,
clock or DSL lines, and the sole contact you had with the outside
world was a radio that could receive only Casey Kasem's ``American
Top 40'' countdown, how would you know what time of year it was?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is anatomical. As the seasons change, so too do the
fortunes of the booty song _ that fast-jiggling, salacious ode to
the gluteus maximus _ on the pop charts. In the winter, ``Thong
Song,'' a celebration of glimpses of scanty female underwear by
Sisqo of the rhythm-and-blues group Dru Hill, was bubbling well
under the Top 40.
</P>
<P>
   But by last week, with spring love in the air and spring break
on the beach, it was up at No. 5 and still climbing. Its
infectiously inane catch phrase, ``Let me see that
thong-tha-thong-thong-thong,'' has slowly become ubiquitous in
clubs, on the radio, on MTV and blasting out of cars, replacing
last year's bouncing booty hook extraordinaire, ``Back That Thang
Up'' by the New Orleans rapper Juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   In the pop charts, summer is generally the time of the light,
frothy single _ fun, catchy and laid back like ``Steal My
Sunshine'' by Len or ``Summer Girls'' by LFO. Fall is when the
superstars come out to play, setting up their albums for Christmas
shopping season with slick blockbuster hits. Winter is when record
companies bring their new bands out of the workshop, hoping that
with superstar season over, there is less to stand in the way of a
fresh face becoming the next big thing. And spring is booty time, a
soundtrack to the streets, in which pale wintry flesh is first
being exposed to direct sunlight, turning a young person's idle
thoughts to fancy.
</P>
<P>
   Soundtracks to spring lust are nothing new, of course. The booty
historian could trace the genre back to medieval maypole dances or,
in modernist times, Stravinsky's ``Rite of Spring.'' The latter not
only depicts the primitive fertility rituals at the root of today's
spring singles but also uses music more dependent on rhythm than
melody, with the fast-driving string ostinatos and emphatic
percussive downbeats that are at the core of Sisqo's ``Thong
Song.''
</P>
<P>
   With more recent origins in styles that have flowered in warm,
beach climates _ specifically, Jamaican dancehall and Miami bass _
modern booty music has been an incredibly inventive genre. Every
year, singers come up with new ways to say the exact same thing. In
the spring of '92, Sir Mix-a-Lot's ``Baby Got Back'' began moving
up the pop charts, chased later by Duice's ode to short shorts,
``Dazzey Duks.''
</P>
<P>
   And who could forget the great booty battle of spring '93, when
two nearly identical booty songs went to war for pop dominance: Tag
Team's ``Whoomp! (There It Is)'' and 95 South's ``Whoot, There It
Is.'' Since then, the charts have been filled with everything from
the 69 Boyz's ``Tootsee Roll'' to Hammer's ``Pumps and a Bump'' to
Freak Nasty's ``Da Dip.''
</P>
<P>
   It is strange that in a culture in which men disembody women in
any variety of ways _ fetishizing legs, breasts, backsides, even
hair color _ only one anatomical part has consistently dominated
the pop charts. Sir Mix-a-Lot's mammary catcall, ``Put 'Em on the
Glass'' experienced nothing near the success of his ode to babies
with back.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, though there are exceptions, there is no
consistently successful genre of female song objectifying the male
body _ despite the wealth of material to be found in protruding
pectoral muscles, six-pack abdomens, soccer-player legs, tight
backsides and the bulge in the pants known as the package.
</P>
<P>
   The pop-chart equivalent for female singers is the ode to the
bulges in men's pockets. This spring, as shallow men have been
booty-watching, single-minded women have been gold-digging.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the year's best singles are about this: Destiny's Child's
``Bills, Bills, Bills,'' in which suitors are asked to pay an
itemized list of the group's bills, and Missy (Misdemeanor)
Elliott's ``Hot Boyz,'' in which she announces the availability of
herself and her friends to men with ``the platinum Visas'' and
``the Benz jeeps and the Lincoln jeeps, nothing cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   As traditional as the booty song, this popular obsession (still
in part a male fantasy because the lyrics were often written by
men) stretches from Massenet's ``Manon'' to Marilyn Monroe's
``Diamonds Are a Girl's Best Friend'' to Madonna's ``Material
Girl,'' a spring single itself.
</P>
<P>
   In a contrived attempt to bridge the gender gap, Sisqo begins
``Thong Song'' with a short spoken introduction that posits the
song as a public service announcement for women, teaching them what
men really think about (as if they didn't know). From there, the
song mimics half a dozen current trends in urban music, including
the mock-classical string samples that Dr. Dre has used to engineer
his comeback, the rhythmic stutter of a Roland drum machine
shaker-sound preferred by Swizz Beats and Timbaland and the
nonsense chants used for counterpoint in recent hits by JT Money
and Jah Rule.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Thong Song'' these devices lack the clarity, immediacy and
sharpness of impeccable producers like Dr. Dre and Timbaland, but
they work, which is all that matters in the realm of a spring hit.
</P>
<P>
   By definition, the booty song is rarely innovative (its use of
synonyms, metaphor and slang notwithstanding): it reinforces the
status quo. The few lyrics of ``Thong Song'' seem hastily written,
quoting Ricky Martin's ``Livin' la Vida Loca.'' The only line that
doesn't rhyme in the song's verse, the reference to Martin, is
another shortcut to increase the song's easy familiarity. The line
before it sells the song to a general audience: ``Not just urban,
she likes her pop.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of ``Thong Song'' goes something like this: ``She had
dumps like a truck-truck, truck/Thighs like what-what what.'' Then
Sisqo begs, ``Let me sing it again.'' And we let him sing it again,
over and over, everywhere we go. In fact, it seems like Sisqo has
no intention of ever stopping. He plans to release a new mix of
``Thong Song'' in July with a naughty rap from Foxy Brown and a
video that promises even more thongs, cranking up the heat on a
spring song to turn it into a summer anthem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
