<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0833 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-VARESE-MESSIAEN-MUSIC     04-18 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VARESE-MESSIAEN-MUSIC-ART-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITES WITH MUCH IN COMMON  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edgard Varese and Olivier Messiaen were born 25 years apart, in
1883 and 1908, but many accidents brought them together. Since
Varese started out late on his public career and Messiaen early,
they both made their beginnings as composers in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   They both spent formative years in southern France, both studied
in Paris and were both indelibly influenced by the music they heard
there, especially Debussy's orchestral works and the early ballets
of Stravinsky. Both were drawn to distant cultures, ancient and
exotic. Both loved the sounds of wind instruments and percussion.
</P>
<P>
   So it is altogether a happy circumstance that brings them
together next weekend at Carnegie Hall. On Friday evening Christoph
von Dohnanyi and the Cleveland Orchestra will present Varese's
``Ameriques,'' and on Saturday evening Seiji Ozawa and the Boston
Symphony will offer Messiaen's ``Turangalila Symphony,'' with the
excellent Pierre-Laurent Aimard in the important part for solo
piano.
</P>
<P>
   There is also an American connection between these works. Varese
began ``Ameriques'' shortly after he had settled in New York, in
1915, and Messiaen wrote ``Turangalila'' for Ozawa's orchestra
(which was then, in the late 40's, Serge Koussevitzky's, though the
first performance was conducted by Leonard Bernstein).
</P>
<P>
   Varese was an eager immigrant. Coming to the United States was,
for him, coming to the future, and no sooner was he off the boat
than he was giving interviews about the new electronic music he was
going to compose. Because technology still lagged behind
imagination, that had to wait.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Ameriques,'' scored for an enormous orchestra, pushes at
the limits of what instruments can produce in terms of intensity
and pitch, as if violins and oboes were striving to become electric
oscillators. It's a powerful and exciting score, and it offers a
portrait not only of the real America seen and heard by a newcomer
_ noise and speed on the streets, sirens and alarms _ but also of
Americas of the mind, journeys of discovery.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the work was completed, in 1921, Varese was living
on Sullivan Street in Manhattan, where he remained until his death,
more than 40 years later, apart from a return visit to Paris for
four years at the end of the '20s. During that time back in Paris
he could have come across Messiaen and his music, and though there
is no record of a direct encounter, the two composers were
certainly moving in the same circles.
</P>
<P>
   Both were impressed by the flamboyant color of the music
produced by another visitor from the Americas, Heitor Villa-Lobos,
and both were intrigued by a new invention: the electronic
instrument designed by Maurice Martenot and known as the ondes
martenot.
</P>
<P>
   Varese used its piercing high frequencies in his ``Ecuatorial,''
a Mayan chant he set for bass and orchestra in the early 1930s.
Messiaen used the ondes martenot in several scores, including
``Turangalila,'' where its unearthly sounds add sweetness, glow and
a voicelike quality to melodies from the violins, or combine with
the piano and tuned percussion to create an Indonesian-style
ensemble of chimes and resonances within the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Though Messiaen lived all his life in France, he had a fondness
for the United States, came here often and, after ``Turangalila,''
wrote several more works for American places and performers:
``Meditations sur la Mystere de la Sainte Trinite'' for organ,
``Des Canyons aux Etoiles'' for piano and orchestra, and ``Eclairs
sur l'Au-Dela'' for orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as all these works loudly declared, what he liked about
America was not the street animation and sleek machinery that so
appealed to Varese but rather the visual splendor of the canyons
and deserts and the sounds to be heard there: wind and birdcalls.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0834 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-VARESE-MESSIAEN-MUSIC     04-18 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VARESE-MESSIAEN-MUSIC-ART-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: and birdcalls.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Turangalila,'' which he completed in 1948, before his first
journey across the Atlantic, as yet contains no knowledge of these
things, but its scenery is already _ and characteristically _
spacious and unspoiled. One movement evokes the wonder of the
heavens, another a garden in which two lovers are in each other's
arms, the whole 10-movement symphony being a gigantic love song.
</P>
<P>
   The city, where it appears in his music, is always the heavenly
Jerusalem. Not only was Messiaen a composer of the countryside _
traveling the world in pursuit of bird songs, which he would put
into the music he wrote, in the main, at his summer home beside a
lake at the foot of the French Alps _ but he was also expressly a
religious composer, whereas Varese, the urban artist, was an
atheist.
</P>
<P>
   So often, though, opposites will meet. The Christian and the
nonbeliever both felt the power of archaic sacredness: Varese wrote
music for the Mayas, and Messiaen composed a monumental threnody
for wind instruments, bells and gongs with images of colossal
Mediterranean and Mesoamerican temples stuck around his desk.
</P>
<P>
   Varese's last major concert piece, ``Deserts'' of 1954, was,
like part of Messiaen's ``Des Canyons aux Etoiles,'' an image of
the desert and of an emptiness that was as much spiritual as
physical. And two pieces written at almost the same time _
Messiaen's ``Sept Haikai'' of 1962 and the ``Nocturnal,'' on which
Varese was working in his last years _ both use violins to imitate
the mouth organ of Japanese court music.
</P>
<P>
   The two composers could evoke ancient civilizations partly
because their musical means were extensive but also because, fired
by Stravinsky's ``Sacre du Printemps,'' they had broken decisively
with the European classical-music culture from which they had come.
Pulse and a manifest rhythmic energy came to steer their music.
Continuity had to take place through abrupt cuts. Musical ideas
would have to be clear and self-sufficient, like signals: hence the
preference for wind and percussion sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, both ``Ameriques'' and ``Turangalila'' were written by
composers in their middle to late 30s, enjoying the flush of early
maturity. However much they may differ in their means, style and
subject matter, they stand side by side in their bounding
confidence and optimism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
