<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0840 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-VIETNAM-PHOTOGRAPHERS     04-18 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-PHOTOGRAPHERS-ABRIDGED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAM TODAY: FORGOTTEN IMAGES REVEAL THE WAR FROM THE COMMUNIST
SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This is a shortened version of BC-VIETNAM-PHOTOGRAPHERS-NYT,
which moved tonight; April 30 marks 25 years since the fall of
Saigon, and this is the second of several articles on Vietnam and
the war's legacy, there and in the United States. A special section
is available on The New York Times.Learning.Network:
www.nytimes.com/learning/saigon) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOI, Vietnam _ Bundled in two sweaters and a coat in his
chilly, tiny apartment, an old photographer described in sharp
detail his most cherished image of the war _ a young woman, bent
under her burden of supplies, laboring up a steep rock face on the
Ho Chi Minh trail.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody _ not even the photographer, Dinh Dang Dinh _ has ever
seen that picture. After three months on the trail in 1974, all his
film, 80 rolls of it, was destroyed in an attack by a U.S. F-4
Phantom jet.
</P>
<P>
   Streamers of exposed film fluttered from a treetop, said Dinh,
who is now 80. His first impulse was to photograph the destruction,
but that is another image that remains only in his memory. All his
cameras were destroyed in the attack as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't sleep for a month, it was so awful,'' he said.
``Sometimes I still can't sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Many thousands of other photographs do survive from a corps of
photographers who recorded the war on the communist side, both in
North and South Vietnam. But these pictures are as little known
outside Vietnam as the long-gone work of Dinh.
</P>
<P>
   Now, decades later, a selection of those photographs is being
gathered by two U.S. researchers who have dug through government
archives and tracked down a dozen of the aged photographers who
risked their lives to take them.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years after the fighting ended, something surprising
is emerging: a new visual record of the war whose images had once
seemed so familiar.
</P>
<P>
   They are pictures of battle and of daily life from the other
side _ of barefoot guerrillas attacking a tank, of an outdoor
operating theater in a swamp, of children studying in a bomb
shelter, of a young soldier smiling brilliantly at the camera
moments before he was killed in a bombing raid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've printed hundreds of these from the original negatives,''
said one of the researchers, Doug Niven, who is preparing a book
along with his associate, Chris Riley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys would just bring us plastic bags full of negatives,
and we'd just hold them up to a loop and go through them,'' Niven
said. ``Some of them are as good as the most famous photographers
on the Western side. But they've been in the shadows for 25
years.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent interviews in Hanoi and in Ho Chi Minh City, formerly
Saigon, seven of the photographers recalled their work and what
they said were the most intense and rewarding years of their lives.
They photographed the war, they said, with the same nationalist
fervor as their comrades, the soldiers. They include:
</P>
<P>
   Doan Cong Tinh, 57, a tough combat photographer who spent more
than two years living under fire in Quang Tri, capturing some of
the most dramatic battlefield pictures from the northern side. He
said he had carried a firearm as well as his camera and used both
of them.
</P>
<P>
   Le Minh Truong, 70, who took up photography after he was wounded
fighting the French in the 1950s, then discovered beauty everywhere
he looked, in the flare of napalm or the contrails of U.S.
warplanes in the rubble of Hanoi or the silhouettes of jungle
fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Mai Nam, 69, whose picture of a U.S. bomber tumbling through the
sky, a parachute floating nearby, was reproduced as a postcard by
the government with the caption, ``Happy New Year 1967.'' When
peace came, he became a pioneer in photographing beauty pageants in
communist Vietnam, and his walls are now adorned by pictures, not
of war, but of beautiful women.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen Dinh Uu, 82, who took his first pictures in 1948 when he
helped capture a unit of French soldiers and then turned their own
camera on them. ``Oh, I was so happy,'' he said, recalling the day
he first held a camera in his hands. ``We were more alive in
wartime, working in the border between life and death.''
</P>
<P>
   Lam Tan Tai, 65, a master of battlefield photo-processing, who
carried his chemicals with him, built little earthen darkrooms and
hung his negatives on the bushes to dry.
</P>
<P>
   And Duong Thanh Phong, 61, who spent the war documenting life in
the hidden tunnels of Cu Chi, just south of Saigon. Then, in the
greatest thrill of his life, he photographed the final day of the
war, April 30, 1975, as victorious guerrillas and their supporters
surged toward the South's capital with flags and guns and laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Those pictures of victory are a revealing counterpart to the
familiar scenes of terrified Vietnamese in Saigon fighting their
way onto evacuation helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Today, most of these photographers are little known even in
their own country. Much of their wartime work has been uncollected
and unused since its original publication decades ago in Vietnamese
and some foreign communist newspapers. Some has never been
published, and some of the photographers have little left besides
the negatives they put aside for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has always been my dream to exhibit my pictures,'' Tinh
said. ``But as you know, the years after the war were very
difficult here and nobody had the money for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is also because the government _ like the
photographers themselves _ viewed their work as part of the war
effort, a project that could be forgotten now that it had served
its purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The photographers acknowledged with pride that their pictures
were deliberately one-sided, that they were fighting as hard with
their cameras as the soldiers were with their guns.
</P>
<P>
   And for the most part, their wartime propaganda _ often stunning
to look at _ is as genuinely descriptive of the conflict as were
some of the great U.S. pictures of battlefield horror or anti-war
protests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
