<HEADER>
A0845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      04-18 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earnings Top Forecasts at EMC, Intel and IBM
</P>
<P>
   Three of the technology blue chips _ Intel, EMC and IBM _
reported earnings that exceeded Wall Street's expectations. The
laggard of the three was IBM, whose earnings rose but whose revenue
declined 5 percent. But both EMC and Intel reported strong advances
in revenue as well as quarterly profits. They join other leading
technology companies that are benefiting from the increased
investment in technology as corporations retool their operations
for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   AOL Has Record Revenue and Profit
</P>
<P>
   America Online reported record revenue and earnings in its third
quarter, crediting subscription growth, advertising sales and
online commerce fees as it handily beat analysts' estimates. Before
it announced its results, shares of America Online closed up
$2.0625, to $60.50, but they remain down sharply from their 52-week
high of $95.8125.
</P>
<P>
   One Margin Call Hits $45 Million
</P>
<P>
   Baruch Israel Hertz's company promises to make investing a
cinch, even for novices. But when stocks plunged on Friday, many
investors who had borrowed heavily to play the market had to put up
more money to cover their losses. And one of the biggest losers was
Hertz, who owes $45 million to four brokerage firms. To meet the
margin call, he pledged 25 million shares of his own company's
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Coke Reports a $58 Million Loss
</P>
<P>
   A day before Coca-Cola holds its annual meeting with
shareholders in Wilmington, Del., which is expected to include
protests by black employees, the company said that it lost $58
million in the first quarter, much of that because of charges for
reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   California Employees Sue SBC
</P>
<P>
   California employees of SBC Communications sued the company,
accusing it of costing the employees $1.1 billion by selling shares
of AirTouch Communications that were in their retirement accounts
after a series of mergers made AirTouch an SBC competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Housing Starts Fell 11.2 Percent in March
</P>
<P>
   Housing starts plunged 11.2 percent in March, the largest
monthly drop in six years, but the decline was attributed entirely
to a slowdown in construction of apartments and other multifamily
housing.
</P>
<P>
   FDA Approves New Antibiotic
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration approved a drug that is
considered an important new weapon in the fight against
antibiotic-resistant germs. The drug, Zyvox, made by Pharmacia, is
the first in a new family of antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the Personalities He Has Seen
</P>
<P>
   Being blind didn't stop Herbert M. Greenberg from founding and
making a success of a human resources consulting firm, Caliper
Management in Princeton, N.J. In fact, the psychological test he
helped develop is said to be particularly suited for placing people
in specific jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Shakeup at British Nuclear Company
</P>
<P>
   Reeling from a series of debacles over its safety and
management, British Nuclear Fuels, the government-owned giant of
Britain's nuclear industry, announced a management shakeup and
pledged ``a comprehensive overhaul'' of safety procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Laidlaw Suspends Stock Dividend
</P>
<P>
   Laidlaw, the Canadian company that runs Greyhound Lines and
North America's largest fleet of school buses, suspended dividend
payments on its common stock and won some temporary relief from
bankers who are renegotiating a long-term loan agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
