<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0858 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-RAUTAVAARA-MUSIC-2TAK     04-18 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAUTAVAARA-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A JOURNEY BEGUN IN OPERA CONTINUES IN SYMPHONY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   Matthew Gurewitsch writes about the arts for The Wall Street
Journal and other publications.  
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Helsinki, Finland _ The crooked side road, the whispering pines,
the flagstone path: I have passed this way before. Snow was hanging
heavy on the branches then. Today, the first fragrant lilacs shiver
in icy breezes that slice like a knife.
</P>
<P>
   The Finnish composer Einojuhani Rautavaara, 71, stands framed in
the doorway, looking nothing like the solitary misanthrope of
legend, an icon of contentment: slightly stooped but tall, thick
dark hair mixed with gray, deep-set eyes sparkling in welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the first thing he shows me is his guest book, open to
the page I signed a dozen years ago, when I came by to hear about
``Thomas,'' his opera on a medieval Finnish bishop and firebrand.
Again, a pen lies ready. Our topic this time is his Symphony No. 8,
subtitled ``The Journey.''
</P>
<P>
   A centennial commission of the Philadelphia Orchestra, it
receives its premiere, conducted by Wolfgang Sawallisch, in
concerts beginning on Thursday at the orchestra's home, the Academy
of Music, with a repeat at Carnegie Hall on May 1.
</P>
<P>
   ```The Journey' isn't just a fancy title,'' Rautavaara says.
``The symphony uses material from a monologue in `Thomas.' The text
there goes: `This journey goes on, it never ends. It will never
end, never.''' (The words, as usual in Rautavaara's operas, are his
own.) ``I had to use that motif again, to write variations on it.''
</P>
<P>
   A Proustian procedure? ``This method has been with me from the
beginning. It's not that the material is so beautiful as such. I
don't quote a la Berlioz or Strauss. It's an organic phenomenon.
Something that was 19 measures in a choral piece turns into 40 or
50 measures in a violin concerto two years later. No one ever
notices. There are people you see every day _ they sell you bread
or cut your hair _ and on the street you don't recognize them.
Maybe they seem vaguely familiar.''
</P>
<P>
   Rautavaara's fluent, often jazzy English harks back to a spell a
half century ago at the Tanglewood Festival in Massachusetts, and
in New York, where he shared a room on 110th Street with a Puerto
Rican woman who taught him to trample ``las cucarachas''
flamenco-style. His American period came about thanks to Jean
Sibelius, whose 90th birthday the Koussevitzky Music Foundation had
decided to observe with a study grant to an aspiring composer of
the old man's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Rautavaara's first meeting with the glowering titan still lay in
the future. ``No one saw him,'' Rautavaara says. ``He was a mythic
monster.'' Yet in his solitude, Sibelius had got wind of
Rautavaara's ``Requiem in Our Time,'' which had won an
international prize in Cincinnati. Characteristically, that piece
had recycled a motif from a distinctly less successful effort, and
Rautavaara can still quote with relish the words of a forgotten
critic who deemed the earlier work a disaster: ``The young man has
to climb the tree from the top down.''
</P>
<P>
   The telegram announcing Rautavaara's unexpected turn of fortune
hangs upstairs, framed, in his study. It reached him at a run-down
palace in Vienna, where he and five Mexican pianists were renting
rooms from decayed nobility. In due course, he set sail for the new
world.
</P>
<P>
   His recollections of Aaron Copland, Vincent Persichetti and
Roger Sessions are affectionate and musically revealing. Copland
shocked him by referring to Schoenberg and Webern as ``the enemy.''
The youthful Rautavaara, later to study among the iconoclasts of
Cologne, was hungry for styles of all kinds. Before learning about
Messiaen's symmetrical scales from Persichetti, he had, on his own,
organized a piece around a theme that matched one of Messiaen's
scales precisely.
</P>
<P>
   That would have been in his ``young soldier'' or avant-garde
phase, preceding the phases of patriarch (upholder of values) and
recluse (or mystic): a threefold Brahminic template Rautavaara has
said he hoped to follow. Perhaps he has, though scarcely in a neat
sequence.
</P>
<P>
   In the composer's life and art, the past seems ever present. The
cult favorite ``Cantus Arcticus'' (recently performed in a Finnish
program by the Brooklyn Philharmonic) incorporates his own
laboriously assembled tapes of bird songs he heard in Lapland as a
child. His ``Sonette an Orpheus'' (Op. 9), an early cycle of Rilke
settings, is open on the piano.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vigilia,'' his majestic, richly varied all-night vigil ``in
memory of St. John the Baptist,'' composed in the early 1970s, is
woven from reminiscences of a boyhood visit to the island monastery
of Valamo in 1939, shortly before the death of his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the last chance to see it, because that year the winter
war broke out, and we lost that part of Finland to the Russians,''
Rautavaara says. ``Looking from the prow of the boat in the early
morning, I was rather bored, seeing only fog. Then the wind sprang
up, and suddenly I could see the towers, all red and gold, and the
bells started to ring, hundreds of bells of all sizes. I'd never
seen anything like the icons with the saints. My family was very
Lutheran, very ascetic. We stayed overnight. As I fell asleep, I
heard the monks' robes sweeping the floor. It all stayed in my
mind. The subconscious is the best friend a composer has.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Rautavaara's music has been recorded on nearly 100 CDs, mostly
on the Finnish label Ondine. Many of his titles have a
transcendental aura, prompting at least one recent reviewer to
suspect the Finnish composer of ``climbing on the celestial
bandwagon'' alongside the likes of Arvo Part, John Tavener and
Henryk Gorecki. In fact, his sensibility _ even in ``Vigilia,'' so
self-evidently inspired by the music of the Eastern Orthodox Church
_ is quite distinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Part's music very much,'' Rautavaara says, going on to
pinpoint the difference. ``But his attitude is Oriental, monotonic.
I'm very much a European, Faustian. Extremes and contrasts are
important to me. European culture is built on polarity, which
creates great energy. That is why Western culture is still strong
and alive after 2,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understood this when I was in Rome for the first time and
saw the Moses of Michelangelo. I saw the statue as a symbol of
European culture, built from two cultures in complete contrast. One
source is Greek philosophy: very rational, very clear. The other is
the monotheism of the hallucinating Hebraic prophets. Writing
`Vigilia,' I asked myself: how can I write hours of music so people
don't die of boredom? Part would probably ask the opposite: how do
I make the music last forever?''
</P>
<P>
   A book by Kalevi Aho discusses Rautavaara's symphonies in the
Hegelian terms of thesis (Symphony No. 1), antithesis (No. 2) and
synthesis (No. 3), with the serial Fourth forming a fresh contrast
to the Third, and the Fifth a synthesis of the Third and the
Fourth. Does the composer accept that model? ``You can see it that
way,'' he allows.
</P>
<P>
   Rautavaara's conversation, so rational and cheerful, seems hard
to square with the chaotic, demonic strain so powerful in much of
his music. Where, I wonder, is the connection to the tormented
heroes of his major operas, Vincent van Gogh among them?
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting rid of a milieu that is not good for you, as Vincent
did, is very familiar to me,'' he replies. ``Once it was very
important to me to have gadgets, cars, villas as all Finns have,
dogs, a motorboat, a family, children: all very normal and comme il
faut, and all completely foreign from what I wanted to achieve. I
had to get rid of them, and I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Rid of his children?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have children from a previous marriage that was a hell of 20
years,'' he says. ``There are two boys. They're grown up and on
their own. I have nothing to do with them. Children are beautiful
at a distance of 10 meters, not to live with. Now I have an ideal
marriage. My second wife and I are children to each other.
Interviews are fun and nice but not important. If I had to choose
between being famous and having my music played all over the world,
or to go and write my music, I would choose the latter. My wife
will tell you: I write on Christmas Eve. This is the common thread
with the heroes of my operas.''
</P>
<P>
   He seems at peace, snuggled in a sweater, yet the room feels
frozen, full of ghosts. His father, dead before the winter war. His
mother, a physician called to the army, dead of exhaustion before
peace returned. A clutch of aunts who took him in and sent him
along, an orphan at 13. The aunt, another physician, who at length
adopted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 17 years old, I read what Richard Strauss said,
that even in the war, he could still create small, private
universes of beauty,'' Rautavaara recalls. ``That was good enough
for me. In music, I found a private world where I was master. I
knew nothing. I went to a friend of my father's who taught theory
and asked him for lessons.'' Still a novice, he soon wound up at
the Sibelius Academy here, Finland's top conservatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some great pianists there, and I was a beginner,''
he says. ``People would look at me and say, `He's supposed to be a
composer, and he can't even play the piano.' It gave me complexes,
which are very important for any composer. They force you to
compensate. I say to friends with children: `Don't forget to give
them complexes. They need them.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
