<HEADER>
A0860 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-LISA-KRUEGER-FILMS-AR     04-18 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LISA-KRUEGER-FILMS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BERKELEY BRAT, SEEKING STRUCTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Mo.)   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent as NYT28 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 23)  
 Margy Rochlin's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about
the actress Catherine Keener.  
 By MARGY ROCHLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When the writer and director Lisa Krueger was 19,
she fled to Paris and lived there for five years. What was she
escaping? Freedom. Namely, the kind engendered by being raised in
Berkeley, Calif., a university town famous for its love of radical
politics, social experimentation and A-to-Z religions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was soothed and relieved to live amongst such rational
people,'' said Krueger, who found the rigidity of French culture
the perfect antidote to America's prizing of individuality. ``Here,
anything is possible, you can completely invent yourself, be
whoever you want. But as a result, there's no anchor, no roots.
It's like your identity is up for grabs.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Krueger, 39, has made only two movies, but the longing
for structure is a central theme in both. Indeed, some of the most
touching moments in her 1996 indie debut ``Manny and Lo'' involve
watching how the lives of two underage orphan runaways (Scarlett
Johannsen and Aleska Palladino) are enriched when they kidnap a
discipline-driven woman (Mary Kay Place) and the three become a
makeshift family.
</P>
<P>
   As for Joline (Heather Graham), the nightclub manager heroine of
Krueger's latest film, ``Committed'' (opening Friday), she finds
comfort in structure, too. But her quest _ to save an unraveling
marriage by hunting down her wayward photojournalist husband, Carl
(Luke Wilson) _ comes at the expense of her happiness and,
eventually, her own sanity.
</P>
<P>
   During Joline's journey, which takes her from New York to a
particularly barren, sandswept corner of El Paso, Texas on the
border of Texas and Mexico, she relies on a battery of New Age
tracking devices that seem a mixture of spiritual intuition and
delirious improvisation. Once her stakeout is set up in El Paso,
her good-natured sense of purpose draws unlikely fans and
well-wishers, including her husband's new girlfriend (Patricia
Velasquez).
</P>
<P>
   In this way, ``Committed'' is a tale of post-feminist romance,
an almost anti-``First Wives Club,'' in which a jettisoned woman
does not feel victimized or vengeful, merely emboldened to save her
confused spouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know `it's better to give than receive' is one of the oldest
notions in the world,'' she said. ``But I feel like we've relegated
that idea to the furthest back burner. We're very intent on getting
what we deserve, getting what's ours. I see the pendulum swinging
the other way. Because this endless getting, getting, getting is an
empty goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding a leading lady who had comic timing and a flighty
charisma and could keep the audience invested in her fanciful
mission turned out to be one of Krueger's trickiest tasks. She
estimated that she admired, but had to write off, 90 percent of the
actresses she considered because they did not seem to have what the
role required.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at somebody like Ashley Judd, you can always see the
wheels turning,'' Krueger said. ``Blind faith is a hard thing to
pull off. I needed someone who would not think, just do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wide-eyed Heather Graham, Krueger found herself the
perfect protagonist. Winningly optimistic and driven almost
entirely by intuition, there is something wholly believable about
Graham's Joline, particularly as she incessantly practices her
mystical rituals, some of which Graham invented under Krueger's
watchful guidance.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd say, `Do some stuff with your hands,''' Graham said.
``And I'd, like, move my hands in a circle twice, then make a
square. Then she'd say: `No, I don't like that. Try patting twice.'
I'd try again. Then she'd go: `OK! Good!'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Incredibly approachable, supportive, a warm, loving person,
but at the same time tough, really demanding,'' is how Graham
categorized Krueger's style as a writer-director. And Graham knows
from writer-directors. In fact, she cavorted openly on the set with
one, her boyfriend, the filmmaker Ed Burns (``The Brothers
McMullen''), often blowing kisses to him and mouthing the words ``I
love you'' right before the cameras were to roll. The possibility
that her star's blissed-out state would add an unwanted love glow
to her portrayal of a character in emotional turmoil did not merely
cross Krueger's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was flipped out, initially,'' said Krueger, who instead of
asking Graham to leave her floppy-haired distraction back in the
hotel room chose to adopt a wait-and-see strategy. ``I wanted to
make sure I was doing the right thing, to see if he was stifling
her. And he just wasn't. He was incredibly respectful. A boyfriend
with a capital `B.' Like, when she was cold, he'd wrap his arms
around her. So I thought, `Well, at least she's very happy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when it comes to the idiosyncrasies of the creative
process, Krueger has probably seen it all. During the early '90s,
after graduating from the University of California at Berkeley, she
found work as a script supervisor for Abel Ferrara, Jim Jarmusch
and James Ivory, independent directors with highly divergent
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   By definition, the script supervisor's job is about keeping
account of a movie's continuity and dialogue. The way Jarmusch
describess it, though, Krueger's specialty was also quirk
management.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
