<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0861 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-OLY-KHANNOUCHI-HNS &LR;      04-18 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-KHANNOUCHI-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID BARRON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
Khalid Khannouchi, the Moroccan-born world-record holder in the
marathon, took another step Tuesday in his efforts to obtain U.S.
citizenship in time to compete for the United States in the Summer
Olympics.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Khannouchi, who has lived in the United States since 1993, met
here with his Houston attorney, Harry Gee, to provide fingerprint
information to Immigration and Naturalization Service officials.
</P>
<P>
   He then boarded a flight to Ireland, where he will recover from
a recent race and await word on whether his citizenship application
will be approved before the May 7 marathon trials in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Gee has said there was an 80 percent chance INS officials would
approve Khannouchi's application by May 3, four days before the
trials, ``but I'm feeling a much higher-percentage chance now,'' he
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (INS) have the information and material they need to
comply with the law and regulations. It's just a matter of
processing,'' Gee said. ``Having said that, you're always a little
hesitant. I never say that something is 100 percent. But I'm really
optimistic that this has a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi, 28, came to the United States from Morocco in 1993
and married a naturalized American citizen, Sandra Inoa, in 1996.
He won the Chicago Marathon in 1997 and 1998, his first two races
at the distance, and in the 1999 Chicago Marathon last October set
the world record of 2 hours, 5 minutes, 42 seconds for the 26-mile,
385-yard distance.
</P>
<P>
   He was favored to win Sunday's London Marathon, his fourth race
at the distance, but finished third in 2:08:36, two minutes behind
winner Antonio Pinto of Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased with the training,'' he said. ``The competition
has been good so far except my last race was a third place, which I
didn't like, but that's life. I still consider myself a rookie in
the marathon. Each and every time I run is a learning experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (citizenship and a shot at the U.S. trials) would mean a
lot to me. I had a dream to come here and succeeded. I have a
better life. My second dream would be to go to the Olympics, and I
don't want to go as a spectator. I want to go and bring something
back for my country.''
</P>
<P>
   If the INS delays his application or if he is unable to recover
quickly from Sunday's race, he could try to qualify at 10,000
meters during the U.S. trials in July at Sacramento, Calif.,
assuming his application is granted by then.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential roadblock may come from the Moroccan athletic
federation, which could file a protest that would require him to
wait three years before representing the United States. Khannouchi
emigrated to the U.S. because of what he described as lack of
support by the federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the (International) Olympic Committee gets involved, I
don't think that will be a problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi struggled during his early years in the United States
and dropped out of a 1995 road race in Connecticut. His future
wife, who also dropped out of the race, gave him a ride back to New
York and offered to act as his coach and manager.
</P>
<P>
   He dumped his coach, former Olympic middle-distance champion
Said Aouita, and married Inoa, a former marathon record holder in
her native Dominican Republic and later a runner's agent, a year
later. She encouraged him to focus on the marathon, and he won his
debut race in Chicago in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi applied for permanent residency status in 1996, two
months after his wedding, but the INS worker who interviewed him
never filed the paperwork, then was indicted and later convicted of
conspiracy, bribery and processing false documents. Although no
wrongdoing was involved in Khannouchi's case, his file was frozen
and his green card was not granted until September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The normal waiting limit to become a U.S. citizen is three
years, which would rule him out for the 2000 Olympics, but the
couple found a loophole in INS regulations when Sandra Khannouchi
earlier this month began working for Elite Racing Inc., a U.S.
company that promotes racing overseas.
</P>
<P>
   INS regulations can provide expedited citizenship for spouses of
U.S. citizens who work overseas for an American company. The law
was used a month before the 1998 World Cup to obtain citizenship
for French defender David Regis, who was married to a U.S. citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Some U.S. track figures, such as former distance runner Marty
Liquori, have spoken out against Khannouchi's efforts, saying they
will discourage the development of U.S.-born runners. Others,
including former Olympic medalists Frank Shorter, Joan Benoit
Samuelson and Bill Rodgers, have supported him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some who don't like what I'm doing, and that
sometimes makes me mad,'' he said. ``I don't like to have enemies
or people who criticize me. What I'm trying to do is my best for
myself and the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   During his brief stop in Houston, Khannouchi had his
fingerprints recorded electronically, which should expedite a
records check by the FBI. Depending on INS action and his recovery
from the London race, he could return within a week to 10 days for
more meetings and, eventually, a citizenship swearing-in ceremony
in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   While the bureaucracy grinds on, Khannouchi remains noncommittal
regarding his status for the marathon trials. He said he has
suffered training injuries every time he has tried to run more than
one marathon a year.
</P>
<P>
   Track mavens have predicted that Khannouchi could perform at 90
percent of capacity and still qualify in the top three for the U.S.
team, but he remains cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``A marathon is a marathon,'' he said. ``You don't know what can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
