<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0862 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-LISA-KRUEGER-FILMS-2N     04-18 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LISA-KRUEGER-FILMS-2NDTAKE-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: quirk management.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jarmusch was often amazed by how Krueger kept track of the lines
his eclectic ensemble casts were encouraged to ad-lib, as well as
the scenes he would be filming and the type of footage he would
need for editing. ``It was like having another eye,'' he said.
``She really understood how we were working.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivory was a stickler for delivering dialogue exactly as written.
During the making of `` and Bridge'' (1990), for example, Paul
Newman accidentally swapped the word ``which'' for ``that.'' Ivory
instructed Krueger to correct the Academy Award-winning legend. ``I
looked at Jim, like, `Do I have to?' And he smiled at me and said,
`It builds character.' And, in a weird way, it (italics)does(end
italics) build character because I learned to see the bigger
picture, to figure out how to tell somebody something technical
without ruining what was going on creatively.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Newman's response to the soft-spoken, slightly
built, earnest looking Krueger was, ``If you're lucky.'' Still, he
complied.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really has everybody on her team because she's so
incredibly diplomatic and endearing,'' said Tom Krueger. Krueger is
Krueger's younger brother and was the director of photography on
``Committed'' and ``Manny and Lo'' as well as ``Best Offer,'' an
award-winning short film Krueger wrote and directed in 1990 which
featured art direction by a third Krueger, brother Matthew. That
Catharine Krueger, the eldest of the four siblings, has temporarily
suspended her photojournalism career while she raises her family in
Texas must bring some comfort to the Krueger progenitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all of our parents' splendor and faults, we are here to
document it,'' said Tom Krueger, a writer and director whose work,
like his sister's, is laced with autobiographical touches. ``We
have so much raw material to choose from _ and not all of it puts
them in the best light. If they only knew they were going to have
four artists, two of them filmmakers to fully explore all of it on
the silver screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Krueger was born in St. Louis, Mo., but by the time she was 10
and the family was living in northern California, divorce and
upheaval had turned the Krueger clan into a two-city household. ``I
grew up in the first wave of parents discovering themselves,''
Krueger said about the split that sent her psychiatrist mother
packing to Berkeley while her orthopedic surgeon father remained in
Lucas Valley; both went on to remarry and build second families.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, I advocate this, but it left me with certain
question marks about what bonds and institutions really mean.
`Manny and Lo,' in a lot of ways, is about not knowing what family
is. `Committed' is about, `What does it mean to be married to
someone?'''
</P>
<P>
   When she made her exodus to Paris' 11th arrondissement she began
studying cinema at the Ecole des Hautes Etudes, teaching English at
the University of Paris and endlessly analyzing film, albeit in a
language that was not her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very exciting time, a real hotbed of critical
thought,'' said Krueger, who has no delusions about the
contributions she made to the debates held by her then-boyfriend,
the French film theoretician Raymond Bellour, and his equally
cerebral friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just this little pipsqueak, offering my opinions in bad
French,'' Krueger said. ``Now that I'm their age, I look back and
think they must have been unbelievably patient.''
</P>
<P>
   On the morning she relayed this bit of background, Krueger was
eating an oatmeal and fruit breakfast in a hotel coffee shop in
Santa Monica. These days, Krueger lives outside Kingston, N.Y.,
with Art Chandler, her husband of seven months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a doctor,'' she said. ``And that's the amazing part.
After all these years, I've met somebody who does what my parents
do.'' For perhaps the fourth time in the span of an hour she
reached for her cappuccino, began following a train of thought and
set her coffee back down, forgetting to take a sip. And how did
that smear of what looked like hot cereal end up on the elbow of
her black sweater?
</P>
<P>
   Such tics of brainy preoccupation make her seem more like a
college professor than a battle-scarred indie filmmaker. Where's
the bitterness and frustration that's the specialty of her ilk?
``Well, I've been lucky,'' she said with a smile. ``I haven't hit
any walls yet. Or at least ones that are perceivable to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I may get rageful some day,'' she added, apologetically.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
