<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIALLO-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIALLO PARENTS SUE CITY AND OFFICERS OVER SON'S DEATH
</HEADLINE>
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The family of Amadou Diallo filed a civil lawsuit on
Tuesday against New York City and the four police officers who were
acquitted of criminal charges in his death.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed by Diallo's parents, Saikou Amadou Diallo and
Kadiatou Diallo, and an administrator of Diallo's estate, Stanley
S. Ostrau, focuses not just on the four officers' actions but also
on the culture and policies of the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   It specifically points to the department's major expansion in
1997 of the Street Crime Unit, to which all four officers were
assigned, and to what it calls the unit's ``policy'' of racial
profiling as factors in the fatal police shooting. Diallo, an
unarmed street vendor and Guinean immigrant, was killed in a hail
of 41 bullets in the vestibule of his Bronx apartment building on
Feb. 4, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is considering whether to prosecute the
officers on federal civil rights charges, and lawyers for the
Diallos said they had hoped to wait until that decision was made
before filing suit. But under the state's statute of limitations,
civil suits must be filed within one year and 90 days after the
incident in question. That deadline is approaching.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Justice Department officials would say only that
their review was continuing. Gregory Longworth, a lawyer with
Worth, Longworth, Bamundo &AMP; London who is representing the four
officers in the civil proceedings, said he would seek a stay of the
suit until the Justice Department had made a determination.
Officials with the city corporation counsel's office would not
comment on the suit.
</P>
<P>
   In the suit, filed in State Supreme Court in the Bronx, the
Diallos are seeking $20 million from the city, as well as $41
million in punitive damages against the officers, Sean Carroll,
Edward McMellon, Richard Murphy and Kenneth Boss, who are accused
of using excessive force and acting under color of law to deny
Diallo's rights. While many such suits are settled out of court,
the family's lawyers have said they will consider using this one to
raise issues in court that they believe were not adequately raised
in the criminal trial.
</P>
<P>
   While the officers contended at their trial that Diallo had
behaved suspiciously, the suit says they approached him ``for no
other reason but that he was black.'' Carroll indicated at the
trial that he had stopped Diallo because he had resembled a sketch
of a serial rapist. Soon after the shooting of Diallo, the police
arrested another man, Isaac Jones, and said he was the serial
rapist. Jones went on trial this week in four Bronx rape cases; he
is charged in 13 others.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit accuses the Police Department of making a policy of
racial profiling by targeting black males for ``stop and frisk''
searches on the street. The department tacitly authorized unlawful
stops by the Street Crime Unit, the suit contends.
</P>
<P>
   According to the suit, the street stops have resulted in the
persistent violation of individuals' constitutional rights. The
suit states that blacks make up 25.6 percent of the New York City
population but that 62 percent of all people stopped by the Street
Crime Unit are black. In the period leading to Diallo's death, the
Street Crime Unit stopped about 16 black residents for every stop
that resulted in an arrest, the suit says.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the suit contends, the ``policy, practice and custom
of racial profiling, established, sanctioned and condoned by the
New York City Police Department, was a contributing cause'' of
Diallo's death.
</P>
<P>
   The officers were also acting in accordance with a mandate that
Street Crime Unit officers seize at least one illegal gun a month,
the suit alleges, and Police Commissioner Howard Safir's tripling
of the Street Crime Unit's size, to 380 officers from 120 in 1997,
resulted in ``grossly inadequate training'' and left the unit
``dangerously unsupervised.'' By assigning inadequately trained
officers to the unit, the suit says, the department ``evidenced
deliberate indifference'' to the rights of the people with whom the
unit had contact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
