<HEADER>
A0865 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BIG-KAHUNA-FILM-ART-$     04-18 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG-KAHUNA-FILM-ART-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DURING A 16-DAY SPRINT, INSTINCT TAKES CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent as NYT29 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 23)  
 Ted Loos' most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about Hilary
Swank.  
 By TED LOOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last winter, the cast and crew of ``The Big Kahuna''
filmed a feature in the time some people spend on a beach vacation.
Made in Manhattan in just 16 days and starring Kevin Spacey and
Danny DeVito, ``The Big Kahuna'' may have set a speed record for
high-minded dramas with big-name actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no time for overanalyzing, hand-wringing, ego or
self-interest,'' said the first-time director, John Swanbeck. ``It
was pure instinct for 16 days.''
</P>
<P>
   Adapted by Roger Rueff from his play ``Hospitality Suite,'' the
90-minute film, which opens on Friday, throws three businessmen
into one claustrophobic hotel room and, with a large dose of humor,
forces them to hash out issues of religion, principle and morality.
</P>
<P>
   To milk these grand themes for drama, the filmmakers had to
think small _ they had a budget of $1.8 million and stuck to it.
``When you don't have money to solve problems, it forces everyone
to come up with creative solutions they wouldn't have thought of
otherwise,'' said Spacey, who also produced the film and raised the
money. ``It puts everybody on the ropes. You find out a lot about
yourself, and about others.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing they discovered was that you can't always trust the
conventional wisdom. Originally, the filmmakers had agreed that
``The Big Kahuna,'' like most plays that become movies, would have
to be ``opened up,'' freed from the limitations of its stage
setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we found that the drama went completely flat,'' said
Swanbeck, a Chicago theater director and acting coach who staged
``Hospitality Suite'' in 1993. ``So we thought, `Let's go to the
opposite direction _ deeper into the room, deeper into the
characters.'''
</P>
<P>
   The three colleagues are representing a chemical lubricant firm
at a convention in Wichita, Kan., trying to land an important new
client with a party in their drab hospitality suite. Spacey plays
Larry, a glib, hard-driving cynic trying to give Bob, a devout
young Christian played by Peter Facinelli, the benefit of his
experience. DeVito's older, quieter Phil has to play referee while
struggling with his own despondency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Roger one day that I see this as a story of one man at
three different stages of his life,'' Spacey said on the telephone
from Los Angeles. ``Each has to imagine the others in his shoes,
and they find out how easy it is for someone to cloak his own
prejudices behind a wall of religion or politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Spacey and Swanbeck nurtured their interest in the material for
almost a decade before the cameras rolled. They first met in 1985
in Chicago, when both worked on the original production of David
Rabe's ``Hurlyburly,'' Swanbeck as an assistant to the director and
Spacey as an understudy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sent him the play back in 1991 or so, and he loved it,''
said the affable, intense Swanbeck. When Spacey started Trigger
Street Productions, his filmmaking company, in 1997, he made the
collaboration a priority. Swanbeck knew that when Spacey finally
found a window between projects, there would be little time to
lose. In January 1999, the call came: ``We're shooting in three
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news was that it would be February, a slow time for
films in New York; this allowed Spacey and Swanbeck to hire an
unusually good crew, including the cinematographer Anastas Michos
(``Man on the Moon''). ``He's really the reason we got the movie in
the can in 16 days,'' Swanbeck said. ``He defied the rule that you
can't have cheap, fast and beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Spacey pulled off his own feat: rehearsing the lead role in
``The Iceman Cometh'' on Broadway by day and filming ``The Big
Kahuna'' at night. He had worked out a deal with the director of
``Iceman,'' Howard Davies, allowing the actor to leave in the late
afternoon during the early stages of rehearsal. His having played
the part in London made moonlighting in another very talky work a
bit easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some strange way they sort of complemented one another,
since I was playing salesmen in both,'' Spacey said. He would begin
rehearsing ``Iceman'' at 10 a.m. Around 4 p.m., he would head to
the film's set at Chelsea Piers.
</P>
<P>
   DeVito and Facinelli filmed their scenes in the early
afternoons; when Spacey got there, they would all rehearse briefly
and then shoot until 11:30 p.m. Back in his hotel, Spacey would
often brainstorm with Swanbeck by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   The frenetic pace of ``The Big Kahuna'' might have cowed another
first-time director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the night before we started shooting,'' said
Swanbeck, who was staying at the New York apartment of a friend.
``I bolted up and thought, `I've forgotten to be terrified.'''
</P>
<P>
   Swanbeck had prepared by producing and editing a short film that
was directed by his wife and longtime collaborator, Nancy Scanlon.
``I thought the best way for me as a director to do a good job for
Kevin Spacey the producer would be to learn his job,'' he said. ``I
could get all the first-timer mistakes out of the way, and then
wouldn't spend the 16 days we had learning who the gaffer is.''
</P>
<P>
   But he still wanted to be candid about his newcomer status. ``On
the first day I said to the crew, `I'll make a deal with you,''' he
recalled. `` `I'll be very clear and decisive about the story we
want to tell. You guys are responsible for catching it on film.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was an apt approach, since Rueff's script deals with the
perils of thinking you have all the answers. A chemical engineer
and playwright who once worked in the lubricants industry himself,
he said the focus of the drama is not religion, though it is a
catalyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about character versus principles,'' Rueff said on the
phone from his home in Naperville, Ill. ``Because I don't think
those are synonymous. In a nutshell, principles are what you have
when you don't have character.''
</P>
<P>
   Though no one abandoned his principles to get the movie made,
shortcuts abounded. They ranged from taking low salaries _
``Originally, we got carfare and a sandwich,'' joked Spacey _ to
using DeVito's own wardrobe when a schedule change caught the
costumer without the shirt needed for a scene.
</P>
<P>
   There were other examples of ``guerrilla filmmaking,'' Swanbeck
said. One night Spacey called him at 2 a.m. with a new idea: to
shoot a scene between two of the characters across a breakfast
cart. But there was no such cart on set.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got there the next day, there's Kevin standing on the
back of the grip truck, dressed in work boots and jeans, unloading
hotel furniture,'' Swanbeck said. ``He had ordered room service
breakfast for two. Then he wheeled the breakfast cart out of the
hotel.'' Swanbeck was careful to add that it was promptly returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he was doing that all the other bellboys were pushing their
carts saying, `Doesn't that bellboy look like Kevin Spacey?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
