<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0867 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-YARD-GAL-THEATER-$ADV     04-18 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YARD-GAL-THEATER-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREET TALK COMPLETE WITH GLOSSARY  
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATT WOLF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ As is often the case by this point in the Broadway
season, London playwrights are having their say. This year, three
of England's senior dramatists are represented in plays both new
and in revival: Michael Frayn (``Copenhagen''), Peter Shaffer
(``Amadeus'') and Tom Stoppard (``The Real Thing'').
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday they will be joined Off Broadway by one of
Britain's younger generation when Rebecca Prichard, 28, makes her
American theater debut with her play ``Yard Gal.''
</P>
<P>
   In previews at the MCC Theater in Chelsea, ``Yard Gal'' is a
study over time of two feisty, quick-witted girl gang members. As
in London, the cast consists of Amelia Lowdell and Sharon
Duncan-Brewster, two little-known English actresses in their early
20s whose performances have been acclaimed for merging seamlessly
as one. (Think a multicultural, not to mention female, English
variant on Philip Seymour Hoffman and John C. Reilly's brothers in
the current revival of Sam Shepard's ``True West'' and you get the
idea.) Lowdell portrays Marie, who is white, and Duncan-Brewster
plays Boo, who is black.
</P>
<P>
   By the play's end, one teen-ager is behind bars, while the
other, the author suggests, is moving ahead with her life, though
not without memories of some people who ``stay inside you ...
always with me, all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   As they carve a frequently lawless and drug-fueled path through
the multiracial streets of Hackney, East London, the young women
speak a heightened local patois, where, among many other variations
in language, ``isn't it'' becomes ``innit'' and ``thieving''
becomes ``tiefin'.'' (The MCC program will include a glossary for
those uninitiated in East End-speak.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Yard Gal'' was originally presented at the Royal Court Theater
(directed there by Gemma Bodinetz, who is repeating her assignment
in New York) and has followed the path to New York of two other
Royal Court plays: Jez Butterworth's ``Mojo,'' which the Atlantic
Theater Company put on in 1997, and Mark Ravenhill's ``Shopping and
...,'' for which Bodinetz served as co-director when it was at New
York Theater Workshop in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Butterworth and Ravenhill are also members of the younger
generation of English playwrights and all three plays employ
stylized speech that their often lower-class characters seem to
revel in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rich and robust,'' Prichard said of the dialogue in
``Yard Gal.'' ``And it reflects the way the street girls are
survivors. I think it has a natural larger-than-life quality.
Hopefully, it's poetic.''
</P>
<P>
   The play's title refers to a member of a girl gang, with a
``yardie'' originally denoting someone from Jamaica. ``It's a
London term,'' Prichard said, ``that is used ironically in the
play. These aren't all yard gals; they're sort of yard gal
wannabes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodinetz, the director, said of the play's language: ``It's so
particular that most people in London didn't know the terms that
were being used. But then they all just said, `Go with it; trust
it.' I don't know that it's going to be that much more difficult in
New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps Bodinetz is simply used to such cultural transplants.
In February she directed the world premiere at the Royal Court of
the American playwright Kia Corthron's ``Breath, Boom.'' Its
subject? A murderous girl gang in the Bronx. ``I had to keep
slowing that down through previews,'' the director said. ``English
audiences couldn't quite keep up with the quickfire way the play
was written.''
</P>
<P>
   Prichard has her own theories about the accessibility of her
dialogue in ``Yard Gal.'' ``You can absorb the world of the play
without understanding every sentence,'' she said, arguing that the
story ``goes on enough of an emotional journey that I don't think
the language is ever a barrier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like when you watch plays from a different era, from
another century,'' said Prichard, who studied drama at Exeter
University and worked as a waitress at Pizza Hut before committing
herself full time to writing. ``It's still worth doing, even if you
can't dissect every line.''
</P>
<P>
   Tall, soft-spoken and possessed of a dramatic presence that
suggests she would be equally at home onstage or off, Prichard
could never be mistaken for either of her ``Yard Gal'' heroines.
``I'm as white middle class as you can get,'' she said with a
laugh, having grown up in Essex, east of London. When she was 9,
her parents divorced and her father, an engineer, now lives in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke of being attracted as a writer to the harsher areas of
existence, which she depicted, she hoped, in a vibrant and
nonpolemical way. ``The alternative,'' she said, ``is a kind of
escapism I don't agree with. It's irresponsible, morally, not to
face up to some of the realities'' of life.
</P>
<P>
   A co-production in London between the Royal Court and the Clean
Break Theater Company, ``Yard Gal'' was commissioned by Clean
Break. The organization was started by two former inmates who
wanted to provide a voice for female ex-offenders and prisoners
past and present.
</P>
<P>
   As is true of all the writers hired by Clean Break since it was
founded in 1979, Prichard grounded her material in issues
surrounding women's experiences in the British criminal justice
system. The bonus was an extensively researched piece of theater _
Clean Break receives money from the government to stage one such
project annually _ possessed not just of a self-evident social
awareness but of writing that was applauded for being buoyantly,
theatrically alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The language is beguilingly rich,'' wrote Charles Spencer in
The Daily Telegraph during the original engagement of ``Yard Gal''
in 1998, which sold out in London and then went on a five-week tour
to prisons, theaters and arts centers around the country.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Prichard said, her aim was to write a play
rooted in the grim realities of London street life without
wallowing in despair. ``I do tend to write about people who've been
marginalized or cut off,'' she said. Her previous play, ``Fair
Game,'' adapted from the work of an Israeli writer, Edna Mazya,
sparked some controversy in the London press over its depiction of
teen-age rape as re-enacted nightly by teen-age actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``For adults' comfort,'' Prichard said, ``we like to think of
childhood as innocent, when what we're protecting is our own kind
of comfort zone.'' In any case, she added wryly, ``none of the
journalists had read the play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, if you brutalize an audience,'' Prichard
said, ``then I think you're defeating yourself. There's got to be
enough humanity for people to stay with it so they don't switch
off. If you don't transcend that, what are you writing about?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
