<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-CUSTODY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDIATRICIAN SAYS ELIAN BEING EXPLOITED BY FAMILY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The public relations battle over the fate of Elian
Gonzalez intensified Tuesday after immigration officials released a
letter from a pediatrician who said the young shipwreck survivor
has been ``horrendously exploited'' by his Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The letter drew an immediate response from the relatives'
attorneys who said the boy is afraid to return to his Cuban father,
and from supporters who said the doctor lacked credibility because
he had not examined the boy.
</P>
<P>
   The claims and counterclaims were the latest in the relentless
war of words over the issue of Elian. The 6-year-old has been at
the center of a custody fight between his Cuban father and
Cuban-American relatives since he was rescued from the ocean south
of Florida last November. His mother and 10 others drowned fleeing
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The exchanges also came amid intense anticipation of a federal
appeals court ruling that could decide whether the boy returns to
Cuba with his father or remains in the United States with his
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Irwin Redlener, the pediatrician advising the federal
government, said Elian is being psychologically abused by the
relatives and should be removed from their home immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elian Gonzalez is now in a state of imminent danger to his
physical and emotional well-being in a home that I consider to be
psychologically abusive,'' Redlener wrote to Attorney General Janet
Reno and Doris Meissner, the commissioner of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``In recent days, the crisis has taken a profound turn for the
worse,'' wrote Redlener, president and director of community
pediatrics at the Children's Hospital at Montefiore in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   Redlener referred to allegations that Juan Miguel Gonzalez, the
boy's father, abused his son and mother, and to a videotape
released by Miami relatives showing the boy angrily refusing to
return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Redlener said he was concerned about the boy's well being
because the recent maneuverings have occurred in ``an environment
of radical hysteria, and suggestions of public defiance and
potential violence promulgated by the custodial family and their
supporters in Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   The INS released the letter Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Redlener recommended the government immediately remove Elian
from the custody of his great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   At the government's request, Redlener selected the panel of
three mental health experts who last week interviewed Juan Miguel
Gonzalez and Lazaro Gonzalez, the boy's great uncle. The two were
interviewed for the sole purpose of establishing guidelines for an
orderly transfer of the boy's custody to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the relatives said the government would understand
Elian's fears if it conducted a psychological evaluation of the
boy, which it has refused to do.
</P>
<P>
   An impending ruling from the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
in Atlanta is expected to clarify the legal issue. Attorneys for
the Miami relatives secured a temporary injunction last Thursday
preventing U.S. authorities from returning the boy to Cuba. The
injunction did not prevent the boy from being reunited with his
father, who came to the United States to claim his son.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the Justice Department last week asked the appeals
court to lift its temporary injunction and allow Juan Miguel
Gonzalez to take sole custody of his son. The motion included a
promise from Gonzalez to remain in the United States until the
appeals process has been exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Miami Herald reported Tuesday that the protection
of Elian and related expenses has cost taxpayers $1 million so far.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
