<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0871 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-HUMMER-ROCKER19-C     04-18 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HUMMER-ROCKER19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hurrah! Rocker shuts his mouth
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The flower of American sportswriting bordered one
entire facet of the Turner Field diamond. Newspapers from New York,
Chicago, Washington and one claiming to represent the whole USA had
urgently dispatched correspondents, as did all your major cable
news networks.
</P>
<P>
   A postseason-type gathering in April. All here Tuesday for John
Rocker Appreciation Night. What a festive occasion.
</P>
<P>
   You may have heard something about the Braves closer being out
the first two weeks of the season with severe spasms of the voice
box. Rocker himself made it known he would have nothing else to say
on the evening of his reinstatement, other than a quick take with
the Braves' flagship radio station.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, I'd rail against the silent treatment. It's real bad
for the journalism business. With his stance, Rocker leaves it to
his more stand-up (read that ``smarter'') teammates to speak to his
situation. But, considering that any time he opens his mouth there
is the high likelihood of something primordial oozing out, he's
better off keeping the door to his soul closed. Should he evolve
into a Steve Carlton or Eddie Murray, then at least something good
will have come of this experience. Any moment not talking to John
Rocker is another that could be spent in conversation with someone
interesting. There are plenty of those in the home clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   So, there we all were Tuesday chasing a story that, frankly,
began running out of legs months ago. The fact that Rocker had
returned and was ready to _ irony alert _ lend some stability to
the Braves' bullpen was a form of news. Other than that, there
really is little new ground to break. All opinions on the subject
have set as hard as a pool deck.
</P>
<P>
   This is what it has come to: A fellow writer wandered the outer
perimeter of the stadium, looking for fan reaction. In the
distance, he spotted two figures who looked to be dressed in white
robes. Now, there's a story, he's thinking. But the two take a step
closer and reveal themselves to be nuns, not Klansmen. What a
comedown.
</P>
<P>
   We try to ferret out such important information as just what
music will accompany Rocker as he runs to the rescue in the ninth
inning. It used to be Twisted Sister's ``I Wanna Rock,'' until the
heavy metal group announced it wanted no connection to an accused
xenophobe. Managing to disgust Twisted Sister should be a
life-changing experience. By the way, no new anthem has been
selected.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine spoke for the team, John Schuerholz lectured on the
media's part in this mess and the world was largely unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   And while all of us tripped over the usual nonsense, there was
this wonderful, poignant moment playing itself out practically
unnoticed during pregame batting practice. A family of four from
Columbia, S.C., was lost amid the mob on the field. The youngest,
6-year-old Brett Ballentine, was there as a survivor, a child who
for more than half his life had fought leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   Over to the Ballentines came Andres Galarraga, author of the one
Braves story that actually deserves constant retelling. His own
comeback from cancer galloping along so well, Galarraga got close
to the child and told him to keep taking his medicine, to keep a
smile on his face. He held out the very real hope of recovery. Then
the huge man enveloped the little boy in a hug.
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday took on real meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
