a leader when it comes to heroin addicts. Reliable
country-by-country numbers have not been compiled, with social
science a low priority in the third world and addicts hard to poll
anyway. But the United Nations estimates there are 1.5 million
heroin addicts in this nation of 150 million, an unfortunate result
of geography, geopolitics, corruption and poverty. Men doing
``Panni'' - sniffing heroin fumes off a tin foil - on the sidewalk
along a major rapd in the old part of Karachi. (Barry Bearak/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) KARACHI, Pakistan -- April 18, 2000 -- PAKISTAN-HEROIN-3
-- Pakistan, which does not lead the world in much, is most likely
a leader when it comes to heroin addicts. Reliable
country-by-country numbers have not been compiled, with social
science a low priority in the third world and addicts hard to poll
anyway. But the United Nations estimates there are 1.5 million
heroin addicts in this nation of 150 million, an unfortunate result
of geography, geopolitics, corruption and poverty. ``Heroin is
written in my fate,'' says Mohammad Aslam, 40, left, with a needle
in his arm.'' With the veins in his extremities withered, addicts
like Jan Sher, 29, right, often inject their heroin near the
crotch. (Barry Bearak/The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) KARACHI, Pakistan -- April 18, 2000 -- PAKISTAN-HEROIN-2
-- Pakistan, which does not lead the world in much, is most likely
a leader when it comes to heroin addicts. Reliable
country-by-country numbers have not been compiled, with social
science a low priority in the third world and addicts hard to poll
anyway. But the United Nations estimates there are 1.5 million
heroin addicts in this nation of 150 million, an unfortunate result
of geography, geopolitics, corruption and poverty. An addict is
assisted with injecting heroin on a street in Karachi. (Barry
Bearak/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) KARACHI, Pakistan -- April 18, 2000 -- PAKISTAN-HEROIN-1
-- Pakistan, which does not lead the world in much, is most likely
a leader when it comes to heroin addicts. Reliable
country-by-country numbers have not been compiled, with social
science a low priority in the third world and addicts hard to poll
anyway. But the United Nations estimates there are 1.5 million
heroin addicts in this nation of 150 million, an unfortunate result
of geography, geopolitics, corruption and poverty. Raees Khan is
assisted in getting his first high of the day off heroin from a
friend while on a median strip along a busy road across from a
mosque. (Barry Bearak/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- April 18, 2000 -- BIRD-THEATER-REVIEW --
Kristine Nielsen, who plays thea wronged queen, with the Green
Bird. Julie Taymor's alternately enchanting and tedious adaptation
of Carlo Gozzi's 18th-century fable is a production that stakes out
an unclaimed patch in the landscape of Broadway entertainment. In
``The Green Bird,'' Taymor sets her sights on an adult audience
with a childlike capacity for wonder, creating a ribald world in
which the impossible is a matter of course. (Sara Krulwich/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) HOUSTON -- April 18, 2000 -- PRESIDENT-SCULPTURE --
David Adickes outside his studio in Houston with three of his busts
of American presidents. The 18-foot sculptures have been barred
from a proposed educational theme park in Virginia because Adickes
and investors in the project lack the appropriate permits from the
local zoning authorities. ``It's a bump, not a barricade,'' said
the plaster-speckled sculptor, who has run into opposition before.
(Phillippe Diederich/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- April 18, 2000 -- BROADWAY-CONDUCTOR-1 --
Paul Gemignani, a musical director renowned for his intuitive
molding of Broadway shows, expresses passion through his baton. He
has conducted for ``Sweeney Todd,'' ``Kiss Me, Kate,'' and ``High
Society.'' ``I consider myself the other actor in the show,'' he
said. (Ruby Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- April 18, 2000 -- BROADWAY-CONDUCTOR-2 --
Paul Gemignani, a musical director renowned for his intuitive
molding of Broadway shows, expresses passion through his baton. He
has conducted for ``Kiss Me, Kate,'' left, and ``High Society.''
``I consider myself the other actor in the show,'' he said. (Sara
Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) ATLANTA -- April 18, 2000 -- BBN-BRAVES-ROCKER --
Arriving at Turner Field, Atlanta Braves relief pitcher John Rocker
waved to cheering fans who greeted him Tuesday after serving a two
week suspension for his racially charged remarks in a Sports
Illustrated article last summer. Rocker rejoins a team that, on the
field at least, has missed him dearly. The Braves hope that his
journey into political incorrectness is behind him. Rocker says he
hopes so, too. (Marlene Karas/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- April 18, 2000 -- NY-BRONX-CORPSE-B&AMP;W --
Since 1939, the Bronx's official bloom has been the Amorphophallus
titanum, better known in horticultural circles as the corpse
flower, or the devil's tongue. The Amorphophallus titanum, native
to the rain forests of Sumatra, is one of the world's largest
flowers, but it blooms only once every 30 years or so, and when it
does, it emits a pungent odor that has been described as eerily
similar to that of rotting flesh. The corpse flower in full bloom
in 1937 at the New York Botanical Garden in the Bronx. (New York
Botanical Garden/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- April 18, 2000 -- FRENCH-COOKBOOK -- On Page 2
of ``The French Laundry Cookbook,'' Thomas Keller, the author, chef
and owner of the Napa Valley restaurant of that name, makes his
approach quite clear: ``Cooking is not about convenience, and it's
not about shortcuts.'' Obviously, practicality is not a strong
point. But as a testament to the work of one of the best chefs in
America and as a piece of art, it deserves its honors. (The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) MILLBURN, N.J. -- April 18, 2000 -- NJ-DEER-DEPORT-2 --
Like many of their neighbors across the suburbs, the people of
Millburn have had it with Bambi. But unlike other places where
hunters or hired sharpshooters cull the herds, Millburn is taking a
costly, though far less volatile approach to the problem. The town
is herding the deer into pens, from which they are to be shipped
out of state. (Laura Pedrick/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MILLBURN, N.J. -- April 18, 2000 -- NJ-DEER-DEPORT-1 --
Danny Pariso, the animal control officer for Millburn, spreads a
mixture that includes apples and molasses to lure deer into pens,
from which they are to be shipped out of state. Millburn officials
admit that exporting deer may sound extravagant, but the
alternative is far less palatable. ``We don't want to have
troubles,'' said Timothy Gordon, the town administrator, referring
to the strife that has engulfed other places that proposed lethal
means for controlling deer. (Laura Pedrick/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- April 18, 2000 -- WINE-TALK -- Soft, round
merlot leads a double life. For all of merlot's inroads in the
United States, it is a pallid bit player here, compared with the
flamboyant star that merlot is in France, from Petrus on down.
(Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- April 18, 2000 -- CABBIE-FUNERAL -- Anna
Maria Estrella, center, is comforted by family and friends as she
leaves the cargo section of an airline at John F. Kennedy Airport
where her husband's body was received for transport to the
Dominican Republic, Tuesday. Estrella's husband, Luis Francisco
Perez, was the sixth cab driver killed in the city this year. New
York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani announced Monday that the city will set
up a fund to help the families of the slain drivers and set up a
special task force to protect livery drivers. (Nicole Bengiveno/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- April 18, 2000 -- LAMB-FARM -- Picholine
serves a loin of lamb with fennel and artichoke hearts, left. At
Caf Boulud, Spring Lamb Trio with pomme olive, petit onions, baby
asparagus and oregano. The consumption of lamb, the ancient symbol
of rebirth shared by Christians, Jews and Muslims, has survived to
this day in modified form. (Barbara Alper/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- April 18, 2000 -- NY-RESTAURANT-LINGERERS --
Now that No Smoking, No Cell Phones and No Laptops icons have
become standard signage at New York restaurants, it may be time for
one more admonishment -- No Lingering! An hourglass over each table
at The Hourglass Tavern, in Manhattan's Restaurant Row, shows
dinners when their time at the table is up. (Thomas Dallal/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) MATTAPAN, Mass. -- April 18, 2000 -- BLACK-VETERANS-BOS--
When he was 19, Paul Parks enlisted in the Army and became part of
the bloody European campaign to defeat the Nazis. But after helping
rid the world of a heinous totalitarian regime, Parks and his black
comrades came home from battle to segregated bathrooms and water
fountains, and seats at the back of public buses. ``A lot of people
still don't know that blacks played a major role in World War II,
and I think that's unfortunate,'' said Parks, now 77, a longtime
civil rights activist and former Massachusetts education secretary.
Parks posed with his uniform during a recent interview. (Bill
Greene/The Boston Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
