<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MIRANDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SAVING THE MIRANDA RULE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, April 19:
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court will hear a challenge today to its pivotal
Miranda ruling of 1966, which requires police to advise suspects of
their rights before beginning an interrogation. As most viewers of
television crime shows can recite, the Miranda rule requires that
criminal suspects be told of their right to remain silent and have
a lawyer present, and that any statement they make can be used
against them. For the court to overturn Miranda would be an
unwarranted rollback of safeguards against coercion in the criminal
justice system.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a mischievous ruling last year by an appellate court
in Virginia, which held that a failure to issue Miranda warnings no
longer required automatic exclusion in federal prosecutions of the
evidence obtained. Congress, the court reasoned, had effectively
overruled the Miranda decision when it enacted a 1968 law for that
purpose. The 1968 statute provides that a confession is admissible
as long as it is ``voluntarily given'' in light of ``all the
circumstances,'' whether or not the suspect was read his rights.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is that the court's Miranda decision was a
constitutional ruling, which Congress cannot overturn merely by
passing a law. That requires a constitutional amendment, which is
why no attorney general of either party has tried to enforce the
1968 law in the intervening decades. True, Chief Justice Earl
Warren's majority opinion in Miranda invited Congress and the
states to develop ``fully effective'' alternative safeguards that
could replace the Miranda warning. But Congress was not trying to
develop better safeguards with the 1968 law. It sought to reinstate
the same case-by-case test for assessing the voluntariness of
confessions that the Supreme Court, quite correctly, found
unworkable two years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The case has stirred old passions and prompted the filing of a
foot-high stack of briefs by ``friends of the court'' on both sides
of the issue. But as a constitutional and law enforcement matter,
this should be an easy call. Much as the court wisely concluded 34
years ago, the Miranda warnings are an important safeguard for
protecting the Fifth Amendment's privilege against
self-incrimination in the coercive atmosphere of police
questioning. An astonishingly high percentage of suspects _ some 80
to 90 percent _ waive their rights and talk to the police anyway,
belying claims that the Miranda rule badly hampers police work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0350 </DOCNO>
