<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0882 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-POLITICS-NYT     04-18 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMBABWE'S OPPOSITION LEADER WARNS AGAINST PUSHING MUGABE TOWARD
MARTRYDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Zimbabwe rolls toward more violence, the worst
thing that could happen, in the estimation of its main opposition
leader, is to create a martyr out of its founder and once popular
hero, President Robert Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, conciliation is the way to undercut Mugabe's push for
confrontation, says the opposition leader, Morgan Tsvangirai, a
magnetic trade union leader who has transformed himself into the
chairman of the six-month-old Movement for Democratic Change.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I would like to take an aggressive stand, that's
what he's looking for,'' said Tsvangirai, who is visiting here to
dramatize the predicament of what was once southern Africa's best
example of economic and social cohesion. ``He's looking to be made
a martyr. We don't need that.''
</P>
<P>
   With more sorrow than anger evident, Tsvangirai described Mugabe
as a ``man I was prepared to die for 20 years ago,'' but who now,
at age 76, is obsessed by money, power and the nation's former
colonial master, Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Tsvangirai, 48, fresh from a visit to London, is making the
rounds of official Washington, seeking support for free and fair
national elections next month. He appeared to be pushing on an open
door. President Clinton's deputy national security adviser, James
Steinberg, sat next to him at a Georgetown dinner on Monday night
and Tsvangirai met with the assistant secretary of state for
African Affairs, Susan Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the Clinton administration has supported Mugabe,
seeking to use his position to bring a settlement to the war in
Congo, where Mugabe has sent about 10,000 of his top troops. It has
shown scant interest in the showdown he was building between
Zimbabwe's white farmers and state-sponsored black squatters.
</P>
<P>
   But patience with Mugabe has worn out.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is trying to encourage what one official
called a ``peaceful de-escalation'' of the crisis so that yet
another African country does not spin out of control. For
neighboring South Africa, Zimbabwe's economic collapse would have
serious consequences: Zimbabwe is South Africa's biggest buyer of
manufactured goods.
</P>
<P>
   Tsvangirai's visit was sponsored by the National Democratic
Institute for International Affairs here. He impressed those who
met him here, the official said, as someone ``who did not focus on
power but on unity and finding a collective way forward.'' It is
vital that the coming elections include international observers,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   But Tsvangirai said Mugabe appeared intent on fomenting chaos so
that the country appeared to be ungovernable and he could declare a
state of emergency and rule by decree. The Parliament was dissolved
on April 12 in preparation for elections, but the absence of a
sitting legislature could also be used by Mugabe as a step toward
one-man rule, he said.
</P>
<P>
   By dwelling on the question of race _ and specifically, the
domination of the most arable land by 4,500 white farmers _
Tsvangirai said he believes that Mugabe has chosen a rallying cry,
but a hollow one.
</P>
<P>
   Most Zimbabweans were so mired in despair _ more than 50 percent
of the population is unemployed and 2,000 people die of AIDS every
week _ that offering a piece of land did not mean very much, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poverty, unemployment, debt problems, corruption have a
terrible effect on the standard of living of 75 percent of the
people,'' Tsvangirai said. ``When you talk of land in that sea of
poverty it's meaningless. What does land do if you haven't got a
meal?''
</P>
<P>
   He said that land redistribution needed to proceed, but in a way
that would not destabilize the agricultural industry, the backbone
of the economy. Land reform, he said, ``must be done with equity,
empowerment and economic viability.''
</P>
<P>
   Tsvangirai said he is confident that in a free election, his
Movement for Democratic Change will overwhelm Mugabe's Zimbabwe
African National Union-Patriotic Front, which has dominated
politics since it took power in 1980. A recent opinion poll showed
that 65 percent of voters wanted a new government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2232EDT &QL; 
