u f BC-BRAZIL-SATELLITE-NYT     04-18 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-SATELLITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL IS ALLOWING U.S. COMPANIES TO USE SATELLITE LAUNCHING SITE
</HEADLINE>
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Brazil reached an agreement with the United
States on Tuesday to allow American companies to use an equatorial
launching site, advancing the ambitions of Latin America's largest
country to tap the lucrative satellite launching industry.
</P>
<P>
   Under the accord, Brazil would not be permitted to gain access
to the technology of American companies and their clients that
launch satellites from Alcantara, a base in northeastern Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The country has invested more than $200 million in Alcantara,
which is just south of the equator. Satellite launches from the
equator are less expensive because the satellites reach orbit more
quickly and require less rocket fuel.
</P>
<P>
   With the capacity for 14 launches a year, the Alcantara base
could bring Brazil an estimated $30 million each year, joining
other nations that already are profiting from the $2.4 billion
satellite launching market.
</P>
<P>
   ``By entering the space market we're showing the world our
capacity to compete with countries like Kazakhstan, China or French
Guiana,'' Ronaldo Sardenberg, minister of science and technology,
said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   American companies are expected to consider the Alcantara base
an alternative to other equatorial satellite launching sites, such
as the nearby Kourou base in French Guiana, because of the
potential savings in fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an operational aspect Alcantara is extremely
attractive,'' said Ronald Covais, the regional president for the
Americas at the Lockheed Martin Corp. ``Our aim now is to become
Brazil's partner of choice in utilizing the site.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies from the United States and other countries currently
use commercial satellite launching facilities in the United States,
China, Russia, French Guiana and Kazakhstan. According to analysts,
the industry is growing nearly 20 percent a year, driven by plans
to create satellite-based global Internet and telecommunications
services.
</P>
<P>
   In South America, the satellite-launching business is heating
up. In addition to Alcantara in Brazil, neighboring Guyana is
weighing a proposal by Beal Aerospace Technologies Inc., a Frisco,
Texas-based company, to use its territory on the equator for the
construction of an advanced launching facility.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil is seeking technological safeguard agreements with
countries besides the United States for the corporate launch of
satellites. And the Brazilian government, acting on behalf of the
country's own satellite-launching program, recently reached an
agreement with the Ukraine for the supply of rocket technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Symbolically it's quite important for Brazil to evolve its
space program,'' said David Fleischer, a professor at the
University of Brasilia.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement reached on Tuesday also holds symbolic importance
for the relations between the United States and Brazil. Differences
over issues such as child labor or American tariffs on Brazil's
exports of orange juice and steel have created tension between the
two countries in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have this type of agreement without a high level of
trust between both parties,'' said Anthony Harrington, the American
ambassador to Brazil. ``It underlines the interest we have in
promoting Brazil's objective of taking advantage of Alcantara.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0352 </DOCNO>
