u a BC-NY-BUDGET-TALKS-NYT     04-18 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAGGLING STIFLES ANY HOPE FOR N.Y. STATE BUDGET DEAL THIS WEEK
</HEADLINE>
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Negotiations over a new state budget came to a
sudden halt on Tuesay after a series of minor squabbles erupted
between Gov. George E. Pataki and leaders of the legislature,
dashing any hopes that the budget would be completed this week, as
lawmakers went home for a nearly two-week break.
</P>
<P>
   The disputes came as Pataki and the leaders were reportedly near
agreement on a major area of spending that had been holding up a
final budget deal: education. The plan being considered calls for
increasing overall state spending for education by a record $1.2
billion, or 8.7 percent, for the coming school year, lawmakers and
their aides said.
</P>
<P>
   The education package has already been approved by legislative
leaders from both parties. It includes $200 million to continue a
program to provide prekindergarten classes to all 4-year-olds and
to reduce class sizes in the early grades. The package also covers
$67.5 million to raise the salaries of teachers in urban districts
like New York City's and $228 million to pay for maintenance
projects in aging school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The budget is now 18 days late, and legislative leaders had
hoped to have the budget completed before members of the
legislature went home for the Passover and Easter holidays. But
those hopes faded on Tuesday as Pataki and his Democratic rivals in
the legislature clashed on several issues largely unrelated to the
budget.
</P>
<P>
   One dispute centered on a state program that provides school tax
rebates to homeowners statewide. The Democrats accused Pataki, a
Republican, of derailing the talks by resurrecting a proposal he
made earlier this year to have homeowners receive rebate checks
directly from the state instead of the way they do now, through
school districts.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have resisted the governor's proposal, calling it
a political ploy meant to give Pataki sole credit for providing the
rebate. But Pataki's allies in the legislature denied that there
was anything political about his proposal, saying that he merely
wanted to give the rebate directly to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   The other squabble had to do with the governor's demand that the
legislature adopt his plan for reining in the state's huge debt.
Pataki is apparently withholding his support for a final budget
deal until the Democratic speaker of the state Assembly, Sheldon
Silver, agrees to back a plan that would strictly limit the state's
ability to borrow without voter approval.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's demand comes as he faces mounting criticism from
conservative groups, once his staunchest allies, for expanding the
state's overall debt while the state has been enjoying
multibillion-dollar budget surpluses. Democrats say they are open
to proposals that would restrict the state's borrowing practices,
but add that the issue should not be tied into the budget
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   The squabbling comes nearly two weeks after Pataki and
legislative leaders from both parties announced that they had
agreed to the parameters of a nearly $78 billion budget. That
agreement helped move the budget discussions further along than
they have been at this date in most years. As part of the deal,
Pataki agreed to refrain from making wholesale vetoes, provided the
legislature remained within that figure.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for allowing the legislature to add $1.4 billion
to the $76.8 billion budget the governor proposed in January. But
that increase will be partly offset, because the legislature
intends to reduce the governor's estimates of what some programs
will cost. In all, aides to the governor and the legislature
estimate that the final budget will be $77 billion to $78 billion,
an increase of 5 to 6 percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
   The spending agreement that legislative leaders reached on
education represents the largest year-to-year increase ever,
providing a total of $13.8 billion to school districts across the
state. New York City is expected to receive more than $400 million
of the $1.2 billion increase that lawmakers are seeking for
education. That is significantly more than the $102 million
increase the city schools would have received under the governor's
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The education package also calls for spending $30 million to
help schools devise programs to reduce violence among students. It
also provides $46 million for a handful of other programs, like
expanding summer school offerings and bilingual education. The
package sets aside an additional $50 million to help poor urban
districts undertake minor repairs in older school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The one part of the education budget whose fate is unclear is a
project favored by Democrats in the Assembly: repairing seriously
deteriorating school buildings. The Democrats insist that some
money for the program be included in the final budget, but the
amount has not been decided.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki is said to be withholding his support for the plan until
Silver agrees to some of the governor's demands, like his plan to
restrict the state's ability to borrow.
</P>
<P>
   The budget was due on April 1, but for the 16th straight year,
the governor and the legislature missed that deadline. The delay
caused by Tuesday's disagreements means that the earliest that
lawmakers can begin passing the budget is May 1, when they are
scheduled to return.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
