<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FAMILY-PLANNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FAMILY PLANNING POLITICS  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, April 19:
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton recently called on Congress to raise aid for
international family planning by $169 million next year, bringing
the total to $541 million in the 2001 budget. That substantial
increase, coming after years of cuts, would merely restore funding
to 1995 levels. Far more is needed. Nearly 600,000 women die
annually from complications of pregnancy and childbirth. Many of
them could be saved by services that help women avoid unintended
pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is also calling on Congress to abolish the pernicious
restriction on advocacy activities that was imposed on foreign
family planning organizations as part of a deal last year to get
Congress to pay back dues owed to the United Nations. Under
longstanding law, no U.S. government funds may be used by foreign
agencies for either abortion services or for lobbying on abortion
policy.
</P>
<P>
   But the restriction, imposed last year, goes further by barring
foreign organizations from receiving American assistance if they
use their own money to provide abortions or to engage in abortion
policy debates in their own countries. A compromise has allowed
Clinton to waive the advocacy restriction, but the waiver
automatically resulted in a $12.5 million cut to family planning
aid. The gag rule is anti-democratic and a prohibition that would
be illegal in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Carolyn Maloney and Nita Lowey, Democrats of New York, are
both sponsoring legislation to end the gag rule. Broad access to
family planning is the best way to reduce the need for abortions.
Congress should finance it without attempting to silence
organizations abroad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
