<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS:
</P>
<P>
   VICE PRESIDENT McCAIN?: Despite their often bitter feud during
the Republican primaries and the seemingly unfinished work of their
rapprochement, Gov. George W. Bush said Tuesday that Sen. John
McCain was among the many people he would consider as a possible
running mate. ``I know he said he's not interested, but until I
talk to him, and find out how interested or not interested he is,
I'll give him consideration,'' Bush said during a news conference
here. ``A lot of people will be given consideration.'' Bush's
unprompted remark about McCain, during an answer to a question
about potential vice presidents, seemed less a signal of intent
than a gesture of reconciliation. Bush and McCain are scheduled to
talk face to face in Pittsburgh on May 9. McCain has repeatedly
expressed an utter lack of interest in the job. Todd Harris, a
spokesman for McCain, said Tuesday night that the senator's
sentiments were still the same.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Frank Bruni
</P>
<P>
   THE REFORM PARTY
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN IN TEXAS: Pat Buchanan's presidential campaign opened a
three-week effort Tuesday to collect the 56,000 petition signatures
necessary for Buchanan to appear on Texas ballots as an independent
candidate. Meanwhile, the Reform Party, whose presidential
nomination Buchanan is seeking, is conducting a separate petition
drive to ensure that their candidate, if not Buchanan, is also
listed. Buchanan told The Dallas Morning News that while he would
prefer to gain ballot access on behalf of the Reform Party, ``we
don't know who's going to claim that the franchise belongs to
them.'' ``He's probably just trying to play it safe,'' said
Elizabeth Hanshaw, director of the Texas secretary of state's legal
division. ``You can't appear twice on the ballot, so if he gets the
Reform Party nomination he would probably just withdraw as an
independent.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Ross E. Milloy
</P>
<P>
   THE SENATE
</P>
<P>
   MONEY GAP WIDE IN PENNSYLVANIA: For months, Democrats have
believed that Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., was one of the more
vulnerable targets in their bid to recapture control of the Senate.
But the Democratic nominee, Rep. Ron Klink, a 48-year-old moderate
from the Pittsburgh area, won a very costly victory. His campaign
treasury is saddled with more than $446,000 in debts and he has
only $119,000 in the bank, according to the latest Federal Election
Commission records. Because he faced no opposition in the
Republican primary, Santorum enjoys an enormous financial edge. He
has raised $6 million and has more than $3.7 million in the bank,
according to the records.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   FEINSTEIN HAS $2 MILLION: For months, Sen. Dianne Feinstein of
California has held an overwhelming lead in the polls over her
Republican challenger, Rep. Tom Campbell, and in the latest
fund-raising period, she collected nearly twice as much cash. In
the period from Feb. 17 to the end of March, Feinstein took in
$988,000 and spent about $360,000. All told, she had about $2.2
million in cash on hand. By contrast, Campbell reported raising
$565,000 in the latest period, and spent almost $700,000, leaving
him with $615,000. In Feinstein's last race, in 1994, her opponent,
Michael Huffington, spent $26 million, much of it his own money,
and she spent almost $14 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Todd S. Purdum
</P>
<P>
   THE INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   COMPLAINT BY BUSH DISMISSED: The Federal Election Commission has
dismissed a complaint filed by the presidential campaign of Gov.
George W. Bush against an Internet critic whose site, gwbush.com,
uses its potentially confusing Web address to serve up scathing
parodies of Bush's official site. The commission said on Friday
that it had dismissed the complaint because it was not important
enough to warrant the use of the commission's resources.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Rebecca Fairley Raney
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY'S SCHEDULES  &QL; 
GEORGE W. BUSH: No public events. &QL; 
AL GORE: No public events. &QL;
</P>
