<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0893 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-CUBA-LEAVE-HNS &LR;      04-18 1406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-LEAVE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBANS LOOK FOR THEIR CHANCE TO VISIT, LIVE IN U.S. 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ Daisy Camejo has been lining up outside the U.S.
diplomatic offices in Cuba's seaside capital for more than a month
now, wearily waiting as her name works its way ever closer to the
eyes of the officials who will decide whether she can travel north
to visit her son in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge left the island several years back to make a better life
in the United States, she said. He was educated in the former
Soviet Union and now works as a computer technician in a city
several hours' drive northwest of Detroit. He sends letters and
photographs home of his new life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very beautiful there,'' Camejo said, leaning against a
tree in a small park where scores of people sat and stood waiting
for word of their visa applications. ``He tells me he is doing very
well. But I need to see him.''
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal of Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old shipwreck survivor
whose Miami relatives are fighting to keep in the United States,
has highlighted the visceral feud between revolutionary leader
Fidel Castro and those who despise him. But it has also drawn
attention to the strong human bonds that tie this communist-ruled
island to the United States and to the gnawing desire of many
Cubans to cross the sea _ either for a while or for a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even as Havana and Washington maneuver to return Elian
home, thousands of Cubans struggle to find a means to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who want to go,'' Camejo said.
``It's very difficult. There is such strict control.''
</P>
<P>
   A hardy _ many would say foolhardy _ few set out in small boats
across squall-whipped seas to Florida, betting on a longtime and
controversial policy that guarantees residency to any Cuban who is
able to set foot on U.S. soil without being apprehended during the
100-mile voyage. Many, including Elian's mother and 10 other people
who were in his boat, died in the attempt.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps nowhere is the wish to leave more apparent than in
the sun-scorched lots and tree-shaded small parks near the U.S.
Interest Section, a modern, seven-story structure on Havana's
seafront that is an embassy in all but name.
</P>
<P>
   Since mid-February, several thousand Cubans have flocked to the
building each weekday to start the lengthy process that could
eventually win them the legal right to move to the United States,
or at least to visit there for a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Others line up to learn about the progress of their petitions. A
more fortunate few come to collect the permanent visas awarded in a
U.S. government lottery.
</P>
<P>
   And still others, no one really knows for sure how many, try
their luck at sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people wait here for two months. You think they don't
want to get out?'' asked Wilbur, a 64-year-old retired construction
worker who hopes to visit a son in Miami. Like many here critical
of the government, he spoke on the condition that his full name not
be used.
</P>
<P>
   ``A human being wants to be free,'' he said. ``We all have our
aspirations.''
</P>
<P>
   The current visa system, which includes the lines and the days
of waiting in the tropical sun, replaced a process that relied on
the mail. It was perhaps more comfortable but far slower. U.S.
officials say the new system has resulted in far more temporary
visas being given out. Some 10,000 visitor permits already have
been issued here this year, compared with 8,500 granted in all of
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Another 20,000 permanent visas will be assigned by the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; About 800 Cubans who set foot in southern Florida have been
processed by the Border Patrol since last October. Nobody knows how
many were lost at sea.
</P>
<P>
   The permanent visas are being drawn randomly from a pool of
545,000 Cubans, or about 5 percent of the island's population, who
threw their names in the hopper in the summer of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials say they have no way of knowing how many people
who arrive on visitors permits try to stay in the country
illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Most everyone in Cuba has someone _ a brother, sister, cousin or
uncle _ who has moved to the United States since Castro took power
in the 1959 revolution. Many Cubans survive on the money sent home
by their U.S. relations. Others have heard tales of Miami and other
U.S. cities from visiting relatives and friends.
</P>
<P>
   While some undoubtedly want out simply to put some distance
between themselves and Castro, many others yearn for a chance to
make a better living and to see something beyond the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really politics,'' said Tomas, a 35-year-old nurse
from the beach resort of Varadero, east of Havana, whose name is in
the visa lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just that you work hard all the time here and you never
get anywhere,'' he said. ``You see people you know who have left
and have plenty of jobs, plenty of money. It all starts to feel so
frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, Cubans are no different than migrants from
Mexico, Indonesia or anywhere else in the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the International Labor Organization, a U.N.
agency, estimates that more than 120 million people are now
migrants worldwide. The study predicts that migration will rise
dramatically in the coming decades when the globalized market
economy widens the disparity between rich and poor nations.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is the main attraction for Cubans. But
thousands more have left for Mexico, Venezuela and other countries.
In many instances, only an invitation from those countries'
citizens to a Cuban is enough for a visa. So, some Cubans work
desperately to get married or for other personal relationships that
could lead to such an invitation.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. tourist permits are more likely to be given to people who
are reasonably certain to return home, officials say. Often, the
successful applicants worldwide are those who can prove they own
property, have substantial bank accounts or hold good jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In Cuba, where wages average $10 a month and private property is
at a minimum, the best guarantee that someone will return is
family. Tourist permits, therefore, tend to go to older applicants
who have spouses, children and grandchildren remaining on the
island.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter and granddaughter are here. I have no reason to
leave forever,'' said Mercedes Barcelo, 47, who found out Tuesday
that her visa request had been rejected. ``I just wanted to go for
a visit.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro's supporters used to call everyone who left ``worms.''
That view has softened over the past decade because dollars from
tourism and Cubans abroad have helped Castro's government survive
the collapse of Communism most everywhere else. Still, those
seeking visas this week said they feel stigmatized in a nation that
harshly distinguishes between its friends and enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never committed a crime in my life,'' said Wilbur, the
construction worker hoping to travel to Miami. ``But now if I want
to leave I am a counter-revolutionary, a criminal, a thief.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as it prepares for Elian's return, the Cuban
government appears to be shifting its public focus to other issues
that can fortify the island's revolutionary zeal. About 100,000
Cubans marched past the embassy of the Czech Republic Tuesday in
protest of that country's call for a U.N. censure of Cuba's human
rights record. ``Traitors, lackeys and puppets,'' the crowd
chanted.
</P>
<P>
   Some working to change Cuban politics and society argue that the
widespread fixation with leaving the island hampers efforts to
transform it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it that the people who have the most, instead of
staying to resolve the problems in Cuba, want to leave the
country?'' asks Raimundo Garcia, a Protestant minister in Elian's
hometown of Cardenas, 90 miles east of Havana. ``Our solution is
not to leave for the United States. We have to be capable of
putting our country together.''
</P>
<P>
   Such arguments carry little weight with many who no longer feel
they have a stake in this society and don't want to endure the long
wait for things to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally hope Elian never comes back,'' said Michael, a
young man sitting at a cafe along the Maecon, Havana's seafront
promenade, giving voice to what amounts to blasphemy in Cuba. ``He
should be like Moses for us: parting the waters so we can all walk
to the promised land.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
