</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGET PLAN SHARPLY SCALES BACK NEW YORK CITY TAX CUTS
</HEADLINE>
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a gesture of compromise to the City Council, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani proposed a $36.7 billion city budget on Tuesday in
which he sharply scaled back his earlier proposal for tax cuts and
restored spending cuts he had proposed for libraries and other
cultural institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's budget proposal also called for several large new
capital projects over the next three years, including $348 million
for a new ambulatory care building, a children's center and a
police laboratory for analyzing DNA evidence, all at Bellevue
Hospital Center, and $96 million for an expansion of Lincoln
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The revised proposal signaled major concessions to the council
even before final budget negotiations, said Ronnie Lowenstein,
chief economist of the city's Independent Budget Office, a
nonpartisan watchdog group. ``This is a very big change from what
he was seeking in January,'' she said. ``He is not just saying here
are a few small things. He's cutting his tax cuts in half.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani on Tuesday projected a record $2.9 billion budget
surplus in the year that ends June 30. In January he said he
intended to use any surplus to eliminate two widely disdained city
taxes _ the commercial rent tax and the 14 percent personal income
tax surcharge _ as the cornerstones of his 2001 budget. The total
tax cuts would have amounted to $1.8 billion over three years.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, apparently in a bow to budget watchdogs like the
comptroller, Alan G. Hevesi, who has warned that an economic
downturn and pending labor contract negotiations could squeeze city
resources next year, he pared his tax cuts nearly in half.
</P>
<P>
   Under his proposal on Tuesday, the income tax surcharge would be
reduced by half, to 7 percent. Giuliani still proposes ending the
commercial rent tax and a flat $2-per-night fee imposed on hotel
guests. He said these tax cuts would total $1 billion over three
years, about $800,000 less than his original proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has also restored $50 million for libraries, museums
and other cultural institutions that he had sought to cut,
provoking an outcry from the council. In other spending, his plan
would set aside $64 million for summer school and $108 million for
air-conditioning in classrooms. It also includes $60 million in
federal funds to expand the police force by 1,230 officers next
year, to 41,440.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor used a City Hall budget address on Tuesday to repeat
his call for the widespread use of merit pay to motivate teachers
and municipal workers.
</P>
<P>
   His budget would set aside a merit pay reserve of $325 million
in 2001, which would grow to $800 million in 2003 and remain
constant in succeeding years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
