<SLUG> BC-BBA-WETTELAND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WETTELAND WONDERS WHAT WENT WRONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rangers closer John Wetteland spent Monday
night ``wracking my brains out.''
</P>
<P>
   Closers must cope with failure. Those who don't will not survive
in their world of high-pressure specialization.
</P>
<P>
   Answers, though, often can't be found.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland uncovered none after failing to preserve a one-run,
ninth-inning lead for the second time in as many days.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the game, I was wracking my brains out,'' said
Wetteland, who converted 18 consecutive save opportunities before
Sunday's loss in Cleveland and Monday's ninth-inning collapse
during the Yankees' 5-4 victory in 11 innings at The Ballpark in
Arlington. ``What could I have done differently? How could I have
done better? I really didn't come up with an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, though, copes well with the bumps and potholes
closers must endure through the course of a 162-game schedule. He
entered the clubhouse yesterday afternoon with his usual good humor
intact and enjoyed his late-afternoon, conditioning skate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got be truthful, though,'' he said. ``I'm affected by it.
I'm affected in that it stinks with the games Esteban \RLoaiza\S
and Darren \ROliver\S threw and in the fact I didn't do my job.
Yet, I also have to weigh whether it was from a lack of
preparation? No. Was it from a lack of application? No. Was it from
a lack of execution? Not really.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland took a plan to the mound, made his pitches and stayed
the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``My stuff was good \RMonday\S night,'' he said. ``The
application was there. The execution was there. It just didn't
work. That's an intangible that happens in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland refused to use his recent workload as an alibi.
Wetteland pitched four consecutive days for only the fourth time in
his career and for the first time since the 1998 season. Yet, he
threw only 37 pitches during his three appearances before Monday's
ninth-inning entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's always been one of my strong suits,'' Wetteland said.
``In fact, I had better stuff \RMonday\S night than I had
\RSunday\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland would not pitch last night after four consecutive
appearances. Rangers manager Johnny Oates planned to call upon
right-hander Jeff Zimmerman should a save opportunity presented
itself.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I've blown two in two days,'' Wetteland said. ``Sadly,
I've been through that before. You just continue to work. I've
never seen anyone get worse from hard work.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
