r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX     04-18 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers could be in a six-team American
League Central if the current realignment proposal passes at the
next meeting of major-league owners in June. That would also mean
four teams in the Western Division and four teams in the East.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers pitcher Rick Helling, a member of the Players
Association executive committee, said he thinks baseball should
consider six five-team divisions _ three in each league _ even if
it means an interleague game every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't bother me,'' Helling said. ``I don't think it
would bother any player as long as the travel is relatively the
same.
</P>
<P>
   As for the 4-6-4 alignment, Helling said, ``Geography is the
main plus. The minuses are obvious. We'd have five other teams we'd
have to beat out in the division. As much as they want to
rationalize it, it's much harder for those teams to win a division
title and get in the playoffs.'' \Nsubheds:Central move still
important Rangers vice president John McMichael, who represented
the Rangers at Monday's owners meetings, said the club still wants
to move to a division within the Central time zone. There had been
some speculation the Rangers were no longer concerned about that
since they had sold their television rights to Fox for the next
10-15 years and were no longer worried about late-night ratings
from the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure we feel as strongly as we used to,'' McMichael
admitted. ``Obviously, when you sell your rights, it has less of a
direct impact. But obviously our rights-holders have paid a lot of
money and we want to preserve the value. Plus, having an unbalanced
schedule and a lot of games on the West Coast hurts us in
generating fan interest and promoting home games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' main goal from realignment is interleague games
with the Houston Astros.  &QL; 
Las Vegas watch
</P>
<P>
   John McMichael said six teams, including the Rangers, remain
interested in moving their spring training base to Las Vegas in
2002, and probably will resume financial negotiations with city
officials next week.
</P>
<P>
   McMichael said he's also staying in contact with Charlotte
County, Fla., officials and is waiting to see what improvements can
be made to the Rangers' Port Charlotte facility. Much depends on a
bill pending in the state Legislature that would provide funds to
improve Florida spring-training facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how the economics go with Las Vegas, if it makes
them a top contender,'' McMichael said. ``Certainly, both sites are
getting much attention.''  &QL; 
Lineup matters
</P>
<P>
   News flashes from the Rangers' lineup:
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palmeiro made his fourth consecutive start at first base
yesterday. Manager Johnny Oates said David Segui will start there
today and Palmeiro will DH.
</P>
<P>
   Oates is planning to give catcher Ivan Rodriguez the day off as
well. Bill Haselman is scheduled to start for the second time this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Oates is also planning to give Jason McDonald his first start.
He'll play left field and give Chad Curtis a rest.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Frank Catalanotto, sidelined with a strained
groin muscle, said he is ``close,'' but trainer Danny Wheat wants
Catalanotto to wait until Friday before he returns to the field.
Catalanotto, available for pinch-hitting duties, said, ``I'm pretty
frustrated. I'm trying to will myself back in there.''  &QL; 
Minor matters
</P>
<P>
   News flashes for the minor leagues:
</P>
<P>
   Triple-A pitcher Brian Sikorski has cleared outright waivers and
been assigned to the Oklahoma Redhawks. He was taken off the 40-man
roster when the Rangers purchased the contract of Jason McDonald on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Redhawks third baseman Mike Lamb, whose defense was a concern in
spring training, committed three errors in an 11-4 loss to
Albuquerque on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa first baseman Carlos Pena, the Rangers' first-round draft
pick in 1998, has 16 runs batted in during the Drillers' first 12
games.
</P>
<P>
   nn
