<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NILE-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. TO CRACK DOWN ON STANDING WATER IN WAR AGAINST WEST NILE
VIRUS
</HEADLINE>
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York City Board of Health passed a resolution
on Tuesday declaring large puddles of water an official public
nuisance, and empowered the Departments of Health and Sanitation to
remove any receptacle containing standing water without warning its
owners.
</P>
<P>
   Effective immediately, if city workers stumble upon mountains of
tires, dirty bird baths, foul kiddie pools or other bodies of still
water that may attract mosquitoes, they will remove them quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, however subtle, is evidence of how last year's
outbreak of the West Nile virus is affecting public health policy
and the activities of city agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, New Yorkers were required to remove accumulations of
water where mosquitoes were likely to breed. But the city was
required to declare the body of water a public nuisance and give
the person it belonged to some chance to remove it.
</P>
<P>
   But that process was too slow, given how fast mosquitoes mature
in an ideal breeding place _ about one week _ said a health
department spokesman, John Gadd. Under the new resolution, if a
receptacle containing standing water is removed by the city, the
property owner may be fined or charged for the cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   The health department hopes that its public information campaign
encouraging residents to clean up their yards will make it
unnecessary to raid yards for tires and the like.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, which will also encourage New Yorkers to use bug
spray and wear long sleeves at night, is one of many steps the city
embarked on this week to prevent a reoccurrence of West Nile, the
mosquito-borne virus that can cause swelling of the brain. The
virus killed seven people and sickened 62 in the metropolitan
region last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
