<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-FUNDRAISING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNER OF CHEMICAL DUMPER GAVE TO N.Y. MAYOR
</HEADLINE>
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Renco Group, a New York-based company whose
holdings include a Utah company that was identified by federal
environmental officials as the No. 1 toxic chemical dumper in the
nation in 1998, donated $100,000 to the soft-money campaign
committee set up to help Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani, according to
federal records.
</P>
<P>
   The contribution was made to the Giuliani Victory Committee,
which was set up to allow Giuliani to skirt federal fund-raising
restrictions in his Senate race. Giuliani's opponent, Hillary
Rodham Clinton, has set up a similar soft-money committee to aid
her campaign. Renco owns Magnesium Corp. of America, which was
cited in a 1998 report by the Environmental Protection Agency on
the dumping of toxic chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure, contained in campaign reports filed in
Washington, came as Clinton campaigned in the Adirondacks raising
questions about Giuliani's environmental record, a theme she plans
to return to on Wednesday in a trip to Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Donated to Giuliani's victory committee, the money was
transferred to the National Republican Senatorial Committee.
Generally the national Republican committee would use the money
over the next year to finance advertisements and get-out-the-vote
efforts to advance Giuliani's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's campaign spokeswoman, Kim Serafin, referred questions
about the donation to the senatorial committee in Washington.
Stuart Roy, a spokesman for the national Senate fund-raising
committee, said it would be unfair for Democrats to try to hold
Giuliani responsible for the donation because it had been made to
the national committee, even though the check was made out to the
Giuliani Victory Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
