<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1019 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-BREWERS-NYT &LR;      04-18 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BREWERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' BATS DELIVER THAT FIRST VICTORY TO HAMPTON
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This was baseball like it ought to be, at least for
the 2000 version of the Mets. Edgardo Alfonzo was driving balls to
the opposite field. Mike Hampton was in command and getting
ground-ball outs. Robin Ventura was hitting a grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets defeated the Milwaukee Brewers last night, 10-7, in a
game that, despite a ninth-inning scare, was played the way the
Mets' front office envisioned when it put together this season's
team.
</P>
<P>
   There was even vintage weather for the occasion. Last weekend,
the Mets sweltered on the artificial turf at Three Rivers Stadium
in Pittsburgh. Last night, they played in 48-degree temperatures
with an unforgiving 20-mph wind blowing straight to right field at
Shea Stadium. The Mets are used to such weather; the last time they
were in New York, on April 9, their game was postponed because of
snow.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, who was batting .152 and said, ``I stink'' before the
Mets began their series in Pittsburgh last Friday, capped a torrid
few days with his first grand slam of the season in the fourth
inning. It was the 14th slam of his career, putting him above
Harold Baines, Ken Griffey Jr. and Mark McGwire on the active list
and putting him into a ninth-place tie, with Gil Hodges, on the
career list. He is a .362 career hitter with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, who has eight hits in his last 17 at-bats, came up in
the fourth with two outs. He had hit only .167 in his career
against Jaime Navarro, the Brewers pitcher, but Navarro was a much
different pitcher than when the two faced each other in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In the first three years of a four-year, $20 million contract
signed with the Chicago White Sox before the 1997 season, Navarro
lost more games in the majors (43) than any other pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   He lacks the off-speed pitches to complement his fastball, which
is usually in the range of 85-88 mph, and has struggled again this
year.
</P>
<P>
   After walking two hitters to load the bases _ one of Alfonzo's
three doubles came between the walks _ Navarro fell behind Ventura,
two balls and no strikes. Navarro followed with an 88-mph fastball,
and Ventura jumped on it, rifling the pitch high over the wall in
right field. It was the first ball Ventura had sent over the fence
with the bases loaded since his famous ``grand single'' that beat
the Atlanta Braves in the fifth game of the National League
Championship Series last October.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura was cheered by the small but hearty crowd, which was
announced as 17,905 but was significantly smaller. He was removed
from the game after six innings, as were two other starters.
Hampton stayed in; he has not enjoyed this kind of success since
spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who went 22-4 for the Houston Astros last season, lost
his first three starts for the Mets as he struggled with his
control. Hampton walked 17 in 13 and two-thirds innings in those
games, but he said his problems were more mental than physical. He
and Dave Wallace, the Mets' pitching coach, both believed Hampton
was thinking too much, trying too hard in an effort to succeed in
his new surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   He was given a four-run Tuesday last night when the Mets scored
four times off Navarro in the first inning. After Jon Nunnally
blooped a leadoff double, Alfonzo, Mike Piazza and Todd Zeile all
had run-scoring hits. Jay Payton knocked in the other run in the
first with a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, blowing on his hands and rubbing up the ball throughout
the night, was shaky in the second inning, walking three and
allowing a two-run single to Raul Casanova. But he was stingy after
that, retiring 17 of the next 19 hitters and erasing the two
runners who reached base on double-play grounders.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers touched Hampton for three runs with two outs in the
eighth, chasing Hampton when Jose Hernandez delivered a two-run
single that cut the Mets' lead to 10-5. It was a nervous 10-7
before Armando Benitez got three outs and a save in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   For the night, Hampton worked seven and two-thirds innings,
allowing five runs on six hits and six walks, striking out seven.
</P>
<P>
   Like Hampton, the second baseman Alfonzo had struggled this year
after enjoying the best season of his career in 1999. He has been
stellar in the field, but his hitting has slumped, partly because
of his inability to hit the ball to right field.
</P>
<P>
   But Alfonzo hit two doubles there Tuesday night, and had his
first three-hit game of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
