<HEADLINE>
WINE OF THE WEEK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Friday, April 21) 
 
By MICHAEL LONSFORD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On this date in 1836, Texas won its independence from Mexico at
the Battle of San Jacinto near what would become the city of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Also on this date in 1918, German flying ace Manfred von
Richtofen was shot down during the World War I battle of the Somme
after amassing the most ``kills`` by any flier in history _ 80.
What was Richtofen's nickname? &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If you like California pinor noir but want to win your
independence from the simplistic, strawberry-juice-in-the-bottle,
give the 1997 Crichton Hall Pinot Noir _ 4 1/2 stars _ a try.
Though chockful of good acidity and some tannins right now, with
deep, bing-cherry and cinnamon flavors, this wine is worth laying
away for a year or two.
</P>
<P>
   The wine, frankly, reminded me of burgundy. But from the Cote de
Beaune or the Cote de Nuits?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a `cote' of many colors,'' co-owner Judith Crichton said.
</P>
<P>
   About $27.99.
</P>
<P>
   Crichton Hall also makes a fine, not-overoaked 1997 Chardonnay _
4 stars _ which is around $17 (great food wine) and a rich, complex
1997 Merlot _ 4 1/2 stars _ which is drinking well now but will age
nicely; it's about $27.99.
</P>
<P>
   Answer: The Red Baron.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
WINE RATING &QL; 
5 stars: Outstanding &QL; 
4 stars: Fine &QL; 
3 stars:Good &QL; 
2 stars: Fair &QL; 
1 star: Poor &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
