<HEADER>
A1022 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOOR-COLLAPSE19-COX     04-18 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOR-COLLAPSE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Floor collapses, 3 hurt at work site in Ohio
 &HT;    By Christine Vasconez
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In a daring rope and crane rescue, Dayton
firefighters saved a construction worker's life Tuesday afternoon
at a downtown RTA construction site where a floor collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   As Michael Reno, 29, floated in and out of consciousness, he
dangled in a wire basket stories above a crane operator who gently
lifted him to safety from an area where the floor had collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never done a rope rescue,'' said Tom Bourquin, a 23-year
veteran Dayton firefighter trained in urban and search rescue. ``I
feel pretty good. I've been training for 12 years and got to use
our skills today, everything went like it was supposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Crane operator Rick Masters, who maneuvered the wire cable and
hook inside the building and removed Reno, said ``Anytime someone
gets hurt it's scary. There's a big trust factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno was in fair condition at Miami Valley Hospital on Tuesday
night with a fractured and dislocated elbow. He and two other
construction workers were cutting through the concrete second floor
of a stairwell as part of an RTA renovation of the historic
13-story American building.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Lee, 23, was in the Intensive Care Unit at Miami Valley in
critical condition with a fractured skull.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Deel, 42, is in stable condition with a fractured arm and
abrasions at Franciscan Medical Center. Firefighters removed both
men through a nearby doorway.
</P>
<P>
   At approximately 1:48 p.m., the three construction workers stood
on the second story sawing off sections of the 12-by-12 floor. They
already had removed the 11 floors above them in work done weeks
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The three workers fell 15 feet to the first floor after the
8-inch thick concrete floor, which had been supported by a
temporary beam, collapsed, said James Denton, safety specialist
with Occupational Safety and Health Administration in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   After rescuing Deel and Lee, firefighters realized Reno was
trapped on the other side of the floor, which nearly became a
vertical wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got there the big slab of concrete was between us and
him,'' Bourquin said. ``Our first thought was to secure the slab,
but we decided to use the crane and basket through the top of the
building.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayton firefighter Mark Huff crawled around the unstable slab to
assess Reno's injuries. Reno was drifting in and out of
consciousness, Bourquin said.
</P>
<P>
   Noticing that his condition was deteriorating,
firefighter/paramedic Phil Myers and firefighter Ray Bush, both
trained in rope rescue, quickly rappelled from a section of the
second floor into what had become a pit.
</P>
<P>
   They carefully put a protective collar around Reno's neck and
lifted him onto a backboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had one doing patient care, then lowered a second to help,
the third firefighter packaged him up'' in the basket, Bourquin
said. ``It was like a little courtyard and the only access was from
the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno, in the basket, was hooked to the crane and Bourquin, who
was standing on another section of the second floor gave hand
signals to a foreman. The foreman motioned to the crane operator to
slowly pull the basket out of the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Reno was put in an ambulance while the rope rescue team was
hoisted out of the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Denton said the three workers had removed the third floor last
week and had no problems.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 to 60 workers have been working at the site, where
renovation started two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton Daily News staff writers Steve Bennish and Mara Lee
contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
