<HEADLINE>
FOR THE KNICKS, AN IMPORTANT MEANINGLESS VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The outcome was meaningless in the playoff standing,
but the Knicks did some work toward patching up their tattered
self-esteem Tuesday night in a 100-88 victory against the Detroit
Pistons.
</P>
<P>
   It was far from a dominating performance by the Knicks _ and the
Pistons didn't play Jerry Stackhouse in the fourth quarter _ but
the team learned to count on the touch of Allan Houston (29 points)
again and rely on the energy of Latrell Sprewell (16 points, 5
assists) once more in front of a relieved crowd at Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't sure what they would see after the Knicks had been
so thoroughly beaten up over the last week. But the Knicks (50-31)
were able to create a 13-point fourth-quarter lead, survive an 11-4
run by the Pistons with a couple of timely jumpers from Houston and
cool off the comeback threat by a Detroit team playing without its
superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Although the playoff positions had been decided for both teams,
and Grant Hill was looking on from the sideline because of an ankle
injury, the Knicks saw this game as important to their mental
state.
</P>
<P>
   In their last two games, the Knicks trailed by 20-plus points
and lost in double-digit humiliations to Toronto and Cleveland. So
the Knicks wanted to use Tuesday night's game as a chance to regain
faith in themselves with only one regular-season game deft to play,
in Boston on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need our best players at their best going into the
playoffs,'' Coach Jeff Van Gundy said before the game. ``None of
our best players have played particularly well over the last few
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last week, Houston, Sprewell and Patrick Ewing have
looked languid and nonresponsive. Their shooting percentages have
plummeted and their defensive lapses have been disturbing. Some of
those same issues dogged the Knicks in the first half against
Detroit. Although Hill wasn't around to deflate them, Stackhouse
whirled around Houston to score 14 points. Houston countered with
14 points of his own by aggressively driving to the basket and
getting to the free-throw line, but his defense was again suspect.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't the only one struggling, though. The Knicks allowed
the Pistons to shoot 48.4 percent and were outrebounded, 19-14.
They were able to tie the Pistons, 47-47, at the half after forcing
the Pistons into 11 first-hal&AMP; turnovers and shooting 50 percent
themselves, but this was not the spirited effort the Knicks wanted.
</P>
<P>
   They came out''in the third quarter much more focused. After
scoring just 5 points in the first half, Ewing was more lively on
offense and active on the boards and helped give the Knicks a 62-54
lead with 6 minutes 7 seconds left in the third. Then, after a
turnover, Sprewell converted the Pistons' mistake into a
crowd-pleasing dunk to put the Knicks ahead, 69-56.
</P>
<P>
   The energy(was back. It didn't matter if their high-voltage
forward Marcus Camby was out with a sprained knee, they had others
step into his place. Kurt Thomas leaped up and swatted away a
driving layup by John Crotty, which resulted in an open 3-pointer
for Houston in transition.
</P>
<P>
   He popped it. And the confidence Houston had been lacking for
the last several games seemed on track again as the Knicks surged
ahead, 75-62, at the end of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   At least for an impressive third quarter, there were signs the
Knicks were motivated again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, you have to wait on the players,'' Van Gundy said.
``Sometimes, you have to wait until they're ready. We've got to get
back on track.''
</P>
</TEXT>
