<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTING IS RIPE FOR UPSETS, SWEEPS AND FITS, TOO
</HEADLINE>
  By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After one week, the Stanley Cup playoffs have provided a lot of
goals in several games, strange goals in some games and one grand
episode of bizarre behavior by a goalie.
</P>
<P>
   As for team themes, the whiney Washington Capitals are on the
verge of being upset in the Eastern Conference while the St. Louis
Blues are helping the San Jose Sharks in their quest for a similar
upset in the West. And the Toronto Maple Leafs are lucky their star
goalie is eligible to play Game 4 in Ottawa  &UR;  &LR; on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The goalie, Curtis Joseph, thought Ottawa forward Daniel
Alfredsson had interfered with him on the winning goal in the
Senators' 4-3 victory Monday night. Joseph protested by jumping up
and down, throwing pieces of his equipment and skating in a
threatening manner toward Referee Mick McGeough.
</P>
<P>
   Although the referee raised his hand in the manner of a traffic
cop saying ``Stop!'' the goalie kept charging. He lost his balance
and fell into McGeough's legs, knocking the referee on top of him.
</P>
<P>
   McGeough could have thrown Joseph out of the game. Instead, he
just gave the goalie a 10-minute misconduct, which was served by
another player. The league could have suspended Joseph on Tuesday
but no announcement was made, a strong suggestion that Joseph will
play Wednesday night in Ottawa, with Toronto leading the
four-of-seven-game series two games to one.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph saw humor in his behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty funny,'' he said. ``I didn't mean to fall. It's best
you laugh about it today. I don't think I should be suspended. I
lost my balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph said the league did not talk to him about the issue but
to Pat Quinn, Toronto's coach, who often complains about goalie
interference. Quinn said: ``I'm boxed in. I have no comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Commenting freely earlier in his series was Ron Wilson, coach of
the Capitals, who trail the Penguins three games to none with Game
4 Wednesday night in Washington. It will be only the second game
there this series because a building conflict in Pittsburgh forced
the teams to play Games 2 and 3 in the Igloo. Usually, Washington,
as the higher finisher, would have gotten the home ice for Games 1
and 2.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson at first joked that he didn't mind playing all seven
games in Pittsburgh, a quote that surfaced on the Penguins'
bulletin board. He also said, more seriously, that his team would
be confident even if it lost Game 1 by 8-1. Then the Penguins
presented the Capitals and goalie Olaf Kolzig with a 7-0 calling
card in the opener.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Wilson complained that the referees favor Jaromir Jagr,
the Penguins' superstar. ``Every time a guy is down, Jagr comes
over to complain,'' Wilson said. ``The next time, we have a guy in
the box.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those guys is Chris Simon, Washington's leading
goal-scorer, who was suspended for Game 2 of the series for
cross-checking _ and is penalized frequently when he is eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson partly blames Referee Paul Stewart. ``He's too good for
the players,'' Wilson said. ``It's his game.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Buffalo-Philadelphia series, it was a video judge's game,
at least for one nondecision on the phantom goal scored by John
LeClair of the Flyers in Game 2. He put the puck through a hole in
the side of the net guarded by the Sabres' Dominik Hasek. The
Flyers led three games to one after losing to the Sabres, 3-2, in
Game 4 Tuesday night in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   The official explanation put out by the television spin machine
after Game 2 was that the illegality of LeClair's goal was visible
only on ESPN's camera mounted in the net, a view unavailable to
video judges until it was too late to nullify the goal. This is
disingenuous. A conclusive view, from high over the net, was
available immediately to the video judges. They simply overlooked
it.
</P>
<P>
   Strange goals are occurring in the Blues-Sharks series, too,
which San Jose leads two games to one. Four of the Sharks' goals
have gone in off Blues players. The most infamous was the one
defenseman Marc Bergevin accidentally threw into the net of his own
goalie, Roman Turek, as he tried to knock the puck behind the net
with his glove.
</P>
<P>
   After Monday's 2-1 victory, the Sharks were not ready to gloat.
Owen Nolan, the Sharks' captain, who scored both goals Monday, said
of the Blues: ``There is a reason why they are first overall in the
league. This series is far from over.''
</P>
<P>
   You can't say that about the Detroit-Los Angeles and the
Colorado-Phoenix series. The Red Wings lead 3-0 with Game 4 in Los
Angeles Tuesday night. Going for their third Stanley Cup in four
seasons, the Red Wings won an 8-5 red-light fiasco in between 2-0
and 2-1 squeakers. The Avalanche, also leading by 3-0, can
eliminate the Coyotes on Tuesday night. In the other Western
series, the Dallas Stars took a two-games-to-one lead into Game 4
at Edmonton Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Another strange goal came in the Devils-Florida Panthers series,
which New Jersey led, 3-0, after winning Game 3, 2-1, on Tuesday
night. It came in Game 1 when Peter Worrell, the Panthers' bruiser
who rarely scores, sent a 50-foot knuckler past Martin Brodeur into
the Devils' net.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
