<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1027 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-DEVILS-PANTHERS-N     04-18 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-PANTHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS CLOSER TO BANISHING PLAYOFF DEMONS 
BY ALEX YANNIS  
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNRISE, Fla. _ It took the Devils 12 manpower advantages before
they scored a power-play goal in the series against the Florida
Panthers. But the one Alexander Mogilny got Tuesday night in a 2-1
victory not only wiped out a 1-0 deficit but may have also erased
three straight years of early playoff futility for New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   By taking a commanding lead of three games to none in the
Eastern Conference quarterfinal series, the Devils put themselves
in position to eliminate the Panthers here on Thursday night and
advance to the second round. Only two teams in playoff history have
come back from 0-3 deficits to win a series: the 1942 Toronto Maple
Leafs and the 1975 Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Mogilny's power-play goal, with 3 minutes 35 seconds left in the
second period, tied the game at 1-1. Brian Rafalski untied it for
the Devils with a blistering shot from the right point early in the
third period after Bobby Holik won a face-off. The Panthers'
goaltender, Mike Vernon, had little chance on Rafalski's shot, one
of 40 the Devils fired at him.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur, who faced only one shot in the second period and
22 in the game, played well in goal in the third period, when the
Panthers pressed for the equalizer. Brodeur allowed a goal to Ray
Whitney in the first period and nothing after that.
</P>
<P>
   With Scott Stevens leading the way, the Devils did another
masterful job of neutralizing Pavel Bure, whose 58 goals in the
regular season led the National Hockey League. Bure has been
limited to only three assists in the series, one in each game.
</P>
<P>
   In the 18 playoffs series the Devils have played, they have
never lost a series after winning the first two games. This is the
fifth time the team won the first two games and the players used
that element as motivation before Tuesday night's encounter.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils had a huge territorial advantage in the first two
sessions, but only managed Mogilny's power-play goal, their first
in 12 attempts in the series with the man advantage. The goal came
with 3:25 left in the second period on a shot from the right circle
that found its way past Vernon through a crowd in front. It offset
Whitney's first-period goal and tied the score.
</P>
<P>
   It also was one of the few times the Devils created traffic in
front of Vernon. The Panthers' goaltender was able to see most
shots taken from far out and he was helped because the Devils were
unable to get any second chances against Vernon as they failed to
go to the net in the first two periods.
</P>
<P>
   So huge was the Devils domination in the first 40 minutes,
though, that they had 31 shots at Vernon while limiting the
Panthers to seven at Brodeur. The lopsided play was most evident in
the second period, when the Panthers had only one shot attempt at
Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   Florida had a marvelous chance to open the scoring during its
first manpower advantage, but Mark Parrish missed wide after a
crafty setup by Bure and Whitney also shot wide from close range on
the left moments later.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney succeeded, however, 9:19 into the game during a
two-on-one break with Mike Sillinger. With Brodeur looking at
Sillinger, who was holding the puck, Sillinger slipped a pass to
Whitney on the left for an easy goal in a sequence that was started
after Bure gained possession in the neutral zone.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Brylin was the forward the Devils used in a defensive
role a great deal against Bure in the first two games of the
series. But he missed Tuesday night's game with a bruised right
knee he sustained in the third period of Game 2, forcing Devils
Coach Larry Robinson to look for another forward to assume that
role.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Pandolfo stepped in, along with Stevens, who was the main
man the Devils had on the ice against Bure. It was an elbowing
penalty to Bure that lead to Mogilny's goal. Stevens started the
play that led to the goal with a pass to Rafalski, who found
Mogilny on the right wing; it was Mogilny's first goal in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   With no extra forwards available, the Devils promoted Steve
Kelly from Albany and he took Brylin's place at left wing with
Holik his center and Randy McKay the right wing. The Devils had a
choice of promoting either Steve Brule or Kelly and Lou Lamoriello
went with Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got some playoff experience,'' Lamoriello, the president
and general manager of the Devils, said before the game, referring
to the six games Kelly played in the playoffs with Edmonton in
1997. ``And he's also more adept at playing the left side.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said, ``I've played mostly center. I don't want to make an
impression here. All I want to do is play solid hockey.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
