<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MARKET IS STILL MORE BULL THAN BEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Younger investors burned by the recent meltdown of the
new-economy stock market as represented by Nasdaq can't really say
they've been through their first bear market.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet, at least.
</P>
<P>
   If the tech-laden Nasdaq rallies from Friday's close and
rebounds from its recent staggering losses, it will not qualify as
a bear market. To be sure, it qualifies technically by dint of
losing more than one-third of its value because a 20 percent
decline officially denotes bear territory.
</P>
<P>
   Real bear markets, however, go beyond mere numbers that quantify
the magnitude of a market index's fall. Bear markets grind your
spirit into the dust. The worst bear markets destroy hope for the
future and end only when nobody believes things will ever get
better.
</P>
<P>
   Times and technology may change, but market psychology doesn't.
The new-economy cognoscenti say information transmission times have
telescoped to the point that even world-shaking events don't take
nearly as long to play out as they once did. Perhaps that is so in
some cases, but it isn't when financial markets reverse direction.
</P>
<P>
   Bear markets can't occur until bull markets have run their
course, and vice versa. Both bear and bull markets are as much
psychological as economic phenomena because both have as much to do
with emotion as money. The old saying about stock markets being
moved by fear and greed gets at this critical psychological
characteristic.
</P>
<P>
   One reason this bull market has run so long is the dearth of
players who have been psychologically scarred by a brutal bear
market. The last one occurred in the '70s, and none of the
relatively few survivors has fully recovered psychologically.
They've been recognizable over the past decade as those who haven't
fully participated in the wild run to riches offered by the stock
market in general and the new-economy Nasdaq in particular.
</P>
<P>
   If you look at the market charts after 1929 and 1969, they'll
tell you the '30s and '70s weren't one long bear market because the
averages rose and fell significantly during those time frames. In
the minds of those who experienced these two horrendous decades,
though, the up-down distinctions delineating bear and bull periods
are psychologically lost. For them, the '30s and '70s were a blur
of seemingly endless terrible times.
</P>
<P>
   Those dreadful experiences, however, set the stage for the
prosperity and roaring long-term bull markets that followed.
</P>
<P>
   They say there are two things you never get over. One is a
brutal physical beating and the other is a devastating bear market.
What makes a real bear market so devastating is what it does to
your psyche over a lengthy period of time. If you're heavily
involved in the market, it gets to the point where you think it'll
never end, that things will never get better.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have taken some hard lumps in the past few weeks may
think they've been bloodied in bear market combat, but they
haven't. For any down market to qualify for bearhood, it must last
long enough so it doesn't just wipe out a good part of your
treasured nest egg _ it also must destroy forever your blithe
spirit and marketplace innocence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
