<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSURED OF HIS ROLE, POSADA SEIZES THE MOMENT 
BY BUSTER OLNEY  
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Watch Jorge Posada bounce to and from the
dugout for each inning. Listen closely to broadcasts of Yankee
games and the shouted voice you hear will belong to Posada. He will
be yelling at the pitcher to cover first, directing the infielders,
cussing vigorously. He is moving with exceptional energy, like a
colt released to pasture on the first day of spring.
</P>
<P>
   This is Posada's time, after years of waiting for the Yankees to
trust him with a full-blown opportunity, and Posada is seizing the
day. He had two hits Tuesday night, including a two-run homer, and
the Yankees dumped Texas, 6-3, for their seventh consecutive
victory; that matches their longest winning streaks of the 1999
season. Orlando Hernandez is 3-0 after four starts. He allowed
eight hits Tuesday night in the Yankees' first complete game of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   It was Posada who spurred the Yankees against the Royals last
Friday with a two-run homer. It was Posada who slammed an
extra-inning home run Monday and it was Posada who executed an
unassisted double play in the turning point of that game. In 13
games he is batting .311, with three homers, a team-high six
extra-base hits and 10 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   After his first 13 games last year, Posada was batting .146,
mired in a slump he did not shake for more than three months. For
that and other reasons, Posada was the team's most significant
question mark when spring training began this year. He caught the
majority of games in 1998 and 1999, but the coaching staff relied
heavily on Joe Girardi, and when Girardi left for the Cubs as a
free agent and the Yankees were restructured for this season, the
front office took a calculated risk: It chose not to acquire
another healthy veteran catcher to back up Posada.
</P>
<P>
   It wanted Posada to come to spring training knowing with
certainty that he would be the catcher. It wanted Posada to
understand fully how much it believed in him, to know that he would
play every day, even if he had a bad day or two or more.
</P>
<P>
   Posada has responded. He guided Ramiro Mendoza through six and
one-third perfect innings Saturday. In the middle of a crisis
Monday night, Posada visited the mound and Cone looked at him and
asked, ``What do you think?'' It was not a question Cone would have
bothered with in the past.
</P>
<P>
   And Posada is hitting.
</P>
<P>
   He moves swiftly to and from his position each inning, the skull
cap bouncing on his head, carrying his glove in one hand and his
catcher's mask in the other. He is having immense fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
