 GAS PRICES DECLINE SLIGHTLY  &HT;     By VERNE KOPYTOFF 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bay Area gas prices have declined a few cents a
gallon from their recent peak after last month's agreement by OPEC
countries to increase oil production, according to the latest
survey by the California State Automobile Association.
</P>
<P>
   Regular unleaded gas in San Francisco now costs an average of
$1.92 a gallon, down from a high of $1.94 a gallon on April 4. In
San Jose, Calif., gas has dipped to $1.85 a gallon from $1.88 a
gallon during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not much to be thankful for after seeing prices jump 35
cents over the last few months,'' said Paul Moreno, a spokesman for
the automobile association.
</P>
<P>
   What precipitated the decline in gas prices is last month's
agreement by OPEC ministers to increase oil production by 7
percent. Since then, the price of crude oil has dropped to nearly
$25 a barrel from nearly $35 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is the relative health of California's oil
refineries, which produce just enough of the required
cleaner-burning fuel to supply the state. In the past, mechanical
problems at some of these refineries affected production and caused
gas prices to surge.
</P>
<P>
   Severin Borenstein, director of the Energy Institute at the
University of California at Berkeley, said it is not surprising
that gas prices have declined modestly. He said it takes six to
eight weeks for lower oil prices to fully reach the consumer at the
pump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we will continue to see declining prices, though those
declines will be slowed some because of the summer driving
season,'' Borenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, though, consumers are still paying nearly 40
cents a gallon more for gas than they did six months ago. It is
unclear what the latest price decline will have on proposals by
some state legislators to reduce gas prices by, among other things,
exempting the fuel from the state sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Verne Kopytoff at  &LR; verne &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
