<SLUG> BC-TERRORISM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERSTANDING OF TERRORISM'S METHODS AND PRACTITIONERS GROWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Terrorists, say experts gathered for the fifth
anniversary of what people here refer to simply as ``the bombing,''
are more cunning than ever.
</P>
<P>
   They exist in ever smaller, more elusive groups. Their motives
are more complex and convoluted, their tactics more varied, the
technology at their disposal more lethal.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the good guys have learned a trick or two themselves.
</P>
<P>
   We understand terrorists _ if not well enough _ better all the
time. We know the simple things _ concrete barriers around key
public buildings, for example _ that make us safer. And time has
taught us which threats to take most seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't solve the problem of terrorism,'' said Brian
Jenkins, author of International Terrorism: A New Mode of Conflict.
``But we can keep the threat in perspective. Our lives are not
always in danger. The republic is not always in peril.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather, said the terrorism scholars and security experts
assembled in Oklahoma City, the struggle for domestic safety is an
ongoing arms war between society's civilized haves and angry
have-nots. It is mostly, they said, a war of smarts.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Oklahoma City will dedicate a memorial to the 168
persons killed April 19, 1995, when a rental truck filled with
fertilizer and fuel oil exploded at the front of the Murrah Federal
Building. Each day of the conference held by the Oklahoma City
National Memorial Institute for the Prevention of Terrorism began
with a moment of silence ``for those who died, those who survived
and those whose lives were changed forever.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, because the bombing hit a Midwestern city rather
than Beirut or London or New York, experts said it made the entire
nation feel newly vulnerable to mass violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the bombing, Oklahomans thought for a long time that
terrorism happened in other places to other people,'' said Stephen
Sloan, a fellow with the institute and a University of Oklahoma
political scientist. ``We know better now.''
</P>
<P>
   And experts agree that the question is not whether the country
will suffer another deep wound from terrorism, but when and where
and how.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, those who study terrorism know their subject better.
Here, in simplified form, are a few of the conclusions being made
about terrorism and terrorists:
</P>
<P>
   - Nobody wakes up suddenly inspired to become a terrorist.
Terrorists are made during adolescence. And though they tend to
adopt political or religious philosophies that color their
violence, they often are drawn to terrorist groups for less noble
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, experts said, membership in a terrorist outfit offers
them prestige. Other times, as with factions of the Irish
Republican Army, it gives a high-minded cover to a form of
organized crime. In some cases, young men turn to terrorism because
their family has ties to the organization, or because it offers
them sanctuary, or because they see it as key to a group identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the police did something malicious to their mother, or
all their friends all belong, or they were the subject of an arrest
they believe was unfair,'' said Alison Jamieson, a terrorism
consultant who has studied members of the Red Brigades in Italy.
``Sometimes they join an organization they believe in and then
gradually fall into terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The striking thing is how accidental the process can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Understanding the factors that make terrorists makes it easier
to find them, Jamieson said.
</P>
<P>
   - In the early 1980s, most of the world's terrorism sprang from
revolutionary groups organized like small-scale armies, said
University of Alabama justice sciences professor Brent Smith.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``During the 1990s, indictments against
international terrorists average less than two persons per case.''
</P>
<P>
   Among right-wing extremists in the United States in particular,
the vogue is cells of ``leaderless resistance'' that insulate
loosely aligned radicals from investigation, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This model has been created specifically to thwart
prosecution,'' he said. Further, Smith said, America's right-wing
terrorists today are deeply devoted to their various
anti-government causes and ``less likely to turn state's evidence''
and inform on colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   - The danger of terrorists employing chemical, biological,
radiological or nuclear weapons is growing. The collapse of the
former Soviet Union, for instance, has fed a black market for
weapons of mass disruption.
</P>
<P>
   And though the experts said governments need to track such
threats, they remain the least likely to be unleashed by terrorists
because of the high costs and sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not look so far into the future that we lose sight
of the clear and present dangers of terrorists using high
explosives to inflict mass casualties,'' said John Parachini of the
Monterey Institute of International Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flash of a bomb and the immediacy of it has an impact that
(unleashing) a disease does not,'' he said. ``For one thing, it
makes more clear who the target is.''
</P>
<P>
   Understanding that bombs and bullets pose the mostly likely
danger, Parachini said, tells governments to spend more money
girding against those conventional attacks.
</P>
<P>
   - Attacks on business hubs in urban areas _ like London's
financial center or New York's World Trade Center _ are taking on
new appeal among terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   John Gearson of the Department of War Studies at King's College
in London said that for terrorists, ``the ability to disrupt
economic activity rather than take human life remains a less
glamorous but potentially more effective choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The IRA believes, he said, that attacking the economy in London
was successful in getting the British to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   That knowledge, he said, can allow security experts to emphasize
defenses around the most attractive targets.
</P>
<P>
   Other terrorist tactics, though, were deemed strategic failures.
For years Timothy McVeigh trumpeted the twisted anti-government
manifesto played out in the pulp novel The Turner Diaries. In it,
the bombing of one federal building sets a match to the tinder for
coast-to-coast revolution.
</P>
<P>
   But McVeigh's bombing in Oklahoma City launched no such revolt,
noted Bruce Hoffman, a Rand Corp. terrorism expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, McVeigh deflated a lot of the militia groups,''
Hoffman said. ``He's probably the most reviled person in the
country today...
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been five years. Where's his revolution?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-00 2339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000418.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1036 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GROWBIZ-INSPIRE-SFCHR     04-18 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROWBIZ-INSPIRE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GROW A BUSINESS: STAFF INSPIRED TO KICK BUTT AND HAVE FUN  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR;   &LR; Business leaders these days are taking some
unusual steps to pump up sales and morale.
</P>
<P>
   Manish Mehta, who takes business seriously but not himself, is a
perfect example. The CEO of San Jose, Calif.'s ELetter Inc. took
his wife to buy black pumps late last year _ not for her, for him.
To spur his colleagues on to greater results, Mehta pledged he
would wear high heels to the office for an entire day if they could
meet an ambitious sales target.
</P>
<P>
   The venture-capital-backed company, which lets businesses send
out direct mailings quickly and cheaply without making employees
stuff envelopes or visit a post office, met Mehta's target and he
was on the hook.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a successful and inexpensive incentive,
albeit embarrassing. Because he was going to wear the shoes only
once, Mehta purchased the pumps at Payless Shoes and spent most of
his workday sitting. Now, some employees have suggested that he
wear a dress to work if ELetter meets another milestone. Mehta
hasn't yet agreed to that proposal, but he says companies must be
as creative with their people as their products.
</P>
<P>
   ``A company's culture is very important,'' he says. ``You can
match other companies' offers to your employees, but to make them
stay, you have to make work fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Offbeat events, even if occasionally in questionable taste, are
one way to foster camaraderie. At Sun Microsystems, CEO Scott
McNealy adopted the motto ``Kick butt and have fun,'' and his
company has attracted attention for elaborate April Fools' Day
pranks. One year, Sun engineers constructed a golf course green in
McNealy's office, complete with water hazard.
</P>
<P>
   Demandline.com CEO Patrick Burns is another big believer in team
building. Two weeks ago, he told five of his top executives to meet
at the airport with cold-weather gear for a five-day trip to an
undisclosed destination. They flew to Alaska, connected with two
guides and climbed Matanuska Peak with ice axes and 70-pound
backpacks.
</P>
<P>
   Burns, who launched Demandline.com in June to let small
businesses band together to get better prices for
telecommunications, financial and other core services, views the
brief Alaska adventure as a metaphor for working at a startup:
``You can get blindsided at any time, and teamwork is essential.''
</P>
<P>
   Before getting an MBA at Kellogg Business School and veering
into technology, Burns planned to become a diplomat. ``You have to
be constantly innovating and creating challenges and value for your
people,'' he says. Surprise trips and parties are ``a retention and
recruiting tool.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Demandline.com held what it called a ``suitcase
party'' at O'Neill's Pub in San Mateo, Calif., for its 31 workers,
their spouses or dates. The winner of a drawing was sent for an
immediate three-day weekend at the Phoenician resort in Scottsdale,
Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   VENTURE CAPITAL SEARCH: Stock market charts lately look like the
EKGs of heart attack victims who have received a few defibrillator
jolts. Most initial public offerings have been put on hold, but
plenty of entrepreneurs with IPO visions are still lining up to win
venture capital financing.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday afternoon at the University of California at
Berkeley's Haas School of Business, eight finalists vying for more
than $70,000 in cash and prizes in the second annual business plan
competition heard RedGorilla.com founder and CEO John Witchel's
advice on ``How to ask for $5 million.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news, says Witchel, is that there is as much venture
capital money available today as there was a month ago _ billions
of dollars _ so ``Don't panic.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is increased emphasis on the ability to show a profit.
Until recently, Witchel says venture capital investors were willing
to fork over increasing amounts of money to meet specific
milestones, such as acquiring customers and getting products to
market. Now, ``the giveaway days are officially over,'' he says.
``If you don't have an intrinsically profitable model, watch out.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent market gyrations could make some business school students
more cautious about becoming high-tech entrepreneurs. Still, 182
teams entered this year's business plan contest. More than 60
venture capitalists whittled the list of contestants to these eight
finalists:
</P>
<P>
   Arrive on Time, a real-time, customized traffic information
service; Harmony123, a B2B investment information and education
company; Imagize, a maker of semiconductors for image-processing;
Infoprotection.com, a B2B service to maintain confidential files;
MechanEx, a maker of online product development tools; SkyFlow, a
developer of software for wireless applications; Somagenics, a
developer of gene-regulating compounds to treat disease; and
Sporteum, an electronic marketplace for the global sporting goods
industry.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at psinton(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
