r f BC-INNERCITY-OAKLAND-SFC     04-18 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INNERCITY-OAKLAND-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 OAKLAND'S FIRMS RISING TO THE TOP  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Oakland, Calif., businesses took five of the top
25 spots on the second annual ranking of 100 inner-city businesses
by Inc. magazine and the Harvard Business School's Initiative for a
Competitive Inner City.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker Technology, an Oakland telecommunications installation
and maintenance firm, placed No. 3 with 1998 revenue of $3.1
million and a five-year growth rate of 4,843 percent. Cambria
Environmental Technology, Fast Track Litigation Support and Hamel
Group placed Nos. 18, 19 and 20, and Give Something Back placed No.
24. A sixth Oakland company, Lori Bonn Jewelry, placed No. 70 on
the list.
</P>
<P>
   Only Cleveland won more spots on the 100 list, with a total of
eight. In the Bay Area, San Francisco had two winners _ IQuantic,
No. 33, and AAA Business Supplies, No. 80.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than merely a list, the Inner City 100 is the most
ambitious project to uncover business successes in America's inner
cities,'' said Harvard Business School Professor Michael Porter,
who started the nonprofit Initiative for a Competitive Inner City
in 1994. ``The Inner City 100 are leading the economic rebirth
taking place in America's inner cities.''
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for the Inner City 100 awards, applicants must be
profitable businesses, with at least 10 employees, $1 million in
sales and a five-year operating history. They also must be located
in economically distressed urban areas where income is at least 50
percent lower than the local norm and unemployment is 50 percent
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly mom-and-pop businesses, the 100 winners have median
annual sales of $4.7 million, a median workforce of 42 employees
and average compound annual growth rate of 50 percent. Forty-one
percent of Inner City 100 employees reside in the inner city and
their average hourly wage, excluding benefits, is $12.83. That
compares with the national private-sector average of $12.77 and is
150 percent more than the federal minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Tucker, founder and CEO of Tucker Technology, pays his 120
workers from $10 to $30 an hour to install telecommunications
systems, and median pay is close to $18 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   One of 11 Inner City 100 companies headed by an African
American, Tucker hires more than half of its employees from urban
core areas.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker was born in the Bronx and counseled prisoners at New York
City's Rykers Island prison after studying sociology in college.
Then he discovered he could earn twice as much money working for
the old New York Telephone and began his career in
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker's company hires about 15 percent of its employees through
links with community-based organizations such as Glide Memorial
Church and welfare-to-work programs. It also uses Laney College in
Oakland and other schools to find and train workers. And Tucker
hires skilled technicians from the Communications Workers of
America union who have either retired or lost their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker moved up from No. 4 on last year's Inner City 100 list to
No. 3. But it hasn't all been smooth sailing.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Tucker had to take time off from adding clients and
staff to replace four of his eight administrators and build a more
take-charge management team.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker used to run his company by telling his employees what to
do. That worked when the company was small. But as it grew to 120
employees from Hawaii to Ohio, Tucker found himself inundated by
everyone else's questions and unsolved problems. As a test, he left
a broken chair in the company's reception area and it remained
there for weeks before someone took the initiative to throw it
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like the `Wizard of Oz,' '' he recalls. ``Everyone was
looking for the wizard to solve their problems rather than taking
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Tucker has a poster on his wall pinpointing the evils of
``It's not my job'' and similar complacent thinking. And the
company is back on the growth path. It just landed a large contract
from Pacific Bell to install digital-subscriber line (DSL) service
in several South Bay and Southern California communities, which
could double Tucker's revenue and workforce.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Like other companies on the Inner City 100 list, Tucker said
proximity to a diverse labor force, public transportation and
cheaper real estate are all advantages of doing business in a core
urban area. Tucker's offices are located near the 12th Street
Station of the Bay Area Rapid Transit (BART) rail system.
</P>
<P>
   Fast Track Litigation Support, a newcomer on the Inner City 100,
is strategically located near BART's 19th Street Station. Company
founder Patricia Nieuwenhuizen said her location in the former
Neptune Orient Lines offices at Grand Avenue and Broadway is useful
for quick access to the company's law firm clients in San Francisco
and local colleges such as the University of California at
Berkeley, which supply many of the firm's 72 part-time workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employees can get to our offices easily and we can serve our
clients without paying exorbitant real estate prices,'' said
Nieuwenhuizen. Her rent of about $1.60 per square foot per month is
a fraction of what she figures she would be paying in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwenhuizen was a litigator before she started her own
computer services company to compile, store and index legal data
for corporate law departments and government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, IQuantic set up its compensation consulting
business at 17th and Harrison streets because owner Mark Edwards
liked ``not having to fight downtown traffic.'' Most of the
company's 40 employees live in the city and also like proximity to
Highway 101 for quicker access to Silicon Valley clients. IQuantic
fell from No. 18 on last year's list to No. 33 this year, but
Edwards said the company is likely to double in size this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Inner City 100 project received more than 900 nominations
this year. Nearly 30 percent of them came from 52 U.S. mayors. Last
year, the contest received only 215 nominations.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; psinton &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
