<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAYLESS-CASHWAYS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYLESS CASHWAYS PLANS SCALED-DOWN ANNUAL MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Payless Cashways Inc. on Wednesday will hold
its third annual meeting since the ``new'' Payless Cashways was
formed in 1997 after the retailer emerged from Chapter 11
bankruptcy reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   Today's meeting is expected to be subdued. In a letter to
shareholders in the company's proxy statement, Chief Executive
Officer Millard Barron warns as much:
</P>
<P>
   ``Please be advised that this year's format will be
substantially different from our past meetings. ... This year we
will meet at our store support center offices, eliminate all
management presentations, and conduct only the formal business
required.''
</P>
<P>
   The only formal business slated for the meeting is the
re-election of three outside directors: Peter G. Danis, who is the
nonexecutive chairman of Payless; David G. Gundling; and Donald E.
Roller.
</P>
<P>
   Barron added that if any shareholder attending had questions,
company officials would be available to answer them.
</P>
<P>
   If it comes off as intended, the meeting will be a marked
turnaround from last year's gathering. That meeting was held in a
hotel ballroom filled with product displays, legions of company
employees and curious shareholders, all eager to meet the new
management.
</P>
<P>
   In another letter to shareholders, this one in the 1999 annual
report, Barron said 1998 was the year the company ``stopped the
slide'' and 1999 was the year it slowly started to turn the ship
around.
</P>
<P>
   And although Payless lost 41 cents a share last year, that was a
63 percent improvement over the $1.12 a share lost in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we will never be satisfied with a loss, our financial
results for 1999 show substantial improvement,'' Barron wrote.
``With the slide stopped and the turnaround effort well under way,
it is important that our team stays focused on the goals of
consistent profitability and renewed growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's shareholders, numbering almost 5,000, hope to see
those goals realized. They have watched the company's stock price
stagnate in the mid- to high $2 range for months. Payless' stock is
traded on the bulletin board system of Nasdaq under the ticker
symbol PCSH. In late 1997, the new stock traded in the high $5
range.
</P>
<P>
   As he has preached since coming on board, Barron says Payless'
mission is to become the supplier of choice for the professional
builder and contractor, as well as the serious do-it-yourself
consumer.
</P>
<P>
   Barron pointed to progress on that front. Though same-store
sales were down 0.8 percent last year, he said, same-store sales to
the target customer segments were up 7.3 percent from the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In summary,'' Barron wrote, ``let me reiterate that although
we still have much to do, significant progress in reinventing our
company has been made over the course of 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   In its proxy statement, Payless reported salaries for its top
officials, ranging from $498,077 for Barron to $175,000 for James
L. Deats, vice president, information systems.
</P>
<P>
   The information on other officials showed David Krumbholz, vice
president, store operations, at $212,000; Kelly R. Abney, vice
president, logistics, replenishments and facilities, $207,000; and
Ronald D. Long, vice president, merchandising, $200,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
