<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAIDLOW-GREYHOUND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREYHOUND'S PARENT COMPANY SUSPENDS DIVIDEND PAYMENTS 
BY TIMOTHY PRITCHARD  
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Trapped in a deepening financial hole, Laidlaw Inc.,
the Canadian company that runs Greyhound Lines and North America's
largest fleet of school buses, suspended dividend payments on its
common stock Tuesday and won some temporary relief from bankers who
are renegotiating a long-term loan agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The news contributed to a slight rally in Laidlaw's share price,
although the company is still among the worst performers in Canada
this year after having been one of the darlings of the Toronto
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Its shares, which a year ago traded at 23.40 Canadian dollars,
rose 3.6 percent here Tuesday, to close at 1.72 Canadian dollars,
or $1.16.
</P>
<P>
   The shares of Laidlaw, based in Burlington, Ontario, have been
pummeled for months by the effects of a failed growth strategy and,
more recently, by reports of improper accounting practices at an
important subsidiary, the Safety-Kleen Corp. of Columbia, S.C.
Three top executives at Safety-Kleen have been suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Burdened with $3.3 billion of debt, Laidlaw has been trying to
sell its 44 percent stake in Safety-Kleen, a waste-handling
concern. But since Safety-Kleen disclosed that an internal audit of
its accounts was under way in March, its shares have fallen more
than 30 percent, closing Tuesday at $1.0625.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the troubles at Safety-Kleen may make Laidlaw's own
financial reports for the last three years unreliable, Laidlaw has
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian parent company has also been trying to unload a
portfolio of ambulance services and health care companies in the
United States. The division, once seen as a business that could be
profitably expanded like buses, has produced huge losses and most
of its assets remain unsold.
</P>
<P>
   Laidlaw expected to receive about $2 billion by selling
Safety-Kleen and the health care units when the disposal plan was
announced in September. Some of the money was to be used to repay
debt and some to invest in more buses.
</P>
<P>
   It now looks as if the sales will yield much less than expected,
and much later than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Laidlaw's other businesses are profitable, but analysts and
investors have speculated that a substantial write-off of its asset
base is n store.
</P>
<P>
   The financial report for the second quarter, which ended on Feb.
29, was to have been released in mid-April. The company said last
week that the report would not be ready until the end of the month,
and added Tuesday that the new arrangement with its bankers assured
that release date.
</P>
<P>
   The banks have waived protection on an existing $1.5 billion
credit, of which $1.2 billion has been drawn. But further advances
under the current agreement will be limited to $30 million. A May
31 target date has been set for a new lending pact.
</P>
<P>
   Canceling its dividend payments, a related agreement, will save
Laidlaw $62 million a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
